<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 00:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7163 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-     01-18 1014
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
FranBlinebury
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
MINNEAPOLIS _ If it had been John Elway, you'd accept it. If it
were Joe Montana, you'd expect it.
</P>
<P>
   But this was Chris Chandler making all of the right reads,
making all of the right plays, and suddenly it was the Falcons who
were soaring.
</P>
<P>
   A nine-yard sideline pass to Terance Mathis, then a 29-yard
strike to Ronnie Harris, and there was hope.
</P>
<P>
   A crack in a collapsing pocket, and there was Chandler lumbering
up the middle for a nine-yard gain, looking about as nimble as an
escaped convict in leg irons. He stubbed his toe on the artificial
turf, tripped and eventually fell to the carpet, hitting his shin
and picking up a noticeable limp.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nice,'' Chandler would say later. ``That must have looked real
pretty.''
</P>
<P>
   Beautiful, gorgeous and fetching were just a few of the
adjectives that came to mind three plays later when Chandler
drilled a death-ray laser into the teeth of the Vikings' defense
for the tying touchdown, then Atlanta went nearly 12 minutes into
overtime before Morten Andersen's 38-yard field goal lifted the
Falcons into the Super Bowl 30-27.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't believe it! They don't believe it! They don't
believe it!'' yelled Atlanta free safety Eugene Robinson, referring
to the crowd of 64,040 stuffed inside the echo chamber they call
the Thunderdome as he raced off the field.
</P>
<P>
   What was there to believe?
</P>
<P>
   That the most prolific offense in the history of the NFL could
be held to just one lonely touchdown for the final 44 minutes of
the game?
</P>
<P>
   That the fearsome combination of Randall Cunningham to Randy
Moss would look like a couple of guys who had their phone lines
disconnected after the first quarter?
</P>
<P>
   That the Vikings' Gary Anderson, who had succeeded on a record
42 consecutive field goals, would be wide left by about a foot on
what would have been the game-clincher?
</P>
<P>
   That five weeks after lying on an operating table undergoing
cardiac bypass surgery, coach Dan Reeves would have the ol' ticker
still beating inside the chest of this unlikely Atlanta team?
</P>
<P>
   Or is the most unlikely chapter in the story the fact that
Chandler wrote the dramatic finish to as gripping, yo-yoing,
unpredictable and wonderfully entertaining a playoff game as has
been served up maybe since San Diego vs. Miami back in 1982?
</P>
<P>
   Chandler took them 71 yards on eight plays in 1:18, the Falcons
are Miami-bound, and now there is a little more elbow room for Bud
Adams in that closet where the NFL keeps the owners of the forlorn
franchises that have never been to even one Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told Chris that it was as good as anything by Elway or any
of them,'' said Reeves. And he should know. Reeves was coaching the
Broncos in 1987 when a young Elway led the 98-yard drive at
Cleveland _ the last conference championship game to go to overtime
_ that firmed up his reputation as a clutch performer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember seeing that drive by Elway on TV,'' Chandler said.
``It did really amaze me. Mine just wasn't as big a finish. I
didn't throw for the winning touchdown like him.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Chandler was exactly like Elway. ``The Drive'' tied
the score in regulation, and the Broncos won on a field goal in
overtime.
</P>
<P>
   Just call this the land of contrasts, where a professional
wrestler can be elected to the highest office in the state and then
the honorable Gov. Jesse ``The Body'' Ventura can celebrate at his
inauguration party by singing a duet with rocker Warren Zevon:
Werewolves of Minnesota. Anything, it seems, can happen.
</P>
<P>
   If the Falcons are indeed the Dirty Birds, then Chandler is the
grungiest of them all, a homing pigeon who got lost and wound up in
Atlanta's nest. An erstwhile Colt, Buccaneer, Cardinal, Ram and
Oiler and now working on his sixth team in an 11-year NFL career,
you figured that Chandler has as much historic precedent to be
leading the charge as Barney the Dinosaur has presiding over the
presidential impeachment trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see this as redemption or vindication,'' Chandler
said. ``I just see it as proof that after getting knocked around a
lot early in my career, this is the proof that I can be a pretty
good quarterback. The satisfaction comes from knowing that all
those teams in my past are still struggling to find their way and
now I've made it to the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frankly, I got tired of looking at the papers where they were
saying that all they had to do to win the game was stop the run. I
took that personally.''
</P>
<P>
   With the NFC's leading rusher, Jamal Anderson, limited to 67
yards on 23 carries by the Minnesota defense, Chandler went to work
constructing the pyre for a Viking funeral, hitting 27 of 43 passes
for 340 yards and three touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   It was as shocking a big-game performance as you'll see,
particularly to the strutting Vikings and their haughty fans who
seemed to truly believe that stuff about the Falcons being 11-point
underdogs. There wasn't a purple-clad person in the building Sunday
who thought Atlanta had the slightest chance to win.
</P>
<P>
   Cunningham hit Moss for a 31-yard touchdown on their first
possession, and the Vikes cranked out 20 points the first four
times they touched the ball. Then, the machine was shut down.
Atlanta used a soft zone to bottle up Moss, who caught five passes
for just 44 yards the rest of the way, and Cunningham began to look
like his former incarnation in Philadelphia as the game got late.
</P>
<P>
   The daring, swashbuckling Vikings became conservative, not
stretching the defense, and even after the Chandler-to-Mathis TD
tied the score, Vikings coach Dennis Green chose to take a knee,
running out the last 30 seconds of regulation and gambling on
overtime.
</P>
<P>
   ``The feeling on our sidelines when Anderson missed that field
goal was like we had already won the game,'' Chandler said. ``All
day long they weren't able to put us away, and all we wanted was a
chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Which they got. Which they made count. Thanks to Chris Chandler,
of all people.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
