<HEADER>
A7169 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-HERSKOWITZ-COLUMN     01-18 0797
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-HERSKOWITZ-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICKEY HERSKOWITZ  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
LAS VEGAS _ Yes, it's true Frans Botha tried to get inside the head
of Mike Tyson. But without the necessary surgical tools, or a saw
and butter knife, the plan was doomed to fail.
<TEXT>
<P>
   As the mystics in the media poked Sunday through the ashes and
tea leaves of Tyson's fifth-round knockout, this much was obvious:
Few believe he can regain his form of the late 1980s, when he ruled
the heavyweight galaxy. It isn't clear that Iron Mike believes so,
either.
</P>
<P>
   As expected, his punches were wild and more or less in the wrong
time zone. After sitting out half of this decade, at the request of
the law and the NBA _ the No Biting Association _ he looked not
only rusty but corroded.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, what Tyson did best was regain his composure and not
unravel after a shaky start. Botha admitted freely, even proudly,
that part of his plan was to upset and incite Tyson, who in recent
years has been about as stable as nitroglycerine.
</P>
<P>
   The amiable South African hit him late, and Mike retaliated.
Botha used the punch-and-clinch tactic, constantly tying Tyson up,
and Mike was frustrated. When Botha hit him after the bell for the
first round, Tyson hit back and gave Botha's arm and upper body a
half nelson. For a few scary seconds, 12,519 antsy patrons thought
they might see Mike implode.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson and Botha kept talking to each other in a taunting and
profane dialogue.
</P>
<P>
   But referee Richard Steele got both fighters under control and
took a point away from Tyson in the second round for ``unnecessary
roughness.'' In football, this would have been a 15-yard penalty,
so Tyson did not complain.
</P>
<P>
   Most observers were waiting to see if Mike was toast or still a
contender. He gave them a fleeting answer with the last punch of
the night, that lightning bolt of a right hand sending Botha
sprawling. Botha said he never saw it coming, and you could not
disbelieve based on his futile attempt to regain his footing. He
was on his back, then on his big buffalo bottom, then pitched face
forward, his nose touching the mat. Finally, he almost fell through
the ropes, and Tyson helped pull him back.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever appeal Tyson has left stems from the suspense of never
knowing what to expect of the one-time Brooklyn delinquent, who
came to the title at 20 with a sense of history and even a touch of
humility. But you study him closely, and it isn't hard to
understand why Tyson identifies with the late Sonny Liston.
</P>
<P>
   ``That might sound pretty morbid and grim,'' he said, ``but he
was absolutely a great fighter. He just wanted people to love and
respect him, and it never happened. He may have got a raw deal, but
we all write our own books in life.''
</P>
<P>
   Love and respect have been continuing themes for Tyson, who has
been devoured by the temptations that have undone many a boxer _
bright lights, fast sex, bad company.
</P>
<P>
   If anyone beat the odds, it may have been Liston, who was sullen
and a loner when he reached the heights and didn't let fame change
him. Sonny died in Las Vegas of a heroin overdose, alone at 38. His
wife found his body when she returned from a trip. It is doubtful
he called for help. He never had.
</P>
<P>
   If Tyson came out of poverty, uneducated and crude, Liston had
it far worse. He was one of 25 children in a destitute family that
lived and worked on a farm. Liston left home at 13, selling a sack
of pecans for bus fare. He couldn't read. His prime assets were his
muscles, and he used them as a head-buster for unions and the mob.
He quit that work when he learned he could use his fists for an
honest living, more or less.
</P>
<P>
   Wistfully, he once recalled his only defeat in his first 11
years of fighting. He had ridden in a chair car from St. Louis to
Detroit for an eight-rounder. His purse was $75, plus train fare.
</P>
<P>
   Sonny arrived in the afternoon, just hours before the fight. He
left with his money from the promoter and a broken jaw from his
opponent. Without even bothering to get the jaw set, he caught the
night train back to St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   Liston enjoyed a brief, golden moment after he won the
heavyweight title from Floyd Patterson. He lost it to the young,
brash Cassius Clay.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Tyson carries on as boxing's most disturbing figure, trying
to rediscover his raw, primitive power. This was his first fight
under the direction of Tommy Brooks, who was the No. 2 man in
Evander Holyfield's corner on bite night 1{ years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Brooks chided Tyson for looping his punches and not working on
Botha's ample body. ``He was headhunting,'' the trainer observed.
``I told him he had to throw his punches straight.''
</P>
<P>
   Just in time, Tyson received and delivered the message.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
