<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 00:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7172 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX--TYSON-HNS &LR;      01-18 0755
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX--TYSON-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By W.H. STICKNEY JR.  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
LAS VEGAS _ The most crucial win in Mike Tyson's career is in the
record books, though not without a great deal of difficulty, as
might be expected, coming off a 19-month layoff.
<TEXT>
<P>
   He overcame a sluggish, tainted, error-filled start Saturday
night against Francois Botha at the MGM Grand Garden Arena to
record a fifth-round knockout in a fight he had to win.
</P>
<P>
   Then, the thoughts of the 32-year-old former undisputed
heavyweight champion turned not to potential opponents or paydays
but to two weeks of rest and relaxation and a return to boxing's
laboratory in an effort to refine skills caked with rust.
</P>
<P>
   ``After two weeks (of rest), I'm going to get back in the gym
and just keep working, capitalizing on everything I screwed up on
Saturday night,'' Tyson said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   His technique was far from perfect, but the power that has
sustained Tyson (46-3, 40 knockouts) through a career that will
land him in the Boxing Hall of Fame was evident to the announced
crowd of 12,519 and a worldwide pay-per-view audience.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson trailed on the scorecards of all three ringside judges
until he floored the 6-2, 233-pound Botha (39-2, 24 KOs) at 2:59 of
the fifth round. But Tyson initially was unaware of what he had
done when Botha hit the canvas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I looked at him on the floor and thought, `Is this guy
quitting?''' Tyson said. ``I didn't know what happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Had he lost, Tyson would have dropped back into the shadows of
the heavyweight division. Now, his path to glory is clearer.
</P>
<P>
   But the thing most clear in the mind of his new trainer, Tommy
Brooks, through the first three rounds was worry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was good for Mike just to get back in the ring
after a year and a half,'' Brooks said. ``I was a little worried at
first because he went out, he started looping his punches. He came
back to the corner, and I told him you've got to throw your
straight punches.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been working for 2{ months on firing at the body; he was
headhunting. But he came out, settled down and started throwing
straight punches.''
</P>
<P>
   But Tyson was sure of himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `I've got him in my sights, coach, just give me some
time,''' Brooks said.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson was asked what he proved with the win.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't prove anything,'' he said. ``I'm just constantly
trying to do well. I have a long way to go. But I have a new
trainer and we're working on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Entering the fifth round, Tyson trailed 39-36 on the scorecard
of judge Bill Graham, 40-35 on Dave Moretti's and 40-35 in the eyes
of Dalby Shirley.
</P>
<P>
   But in the fifth round, he caught Botha with a short right to
the head that dropped him. Botha twice struggled to regain his
feet, the second time nearly falling through the ropes after he had
been counted out, when he was restrained by Tyson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Listen, he's a brother,'' Tyson said. ``What can I say? It's
not that serious; it's just a boxing match.''
</P>
<P>
   But there was no love lost between the two in the ring. The
first two rounds yielded dirty, illegal tactics by both, most after
the bell.
</P>
<P>
   When the first round ended, the two had to be separated by
handlers from each corner, turning the ring into a scene
reminiscent of June 1997, when, in the same ring, Tyson bit the
ears of Evander Holyfield to earn a one-year suspension of his
boxing license and a $3 million fine.
</P>
<P>
   ``He (Botha) got rough with me; I got rough right back,'' Tyson
said.
</P>
<P>
   In the second round, Tyson had a point deducted by referee
Richard Steele for unnecessary roughness.
</P>
<P>
   ``He twisted my arm,'' Botha said. ``He was trying to break
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if that was his intention, Tyson said yes.
</P>
<P>
   Although Tyson might not be considering potential opponents,
Shelly Finkel, his new adviser, has drawn up a list that includes
Lou Savarese of Houston, Vaughn Bean and Shannon Briggs.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson on Sunday emphasized his desire to fight four more times,
then retire.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I fight four more times this year, then, yeah, I'm gone,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond boxing, Tyson has a couple of immediate personal matters
to clear up. On Feb. 5, he faces sentencing in Maryland on a
no-contest plea to two misdemeanor assault charges that stemmed
from a minor auto accident last summer. Tyson has settled out of
court with the two other drivers involved. Depending on the outcome
of the sentencing, Tyson could be judged in violation of his
Indiana parole and put back in jail.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
