<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 00:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7173 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-BRONCOS-JETS-COX     01-18 0980
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-BRONCOS-JETS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Denver comes back, holds off Jets in AFC Championship
 &HT;    By Kent Mincer
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ Something had to give.
</P>
<P>
   Denver Broncos coach Mike Shanahan and New York Jets coach Bill
Parcells both went into Sunday's AFC Championship at Mile High
Stadium unbeaten in conference championship games.
</P>
<P>
   What gave was a Jets defense that had held the Broncos scoreless
through the first half.
</P>
<P>
   Denver spotted new York the game's first 10 points Sunday before
roaring back to score the final 23 and earn a berth in their sixth
Super Bowl, 23-10.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, the game Jan. 31 will be against the coach who took
Denver to three of those Super Bowls, Atlanta's Dan Reeves, whose
Falcons pulled off the upset of the playoffs in defeating Minnesota
on the road 30-27 in overtime.
</P>
<P>
   If mistakes are a key in a conference championship game (and
they are), both teams failed early in their attempts to establish
dominance.
</P>
<P>
   New York drove nine plays after taking the opening kickoff but
Jets kicker John Hall missed wide right from 42 yards out, hampered
by an 20-30 mile-an-hour wind that brought the wind chill in Mile
High Stadium to 18 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Denver went nowhere on its first series. The Jets took over at
their own 38 after the punt and Curtis Martin promptly fumbled. The
Broncos drove 55 yards in 12 plays, converting one fourth-down
play. But the drive stalled at the Jets 1 when the Broncos again
went for it on fourth and one, quarterback John Elway's pass
attempt being tipped as he released it.
</P>
<P>
   But New York coughed up the ball again, Keith Byars fumbling
after a Glenn Cadrez hit and John Mobley recovering at the Denver
13 with 10:14 left in the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   It was becoming a tale of opposite offenses. New York
quarterback Vinny Testaverde completed his first 13 passes, a
personal record, but the Jets' Curtis Martin, who rushed for 124
yards in their divisional playoff win over Jacksonville, was held
to 11 yards on eight carries in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, seven of Elway's first eight passes fell incomplete,
but Bronco running back Terrell Davis, the NFL's leading rusher
this season, had 75 yards rushing and 12 yards receiving through
the first 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the best running back in football,'' Elway said. ``He's
what every quarterback wishes for.''
</P>
<P>
   But with 38 seconds left in the first half, New York took over
at the Denver 46 after a punt. Six plays (including four
completions) later, Hall, who had missed four of his previous six
field goal attempts on the road, connected from 32 yards out as the
half ended for the game's first score.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets made things happen three minutes into the third quarter
as the Broncos, backed up by a 52-yard John Kidd punt and a holding
penalty, went nowhere and were forced to punt. Blake Spence stepped
in to block Tom Rouen's attempt and Fred Baxter recovered at the
Denver 1. Martin then took a pitch over left tackle to put the Jets
up 10-0.
</P>
<P>
   It took the Broncos 3:33 to tie the game.
</P>
<P>
   Denver moved from its own 36 to the New York 11 in two plays,
including a 47-yard pass reception by Ed McCaffrey on first down.
Elway connected with fullback Howard Griffith for the score as the
Broncos cut the Jets' lead to three with 10:18 left in the third.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was my fault; I bit on the crossing route,'' New York
safety Victor Green said. ``If we had made a stop there, we would
have been in control of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Elway later said that McCaffrey and Rod Smith got switched
around coming out of the huddle before the big play. Ironically, it
was McCaffrey who was supposed to come underneath on a crossing
pattern with Smith heading deep on a post route.
</P>
<P>
   A short kick on the ensuing kickoff became a loose ball, with
Denver's Keith Burns pouncing on it, giving Denver possession at
the Jets' 31. A holding penalty wiped out a Davis run to the 11,
but Jason Elam tied the game with a 44-yard field goal.
</P>
<P>
   Denver forced a punt on New York's next series. On fourth down,
Elam hit from 48 yards out to give Denver its first lead at 13-10
with 2:58 left in the third.
</P>
<P>
   Forcing another punt, Darrien Gordon returned it 36 yards to the
Jets 38. Davis ran it three straight times, the final from 31 yards
out to the end zone. And in a little more than 11 1/2 minutes, the
Broncos went from 10 points down to 10 points ahead.
</P>
<P>
   New York drove into Denver territory to start the fourth
quarter, but Steve Atwater forced a fumble by Alex Van Dyke, New
York's fourth of the day, after a pass reception, with Bill
Romanowski recovering at the Denver 28.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the combination of turning the ball over three times
across midfield, which limited our scoring opportunities,'' said
Parcells, who added he will be back as coach next season. ``Then we
had special teams mistakes as well.''
</P>
<P>
   The Broncos scored their final points on a 35-yard Elam field
goal with 3:40 remaining.
</P>
<P>
   It was left to Gordon to seal the win with a pair of
interceptions sandwiched around Elam's final boot.
</P>
<P>
   ``We beat a very, very good football team, well-coached,''
Shanahan said following the win. ``We managed to keep our
composure, even though we made a bunch of mistakes. That's the sign
of a good football team.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the prospects of facing the Falcons and the man
under whom Shanahan served as offensive coordinator, the Broncos
coach admitted, ``They're playing great defense, great offense.
That's a credit to Dan and his staff.''
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons and the Broncos will meet at 4:18 Mountain Time in
two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   And once again, with the Broncos facing their former coach, who
is 0-3 as a head coach in Super Bowls, something has to give.
</P>
<P>
   Kent Mincer writes for The Daily Sentinel, Grand Junction, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
