<HEADER>
A7174 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-BRONCOS-JETS-SIDE     01-18 0742
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-BRONCOS-JETS-SIDE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Elway not perfect _ but good enough
 &HT;    By Kent Mincer
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ He didn't have his best day as a Bronco.
</P>
<P>
   No, John Elway completed only 13 of 34 passes against the New
York Jets in Sunday's AFC Championship game. In fact, he was only 4
of 14 in the first half and, barely three minutes into the second
half, he found his team trailing 10-0.
</P>
<P>
   But there's always been something special about the Elway magic
at Mile High Stadium. That magic was never more evident than in the
second half, when Elway and the Broncos scored 23 unanswered points
to defeat the Jets 23-10 and move into Super Bowl XXXIII Jan. 31 in
Miami.
</P>
<P>
   The momentum was definitely leaning New York's way when the
Broncos quickly answered to the Jets' lone touchdown, set up by a
blocked punt at the Denver 1.
</P>
<P>
   Denver got a touchdown in three plays, recovered a free ball on
a kickoff and tied the score within a span of 3:33 and went ahead
for good with less than three minutes remaining in the third
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   And while Terrell Davis, the NFL's leading rusher this season
with 2,008 yards, certainly had a hand in things with 167 yards and
one touchdown, it was up to Elway to summon the comeback magic
that's hallmarked his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``This one was probably the ugliest,'' Elway said of his five
AFC championship wins. ``But they all feel the same when they're
over.''
</P>
<P>
   Elway connected on 9 of 20 passes in the second half, including
an 11-yard touchdown to fullback Howard Griffith.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we were a little shocked at halftime that we were down
3-0,'' he said of a Jets field goal at the end of the half which
were the half's only points. When asked if he said anything to his
team in the locker room at intermission, he said, ``Yeah, 'We've
got to get going. We definitely can't win scoring no points.'''
</P>
<P>
   But the day was most magical because it was anticipated that
this might be Elway's last appearance at Mile High Stadium. He's
rumored, as he was last season, to be considering retirement at the
end of the season.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd knew it could be the last time it got to see his Mile
High Magic. With less than two minutes remaining and the Broncos
moving for what appeared to be their last drive, flashbulbs popped
all over the stadium, fans grasping to catch Elway's final moments
on the fabled turf.
</P>
<P>
   With 1:09 left and the Broncos offense exiting after giving the
ball over on downs _ he just overthrew Ed McCaffrey in the end zone
_ a cheer erupted throughout the stadium as fans cheered Elway off
the field.
</P>
<P>
   He stepped to a makeshift podium in the middle of the field to
interview with a postgame television broadcast that was boomed over
the public address system. ``One more year,'' the fans chanted.
</P>
<P>
   When asked if it was, indeed, his last game in Denver, Elway
hedged. ``I can't tell you that yet,'' he said to a rousing
ovation.
</P>
<P>
   At a postgame press conference, Elway, who took a victory lap
around the stadium after the television interview, said his
greatest recollection of the lap was ``how happy the fans were.''
</P>
<P>
   Elway again was hesitant to make any commitments after the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will not make any decisions until down the line,'' he said.
``My main focus is to finish out this year before I think about
next year,'' he said, vowing to spend the next couple of weeks
concentrating instead on the upcoming Super Bowl battle with the
Atlanta Falcons.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, it will be against a coach with whom Elway had his
share of disagreements during Dan Reeves' tenure in Denver, which
included three trips to the Super Bowl, all losses. Still, Elway
gave Reeves his due for getting the Falcons into the big game.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got them playing great,'' said Elway. ``And Dan's a great
football coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the Falcons to go into Minnesota and win there (30-27 over
the favored Vikings in overtime Sunday), they're playing great.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Elway said he and his teammates ``are just
thrilled to death to be there.''
</P>
<P>
   So the legend in Denver vows to spend the next two weeks
focusing on how to beat Atlanta in Miami in two weeks. He'll be
making his fifth start in a Super Bowl, an NFL record.
</P>
<P>
   He's got plenty of time in the off-season to worry about the
future.
</P>
<P>
   Kent Mincer writes for The Daily Sentinel, Grand Junction, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
