<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990118.0016 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 00:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7195 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-NFC-HNS &LR;      01-18 1024
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFC-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JODY GOLDSTEIN  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ They were 14-2 in the regular season but didn't
earn the home-field advantage throughout the NFC playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   They knocked off perennial power San Francisco in the divisional
round but still weren't thought to have a chance.
</P>
<P>
   They had won 10 consecutive games but entered the NFC
Championship Game as 11-point underdogs.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, the Atlanta Falcons proved everyone wrong.
</P>
<P>
   In the first overtime conference-championship game since coach
Dan Reeves' Broncos beat Cleveland in the January 1987 AFC title
game, Reeves' Falcons (16-2) knocked off the Minnesota Vikings
(16-2) for Atlanta's first trip to the Super Bowl. Minnesota, only
the third team to finish the regular season 15-1, becomes the first
of the three not to win the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are the best-kept secret in the NFL,'' Atlanta free safety
Eugene Robinson said. ``I looked at ESPN, Fox, CBS, TNT, Fox Sports
South, Fox Sports West and nobody thought we could win the game.
But there's something special about this team.''
</P>
<P>
   Surprisingly, the game turned on a missed field goal by the
Vikings' Gary Anderson. He had already connected on kicks of 29 and
35 yards, improving his streak to 42 straight field goals this
season. But with Minnesota leading 27-20 with 2:07 remaining,
Anderson's 38-yard attempt was wide left, and the Falcons were
still in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Though he didn't get credit, Atlanta cornerback Ray Buchanan
said he got to the ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I nicked the ball,'' Buchanan said. ``I think he still hooked
it enough trying to get away from the pressure on the left side. I
was coming around the left side, and it went wide left. If he would
have kicked it straight, it would have been clearly blocked because
I got right through. Then when I got to the sideline, I thought,
`Wow, that was my man right there. He had a perfect season. He's a
Pro Bowl guy.' Man showed us a little favor right there.''
</P>
<P>
   It was one of several big plays. The Falcons got the ball back
needing a 71-yard touchdown drive to tie the score. Quarterback
Chris Chandler completed three straight passes, including a
29-yarder to Ronnie Harris, his only catch of the game. Finding an
open lane, Chandler scrambled to pick up nine yards and reach the
Vikings' 22. Jamal Anderson, who had been contained most of the
afternoon, picked up six yards to the Minnesota 16, and Chandler
then threw a bullet to Terance Mathis in the end zone to tie the
score at 27 with 49 seconds remaining.
</P>
<P>
   The momentum swung back and forth in overtime. With less than
nine minutes remaining, Vikings quarterback Randall Cunningham
threw a long pass to rookie Pro Bowler Randy Moss near the Atlanta
16 on third-and-10. Robinson knocked it down to get the ball back
for the Falcons.
</P>
<P>
   On Atlanta's second OT possession after it stopped Minnesota
twice, Chandler connected with tight end O.J. Santiago for pickups
of 15 and 26 yards. The Falcons, who started on their nine-yard
line, ran nine plays to the Minnesota 21 before bringing Morten
Andersen onto the field. Andersen connected on a 38-yarder to send
the Falcons to Miami.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't intimidate us,'' Santiago said. ``Nobody has done it
all year long. We are 14-2 (during the regular season). I don't
understand why people don't realize we were 14-2. You don't go 14-2
being scared, being intimidated. You go 14-2 with consistent play
on offense, defense and special teams.''
</P>
<P>
   The Vikings, who set an NFL scoring record this season, were
known for big plays. But with the exception of a 31-yard touchdown
pass to Moss on their first possession, there were none longer than
17 yards. The Falcons, meanwhile, had a 70-yard pass from Chandler
to Tony Martin to set up an Andersen field goal early in the fourth
quarter. There were four other plays of 19 yards or more.
</P>
<P>
   And when the Vikings were able to contain the league's
second-leading rusher, holding Jamal Anderson to 67 yards, Chandler
took to the air, passing for 340 yards and three touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been talk in the paper, we kind of heard it all
week, that `If you stop the running game, stop Jamal, we're going
to beat the Falcons,''' Chandler said. ``I wanted to show
everybody, especially the Vikings, that we can throw the ball as
well as you guys can. We can make a lot of big plays throwing the
ball. To overlook our passing game is a mistake. We were very
effective throwing the ball today.''
</P>
<P>
   They had to be, especially after Minnesota took a 20-7 lead.
Atlanta scored on its opening possession as Anderson caught a
five-yard pass from Chandler. The Vikings then scored 20 unanswered
points, in part the result of two Atlanta fumbles. The first, by
running back Harold Green, was recovered at the Minnesota 40 and
eventually led to a field goal early in the second quarter. The
next, a fumble by Santiago on Atlanta's first play of the ensuing
possession, turned into a Minnesota touchdown as Cunningham plunged
the final yard to cap a six-play, 33-yard drive.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta cut that lead to six before halftime when Chuck Smith
forced a fumble with a sack on Cunningham and Travis Hall recovered
the ball. The Falcons got the ball at the Minnesota 14, and
Chandler connected with Mathis for a one-play touchdown drive to
cut the deficit to 20-14 at halftime.
</P>
<P>
   The Vikings scored only once more, on a five-yard pass to
Matthew Hatchette with 13:41 remaining in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Atlanta came here and played a perfect game,'' Moss said.
``They were down, and they stuck with their game plan. I think we
got a little rattled in the end, and we couldn't make anything
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   The trip to the Super Bowl pits Reeves against the franchise he
took there three times. And for a guy five weeks removed from
quadruple-bypass surgery, life doesn't get much more exciting.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I can stand today, my heart's got to be in great shape,''
Reeves said. ``It can't be much harder. The only thing harder will
be dancing in downtown Atlanta the `Dirty Bird.' That's not going
to be a pretty sight.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
