<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 00:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7198 &Cx1f; tth-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NFC-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI &LR;      01-18 0978
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NFC-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHANDLER'S TIME HAS COME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ Aside from the tight knot of Atlanta Falcons
celebrating disbelievingly at the bottom of the Metrodome, the only
sound in the moments after the NFC championship game Sunday was the
bonk of 64,000 strong Norwegian jaws dropping onto the concrete
floor in front of them.
</P>
<P>
   One jaw, however, was making a different noise.
</P>
<P>
   Bounding from the field up the stairwell toward the locker room,
three steps at a time, was Eugene Robinson, who really didn't need
steps.
</P>
<P>
   To no one and everyone, in the high-pitched staccato screech
that earned him the nickname ``Orca'' by his former Seahawk
teammates, the Falcons' safety shouted:
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't believe it!
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't believe it!
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't believe it!''
</P>
<P>
   Most assuredly, they didn't believe it. And remember, this is a
population that recently elected a pro rassler as governor, so its
capacity for active imagination is not to be underestimated.
</P>
<P>
   Yet not in their darkest, lutefisk-induced nightmares did
Minnesotans envision Sunday: Their invincible, invulnerable
Vikings, a magnificent 16-1 this NFL season, losing a berth in the
Super Bowl 30-27 in overtime to an 11-point underdog team led by a
peripatetic grid hobo, Chris Chandler, whose nickname, ``Chrystal
Chandelier,'' is a testament to his physical fragility.
</P>
<P>
   By the Falcons' own admission, they are Dirty Birds, coached by
a guy who needs a zipper on his chest to deal more easily with his
heart problems. The relentless Vikings put 20 unanswered points on
that heart in less than 14 minutes of the first half, usually a
signal for even a healthy ticker to take the rest of the career
off.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the Vikings lost, fergawdsakes, AT HOME, where rivals' ears
go to die.
</P>
<P>
   ``To come in here, with this crowd, and do what we did,'' said a
beaming Chandler, ``is amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a description he might have reserved for himself, not only
for Sunday but for his advance from the back alleys of pro football
to the Boulevard of Pigskin Dreams, which this year is shaded by
the palms of Miami.
</P>
<P>
   The Everett native and former University of Washington
quarterback was good for a pick-free day of 340 yards and three
TDs, including a 16-yarder to Terance Mathis inside the final
minute of regulation. That touchdown not only concluded a marvelous
clutch drive that forced overtime, it drove home a point Chandler
was eager to make.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got tired of looking at the papers and seeing (the Vikings
say) all they had to do was shut down our running game,'' he said.
``I took that personally.''
</P>
<P>
   For those who have known Chandler through his often convulsive
career as a Husky and in the NFL, they know that when he takes
something personally, drama is imminent. Earlier in his career, the
drama was often self-destructive. But these days, a more serene
Chandler simply gets even. Or, as was the case Sunday, three points
better.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons were 15-2 primarily upon the rushing feats of
running back Jamal Anderson, who had 1,800 yards during the season.
Held to a quiet 67 Sunday, the offense for the biggest game in the
Falcons' tepid NFL history reverted to Chandler, heretofore a
figure in NFL records only because he is the sole quarterback to
start for six different teams.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Dan Reeves, not long off a hospital gurney after bypass
surgery, armed Chandler with the key maneuver to survive the audio
riot _ a silent snap count, which eliminated the need for words
beyond the huddle. To carry out the lip-synch, Chandler even bobbed
his head as if he were calling signals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We worked hard on the silent count all week,'' said Chandler's
partner in deceit, center Robbie Tobeck, who happens to be the QB's
natural-born enemy _ he's a Washington State Cougar (class of '93.)
``It really helped because it took the crowd's influence out of the
game. I don't think we had a single problem with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Teams often use silent counts for two or three series in a domed
stadium, and rarely have the cohesion to sustain it for a game. But
the Falcons used it throughout to accumulate 427 yards of offense,
including a touchdown and two field goals in the final 23 minutes
of play.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to tip your hat to Atlanta,'' said Vikings cornerback
Jimmy Hitchcock. ``They were prepared for the noise.''
</P>
<P>
   Added offensive teammate Randy Moss: ``Atlanta came here and
played a perfect game.''
</P>
<P>
   For Chandler, a third-round pick in the 1988 draft, it was a
perfect, albeit tardy, breakthrough to the big time. Always
well-praised for his skills, he nevertheless had either bad timing
or bad luck _ and occasionally a bad temper _ that produced pink
slips from Indianapolis, Tampa, Arizona, the L.A. Rams and Houston.
But at 33 and with his sixth team, he has found health, quality
teammates and some security _ in September, he signed a four-year,
$25 million extension that included a $6 million signing bonus.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been to a lot of places in this league,'' he said. ``None
of them were good _ until now.''
</P>
<P>
   Because his previous teams never won, Chandler might be the most
obscure quality quarterback in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a tough guy, and very good,'' said Falcons tight end O.J.
Santiago. ``We know that in Atlanta. If the rest of the country
doesn't know it, maybe they will after today.''
</P>
<P>
   After outdueling the more celebrated Randall Cunningham, the
Vikings, suspected of being one of the great teams of the decade,
are no longer making that misjudgment.
</P>
<P>
   Too late.
</P>
<P>
   ``To overlook our passing game was a mistake that hurt them,''
said a defiant Chandler, still taking it personally long after the
Vikings and their noisy fans felt an insult far more deeply.
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
