</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYC-KING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN THE SPIRIT OF DR. KING, PLEAS FOR COOPERATION
</HEADLINE>
   (ms) 
 By NADINE BROZAN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  NEW YORK _ The words spoken at the Abyssinian Baptist Church in
Harlem Sunday morning were probably much like those delivered from
many pulpits on the day before the federal holiday honoring the
nation's most celebrated civil rights leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``The situation of the poor in America is our plight, our
sickness,'' the speaker said, quoting a close friend and ally of
the Rev. Dr. Martin Luther King Jr. ``To be deaf to their cry is to
condemn ourselves. Martin Luther King is a voice, a vision and a
way.
</P>
<P>
   What was unexpected for a Baptist church setting became clear as
the quotation continued:
</P>
<P>
   ``I call upon every Jew to hearken to his voice, to share his
vision, to follow in his way. The whole future of America will
depend upon the impact and influence of Dr. King.''
</P>
<P>
   That call was first delivered on March 25, 1968, by Rabbi
Abraham Joshua Heschel in a talk to a meeting of rabbis 10 days
before King was assassinated. The words were reiterated Sunday by
Rabbi J. Rolando Matalon, who along with Rabbi Marcelo R. Bronstein
and 100 members of Congregation B'nai Jeshurun, the Conservative
synagogue on the Upper West Side, snapped up the limited number of
seats reserved for them at the Harlem church.
</P>
<P>
   They had come in response to an invitation issued on Jan. 9 by
the Rev. Calvin O. Butts III, pastor of the church, when he
delivered a sermon to the synagogue as a possible first step in
forging an alliance between the congregations to fight racial,
social and economic injustice.
</P>
<P>
   ``At last there is a chance, maybe not to stretch hands across
the sea but to begin to close a chasm,'' one of the synagogue's
members, E.M. Broner, a writer, said as she stood in line outside
the church Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The B'nai Jeshurun rabbis and Butts repeatedly invoked role
models for cooperation in their talks from the pulpit. They cited
King, who would have turned 70 on Jan. 15 and whose birthday
celebration provided the theme of the service, and Heschel, the
Jewish theologian who marched with King in Selma and who persuaded
him to become involved in protests against the Vietnam War.
Heschel's 26th yahrzeit, the anniversary of his death, was observed
last week.
</P>
<P>
   In his sermon, whose title, ``Moral Grandeur and Spiritual
Audacity,'' was taken from Heschel, Butts said, ``This church
celebrates Abraham Joshua Heschel, who helped to guide Martin
Luther King, and now we have the opportunity to move forward to
better the city, the state, the country, the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``Martin Luther King and Abraham Joshua Heschel were hit by the
spirit, and they joined hands. They knew the storm troopers were
out there. They knew there was a bullet that had King's name on it,
but the spirit of audacity brought them together.''
</P>
<P>
   In his talk on Jan. 9, which won a standing ovation, Butts said
of the two men he called prophets: ``It didn't matter that one was
a rabbi and one was a Christian clergyperson. What mattered was
that they shared the same experience with God and were willing to
run the risk of facing violence arm in arm in Selma on the bloody
Sunday when marchers were beaten into the ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do we have to do that again?'' he implored. ``Do we have to
stand in the face of that kind of ugliness? Eventually, if not
today, we're going to have to start walking together.''
</P>
<P>
   But will the impassioned words delivered in sermons translate
into tangible action for onetime allies whose relationship has been
sorely tested?
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of us have for a long time felt the cooling off of
black-Jewish efforts,'' Matalon said the other day. ``There was a
time when blacks and Jews collaborated in significant projects
bringing about social change. Then a number of factors divided and
separated those communities, all sorts of issues, some having to do
with affirmative action, South Africa, the Middle East and the
emergence of a vocal sector in the Jewish community that is much
more politically conservative. The majority of American Jewry fell
into silence and acquiescence. Now it is time to rebuild those
coalitions to move forward together.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert E. Pollack, a professor of biology at Columbia University
and the president of the Jewish Campus Life Fund, who described
himself as ``probably the only member of B'nai Jeshurun to know
Reverend Butts longer than I know my own rabbis,'' seemed
optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I met Reverend Butts 15 years ago when I was the dean at
Columbia College and he was the mediator to end the blockade of
Hamilton Hall protesting the investment in South Africa,'' he
recalled. ``This is not merely a political event between blacks and
Jews, but is a coming together of serious Jews and serious
Christians. This morning is a statement of shared commitment.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-18-99 0031EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
