<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-SUPER-NYT </SLUG>
  
 EDITORIAL: AN ALMOST-SUPER SUNDAY  (jw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Monday, Jan. 18:
</P>
<P>
   Super Bowl Sunday, in two weeks, will have to summon up some
heavy-duty drama to match Sunday's conference finals, which
produced one big upset and two tense, competitive games. Sadly for
New York fans, the Jets' remarkable season came to an end with a
23-10 loss to the Broncos on a cold, windy afternoon in Denver.
Repeated turnovers _ fumbles, a botched kickoff return, two
interceptions _ destroyed whatever hopes they had of reaching their
first Super Bowl in 30 years. The Jets needed a mistake-free game
to beat last year's Super Bowl champions, and they did not deliver.
</P>
<P>
   What they did deliver was a courageous defensive game and an
honorable performance under difficult conditions by Vinny
Testaverde, their quarterback. The Jets' running game disappeared,
so Testaverde threw, passing for more than 300 yards. Neither
interception was completely his fault. As for the defense, it held
the Broncos scoreless in the first half, a remarkable achievement
against a team that outscored its opponents 207-74 in the first
half in its games earlier this season. Indeed, a field goal and a
touchdown following a blocked punt gave the Jets an improbable 10-0
lead early in the second half. But it was only a matter of time
before John Elway, the Denver quarterback, and Terrell Davis, the
Broncos' magnificent running back, got their acts together. When
they did, the Jets were done.
</P>
<P>
   The day's first game, between the Atlanta Falcons and the
heavily favored Minnesota Vikings, came down to two kickers, one
named Anderson and the other Andersen, and the guy with an ``e'' in
his name was one kick better. Minnesota's Gary Anderson, who had
not missed a field goal all year, pulled one to the left late in
the fourth quarter that almost surely would have have put the game
out of reach. With 3:22 left in overtime, Morten Andersen was
successful on a virtually identical kick to give the Falcons a
30-27 victory and their first conference championship in team
history. This was a superb matchup. The Falcons kept Minnesota's
awesome passing attack under reasonable control, and gave their own
quarterback, Chris Chandler, time to operate.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons are the sixth team in the last decade for the
33-year-old Chandler, who played much of the final quarter on an
injured knee. He was one of three aging re-treads on view Sunday.
The others were two 35-year-olds, Testaverde and Randall
Cunningham, who came out of retirement and off the bench and
performed magically for the Vikings all season.
</P>
<P>
   But the oldest and best of all of them is Elway who, at 38, is
likely to retire after the Super Bowl. The oddsmakers say he will
go out a winner. As John Glenn demonstrated in a wholly different
context, age doesn't mean that you can't repeat the past.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-18-99 0032EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990118.0020 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 00:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7207 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-DEFENSE-NYT &LR;      01-18 0616
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-DEFENSE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 EDITORIAL: MORE REALISTIC DEFENSE BUDGETING  (jw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Monday, Jan. 18:
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton wants to increase military spending by $110
billion over the next six years, the first significant increase in
the defense budget since Ronald Reagan's Cold War buildup of the
mid-1980s. Congressional Republicans want to spend even more. But
soaring spending is unnecessary to assure that America's armed
forces remain strong, decently paid and appropriately equipped for
the battlefields of the 21st century. Most of what the Pentagon
legitimately needs can be paid for by trimming pork from
acquisition programs, closing unneeded bases and reducing America's
nuclear arsenal from excessive Cold War levels.
</P>
<P>
   For next year, Clinton will request $269 billion. That is $4
billion more than he originally planned to seek. But he will also
let the Pentagon retain and spend an additional $8 billion in
savings from lower than expected inflation. Although a detailed
breakdown is not yet available, the White House has already
indicated that $2.5 billion will go for well-deserved pay and
pension increases, an additional $2 billion will support
peacekeeping in Bosnia and most of the remainder will be used for
spare parts and recruiting. In the five following years, most of
the new spending will be for new weapons programs, including $7
billion to be set aside for possible later construction of a
limited missile defense system.
</P>
<P>
   In the future smart weapons will shape the battlefield and
defense priorities will include shielding vulnerable computer and
telecommunications networks and protecting civilians from
biological and chemical attack. Unfortunately, much of the new
money Clinton seeks will go to advanced fighter aircraft and
nuclear attack submarines, areas where the United States is already
far ahead of any prospective foe.
</P>
<P>
   Under the 1997 balanced-budget agreement, any increase in
defense spending must be paid for by tax increases or reductions in
domestic programs. The White House hopes to get some defense money
from a new cigarette tax. But if the Republicans approve such a
tax, the money should be used for health programs. Meanwhile, the
administration has failed to identify any domestic programs it will
cut. Some compensating savings will have to be found, and the first
place to look should be elsewhere in the defense budget. New
weapons spending should be cut back. America does not need three
separate advanced fighter plane programs. Two would be more than
enough. The production of additional attack submarines, which serve
no current military need, could be slowed.
</P>
<P>
   Congress has blocked two more rounds of base closings proposed
by the Pentagon that could save as much as $2 billion a year.
Legislators also shamelessly fatten defense budgets to benefit home
districts, last year adding $5 billion for weapons, research and
military construction the Pentagon had not requested.
</P>
<P>
   Further savings can be achieved by reducing America's nuclear
arsenal to the target level of 2,500 warheads Washington seeks in
the next arms reduction agreement with Russia. Even without a
treaty, financial pressures will lead Russia to match America's
cuts. Together, these savings could finance more than half of the
increased spending Clinton is proposing.
</P>
<P>
   The post-Cold-War world has not turned out to be as peaceful as
Americans originally hoped and the United States needs to maintain
a strong and ready military. But it should do so by reallocating
existing defense spending, not by raiding already threadbare
domestic spending programs.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
