<HEADER>
A7210 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-KING-NYT &LR;      01-18 0628
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-KING-NYT </SLUG>
  
 EDITORIAL: MARTIN LUTHER KING JR.'S AMERICA  (jw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Monday, Jan. 18:
</P>
<P>
   For many young Americans, the heroic life and tragic death of
the Rev. Dr. Martin Luther King Jr. are historical artifacts from
the turbulent 1960s, distant chapters in the multi-volume history
of the American experiment. In the decades since then, the ranks of
those with vivid memories of the human rights struggle King waged
in the South and up North have thinned. Yet neither of these
circumstances should nudge Americans toward allowing each year's
observance of his birthday to morph into another three-day get-away
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's religious ceremonies and commemorative speeches have
value in and of themselves. But in the long run, it is more
important for Americans of all classes, colors and creeds to
recommit themselves to King's unfinished human rights agenda. From
Jasper, Texas, where a black man was dragged to death behind a
pickup truck to the abyss between whites and blacks in income and
wealth, one does not have to look far to find the damage done by
intolerance and discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   It is not possible to divine how King would assess these United
States in 1999. Yet his words remind us that continuing to inch
toward a colorblind, equitable society requires so much more than
court rulings and laws. In a 1968 essay, published posthumously and
entitled ``A Testament of Hope,'' he dissected the riddle that
bedevils American society to this day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why is the issue of equality still so far from solution in
America, a nation that professes itself to be democratic,
inventive, hospitable to new ideas, rich, productive and awesomely
powerful?'' King asked. ``The problem is so tenacious because,
despite its virtues and attributes, America is deeply racist and
its democracy is flawed both economically and socially. All too
many Americans believe justice will unfold painlessly or that its
absence for black people will be tolerated tranquilly.''
</P>
<P>
   Fresh evidence of the persistence of racism is visible in the
predicament of Sen. Trent Lott, R-Miss. The Senate majority leader
has fumbled numerous opportunities to clarify his links to the
white separatist group called the Council of Conservative Citizens.
Rather than apologize for giving speeches to a racist organization
or explain why he allowed the Mississippi group to use his name, he
chose the path of obfuscation.
</P>
<P>
   Through a spokesman, Lott said he had ``no firsthand knowledge''
of the CCC's thinly veiled white supremacist agenda. Lott's uncle,
Arnie Watson, said otherwise. Watson told The Times' John Kifner
last week that his nephew, the senator, was ``an honorary member''
of the group and had spoken at its meetings. Others with ties to
this group include Gov. Kirk Fordice of Mississippi and Sen. Jesse
Helms of North Carolina, both Republicans. Rep. Bob Barr, R-Ga.,
has also been criticized for speaking before the group.
</P>
<P>
   After a month of questions, Lott released a statement that
broadly condemned bigotry, declaring, ``I have made my condemnation
of the white supremacist and racist view of this group, or any
group, clear. . . .'' His shifting explanations suggest that he
knew it was wrong to appear before the group, but did so to curry
favor and political support. To preserve respect for his office,
Lott needs to repudiate the CCC, a direct descendant of the
Citizens Councils that opposed the Supreme Court's 1954 school
desegregation decision. Until he does so, he will inevitably raise
questions about his fairness in leading the U.S. Senate, an
institution that ought to be wholeheartedly committed to Martin
Luther King's unfinished agenda.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
