<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-GIFFORD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAMES GIFFORD, 56, A SPOKESMAN FOR BUSINESS AND CHARITY GROUPS
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By WOLFGANG SAXON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ James Priest Gifford, a political strategist,
spokesman and lobbyist for New York businesses and institutions,
died in Manhattan on Jan. 9. He was 56 and lived on the East Side.
</P>
<P>
   He suffered a heart attack while on a midtown shopping trip,
said Evangeline Binder, vice president of Hudson Strategies Inc.
Dr. Gifford, its president, founded the company last year. It
represented businesses and other clients in their dealings with New
York City and New York State.
</P>
<P>
   Clients who sought his expertise in public policy included the
Chase Manhattan Bank, the Brooklyn Museum of Art, Trinity Church
and the Nonprofit Coordinating Committee of New York, of which he
was a founding board member. The committee, formed in 1983, is a
consortium of more than 800 nonprofit organizations; he sat on
several of their boards.
</P>
<P>
   He was a former executive vice president of the New York Chamber
of Commerce and Industry as well as the New York City Partnership,
a business alliance affiliated with it. He held leading posts in
both organizations from 1983 to 1996, acting as lobbyist and chief
spokesman before city, state and Federal offices.
</P>
<P>
   Gifford was born in Mechanicsburg, Pa. He graduated in 1963 from
Hamilton College in Clinton, N.Y., and received his M.A. (1965) and
Ph.D. (1970) degrees in political science and public administration
at Columbia University. He taught political science at the State
University at Stony Brook, Jersey City State College and Rutgers
University.
</P>
<P>
   He joined the faculty of City University's John Jay College of
Criminal Justice in 1970, rising to acting chairman of the
department of government. In 1978, Frank J. Macchiarola, Chancellor
of the New York City Board of Education, named him a special
assistant. He earned his spurs as a lobbyist and spokesman while
serving as the board's legislative representative from 1978 to
1981.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, he was chairman of the New York City Youth
Board; a trustee of Sailors' Snug Harbor, a seamen's retirement
home; director of the New York Business Group on Health, and
co-chairman of the New York City Human Services Action Group
Steering Committee.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by a sister, Judith Neunzig of Bethlehem, Pa.,
and his wife, Karen Gifford of Manhattan, from whom he was
separated.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-18-99 0040EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
