<SLUG> BC-OBIT-GOSSI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TETHERED SATELLITES, DIES AT 74 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Italy, Russia, Mass., Texas ) DR. MARIO GROSSI, DEVELOPER OF By WOLFGANG SAXON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dr. Mario Dario Grossi, a radio physicist and engineer who
developed the concept of tethered satellites as well as the
hardware that made such free-flying space maneuvers possible, died
Jan. 11 at Boston Medical Center in Boston. He was 74 and lived in
Cambridge, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was congestive heart failure, his family said.
</P>
<P>
   Teaming with a colleague, Dr. Giuseppe Colombo, Grossi did much
of his work at the Harvard-Smithsonian Center for Astrophysics,
where he had an office to work on the tether project. Until 1995 he
was also a consulting engineer for the Raytheon Company in
Cambridge.
</P>
<P>
   Grossi first approached the National Aeronautics and Space
Administration with the idea of tethered space orbiters in 1972. He
and Colombo of the University of Padua studied and tested its
feasibility, and NASA issued the contract to build a system in
1982.
</P>
<P>
   It took another 10 years for the space shuttle Atlantis to put
the tether to the real test in space, in July 1992, and it worked.
The shuttle crew reeled out a half-ton satellite of the Italian
Space Agency dangling on a spaghetti-thin cord 12 miles long.
</P>
<P>
   The purpose was to place the spherical research satellite, five
feet in diameter, high above the shuttle. An Italian
astronaut-engineer, Franco Malerba, oversaw the operation from the
shuttle cabin as the sphere flew away and, hours later, was reeled
back in.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to its scientific harvest, the successful flight
provided data on how long wire tethers could be used in building
space stations and operating instrument-laden satellites far from
the shuttle.
</P>
<P>
   Mario Grossi was born in Tuscany. He received a doctorate in
radio engineering at the University of Pisa in 1948 and a degree in
microwave physics at a center in Florence. He worked as a research
and design engineer in Italy before he joined Raytheon's Equipment
and Systems Division in 1958 as an engineer.
</P>
<P>
   The next year, he also became associated with the Smithsonian
Observatory and accepted the position of research associate at the
Harvard College Observatory. His investigations covered many areas
in radio physics and engineering and contributed to various NASA
projects besides the tethering.
</P>
<P>
   Grossi also engaged in humanitarian work, like helping dissident
Jewish scientists leave the Soviet Union. In 1996, the president of
Italy presented him with the country's Gold Medal for the
Betterment of Science and Culture.
</P>
<P>
   Grossi's survivors include his wife of 42 years, Adele Sangi
Grossi; a daughter, Marina Grossi of Boston; a son, Fabio, of
Grapevine, Texas, and two granddaughters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-18-99 0043EST &QL; 
