</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-RYAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FATE GIVES ANDERSON SWIFT KICK 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ This was right out of Sophocles or Aeschylus or
whomever happens to be your favorite Greek playwright.
</P>
<P>
   It was all about gods and fates and mortality. The moral of the
story: do away with perfection before it comes back to bite you in
the you-know-what.
</P>
<P>
   Entering Sunday's NFC Championship Game, Minnesota Vikings
kicker Gary Anderson was perfect for the entire season. He had been
good on 37 of 37 field goal attempts (35 in the regular season and
two last week in a 41-21 victory over the Arizona Cardinals). He
had been 59 for 59 on extra points.
</P>
<P>
   That's why any intelligent Vikings fan should have been very
nervous when Mr. Anderson set up for a 38-yard field goal that
would have given the team a 10-point lead over the Atlanta Falcons
with 2:07 remaining in the fourth quarter. This is the NFL, and you
just don't do perfect in the NFL. You can be almost perfect. You
can be real good. You can be real, real good. But in the history of
this league no one ever has gone through a season without missing
at least one field goal attempt.
</P>
<P>
   To get this far in the season without a miss is to thumb your
nose at the fates. And so when the snap came from center Mike
Morris to holder Mitch Berger it was ball down, kick up and _ OH
NO! IT'S A HALF-FOOT WIDE TO THE LEFT!
</P>
<P>
   Like anyone should have been surprised.
</P>
<P>
   You know the rest. You know that the feisty Falcons drove 71
yards in eight plays, tying the score at 27 on a 16-yard Chris
Chandler-to-Terance Mathis pass with 57 seconds left and that in
overtime Atlanta's Morten Andersen, no stranger to late-game
boo-boos (ask anyone in Jacksonville), nailed a field goal from the
exact same spot on the field to give Atlanta a 30-27 win and send
the Falcons to the Super Bowl for the first time in history.
</P>
<P>
   The men in question have been in just about every situation
during their lengthy careers. Anderson, a native of South Africa,
is 39. This is his 17th year in the league. Andersen, 38, is
likewise in his 17th year. Each has had a Hall of Fame career. That
such a high-stakes game should come down to a matter of which one
could make a 38-yard field goal is, well, I really don't know.
Football, I guess.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never saw it,'' said Anderson. ``I was buried under a couple
of guys. Obviously, there are no words to describe how disappointed
I am.''
</P>
<P>
   This was not exactly Anderson's happiest day in football, but he
faced the media hordes like a professional and a gentleman. He must
have used variations on the word ``disappoint'' a half-dozen times
in the span of two minutes, but what else could he say? He never
has wanted to make a field goal more in his life. A 10-point lead
with two minutes and change left would have put the game away. Now
the Vikings are going home.
</P>
<P>
   He swore he never had dwelled on the fact that he had been
perfect. He certainly never had entertained notions of missing an
unneeded field goal on purpose merely to satisfy the gods. ``It's
just part of field goal kicking,'' he said with a sigh. ``It's the
way kicking goes. You try to approach every kick the same.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, I feel bad for him,'' said Andersen. ``I know how
he must feel.''
</P>
<P>
   Andersen also claims he hadn't thought much about the
ramifications of his counterpart's perfect status entering the
game. To Morten Andersen, what Gary Anderson was doing made perfect
sense, if you'll pardon the expression.
</P>
<P>
   ``It never crossed my mind (that Anderson was due for a miss),''
claimed Andersen. ``Gary is just so solid.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Andersen, whose own 38-yarder was right down Broadway, he
said he was very calm. ``I was just waiting patiently for my
chance,'' he said. ``You just have to let these situations come to
you. You can't force anything. I find that patience really helps in
these situations.''
</P>
<P>
   Now then. Can we accurately say that Gary Anderson lost the game
for his team? Certainly not. He could have clinched it; that's all.
The Minnesota defense had to hold in what was Atlanta's most
important possession, and it didn't. The most famous offense in the
league scored 7 points in the second half. As in any such game,
there were the usual litanies of shouldas and couldas and wouldas,
of turnovers and dropped passes and missed assignments and
inefficient tackling and all sorts of human imperfections that both
preceded and followed Gary Anderson's brush with destiny.
</P>
<P>
   And still ... it was set up for the perfect kicker to deliver
the goods. He was 23 for 23 outside the 30 during the regular
season. He was kicking, as usual, on turf, the kicker's best
friend. He had his usual snapper and his usual holder. He didn't
say anything about the snap or the hold being bad. He just ...
</P>
<P>
   Missed.
</P>
<P>
   No one expected him to miss _ on either side. I'm sure Atlanta
coach Dan Reeves figured his team's wonderful ride was over as
Anderson trotted onto the field. ``A guy who hadn't missed all year
missed and gave us a chance to win it,'' said the Falcons mentor.
</P>
<P>
   The Vikings won the toss at the start of overtime, and so most
everyone figured they would make a few first downs and Gary
Anderson would have a chance to redeem himself. Unfortunately, he's
still waiting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Randall Cunningham came over and said, `Don't worry; you'll
get another chance,''' said Anderson. That was certainly a logical
assumption and a very good bet. But the best Minnesota could do in
the overtime was get to its 42. Gary Anderson is very good, but
neither he nor anyone else has a 75-yard field goal in him.
</P>
<P>
   You say life will go on, but Gary Anderson is 39. Was this his
final chance to be kicking in front of the entire nation on Super
Sunday? Very likely. ``That's why it's so disappointing,'' he said.
``We had such a great year. But that's what field goal kicking is
all about. You have to be a man about it. This is your job, to line
up and fire that field goal through. With the year we've had, not
to make it to the Super Bowl is bitterly disappointing.''
</P>
<P>
   Gary Anderson made no excuses. He kicked the ball the way he
usually does, but this one time the ball went about a half-foot
wide. All it goes to show is that no one is perfect. Not now, not
ever.
</P>
<P>
   You just can't fool with the fates.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
