<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-PANTHERS-BURE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PANTHERS OBTAIN BURE IN A SEVEN-PLAYER TRADE
</HEADLINE>
   (ms) 
 By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pavel Bure refused to return to Vancouver this season and forced
the Canucks to trade him. The Rangers and the Islanders were among
the teams bidding for The Russian Rocket, one of the elite hockey
players in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Bure will play in New York twice this week, but not in a
home-team uniform. The 27-year-old right wing is scheduled to
appear at the Nassau Coliseum on Wednesday and in Madison Square
Garden on Thursday as a member of the Florida Panthers.
</P>
<P>
   They obtained Bure Sunday in a multiplayer deal that may be the
National Hockey League's most significant trade since Edmonton sent
Wayne Gretzky to Los Angeles in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's fast and exciting, and he's a guy who gets points,'' said
Bryan Murray, general manager of the Panthers. ``It's something we
needed now.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers were among the final teams contacted by Brian Burke,
the Vancouver general manager, before he concluded the trade. Burke
wanted the rookie center Manny Malhotra from the Rangers as part of
any package.
</P>
<P>
   Burke said he asked the Rangers' general manager, Neil Smith:
``Is Malhotra definitely out of the question?'' Smith replied:
``He's definitely out.'' At that point, Burke told Smith, ``There
isn't much left to talk about.'' Even with Malhotra, Burke added,
the Rangers' package might not have been better than the Florida
offer.
</P>
<P>
   The most important player going from the Panthers to Vancouver
is Ed Jovanovski, 22, a big defenseman in his fourth season. Also
involved were center Dave Gagner, goalie Kevin Weekes and left wing
Mike Brown.
</P>
<P>
   Defensemen Bret Hedican and Brad Ference join Bure in going from
the Canucks to the Panthers. In addition, the Canucks will get
Florida's first-round draft choice in either 1999 or 2000. When
that happens, the Panthers will get a third-round pick from
Vancouver.
</P>
<P>
   Bure has been living in Moscow this season and working out with
a team there. The Panthers said he will not play in Monday's home
game against Buffalo but will report to the team Tuesday. Bure led
the Russian Olympic team to a silver medal last winter at Nagano,
Japan. In NHL play, he scored 51 goals and totaled 90 points over
all, tied for third in both categories.
</P>
<P>
   Although he had one year remaining on his contract, Bure refused
to report to the Canucks for his eighth season for reasons he has
not discussed publicly. He was to make $8 million this season.
Unless he signs an extension with the Panthers, Bure will be a
restricted, Group 2 free agent this summer. Jovanovski's contract
also is in its final season.
</P>
<P>
   A fast skater with a hard, accurate shot, Bure is one of the few
players in the 27-team league with the charisma to sell tickets at
home and on the road. By acquiring him, the Panthers could become a
threat to win the Southeast Division and contend in the Stanley Cup
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Currently 15-15-11, the Panthers are second in their division,
four points behind Carolina. In the Eastern Conference, they are
tied for ninth place; eight teams from each conference make the
playoffs. Divisional winners get automatic berths.
</P>
<P>
   Burke said Sunday that Bure told him he resented the Canucks'
ownership and management for not backing him more vociferously when
people questioned Bure's back injury, and for accusing him of
threatening not to play in the 1994 Stanley Cup finals against the
Rangers unless the Canucks negotiated a new contract immediately.
Burke said he explained to Bure that the Canucks have different
owners and management now, but that did not sway him.
</P>
<P>
   Early this season, Burke talked to Mike Milbury, the coach and
general manager of the Islanders, about Zigmund Palffy, who was
without a contract and not playing at the time. Burke said he spoke
with Milbury again last week but nothing came of it.
</P>
<P>
   The Canucks (14-23-5) are currently out of the playoff picture
under Coach Mike Keenan and captain Mark Messier, who led the
Rangers to the 1994 Cup. Burke said Sunday he is aware that Messier
might not be happy with the immediate returns in the deal. ``My
guess is he's not ecstatic,'' Burke said. But he added that he told
Messier that Messier is just a player, not a personnel director, in
his 20th season, with one year left on his contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am mindful of the clock ticking on Mess,'' Burke said. ``But
this is the best proposal we received short-term.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
