<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 00:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7226 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-FALCONS-VIKINGS-B     01-18 1043
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-VIKINGS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ATLANTA REACHES FIRST SUPER BOWL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ Long after Morten Andersen had hit a 38-yard field
goal to kick one of the most futile franchises in NFL history into
the grandest surprise of all for Dixie, the Super Bowl, Gary
Anderson still was sitting in the Vikings Lounge atop the
Metrodome.
</P>
<P>
   The scene could have been from a wake. Friend after friend came
by to pat the Vikings kicker on the shoulder. Teammate after
teammate came by to whisper comforting words, quarterback Randall
Cunningham talking to Anderson at length.
</P>
<P>
   ``There just can't be words to describe the disappointment I'm
feeling,'' said Anderson, ``especially with the season we had.''
Then, when he was left alone, Anderson crossed his arms against his
chest and stared into the void.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta Falcons advanced to the Super Bowl two weeks hence
in Miami with a 30-27 win over the Vikings in overtime Sunday, a
game that may have been one for the ages. For sure, though, the
shocking loss by the 16-1 Vikings will heat the cold and brutal
winters of Minnesota with debate for decades to come.
</P>
<P>
   That's because Anderson, the first NFL kicker to be perfect
during a season, missed a 38-yarder with little more than two
minutes to play, letting the Falcons come back and tie the game and
then win it in OT.
</P>
<P>
   Said exuberant Falcons safety Eugene Robinson, ``When Anderson
missed, I ran up up to Chris Chandler (the Atlanta quarterback) and
I said, `Chris, that's it, he missed it. Now we have a chance, now
you have a chance.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``No question, if he makes that field goal, it was going to be
much, much harder for us to win,'' said Chandler of Anderson's miss
with Minnesota leading, 27-20. ``And when he missed it, the whole
sideline erupted as if we just won the game. It gave us a new
life.''
</P>
<P>
   Chandler took over on his 29-yard line with 2:07 to play, and
moved the Falcons 71 yards, but not without a few frights. Such as
when he scrambled for 9 yards with 1:47 left, banged his knee, and
had to use a timeout he did not wish to use to limp to the
sideline.
</P>
<P>
   ``I banged the inside of my knee,'' he said. ``I'm sure all of
you have done it, where you hit that inside part of your knee and
it really hurts.''
</P>
<P>
   But Chandler stayed in the game, and a couple of plays later
fired a pass to the inside of the field toward Terance Mathis, a
pass virtually identical to one Mathis had dropped for a TD earlier
in the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tried the exact same route where one of their guys had
gotten a hand on it,'' said Chandler of the ball that this time
went for a 16-yard score. ``They flushed me from my left and I
rolled to my right _ at that point, it was just schoolyard football
_ and I looked and saw Terance coming into the hole and I just
threw it as hard as I could.''
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons' Andersen had to try the extra point for the tie
twice, the Vikings being offside the first time. Andersen was just
as good on his second try.
</P>
<P>
   With the Vikings tied at 27 with 57 seconds left, the true
shocker came next. Cunningham scrambled for 7 yards from his 20,
then threw incomplete on a bomb to Randy Moss.
</P>
<P>
   On third down, with 30 seconds left, only 40 or so yards from
field goal range, Vikings coach Dennis Green waved the white flag
for the rest of regulation time, instructing Cunningham to take a
knee. There was stunned silence in the Metrodome, and all
throughout football, as the best offense in the league decided not
to take a chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll tell you why they took a knee then,'' said Atlanta
defensive lineman Chuck Smith. ``They were afraid, that's why. They
were afraid of me doing what I did just before the half, stripping
the ball from Cunningham.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Smith had turned the game around for his team in the
second quarter. The Vikings were leading, 20-7, and were on the
move when Smith cleanly beat star tackle Todd Steussie and caused
Cunningham to fumble at his 14. One play later, Chandler hit Mathis
for a TD and Atlanta was still breathing, trailing only 20-14.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're down to 30 seconds, then you need to take two good
downs, and if you don't have a first down by then, then you'd
better move on and go the other way,'' said Green of his decision
to run out the clock. ``We had had troubles in protection schemes
and we had a couple of fumbles. We took two good shots at it and
hoped to get it done. We didn't. It did work to our favor. We
(received) the kick (in overtime), we got the return, but we just
didn't score with it.''
</P>
<P>
   But Green's decision not to go after the victory at the end of
regulation had sent a clear signal. ``They were saying they didn't
have to try and score then,'' said Robinson. ``They were saying
they just had to come out in OT and they'd score on our defense.
Well, they're not the first ones not to respect us, and they're not
the last ones who'll pay the price.''
</P>
<P>
   On his first drive in OT, Cunningham was short-arming his
passes. On Chandler's first drive in OT, he looked like a triplet
to Jake Plummer and Scott Zolak.
</P>
<P>
   So it was that Minnesota could get only two first downs despite
having its hands on the ball twice. Then, on Atlanta's second OT
chance, starting from its 9, Chandler was immense. Twice he found
tight end O.J. Santiago for huge gains, one a 15-yarder and the
next a 26-yarder on which Santiago beat linebacker Bobby Houston to
get it to the Vikings 48.
</P>
<P>
   ``I took it personal when they said all they had to do was stop
the run,'' said Chandler, the son-in-law of former NFL great John
Brodie. ``I know we have a passing game, too, and you can't think
if you just stop Jamal Anderson you're going to beat us. So I had
more motivation, a little more zeal coming into this game. And
ending it.''
</P>
<P>
   Reeves was so proud of the performance by the well-traveled
Chandler that he told his QB his effort ``ranks right up there with
any of the big-time quarterbacks.''
</P>
<P>
   In time, as Jamal Anderson toted the ball three straight times
into field goal position, the Vikings' Anderson kept pacing the
sideline. And when the Falcons' Andersen booted the ball, the
Metrodome suddenly was silent. So silent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
