<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PREDATORS NO LONGER THE PREY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The Bruins are expected to break their three-game
winless streak when they meet Nashville Monday. In fact, nearly
every NHL team expects to end its misfortune or continue its good
fortune when it meets the expansion Predators.
</P>
<P>
   But that perception seems to be changing as Nashville remains in
playoff contention.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time a team loses to us, you would think the world ended
for them,'' Nashville coach Barry Trotz said Sunday. ``I'm upset
that teams think that way. We're no different than anyone else. Our
players look for respect. Every night we go out and we have to earn
respect.''
</P>
<P>
   Nashville has mostly achieved that, despite an occasional 8-0
loss to Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Philadelphia game (last Monday) was one of those nights
where they scored on every power-play shot,'' Trotz said. ``They
also scored twice in the last minute and a half when our goaltender
let in goals that shouldn't happen at this level.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were able to break the Philadelphia trap and get some
two-on-ones, but we just couldn't convert. It was a long night, but
instead of beating ourselves up over it, we went over what we did
well and what we didn't do well.
</P>
<P>
   ``We try to learn from every game and go on. If we had dwelled
on that game too long, it would have been a long year. Every second
day, we are preparing for a team we don't match up against, and we
have to rely on work ethic, good team play, good goaltending to
stay competitive.''
</P>
<P>
   The formula has produced impressive wins over Detroit and
Phoenix recently, and Nashville's 34 points in 42 games has it in
third place in the Central Division.
</P>
<P>
   Trotz and general manager Dave Poile emphasized ``character and
quickness'' in building the team. They brought in Tom Fitzgerald as
captain, drawing on his experience with Florida's expansion team in
1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``We weren't sure what to expect,'' center Scott Walker said.
``Tom had been through it before and he told us that if we relied
on each other, expected a lot from each other, worked hard and
played hard, we would have a lot of fun. People would be willing to
give us a break if we gave an honest effort. It's not fun when you
are losing 8-0, but we've beaten some good teams and it's not like
we're sacrificial lambs.''
</P>
<P>
   Nashville has not been at full strength, though.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, we've been going with our No. 2 and 3 goaltenders
and with six or seven guys out of the lineup and we keep plodding
along and getting some wins,'' Trotz said. ``In the past, some
expansion teams would probably have crumbled, but we've stayed
together. Sometimes you have to look past the names on the jerseys.
Some players who have name value in the league are not much
different than the guys we have, who don't have the name value. You
might have never heard of them, but they do a great job.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in the playoff race and I don't think anybody expected
that. From Day 1, our expectations have been to be competitive on a
nightly basis, and so far we've attained that. Secondly, we wanted
to win on a consistent basis. Thirdly, we want to make the
playoffs. On the ice, we don't match up with any team. Every team
is more experienced, bigger, or they have more skill. There are not
a lot of areas we can say we're better. But we work hard and we've
gotten good goaltending and done the simple things.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
