<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SHAUGHNESSY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TUNA NO LONGER ON A ROLL 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ With just under 12 minutes to play in the third quarter
Sunday, the Jets were ahead of the Denver Broncos, 10-0, and 75,482
orange zealots were sitting on their hands as the Broncos took over
on their 36-yard line.
</P>
<P>
   Standing on the visitors' sideline, the Great White Tuna had to
be feeling pretty good. His defensive coordinator, Bill Belichick,
had taken Terrell Davis out of the game and the Jets were on the
brink of making their first trip to the Super Bowl in three
decades, just two years after going 1-15.
</P>
<P>
   Then it unraveled in a hellish hail of blown coverages, fumbles,
interceptions, and stupid mistakes. For Bill Parcells, it must have
felt a little like Desmond Howard Redux as the Broncos seized
control with a 20-point third-quarter blitz en route to a 23-10 AFC
Championship Game victory and a return ticket to the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   At game's end, Parcells looked like Humphrey Bogart playing Rick
Blaine _ standing on the train platform in Paris, rain streaming
off his hat as he waited for a woman who wasn't coming.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a good team,'' the former Patriots coach said after
shaking the hand of Denver head man Mike Shanahan. ``I don't think
we can do the things we did and expect to win a championship game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we had 'em on the ropes in the first half (which ended
with the Jets leading, 3-0). Then we went to sleep. Victor Green
went to sleep. That's that. It's disappointing.''
</P>
<P>
   This would have been an upset of monstrous proportions. The
Broncos are 16-2, defending Super Bowl champs, and haven't lost a
home game in two seasons (19-0). They were 9-point favorites
against a Jets team that two years ago was the laughingstock of the
NFL.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Parcells thought he might be able to come in here and
steal one with inferior talent, and for 33 minutes he was looking
pretty good.
</P>
<P>
   But the mistakes were too much to overcome, especially against a
team of Denver's caliber. This was a game in which Curtis Martin
fumbled to give the Broncos possession near midfield. It was a game
in which the always-reliable Keith Byars (another ex-Patriot)
fumbled when it looked like the Jets were streaking toward a
second-quarter touchdown. It was a game in which Jets strong safety
Green ``fell asleep,'' getting beaten on a long pass play that
eventually allowed the Broncos to get on the scoreboard in the
third quarter. And it was a game in which none of the Jets bothered
to pick up a Denver kickoff, which resulted in a Broncos recovery
that led to a 10-10 tie (imagine what we'd all say if Pete
Carroll's team did that).
</P>
<P>
   Before it was over there would be another Jet fumble (four lost
in all), a couple of Vinny Testaverde late-game, desperation
interceptions, and a lot of Bronco-mania in honor of what likely
was King John Elway's last home game.
</P>
<P>
   And the Jets went home. Disappointed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told 'em I was proud of a lot of things they accomplished
this year,'' said Parcells. ``I thought we did a good job in many
areas. But it's foolish to be told you can pick up where you left
off next season. You have to go back and start where we started. I
hope to get back to this game with a different perception of what
it takes to win it.''
</P>
<P>
   Peppered with questions about the turnovers, dumb mistakes, and
disappointment, Parcells could not help but remind the media,
``Look, there's not anybody standing there that thought we'd be
here talking about this. Not one.''
</P>
<P>
   When a well-meaning reporter asked about the ``baby steps'' it
takes to get to a championship level, the Tuna said, ``This wasn't
baby steps. This was a quantum leap for this team, about as far as
you can jump. I think it compares favorably with any team in
history over a two-year period. I'm not saying that from an
egotistical standpoint, but from an accomplishment standpoint on
the players' part.''
</P>
<P>
   And so the Super Bowl will go on without him. Instead of two
weeks of Tuna and Dan Reeves, a pair of former Giant coaches
squaring off, we'll have two weeks of Reeves vs. Mike Shanahan, the
once and present Broncos coaches. While Shanahan works eight days a
week to prepare for the Falcons, Parcells will stack some doo-wop
cassettes in the front seat of his Caddy, and hit the Jersey
Turnpike, bound for Palm Beach. He won't have an opportunity to
ruin Bob Kraft's Super Bowl week for the second time in three
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing too much else, fellas,'' he said as he left the
podium. ``I'm a little tired.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
