<SLUG> BC-TEN-AUSTRALIAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH SAMPRAS OUT, THE AUSTRALIAN OPEN IS WIDE OPEN
</HEADLINE>
 - OPEN-NYT   (ms) 
 By CHRISTOPHER CLAREY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MELBOURNE, Australia _ A weary Pete Sampras decided to skip the
Southern Hemisphere this month. Others will have to swat away the
flies, pull their caps low in the dry heat and withstand the bump
and grind of three-of-five-set tennis on the rubberized hardcourt
surface at Melbourne Park, which can make young joints feel like
older joints.
</P>
<P>
   In Sampras' opinion the tennis season is too long, and he has
shortened it by choosing, surprisingly, not to chase Roy Emerson's
record of 12 Grand Slam singles titles on Emerson's turf at the
Australian Open. Sampras' rivals, several of whom played more
matches than he did last year, would surely relish extended
vacations of their own. But the other 29 men in the top 30 are all
back at work, and when play begins here on Monday, there will be no
one man to beat.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the best player in the world doesn't show up to a Grand
Slam,'' said Mark Philippoussis of Australia, ``it's a big
opportunity for everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   The No. 1 ranking is also there for the taking, but not everyone
with a big reputation appears poised to seize the opportunity.
Marcelo Rios, the left-handed Chilean who temporarily bumped
Sampras out of the top slot last year, is nursing a sore leg and
back, and had to default from his most recent tournament in
Auckland, New Zealand. Patrick Rafter, the two-time defending U.S.
Open champion, has responded to the massive support and interest he
generates in his native Australia by losing early in his first two
tournaments this year. After cutting his 1998 season short in
November to rest and rehabilitate a sore knee, Rafter has looked
more rusty than fresh and more awkward than at home under a
powerful microscope.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, it's not a physical thing, it's definitely a mental
thing having to deal with the expectations all the time,'' said
Rafter, who has yet to reach the quarterfinals at his national
championships.
</P>
<P>
   Petr Korda, last year's winner here, had such a miserable second
half of the season that he is unseeded, and now he must defend his
title as he continues to defend his reputation after a positive
test for the steroid nandrolone. More Korda scissor kicks on the
final Sunday appear unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   Andre Agassi, another former champion here, who can still
generate as much controlled pace from the baseline as anyone, has
not advanced past the fourth round in a Grand Slam event since 1996
and is bearing an increasingly strong resemblance to a
best-of-three-set player. But when fit and motivated, as he is now,
Agassi cannot be discounted; not with his timing and returns. ``I
feel more ready now than I have in a long time,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   If there is a slight favorite among the men, it is Alex
Corretja, the Spaniard who won the ATP Tour Championship in Germany
in late November and is now ranked third behind Sampras and Rios
(though he lost to the American Todd Martin, another player in fine
fettle, in the final of last week's ATP event in Sydney). Corretja,
who was to play his first-round match against Takao Suzuki of Japan
early Monday, is striking his groundstrokes and passing shots with
enormous confidence and attacking more frequently. His game is
well-suited to the high bounce that balls take off the Rebound Ace
surface here, and he has an excellent early draw, but he has never
won a Grand Slam event or made it past the third round in
Melbourne, and like Sampras, he played a great deal of tennis down
the stretch in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Among them, the 16 seeded men have won a total of eight Grand
Slam singles titles: three fewer than Sampras, and 13 fewer than
Steffi Graf, who has returned to Melbourne after a one-year hiatus
and is in good spirits and, more important for her, good health.
</P>
<P>
   The last time Graf's longtime rival Monica Seles played at
Melbourne Park, it was still known as Flinders Park. That was in
1996. She won the tournament, just as she had on her three previous
visits. Her career record in the Australian Open is 28-0, but she
will play here without her Australian coach, Gavin Hopper, with
whom she split late last year after a brief but relatively fruitful
partnership during which she reached the French Open final.
</P>
<P>
   Seles will face a qualifier in the first round. Her fellow
American Lindsay Davenport, seeded first for the first time at a
Grand Slam event, drew Gala Leon Garcia of Spain but has bigger
potential hurdles to clear in the third round, where Lisa Raymond
could be lurking, and in the quarterfinals, where fifth-seeded
Venus Williams should be lurking. But if the 6-foot-2-inch
Davenport, who took over the No. 1 ranking in October, continues to
play as confidently and aggressively as she did in beating Martina
Hingis in straight sets in Saturday's final in Sydney, the hurdles
will start to seem smaller.
</P>
<P>
   The Davenport-Hingis rivalry is now tied at 7-7, and Davenport
holds a 6-3 edge on hardcourts, the surface she grew up with in
Southern California. But Hingis is the two-time defending champion
here. She will play Lilia Osterloh of the United States in the
first round and could face the promising 15-year-old Australian
Jelena Dokic in the third round. Dokic, the 1998 U.S. Open junior
champion, defeated Arantxa Sanchez Vicario in the Hopeman Cup
earlier this month, giving Australians a hint that they might have
a future force in the women's game to complement Rafter and
Philippoussis in the men's.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-18-99 0052EST &QL; 
