u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-FALCONS-ROBINSON-     01-18 0615
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-ROBINSON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THERE'S A JUMP IN ROBINSON'S STEP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ When Morten Andersen's kick had sailed between the
uprights, when the Atlanta Falcons jumped onto a platform at
midfield to accept the NFC title trophy and, of course, do their
``Dirty Bird'' dance, Eugene Robinson finally began running off the
Metrodome field.
</P>
<P>
   From time to time, the Atlanta safety would stop, but his mouth
never did.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got a solid team here, man,'' Robinson shouted. ``We got a
bona fide team here that can win. We can flat out play and nobody
would ever recognize that. Nobody, I say. Nobody.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson was giving the familiar football player's lament _
``Nobody respects us'' _ when suddenly the safety who had been to
the last two Super Bowls with Green Bay began blurting out, ``The
Patriots ... the Patriots were the same way.''
</P>
<P>
   Excuse me? The Patriots are home by the hearth, no longer
playing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hostile territory here, man, and we come right in and do it,''
Robinson shouted. ``This reminds me of the Patriots game when we
went into the Patriots and we played them tough. Man, we almost
dismantled the Patriots (winning, 41-10). So we played the Patriots
tough. And the same hostile atmosphere that the Patriots had was
here. The same hostile atmosphere existed here. And we didn't give
up, not even when it was 20-7 (Vikings) in first half.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor did Robinson give up on his biggest play of the game, when
Vikings quarterback Randall Cunningham threw a ball 65 yards in
overtime toward Randy Moss. The ball seemed to hang in the
Metrodome atmosphere, with Moss and Robinson at the Atlanta 15,
ready for the jump ball that just might decide each other's season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somehow I come up and make plays,'' said Robinson, his mouth
still moving very swiftly. ``Somehow I come up and keep on making
plays.''
</P>
<P>
   But this play had to be made, or the season almost certainly
would be over. Moss, the Vikings' brilliant rookie, had outjumped
many a defensive back in similar situations all season, coming down
with the ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, Moss is faster than me, yeah, Moss can outjump me,''
shouted Robinson. ``I'll concede that. I'll give him that. But when
that ball was in the air, I just said, `I'm just going to play that
ball.' All my career, all I ever did was play the ball, and so I
made up my mind I'd play the ball and I'd meet Moss at the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   This was football at its ultimate. The uncoverable rookie, the
receiver who just may become one of the best in football history,
staring up at that ball with Robinson, the canny veteran who had
come out of Hartford, gone to Colgate, somehow found his way into
the NFL, and become one of the best. Not just the ball, but the
season, hung in the balance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, Moss may be faster than me but he may be too fast,''
said Robinson. ``We had studied the film and we'd seen that Randall
tends to underthrow Moss because of Moss's speed. And he underthrew
him this time, too. It worked for me that Moss has that speed
because Randall couldn't get him the ball and I had time to
react.''
</P>
<P>
   Moss and Robinson jumped for the ball. It was exquisite. Each
got their hands on it. There was a hush in the Metrodome. Who would
come down with it? The ball fell to the turf. The Vikings punted.
Atlanta soon would have its winning field goal. Once again, Eugene
Robinson had made the play. And, because of that play, Eugene
Robinson would be going to his third straight Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who'd have thunk it?'' Robinson blurted. ``The Dirty Birds
going to the Super Bowl. Who'd have thunk it?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
