<HEADLINE>
BRUINS' RECRUITS COULD GO TO HEAD OF CLASS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The UCLA Bruins are in position to land another
top-ranked recruiting class, with a half-dozen elite players
expected to commit this month.
</P>
<P>
   The latest to commit is Dallas-area receiver Ryan Smith, who has
been compared in size and style to Danny Farmer. He's also a former
Westlake Village resident and close friends with Westlake tight end
_ and UCLA recruit _ Mike Seidman.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins have 11 oral commitments, including Smith, leaving 10
unclaimed scholarships. The names to watch in coming weeks are:
</P>
<P>
   __ Seidman, one of the nation's top tight ends. He has narrowed
his choices to UCLA and USC. Recruiting insiders believe he'll sign
with the Bruins.
</P>
<P>
   __ San Jose's Marcus Reese, the top-ranked linebacker in the
state. Sources said he has given the Bruins a soft commitment and
will make it official as early as today.
</P>
<P>
   __ Steve Sanchez, a 280-pound defensive lineman from Visalia and
the nephew of former UCLA cornerback Lupe Sanchez. Steve Sanchez
has given Cal a preliminary commitment but is reconsidering.
</P>
<P>
   __ Fresno cornerback Ricky Manning, whose finalists include
UCLA, USC, Michigan and Notre Dame.
</P>
<P>
   __ Narbonne safety Nnamdi Asomugha, who has UCLA and Cal on his
short list. He is expected to make a decision this week.
</P>
<P>
   __ Norman Boebert, a defensive end from Glendale, Ariz., and a
nationally ranked player whose finalists are UCLA and Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   __ Atari Callen, a defensive back from the storied Concord De La
Salle program. It's UCLA and Washington.
</P>
<P>
   __ T.J. Duckett, a 250-pound linebacker from Kalamazoo, Mich.,
and the No. 1-rated player in the country _ any position. Michigan
State will be tough to beat, but the Bruins are running a close
second. Duckett is so good his signature would instantly give UCLA
a top-five class.
</P>
<P>
   __ Borges update: Offensive coordinator Al Borges interviewed
Friday for the same post with the San Diego Chargers. The situation
could be resolved this week, Borges said.
</P>
<P>
   __ Knee problems: Senior safety Larry Atkins did not sprain the
medial collateral ligament in his right knee in the Rose Bowl,
after all. He did much worse, tearing the anterior cruciate
ligament. Atkins will not recover before the NFL draft in April.
</P>
<P>
   __ Linn's in: UCLA has named Mike Linn as its new strength
coach. Linn was an assistant under former coach Kevin Yoxall, who
departed several weeks ago for Auburn. A former UCLA player, Linn
has received stellar reviews from the players.
</P>
</TEXT>
