A7239 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-TYSON-BOS &LR;      01-18 1105
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-TYSON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIG RIGHT WINS IT FOR TYSON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ The only thing shot at the MGM Grand Saturday night
was Mike Tyson.
</P>
<P>
   Nineteen months after his rematch with Evander Holyfield turned
into a riot in which shots allegedly were fired in the MGM's casino
after Tyson was disqualified for biting Holyfield, Tyson returned
to boxing by knocking out Francois Botha in the fifth round with
one crushing right hand. Many will misread that, believing Tyson is
back because of it, despite the fact that he looked rusty and often
amateurish while losing the first four rounds on two judges' cards.
</P>
<P>
   But if Tyson is as much a student of boxing as he claims, he
will know better because the true meaning of what happened is not
that he still can punch _ which has been the case during his
ascendancy and his slow decline _ but that his mystique is gone.
</P>
<P>
   This is nothing new in the fight game. Punchers traditionally
get older faster than boxers, and punchers who have led the kind of
troubled life Tyson has get older quicker than the rest.
</P>
<P>
   There is much proof of that in the career of the fighter he says
he most admires, Sonny Liston, but a student of the game will
remember back to another night and another big punching heavyweight
who came back from a bad defeat and a layoff the same way Tyson
did.
</P>
<P>
   They will remember how Jack Dempsey lost badly to Gene Tunney in
a fight people dismissed as a fluke, then came back to knock Jack
Sharkey flat after struggling with him. Everyone said Dempsey was
back. His next fight he lost to Tunney again and retired.
</P>
<P>
   So part of the lesson of Tyson's one-punch devastation is not to
forget it came after he'd been beaten up twice by Holyfield, sat
out 19 months after being suspended, and came back to lose the
first four rounds to Botha and looked uncomfortable doing it until
he landed the kind of bomb that can erase many things, including
both short-term and long-term memory.
</P>
<P>
   What it can't erase is the fact that no one's afraid of Mike
Tyson any more. They may lose to him. They may even be knocked out
by him. But as Botha proved with his fatal cockiness, no one fears
the beaten bully, which means every fight from now on will be
dangerous and difficult.
</P>
<P>
   Every time Tyson enters the ring he will get hit more than he's
ever been hit and he will know pain more than he ever did and he
will be pressured more than he ever was because Holyfield has shown
everyone the way to beat him and Botha showed the plan still can
work if you follow it.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was sticking to the game plan until he got cocky,'' said
Panama Lewis, Botha's trainer. ``He dropped his hands and got
caught, but I can't take anything away from him.''
</P>
<P>
   That's because until he did, Botha lured Tyson into the same
mistakes Holyfield had and made him look worse. The fact that he
couldn't finish the job was more a reflection of what Botha is not,
not what Tyson still is.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a little embarrassed,'' Tyson (46-3, 40 knockouts) said.
``If I was fighting Mike Tyson and he was fighting like that, he'd
have been through.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, the old young Tyson would beat the new old
Tyson. Frankly, so would more than a few other top heavyweights
today, given the opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   During those first 12 minutes of Saturday night's 10-round
fight, Botha not only roughed Tyson up on the inside but talked
trash to him the way no opponent ever has, goading him and once
boxing his ears. At one point, he even shoeshined Tyson with a
flurry that had the crowd at the Grand Garden Arena laughing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really expected more from him,'' Botha (39-2, 24) said.
``Mike has a lot of power and I walked into a punch you don't see
but I was controlling the fight real easy and keeping away from his
power until I got cocky. I started fooling around too much,
probably. I got careless. I'd like to have a rematch but I know a
lot of other people want a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   That, too, is a new fact of Tyson's boxing life. Opponents
always have wanted to sign to fight him, but few besides Buster
Douglas and Holyfield actually wanted to fight him. Now they all
do, which means life just became much more difficult for a man who
always has been a small heavyweight made to look bigger by an aura
of intimidation that won him many fights before they had begun. As
Tyson's trainer, Tommy Brooks, said several weeks ago, ``That's
gone. Now he has to learn how to fight.''
</P>
<P>
   At 32, it is difficult to learn those lessons under the white
heat of a heavyweight assault. You may look good in the gym, as
Tyson did, but when the fight comes and your opponent is coming
forward instead of backing up and punching rather than covering up,
you forget those gym lessons quickly and revert to what you are _
which in Tyson's case is a one-punch knockout artist.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most ominous for the future was that at the end of the
first round, the two fighters engaged in a brutal moment of
violence in which Tyson seemed to suddenly lose it just as he had
in the Holyfield rematch, twisting Botha's arm against his side as
the bell rang. When later told Botha accused him of trying to break
it, Tyson said, ``He's correct.''
</P>
<P>
   A second later, Tyson pushed his left forearm into Botha's
throat as Botha hollered and tried to free himself. When he could
not, he hit Tyson after the bell and both corners emptied while
police rushed the ring apron and surrounded it, fearing the worst.
</P>
<P>
   Had referee Richard Steele wanted to disqualify Tyson right then
he could have but he did not and a round later Tyson was screaming
at him, claiming Botha was headbutting. Tyson made the same false
charges against Holyfield yet after the fight was over his new
manager, Shelly Finkel, said ``a lot of things were done in there
but the best part was Mike's composure was there early.''
</P>
<P>
   Finkel did not explain if that was before or after the cops
arrived.
</P>
<P>
   When order was restored, the second round began with a clearly
wild-eyed Tyson whistling amateurish punches well over Botha's
head, losing his balance and stumbling several times when he did.
More and more the two began to wrestle in the clinches until Tyson
tried to push Botha in the face with an open glove and Steele took
a point away from him. This is composure?
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, Tyson did solve Botha and when he did he had a
moment of clarity. Later he would say he never realized he had
thrown the lethal right hand that dropped Botha at his feet like an
unwanted leaflet and he was not lying. Punches like that come from
instinct, not plann
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
