<HEADER>
A7240 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-ROBERTSONCOLUMN-H     01-18 0882
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-ROBERTSONCOLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DALE ROBERTSON  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
DENVER _ You didn't have to be a lip reader to know John Elway said
a naughty word. His presumed final pass ever at Mile High Stadium,
which should have produced an exclamation-point touchdown, was
instead just another incompletion. He flat-out missed his tallest
target, Ed McCaffrey, who had a huge step on the nearest Jet in the
end zone.
<TEXT>
<P>
   And Elway knew it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I messed up,'' he admitted. ``But Eddie almost made a great
catch.''
</P>
<P>
   Elway knew he missed a bunch of targets Sunday. He knew he
messed up a lot. He threw too short, and he threw too long. He had
four passes pawed off course. Denver's brisk and chilly crosswinds,
with which he has such a wealth of experience, repeatedly bedeviled
him.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, when New York held its 10-0 lead, Elway was a
hapless _ hopeless? _ 4-for-18 for 33 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were out of sync,'' he understated.
</P>
<P>
   Not the stuff of legends, that ugly ratio. Artistically
speaking, of the countless games Elway has played here in the
shadow of the Front Range over his 16 seasons, this one, with
another AFC championship at stake, wouldn't have cracked his
personal top 100.
</P>
<P>
   Those statistics, though, like the aforementioned McCaffrey
misfire, were rendered inconsequential by the Denver 23, New York
10 score. The afternoon wrapped exactly as it was supposed to, with
the most famous smile in football back where it belonged, plastered
upon Elway's chiseled face. On the top of his head, sitting there
like a deserved crown, would rest the Lamar Hunt Trophy, the prize
awarded to the AFC's premier team.
</P>
<P>
   So retirement is a minimum of four quarters away for King John,
Denver's divine. One game remains, a game that will make him the
only quarterback to date to start a fifth Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   The miracle of Elway's career is that he entered the league in
1983 as one of the NFL's most overhyped prospects, certainly up to
said point in the league's history. Yet he somehow exceeded the
absurd expectations for him. Whatever happens in Miami on the final
day of January, and whatever his subsequent decision about staying
or going, the erstwhile ``Golden Boy'' will, in the end, go out
with pure platinum credentials.
</P>
<P>
   Is he done in Denver?
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't say that yet,'' Elway replied. ``I'll make my decision
after the Super Bowl.''
</P>
<P>
   People close to him say his farewell is a foregone conclusion.
Of course, we believed that to be the case last January, when he
finally won a Super Bowl after three humbling experiences in same.
Why would he push his luck, we wondered. What sense would it make
to return?
</P>
<P>
   Had the Jets proved capable of playing a second half worthy of
their first, you can bet the subject would have been revisited. Had
Vinny Testaverde _ 13-for-13 at the outset _ stayed his unconscious
early course, Elway likely wouldn't have been in a position to go
out as a two-time champion.
</P>
<P>
   It would have proved a bitter, unsettling conclusion to a year
launched with 13 successive victories and the resulting crush of
contemplation regarding a possible perfect season. It would have,
no question, left a speck of tarnish on Elway's glittering
mystique.
</P>
<P>
   But then everything turned on a single play, a perfect Elway
strike for 47 yards over the middle to McCaffrey immediately
following the Curtis Martin touchdown that put New York up _
improbably _ by 10.
</P>
<P>
   McCaffrey, the right guy in the wrong place at the right time,
slipped behind a dozing Victor Green. Elway laid the football
squarely in McCaffrey's hands, and the Jets' long day's journey
into night had begun.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the play we needed to get us out of our funk,'' Elway
said. ``It was huge. It got the momentum going, got our fans back
in it, restored a little confidence and perked everyone up.''
</P>
<P>
   Typical Elway, too, right?
</P>
<P>
   Well, not quite. The comebacks he's most noted for are
fourth-quarter spectaculars, dramas that commence just as all hope
appears lost. By Elway's standards, Sunday's script was mundane at
best. Once the Broncos got rolling, posting 20 points in a
10-minute third-quarter blitz, the Jets were rendered about as
impotent as the 1-15 ragnots Bill Parcells inherited in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   By any measure, New York had a remarkable season, going 12-4 to
win the AFC East, then beating Jacksonville in the divisional round
last week. By no measure were the Jets ready to supplant the
Broncos as champions of the resurgent American Conference, no
longer the NFL's grubby stepchild.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one person in this whole arena thought we could be doing
what we did today,'' Parcells argued.
</P>
<P>
   Least of all Elway. He would not be further upstaged by the
upstarts from the Jersey swamp. After all, had the tide not turned,
he would have had to return next season to make amends. This way,
he's got closure _ if he wants it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love you!'' Elway screamed to the madding crowd.
</P>
<P>
   And his love, as you might have guessed, was not of the
unrequited variety.
</P>
<P>
   ``One more year! One more year! One more year!'' the
Broncomaniacs pleaded as Elway took his victory _ farewell? _ lap
around the field.
</P>
<P>
   Wishful thinking, by all accounts. But who could blame them for
asking?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-18-99 0055EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990118.0041 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 00:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7241 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-AFC-HNS &LR;      01-18 1104
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-AFC-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN McCLAIN  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ If Sunday's AFC Championship Game against the New York
Jets turns out to have been Denver quarterback John Elway's last
game at Mile High Stadium, his coronation was fit for a king.
</P>
<P>
   With 75,482 fans worshipping at his altar, Elway provided the
inspiration and Terrell Davis the perspiration in the Broncos'
23-10 victory that sends them to Miami for Super Bowl XXXIII
against the Atlanta Falcons and their former coach, Dan Reeves.
</P>
<P>
   In the week leading up to the game, Elway was besieged with
questions about his imminent retirement. The Denver media have been
predicting that he will retire at some point after the Super Bowl.
The newspapers ran farewell tributes to him Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this was John's last game here, we sure didn't want him to
go out a loser,'' Broncos tight end Shannon Sharpe said. ``When you
consider everything he's done here, I don't think there's any
player who symbolizes his city more than John.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people think of Denver, they don't think of skiing. They
think of John Elway.''
</P>
<P>
   After the game, Elway saluted his coaches and teammates, told
the fans he loved them and did a victory lap around the field where
he became one of the most legendary players in the history of the
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``My focus is to finish this season before I think about what
I'm going to do,'' Elway said. ``I told the fans I love them
because they've been great for 16 years. I'm thrilled to get back
to the Super Bowl, but our work isn't done.''
</P>
<P>
   Denver, the defending Super Bowl champion, ended the Jets'
seven-game winning streak and denied Bill Parcells' attempt to
become the first coach to take three different teams to the Super
Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always very disappointing to lose a game like this, but
there's not one person in this whole arena who thought we could be
doing what we did today,'' Parcells said about the Jets' storybook
season. ``Hopefully, we can start from here next year and improve
the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I congratulate Denver. They're a good team. They have a chance
to win two (Super Bowls) in a row, and that's no small task.''
</P>
<P>
   Playing in a wicked wind that caused problems for the
quarterbacks, kickers and punters, Elway overcame a horrible first
half to become the first quarterback who will start in five Super
Bowls.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets led 3-0 after the first half, when Elway was 4-of-14
for 33 yards. The Broncos fell behind 10-0 before Elway, Davis,
kicker Jason Elam and an underrated defense ignited a brilliant
comeback with a 20-point third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Elway finished 13-of-34 for 173 yards and a touchdown. He wasn't
intercepted.
</P>
<P>
   Davis carried 32 times for 167 yards and a touchdown. He had 199
yards rushing and two touchdowns in the divisional win over Miami.
</P>
<P>
   ``Terrell could have run for 200 yards,'' Sharpe said. ``We have
to tip our hats to our offensive line.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we saw what kind of problems the wind was causing, we
couldn't throw the ball down the field much. We knew we had to keep
giving the ball to Terrell up the middle. That's always pretty good
strategy.''
</P>
<P>
   Denver's defense doesn't get nearly as much credit as it
deserves. The Broncos forced six turnovers _ five by the defense _
and limited the Jets to 14 yards on 13 carries. It was the second
consecutive playoff game in which they allowed only 14 yards
rushing on 13 carries.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had some adversity in the first half, but we kept our
composure and stepped up in the third quarter,'' Denver coach Mike
Shanahan said. ``The wind was a huge factor for both teams, and it
caused a lot of problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we had it in the third quarter, we decided to air it out
to try to keep them off-balance.''
</P>
<P>
   During the regular season, the third quarter was the Broncos'
worst. In 16 games, they scored only 64 points in the third
quarter, but they got 20 Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Broncos, the biggest play came after the Jets
had blocked a punt at the Denver one and scored their only
touchdown on Curtis Martin's one-yard run for a 10-0 lead with
11:56 left in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Elway called a play in which receiver Ed McCaffrey was supposed
to run a crossing route and receiver Rod Smith was supposed to run
a post route. McCaffrey and Smith lined up wrong, but they made the
right adjustment. Smith ran the crossing route, and McCaffrey went
deep to catch a 47-yard pass to the Jets' 17.
</P>
<P>
   Two plays later, Elway threw an 11-yard touchdown pass to
fullback Howard Griffith.
</P>
<P>
   ``They got it backward,'' Elway said about McCaffrey and Smith.
``They came out on the wrong side, but they're bright guys and they
just switched assignments.
</P>
<P>
   ``That play was huge because it got the fans back in the game
and gave us the momentum. It got us out of a funk, restored a
little confidence and perked everyone up.''
</P>
<P>
   On the next kickoff, Elam kicked the ball high and into the
stiff wind. It bounced backward and was touched by Jets linebacker
James Farrior and covered by Broncos linebacker Keith Burns at the
New York 31. The Broncos took advantage by tying the score on
Elam's 44-yard field goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a very big play,'' McCaffrey said. ``After we got the
ball, we scored a lot of points in a hurry. That was the difference
in the game.''
</P>
<P>
   The next time the Broncos got the ball, they drove to the Jets'
29, and Elam kicked a 48-yard field goal to give them a 13-10 lead
they would never relinquish.
</P>
<P>
   Darrien Gordon's 36-yard punt return to the New York 38 set up
their next score. Davis carried three times for all 38 yards. His
touchdown came on a 31-yard run.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a pitch, and the back side was open,'' Davis said. ``I
told myself to be patient. I saw the flow of the line and cut back.
When I saw the seam, I just went as fast as I could.''
</P>
<P>
   The Jets committed three turnovers in the fourth quarter, with
Elam completing the scoring with a 35-yard field goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a lot of pressure on us,'' Broncos linebacker Bill
Romanowski said about the defense. ``We stepped up and made a lot
of big plays. If you don't play good defense in big games like
this, you're making plans for the offseason.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon intercepted Jets QB Vinny Testaverde two times in the
fourth quarter. Testaverde finished 31-of-52 for 356 yards. He
didn't have a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice to come this close, but losing still's a big
disappointment,'' Testaverde said. ``Turnovers and penalties killed
us.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a team, we were very successful this season. We came a lot
farther than people expected.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
