<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 00:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7242 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-AFCCHAMPIONSHIP-A     01-18 1139
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-AFC </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELWAY LEAVES HIS FANS THE RIGHT WAY 
</HEADLINE>
 CHAMPIONSHIP-ANALYSIS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ His numbers were not like the old days, and neither was
his performance or his team's need for him, but in the end John
Elway left Mile High Stadium the way he should have Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   He left after making the play, and if he never plays another
game in Denver, isn't that how he should be remembered?
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't the final play this time. It wasn't the game-winning
play or the most dramatic play or the fourth-quarter comeback play
he's made 47 times in his career. Certainly it wasn't the only play
because, frankly, running back Terrell Davis made most of those in
Denver's 23-10 AFC Championship Game victory, but Elway made a
winner's play.
</P>
<P>
   What he did was what he has been doing for 16 years in Denver.
He made the play that righted his team when it seemed like it might
sink under the relentless defensive assault of the New York Jets.
He saved the day if not the game. He was, for a few brief minutes
at least, once again ELWAY.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets had just gone ahead, 10-0, with 11:56 to play in the
third quarter after having conspired with a stiff wind to hold
Elway to 33 yards passing and the Broncos to no points in the first
half, and now people began to mumble about seeing a repeat of the
Falcons' upset of the Vikings in the NFC title game that was less
than two hours old.
</P>
<P>
   It was at that moment that Elway became ELWAY. He was no longer
a little bit older and a little bit slower and a little less able
to throw any pass he wanted. Right then, when the Broncos needed
him more than anyone else, he fired footballs into the air and his
team was back in business.
</P>
<P>
   The Broncos came out of the huddle with the ball on the 36-yard
line barely 40 seconds after the Jets' Curtis Martin had scored a
1-yard touchdown to take a 10-0 lead and Elway noticed his two
receivers had lined up on the opposite sides of where they should
have been. Rod Smith gave Elway a hand signal that he knew what
route to run and understood the mixup but Ed McCaffrey was
frantically running toward him, baffled and panicked.
</P>
<P>
   As he approached, Elway calmly whispered, ``A post,'' meaning
his assignment was now to run the route Smith originally had been
assigned. As he did, Elway took the snap, gave a perfect play fake
that froze the defense, and hit a wide open McCaffrey downfield
with a 47-yard pass to the Jet 17. Two plays later he threw an
11-yard touchdown pass to Howard Griffith that may well be his last
in Denver if he follows through on what many here believe is a plan
to retire after Super Bowl XXXIII, and the Broncos were in the
game.
</P>
<P>
   Minutes later he would complete a 10-yard throw on third-and-15
that got Denver just close enough for Jason Elam to kick a
game-tying 44-yard field goal, and the world was safe for Terrell
Davis once again.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a big momentum swing for our team, being down 10-0,''
said Denver coach Mike Shanahan.
</P>
<P>
   After that, Davis tore the Jets apart. He rushed for 167 yards
and scored a 31-yard touchdown that broke the Jets' spirit as the
third quarter ended and made Elway a footnote in his sixth and
possibly final AFC Championship Game.
</P>
<P>
   Yet you never can be a footnote in Denver if you are Elway, even
at a time in his career when he no longer carries the Broncos but
instead vies for Best Supporting Actor nominations to Davis's
starring role.
</P>
<P>
   ``Terrell is always the most important thing to have in the
backfield,'' Elway said, knowing that for years that would have
been a lie. For years the Broncos never would have won a big game
in which John Elway was 13 of 34 for 173 yards and was sacked three
times.
</P>
<P>
   For years Elway was the Broncos and he relentlessly took them to
three Super Bowls on the strength of his arm and legs alone and
lost them all, only winning on his fourth try last season because
Davis was there to pound out a victory over the Green Bay Packers.
</P>
<P>
   Elway understands this change, but what he also understood after
everything was done if not quite yet all said was that something
more was required of him before he left Mile High one last time
than to throw three critical passes. Something he didn't
particularly feel comfortable doing but was being urged to by
Shanahan.
</P>
<P>
   The game was over. They were returning to the Super Bowl. It was
done. So now, Shanahan told him, it was time for a victory lap. Not
the Broncos, just the soul of the Broncos. Just ELWAY.
</P>
<P>
   And so he went.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an emotional thing for John,'' Shanahan said. ``He got
to take that lap around the field. I urged him to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a good thing he did because otherwise Elway would have
left with his thumb pointing to the sky after having told the fans
he loved them at the presentation of the Lamar Hunt Trophy and
nothing more. But this moment, if it was his last in Elway City,
required something more, and the fact that he took the lap may have
spoken louder about his retirement plans than all his pubic
insistences that he has not yet made a decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fans have been great to me for 16 years but, I don't know,
I didn't feel comfortable (doing a victory lap) but now I'm glad I
did it,'' Elway said. ``When you're here, you're focused on the
game. It was nice to be able to focus on the fans. It was so great
to see how happy the fans were.''
</P>
<P>
   They were happy about everything but the prospect of Elway not
returning, and they let him know it as he rounded the field.
</P>
<P>
   They continued their lobbying efforts during his postgame news
conference outside the locker room and every shout of encouragement
made Elway smile that smile that still makes him look like a kid
despite the age lines around his eyes. In the end, those pleadings
will not deter him, just as no defense ever did. He will do what he
wants, as he has for most of his career with so many defenses
massed to prevent him.
</P>
<P>
   He will also do what he believes is right, as he did when he
told McCaffrey to run the deep post, then found him with what may
be his last long ball at Mile High Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   But if he goes, John Elway will have to make one last stop at
the Super Bowl first, a place he's been to five times now. If he
wins, he will be among the few to do it twice in a row, joining
Terry Bradshaw and Bart Starr and Joe Montana. And if he doesn't,
does it matter?
</P>
<P>
   Not to Shannon Sharpe.
</P>
<P>
   ``John has done so much for Denver,'' the Broncos tight end
said. ``He has more wins than any other quarterback. He'll be
starting his fifth Super Bowl. When you think Denver you don't
think skiing. You think John Elway.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, for just a few short minutes when his team needed him
most, he reminded anyone who might have forgotten why that is.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
