<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 01:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7246 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-KEISSER-COLUMN-LA     01-18 0978
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-KEISSER-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELWAYS-REEVES FEUD A SPICY DISH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 c.1999 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It wouldn't be a Super Bowl if there weren't a few sweet
storylines emanating from the NFL Palace.
</P>
<P>
   In the two weeks between now and kickoff of Super Bowl XXXIII,
also known as the longest fortnight, you will be treated to the
literally heart-rendering story of Dan Reeves, the last ride of
John Elway, the Lourdes miracle that is Chris Chandler, and the
up-from-pigeonhood saga of the Dirty Birdz.
</P>
<P>
   But at the risk of interrupting the league's bliss, this Super
Bowl will also offer something hot and sweaty, something that's
been missing on Super Sunday since the AFL's grubby Jets
cold-cocked the NFL's arrogant Colts 30 years ago: malice and
retribution.
</P>
<P>
   Malice might be too cold a word, especially in light of Reeves,
the Falcons coach, going from ICU to SB. But retribution fits.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves, Elway and Mike Shanahan once worked together in Denver.
Reeves was the coach who took the team to three Super Bowls. Elway
was the league's best clutch quarterback. Shanahan was the
innovative strategist. Sometime in 1991, this triangle blew apart
like a natural-gas explosion.
</P>
<P>
   After the 1991 season, which ended with a AFC title game loss to
Buffalo, Reeves fired Shanahan, claiming the assistant coach had
overstepped his authority.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, Elway and Reeves feuded daily, leading to a
playoff-less 8-8 season and Reeves' firing by Broncos owner Pat
Bowlen.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, Elway brayed that playing under Reeves had been
``hell'' and that Reeves' conservative style had held Elway and the
Broncos back all those years. Reeves responded by calling Elway a
spoiled brat, among other things.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, Shanahan, fresh from three successful years with the
49ers, returned to Denver as head coach, which was all Reeves
needed to support his decision to fire Shanahan in the first place.
Shanahan obviously learned a few things in his year-plus as the
sorcerer's apprentice with the Raiders.
</P>
<P>
   Chances are excellent that the participants of this mess will
try to gloss over it as much as possible. The NFL might promote the
War Theatre philosophy to attract fans, but it actually hates
infighting (see Al Davis v. NFL, et al).
</P>
<P>
   But there is no love lost here. Reeves, less verbose, has
limited his comments of late to sarcastic digs. Back in August,
Reeves said Chandler throws the best deep ball of any quarterback
he's ever worked with. His praise of Chandler after Sunday's upset
of Minnesota focused on his ability to play within himself and the
team's philosophy.
</P>
<P>
   In their three years together at the top of the Broncos food
chain, years that have seen the Broncos transform their image from
mules to stallions, Shanahan and Elway talked up the new era at the
expense of the old.
</P>
<P>
   Elway said Reeves' philosophy was physically draining _ play
conservative on offense, nibble for field position, take advantage
of turnovers, stay in the game, and then storm the goal line in one
all-out push if needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``That drains you,'' said Elway during his run to the Super Bowl
last year. And here you thought he enjoyed his 40-plus comeback
wins. ``I hated that, always having to stay close, stay close, stay
close until Dan would say, `OK, go ahead and win.'
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't just the drive. I'd be pacing the sidelines during
the entire game wondering how I was supposed to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Elway has since admitted he often blew off some of Reeves' play
calls, most often by ad-libbing in the pocket. Shannon Sharpe,
Elway's favorite receiver and The Human Quote around Denver,
described Reeves' use of Elway thusly: ``It was like making Picasso
paint with a spray can.''
</P>
<P>
   Shanahan has said there isn't a NFL passing record Elway
wouldn't own if he had played in a system that used his talents
rather than neutered them. ``And no one but Elway could have taken
those (Broncos) teams to the Super Bowl.''
</P>
<P>
   Those teams would be Reeves' three Broncos teams that were
impaled in Super Bowls _ 39-20 by the New York Giants, 42-10 by
Washington and 55-10 by San Francisco. In Denver, the history of
Orange Crushed was demoralizing enough for the franchise to shed
its trademark orange jerseys.
</P>
<P>
   As the two sides prepare to stare at each other, there is
probably some truth in both sides of the story.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, Elway has benefited from the change. The offense is
more wide open and the Broncos now go for the jugular in the first
quarter. Elway's yardage, touchdowns and efficiency rating have all
improved the last three years, and his interceptions are down.
</P>
<P>
   Elway also has better personnel around him, notably the
franchise's best running back ever, Terrell Davis, and receivers
Sharpe and Ed McCaffrey.
</P>
<P>
   But Reeves can also point to Davis as the big difference in
Denver. It wasn't necessarily Reeves' fault that he was never in
draft position to get any back better than Sammy Winder, or any
receivers taller than the smurf-like Three Amigos.
</P>
<P>
   His presence in the Super Bowl supports his philosophy that a
running game, some Art Shell-instructed linemen and a quarterback
who doesn't beat you can take you a long way. In the shallow water
that is quarterbacking in the NFL, The Dirty Birdz are a tonic to
all teams that do not have an Elway.
</P>
<P>
   There are a half-dozen other subplots which enrich the
anticipation, including Chandler and Denver's Howard Griffith
staging their own little Los Angeles Rams alumni meeting, and the
vision of Shanahan and Shell on opposite sidelines of a Super Bowl.
The Silver and Black are back, they're just not in Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   But the vicious triangle that is Reeves, Shanahan and Elway is
keenest. Having seen too many boring Super Bowls, you'll forgive me
if I pass the sugar and go right for the hot stuff.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
