<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; For MONDAY PMs  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Monday, Jan. 18, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   HURRICANE-MIGRANTS (Tapachula, Mexico) _ Spurred by the ravages
of Hurricane Mitch, Central American migrants are now crossing the
Guatemalan border with Mexico and heading to the United States in
alarming numbers, officials say. By Ginger Thompson. (With photo.)
</P>
<P>
   CANADA-ARCTIC (Igloolik, Northwest Territories) _ During the
Arctic's ``great darkness'' the sun does not appear at all for
seven weeks. The day the sun finally did emerge from the horizon
was the most important day of the year for Igloolik's eskimos. Now,
after years of neglect, some of the old ceremonies that used to
welcome the sun's return are coming back. By Anthony DePalma.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NY-TRASH-VIRGINIA (New York) _ Yes, Virginia, there is a lot of
trash in New York. And getting rid of it is a problem. But where to
go? A look at why nobody in the Old Dominion wants Gotham's
garbage. &UR;  &LR; By Blaine Harden.
</P>
<P>
   MISLEADING-MORTGAGES (New York) _ A mortgage lender named Delta
Funding has made a profitable business of loaning money in poor
neighborhoods, where many homeowners can't afford to make their
monthly payments and thus default, losing their homes. Delta is
affiliated with Bankers Trust, and its business has drawn the
attention of law enforcement officials and low-income housing
advocates, who contend that the company is violating federal and
state laws by misleading borrowers and signing homeowners up for
mortgages they cannot afford. &UR;  &LR; By Randy Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   SANFRAN-SPCA (San Francisco) _ San Francisco's SPCA not only has
a no-kill policy for the pets left with it, but plush
accommodations for them, too. Now it has $200 million to take
no-kill national. By Evelyn Nieves. (With photos.)
</P>
<P>
   PHILLY-POLITICS (Philadelphia ) _ Philadelphia has come a long
way with Ed Rendell, one of the nation's best-known mayors, leading
it, but now that he's not seeking re-election, the city trembles a
bit as it waits to see the candidates who would succeed him. By
Michael Janofsky.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-GUNSALES (Los Angeles) _ Acting on a growing body of
research showing that gun dealers are selling firearms into an
illegal black market, the Los Angeles City Council is about to
limit gun buyers in the city to one gun per month.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON _ (Moved in ``w'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-LEGAL (Undated) _ After three days of impeachment
arguments from the House managers, constitutional law scholars said
the presentations last week gave the strongest legal arguments yet
against Clinton. But in a series of interviews over the weekend
that amounted to evaluations of the House's impeachment case so
far, some legal authorities generally agreed that if the House
Republicans made any headway in their case against the president,
it was merely in a subtle shifting of emphasis that could easily
shift again. By William Glaberson.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; CAMPAIGN-MONEY (Washington) _ The compressed calendar of primaries
and possibly the most wide-open race for the White House in decades
has set off a frenzy among Republican and Democratic prospects who
believe they must begin to raise money almost immediately or they
may find it impossible to catch up. In many ways, this year is more
crucial than 2000 in determining whom the two parties will
nominate, because as experts in both parties agree, for now the
survival of candidates comes down not to issue stands or personal
appeal, but to who has enough money. By Richard L. Berke.
</P>
<P>
   MILITARY-SPENDING (Washington) _ Not much has changed in the
office deep inside the Pentagon where Franklin C. Spinney has
worked ever since he had a few moments of notoriety in the 1980s
with this shocking assessment: the more Reagan spent on defense,
the less the military was ready to fight. Nearly two decades later,
Clinton has proposed the largest increase in Pentagon spending
since those heady days, and to Spinney (and a few stray voices in
Washington), the same is true today. By Steven Lee Myers.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   VODAFONE-AIRTOUCH-TALKS (Undated) _ It took two weeks of
all-night strategy sessions and telephone calls between
sleep-deprived executives in four time zones for Vodafone to woo
Airtouch from the embrace of Bell Atlantic. Vodafone prevailed and
last Friday announced a $60 billion Vodafone-Airtouch combination
that will create a global wireless powerhouse to rival
telecommunications blockbusters like AT&AMP;T or British
Telecommunications. By Laura Holson. (With graphic.)
</P>
<P>
   AIRTOUCH-GINN-PROFILE (Los Angeles) _ Sam Ginn's gamble has paid
off, in a huge way. With the acquisition of Airtouch Communications
Inc. by Vodafone Group PLC, Ginn, the chairman and chief executive
of Airtouch, will walk away with hundreds of millions of dollars
from stock and options he owns. By Andrew Pollack.
</P>
<P>
   TV-TABLOIDS-MEDIA (Undated) _ At the very moment when tabloid
topics have become big news on the most respected television news
programs, the generation of shows that spawned the term ``tabloid
television'' is dying. From a heyday when there were a half-dozen
such shows, only three remain. Tabloid TV news magazines have
withered because certain kinds of tabloid-style stories have
migrated to the traditional news organizations. By Laurie Mifflin.
</P>
<P>
   TV-HITS-MEDIA (Pasadena, Calif.) _ Maybe network television can
still produce hits after all. In five days, three networks started
new series and all of them scored ratings that would qualify them
as significant hits, by far the biggest new hits of what has been a
woebegone television season. By Bill Carter.
 &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; INTERNET-FRENZY-MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ You want Internet
companies? We'll give you Internet companies. That's the message
Wall Street is sending investors in the first quarter. But analysts
are warning that investors could suffer huge losses by eagerly
chasing these hot and volatile issues. By David Barboza.
</P>
<P>
   LINUX-MICROSOFT-CHALLENGE (Undated) _ A young Swiss programmer
is coordinating a project intended to let PC users run their
normally Windows-dependent programs on Linux _ a free operating
system, whose devotees would very much like to overthrow
Microsoft's hegemony. The growing numbers of proponents of the open
source software movement argue that open source is the path to
higher quality, more reliable programs. By John Markoff.
</P>
<P>
   ONLINE-ANTISMUT-LAW (Undated) _ The American Civil Liberties
Union and 15 other groups and businesses have filed a lawsuit to
overturn the Child Online Protection Act, which makes it a crime
for a commercial Web site to knowingly make available to those
under 17 certain sexually explicit material. The ACLU contends that
a virtual brown-paper wrapper would undercut not just free speech
online but Internet commerce. Hearings are scheduled to begin
Wednesday in U.S. District Court in Philadelphia. By Pamela
Mendels.
</P>
<P>
   DIGICOM-COLUMN (Undated) _ Few industries have gorged themselves
on digital commerce with greater appetite than the
telecommunications companies. But the result has been a wired world
that to many customers seems like a cross between the best-known
works of Edvard Munch and Jean-Paul Sartre: we scream, but there is
no exit. By Denis Caruso.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY (Moved in ``k'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SAFIRE-COLUMN (Washington) _ Forty years ago, a hotshot press
agent in his late 20s agreed to publicize a meeting of lawyers to
support an outfit that was having its troubles in the South, even
though the outfit was led by a dedicated dissident suspected of
being manipulated by a Communist backer. By William Safire.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CULTURE (Moved in ``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   &LR; CIVIL-RIGHTS-PHOTOS (New York) _ The debut of ``America and the
Civil Rights Movement, 1954-1968'' offers more than 50 images
documenting the civil rights movement. The photographs are
accompanied by text and information-laden captions because, the
show's curator says, many people still do not know why a civil
rights movement was needed. By Felicia R. Lee.
</P>
<P>
   UNKNOWN-INDIAN-MUSEUM (Los Angeles) _ The Southwest Museum, the
oldest museum in Los Angeles, is considered by many experts to be
one of the top collections of American Indian artifacts in the
country. The collection, only about 2 percent of which is ever on
display, focuses on the Indians of the Southwest, the Great Basin,
California, the Plains and the Northwest. It is also nearly
unknown, except to scholars, By James Sterngold.
</P>
<P>
   HAUNTED-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``The Haunted Wood,'' by Allen
Weinstein and Alexander Vassilliev, is a history of Soviet
espionage in America during Stalin's dictatorship and will appeal
most of all to readers thoroughly familiar with the previous record
of Soviet espionage. Reviewed by Christopher Lehmann-Haupt.
</P>
<P>
   MOONDRUNK-MUSIC-REVIEW (New York) _ ``Moondrunk'' is part of a
valorous attempt by Lincoln Center's ``Great Performers'' series to
give classical concerts a new look in different venues. One is
thankful even while disagreeing with some of the results. Reviewed
by Bernard Holland.
</P>
<P>
   TV-HOOVER-REVIEW (Undated) _ Monday night's ``American
Experience'' leaves no doubt that the Hoover Dam was quite a gamble
for its time and produced big winnings for its major players and
for America's Southwest. Reviewed by Walter Goodman.
</P>
<P>
   TV-NIGHT-REVIEW (Undated) _ Rick Schroder is hot. This week the
young star (a recent addition to ``N.Y.P.D. Blue'') is on the cover
of TV Guide, smiling just above the words ``He's great!'' On Monday
night he's the star of an ABC movie, ``What We Did That Night.''
Well, every career move can't be a winner. Reviewed by Anita Gates.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (Moved in ``s'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BOX-TYSON (Undated) _ Tyson's career has come back to life. But
can he keep it going? By Timothy Smith.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NYT News Service &LR;  &QL;
