<HEADER>
A7297 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-AUS-OPEN-RESULTS-     01-18 0799
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-AUS-OPEN-RESULTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CORRETJA AND VENUS WILLIAMS SURVIVE OPENING ROUND
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: See also TEN-AUSTRALIAN-OPEN, which focuses on Sampras
withdrawing and does not contain results; Monday is cq in 4th
graf.) 
 (nk) 
 By CHRISTOPHER CLAREY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MELBOURNE, Australia _ The opening day of the year's opening
Grand Slam tournament did not begin with major upsets, but that
does not mean it was lacking for surprises.
</P>
<P>
   Who would have expected a slender Croatian with a ranking of 82
to get within 2 points of beating fifth-seeded Venus Williams in a
marathon third set? Or for a Japanese man playing in his first
Grand Slam event to serve for the match in the fourth set against
second-seeded Alex Corretja?
</P>
<P>
   But in a global sport, there are no shortages of potential
hazards for the stars, and though Takao Suzuki and Silvija Talaja
could not finish what they had started, neither Williams nor
Corretja will forget their opponents' games or names soon.
</P>
<P>
   Williams won her match Monday on Court 1 by 3-6, 6-3, 9-7.
Corretja won his on Center Court, 6-3, 4-6, 3-6, 7-6 (7-5), 6-2.
</P>
<P>
   It is difficult to say which seeded player had the more
difficult time on a day when the sun shone brightly but the
temperatures did not soar.
</P>
<P>
   Williams began her 1999 Grand Slam season in a black and red
ensemble that left most of her back exposed. But her tennis was not
quite as striking as her attire. She made a rash of unforced errors
and struggled with her serve against Talaja, a steady 20-year-old
baseliner with a wicked backhand and a combative temperament.
</P>
<P>
   Talaja has won only one match in a Grand Slam event, but she
might have won more if not for a right shoulder injury that forced
her to miss nearly six months of activity at the end of 1997 and
the beginning of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   She has now recovered, and she tracked down Williams's powerful
ground strokes in the corners throughout the match. She could not
find a way to close out the match against the younger yet much more
experienced Williams.
</P>
<P>
   The closest the Croatian would come was in the third set when
Williams served to stay in the match at 4-5 and quickly fell behind
by 0-30 on her serve. But Williams would win the next 4 points to
get even. She was still a long way from getting to the second
round. She served for the match for the first time at 7-6 but
squandered two match points at 40-15, the second with a double
fault, and Talaja then finished off the break.
</P>
<P>
   Williams returned the favor in the next game and this time, she
did not flinch when she served for the match. When it ended, she
thrust both long arms into the air with relief. The Croatian fans
were no longer waving their national flags.
</P>
<P>
   There had been a few Japanese flags in motion on Center Court
earlier in the afternoon. No Japanese man had won a match at the
Australian Open since 1989, and though Suzuki could not put an end
to that losing streak, he came close enough to make Corretja very
uncomfortable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was waiting for my chance, and I have to say that I was
almost done,'' Corretja said.
</P>
<P>
   Suzuki, the 118th-ranked player in the world, served for the
match at 5-4 in the fourth set. The quick young man from Sapporo
had gotten to that point by playing like the Australians of yore,
serving and rushing the net with regularity and success, knocking
away tightly angled volleys and reading Corretja's normally passing
shots consistently well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he was playing fantastic tennis,'' Corretja said.
</P>
<P>
   But Corretja has experienced a lot more pressure-filled moments
in his career than Suzuki, who was making his Grand Slam debut in
front of a large crowd on Centre Court. At 15-15, the genial
Spaniard would finally take control. He won the first point after
hitting an odd, looping backhand return that landed on the line and
forced Suzuki to retreat and fire up a weak lob. He won the next
point with a swashbuckling forehand pass down the line. He then
broke Suzuki's serve by passing him down the line with a backhand.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice to know that even if you are struggling and you
trust in yourself, good things can happen,'' Corretja said.
</P>
<P>
   MATCH POINTS
</P>
<P>
   The ATP Tour Player Council announced on Monday that it would
support an increase in the ban from one years to two years for
players who test positive for a Class I performance-enhancing
substance. The International Tennis Federation has announced its
support for the change, which would bring tennis in line with most
other Olympic sports and satisfy the International Olympic
Committee's demand for uniformity as it prepares to host a drug
conference in early February. The Women's Tennis Association has
expressed preliminary support for the increase but has yet to
announce a final position.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
