<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 01:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7300 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WHY-MICHAEL-MATTERS-E     01-18 1231
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHY-MICHAEL-MATTERS-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JORDAN: THE RARENESS OF `HIS AIRNESS'  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors)   (This insightful 1,050-word ``separate buy'' article is from the
current (week beginning 16 January 1999) Economist magazine.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada except to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate in New York at 1-800-972-3550 or 212-499-3333, or
fax us at 212-499-3382.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into the ``k''
commentary news, ``a'' domestic/general news and ``s'' sports news
files.)  
  
 c.1999 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
 (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Praise be to Michael Jordan. At long last a grateful nation has
a good reason to turn its attention from the travails of Bill
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Basketball's transcendent star is at last retiring. This week,
even the expectation of such an announcement was enough to claim
front-page coverage, first spot on the television news and a sober
lead editorial in the New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   Surely only insensitive curmudgeons, remote from the feelings of
ordinary folk, will argue that the priorities were wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Yet some non-sporting innocents will still need convincing. To
them basketball is just a game in which very tall men crowd on to a
rather small court to bounce a ball and then throw it through a
hoop.
</P>
<P>
   Why these physical freaks should be paid so much (the average
salary in the National Basketball Association last year was $2.6
million, and Jordan's was an astounding $33 million, to which he
added more than $40 million in commercial endorsements) is a
mystery explicable only by the bizarre economics of television and
the willingness of young men to buy overpriced sneakers as though
clothes alone will help them emulate their heroes.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps these innocents have a point. Even the sport's fans have
been bemused over the past few months by a self-destructive dispute
between owners and players which, it was accurately argued, boiled
down to a wrangle between short billionaires and tall millionaires.
</P>
<P>
   But there are two points they neglect. The first is the sheer
athleticism of the sport. No other American sport, certainly not
football, with its regimented moves, or baseball, with its tedious
longueurs, has the same combination of sustained physical grace,
effort, creativity and personality.
</P>
<P>
   To watch the slender Reggie Miller of the Indiana Pacers draw
away from his marker and score from the three-point line is to see
poetic elegance; to watch Patrick Ewing of the New York Knicks play
on despite a recently fractured wrist is to see a courage money
does not buy.
</P>
<P>
   The second point is Jordan himself. ``His Airness'' (the title
is thanks to his gravity-defying slam-dunks and jump shots, and the
Air sports shoes that Nike named after him) is a star who deserves
his status.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the evidence is statistical: five times the league's
most valuable player; six times a championship winner with the
Chicago Bulls; twice an Olympic gold medallist.
</P>
<P>
   At his retirement press conference, the Bulls' owner, Jerry
Reinsdorf, described him as ``simply the best player who ever put
on a basketball uniform.'' With due respect to Wilt Chamberlain and
Magic Johnson, Reinsdorf is right.
</P>
<P>
   But so what? It is true that America, in contrast to those
countries that meanly cut their stars down to size (Australians
call it ``the tall poppy syndrome''), is a country happy to be
star-struck.
</P>
<P>
   After all, to be a star is to outshine the competition, which
for America's values is an essential attribute; hence the ready
acceptance of salaries for corporate chieftains that elsewhere
would seem quite grossly excessive.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, even in America, Jordan seems an exceptional star. Would
the retirement of Bill Gates, richer even than Jordan, command
quite such rapt attention? Possibly not.
</P>
<P>
   But then Gates is simply an exceptional example of a common
phenomenon, the successful white businessman. Michael, as his fans
tend to call him, is also a successful businessman, but he is a
black one, and that combination is dispiritingly uncommon.
</P>
<P>
   Black stars shine mostly in sports and show business, and even
there precious few appeal to the white majority.
</P>
<P>
   Muhammad Ali is one, but only since the baby-boomer generation
reached maturity and disregarded their elders' fears of Ali's Islam
and his opposition to the Vietnam war. O.J. Simpson was another,
but that lasted only until his trial for murder.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Jordan's reach beyond the boundaries of race is
unqualified: his shaven head is a poster icon for black and white
alike (one piece of market research found that the back of his head
is more recognized than the faces of Bill Clinton, Newt Gingrich
and Jesus Christ).
</P>
<P>
   His presence on the basketball court has helped a sport that is
80 percent black win an audience that is 80 percent white; and the
products he endorses, from Gatorade soft drinks to MCI telephone
services, are aimed at the whole nation, not just its black
minority.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, when Fortune magazine analyzed what it called ``the
Jordan effect,'' it calculated that, since joining the NBA in 1984,
he had brought the league some $10 billion in tickets, TV revenues
and merchandise sales _ only a small part of which can have come
from America's blacks.
</P>
<P>
   In truth, Jordan's multiracial appeal should be no mystery at
all. In a sport in which too many players are ill-educated or badly
behaved, the articulate Michael embodies virtues that pretty well
all Americans can identify with: an extraordinary discipline and
work ethic, enabling him to be the best in his field even at the
age of 35; an ability to inspire his colleagues; and a will to win
so strong that in one session of the 1997 finals against the Utah
Jazz he played a winning game despite a high fever.
</P>
<P>
   So what now? Unlike most sportsmen, Jordan has retired at the
top (his very last shot was the one that last year won the NBA
championship with just 6.6 seconds left to play).
</P>
<P>
   Jim Brown, the greatest running back in professional football,
is another black American who retired at the top; he then went on
to be a movie star and businessman.
</P>
<P>
   Brown this week had some cautionary words in the New York Times
for well-paid black athletes in white-controlled sports: ``They
keep saying the owners should hire more black coaches, but even if
you had all black coaches, that's not helping black people.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real problem is that the owners and the agents control the
black athlete. The athletes should take the bull by the horns and
have more control over their lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Will His Airness take up the challenge? It would be progress for
all Americans if the short white billionaires in the owners' box
were to be joined at last by a tall black one. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this excellent 1,050-word article, it must be purchased
from the New York Times Syndicate in New York at 1-800-972-3550 or
212-499-3333, or fax us at 212-499-3382.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITORS: Please note that this article is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
