<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 02:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7311 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-TCUCOACH-TEX     01-18 0561
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-TCU </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TCU, FRANCHIONE AGREE ON SEVEN-YEAR DEAL
</HEADLINE>
 COACH-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ TCU and football coach Dennis Franchione
have agreed to a new seven-year contract worth up to $7.3 million,
sources close to the negotiations said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   TCU officials have called a news conference for Monday
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Franchione's deal will pay him from $700,000 to $900,000 a
season for seven seasons, including incentives for bowl berths,
player graduation rates and conference championships, sources said.
</P>
<P>
   His new contract provides for a $1 million bonus if TCU wins a
national championship. It also includes raises for all of his
assistant coaches.
</P>
<P>
   TCU Athletic Director Eric Hyman offered no comment last night,
other than to say, ``Look for a major announcement (today) as far
as TCU athletics'' is concerned. Franchione was unavailable for
comment.
</P>
<P>
   Sources said Franchione secured a clause that allows him to
leave without penalty for any of four schools: Notre Dame, Texas,
Texas A&AMP;M and Arizona State. TCU, meanwhile, negotiated a stiff
buyout clause as a deterrent for programs looking to raid Fort
Worth when a coaching position opens.
</P>
<P>
   TCU recently finished its first season under Franchione,
improving from 1-10 in 1997 to 7-5, including a 28-19 upset of
Southern California in the Sun Bowl on Dec. 31.
</P>
<P>
   Franchione had five years remaining on his previous contract
that paid him approximately $450,000 a season.
</P>
<P>
   TCU officials had been looking for ways to keep Franchione as
the Horned Frogs coach since the Sun Bowl victory, including a plan
to renegotiate his contract.
</P>
<P>
   Franchione and Hyman had numerous discussions before an initial
offer was made eight days ago. Negotiations slowed while Franchione
attended a coaches conference in Nashville, Tenn., last week, but
sources said that all sticking points except for a few minor
details, including specifics of the buyout clause, had been worked
out going into this past weekend.
</P>
<P>
   TCU waited to announce Franchione's new contract to allow time
for trustees to be notified.
</P>
<P>
   Franchione was repeatedly mentioned as a possible candidate when
jobs opened up at Oklahoma and Colorado after the 1998 season. Iowa
contacted Franchione about interviewing for its football post after
Hayden Fry stepped down, but he declined.
</P>
<P>
   Trustee Malcolm Louden said he hopes that Franchione's new
contract will serve as a sign of the coach's commitment to TCU and
the university's commitment to building a nationally prominent
athletic program.
</P>
<P>
   The new deal would seem to put Franchione on a level comparable
with some other high-profile coaches. At Texas, coach Mack Brown
recently signed a 10-year deal increasing his compensation package
to $850,000 a year. Kentucky coach Hal Mumme also signed a contract
extension recently, boosting his salary from $450,000 to $800,000
annually.
</P>
<P>
   And Franchione's contract comes at a crucial time for TCU. The
Horned Frogs are attempting to establish themselves as important
players in Division I athletics before an expected round of
conference realignments begins. TCU has already taken some steps,
including approval in November of $8 million in athletic facilities
improvements.
</P>
<P>
   The next step will occur, at least officially, Monday afternoon.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
