<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990118.0078 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 08:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7448 &Cx1f; kan-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TAMMEUS-TIES-KAN &LR;      01-18 0659
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAMMEUS-TIES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DEFENSE OF TIES BY A MAN WHO LOVES THEM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL TAMMEUS  
 c. 1999 KANSAS CITY STAR 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Apparently no one but me is man enough to defend the necktie,
which recently has taken enormous and utterly unwarranted abuse. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I'm sure you read or heard about the asinine display put on some
weeks back by Prince Claus of the Netherlands. In the midst of a
speech, he ripped off his navy blue necktie and hurled it at the
feet of his wife, Queen Beatrix. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``A snake around my neck,'' he is said to have growled. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Since then various media outlets _ following, naturally, instead
of leading _ have run stories about men freeing themselves from
these alleged nooses. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Well, it's all ridiculous. The necktie, or cravat, as some are
wont to call it, is in fact a wonderful and endlessly fascinating _
if seemingly functionless _ piece of clothing. I say seemingly
functionless because, in fact, it has several important functions
that men (a category in which I include myself, despite all the
nasty _ and sometimes true _ things said about the species) would
be foolish to abandon. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I know all this because ties are my vice. I own hundreds of
them, and each one reminds me of some important part of my life.
For instance, the flowery blue, gray, pink and burgundy tie I have
on as I type these mortal words was given to me years ago for
Father's Day. The little tag inside the small end says it was made
in the U.S.A. of 100 percent Italian silk. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That's one good thing about ties right there. They're very
educational. For instance, the flowers on my tie today appear to be
pansies. And that has caused me to look up the information that
pansies are members of the Viola species and of the Violaceae
family. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And if you ask your Web search engines to tell you about silk
and Italy, why, the fascinating information is almost endless. For
instance, did you know about the silkworm plague that devastated
the silk industry in both Italy and France starting in 1854? And
did you know the Italian _ but not the French _ silk industry
recovered? Which explains the label on my tie, no doubt. Cool. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Well, before I got bumper-carred off to Italy there, I started
to tell you that one of the important things the now-maligned tie
does is to tell you a great deal about its wearer. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Is the man daring but only within reason? Is he completely wild?
Is he simply an old fuddy-duddy? Is he color blind? You can almost
immediately answer those questions simply by looking at a man's tie
in relation to the rest of his clothing. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Without the tell-tale tie, you might have to spend days, weeks
or months determining all that, by which time the guy may have
fleeced you or convinced you to invest in some wildly speculative
venture like frozen octopus bellies. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Even the knot is revealing. Is it neat and gently tight and of
an appropriate size? Now THERE'S a man who may be worth knowing. By
contrast, is the knot simply a huge wad at the throat, sloppy and
much too large for the collar? (See Sam Donaldson.) There's a man
with no sense of proportion, a man convinced of his own greatness
and possibly even his own immortality. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Is he inordinately attracted to one color and is it a hue that
makes you want to hurl? (See David Letterman's relentless
collection of green ties.) Such a man will always insist on his own
way, even if that way is stupid. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Does he now and then wear _ and tie _ a bow tie? Ah, there is a
man sure of himself, insightful and considerate. Hire or marry such
a man. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Does he rip off his tie in public and denounce it? Force such a
man to abdicate. He cannot be trusted with power. Tie him up in a
corner. Use his own tie. The world will be a better place. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Tammeus is a columnist for The Kansas City Star. This
article was distributed by The New York Times News Service. E-mail:
tammeus(at)kcstar.com.) &QL;
</P>
