<HEADER>
A7504 &Cx1f; var-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-REVIEW-BUDGET-FINAL     01-18 0985
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-REVIEW-BUDGET-FINAL-NYT </SLUG>
  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Editors: The following items from The N.Y. Times Week in Review
for Sunday, Jan. 17, moved Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   _ In the `a' category:
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-HOWLONG?-REVIEW (Washington) _ Whether they want to see
President Clinton driven from office or they have completely tuned
out the Senate trial, most Americans agree on one thing: they want
it to be over. But the dissection of the the Lewinsky affair will
continue at least as long as the Senate trial grinds on and maybe a
lot longer than that. By Jill Abramson.
</P>
<P>
   FLYNT-BARR-REVIEW (Undated) _ Porn publisher Larry Flynt has
shown that he can get the mainstream media to give him a platform
in exposing the sexual misconduct of conservative Republicans. But
it is also clear that, unless the target of his attacks responds
and thus makes news himself, self-appointed newsmakers like Flynt
can't necessarily keep the press' attention very long. His
accusations against Rep. Bob Barr received relatively little news
coverage. By Felicity Barringer.
</P>
<P>
   FIDGETING-CALORIES-REVIEW (Undated) _ Old-fashioned fidgeting _
tapping your pencil against a conference table in a make-or-break
meeting, jiggling your leg while gabbing on the phone, pacing back
and forth behind your desk _ may emerge as a new weight-control
strategy. That seems to be a major implication of a Mayo Clinic
study that sought to explain why some people can eat anything and
everything and not gain an ounce, while others bulk up with every
swallow. By James Barron.
</P>
<P>
   AIRPORT-SECURITY-REVIEW (Washington) _ Airport security can
leave passengers feeling insecure. Checkpoint screeners miss
weapons that undercover testers hide under their clothes, or they
notice them but do nothing. Ticket agents forget to ask if
passengers are carrying packages from strangers, or fail to react
properly if the answer is yes. Airport employees don't single out
passengers who buy tickets with cash at the last minute or
otherwise act suspiciously. Ground crews leave airplanes unlocked
and unattended, giving intruders an opportunity to plant a weapon
or a bomb. By Matthew L. Wald.
</P>
<P>
   STANDARDIZED-TESTS-REVIEW (Undated) _ Standardized reading tests
in New York and other states raise questions about the difficulties
of placing a yardstick against the wide range of development of
students so young _ and about whether their ability to deconstruct
a fable, which was included in the New York test, is an appropriate
benchmark and predictor of future success. By Jacques Steinberg.
</P>
<P>
   JORDAN-ANALOGIES-REVIEW (Undated) _ Not every sports star can be
called another Michael Jordan. There's no Michael Jordan of golf
because there's a Tiger Woods of golf. Olympic gold gave freestyle
skier Jonny Moseley so much cachet that he doesn't need anybody
else's famous name. So here's a guide to Jordans still at work.
Meet the Michael Jordan of ... By Caitlin Lovinger.
</P>
<P>
   TRAFICANT-SPEECHES-REVIEW (Undated) _ Rep. James Traficant,
D-Ohio, is a pro-labor, pro-school prayer ex-county sheriff
congressman who has turned the House's traditional one-minute
speech into a personal trademark and art form. A look at some of
his mini-addresses.
</P>
<P>
   DEAD-MAN-WHINING-REVIEW (Hollywood) _ A look into a heated
dispute between actor Sean Penn and 20th Century Fox over the use
of a corporate jet. By Bernard Weinraub.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-QUIXOTE-REVIEW (Undated) _ Impeachment, Henry Hyde, `Man
of La Mancha' and Don Quixote. By Melinda Henneberger.
</P>
<P>
   THISWEEK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Some highlights of the week. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ In the `i' category:
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL-LEGACY-REVIEW (Undated) _ Brazil has been attracting
treasure hunters of all stripes for centuries. From the Portuguese
who colonized it beginning in the 16th century to the Wall St.
money managers who made it a darling of emerging-market investors
in the 1990s, Brazil's economic promise is a perennial lure. But,
as Brazilians like to joke, theirs is the country of the future _
and always will be. By Timothy L. O'Brien.
</P>
<P>
   EXEC-PAY-REVIEW (Undated) _ As the global economy spawns more
mergers between American and foreign companies, discrepancies in
the pay of top executives from each country quickly become
apparent. Then the pay of key officers of the merging companies
typically rises to the higher denominator, and American-style
capitalism claims a little more foreign turf. But is the American
way of compensating top executives _ with opportunity for
tremendous riches from bonuses and incentives tied to a rising
stock price _ better? By Adam Bryant. WITH GRAPHIC.
</P>
<P>
   UNSCOM-REVIEW (Washington) _ The United Nations Special
Commission, charged with disarming Iraq after the 1991 gulf war,
became an international intelligence service for the new world
order. It was the first of its kind _ and, it now seems, maybe the
last. For the more secret its work became, and the more estranged
the enforcers of disarmament grew from each other, the less Unscom
could withstand accusations of serving the last superpower, its
main supplier of spycraft: the United States. By Tim Weiner.
</P>
<P>
   CUBA-REVIEW (Miami) _ One year after Pope John Paul II visited
Cuba and urged the island nation to open itself up to freedom and
to the outside world, the Cuban government has made little progress
in improving its record on human rights, religious freedom and
economic reforms. By Larry Rohter.
</P>
