<HEADER>
A7510 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-THISWEEK-REVIEW-NYT     01-18 1071
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-THISWEEK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
 
 (Repeating for all needing.) 
 The Week in Review 
(bl)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Clinton Is Advised Not to Free Pollard  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Last fall, President Clinton came under pressure from Israeli
Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu to free Jonathan Pollard from the
life sentence he is serving for spying for Israel. The president's
key national security advisers now appear unanimous in urging the
president to keep him locked up.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright said there is no
compelling foreign policy reason to free Pollard. The director of
Central Intelligence, George Tenet, and Defense Secretary William
Cohen said Pollard severely damaged U.S. national security.
</P>
<P>
   _ By JAMES RISEN
</P>
<P>
   A New Look At the Right to Move
</P>
<P>
   The federal welfare revision of 1996 was notable for ending the
concept of welfare as an entitlement, but a less noticed provision
was perhaps even more radical. By letting states pay lower benefits
to newcomers than to long-term residents, Congress challenged a
long-held assumption about U.S. citizenship: that people can move
from state to state without being relegated to second-class status.
</P>
<P>
   California's two-tier welfare program, which holds newcomers for
the first year to the benefits they would have received in their
home states, has now been challenged before the Supreme Court, and
the justices were not buying the state's argument that this was a
minimal, cost-saving measure.
</P>
<P>
   Deeper values were clearly at stake. It was the ``genius'' of
the American system, Justice Ruth Bader Ginsburg said, that
``people can pick their states, but the states can't pick their
people.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By LINDA GREENHOUSE
</P>
<P>
   A Break-In, Yes. But No Watergate.
</P>
<P>
   A break-in at the Washington offices of an American pollster who
advises Ehud Barak, the leader of Israel's opposition Labor party,
at first seemed to have the makings of an Israeli Watergate. But it
caused hardly a ripple in Israel's election campaign, where the two
main candidates were otherwise preoccupied. Barak was at a Labor
convention securing slots for his allies on the party slate. Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu was shoring up support in his own Likud
party, where Moshe Arens, a former ally and mentor, announced that
he would challenge Netanyahu for the party leadership.
</P>
<P>
   _ By JOEL GREENBERG
</P>
<P>
   Olympic Scandal Fallout
</P>
<P>
   Last Thanksgiving, Salt Lake City Mayor Deedee Corradini was
letting slip to reporters that members of the International Olympic
Committee were encouraging her to run for a third term, perhaps
allowing her to preside over the 2002 Winter Olympics in Utah. But
only two months later, the Olympic Committee is imploding over
reports that Salt Lake got the games by bribing members with land
deals, tuition payments, free surgical operations and contributions
to political campaigns and charities.
</P>
<P>
   Now Mayor Corradini has announced she will not run for
re-election this year. Three days before she took that step, the
top leadership of the Olympic Committee resigned, and reporters had
begun to ask the Mayor what she knew about Salt Lake's methods of
winning the selection process.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor has not been publicly linked with any Olympic
corruption allegations.
</P>
<P>
   _ By JAMES BROOKE
</P>
<P>
   Trash Talk From Giuliani
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps eyeing higher office, New York City Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani has roamed from California to New Hampshire touting his
record of cleaning up New York. Now Giuliani is trying to spread
something else around the country: surplus city garbage. New Jersey
balked at his plan to ship trash there, and Virginia wants to block
New York waste.
</P>
<P>
   But the mayor declared that in return for cultural and financial
benefits generated by the city, the rest of the nation has an
obligation to dispose of Gotham's garbage. He even warned of suing.
While his Solutions America political committee is promoting the
mayor nationally, his trash talk ruffled two prominent Republicans,
Govs. James Gilmore of Virginia and Christie Whitman of New Jersey.
Her response: ``Whitman to New York Garbage Plan: Drop Dead.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By BRUCE LAMBERT
</P>
<P>
   A Harsh Strategy For Breast Cancer  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For women with a high risk of breast cancer, a report published
last week offered hope, but at a cruel price. Removing both breasts
while they are still healthy reduces the risk of getting breast
cancer by 90 percent, according to a study of 639 women who had the
surgery from 1960 to 1993 at the Mayo Clinic in Rochester, Minn.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers cautioned that the findings should not be used to
put pressure on patients to take such desperate measures. But women
who wanted the surgery in hopes of preventing breast cancer _ many
of whom had seen mothers and sisters die of the disease _ said
doctors were overly reluctant to recommend the procedure, or, in
some cases, even to talk about it.
</P>
<P>
   _ By DENISE GRADY
</P>
<P>
   A Candidate By Any Other Name
</P>
<P>
   When Lauryn Kaye Valentine of Chicago changed her name to Carol
Moseley-Braun last September, she said she wanted to honor one of
her heroes, Sen. Carol Moseley-Braun, D-Ill.
</P>
<P>
   Honored indeed, said the senator.
</P>
<P>
   But no longer.
</P>
<P>
   The original Ms. Moseley-Braun is out of office now, having lost
a re-election bid in November. But the newly minted Ms.
Moseley-Braun is in, running hard to unseat a veteran Chicago
alderman, Percy Giles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Identity theft,'' says Ms. Moseley-Braun I.
</P>
<P>
   ``Name trickery,'' echoes Giles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Incensed,'' says Ms. Moseley-Braun II.
</P>
<P>
   _ By B. DRUMMOND AYRES Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Princeton Gets the Shivers &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Princeton University president Harold Shapiro suggested ending
the Nude Olympics, an annual tradition in which sophomores run
naked through a campus courtyard at midnight after the first big
snowfall. The problem: Many of the streakers use liquor to numb
their modesty before the cold numbs everything else.
</P>
<P>
   Running drunk and naked in circles around a frozen courtyard can
be perilous. After 350 students participated in this year's run,
five were hospitalized with alcohol poisoning and four more were
treated at the university's health center.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am simply not willing to wait until a student dies to take
preventive action,'' Shapiro wrote in a letter to The Daily
Princetonian, the student newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   _ By DAVID M. HERSZENHORN
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-18-99 0921EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
