<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Monday, Jan. 18, 1999      The Hearst News Service will file the following stories for
Tuesday. If you have questions, please call Tim Spence at
202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   WINTER-SALT (Albany, N.Y.) _ Salt is everywhere these snowy and
icy days. It's essential but destructive. Here are alternatives
that can help make getting through winter easier and with less
mess. By STEVE BARNES.
</P>
<P>
   4WD-SCHOOL (Albany, N.Y.) _ Four-wheel-drive enables you to go
better, but not stop better, said Greg Nikolas, an instructor at
the Land Rover Driving School in Manchester, Vt. ``It's not magic.
It doesn't turn a wet road into dry pavement.'' By JAY JOCHNOWITZ.
</P>
<P>
   CAT-FURNITURE (Albany, N.Y.) _ Almost any cat owner will tell
you that their tabby is used to being pampered. But if you don't
allow kitty in bed with you, don't fret. You can go furniture
shopping instead. A trip to most pet stores will put you in touch
with a fun line of bedding for your feline. By FRANCES INGRAHAM.
</P>
<P>
   TURNING-30 (San Francisco) _ Julie Tilsner marked her 30th
birthday by quitting her job, packing a backpack and joining an
Israeli kibbutz. She also wrote a book, ``29 and Counting: A
Chick's Guide to Turning 30,'' a humorous, light-hearted look at
what can actually be a traumatic subject for many. By CRAIG MARINE.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL (``t'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-COLUMN (Houston) _ One of the most satisfying aspects of
travel is when we come upon a place, or a happening, that takes us
completely by surprise. A secret find. Vintage black-and-white
photographs inside a small chapel in Natchez, Miss., and rekindling
the stagecoach era at the Wolf Creek Tavern in southern Oregon come
to mind. By HARRY SHATTUCK
</P>
<P>
   FILM-TRAVOLTA-PROFILE (Dallas) _ Actor John Travolta talks about
his role in ``A Civil Action,'' his love of flying, his knack for
picking roles and his role in the acclaimed war movie ``The Thin
Red Line.'' By LOUIS PARKS
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   DAVIS-CONSULTANTS (Sacramento, Calif.) _ California Gov. Gray
Davis, who casts himself as a Clinton-style moderate Democrat, is
following the president's lead by keeping his own small army of
consultants and pollsters around after the election. It's what
Clinton and his aides dubbed the ``eternal campaign.'' By ZACHARY
COILE.
</P>
<P>
   PRIEST-LAWSUIT (San Francisco) _ In a highly unusual legal
complaint to secular authorities, a Roman Catholic priest has filed
a lawsuit against San Francisco's archbishop alleging that he was
defamed and penalized for reporting suspected child abuse. By
ELIZABETH FERNANDEZ.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   OUTDOOR-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ The UniCat looks like a garbage
truck in which somebody stuck a Mercedes logo on the grill as a
joke, or maybe a giant 4-wheel-drive Brinks truck loaded with a
million dollars. But it turns out this vehicle is like no other
4-wheel-drive camper in the world. By TOM STIENSTRA.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   E-COMMERCE (San Francisco) _ Sure, some Web sites get a million
hits a day. But how to convert those hits into actual on-line sales
to repeat customers is a whole, 'nother Internet ball of wax.
Studio Archetype Inc., a San Francisco-based Web site design firm,
says it has identified six characteristics will engender the most
trust from consumers. By WENDY TANAKA.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Vast right-wing conspiracies
ain't what they used to be. When we were kids, we watched
military-takeover movies like ``Seven Days in May'' and later
became very paranoid about who was shooting the nation's leaders.
We never thought we'd live to see right-wingers try to overthrow a
president by boring the population into submission. By ROB MORSE.
</P>
<P>
   SALTER-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ We news media types bear much
responsibility for the perceptions of rampant crime that scare Good
Samaritans into hiding. The horrors are rarities. But, somewhere
along the way _ likely with the glut of all-news-all-the-time _
people stopped perceiving of them as rare. By STEPHANIE SALTER.
</P>
<P>
   ROSENFELD-COLUMN (Albany, N.Y.) _ Much of the argument for the
conviction of Bill Clinton presented to the Senate by the
Republican prosecutors rests on the premise that Clinton interfered
with Paula Corbin Jones' ability to have her day in court. By HARRY
ROSENFELD.
</P>
<P>
   ROBISON-COLUMN (Austin, Texas) _ Texas lawmakers, who spent much
of last week praising the Senate's bipartisan traditions, are
taking a step toward partisan politics. And even if this session
manages to mostly avoid partisan fights, watch out in 2001. By CLAY
ROBISON.
</P>
