<HEADER>
A7616 &Cx1f; taf-z
s k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ON-LANGUAGE-$ADV24-NY     01-18 1000
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ON-LANGUAGE-$ADV24-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SWIFT ON CENSURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Jan. 24)  
 (Eds: Items in bold should be set in italics.)  
(mk) 
 By WILLIAM SAFIRE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   What about  &UR; CENSURE &LR; ? in the weeks after House impeachment of
the President,  &UR; censure &LR;  promptly rented space in the halfway house
between Senate conviction and acquittal.
</P>
<P>
   Because this column's pristine purpose is to elucidate, not to
calumniate, let's pull the politicized word out by its roots.
</P>
<P>
   The Latin  &UR; censura &LR;  means ``an assessment, a judgment, a
reprimand.'' The title  &UR; censor &LR;  was given to magistrates in ancient
Rome who supervised public morals and drew up the register, or
 &UR; census &LR; , of citizens. (Enumerating them one by one, of course, not
using statistical sampling, although the related  &UR; censere &LR;  means
``to estimate.'' But back to pristine purpose.) That Latin word for
``judge'' shot off in two directions in English.
</P>
<P>
   One branch led to  &UR; censor &LR; , as the judgment ``to delete or
suppress expression objectionable to those in authority.'' John
Bellenden, in his translation of Livy's history of Rome, observed
in 1533, ``In this yere began the office of  &UR; censouris &LR; ,'' and
 &UR; tsouris &LR;  (Yiddish for ``trouble'') is what writers have been given
ever since. Shakespeare picked it up in ``Coriolanus,'' having
Junius Brutus recall Coriolanus' ancestor as ``twice being
 &UR; Censor &LR; .''
</P>
<P>
   The other branch led to  &UR; censure &LR; . That noun's early meaning of
``opinion'' soon gave way to ``condemnation,'' the sense we use
today. ``Duke Robert justly  &UR; censured &LR;  stood,'' went a 1596
historical poem by Michael Drayton, ``For Disobedience and
Unnaturall Pride.'' (The Duke of Normandy's full name was Robert
Short-Thigh. The surname was quickly discarded by descendants.)
</P>
<P>
   Shakespeare understood the meaning of both branches of
 &UR; censura &LR; . In ``Measure for Measure,'' he had Duke Vincentio opine
that holders of high office cannot escape unfairly harsh criticism
in this life: ``No might nor greatness in mortality/Can  &UR; censure &LR; 
scape; back-wounding calumny/The whitest virtue strikes. What king
so strong/Can tie the gall up in the slanderous tongue?'' White
House aides might consider these words for placement in a stone
carving over the entrance to the Clinton Library.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, the satirist Jonathan Swift, in his 1726
``Gulliver's Travels,'' had a Lilliputian tell the captured
Gulliver, a giant they considered to be threatening their state,
``The council thought the loss of your eyes too easy a  &UR; censure &LR; .''
</P>
<P>
   The verb form paralleled the noun's meaning. Today, the verb  &UR; to
censure &LR;  means ``formally to find fault; to pronounce adverse
judgment; to lay blame; to condemn as wrong.'' In general use, it
need carry no penalty or other punishment.
</P>
<P>
   BLUENOSES
</P>
<P>
   ``Both were single,'' wrote the Times columnist Anthony Lewis
about some snooping into a relationship, ``so the most prurient
 &UR; bluenose &LR;  could not have objected.'' And in David Shaw's book
``The Pleasure Police,'' the media reporter provided the subtitle
``How  &UR; Bluenose &LR;  Busybodies and Lily-Livered Alarmists Are Taking
All the Fun Out of Life.''
</P>
<P>
   The color  &UR; blue &LR;  has long been associated with sex and
profanity. In 1864, John Hotten's slang dictionary had this entry:
`` &UR; Blue &LR; , said of talk that is smutty or indecent,'' and the
slanguist John Farmer noted in 1890 that  &UR; to make the air blue &LR; 
meant ``to curse; to swear; to use profane language.'' A century
before, laws enforcing public morality were christened  &UR; blue laws &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   But whence  &UR; bluenose &LR; ? That word was used by Washington Irving
in 1809 about a New England cheese, and in 1836 by Thomas
Haliburton, Canadian creator of Sam Slick, the Clockmaker, to
describe natives of Nova Scotia. (One theory: It's cold up there,
and noses can turn  &UR; blue &LR; . Another: Fishermen would rub their noses
on their wet  &UR; blue &LR;  sweaters, picking up the dye.) The word was
also applied to a purplish potato and a shellfish known to that
area. In 1858, Oliver Wendell Holmes spoofed the term with
``ceruleo-nasal'' (from the Latin  &UR; caerule &LR; , ``deep blue''), in
reference to a Canadian provincial character working on the
trans-Atlantic submarine cable.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Blue-nose &LR;  was later used to derogate Scottish Presbyterians,
but gained a happier connotation as the name of a speedy fishing
schooner that Canadian yachtsmen still revere, and appeared in 1937
on that nation's 10-cent piece.
</P>
<P>
   Then came Demon Rum. The word was used by friends of John
Barleycorn to sneer at temperance forces inveighing against the
users of alcohol. The OED cites a 1927 usage during the rise of
Prohibition: ``a lot of  &UR; blue noses &LR;  on the Board.'' In that year,
hard-drinking newspapermen who frequented Lipton's saloon in New
York City, near The New York Times building, then on Nassau Street,
referred to the prohibitionists' `` &UR; Blue-Nozzle &LR;  Curse.''
</P>
<P>
   Etymology now has a great tool in cybersearching. I don't
personally indulge, but my research assistant, Kathleen Miller _
with the help of JSTOR, a zingy database that includes obscure
academic publications _ found a reference to  &UR; bluenose &LR;  in a 1990
article by David Jaffee in The William and Mary Quarterly. That led
to an early-19th-century Farmer's Almanack, in which Robert B.
Thomas made up a character, ``Tom  &UR; Bluenose &LR; ,'' along with a
saloonkeeper, ``Toddy Stick,'' to deliver the message of
temperance. (This makes me feel like the madman who contributed
citations to the OED's Sir James Murray.)
</P>
<P>
   The sense of  &UR; bluenose &LR;  we seek goes beyond the temperance
movement to mean ``one who is excessively puritanical; a moralizing
snoop.'' Merriam-Webster has the earliest dictionary citation, from
the 1903 Frank Norris novel, ``The Pit'': ``I was vegetating there
at Barrington, among those wretched old  &UR; blue-noses &LR; .'' Today it
has become an attack on all moralists, whether sincere defenders of
moral principles or the hypocritical hounds: Its meaning is now
``disapproving busybodies.''
</P>
</TEXT>
