<P>
   SOUTHERNSTATES _ With President Clinton's State of the Union
address scheduled tonight, here is a look at the state of the
Southern states, from addresses by their governors over the past
week: Celebrating a new century a year early, the Southern
governors of the new millenium have plugged into the vision thing,
promising higher educational standards for a high-tech economy_and
enough gambling money to pay for them. Education and technology
dominated as themes in inaugural addresses and state-of-the-state
speeches delivered the past week by governors who will lead the
South through the 2000 curtain and into the 21st Century. (Taylor,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS
</P>
<P>
   DELTA _ There's life after airlines for Tom Roeck, even if it's
not with a widebodied corporation. The former Delta Air Lines chief
financial officer, jettisoned along with other top executives in
the management overhaul at Atlanta's biggest employer, has landed
with a small but growing health care firm that blends business and
altruism. We catch up with him and talk about the new job as well
as his days at Delta. (Thurston, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   GPCO _ Companies, like cars, eventually need a tune up. And
that's what Genuine Parts is getting in hopes of reigniting
double-digit sales and earnings growth in its slow-growing, but
highly profitable, distribution businesses. (Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
