<HEADLINE>
KENNETH BRANAGH ON HELENA, HAPPINESS AND THE ART OF ACTING 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of Kenneth Branagh with Helena Bonham Carter
in a scene from ``The Theory of Flight.'' 
 By CINDY PEARLMAN  
 World rights except Chicago 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    You've heard about Kenneth Branagh's allegedly boundless
ambition, his stage triumphs, his epic Shakespearian films, his
sensational divorce from Emma Thompson and his relationship with
Helena Bonham Carter. Could there be anything more to be heard?
 &HT;    How about his life of crime?
 &HT;    The time: winter 1969. The place: a poverty-stricken
neighborhood in war-riven Belfast, Northern Ireland. Enter young
Ken Branagh.
 &HT;    ``The streets were going crazy and people started breaking into
this supermarket,'' the actor recalls. ``The whole place was in an
uproar, and I was gripped by the hysteria.''
 &HT;    Branagh ran in and swiped a package of soap powder.
 &HT;    ``I took it home as a trophy for my mother,'' he says. ``Before
I could say a syllable, I got a smack on the head and was dragged
by the ear amid a mob of rioting people. I had to put the soap back
on the shelf.''
 &HT;    Don't worry, that was long ago. And the soap in his suite at Los
Angeles' Four Seasons Hotel is safe _ since that day, Branagh
hasn't stolen anything but scenes.
 &HT;    Some of those scenes occur in his latest film, Paul Greengrass'
``The Theory of Flight,'' which co-stars Bonham Carter and opens
nationwide Jan. 22. Branagh plays an eccentric artist who, while
trying to build his own flying machine, finds himself the caretaker
to a young woman who, despite being crippled by Lou Gehrig's
disease, is determined to lose her virginity.
 &HT;    It's the latest entry in a barrage from the previously
slow-paced Branagh, including Robert Altman's ``The Gingerbread
Man'' (1998), Woody Allen's ``Celebrity'' (1998) and, opening July
3, a rare big-studio role in ``The Wild, Wild West.''
 &HT;    ``The Theory of Flight'' is by far the smallest in scale of his
recent spate, and Branagh was attracted to it in part by the chance
to work with Bonham Carter for the first time since they met while
co-starring in ``Mary Shelley's Frankenstein'' (1994).
 &HT;    ``Doing this film wasn't just about working with Helena,'' he
adds quickly. ``I admired the writing enormously and admired the
director. Essentially for me, it's all about what's on the page. If
I feel a strong connection, then that is my bedrock.''
 &HT;    Not that Bonham Carter's presence hurt.
 &HT;    ``Of course that was nice,'' Branagh says with a laugh, ``but I
didn't look at our chemistry. It was all about the chemistry
between the characters.
 &HT;    ``Chemistry is such a strange thing. You just feel it,'' he
adds. ``When I audition with actors, there are some people who just
walk into a room and you know you will have it with them, whatever
it is. A compelling, charismatic personal quality sadly has nothing
to do with it _ it really is in the way this person talks or reads
for the part.''
 &HT;    Branagh's most successful performances have come in films which
he also directed _ ``Henry V'' (1989), ``Dead Again'' (1991),
``Peter's Friends'' (1992), ``Much Ado About Nothing'' (1993),
``Hamlet'' (1997) _ but he says he didn't feel awkward acting for
another director.
 &HT;    ``The enjoyment of just acting and having one thing to worry
about was delicious,'' he says. ``I just had to keep my mind
occupied with how I could convey the facets of this troubled,
funny, passionate and slightly crazy man.''
 &HT;    He was never tempted to offer directing suggestions, Branagh
adds.
 &HT;    ``It only occurs to me to direct if I must,'' he says. ``If the
subject matter compels me to the point where I can't do anything
about it but direct, then I step behind the camera.
 &HT;    ``It's like being a painter,'' he adds. ``Sometimes you have to
paint. When I direct, I will notice that something has been
bubbling away at me for two or three years until I must find the
form to tell it.''
 &HT;    Despite his roots in an Irish tobacco-factory town, Branagh is
the first to admit that his rise to fame was meteoric.
 &HT;    ``I hear actors talk about the hard times,'' he says, ``but I am
loath to complain abut anything. I think I've had a very pleasant,
privileged time.
 &HT;    ``My notion of hard times would make many people laugh.''
 &HT;    Actually, his worst moments came after he achieved stardom.
 &HT;    ``I would say that my toughest time was in the wake of making
`Henry V' (1989),'' the actor says. ``I felt I arrived at a
position in the business where there was a level of attention that
I had not remotely anticipated.
 &HT;    ``The years that followed were hard,'' he says. ``It's not like
it was any kind of burning tragedy for me, but I found it difficult
to adjust myself to what seemed to be expected of me. Honestly, I
did not feel myself worthy of the attention or the praise that was
lavished on me.''
 &HT;    It wasn't all praise. The London tabloids had a field day when
Branagh and Thompson, the young ``first couple'' of English acting,
divorced.
 &HT;    ``I guess I don't feel like I was victimized,'' Branagh says,
``but there were some slings and arrows thrown. I was thrown a bit,
and it took awhile to adjust. I had to keep reminding myself that
this was just a tiny and passing phenomenon.''
 &HT;    Do the tabloids still spy on him?
 &HT;    ``Not that I know of,'' he says cautiously, ``but perhaps they
still do. I'm not terribly worried _ I'm convinced that, even if
they were, nobody who reads those things really gives a damn about
me. People are not waking up this morning in this fine land of
yours wondering what I'm up to. It's just as simple as that.
 &HT;    ``I mean, you've got Leo and about 9 million people in front of
me. They're waking up wondering what's going on with them.''
 &HT;    In the wake of unsought notoriety, and with his string of hits
emphatically broken by the failure of ``Frankenstein,'' what's left
for Branagh is the craft of acting. A graduate of the Royal Academy
of Dramatic Arts in London, he went on to become a member of the
Royal Shakespeare Company and the director of his own troupe, the
Renaissance Theater Company.
 &HT;    It was through that group that he met Thompson, and the two rose
to fame together in ``Henry V,'' ``Dead Again,'' ``Peter's
Friends,'' ``Much Ado About Nothing'' (1993) and a television
production of John Osborne's ``Look Back in Anger'' (1993).
 &HT;    Then came ``Mary Shelley's Frankenstein,'' for which
director/star Branagh received precious little critical praise in
either capacity and meager rewards at the box office.
 &HT;    ``I've learned you move on,'' he says. ``You do the best job you
can. I don't think in terms of failure or success _ the success is
if you're happy with the work the moment you say `Cheerio' to it.''
 &HT;    Next up for Branagh is his latest Shakespeare adaptation, a
musical version of ``Love's Labour's Lost'' in which he will
co-star with Alicia Silverstone and Nathan Lane, among others.
 &HT;    ``There's a spectacular dance number,'' he says
enthusiastically. ``The piece also contains this fantastic charm,
sweetness and a great deal of melancholy.''
 &HT;    Branagh concedes that the songs have him a little nervous.
 &HT;    ``I've never done a musical before,'' he says. ``So in the last
few weeks I've been meeting with choreographers. I have to decide
the tempo and sketch out the numbers. I could spend six months
talking about these matters.
 &HT;    ``I've got a shot of panic now,'' the actor admits. ``And then
you take a deep breath and realize that it will all come together.
Each day is a baby step closer to my goal.''
 c.1999 Cindy Pearlman  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Cindy Pearlman is a Chicago-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: Further details on ``The Theory of Flight'' are available
at www.flf.com. &QL; 
