<HEADER>
A7626 &Cx1f; tab-z
w e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCOTT-ADAMS-ON-DILBER     01-18 1443
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTT-ADAMS-ON-DILBERT-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM CUBE TO TUBE: SCOTT ADAMS TAKES `DILBERT' OUT OF HIS CUBICLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of cartoonist Scott Adams at his drawing
board. 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    The carcasses of failed TV shows, plays and movies based on
comic strips and comic books litter the entertainment highway. The
films ``Popeye'' (1980) and ``Howard the Duck'' (1986), the stage
musical ``Doonesbury'' and the television sitcom ``Hazel'' spring
instantly _ and painfully _ to mind.
 &HT;    Yet here comes ``Dilbert,'' debuting Jan. 25 on UPN. Based on
Scott Adams' comic strip about a profoundly overburdened engineer
trapped in his microscopic cubicle, the series features Daniel
Stern as the title character's voice, with Larry Miller as his
tactless Pointy-Haired Boss and Susan Griffin and Gordon Hunt as
his co-workers, the high-strung Alice and the lazy Wally. Back
home, Jackie Hoffman is his busybody Dilmom and Chris Elliott
voices his smart-aleck pooch, Dogbert.
 &HT;    ``It seemed like an obvious idea to all involved,'' Adams says.
``When a cartoon is successful you always think about how to expand
it, and TV is the obvious way to go.''
 &HT;    But will Dilbert _ whose empire already encompasses 1,900
newspapers, four hardcover business books, a dozen reprint
collections, a heavily visited website and more than 100 licensed
products, from CD-ROM games to magnets, ties to training videos _
cut it on television?
 &HT;    ``It's just a matter of good writing,'' the 41-year-old Adams
says by telephone from his home in Danville, Calif. ``I'm not sure
how to define that, other than to say we're trying hard to avoid
all the normal cliches people can see on every other show.
 &HT;    ``Every sitcom, every season, has at least one major episode in
which a major character has a conflict about whether or not they
may be gay,'' he says. ``We won't do that episode.
 &HT;    ``Being a cartoon, we can go places and do stuff you can't do on
a sitcom,'' Adams adds. ``We can change our scenery, bend reality
and violate physics. So we'll take advantage of that.''
 &HT;    Along with Larry Charles of ``Seinfeld'' fame, Adams serves as
executive producer of ``Dilbert.'' He co-wrote the pilot episode,
``The Name,'' and will help write subsequent half-hours as well.
 &HT;    Adams also oversaw the progression of the animation, in order to
ensure character consistency and the proper backgrounds and color
schemes.
 &HT;    ``I can't say I felt at home with the writing,'' he admits,
``because I clearly could not have sat down and written a script
from beginning to end without lots of other people being involved.
I might develop that skill at some point, but it felt to me like
wading into unfamiliar territory.
 &HT;    ``It was fun, though,'' the cartoonist adds. ``I was comfortable
any time I was writing dialogue, but trying to hold in my head an
entire 21-minute story with several subplots is tough.''
 &HT;    A few episodes had been written by the time the actors had been
cast. Once he had the tapes, however, Adams says it made a major
difference.
 &HT;    ``That changed how I wrote,'' he says. ``At this point, when I
write dialogue, I hear the actors' voices. In particular, I hear
Larry Miller when I'm writing the Boss.
 &HT;    ``Oddly enough, I do not hear voices when I write the strip.''
 &HT;    It's been just over a decade since Dilbert first heaved a sigh
of frustration. Bored by his job at Pacific Bell, Adams began
scribbling cartoons in 1988, and one thing led to another.
 &HT;    Adams fine-tuned several strips and shopped them around until
United Features Syndicate agreed to distribute ``Dilbert.'' By
1989, the strip was running in 50 newspapers.
 &HT;    Even then, Adams held onto his day job, drawing his strip early
in the morning before leaving for work. He didn't leave until 1995.
 &HT;    Leaving Pacific Bell gave him pause, Adams acknowledges. He
wondered if ``Dilbert'' might lose its edge once he was out of the
day-to-day workplace politics that had furnished his inspiration.
 &HT;    ``You always worry about that kind of thing,'' he says, ``but,
like so many things you worry about in life, it turned out to be
the opposite of what you imagined.
 &HT;    ``In reality, when I went to the office, I was usually in a
little closed room with two or three people I knew pretty well,''
he recalls. ``So my work life was not very rich with experience.
Being free of that, being able to look through e-mail and broaden
my horizons a little, I probably have a richer pool to draw from at
this point.''
 &HT;    So now Adams devotes his full energies to ``Dilbert'' in all its
myriad incarnations.
 &HT;    ``I imagined it all could happen,'' Adams says, stressing the
second word. ``If you'd put a gun to my head and said, `You must
bet your life that it will happen,' I'd have bet against it.
 &HT;    ``But I'm so eternally optimistic that I always imagine I'll be
changing the world, winning the lottery and learning to levitate my
body with pure thought,'' he says, laughing. ``So I kind of live in
this artificial world of extreme optimism.
 &HT;    ``The most bizarre aspect of it being a reality is that I always
have something to talk about with strangers,'' he adds. ``I'm
naturally shy, but now you can put me in any social context and
I'll automatically have something somebody else wants to talk
about, which makes it easier for me to talk.
 &HT;    ``Totally by accident, I solved the biggest social problem in my
life.''
 &HT;    Now Adams is being asked to solve UPN's problems. The
long-fledgling network counts only ``Star Trek: Voyager'' and
``Moesha'' as bona-fide hits, and is bleeding affiliates and
viewers to its fellow upstart, the WB network.
 &HT;    Some industry watchers speculate that UPN's survival depends on
``Dilbert,'' but Adams refuses to put that kind of pressure on
himself or the show.
 &HT;    ``Clearly, in my opinion, `Dilbert' is not UPN's last, great
hope,'' he says. ``They have very deep pockets, and I think they're
in it for the long haul.
 &HT;    ``Secondly, that seems more like their problem than mine,'' the
cartoonist says. ``My world goes up to but not beyond making a good
cartoon for TV. After that, it becomes an external thing for me
whether or not `Dilbert' changes UPN's fortunes.
 &HT;    ``I mean, I hope it does,'' he adds hastily. ``I want it to,
because I like the people there, and I want them to be successful.
But my responsibility ends at making a good product.''
 &HT;    But even if it succeeds, is there such a thing as too much
``Dilbert?''
 &HT;    ``You worry about how much is out there,'' Adams admits, ``but
if you compare `Dilbert's' exposure to, let's say, `Garfield,'
`Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtles,' `Barney' or `The Simpsons' in its
first year or two, it really doesn't approach that level.
 &HT;    ``Usually, the ones that get exposed to death are child-oriented
properties,'' he adds. ``The ones that can endure a little longer
tend to be ones that reach into adulthood. Mickey Mouse is
well-managed. `Peanuts' is growing like crazy, in Japan in
particular.
 &HT;    ``So you can last 40 years in this business, if you don't rub it
in people's faces.''
 &HT;    Not that he's thinking 30 years down the road.
 &HT;    ``I intentionally don't plan far in advance,'' Adams says.
``I'll almost certainly do `Dilbert' for five more years. Beyond
that, who knows?
 &HT;    ```Dilbert' is a painless thing to do,'' he adds. ``It's easier
for me to imagine me doing it than not doing it, if people still
want to see it. It's a job. It's not enjoyment, like laying at the
beach is enjoyment, but I'm the kind of person who needs to be
working to feel useful.
 &HT;    ``And, as jobs go, it doesn't get any better than this.''
 c.1999 Ian Spelling  
<TEXT>
