<HEADER>
A7627 &Cx1f; tab-z
w e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COUNTRY-SINGER-CHARLE     01-18 1386
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COUNTRY-SINGER-CHARLEY-PRIDE-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MATTER OF PRIDE: CHARLEY PRIDE'S ENDURING LOVE AFFAIR WITH
MUSIC  
 ATTN: TEXAS, MISSISSIPPI 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of country singer Charley Pride. 
 By JERRY ARMOR  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Country singers love to sing about the hardships they've faced,
and more than a few can sing almost as sad a song offstage. The
road to success is a rocky one, they say, and they had to surmount
a lot of obstacles to reach the big time.
 &HT;    Some of them could do with spending a few minutes with Charley
Pride. Virtually none of today's performers has had to contend with
the social and cultural barriers that confronted country music's
greatest black entertainer.
 &HT;    Pride never set out to be a pioneer. He became acquainted with
country music listening to his father's Philco radio in their home
in Sledge, Miss. As the Grand Ole Opry broadcasts filled the
sharecropper's house each weekend, Pride came to know and love the
likes of Roy Acuff, Ernest Tubb and Hank Williams.
 &HT;    Even then, it seemed strange. Many of Pride's family and friends
wondered why a black youngster should be so enchanted with white
folks' music.
 &HT;    Those questions multiplied when Pride acquired a Sears &AMP; Roebuck
guitar, bought with money he'd earned in the cotton fields, and
began to perform that music.
 &HT;    ``Folks were not necessarily angry at me for singing the whites'
music,'' Pride hastens to add. ``It was more curiosity than
anything else, the uniqueness of it _ they were baffled.
 &HT;    ``It's not like they wanted to beat me up or anything,'' he
says. ``It was like, `How come you look like us but sound like
them?' And for the whites, it was `How come you sound like us but
look like them?'''
 &HT;    In the South of Pride's youth, it wasn't only in music that
lines were drawn. Racial segregation was at its height, and every
aspect of life was more complicated for a black youth.
 &HT;    ``You and I could be talking on the street and decide to go into
the drugstore to get a soda,'' Pride tells a white interviewer.
``But we would have to go in through separate doors and sit on
separate sides of the counter. The waiter would serve you, and then
he would turn and serve me.
 &HT;    ``We would be sitting there talking to each other, watching the
same television, yet there was still this barrier between us.''
 &HT;    By the late 1950s, Pride was a confirmed devotee of country
music, but not necessarily a professional. The industry offered
precious few opportunities for a black singer, and Pride _ always a
gifted athlete _ decided that his way to a better life was through
baseball.
 &HT;    A pitcher and outfielder, he began playing in semipro leagues in
the South and later in Montana, soon catching the eye of
major-league scouts. He kept singing, but merely as a diversion.
 &HT;    In 1961 the young man got his shot at the majors, getting an
opportunity with the newly formed California Angels. The music
industry unknowingly got lucky, however, when a nagging injury cut
his sports career short.
 &HT;    ``I had a 90-plus-mile-per-hour fastball,'' Pride recalls. ``But
I had cracked my elbow and tried to come back too soon. The muscles
just never developed. They sent me packing with a tuna-fish
sandwich and an orange.''
 &HT;    So music became his career and baseball the diversion. Even
today he keeps his hand in, occasionally working out with the Texas
Rangers.
 &HT;    ``For a 60-year-old,'' he adds, ``I can still hit the ball
pretty good.''
 &HT;    After being released by the Angels Pride returned to Montana,
where he had a regular job with a mining company. He began singing
in area bars and clubs, where several established artists heard him
and encouraged him to try his hand in Nashville. A contract with
RCA followed, and Pride was on his way.
 &HT;    ``'Most everyone I came into contact with was supportive,'' he
recalls. ``I'm sure there were skeptics, but no one would admit it.
 &HT;    ``But there were certainly some that were behind me from the
beginning, like Red Sovine,'' he adds. ``His son Roger and I are
still good friends _ he knows what his dad meant to me. And there
were others like Ernest Tubb, Buck Owens, Marty Robbins and Mel
Tillis. I could go on and on.''
 &HT;    It wasn't always easy. When he was introduced to an unsuspecting
white audience, he says, a noticeable hush often fell over the
crowd. But it didn't take long for Pride's self-deprecating humor
and warmth _ plus his musical talent _ to win them over. A
truckload of awards, membership in the Grand Ole Opry and 32 No. 1
hits attest to his enduring appeal.
 &HT;    Nevertheless, while a few black country singers have followed in
his footsteps, Pride remains a rarity in an overwhelmingly white
industry.
 &HT;    ``It's like asking why there haven't been any more black
senators or a black president,'' he says. ``I don't think there's
one specific reason. Our society has always been into `ya'll, them
and us.' And that's brought with it years and years of neglect and
being told, `You keep yours and I'll keep mine.'
 &HT;    ``There are too many people still going along with that way of
thinking _ `ya'll, them and us,''' Pride says. ``I've got grandkids
still having to deal with it. What bothers me is that we're still
talking about the same problem, but the problem's still there.
 &HT;    ``I succeeded because I was able to slide around that system of
neglect and being left out.''
 &HT;    Today, Pride says, he's struggling with a different, more subtle
type of discrimination. He and other country-music veterans are
finding themselves pushed aside in favor of younger,
radio-friendly, video-active artists.
 &HT;    ``The moguls have this idea now of throwing 25 artists against
the wall to see if two stick,'' the singer says bluntly. ``But I'm
not going to prostitute myself just to sell a few records.
 &HT;    ``I was still selling when the industry shoved artists like me,
Waylon and Dolly off the labels,'' he says. ``But I think the
pendulum is swinging. I think the moguls are in a quagmire right
now and don't know what to do.
 &HT;    ``I'm going to watch and see how it plays itself out, and I'll
still be here if it swings back around.''
 &HT;    Pride is far from idle, he adds quickly. He performs regularly,
even if he has no current record contract.
 &HT;    ``I'm doing the same thing I've been doing for years,'' he says.
``We'll be going to England, France and Ireland. I've got dates in
Maryland, Texas, North Dakota, Georgia and Iowa. There are places
all over America that are waiting for me to come back. I wish I
could play one show in every state for those fans that I've
neglected.
 &HT;    ``I'm not recording anything new right now,'' he admits, ``but
my management people are talking about it. I feel bad about not
having any new material out there right now _ I've got four
generations of fans that would like to hear something new from
Charley Pride.''
 &HT;    Now, however, Pride seems less inclined to fight the industry
head-on. Secure in his place in musical history, he won't let the
1990s get him down.
 &HT;    ``I'm not trying to compete anymore,'' he says. ``I just want to
do the best I can, do some living of my own and enjoy life. I want
to have the best of both worlds, if I can.
 &HT;    ``The Lord's still blessing me and I can still sing, and if it's
meant to be, it will happen.''
 c.1999 Jerry Armor  
<TEXT>
