<HEADER>
A7628 &Cx1f; tab-z
w e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FRAN-DRESCHER-IN-THE-     01-18 1509
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRAN-DRESCHER-IN-THE-NANNY-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GETTING OFF THE NANNY TRACK: FRAN DRESCHER ON LIFE AFTER `THE
NANNY' 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of Fran Drescher with Charles Shaughnessy in
a scene from ``The Nanny.'' 
 By CHRISTOPHER LOUDON  
 c.1999 TV Guide Canada  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Look up the word ``chutzpah'' in the Hollywood lexicon, and
you're sure to find a photo of Fran Drescher.
</P>
<P>
   Get past that trademark voice _ an attribute she delicately
refers to as a ``nasal nuance,'' though it's more akin to a sack
full of feuding tomcats _ and the carefully cultivated ditziness,
and you'll discover the sharpness and savvy of a corporate
barracuda.
</P>
<P>
   The self-proclaimed ``Jewish neurotic/control freak'' leaves
nothing to chance. Serving as star, executive producer and
occasional director of her six-season hit, while also personally
overseeing everything from publicity photos to script rewrites,
Drescher has not only parlayed her larger-than-life persona into
CBS' longest-running sitcom, but also expanded it into a hit film _
``The Beautician and the Beast'' (1996) _ and her best-selling book
``Enter Whining'' (Regan Books, 1996), not to mention a sizable
fortune.
</P>
<P>
   She's also smart enough to know that it's best to quit while
you're ahead. On Jan. 8, Drescher caught everyone, including her
own network, off guard by telling ``Entertainment Tonight'' that
she had decided to pull the plug at the end of this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always stayed too long at the fair my whole life,'' she
said, ``and I'm not going to do that with `The Nanny.'''
</P>
<P>
   Drescher may have erred in the past, but if so it was always the
result of excessive enthusiasm, not lack of commitment.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you throw yourself into life, you always come back with
gold,'' she wrote in her book.
</P>
<P>
   It's a grab-the-bull-by-the-horns attitude that has served her
well since her high-school days in Queens, N.Y. At age 17, while
working as head fryer at the local Chicken Jamboree, she shelled
out 15 hard-earned bucks to enter herself in the Miss New York
Teen-ager competition.
</P>
<P>
   Disappointed at being only first runner-up, she was convinced by
her mother that coming in second still made her a winner. Yes, she
agreed, and began calling talent representatives, promoting herself
as ``Fran Drescher, the winner of the Miss New York Teen-ager
pageant.''
</P>
<P>
   It wouldn't be everybody's tactic of choice, but it worked. She
got herself an agent and, not long afterward, landed her first
speaking role, a bit part in ``Saturday Night Fever'' (1977).
</P>
<P>
   When the day came to shoot her scene, star John Travolta
announced that he was too tired and depressed to work. But the
determined Drescher refused to let Hollywood histrionics interfere
with her career development. Marching over to Travolta, the
neophyte actress suggested that he smarten up and start behaving
like a professional.
</P>
<P>
   He did. She followed him onto the set, uttered her one line _
``Are you as good in bed as you are on the dance floor?'' _ and
gave him a playful pat on the bottom.
</P>
<P>
   A string of larger parts in less memorable films _ ``American
Hot Wax'' (1978), ``Gorp'' (1980), ``Doctor Detroit'' (1983) _
followed, prompting one magazine writer to refer to her as ``the
actress you can't forget in movies you can't remember.''
</P>
<P>
   The future finally brightened in 1984, when the pivotal role of
music promoter Bobbi Fleckman in Rob Reiner's small-budget cult
classic ``This Is Spinal Tap'' gained her a modest degree of
attention. It led first to a pass from Warren Beatty _ she said no
thanks, she reports _ and ultimately to a more bankable offer from
CBS.
</P>
<P>
   Cast opposite Twiggy and Julie Hagerty, Drescher found herself
on the network's 1991 prime-time schedule as one of the
``Princesses.'' The series lasted less than six weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Her show may have bombed, but the actress's plucky determination
continued unabated. Cornering CBS president Jeff Sagansky on a
trans-Atlantic flight, she convinced him to let her and Peter
Jacobson, her husband and one-time high-school sweetheart, shape a
sitcom more in tune with her unique comic skills.
</P>
<P>
   Voila _ 18 months later, ``The Nanny'' was born.
</P>
<P>
   Six subsequent years as America's favorite ``gefilte fish out of
water'' hasn't dampened Drescher's enthusiasm, but it has made her
wiser.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest rule about show business,'' she says, ``is that
there are no rules. You can be the most talented person in the
world and never get arrested, or you can be the biggest lox and
become a huge star. It doesn't correlate.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you go to medical school and you're an excellent doctor,''
Drescher adds, ``you'll probably work very successfully. But you
can go to Yale and study to be an actor and speak the King's
English and never get a job.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is that the more you know and the more you do
within the industry, the more options and choices you have,'' she
concludes. ``Consequently, now that I have the good fortune of a
hit series, within that realm I'm a director, a producer, a writer
and an actress. And so, when the time comes for `The Nanny' to go
away, I'll have options to do things behind the camera as well as
in front of the camera.''
</P>
<P>
   Already in the works are another high-profile film, a second
volume of memoirs _ ``Still Whining,'' naturally _ and a
development deal with MTV for a comedy series to be called ``The
Daytrippers.''
</P>
<P>
   But ``The Nanny'' has remained her core business, and despite
declining ratings that may have hastened her decision to end the
show, the actress insists that she has no regrets about having
violated one of the cardinal rules of television sitcoms: Don't
change anything.
</P>
<P>
   Altering a well-established show's dynamics with a marriage or a
baby usually rings the death knell _ just ask the folks at ``Murphy
Brown'' or ``Mad About You.''
</P>
<P>
   But Drescher took the lead in pushing to do exactly that,
incorporating both a wedding _ at the end of the past season her
character married her boss, wealthy Broadway producer Maxwell
Sheffield (Charles Shaughnessy) _ and a pregnancy.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were countless discussions about whether or not we
should do this,'' she admits. ``The character is a bit of a sex
symbol, and me getting bigger than a house doesn't somehow go part
and parcel with that. But, just like everything else, we're taking
a leap into the unknown. It kicks us into a whole other place.''
</P>
<P>
   Drescher does, however, concede that the pressure of maintaining
the series has taken a personal toll. Though Jacobson is still
involved with the show, in October 1995 the couple separated after
17 years of marriage and, despite various attempts at
reconciliation, the split now seems permanent.
</P>
<P>
   These days, her companion of choice is Chester _ or, as she
calls him, ``Chest-ah Dresch-ah'' _ an orange Pomeranian that she
purchased as a pup more than a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   Arguably the most pampered pet in Hollywood, Chester goes
everywhere Drescher does and travels with his own luggage _ a
gourmet-takeout bag stuffed with toys, snacks and a chilled bottle
of Evian.
</P>
<P>
   ``What can I say?,'' the actress says with a shrug. ``I totally
indulge him.''
</P>
<P>
   She may be unattached, Drescher adds, but celebrity-spotters
shouldn't waste time looking for her at the Hollywood hot spots on
her rare days off.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know what? I rarely get out of bed,'' she says. ``I have a
massage Saturday morning, and then usually I'm dead all day. I
always have writing to do, so if I can I work out of my bed,
spending hours and hours making very concrete notes and fixes for
the script. Then I get reflexology, and sometimes I turn the phones
off for the rest of the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm telling you, I'm out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   And no, there's nobody sharing those sheets except Chester.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got news for you,'' she says. ``Ever since Peter and I
separated, Chester's got his side of the bed and I've got my side.
All this dog wants is that I should have his puppies _ he totally
thinks that he's my husband now.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Christopher Loudon is the editor of TV Guide Canada, based in
North York, Ontario.) &LR; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) &QL; 
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
