<HEADER>
A7641 &Cx1f; tic-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-IMPEACH-PHOTOS-A     01-18 0388
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-IMPEACH-PHOTOS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE'S BAN ON PHOTOGRA PHY IS DISSERV ICE TO READERS, HISTORY  
 (ADV: THIS EDITORIAL APPEARED IN THE JAN. 17 ARIZONA REPUBLIC) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Imagine an historic event occurring _ only the second
time such a thing took place in the nation's history _ and there
being no way to photograph it.
</P>
<P>
   That's exactly what's happening in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate bars photographers from its chambers. This means that
during President Clinton's impeachment trial, photographers are
allowed only outside the main entrance to the Senate chambers.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, there are visuals available from television recordings made
inside the chamber. But adapting those images to print is difficult
and results in such poor technical quality that the readers of
newspapers and magazines are at a distinct disadvantage in
reviewing the proceedings and the conduct of their elected
officials.
</P>
<P>
   And there's the matter of posterity. Video is one way of
recording history. Still photography is another. Still photos are
easier to view, requiring no equipment or special settings to
peruse. Given the gravity of the proceeding, senators have a
responsibility to ensure maximum documentation of the historic
event.
</P>
<P>
   Some opponents argue that opening the chamber to photography
will be disruptive and distract from the business at hand. Nothing
could be further from the truth. Technical advances allow
photography from the gallery with available light and extremely
quiet equipment. Plus, many news organizations are capable of
providing a pool photographer _ a single photographer whose work is
then pooled and shared with participating news organizations.
</P>
<P>
   The House allowed still photographers in its chambers for its
proceedings, and the photographers produced an important
documentary record of the impeachment debate and vote last month.
</P>
<P>
   Many organizations _ including the American Society of Newspaper
Editors, the Associated Press and the Standing Committee of Press
Photographers _ have urged Sens. Trent Lott, Mitch McConnell, Tom
Daschle and Christopher Dodd to permit the Senate proceedings to be
photographed.
</P>
<P>
   We urge you, newspaper and magazine readers, to do the same.
It's your interests that are at stake. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-18-99 1227EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990118.0129 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 12:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7658 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WINTER-SALT-HNS &LR;      01-18 1140
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINTER-SALT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SALT: THE NECESSARY INGREDIENT OF WINTER LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: Optional chart follows.)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEVE BARNES  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Consider salt, that lowly crystal.
</P>
<P>
   It once was precious: The word ``salary'' derives from
``salarium,'' the Latin word referring to money given to Roman
soldiers to purchase salt.
</P>
<P>
   These days common salt (chemical name sodium chloride, symbol
NaCl) is, well, common: Sprinkled from shakers, spun by the ton
from the stern of salting trucks, used to cure leather and to
season the meat from which the hide was skinned.
</P>
<P>
   A necessary component in blood, salt also is used to keep the
contents of our traffic arteries flowing. Similarly, just as too
much salt in a diet causes health problems, excess sodium chloride
outside is harmful.
</P>
<P>
   Look at the side of your car, wainscotted with road salt.
</P>
<P>
   Look at your carpets, at that pale perimeter adding
circumference daily from footwear puddles.
</P>
<P>
   Look at your pet, busily licking its paws before trotting to the
water bowl to soothe a salt-scorched tongue.
</P>
<P>
   Salt is destructive. But it is a necessary nuisance. The
alternative? Roads that resemble bobsled chutes. Slick sidewalks
and whoops, off to central casting goes another fractured wrist,
hip, noggin.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really don't like to see the level of (salt) usage that we
have now,'' said Willard Bruce, commissioner of the Department of
General Services in Albany, a snowy upstate New York city that
spends $250,000 a year on road and sidewalk salt alone, about a
quarter of its snow-removal budget. During an average winter, the
area uses 100,000 tons of salt to tame the snow and ice.
</P>
<P>
   However, Bruce said, ``We're a city, a population of people who
travel by foot. We don't have an alternative.''
</P>
<P>
   Salt keeps us going in the winter. But we needn't suffer its
ravages passively.
</P>
<P>
   For homeowners, other ice-melt compounds less corrosive than and
superior in performance to sodium chloride are available to scatter
on sidewalks and driveways. Different types of salt _ potassium or
calcium chlorides _ cost too much to use on roads but are ideal for
smaller jobs: They work faster and at lower temperatures than
common salt. And nitrogen fertilizer, or urea, won't harm grass,
plants or concrete the way salts do. Its downside: slow melting
speed.
</P>
<P>
   Urea is the suggested method of attack on walkways, around
flowerbeds and on driveway edges, said Ken Carnes, the
commercial-landscape nursery agent for Cornell Cooperative
Extension of Albany County. Salts of all kinds seep into the soil
and compete with plant roots for moisture, whereas fertilizer soaks
into the ground and helps plants and grasses immediately. Only
several days of strong spring rains will help leach salts from the
earth, Carnes said.
</P>
<P>
   Salts thrown from snowblowers also damage evergreen trees and
bushes, Carnes said, by extracting moisture from their needles. His
suggestion: urea again, or a secure winter cloak of burlap for pine
bushes.
</P>
<P>
   Salt similarly sucks the suppleness from leather shoes, which
can suffer permanent damage if salt residue isn't removed daily.
Regular cleaning and treatment with protective oils is recommended.
</P>
<P>
   The first step toward preventing salt damage to rugs and carpets
is an entryway rubber mat and a strict rule against walking onto
rugs with snow- and slush-coated boots, said Jim Hennesey, owner of
Carpetmaster Carpet Cleaning in Cohoes, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   ``The acid nature of salts can permanently bleed and bleach
carpeting,'' Hennesey said. Blot up any trailed-in snowmelt, he
suggests, and vacuum thoroughly once the spot dries. A steam or
hot-water-extraction cleaning of carpets once or twice a winter
will fully flush any remaining salts or their oils.
</P>
<P>
   Salts irritate and can cause sores on pet paws, said Dr. Jane
Farrell, a veterinarian at Animal Health Center in nearby Clifton
Park. That's more of a problem with dogs, who walk on sidewalks and
roads with owners.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rock salt is known to cause inflammation in between the toes
and the pads,'' Farrell said. ``One of the signs is that the dog
starts to lick its feet excessively, and sometimes if it's really
bad they will limp.''
</P>
<P>
   Farrell advised a thorough paw rinse when the dog returns
indoors or, if the pooch will tolerate them, dog booties.
</P>
<P>
   There are no snow booties for cars. Drive a car in the snow and
it soon will wear a chloride coat.
</P>
<P>
   ``We love to see salt on the roads and cars getting dirty,''
said Tom Hoffman Jr., whose family owns 16 carwashes in the Albany
area. Winter is the company's busiest season, Hoffman said, and
customers especially appreciate Hoffman Car Wash's ``bottom blast''
feature that hoses off undercarriages, where rust usually starts.
</P>
<P>
   Yet when the weather is as sloppy as it has been so far this
month, customers bathe their vehicles less frequently than when
regular storms are separated by several nice days.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need some sunshine,'' Hoffman said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Among the popular ice-melt products available in hardware,
grocery and home-care stores:
</P>
<P>
   _ Sodium chloride (rock salt). Characteristics: The same stuff
as table salt but less refined; like all salts, melts ice and/or
lowers the freezing point of water; good down to about 5
Fahrenheit. Pluses: Cheap, effective, widely available. Minuses:
Corrosive; catalyst for vehicular rust; harms shoes, plants, grass,
evergreens, pet paws, concrete; doesn't work in extreme cold.
Price: About $5 per 50-pound bag.
</P>
<P>
   _ Calcium chloride. Characteristics: Available in pellet and
flake forms; concentrated, meaning less needed per application;
some blends good down to 15 or 20 below zero. Pluses: Fastest
melter, less likely to be tracked into homes and cars, less
corrosive than salt. Minuses: Expensive, more corrosive when pure
than in blends. Price: About $15-$20 for 50 pounds, depending on
type and blend.
</P>
<P>
   _ Potassium chloride. Characteristics: Usually found in blends
with sodium chloride and/or other chemicals; faster than salt but
slower than pure calcium chloride; good for down to just below
zero. Pluses: In pure form is safest for all surfaces; less
corrosive than salt. Minuses: More expensive than salt; slower than
calcium chloride. Price: $12 to $15 for 50 pounds, depending on
blend.
</P>
<P>
   _ Nitrogen fertilizer (urea). Characteristic: Not a salt, so
won't harm vegetation; good down to just above zero. Pluses:
Cheaper than calcium and potassium chlorides; fertilizes lawns,
flower beds as soaks into soil; doesn't harm walkways; less residue
to be tracked in. Minuses: Works more slowly than salts; more
needed per application than salts; will damage shoes, rugs, pet
paws. Price: About $10 for 40 pounds.
</P>
</TEXT>
