<HEADLINE>
GOOD SAMARITANS: AS RARE AS HEINOUS CRIMES 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEPHANIE SALTER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Reports of violent crime are down all over
America with murder at its lowest level in 31 years. All the law
and order agencies who keep statistics swear the decline is real.
</P>
<P>
   Do you feel safer? Find yourself relaxing with your kids in the
car? Taking solitary walks at night? Trusting strangers more? Why
is the reality of a safer America so hard to accept?
</P>
<P>
   I've been thinking about this ever since my friend Bernie Ward,
a radio host in San Francisco, called to ask my opinion about a
recent encounter he had. Driving home from work after 1 a.m., he
stopped at a red light where a man was standing in the street,
screaming for help because someone had stolen his car.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe if the light had turned, I'd have driven on,'' Bernie
said. ``But I was stuck, and I made eye contact. The guy was
desperate.''
</P>
<P>
   Bernie not only stopped, he let the man get in his car, and gave
short chase when they saw the stolen vehicle a few blocks away.
After the thief ditched them, Bernie waited while the man called
the cops and gave them a report. Then he taxied the carless guy to
his house a few miles away.
</P>
<P>
   Bernie's wife (and mother of their four children) was furious
that he'd put himself in such a dangerous position. About 95
percent of Bernie's weeknight audience _ he shared the story on the
air _ sided with his wife. Even his Sunday morning ``Godtalk''
listeners, typically a kinder, gentler bunch, overwhelmingly agreed
he shouldn't have done it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still kind of flabbergasted,'' Bernie said. ``Is the Good
Samaritan dead?''
</P>
<P>
   My guess is, no. But he and she are so deep in hiding, they
might as well be.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe this is because people today are harder-hearted than they
were when Jesus spoke of a Samaritan who put aside sworn enmities
and carried a battered Jew to safety. Much more likely, the
potential Good Samaritans of 1999 are simply paralyzed with fear _
irrational fear, based on perception, not reality.
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago while I was home in Indiana, I walked into a
Sam's Club, the members-only offspring of Wal-Mart. On display in a
clear plastic case near the entrance of the store was a lightweight
bullet-proof vest.
</P>
<P>
   Part of a police exhibit? No. It was a coming attraction for the
store's shelves. As the printed material in the case explained, a
bullet-proof vest was the ultimate protection for today's smart and
concerned American.
</P>
<P>
   I looked around at the housewives in sweatsuits, the
overall-clad farmers, the jeans-and-T-shirted college kids, and I
wondered: What kind of society produces small town, hard-working
Hoosiers who believe they need a bullet-proof vest to survive life?
</P>
<P>
   Although it is not exclusively our fault, we news media types
bear much responsibility for this sorry phenomenon. As much as any
force, we help scare Good Samaritans into hiding. Every day on the
front page and on the nightly news, we deluge folks, not with the
accounts of millions who made it home safely, but with murders,
rapes, kidnappings and mega rip-offs.
</P>
<P>
   These horrors are rarities; that is why they are ``news.'' But,
somewhere along the way _ likely with the glut of
all-news-all-the-time _ people stopped perceiving of them as rare.
</P>
<P>
   When Bernie first told me his story, I had many of the same
reactions his wife and listeners had. But as we talked, something
dawned on me: Bernie recounted the story, not from a hospital bed
or posthumously via dramatic 911 tape, but from the peace of his
living room. Nothing bad had happened to him.
</P>
<P>
   Was this just because he was ``lucky''? Or was it because the
odds of getting killed, injured or badly suckered _ even when you
help a stranger late at night on a city street _ are still mighty
low?
</P>
<P>
   ``Forget all the crud we report for a minute,'' I told Bernie.
``How many people do you personally know who got killed, hurt or
ripped off because they stopped to help someone in trouble?''
</P>
<P>
   Bernie thought. I thought.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody,'' he finally said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Me either.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stephanie Salter is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
