<SLUG> BC-CABIN-FEVER-LIFEBEAT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOUR CURES FOR CABIN FEVER
</HEADLINE>
  By LORI B. MURRAY 
 c.1999 Lori B. Murray 
 World rights 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   By the time February arrives, the holidays are long gone, and
midwinter blues are center stage. It's time to get creative about
your leisure time with the kids -- before cabin fever gets the best
of everyone.
</P>
<P>
   Here are a few ideas:
</P>
<P>
   _ BUILD A BACKYARD ICE RINK
</P>
<P>
   Even if you're lucky enough to have a pond nearby, it may not be
safe for skating. Build your own fun with a backyard ice rink.
Invite the neighborhood kids and serve hot chocolate to warm little
bodies.
</P>
<P>
   1. Locate some level ground. Build a frame using lumber that is
1'' thick and 10'' high. Stake the frame on the outside so that
when the ice expands, your frame won't be knocked over.
</P>
<P>
   2. Build your frame on a warm day when the ground is still soft.
</P>
<P>
   3. Material for the inside of the rink should not be put in
place until it gets cold. It should be in one piece, without seams,
and it cannot be taped together. Either Visqueen (8 millimeter
thickness) or Permalon white plastic work well as a liner and can
be found at building supply stores. Don't use dark colors since
they absorb sunlight, making it harder to freeze.
</P>
<P>
   4. Carefully place the plastic sheeting inside your frame,
butted completely against the wall or frame. When you add water,
you will need to adjust the plastic so that it fits snugly but does
not pull.
</P>
<P>
   5. Use furring strips to hold the plastic in place over the top
of the frame.
</P>
<P>
   6. Keep leaves off the ice. Flood the ice nightly to smooth it
out after use and thawing.
</P>
<P>
   7. Add lighting for night skating if you wish.
</P>
<P>
   _ BAKE BREAD
</P>
<P>
   Whether you bake basic bread or quick, sweet bread, there's
nothing more satisfying than the smell of fresh bread baking in the
oven on a winter day. Don't be shy about making a loaf from
scratch; kids like to get their hands gooey and watch the dough
rise.
</P>
<P>
   Try the following kid-friendly books for bread recipes and tips:
</P>
<P>
   ``Bake Bread!'' (J.B. Lippincott Co., 1976); ``Knead It! Punch
It! Bake It! -- Make Your Own Bread'' (Thomas Y. Crowell, 1981);
``Let's Bake Bread!'' (Lerner Publications Co., 1973); ``Betty
Crocker's Breads'' (Western Publishing Co., 1974); ``The
Breadbasket Cookbook'' (Walker Books Limited, 1982).
</P>
<P>
   _ HAVE AN INDOOR PICNIC
</P>
<P>
   Get out the picnic basket, spread the tablecloth on the floor,
and build a fire in the fireplace. All you need now is some great
picnic food to complete the mood.
</P>
<P>
   Here is a simple menu:
</P>
<P>
   Roasted Whole Chicken
</P>
<P>
   Waldorf Salad (easy and fun for kids to make)
</P>
<P>
   Banana Cupcakes
</P>
<P>
   _ CAMP IN
</P>
<P>
   Sure, it's too cold to camp in the snow, but an indoor camp-out
in the family room by the fireplace sounds inviting. Pull out the
sleeping bags, hoist the tent, roast some marshmallows, and tell
campfire stories or sing songs. You won't have any stars to gaze
at, but the flames in the fire will do.
</P>
<P>
   --------
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Lori B. Murray is a free-lance writer based in Columbus,
Ohio.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call New York Times
Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at (732) 390-4480 or
fax her at (732) 390-4697.
</P>
