<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BELOW THE BELTWAY BOREDOM 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROB MORSE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Vast right-wing conspiracies ain't what they
used to be.
</P>
<P>
   When we of Bill Clinton's generation were kids, we watched
military-takeover movies like ``Seven Days in May'' and later
became very paranoid about who was shooting the nation's leaders.
</P>
<P>
   We never thought we'd live to see right-wingers try to overthrow
a president by boring the population into submission.
</P>
<P>
   How many of you listened to all of the Republican ``impeachment
trial managers'' cite the same evidence against President Clinton
over and over again?
</P>
<P>
   How many of you were electrified by the constantly repeated
high-flown verbiage about Clinton's low acts and misdemeanors,
words like ``perjurious,'' ``egregious'' and ``web of deceit''?
</P>
<P>
   How many of you snapped your fingers and said, ``I get it now.
He's a liar. It isn't about sex. It's about perjury.''
</P>
<P>
   Sorry, but approximately zero Americans stayed tuned through the
dullest attempted coup in history. Exactly zero changed their minds
about anything.
</P>
<P>
   Mind you, boring the populace into passivity isn't just a
Republican tactic, although they seem to have perfected it.
</P>
<P>
   Inflicting boredom is how both parties keep the citizenry out of
politics, leaving democracy in the hands of reliable fanatics,
advertising geniuses and rich special interests.
</P>
<P>
   At newspapers, where some of us feel obliged to witness history
even at its most tedious, we stayed awake by having contests based
on the trial managers.
</P>
<P>
   Worst comb-over: Steve Chabot. The immobile camera was a
comb-over cam, installed at a very unflattering but appropriate
angle _ looking down on the trial managers.
</P>
<P>
   Worst folksy opening: Bill McCollum's golly-geeing about his awe
at God and nature when he saw the snow and geese outside the
Capitol. Apparently, the geese were attracted by all the honking
inside.
</P>
<P>
   Best mispronunciation: McCollum pronouncing ``genitalia'' as
``genitillia.'' He was talking about something all too famillia.
</P>
<P>
   Best saying: Ed Bryant's comment, ``In Tennessee, we have a
saying for situations like that. It's `That dog won't hunt.''' We
have a saying in California: ``Totally bogus.''
</P>
<P>
   Best title for a chart: ``The Seven Pillars of Obstruction'' _
just like T.E. Lawrence's book ``The Seven Pillars of Wisdom,'' but
without the wisdom.
</P>
<P>
   Worst disease metaphor: Bob Barr's call to excise ``insidious
cancers that eat at the heart of our system of justice so they
might not fester as a gaping wound, poisoning our system of justice
and future generations.''
</P>
<P>
   Off with his head and the pointy white hat he probably wears on
it.
</P>
<P>
   Most dramatic moment. Hell, only dramatic moment: Sen. Tom
Harkin stood up just before Barr could end Friday's presentations
and, in words that actually said something, objected to the trial
managers referring to senators as jurors.
</P>
<P>
   I fell out of my chair. The senators apparently all woke up or
dropped their hidden Agatha Christie novels.
</P>
<P>
   Harkin listed the ways in which senators are different from
jurors, left Barr with nothing better than his mixed disease
metaphor, and captured the evening news for the Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   The problem with trying to bore the populace into submission is
that one interesting interruption blows the whole thing.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it didn't really blow the whole thing. It just
temporarily took the windiness out of the prosecution's sails. Who
cares if senators are called jurors? Is it yet another exercise in
applied semantics by a Democrat? Well, yes. But it also was a
living demonstration that impeachment really is political, as
Alexander Hamilton wrote in the Federalist Papers.
</P>
<P>
   It also was an assertion by a senator that no upstarts from the
House could call him a mere juror. Chief Justice William Rehnquist
of the Supreme Court sustained Harkin's objection, and suddenly
Rehnquist was no longer a dignified prop in the Republicans'
droning production.
</P>
<P>
   Harkin made a carefully calculated guerrilla attack on the House
Republicans' slow-moving impeachment train, perhaps even risking
imprisonment, and suddenly we were in a world of spin _ not that
many Americans were paying attention.
</P>
<P>
   I can't blame you. I feel like I've been trampled by stampeding
mice. Do the Republicans really think they can destroy Clinton with
their constant squeaks of ``perjurious'' and ``genitillia''?
</P>
<P>
   This whole thing was just to convince the Senate to call
witnesses, specifically the two most familiar with the genitillia
in question.
</P>
<P>
   If the case against Clinton is so open-and-shut, as the
impeachment managers kept saying, why do they need witnesses? They
just want to drag Monica and Bill into the Senate and titillate the
nation into understanding how awful the president is.
</P>
<P>
   These Republicans should find some dirty sites on the Internet
and leave the rest of us alone.
</P>
<P>
   Oh well, fair's fair. Now the Democrats will have their chance
to bore the nation into passive pulp, and I have full faith they're
up to the job.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
