<HEADLINE>
NEW BALANCE: SURPRISINGLY, IT'S A LA MODE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TINA CASSIDY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Alysson Saada has a black pair, a red pair, and a gray
pair, effectively covering her footware needs. No surprise in this
fashion-setting metropolis.
</P>
<P>
   But the real shock is this: Her shoe of choice is an
original-style New Balance sneaker, known around Boston, where the
company is based, as a more pedestrian, comfort-oriented selection,
prescribed by podiatrists and worshiped by marathoners.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, they are very popular,'' said Saada, a Parisian teenager
who teethed on glossy sartorial publications.
</P>
<P>
   The retro-looking sneakers, however, are not just a youth fad.
</P>
<P>
   At Les Galleries Lafayette, an ornate, designer-clothing
department store here, men's New Balance in camel-colored suede are
on display in the Trends section, along with space-age luggage,
rubber vases, fold-up motor scooters, and other sharp design ideas.
The price: 650 francs. That's more than $100.
</P>
<P>
   In a minimalist but casual restaurant, a New Balance stick out
from under a waitress's long white apron. A man on a cell phone
outside the Hugo Boss shop dons a pair to match his black pinstripe
pants.
</P>
<P>
   And window displays across the city show the sneakers next to
cashmere sweaters and stylish slacks.
</P>
<P>
   New Balance executives trace the fad to the spring of 1997, when
designer Lucien Pellat-Finet used the funky-colored sneakers in his
runway fashion show here. He chose the company's oldest
``heritage'' styles, known as numbers 576 and 572, which have not
changed much since they were first rolled out, except for the new
tones.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a performance-oriented company, rather than
fashion-oriented,'' said Ariane Kjellquist, a New Balance
spokeswoman. ``We were just trying to do something a little
different with it. We weren't changing the components. The fashion
market decided it was fashionable.''
</P>
<P>
   A rainbow line was introduced in Europe so as not to interfere
with the company's deftly cultivated image in the United States as
a serious running shoe. But New York retailers picked up on the
trend and began illegally importing the shoes, selling them for
$150.
</P>
<P>
   So New Balance coalesced and introduced the line back home
beginning in August in four colors: orange, sky blue, lime green,
and red. In October, another shipment came to America in teal,
wheat field (mustard), and deep purple. They cost about $110 here,
mostly sold in upscale department stores.
</P>
<P>
   Designer Tommy Hilfiger and even the august fashion house Hermes
are knocking off the look _ Hermes in gold lame.
</P>
<P>
   Sneakers have been part of street fashion for years, especially
in the 1990s, and especially dominated by Nike Inc. That company,
based in Beaverton, Ore., is in turmoil because of an economic
slowdown in Asia, sluggish sales in the United States, and a poor
performance in Europe, according to financial analysts who follow
the footware giant.
</P>
<P>
   One can see the shift toward a ``fresher'' footwear look on the
streets of Paris, even if they are the same old sneakers New
Balance has been making since the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   Saada, in her gray New Balance, and her friend Fiona Alliel, in
a black pair constructed of nylon and suede, strutted comfortably
on a recent day not far from the upscale Place Vendome. They left
their dusty Nikes in the back of the closet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got one pair of Nikes,'' Alliel said. ``But these are
more popular.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Saada, looking down at her feet: ``It's fashion a la mode,
of the moment. Nike is passe. Voila!''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
