<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-QUESTIONS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT'S UP WITH THE MOON? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID ROPEIK  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. The moon has been up to some unusual behavior recently,
prompting question from several readers, including J.B in Groton,
Mass., and C.C., who didn't provide a hometown.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. There are two full moons this month and again in March on the
same dates (the 2d and the 31st), but no full moon at all in
February. That last happened in 1915, and it won't happen again
until 2018.
</P>
<P>
   February last lacked a full moon in 1961; it won't again until
2018.
</P>
<P>
   December's full moon fell on the first day of winter; that last
occurred in 1980, and it will happen again this year.
</P>
<P>
   The moon takes an average of 29 1/2 days to orbit the Earth. But
the lengths of our months _ 28 to 31 days _ don't precisely match
the moon's cycle. So each phase of the moon occurs 12.3683 times
per year. That's why over the years oddities like this one occur.
</P>
<P>
   The instant the moon passes the sun it's known as the
astronomical new moon. If the moon passes directly in front of the
sun it causes a solar eclipse, but usually it passes just above or
below and rises and sets almost at the same time, abandoning the
night sky
</P>
<P>
   A week later, we see half a moon, what astronomers call the
first quarter moon. One week later, with the sun and moon on
opposite sides of Earth, the whole moon is glowing and is view most
of the night. That's the full moon. The last quarter moon occurs a
week later. The tiny crescent moon phase occurs a day or two on
each side of the new moon.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Why is our atmosphere so different from that of Venus, which
is 90 times thicker than ours?
</P>
<P>
   D.T., Rockport (Mass.) High School
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. In one way, carbon dioxide-breathing plants would be very
happy on Venus. The atmosphere there is 96 percent CO2. Compare
that with our atmosphere, which is a third of 1 percent CO2.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, all that carbon dioxide creates other conditions on
Venus, the second planet from the sun, that plants would not be
happy about. Like a surface temperature of 860 degrees Fahrenheit,
caused by the greenhouse effect of carbon dioxide; it traps solar
radiation before it can bounce off the planet's surface and back
out into space. In fact, though Venus is twice as far from the sun
as Mercury, it's surface is much hotter. Don't put lead in a
spaceship to Venus. It would melt!
</P>
<P>
   The different composition of the Venusian atmosphere creates a
surface pressure 90 times greater than sea level air pressure on
Earth. Standing on the surface there would be equivalent to being
about 3,000 feet down in the ocean here.
</P>
<P>
   Earth and Venus are made of the same basic minerals, they're
close in size and mass, and are thought to have similar seismic,
volcanic and tectonic activity. The reason the atmosheres are so
different is, in a word, life. On Earth, biological processes
gobble up carbon dioxide as it erodes out of minerals and enters
the atmosphere. The ocean's plants are a huge `sink' for CO2, for
example. So are terrestrial flora. But on Venus, when CO2 goes up,
it stays up.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Readers are invited to send science questions to How&AMP;Why. Write
to How&AMP;Why, Health/Science, Box 2378, The Boston Globe, Boston, MA
02107; or send via Internet to: howwhy(at)globe.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-18-99 1328EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990118.0140 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 13:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7702 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRELAND-CHANGE-BOS &LR;      01-18 1649
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRELAND-CHANGE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRELAND CHANGING _ FOR BETTER OR BITTER? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DUBLIN _ What does it say about Ireland when they'll bulldoze a
house James Joyce lived in and yet spend $5 million on a
contemporary artwork that no one seems to like?
</P>
<P>
   It says, in short, that Ireland has changed and, as Yeats once
put it, changed utterly.
</P>
<P>
   Ireland's booming economy has wrought some wonderful things,
none better than that most young Irish people are no longer forced
to leave their homeland to make a living. And in a country where 45
percent of the population is under 25, and which has scattered
generations across the world since the potato blight of 1845, that
is no small change.
</P>
<P>
   But prosperity has some unwelcome byproducts as well: more
crime, traffic gridlock, a growing gap between rich and poor, and
spiraling housing prices that make it nearly impossible for
first-time buyers to find a home within an hour's drive of Dublin,
where a third of the country's 3.6 million people live.
</P>
<P>
   Yet perhaps the most profound effect this new prosperity has had
on Irish society is the consensus that anything new is inherently
better than anything old, that something big and bold is
intrinsically preferable to something smaller or subdued. That
mentality led to Joyce's onetime home on Millbourne Avenue _ the
one in ``Portrait of the Artist As a Young Man'' _ being torn down
against only the isolated howls of Joycean scholars. And it is the
same mentality that proposes putting up a 300-foot stainless-steel
pole at the end of O'Connell Street to mark the millennium.
</P>
<P>
   For generations, the Irish have been poor but comforted by
knowing they were among the most literate people on the planet. Now
prosperity seems to be steamrolling over things the Irish once held
sacred, such as literary heritage.
</P>
<P>
   Recent European Union studies found that the Irish are spending
the bulk of their new disposable income on gourmet food and
alcohol, as fine wine makes inroads against the durable Irish
favorite, the dark and mysterious stout, usually Guinness. Another
study found that many of the trendy Dublin restaurants have noise
levels that could damage the hearing of those working in them.
</P>
<P>
   But while some, such as the Dublin writer Hugo Hamilton,
complain that prosperity is turning Ireland into a bland,
homogenous place where art is being squeezed out by the cult of
celebrity, others say Ireland is undergoing an artistic renaissance
not seen since the turn of the century, when Yeats, O'Casey, Wilde,
Shaw, Synge, and others helped define what it was to be Irish.
</P>
<P>
   Carmel Fitzsimons, the London-based Irishwoman who just won the
prestigious Patrick Kavanagh Poetry Award, says the economic boom
is being matched by a cultural boom.
</P>
<P>
   ``At last, it is cool to be Irish,'' Fitzsimons says. ``We are
no longer the barmen and waitresses of the world. It's culture, not
boozing, that is flourishing again in Ireland.''
</P>
<P>
   Helena Kennedy, who recently became the first woman to head the
British Council, Britain's biggest cultural organization, agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nations going through periods of dramatic change often have a
surge of creativity,'' says Kennedy, a Scot whose grandmother was
Irish. Kennedy believes the Irish are at the height of their
cultural influence internationally, from U2, the singing group, to
Seamus Heaney, the Nobel poet, to Martin McDonagh, the young
playwright whose ``Beauty Queen of Lenane'' won four Tony awards on
Broadway last year.
</P>
<P>
   Ireland lets its artists live tax-free, and it is one of the few
nations that puts its writers on its currency. But even that will
end in three years as the euro replaces the Irish pound, a telling
development because Irish culture is increasingly becoming a hybrid
of ancient Celtic and modern European influence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Riverdance,'' the phenomenally successful dance show, was
actually the outgrowth of a segment staged for the Eurovision song
contest, part of the EU's attempt to promote the notion that there
is something approaching a common European culture. ``Riverdance''
has exposed Irish dance to millions who would otherwise never have
seen it. But is it truly a modern version of traditional Irish
stepdancing? Or is it, and its progeny, ``Lord of the Dance,'' just
a sexualized version of Irish dance that uses great athleticism and
skimpy outfits to market something deemed unwatchable by someone
not Irish?
</P>
<P>
   Are the Corrs authentically mixing traditional music with their
catchy pop tunes, or is it, as some critics claim, a faux,
patronizing Irishness?
</P>
<P>
   There are some who believe the critics take themselves too
seriously. Geoffrey Keating, the Irish government's cultural
attache in London, believes Irish culture has never been more
accessible nor a more accurate reflection of a people who claim a
diaspora of 70 million around the world, including 40 million
Irish-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being Irish used to be this narrow test that was
exclusionary,'' Keating says. ``Now it's inclusive, it reflects the
diversity of what it means to be Irish.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Change is everywhere in Ireland. Galway is the fastest-growing
city in Europe, its narrow streets clogged with young people and
hip shops. The rural countryside, its haunting beauty an
inspiration to generations of writers and visual artists, is
increasingly becoming dotted with vacation homes, some of them used
only a few days or few weeks of the year. In the past, most homes
in the lush fields of West Cork or the moonlike landscape of
Connemara belonged to rich foreigners. Now, the countryside is
being spoiled by noveau riche natives, many of whom have built
large, ostentatious second homes for the generous tax break
involved.
</P>
<P>
   But for all the change in the countryside, nowhere is the change
more pronounced than in Dublin. Bewley's Oriental Cafe, a fixture
on Grafton Street, the city's main shopping area, recently had a
face lift that some traditionalists abhor, lamenting that a Dublin
institution has been transformed into something resembling one of
the ubiquitous new cosmopolitan cafes.
</P>
<P>
   The traditional pub, so central to Dublin's character, is
gradually being replaced by European-style cafes with sleek lines,
plateglass windows and, despite only infrequent sunshine, alfresco
seating. The European ethos of these places is just the opposite of
the traditional pub, which values privacy, its snugs offering a
quiet, secluded corner to nurse a pint and peruse a newspaper. In
the new cafes, the object is to be seen.
</P>
<P>
   The Bailey, a Duke Street pub where Anthony Cronin famously
described the last pints imbibed by Brendan Behan before the writer
drank himself to death, has been gutted and turned into something
unrecognizable to someone who remembers its narrow hallways and
dark corners. Gone are the nooks and crannies where Cronin recalled
that final meeting in his classic memoir of the mid-20th-century
Dublin literary renaissance, ``Dead As Doornails.''
</P>
<P>
   It could be that, as for Cronin, places like The Bailey hold too
many bad memories to be thought of fondly. And so they, like
Joyce's house, get torn down or rehabilitated beyond recognition.
</P>
<P>
   Modern, chic hotels have opened all over Dublin, from The
Clarence, owned by U2 and the only place where rock stars deign to
stay, to The Merrion, where rooms go for more than $400 a night, a
price that only a few years ago would have been laughed at. These
days, it's hard to get a room at either hotel.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, for all their sophistication and minimalist design,
none of these new boutique hotels has the charm, or the feel, of
Dublin about them, of the old Shelbourne on St. Stephen's Green.
</P>
<P>
   Not that young people, who, after all, make up about half the
population and whose pocketbooks are fueling all this change, seem
overly concerned about any of this. They see themselves as
Europeans as much as Irish. If Dublin is starting to look like any
other continental capital, with more cafes than pubs, who cares? If
Irish-owned businesses are being bought out by British
conglomerates, who not only are making the shopping areas of
Ireland's capital look like any other mid-sized provincial English
city but also are taking the profits out of the country, who cares?
</P>
<P>
   The attitudes producing this remarkable change in Ireland are
either evidence of extraordinary confidence in or breathtaking
disregard for one's identity. As with anything in Ireland, you can
find articulate, passionate arguments for either conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   The Irish theater, meanwhile, seems to be getting the mix a bit
better than the dizzying proliferation of bars, restaurants, and
hotels. The Abbey, the national theater, and especially the smaller
Peacock, downstairs from the Abbey, will stage young Irish writers
as often as they will dust off the masters. The Druid in Galway is
among the most dynamic companies in the world. Its productions of
McDonagh's plays, including ``Beauty Queen of Lenane,'' have set
the standard for Irish drama that can still draw on universal
themes.
</P>
<P>
   One thing that Dubliners of all generations and political
persuasions seem to agree on, however, is the proposed millennium
pole: They are not impressed.
</P>
<P>
   Dubs have a quirky sense of humor; the 300-foot spike planned
for the end of the city's main promenade is already known here as
``The Pin in the Bin'' and ``The Spire in the Mire.''
</P>
<P>
   Yeats had it right. Ireland has changed, changed utterly. But it
has taken nearly a century for his observation about violent
nationalism to be applied to the national culture. It is both
wonderful and awful.
</P>
<P>
   A terrible beauty, indeed.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Kevin Cullen moved recently from Dublin to London, where he is the
Globe's bureau chief. He also lived in Dublin in 1979-'80, while
attending Trinity College.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-18-99 1330EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990118.0141 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 13:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7703 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WORK-TELECOMMUTING-BO     01-18 1341
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORK-TELECOMMUTING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NICE WORK IF YOU CAN HACK IT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW BRELIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Telecommuting seems like a great gig, often touted as the
biggest advance for employees since the 40-hour week.
</P>
<P>
   Working at home, one avoids the grind of rush-hour traffic, not
to mention the distractions of the office. Want to skip your
shower? Wear sweatpants instead of a suit? Go ahead.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 9 million Americans telecommute _ or telework, as
it is sometimes called. Their number, while hard to pin down
precisely, is increasing by more than 10 percent each year.
</P>
<P>
   But also growing is evidence that working from home is not as
liberating as one might think, and that the flexibility it offers
does not, in the end, do much to empower the worker. And it has
other, less tangible drawbacks.
</P>
<P>
   Sociologist Richard Sennett points to the writings of
18th-century French philosopher Denis Diderot to argue that routine
_ the kind found in the human interaction and daily rituals of the
workplace _ helps builds character and long-term commitments. At
the end of the 20th century, not only is job stability
disappearing, but so too may be the office as a valuable touchstone
in our daily lives.
</P>
<P>
   Further, Sennett says, those who telecommute can end up facing
greater surveillance at home than they do at work.
</P>
<P>
   Telecommuting ``arouses great anxiety among employers, who fear
losing control over their absent workers and suspect that those who
stay at home will abuse their freedom,'' Sennett writes in
``Corrosion of Character,'' his new book. ``As a result, a host of
controls have come into being to regulate the actual work processes
of those who are absent from the office. People may be required to
phone in to the office regularly, or intranet controls may be used
to monitor the absent worker; e-mail is often opened by
supervisors.''
</P>
<P>
   But there are more obvious pressures for many telecommuters, say
sociologists and those who work at home.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, telecommuting means that you are never truly off
the job. When Julie Schneider, who works for Check Point Software
from her Raleigh, N.C., home, hears the phone ring in her office,
she feels compelled to answer it _ even after hours. It's a problem
shared by telecommuters everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   With organizational loyalty low and the risk of being downsized
high, many workers feel increased pressure to produce, produce,
produce, and that is especially true of telecommuters, says
Christene Nippert-Eng, an Illinois Institute of Technology
sociologist who is finishing a book, ``Transition to
Telecommuting.''
</P>
<P>
   The pressure to produce more is a common trap for telecommuters,
says Roberta Fox, a management consultant with Deloitte and Touche.
At first, Fox says, home-based workers are excited and feel
liberated. They enjoy not having to face traffic, and the novelty
of working at home. With fewer distractions, they get more work
done.
</P>
<P>
   That sense of accomplishment, however, gives way to the
teleworkaholic syndrome, Fox says. Because they are producing more,
and may view telecommuting as a perk, they feel they have to always
do more work in order to justify their situation. That leads to
burnout and resentment. ``Some people really get quite extreme, and
you have to say `These are your hours of work. Do not exceed them,'
'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps most important, working at home can be isolating in
the extreme. Workers discover that contact with the FedEx delivery
person and the mailman is not enough, and often reevaluate why they
want to telecommute. For them to succeed, they need to reach out to
the company, go into the office, have lunch with bosses and
co-workers.
</P>
<P>
   Some companies, however, in an effort to save on overhead, may
not have room for telecommuters to return, says Nippert-Eng. Or if
they do, it is in a very impersonal way that sends a clear message
to the worker that their work, or their position, is not highly
valued by the company.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a phenomenon called `hot desking' or `hoteling,'
where there are generic desks that can be used for the day, but you
can't stick up a photograph or write on the blotter,'' Nippert-Eng
says.
</P>
<P>
   Usually, telecommuting arrangements are for a set amount of
time. For example, a parent may work at home so that his or her
teenager is not a latchkey child for the last two years before
heading off to college. Or the telecommuting may involve one
specific project, and when it is complete, the worker returns to
the office on a regular basis.
</P>
<P>
   But Nippert-Eng says that her research indicates a large number
of telecommuting efforts end prematurely. As recently as 1995, the
rate of failures was about 50 percent; now, with more planning
taking place before telecommuting begins, her research indicates
only about 20 percent fail.
</P>
<P>
   The reasons for ending a telecommuting arrangement early are
varied. It could be that workers do not get the support they need
from employers, or from the family, or do not have the discipline
and self-motivation they need to work alone. Even though it may
look like home, it can be like working in a vacuum.
</P>
<P>
   Telecommuting, says Nippert-Eng, also raises troubling questions
about privacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you work at a humane company and are terminated, they will
probably have a security guard escort you to your desk, let you
collect your belongings, and escort you out of the building. If
they are not humane, they may just mail it to you within a few
weeks,'' she says. But what happens if you are telecommuting and
the company wants its information and equipment out of your house?
``Do they put a yellow police `Do not cross' ribbon around your
house?'' Nippert-Eng wonders. ``Do they have the right to go
through everything in your hard drive?''
</P>
<P>
   Many companies, however, increasingly allow _ or even encourage
_ telecommuting because it saves them money. Not only is the office
overhead lower, telecommuting attracts high-quality, valued workers
who might otherwise choose to go to another company. And it can
boost efficiency, if done right. After all, says Nippert-Eng, ``the
office is a terrible place to do office work; it is full of
distractions and interruptions.''
</P>
<P>
   There are some studies that show productivity rises if
telecommuting is done for one or two days a week.
</P>
<P>
   Fox, the management consultant, says that telecommuting's
negative aspects are worst if it's done full time. She has examined
the productivity of workers in several companies who have
telecommuted and found that external workers (people in sales and
consulting) had huge productivity increases in day one and day two,
and by day three, their productivity was still above what it had
been in the office.
</P>
<P>
   Internal workers (people in accounting, purchasing, and
information resources) saw increases in productivity on days one
and two, but on day three, productivity was lower at home than it
would have been in the office. Fox was not able to explain the
results but said they were consistent in studies at different
companies.
</P>
<P>
   That comes as no surprise to either Nippert-Eng or Gordon. ``In
terms of planning work, it is very easy to do one day, or even two
from a remote site, but it becomes geometrically harder for days
three and four,'' said Gil Gordon, a New Jersey-based telecommuting
consultant and editor of a telecommuting newsletter. ``You need
files that might be at the office and you need interaction. Even
good telecommuters are not hermits.''
</P>
<P>
   For Schneider, the hardest thing about telecommuting is the loss
of social interaction.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't get to talk to anyone around the water cooler or the
printer'' she says. ``I am a social person and I was climbing the
walls.'' Her solution was to create conference calls with other
company telecommuters in other regions. ``For the first five
minutes, while you are waiting for everyone to join in, you can
talk about family and friends.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Matthew Brelis is the Globe's Focus writer.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
