<HEADLINE>
`RESCUERS' NEEDS HELP; `STELLA' REALLY GROOVY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL BLOWEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW RELEASES: ``The Rescuers'' _ Back when the Disney Studio was
searching for its identity, it released a series of spineless
animated movies. This is one of them. Nicely drawn and carefully
constructed, the barnyard tale lacks villainy _ the one element
that keeps animated children's films from being boring. (One
consumer note: Disney has recalled thousands of copies of the video
because the image of a nude woman was inserted at some point along
the production line. Parents should make suitable inquiries before
purchasing a copy.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``How Stella Got Her Groove Back'' _ Finally, an older
woman-younger man movie with some verve and spice to boot. A fine
performance by Angela Bassett, and some intelligent writing, gives
this reversal of the usual romantic pairing its energy.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Project Grizzly'' _ One of the oddest documentaries this side
of Errol Morris features Troy Hurtubise's zany but serious quest to
perfect a bear-proof suit of armor. Hilarious. Spellbinding. Weird.
What more can you ask for?
</P>
</TEXT>
