<SLUG> BC-HOOKER-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOT WISE TO LOAD UP ON SECTOR FUND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I am 40, earning $40,000 a year. My employer does not offer a
retirement or savings plan. I have the following IRA accounts:
$24,000 in Fidelity Asset Manager Growth fund, $26,500 in Fidelity
Utilities fund, $27,500 in Fidelity Contrafund, $8,500 in Fidelity
Europe fund, and $20,000 in Fidelity Convertible Securities fund. I
also have $5,000 in a taxable account in Fidelity Disciplined
Equity fund. I have been contributing $50 a month to the retirement
accounts, and hope to increase that level to $100 this year. What
do you think of these funds, and where should I add new money? What
do you estimate I will have in 25 years?
</P>
<P>
   M.C., Fort Worth &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. To tell the truth I'm not particularly wild about your fund
selections. For one thing, your portfolio seems to me to be too
conservative for a 25-year investment time frame; for another, it
seems to me to lack a distinct core position.
</P>
<P>
   You have three sizable holdings -- Asset Manager Growth,
Utilities, and Convertible Securities -- which are to varying
degrees too closely tied to the bond markets rather than stocks.
While Asset Manager Growth leans in the right direction, it remains
a balanced fund, and it holds nearly 28 percent of its assets in
cash and bonds, as of the last report from Morningstar Mutual
Funds. Both Utilities and Convertible Securities are funds which
focus their investments on dividend yields, accordingly sacrificing
a good deal of potential for capital appreciation. That leaves you
with the Contrafund and Europe positions, representing only 38.5
percent of the IRA portfolio, which are concentrating entirely on
growth. I suspect you came up with this array because you're
fundamentally pretty conservative, so I won't suggest you eliminate
these income-oriented funds entirely. But I do suggest you boost
the Contrafund position to $50,750 -- obtaining the funds by
cutting the positions in Utilities and Convertible securities in
half.
</P>
<P>
   For new investments, I'd suggest further diversification,
building a small position in Fidelity Select Health Care, another
in Fidelity Mid-Cap Stock, and maybe a third in the Small-Cap
Selector fund. (If you're second-guessing me by looking to the
Morningstar reports and see the below-average rating for Small-Cap
Selector, you should consider that the rating reflects the
downtrodden small-cap sector as much as the results of this fund.)
Finally, I think I'd move the holding in Fidelity Disciplined
Equity fund. The goal of this fund is to surpass the results of the
Standard and Poor's Index 500 using a selected portfolio that
tracks the industrial sectors of the index, but not all the stocks.
This strategy has relied in large part on a computer analysis of
the 500 stocks. It seemed to work nicely for the first six full
years of the fund's existence, from 1989 to 1994.
</P>
<P>
   But it has missed the mark ever since. If you compare five-year
results of the fund to those of Fidelity Spartan Market Index,
which simply seeks to track the S&AMP;P 500, you'll see average annual
gains of 18.71 percent for Diversified Equity, compared to 22.62
percent for Market Index. One- year and three-year figures show
even bigger variances, both times in favor of Market Index.
</P>
<P>
   Oh yes -- where might you end up in 25 years? I think if you
adopt my suggestions it would be fair to assume 9.5 percent average
annual total returns from the portfolio. With your $100 monthly
contributions, that would take you to $1,066,595. If you want to
stick with the more cautious kind of portfolio you have now, you'll
probably sleep better, but in exchange for those extra winks you
should reduce the growth assumption to 8 percent average returns.
Thus the 25-year projection would fall to $765,519.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I need to roll over $16,000 I have in a former employer's
401(k) account, and I'm at a loss as to where to put it. I
currently have about $70,000 invested in an IRA that's in Vanguard
Specialized Health Care fund, and have another $10,000 in a
Vanguard Wellington fund IRA account. I'm a 47-year-old single
woman with a new job at $63,000 a year. I have started to save 10
percent of my salary in a 401(k) plan, with the investments evenly
divided among Merrill Lynch High-Income bond fund, Fidelity
Puritan, Vanguard Index 500, and Fidelity Contrafund. Am I on the
right track at all? I've been told that I shouldn't have the bulk
of my retirement money in a sector fund, but this one has been very
good to me. Should I dump the $16,000 there or diversify? I am
considering Vanguard's U.S. Growth fund.
</P>
<P>
   A.K., Haverhill, Mass. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Well whatever you do, don't buy still more of the health care
fund. I have long been an enthusiastic supported of Vanguard
Specialized Health Care -- but I also suggest it only as a fairly
small percentage of a long-term portfolio. It's now nearly 73
percent of your total retirement savings, and that's a mighty heavy
bet.
</P>
<P>
   Because I really like this fund, my first instinct was to
suggest that you simply let the Health Care position remain as it
is, waiting for the rest of the portfolio to grow to the point that
the Health Care position represents a more appropriate allocation
-- say 25 percent at most. But the numbers just don't work. If you
maintained current-level portfolio contributions until age 65, the
pool would grow to $819,400, presuming average 10 percent annual
portfolio growth. But even if the health care fund only matched
that growth and you bought no more shares, at age 65 the health
care position would still be 47.5 percent of the portfolio -- and
since it's reasonable to assume that the volatile but rewarding
health care sector will outperform the equity market in general
during those 18 years, the chances are that the percentage would be
higher.
</P>
<P>
   Investing is a discipline, and investing for retirement is a
very serious discipline. I suggest you sit down in front of a
mirror and ask yourself whether you want to bet your retirement
security that all of the generations of financial advisors who have
recommended diversity, and who have recommended that sector plays
be held to a minor percentage of a retirement portfolio, are wrong.
I hope you come up with the right answer -- and then cut your
Vanguard Health Care position in half -- which still leaves it at
36 percent of your entire retirement accounts. I would then leave
that account alone, buying no further shares until the portfolio
reaches a point where the Health Care position falls below 25
percent; at that point, I'd only buy enough to maintain the 25
percent maximum allocation.
</P>
<P>
   Vanguard U.S. Growth is a solid fund; added to Fidelity
Contrafund and Vanguard Index 500, these positions could be treated
as the ``core'' of your retirement portfolio. I'd not only put the
$16,000 from the old 401(k) in one of these three funds (as a
rollover IRA), but I would allocate $32,000 from the sale of Health
Care shares to these positions, bringing that ``core'' up to 50
percent of the portfolio. I suggest you then take the final $3,000
to start a position that represents still further diversification
-- either with Vanguard's Small-Cap Index or its International
Growth fund.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am over age 66 and work full time. I have worked all my
life and am self-supporting. A few weeks ago a letter appeared in
your column from a woman aged 40, who said her plans involved
working until age 70. From my own experience I wonder if people
realize how difficult this is. You may be in good health, but the
body is tired physically and mentally, and if you commute into the
city this is an added burden. For these reasons, I don't think this
is something people should count on, or earnings they should depend
on. If they can do it, more power to them.
</P>
<P>
   N.S., Boston &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. You've said it very nicely: that people should begin their
retirement planning early enough so that they at least will have
the option of retiring at a traditional age, if not earlier.
</P>
<P>
   True, there are some people who not only have the stamina and
appetite to work beyond age 65 or thereabouts, but who would simply
go nuts if they suddenly found themselves with nothing to do.
</P>
<P>
   But your point is very well taken: People should provide
themselves with enough financial security that retiring at a
traditional age will be an open option. And yes _ I should have
mentioned that to the lady.
</P>
<P>
   (Send letters, including your name, address and telephone
number, to: Kenneth Hooker, The Boston Globe, Boston, MA
02107-2378.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
