<HEADLINE>
SPRINKLE FLESHES OUT HYPOCRISY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Annie Sprinkle will be at the Coolidge Corner Theater Tuesday
through Thursday in ``Annie Sprinkle's Herstory of Porn Reel to
Real,'' in which she chronicles her 25-year metamorphosis from shy
young girl to porno actress to performance artist.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pornography is a big part of our culture, even if we don't
want to admit it,'' said Sprinkle from Provincetown, Mass., where
she was visiting a friend. Pornography is increasingly mainstream,
she said, its influence is apparent in subtle and not-so-subtle
ways: ``Look at Madonna, the Spice Girls, so many others. And
lingerie. When I first started in porn in the early `70's, you
couldn't find sexy lingerie. Now you go into Macy's and there are
racks and racks of the stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Thanks in large part to Kenneth Starr's painstaking
investigation of the White House sex scandal, pornography is now
mainstream daily news. ``I'm just so amazed by Larry Flynt,''
Sprinkle said, echoing the sentiments of a nation. ``Here's our
most radical pornographer now wielding all this political power.''
</P>
<P>
   Is the scandal all about sex? Sprinkle doesn't think so. ``I
think the truth is more important than anything,'' she said. ``If
he lied under oath, then he should go. I believe in people telling
the truth. Even politicians.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had a such a good chance to be open about it. Instead he
chose to lie, to cover up. I feel really bad for the women
involved. Chelsea and Hilary, and Monica.''
</P>
<P>
   Lying about sex is reprehensible to Sprinkle, a self-described
sexual revolutionary who, in her own outrageous way, has spent her
adult life battling sexual hypocrisy. Sprinkle's body of work is
the sort of stuff that gives Jesse Helms and his ilk the vapors.
Much of what she does and what she's done can't be described here.
Suffice it to say there are very few areas of sexuality that
Sprinkle has not explored _ and been photographed or filmed
exploring.
</P>
<P>
   Her Brookline, Mass. appearance is sponsored by the women's
erotic boutique The Grand Opening. The performance piece includes
film clips from every stage of her career: `. . . my kinky phase,
my art phase, my spiritual phase. . . . It tells my story but it
also says a lot about sex in our society. It's funny. It's not
supposed to be erotic, although if people want to see it that way,
it's fine with me.
</P>
<P>
   She described her current phase as being a wise woman, ``kind of
the Shirley MacLaine of porn.'' She teaches workshops in erotic
massage and spriritual aspects of sexuality, among other subjects.
``I'm really a very spiritual person,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In her autobiography, ``Post-Porn Modernist,'' she writes that
originally she was Ellen Steinberg, a name that ``just didn't sound
sexy enough to me.'' She describes how she came to change that
name: ``I was lying on my bed and I heard a voice whisper, clear as
a bell, `Annie Sprinkle.''' Later she discovered a grave in
Baltimore of an Annie Sprinkle who died in 1861, at age 17. ``I
believe that it was her spirit that whispered her name in my ear
and that she now lives vicariously through me,'' she wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Recently Sprinkle was inducted into the porn industry's Hall of
Fame in Las Vegas. It was an honor she never expected because she
was always ``a fringe figure in the porno world, a radical, a
feminist.'' Her induction came about because so many young women
are now influential in porno filmmaking. ``Girl power,'' she
said.``My biggest fans are women in their 20s.''
</P>
<P>
   Sprinkle lived in Provincetown for a year and a half, but moved
back to California 15 months ago. She now lives in Sausalito, on a
houseboat she calls her mermaid sanctuary. ``I miss Provincetown,''
she said. ``It's so beautiful. But it's definitely more
conservative.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Diane White is a columnist with The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
