<SLUG> BC-ROSENFELD-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAULA JONES GETS HER DAY IN COURT 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By HARRY ROSENFELD  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Much of the argument for the conviction of Bill
Clinton presented to the Senate by the Republican managers of the
case rested on the premise that the president's actions interfered
with Paula Corbin Jones' ability to have her day in court.
</P>
<P>
   Again and again, Republican managers, for the benefit of the
Senate and the television audience, painted a portrait of Jones, a
former Arkansas state clerical worker, as a waif, beset in the
storm by the power of the presidency seeking to deny her rights.
</P>
<P>
   Reciting the indictment constructed by Independent Counsel
Kenneth Starr, the prosecutors alleged that because Clinton
perjured himself before the grand jury and in his deposition in the
Jones suit against him, Jones was blocked from getting justice.
</P>
<P>
   It was a line of attack to stir the compassion and indignation
of a public so far unconvinced by feverish Republican attempts to
evict Clinton from the presidency. However, it was troubled by a
fatal flaw. In court, Jones had, in fact, received full hearing and
thorough justice, irrespective of the allegations now before the
Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Noteworthy in their attempt to use the Jones case was one fact
that the Republican managers somehow overlooked. It was that the
Jones suit was summarily dismissed in federal court because it
lacked merit four and half months before Clinton was summoned to
testify before the grand jury by Starr. Therefore, logically,
anything he said to the grand jury could not have had bearing on
the case already thrown out.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, Clinton is accused of perjuring himself over his
relationship with Monica Lewinsky. But that would not have affected
the court decision. U.S. District Judge Susan Webber Wright ruled
that Jones had suffered no damage, in her job or in her person,
even if her version of the encounter with Clinton, when he was the
governor of Arkansas, was correct. The judge ruled: ``Whether other
women may have been subjected to workplace harassment, and whether
such evidence has allegedly been suppressed, does not change the
fact that the plaintiff has failed to demonstrate that she has a
case worthy of submitting to a jury.''
</P>
<P>
   In their zeal to make their case, the Republican managers
neglected to be governed by the action of the House of
Representatives, which specifically voted down a proposed article
of impeachment on Clinton having committed perjury in the Jones
case. The prosecutors nevertheless repeatedly shifted their perjury
accusations from the Jones hearing to the grand jury and back.
</P>
<P>
   In an actual court of law, presumably the judge would have
instructed them to stick to the terms of the indictment.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, before the Senate trial began, before the House voted
the articles of impeachment, the president agreed to pay Jones
$850,000 to make the case go away four years after it had begun.
But he did not issue an apology, which Jones had been fierce about
receiving in order to restore what she considered her good name.
</P>
<P>
   Nor did the president acknowledge any wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   So with $850,000 enlarging the pockets of Jones and her lawyers,
she seemed to have done rather well for someone with a legal
argument that had been found to be without merit.
</P>
<P>
   It is useful to recall the key events that led up to it, because
they illustrate the political machinations and ulterior motives
that underpin what is happening today.
</P>
<P>
   Jones said she encountered Clinton in a Little Rock hotel room
in 1991, to which she had been summoned by the governor by a state
trooper. Once in the room, she said he exposed himself and proposed
oral sex. She said she declined and left the hotel room.
</P>
<P>
   The Arkansas state trooper testified that she did not seem
unhappy from her encounter with the governor and earlier that day
had suggested to the trooper that she would be glad to become the
governor's girlfriend.
</P>
<P>
   He also said she later discussed with him how much money she
might make from the incident. One of her sisters also said Jones
was interested in getting money out of it.
</P>
<P>
   In December 1993, a right-wing magazine, the American Spectator,
published an article on Arkansas Troopergate, recalling the hotel
incident and identifying the woman only by her first name, Paula.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly two months after the publication of that account, and
three years after the incident allegedly occurred and just before
the statute of limitations was to run out, Jones announced her suit
under the sponsorship of conservative groups. She complained her
reputation had been sullied, but she did not sue the conservative
magazine. She chose to go after Clinton, who had not said one
public word about the event.
</P>
<P>
   Conservatives made the case into a cause, set about using it to
raise funds and exploited it as a political weapon against the
person who had long been their arch enemy: Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   In that context, Clinton did not own up to his consensual affair
with Monica Lewinsky in his Jones case deposition, which history
should have taught him would have been the best way out of his
troubles no matter the embarrassment and pain it would have caused.
He lied to the American people, his staff and his family.
</P>
<P>
   All came out anyway, and no one was spared, least of all the
American people, now suffering through an unwarranted assault on
the presidency itself.
</P>
<P>
   But whatever else is yet to befall Clinton, and despite the
manipulations of the Republican prosecutors, Jones did get to have
her day in court.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Harry Rosenfeld is editor-at-large of the Albany Times Union,
P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
