<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOMENRULE-2000(4TAKES)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEN WHO'VE LED THEIR COUNTRY WITH A STRONG, FEMALE HAND
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LIZ STEVENS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Poor old U.S.A. Here we are playing catch-up again.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Dole hints at a bid for the White House and it throws
the pundits into a frenzy: ``Are Americans ready for a female
president?'' Many a Sunday-morning news show will no doubt debate
the question into oblivion.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, much of the world yawns. From an international
perspective, female heads of state are old hat. There are currently
24 living women who are or have been presidents or prime ministers,
according to the Council of Women World Leaders, and don't count on
that number shrinking.
</P>
<P>
   Estrogen has governed the modern countries of Canada, Haiti,
Bolivia, Rwanda, Norway, Burundi and Bangladesh, to name a few, and
female leaders include some of the most influential and admired
figures of the 20th century: Indira Gandhi, Golda Meir and Margaret
Thatcher.
</P>
<P>
   As a reminder of this not-so-new phenomenon, we've compiled a
list of 10 women who ruled the world _ or parts of it, at least.
Liddy Dole might do well to take notes.
</P>
<P>
   1. BENAZIR BHUTTO, born 1953
</P>
<P>
   Prime minister of Pakistan, 1988-1990 and 1993-1996
</P>
<P>
   Political background: Educated at Harvard and Oxford, Bhutto is
the eldest child of Zulfikar Ali Bhutto, president and then prime
minister of Pakistan from 1971 to 1977. After the elder Bhutto's
government was overthrown and he was hanged, Benazir became her
political party's most powerful voice. Her opposition to the new
military government landed her in jail, although eventually she was
allowed to leave Pakistan for London. In 1986, hundreds of
thousands of Pakistanis celebrated her return to the country. Two
years later,
</P>
<P>
   Bhutto, at age 35, became the first woman to rule a modern
Islamic nation.
</P>
<P>
   Known for: Having spent time in the United States and England,
Bhutto knew how to deal with the Western press, one of her
strengths on the international stage. ``Her foreign persona was a
really powerful one,'' said Laura Liswood, co-founder of the
Council of Women World Leaders. Bhutto also established women's
police stations, where women could report rape. During both of her
rocky governments, Bhutto faced charges of corruption and abuse of
power. In September, Swiss authorities handed over to Pakistani
officials evidence that Bhutto may have laundered money and taken
kickbacks while in office. The fiery Bhutto denies the charges and
continues to be an outspoken critic of the current Pakistani
government.
</P>
<P>
   Personal facts: Now 45, Bhutto is the mother of three. Despite
her international prominence, she is acutely aware of her place as
a woman in a Muslim society. ``I must always maintain a certain
degree of formality,'' she has said. ``For instance, I have to be
accompanied by a proper chaperone, I must be careful how I talk to
people, I can't develop the same kind of camaraderie that exists
among men.''
</P>
<P>
   2. GOLDA MEIR, born 1898
</P>
<P>
   Prime minister of Israel, 1969-1974
</P>
<P>
   Political background: Meir was 8 when her father, a carpenter,
moved the family from the Ukraine to Milwaukee. As a young woman
she became drawn to Zionism and moved to Palestine with her
husband, Morris Meyerson, in 1921. Through positions with the
Israel Labor Federation and World Zionist Organization, Meir drew
recognition as a powerful political force. She was elected to the
Knesset in 1949, appointed minister of labor that same year and
then minister of foreign affairs in 1956. In 1969, after the sudden
death of Prime Minister Levi Eshkol, party officials chose Meir,
then 70, as the fourth prime minister of Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Known for: Meir took a hard line toward the Arab world. Her
government refused to stop building settlements in the occupied
Palestinian territories and rejected a peace agreement with Arab
states. But she encouraged emigration of Soviet Jews to Israel and
strengthened Israeli ties with the United States. Meir resigned as
prime minister in 1974, in the aftermath of the 1973 Yom Kippur
War, in which Arab attacks caught the country by surprise.
</P>
<P>
   Personal facts: A chain-smoker who rejected makeup, Meir ranked
fourth on the list of women most admired by Americans in a 1969
poll. David Ben-Gurion once called her ``the only man in my
Cabinet.'' Meir had two children and was, by several accounts, an
accomplished cook.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
</TEXT>
