<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOMENRULE-2ndTake-TEX </SLUG>
 
UNDATED: accomplished cook. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   3. ISABEL PERON, born 1931
</P>
<P>
   President of Argentina, 1974-1976, not to be confused with Eva
Peron, a k a Evita, the popular demagogue and second wife of Gen.
Juan Peron.
</P>
<P>
   Political background: The third wife of Juan Peron, Isabel Peron
met her future husband in the mid-1950s while working as a dancer.
Gen. Peron recently had been ousted as the ruler of Argentina, and
she became his personal secretary, settling with him in Madrid.
They were married in 1961 when he was 65 and she was 30. Through
several diplomatic visits to Argentina, Isabel paved the way for
her husband's triumphant return in 1973, when he was re-elected
president and she assumed the vice presidency. Less than a year
later, Juan Peron died of heart failure, and Isabel came to power.
</P>
<P>
   Known for: Like Evita before her, Isabel championed the causes
of Argentine women, but could not overcome the economic and
political strife in her country. Her government imposed martial law
and saw inflation rise to 200 percent, which led to crippling union
strikes. A military junta overthrew her regime in 1976, and she
eventually went into exile in Spain.
</P>
<P>
   Personal facts: Isabel Peron is said to have believed in
astrology and enjoy fencing. Unlike Evita, she was shy and often
compared negatively with her husband's second wife. A 1973 profile
in Time magazine commented that she sometimes appeared ``as if she
had been laminated in plastic.''
</P>
<P>
   4. CORAZON AQUINO, born 1933
</P>
<P>
   President of the Philippines, 1986-1992
</P>
<P>
   Political background: Aquino was born to a wealthy family with
political ties and schooled at convents in the United States. She
married Benigno Aquino in 1954, raised five children and watched
her husband's political career take off. When Ferdinand Marcos
declared martial law in 1972, he jailed his political nemesis,
Benigno, for nearly eight years before allowing the Aquinos to flee
to the United States. In 1983, Benigno returned to the Philippines
and was gunned down at the Manila Airport; Corazon vowed to
continue his work, and in 1986 forced Marcos into exile in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   Known for: During her tumultuous tenure, Aquino restored some
civil rights and released political prisoners, while her government
survived at least seven coup attempts. Her presidency inspired a
renaissance in the arts in her country and renewed international
economic interest in the Philippines, although critics said she
didn't advance the country economically as much as she might have.
</P>
<P>
   Personal facts: The petite Aquino, 65, is a devout Roman
Catholic who found the Marcos' opulent presidential palace
uncomfortably extravagant and set up an office in the guest house
of her more modest home.
</P>
<P>
   5. MARGARET THATCHER, born 1925
</P>
<P>
   Prime minister of Great Britain, 1979-1990
</P>
<P>
   Political background: With an eye to his daughter's political
future, the lower-middle-class father of Margaret Thatcher paid for
his daughter to take extra lessons in the classics and Latin. At
Oxford, she studied chemistry and became involved in Conservative
Party politics. After marrying, giving birth to twins and
practicing law, she ran for Parliament in a wealthy suburb of
London and held the seat from 1959 to 1992. In 1975, she took the
reins of the Conservative Party, and four years later was elected
prime minister on a platform of abolishing the welfare state.
</P>
<P>
   Known for: Thatcherism, the prime minister's major contribution
to political science, not only encompassed her policies but her
style. ``Under her forceful, if sometimes strident, leadership, the
Conservatives accomplished what no previous British government in
the postwar period had done: They emasculated the unions,
denationalized important industries, curbed inflation and swelled
the ranks of the middle class,'' according to Current Biography
Yearbook. Meanwhile, unemployment soared and the gap between the
haves and have-nots grew.
</P>
<P>
   Personal facts: Since her resignation, Baroness Thatcher has
written her memoirs and continues to weigh in on matters of state.
She recently came out against the extradition of Chilean Gen.
Augusto Pinochet and, as of December, was still the
fourth-most-admired woman by Americans, according to a Gallup Poll,
right after No. 3, Elizabeth Dole.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
