<DOCNO> NYT19990118.0149 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 13:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7713 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WOMENRULE-3rdTake-TEX     01-18 0754
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOMENRULE-3rdTake-TEX </SLUG>
 
UNDATED: Elizabeth Dole. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   6. MARY EUGENIA CHARLES, born 1919
</P>
<P>
   Prime minister of the Commonwealth of Dominica, 1980 to 1995
</P>
<P>
   Political background: Charles was born in 1919 on the eastern
Caribbean island of Dominica and received her bachelor's degree
from the University of Toronto and her law degree from the London
School of Economics and Political Science in the 1940s. She
returned to Dominica, becoming the first female lawyer on the
island. Her involvement in politics culminated in election to the
House of Assembly in 1975, as leader of the opposition Freedom
Party (the country achieved independence from Britain in 1978).
Charles' harsh criticism of the Labor Party government was
partially responsible for the resignation of Prime Minister Patrick
John, whom she succeeded in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   Known for: Dominica was a founding member of the Organization of
Eastern Caribbean States in 1981. In 1983, Charles requested that
the United States send troops to another OECS member nation,
Grenada, to thwart an overthrow of that country's government by
leftist extremists. The invasion drew criticism from the United
Nations. A forceful presence, Charles is nicknamed the Iron Lady of
the Caribbean. Her detractors claimed Charles, a fiscal
conservative, ran the country too much like a business, with little
regard for its citizens.
</P>
<P>
   Personal facts: She was the granddaughter of a former slave, and
Charles' father was a successful fruit exporter who lived to be
107. In 1994, she told an interviewer that the person she admired
most in the world was Golda Meir.
</P>
<P>
   7. VIGDIS FINNBOGADOTTIR, born 1930
</P>
<P>
   President of Iceland, 1980 to 1996
</P>
<P>
   Political background: Finnbogadottir studied drama and
literature at the Sorbonne in France and in 1972 was appointed
director of the Reykjavik Theater Company. She hosted a television
series on drama and lectured on Icelandic culture before becoming
the chairwoman of the Advisory Committee on Cultural Affairs in
1978. At the time, women's issues were coming to the fore, and
colleagues persuaded Finnbogadottir to make a run for the
presidency. She won her first four-year term, beating four male
opponents, in 1980. She ran unopposed in 1984 and in 1992; in 1988
she won the presidency with 92 percent of the vote.
</P>
<P>
   Known for: Although the presidency in Iceland is more a
ceremonial role than a political one, Finnbogadottir has championed
numerous causes including Icelandic culture and reforestation. She
founded the Save the Children Association of Iceland and in 1995
was the keynote speaker at the UN Conference on Women in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   Personal facts: In 1972, Finnbogadottir became a single parent
after adopting a baby girl. She remains a national icon since
leaving office, and is now co-founder of the Council of Women World
Leaders based at Harvard's Kennedy School of Government.
</P>
<P>
   8. MARY ROBINSON, born 1944
</P>
<P>
   President of Ireland, 1990 to 1997
</P>
<P>
   Political background: Robinson's activism evolved at a young
age: While at an exclusive Catholic boarding school, Robinson
petitioned for the right to read the Protestant Irish Times. She
graduated from Harvard Law School in 1968 and became the first
woman to be a faculty member at Trinity College Dublin, where she
began working to improve the lives of women through the law. She
fought for the right of women to sit on juries, for laws protecting
illegitimate children and for gay rights. Upon her election to the
Senate in 1969 (she was only 25 years old), she introduced a bill
to legalize contraceptives. In 1989, she resigned from the Senate,
only to accept the Labor party's nomination as its presidential
candidate the next year.
</P>
<P>
   Known for: As in Iceland, the Irish presidency is a largely
symbolic post. But Robinson's victory seemed ``to symbolize
Ireland's desire for genuine change, given her stands on such
charged issues as abortion and reproductive rights, which have been
anathema to other Irish leaders. ... Mary Robinson has indeed used
her title to promote tolerance, compassion and national debate,''
according to ``A Rising Public Voice: Women in Politics
Worldwide,'' edited by Alida Brill.
</P>
<P>
   Personal facts: Upon her entry into politics, Robinson was
derided for what some considered a lackluster personal appearance.
When she became president, she underwent an image makeover.
Robinson resigned the presidency in September 1997 to become United
Nations human rights commissioner. She was succeeded as president
by Mary McAleese.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
