<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990118.0150 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 13:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7714 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WOMENRULE-4thTake-TEX     01-18 0578
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOMENRULE-4thTake-TEX </SLUG>
 
UNDATED: Mary McAleese. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   9. VIOLETA CHAMORRO, born 1929
</P>
<P>
   President of Nicaragua, 1990-1997
</P>
<P>
   Political background: Born into a wealthy, landowning family,
Chamorro was schooled in San Antonio and Virginia. Back in
Nicaragua, she married Pedro Joaquin Chamorro, an activist against
the Somoza dictatorship and scion of the family that owned the
liberal La Prensa newspaper. His articles consistently landed him
in jail. Pedro was ultimately assassinated by the right-wing
dictatorship in 1978, and Violeta took over the newspaper. When the
Somoza government fled, Daniel Ortega's Sandinista party became the
dominant political force, and Chamorro became an outspoken
opposition leader.
</P>
<P>
   Her political defeat of Ortega ended 10 years of civil war.
</P>
<P>
   Known for: Chamorro's presidency faced significant challenges,
including rising unemployment, strikes and continued fighting
between Sandinista militants and rebellious contras. Her most vocal
critic was Sen. Jesse Helms, who accused her of selling out to the
Sandinistas and who threatened to withhold financial aid to the
country.
</P>
<P>
   Personal facts: Chamorro ``was very symbolic of the unity of
Nicaragua,'' said Liswood, of the Council of Women World Leaders.
``She had four children, two Sandinistas and two contras.''
Chamorro's autobiography, titled ``Dreams of the Heart,'' received
generally favorable reviews in the United States when it was
published in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   10. INDIRA GANDHI, born 1917
</P>
<P>
   Prime minister of India, 1966 to 1977 and 1980 to 1984
</P>
<P>
   Political background: Indira Gandhi, the only child of
Jawaharlal Nehru _ India's first prime minister, from 1947 to 1964
_ was enmeshed in Indian politics from her earliest years. Although
she was not related to India's spiritual leader Mohandas Gandhi, he
was close to her father and encouraged her involvement in the
resistance movement against British rule. Because her mother had
died in 1936, Gandhi became India's ``first lady'' during her
father's government, accompanying him on trips and gaining a
prominent political reputation. In 1959, one year before the death
of her husband, Feroze Gandhi, she was elected president of the
Congress Party, the second-highest political position in the
country. When Prime Minister Lal Bahadur Shastri, Nehru's
successor, died in 1966, Gandhi was elected prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   Known for: In the early 70s, Gandhi was said to be perhaps the
most popular leader in the world, although her term was not so
rosy. Under Gandhi, India exploded its first nuclear device.
Although she promised to abolish poverty, she was also beholden to
the rich for her power base. In the mid-'70s, Gandhi limited
personal freedoms and began jailing political rivals. In response,
she was voted out of office in 1977, but regained power in 1979.
When her son and heir-designate, Sanjay, died in a plane crash, she
began grooming son Rajiv as her successor. In 1984, after ordering
a violent raid on a Sikh temple, she was assassinated by two of her
bodyguards.
</P>
<P>
   Personal facts: Gandhi wrote in her autobiography, ``To a woman,
motherhood is the highest fulfillment,'' and the Nehru-Gandhi
dynasty continues to play a vital role in India's politics.
Although Rajiv, who followed his mother as prime minister, was
assassinated in 1991, his widow, Sonia, now chairs the opposition
Congress party.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
