r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KIRKFRANKLIN-LAWSUIT-     01-18 0863
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIRKFRANKLIN-LAWSUIT-1400(2TAKES)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MONEY AT ISSUE IN DALLAS WOMAN'S SUIT AGAINST SINGER KIRK FRANKLIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE FERMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Less than two years ago, Kirk Franklin and Metroplex choir God's
Property owned gospel music, and looked to do so for years to come.
</P>
<P>
   Franklin, 28, was already a multimillion-selling gospel
superstar by 1997, when the debut CD by God's Property _ formed by
Dallasite Linda Searight in 1992 after what she calls a ``vision
from God'' _ was released by B-Rite Records, the sister company of
GospoCentric Records, Franklin's label.
</P>
<P>
   ``God's Property From Kirk Franklin's Nu Nation,'' which
Franklin had produced, written songs for and performed on, quickly
ascended to the top of the gospel charts. By summer, the flagship
video, ``Stomp,'' was in heavy rotation on MTV, and GP was the
hottest name in gospel.
</P>
<P>
   Within just over a year, though, it would all fall to ashes, a
heap of accusations and counteraccusations. Now Searight and
Franklin (who was just nominated for a Grammy for song of the year)
face off through legal papers and lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   In October, Searight filed a lawsuit in Los Angeles, naming
GospoCentric President Vicki Mack Lataillade; B-Rite President (and
Vicki Mack's husband) Claude Lataillade; Franklin; his production
company, Fo Yo Soul; and Interscope Records, which owns part of
both labels.
</P>
<P>
   She is asking for $70 million in royalties and potential
earnings, claiming that Franklin and Vicki Mack Lataillade
conspired to usurp her power and authority within the choir and
poisoned her relationship with its members by telling them that she
withheld money from concerts. (Seventeen choir members and
employees were named in the suit but later dropped.)
</P>
<P>
   Searight also asserts that Lataillade (pronounced
``lah-tay-ODD'') and Franklin pressured her into signing an unfair
contract with B-Rite, one which guarantees that no matter how much
money the CD makes, she will forever be in debt for advances and
promotional costs.
</P>
<P>
   She and GP manager Thomas Hall say they've never made any money
from the CD, which has now sold nearly 3 million copies. Statements
from B-Rite claim that she's in debt to the label for
$2,149,548.87.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just seems unbelievable,'' said Searight, 50. ``It's hard
to conceive of accomplishing what we've accomplished and not having
made anything from it. It just seems unbelievable and unfair.''
</P>
<P>
   B-Rite fired back in November, suing Searight for breach of
contract and asking that members who have left the group be allowed
to record for the label. Supposedly, many members had left because
of what the suit called ``misguided, dictatorial, secretive, unfair
and unreasonable conduct'' on Searight's part.
</P>
<P>
   The suit also asks for an accounting of the money Searight has
made from selling merchandise at GP shows.
</P>
<P>
   No court date has been set.
</P>
<P>
   Franklin, who lives in Arlington, Texas, asked to be dropped
from the Searight lawsuit. His lawyer, Peter Haviland, says he was
only named in the suit because of his name recognition. U.S.
District Judge Dean D. Pregerson denied the request in December.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once the facts are presented to the court, Linda Searight's
claims will dry up and evaporate like mist under a hot morning
sun,'' Haviland said. ``The lawsuit is crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   WHAT THE SUITS SAY
</P>
<P>
   The legal battle really breaks down into two main contentions,
the first concerning the contract that Searight signed in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   The contention over the contract is about the pressures that
supposedly led Searight to sign it, more than its content. She and
Hall claim that they were told by Lataillade and Franklin that if
they didn't sign the contract, there were plenty of other groups
that would be happy to, and GP would lose its golden opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was constantly asked if I'd signed by Kirk,'' said Searight.
``There was an urgency to get going on the project.''
</P>
<P>
   Channing Johnson, legal counsel for both GospoCentric and
B-Rite, says no pressure was put on Searight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing could be further from the truth,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The second main contention is over Searight's handling of the
choir, and how many people have left.
</P>
<P>
   The countersuit paints Searight as a woman who wanted to
exercise too much control over the choir and wouldn't stay in the
background.
</P>
<P>
   Searight says Lataillade and Franklin constantly undermined her
authority, although both she and Hall said the specifics would have
to wait for the courtroom. But she did say that not being able to
appear in the ``Stomp'' video undermined her authority in the group
and upset her.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's her problem,'' said Johnson. ``We didn't want her in
the video. She's not the artist. She delivered the choir. She's an
intermediary.''
</P>
<P>
   The breaking point seems to have been the night of the Billboard
Music Awards in December 1997. Searight claims that Lataillade and
Franklin accused her, in front of the group, of withholding money
from them.
</P>
<P>
   She also says Lataillade, who is black, said she didn't want
Searight accepting awards for GP and called her an ``old, fat,
black woman.''
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
<P>
   Johnson doesn't deny the statements were made (''well, I'm not
sure `old' was used,'' he said with a chuckle) but says they were
misconstrued.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a statement made about Linda getting up there,'' he
said. ``She (Lataillade) wanted the group up there. The statement
(about withheld money) was a simple statement of truth, not
pointing the finger. Remember who the contract is with. Any
compensation we would pay, we'd pay through Linda, and she has an
obligation to pay them.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson says that the contract is ``standard'' for the industry
and that Searight has never asked for an audit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can get behind any of our numbers any time she wants to,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   After December 1997, Johnson says, GospoCentric gave members
money ``because they were broke. They were complaining about not
having any money and, more important, not knowing how much they
should or should not have from those performances.''
</P>
<P>
   And over time, Johnson says, ``25 to 28'' members of God's
Property, a little less than half, have left, unhappy with how
Searight ran GP and/or with their financial situations.
</P>
<P>
   Totally inaccurate, says Searight. While some members have gone
on extended leaves or moved due to school or job situations, nobody
has resigned from God's Property ``as a result of this situation.''
And she's forced nobody out.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole thing is ludicrous,'' she said. ``Ask him (Johnson)
to provide proof of who has left. I'd love to see it.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, Searight's God's Property (which she says includes 55
members) continues to perform. Yes, she says, merchandise with
God's Property's name on it (baseball caps, T-shirts, posters and
more) has been sold at some concerts, but not much.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson says that there are plans for B-Rite to put out a God's
Property CD sometime in the future _ if Franklin signs on. The
group, he says, will include members who have left Searight's
group.
</P>
<P>
   EVERYBODY LOSES
</P>
<P>
   In the end, there are only two facets of the case that both
sides can agree on. One is that not putting out a GP CD for so long
is costing the group valuable momentum and will no doubt hurt
future sales. The other is that an out-of-court settlement is
likely.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Searight says she has not spoken to Kirk Franklin in some
time, but that if she saw him tomorrow in the mall, she'd want to
talk to him, and she hopes he feels the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure we'd still be cordial with each other,'' she said.
``He used to call me `Mother Searight.' We've never had a problem
speaking with each other. This is business.''
</P>
<P>
   (Dave Ferman is pop music critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Contact him at dfer(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
