<SLUG> BC-CONFERENCE-NEWNAME-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANTI-PREJUDICE GROUP ADOPTS A MORE INCLUSIVE NAME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM JONES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the nation's best-known organizations for fighting
religious prejudice, the National Conference of Christians and
Jews, has changed its name.
</P>
<P>
   The new name, the National Conference for Community and Justice,
will better reflect the religious and racial diversity of America,
said Emily Trantham, executive director of the Fort Worth chapter
of the organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``We may have a new name, but we have the same mission,'' said
Trantham. ``We are still trying to promote understanding and
respect among religious groups.''
</P>
<P>
   She noted that the organization will still have the same
initials: NCCJ.
</P>
<P>
   Trantham said the growing religious diversity in America that
includes world religions such as Islam, Hinduism and Buddhism was
one factor in the name change.
</P>
<P>
   ``The name had become a barrier, because some people felt left
out,'' she said. ``If there is one word the NCCJ stands for, it is
`inclusion.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Since its founding in 1927, the NCCJ has expanded from its
original focus on building interfaith understanding to also
nurturing interracial and intercultural understanding, she said.
</P>
<P>
   When the National Conference of Christians and Jews was founded,
the Ku Klux Klan was spreading hatred against Jews. Also,
anti-Catholic sentiment was present in the country. Al Smith was
maligned for his Catholic faith during his unsuccessful campaign
for the U.S. presidency.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL ADD FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   A ``Trios'' program was developed in the early years of the
local organization, in which a Catholic, a Protestant and a Jew
would go into public schools and discuss their beliefs, Trantham
said.
</P>
<P>
   Now the local group sponsors many projects aimed at increasing
religious, racial and cultural understanding. It honors local
individuals who fight prejudice at a Brotherhood-Sisterhood Banquet
each spring.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, a Muslim-Jewish-Christian dialogue was held at
University Christian Church in Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the local NCCJ sponsors an ``Anytown Texas'' project in
which high-school students participate in intercultural and
interracial workshops. The local group recently completed its
annual seminarians conference at Laity Lodge near Kerrville in
Central Texas. Students from Protestant and Catholic seminaries in
Texas and the University of Judaism in Los Angeles discussed
differences in their faiths.
</P>
<P>
   (Jim Jones is religion editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Contact him at jimjones(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
