<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 13:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7719 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-WITNESSES-BOS     01-18 0806
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-WITNESSES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWYERS SEE GOP RISKS IN CALLING WITNESSES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ADAM PERTMAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When courtroom experts hear the GOP drumbeat for
witnesses to bolster their impeachment case against President
Clinton, they frequently recall this adage: Be careful of what you
ask for, because you might get it.
</P>
<P>
   It is not that most lawyers think the Republican strategy is
wrong. Indeed, they generally agree that calling witnesses, which
Democrats on the whole oppose, probably constitutes the House
prosecutors' sole chance of winning their case for ousting Clinton.
At the same time, they believe it is a high-risk gamble that has at
least as much chance of backfiring.
</P>
<P>
   That is partly because three of the major players whose
testimony is sure to be sought _ Monica S. Lewinsky, Vernon E.
Jordan Jr., and Betty Currie _ seem at least as likely as not to
try to fashion their comments to favor the president. All three
underwent bruising examinations from the independent counsel,
Kenneth W. Starr, and his team of attorneys, so most observers
doubt there is much damaging information left to obtain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am firmly of the view that the testimony of all of these
witnesses is, on balance, going to help the president,'' said Bruce
Yannet, a New York lawyer who worked for special prosecutor
Lawrence E. Walsh during the Iran-Contra investigation. ``They've
never been questioned by anyone remotely friendly to the president
before, so all the bad stuff's already out there. All that's left
is the good stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Many defense attorneys, former prosecutors, and legal scholars
agreed with that assessment. And some said the risk being taken by
House managers transcends a defeat on the Senate floor.
</P>
<P>
   They suggested that a majority of voters, already weary of the
long-running impeachment drama and opposed to congressional action
against Clinton from the start, would demonstrate their disapproval
at the polls.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe the biggest danger is to the Republican Party,''
said Norman Zalkind, a defense lawyer in Boston who nevertheless
said he thought the GOP's pursuit of witnesses was a solid
strategic decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless they really come up with something big from one of
these witnesses, people outside the beltway are going to say: `Why
are you extending this? What are you doing?' I think it could be a
disaster for them,'' Zalkind said.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, Clinton's Republican critics also could be
vindicated, and presumably could score big electoral points, if
they use witnesses to demonstrate that the president deserves to
lose his job because he committed perjury and executed an illegal,
elaborate scheme to obstruct justice. And, as outlined in the Starr
report and in the House prosecutors' presentation last week, all
three of the key witnesses have given testimony that casts the
president in an unfavorable light.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph diGenova, a former federal prosecutor, said he believes
the gamble is worthwhile because it will pay off. In particular, he
said careful questioning of Lewinsky, Currie, and Jordan _ even if
it does not produce any bombshells _ could vividly demonstrate that
Clinton repeatedly tried to obstruct justice.
</P>
<P>
   For example, he asserted, the president tried to silence
witnesses in a civil trial by giving gifts to Lewinsky and
arranging for Jordan to find her a job, and influence the testimony
of others by trying to reshape Currie's memories about events
surrounding his relationship with Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``And there can always be a surprise,'' diGenova added. ``Could
it be one that rebounds against the prosecution? Sure. But it could
also demolish the president, which is why neither he nor the
Democrats want to call witnesses.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet the prosecutors may be taking less of a risk than it might
initially appear if they win their effort to secure live testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Before any witnesses would testify on the Senate floor,
depositions would be taken _ as they are in most civil and criminal
cases _ so House lawyers and the president's attorneys could
determine what the potential witnesses have to say. Since the
Senate has agreed it will vote on approving the appearance of
witnesses, the GOP majority presumably could keep Lewinsky, Currie,
Jordan, or anyone else from testifying if their accounts don't
further the prosecution's case.
</P>
<P>
   Some Republican senators might decide against live testimony
because of the risks, according to the legal analysts. They agreed
that Lewinsky, because of her emotional involvement with the
president, presented a particularly nettlesome choice for senators.
</P>
<P>
   ``She would be like a tornado hitting the Senate floor,'' Yannet
said. ``It's totally unpredictable who will be left standing after
she finishes testifying.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
