<SLUG> BC-SCI-OLDER-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICA'S CHRONIC CARE CRISIS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD A. KNOX  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like anyone who has lived more than 76 years, Leonard Rallo has
accumulated many identities: decorated World War II pilot,
businessman, husband, father, grandfather, dogged survivor of a
stroke that left him paralyzed on the right side. But right now,
Rallo feels mostly like a casualty of Uncle Sam's decision to
retrench on paying for home care help.
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't ask for much. ``I need someone to help me get out of
bed in the morning, take a shower, and get dressed,'' Rallo says in
the labored speech he has struggled hard to regain after the
stroke. ``And I need to have someone put me to bed at night. I
can't do that myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither can Anne Rallo, his wife of 52 years, because Leonard
weighs about 200 pounds, and she has a bad back.
</P>
<P>
   Until last September, Medicare paid for a health aide who
enabled Rallo to function at home. But strict new limits on
Medicare payments for home care _ part of a drive to balance the
federal budget and curb perceived abuses by home care providers _
have forced home care agencies to slash patients from their
rosters, reserving help for only the most medically needy.
</P>
<P>
   Rallo is one of nearly 9,000 Bay State elders kicked out of
Medicare's home care program in the past year. That in turn forces
states that pay for home care for some residents to put strict
limits on how many cases they take on and how much care they
provide.
</P>
<P>
   In Massachusetts, ``refugees'' from Medicare have driven up
state home-care caseloads 3 1/2 times faster than projected, and
the average cost-per-case is capped at $199.60 a month on average,
or $6.65 a day _ enough to buy about a half-hour of care. But the
Rallos don't even qualify for that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I worked for 50 years, paid my taxes, and never asked for
anything,'' he laments. ``Now I need some help, and there's none to
be had.''
</P>
<P>
   The Winchester, Mass. couple painfully illustrate the biggest
gap in America's health care system: the lack of a mechanism to pay
for the long-term care that many elders will need at one time or
another. Analysts see no hope of filling that gap in the
foreseeable future.
</P>
<P>
   The nation's ambition to do something about it has shrunk
radically over the past five years, even as its wealth has
ballooned. When President Clinton floated his ill-fated national
health plan in 1994, it included a mechanism to fund long-term care
in the home and community day-care programs (but not nursing homes)
at a projected cost of $30 billion.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, a long-term care plan proposed by Clinton this
month would spend a mere $1 billion a year, most of that in a
$1,000 tax refund that would benefit the six out of 10 elders who
have enough income to pay taxes. That would cover about six weeks
of the modest assistance the Rallos need.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, recently enacted Medicare cuts will trim $20 billion
a year from the coverage of other medical needs _ about 10 percent
of the giant program's budget _ leaving elders with less money to
pay for home care on their own. Medicare covers very little home
care, a fact that comes as a shock to many elders who think the
program will help keep them out of the nursing home.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of offering people a refund on their income taxes to
help pay for long-term care ``is warmed-over many times,'' says Al
Norman of the Massachusetts Home Care Alliance. ``Tax credits help
the wrong people, and there's a lot of red tape involved. It's just
throwing a bone to family caregivers while Congress undercuts
Medicare home health coverage, with White House approval.''
</P>
<P>
   Others agree with Norman on tax credits but are more positive
overall about the Clinton plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``It excludes the poor and some of the moderate- and
lower-income people you'd probably want to start with,'' says
Joshua M. Weiner of the Urban Institute. ``But at least it gets
long-term care on the agenda. Most people interested in aging
issues have been frustrated that we've completely ignored long-term
care in this debate we're having on Social Security and Medicare.
It's the third vital component of retirement security and the part
we're least equipped to deal with.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the $1,000 tax credit, the Clinton plan has three
other components.
</P>
<P>
   --It would leverage federal employees' purchasing power to boost
the growth of private long-term care insurance. If the government
negotiated a premium discount with insurers, Clinton hopes 300,000
government workers would opt to buy such coverage, and corporations
might get interested in offering similar employee-pays-all group
policies.
</P>
<P>
   --The plan would grant states $125 million a year to set up
programs to counsel 250,000 elders and families on long-term care
issues, help them gain access to whatever help is available, and
pay for some ``respite care'' so family caregivers can get out of
the house occasionally.
</P>
<P>
   --The government would mount a $10 million campaign to inform
Medicare's 39 million beneficiaries that the program will not pay
for most long-term care.
</P>
<P>
   That last provision may seem odd _ spending tax dollars to tell
people what Medicare does not cover. But some see a hidden
political purpose: pushing people to buy private long-term care
insurance, stirring up support for a federal program _ or both.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's setting the stage for the Gore Administration to
take on long-term care as the next big issues,'' says Robert
Friedland of the National Academy on an Aging Society.
</P>
<P>
   If the proposal passes _ a possibility, observers say, since
many of the ideas come from congressional Republicans _ it will
focus unprecedented attention on a type of insurance that most
Americans know little about, and understand less.
</P>
<P>
   ``Long-term care insurance is a very complicated product _ much
worse than auto insurance,'' says Norman, the Massachusetts home
care advocate. ``It's poorly perceived, poorly understood, its
benefits are not clear, and it's fairly expensive. And by the way,
if you have a preexisting condition, you're probably not going to
be able to buy it.''
</P>
<P>
   That's what happened to William Kozera, a 74-year-old Hadley
man. A broker tried to sell coverage to his wife Gladys, who
counsels other elders about Medicare and other coverage issues. But
the insurer refused to cover William because of his health
problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``It didn't appeal to me that I would be covered but my husband
wasn't,'' Gladys Kozera says.
</P>
<P>
   Long-term care insurance covers a portion of the cost of home
care and nursing home care _ say, $100 toward the daily cost of a
nursing home stay _ and typically kicks in after the subscriber has
paid out-of-pocket for up to a year of care. Coverage can be
unlimited, or it can end after two to four years.
</P>
<P>
   Comparing among plans is daunting; one trade group estimates
there are 3,000 variations. Brokers in many states don't have any
special training or certification.
</P>
<P>
   Experts caution that people should beware of pitches for
inexpensive long-term care policies _ those costing $100 to $400 a
year for people who sign up in their 50s, 60s, and 60s. They don't
cover much, the benefits don't keep pace with inflation, and
subscribers won't get any of their premium money back if they
decide to let the policy lapse.
</P>
<P>
   Good coverage costs plenty, and the price rises rapidly with
age-of-signup: typically $1,700 a year for a 50-year-old, $2,400
for a 60-year-old, $7,400 for a 70-year-old. Clearly, it makes
sense to lock in a rate at a young age _ but that's when people are
paying for children's college and saving for retirement, and the
need for long-term care seems remote.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are very few people who have sufficient income and
assets for long-term care insurance to make sense,'' says John
Capitman of Brandeis University. ``If more people bought it, at
some point the price would begin to decline and the quality of the
benefits would increase. Until then, I tell people: Don't buy it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Richard A. Knox's e-mail address is knox(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
