u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SLAVE-PILGRIMAGE-BOS &LR;      01-18 1416
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SLAVE-PILGRIMAGE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXAMINING RACISM, STEP BY STEP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TATSHA ROBERTSON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There was tension in the hot, Southern summer air as 60 walkers
on a pilgrimage to retrace slavery trekked through a small Alabama
town.
</P>
<P>
   With each step, there were more stares from white locals. The
multicultural group of walkers, which started out from
Massachusetts in June, was aware that the state had been a racial
battlefield during the civil rights movement of the 1960s. The
walkers worried they wouldn't be accepted there.
</P>
<P>
   They were right, but the discrimination they eventually faced
didn't come from the white onlookers, but from members of a black
church. The church leaders had promised to put them up for the
night, but sent word that there was no room for ``heathens,''
recalled several walkers.
</P>
<P>
   The walkers _ Japanese Buddhist monks and Christians, both black
and white _ were all participants in an ongoing trip called the
Interfaith Pilgrimage of the Middle Passage. The chilly reception
from the black church in Alabama was just one in a series of
strange, yet enlightening, twists in their odyssey.
</P>
<P>
   The trip's purpose, in theory, was to address racism in America
by tracing in reverse the treacherous route of the trans-Atlantic
slave trade through which an estimated 11 million Africans were
sold in Europe, the United States, Caribbean nations, and Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   But according to participants, the journey, which is scheduled
to end in South Africa in May, became something more. They say it
developed into an internal examination that forced them to confront
their own prejudices through the actions of others and compelled
them to deal with racial tensions among themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tensions were going to impede the trip so we had a strong
incentive to work out problems,'' said Skip Schiel, a photographer
from Cambridge.
</P>
<P>
   In early June, the walkers, some of them wearing long dredlocks
and others with shaved heads _ passed through Boston during an
early stage of the pilgrimage, which is designed to take them 2,400
miles on foot. Chanting and carrying African flags, they were to
walk along state roads, cross the Northeast, journey through the
Deep South, and end the American leg on Nov. 3.
</P>
<P>
   As in the larger society the group was examining, the problems
that arose between black and white pilgrims on their journey
centered on issues of white privilege and black resentment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are a microcosm of this society that we are trying to
change, so it has been very, very interesting and grueling _ both
emotionally and psychologically. It has been a real Middle Passsage
experience,'' said Ingrid Askew, who is black and one of the two
organizers of the pilgrimage.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, Schiel, 58, who is white, believed the walk would
give him the opportunity to witness the struggles of
African-Americans while offering support to the black walkers.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he said he found himself resented by black female
walkers who believed that as a white man he tried to assume
leadership positions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It pained me to be accused of exhibiting white privilege,'' he
said. ``So I drew back, the typical white thing to do is draw
back.''
</P>
<P>
   Soul Brown, a 38-year-old black woman from Boston's Roxbury
neighborhood, saw things differently.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, who chronicled the journey in a series of articles for
the Globe, said the trip was a sacred time for the black
participants to grapple with their ancestors' suffering as well as
to look within for their own racism.
</P>
<P>
   The only way the black walkers knew how to do this, said Brown,
was to come together, which caused white participants to feel
excluded. But those same white walkers, said Brown, wanted to see
blacks as victims, but not look at themselves as perpetrators or
beneficiaries of a racist system.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then it was a question of why are you here? How could you
disavow your own involvement? This created a lot of tension,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   But African-Americans, too, were reluctant to deal with their
own issues, such as the need to be seen as distinct from other
blacks who were not American-born, said Trinidad native Jennifer
Ire. ``This pilgrimage threw up a whole lot of mirrors for us to
look at ourselves and to look at how we live with each other,''
said Ire of New Salem.
</P>
<P>
   ``At a point I began to ask myself,'' said Schiel `` `Why am I
going on this pilgrimage with these people to Africa?' ''
</P>
<P>
   If he felt uncomfortable during the black-led ceremonies on the
pilgrimage, then he questioned how would he feel in Ghana at the
site of the infamous slave castles.
</P>
<P>
   The numbing pain of self-evaluation was coupled with the
physical strain of walking 20 to 30 miles a day.
</P>
<P>
   Askew usually traveled a few states ahead of the group to find
churches where they could sleep. Despite her efforts, there were
times the weary walkers had no idea where they would spend the
night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes we would have a bed, sometimes we would have floor,
sometimes we would sleep on concrete, sometimes it was outside of
the church,'' said Askew.
</P>
<P>
   In the morning, they would rise early to visit historical
landmarks such as a former slave shack in the back of a suburban
New York home.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't until they reached the Carolinas, said Brown, that
they felt they had reached a turning point. Previously, she said
they had traveled through northern cities and suburbs, but now they
were crossing sprawling cotton fields.
</P>
<P>
   It was in the South where they could witness remnants of the
civil rights movement: In Greensboro, N.C., they sat at the
Woolworth's counter where in 1960 four African-American students
staged a sit-in that proved to be one of the key moments of the
civil rights movement.
</P>
<P>
   In Sparta, Ga., Ramona ``Nosapocket'' Peters, a Wampanoag Indian
from Mashpee, traced a painful segment of her own history. It was
the birthplace of her grandmother, who was part Cherokee Indian,
African-American, and white. But Peters, 47, said her grandmother,
who was very light-skinned, placed lesser value on darker-skinned
people.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was learned behavior and I got to see where she learned
it,'' said Peters. ``Knowing the damage internalized racism can do
to a family, I wanted to find the medicine to cure it.''
</P>
<P>
   Peters, who calls herself a ``black Indian,'' was now able to
leave the journey, but as other walkers crossed the Georgia border
to Alabama, the theme of internal racism would come up again.
</P>
<P>
   When they entered the small town of Heflin, Ala., there were
stares and a few motorists screamed racial epithets.
</P>
<P>
   As the ``pointers'' on the trip directed them with a map to the
church, say pilgrims, they believed only when they reached the
church would they be embraced. But they never got that far.
</P>
<P>
   Some later said the black church members wouldn't accept whites
or Buddhist walkers. Others believed they were afraid that such a
diverse group would stir up trouble with local whites.
</P>
<P>
   Church members who disagreed with the decision to leave the
group stranded found them an abandoned home to stay in and food.
</P>
<P>
   For Brown and other African-Americans, the reaction of the
church members forced them to realize that blacks sometimes exhibit
the same attitudes they have fought.
</P>
<P>
   ``It forced us to look deep within ourselves for racism,'' said
Brown.
</P>
<P>
   Said Ire: ``It was sad. It showed that some blacks had also
absorbed some of the hatred that had been thrown to them and now
they were throwing it back.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time the group arrived in New Orleans, Schiel had decided
not to continue with the group to Africa.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just had to go,'' he said. ``But, I learned I have to be
much more sensitive about using white privilege and I thought I
knew something about that.''
</P>
<P>
   At least 40 walkers remained on the pilgrimage _ most of them
black.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, they couldn't find a boat to sail to Africa, but
someone loaned them one. They are now in Puerto Rico. The lack of
funds to continue is still a big problem, said Askew, who is in
Boston to raise money.
</P>
<P>
   Soul Brown left Puerto Rico last week to take a job in
television in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel as a person I have grown tremendously and have seen
things I would never have gotten an opportunity to see in life,''
she said. ``But things were not always perfect. All the problems in
society with blacks and whites, all these things appeared and rose
up during the course of the pilgrimage.''
</P>
</TEXT>
