<HEADER>
A7727 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NOLAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      01-18 0685
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOLAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEITHER A CRISIS, NOR A TRAGEDY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARTIN F. NOLAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO -- This is a week of anniversaries. Harry Truman
was inaugurated 50 years ago, Bill Clinton was inaugurated six
years ago and two years ago. And I celebrate the end of a year of
being Monica-free.
</P>
<P>
   The Lewinsky-Clinton-Tripp-Starr-Hyde scandal staggered on
without my opinion throughout 1998. The reasons will, in the
judgment of peers, probably disqualify me for any position of
trust, honor or profit in the current frenzied state of American
punditry: I don't think it's a crisis and I sympathize with
arguments on both sides.
</P>
<P>
   A crisis? As Exhibit A, I submit a press release, numbered 302,
from the National Football League, headlined: ``NFL Football
Outrates Impeachment Coverage.'' On Dec, 19, while the House was
pondering impeachment, CBS coverage of the New York Jets vs. the
Buffalo Bills ``dramatically outrated'' the other networks, stuck
with the slow ground game in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   A crisis? House members, after some melodrama, survived their
date with destiny. All but 13, the impeachment managers, have moved
out of camera range.
</P>
<P>
   Any ritual that can stifle 100 senators is solemn and serious,
and therefore no waste of time. The argument that impeachment
disrupts important business is specious. Senators do not lack
information about health care, Social Security or the Brazilian
centavo. What they need is the will to decide. Sitting and thinking
quietly about a tough vote is excellent preparation for such
decisions.
</P>
<P>
   A crisis? The person who has kept the scandal from becoming a
crisis is the president himself. Were he to sit whimpering in the
White House or cowering in despair at Camp David, that would be a
crisis. But he is as chatty as ever, wonking on at the drop of a
policy statement.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's ability to compartmentalize is admirable and real, in
vivid contrast to that of Richard Nixon. During Watergate, after
Nixon had avoided reporters for five months, he called a press
conference near his home in San Clemente. Waiting under a broiling
sun, Dan Rather of CBS asked me, ``What's the toughest
non-Watergate question you could ask him?'' My response, which
Rather recounted in his memoirs, was: ``Mr. President, what do you
do all day?'' Dan said, ``Oh no, that would be too tough.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is tougher than Nixon and considerably less culpable.
The conservative animus against Clinton exceeds that of the liberal
fury against Nixon. The anti-Clinton fever of the Vincent Foster
Memorial Society evokes right-wing rumors about Franklin Roosevelt
cackling maniacally in the White House after planning the attack on
Pearl Harbor.
</P>
<P>
   Nutcakes form a perilously large portion of the Republican
Party's base and have polluted politics. Lying about sex is usually
trivial and hardly seems impeachable. And yet, and yet.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton may be getting a bad deal, but he has dealt many of the
cards himself. ``I have never had sexual relations with Monica
Lewinsky,'' the president said in a civil deposition Jan. 17. Some
lawyers have argued that Clinton need not have testified at all,
but should have defaulted the Paula Jones case. Defaulting would be
the political equivalent of taking the Fifth Amendment, other
lawyers have said. So? Was that worse than being impeached?
</P>
<P>
   It was Clinton's choice, which he faced again seven months
later. In a life of striving, networking and Renaissance
Weekending, he usually talked his way out of everything. Before the
federal grand jury in August, he could have amended his testimony
with something closer to the truth. Had he done so, his poll
ratings would have soared and Kenneth Starr would have packed his
bags for Malibu. Instead, he quibbled about verbs.
</P>
<P>
   To be or not to be. This scandal is neither a crisis nor a
tragedy because Clinton's problem is not animal instinct. Clinton's
tragic flaw is not sexual, but intellectual. Among the seven deadly
sins, pride outpolls lust.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Martin F. Nolan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
