<HEADER>
A7730 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKO-CHINA-BBALL-BOS &LR;      01-18 1134
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKO-CHINA-BBALL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINA'S HOOP PHENOM FACES CAPITALISTIC DILLEMMA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (i and s coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By INDIRA A.R. LAKSHMANAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHANGHAI _ China should not mourn the loss of Michael Jordan.
After all, it has Yao Ming. At 18, Yao is already playing
basketball head and shoulders _ maybe even half a torso _ above
most other players in China.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, he is 7-foot-5.
</P>
<P>
   Yao plays in the Chinese Basketball Association, which draws 130
million television viewers _ as many as watch the Super Bowl _ for
regular season games. Fans of what has become China's most popular
sport are pinning their hopes on the mobile, muscular star of the
Shanghai Sharks to become the first Chinese player to join the
National Basketball Association. And in the new China, there may be
a better chance of that than ever before.
</P>
<P>
   Already considered one of the three best professional centers in
China, the high school senior attended Nike's All-America Camp in
Indianapolis last summer, where he ranked second among 40 top high
school centers.
</P>
<P>
   But American college coaches who have called his mother and
approached his managers so far have gotten nowhere. Fame and
fortune may beckon, but the Chinese system dictates that Yao
belongs to his team, his league, and ultimately, his country.
</P>
<P>
   Yet rules and values are changing here, perhaps faster in
Shanghai than anywhere else. And Yao's dilemma _ to serve his
country or himself _ illustrates that evolution. To leave China for
big money and better competition would once have been denounced as
unpatriotic and capitalistic.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Yao's managers speak almost in passing of duty to the
communist nation. Their bigger concern is the bottom line: How much
money will they be able to get for him when the time comes?
</P>
<P>
   Chinese pop culture has embraced almost everything American,
particularly basketball. NBA games air several times a week on
cable, and the marketing opportunities of a Chinese player in the
NBA would be tremendous.
</P>
<P>
   Yao says he is not interested in money and declined to reveal
how much he currently earns. But a team manager says his salary,
like other rookie Chinese players, is $61 a month. That is
supplemented by bonuses from the club, tournament hosts, and the
national team, for which Yao also plays. Even so, the total,
together with free dormitory food and housing, can't approach even
the lowest salaries in the NBA, which are around $250,000.
</P>
<P>
   To play abroad, Yao would need approval from his club, the CBA,
and government authorities, says Yu Xiao Miao, vice general manager
of Shanghai Oriental Television Basketball Club, known to millions
as the Shanghai Sharks.
</P>
<P>
   But ``the municipal government of Shanghai is very open-minded,
so they'd never hold him back,'' said Yu. ``And for our club, it's
a commercial decision. He's under contract and we'd like to train
him more. The better he is, the better price we can sell him for.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet it is not that simple. Years of schooling in duty to his
nation and a sense of obligation to the club that has housed and
fed him for the last four years tug at Yao. The amount of food he
has eaten as a teenager would have impoverished his parents, one of
his managers jokes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't really thought about it, but I think it would not be
difficult for me to decide,'' Yao said this week in a rare
interview, when asked whether he would play in the United States if
given the chance. ``If my boss thinks it's good for my development,
I would go.''
</P>
<P>
   Yao is on the sidelines now, his size 18 left foot broken and
wrapped in a gigantic cast clad with a sock his mother knitted to
keep him warm in the unheated gym.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what he would do if forced to choose between playing in
America or on the Chinese Olympic team, he smiled gently and
skirted the question with a finesse far beyond his age. ``Isn't it
too early to ask that question?''
</P>
<P>
   Pressed again, Yao turned philosophical. ``Whatever you decide,
you lose something,'' he said. ``If I stay in China, I lose the
opportunity to go to the NBA. But if I go to the NBA, I lose the
chance to serve my country. And my country is the most important
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Teammate Wayman Strickland, 28, the only American on the Sharks,
said Yao can serve his nation beyond playing for the national team.
The mere chance to become the first Chinese player in the NBA,
Strickland said, would be ``a big deal for China.''
</P>
<P>
   There is a precedent. In 1997, Zheng Haixia, a 6-foot-8 veteran
of China's women's Olympic team, joined the Women's National
Basketball Association in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Strickland believes Yao would be one of the top three picks if
he entered the NBA draft. ``He's got the ability to run up and down
the court, a nice touch, and good basic skills,'' said Strickland.
``Combine that with being almost 7-foot-5, and you've got
tremendous potential.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of Americans couldn't contemplate why he wouldn't just
leave, go to university for a year and then the NBA,'' added
Strickland, a San Francisco native. ``But he'd be leaving
everything. If he went without permission, he couldn't even contact
his family. Here it's family and duty first . . . It's a huge
cultural difference. Everything is a group decision _ you go
through the system and you do what's best for the group, not the
individual.''
</P>
<P>
   Fiercely protected by his team and parents, Yao seems unaffected
by his fame and spends his free time reading Chinese history and
playing computer games on his Sony Playstation. He has been living
in a government sports dormitory since he was 14, when he began
playing for the Shanghai junior team. He became a professional last
season, but still attends school three days a week.
</P>
<P>
   Yao started playing basketball at age 9, influenced by his
mother, who is 6-foot-3 and his father, who is 6-foot-7. Both both
played for China's national teams in the 1970s. His favorite player
is Houston Rockets star Hakeem Olajuwon, for his speed and moves.
He admires the Larry Bird-era Boston Celtics for ``creating a new
era in history,'' but politely said the current Celtics are ``not
as good as before.''
</P>
<P>
   Yao plays basketball for four hours a day and studies for two
hours, in addition to his classes and weekend visits to his
parents. He doesn't have a girlfriend _ ``I don't have time,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Yu, the Sharks vice general manager, said, ``Although Yao Ming
is a very good person, he is not yet a member of the Communist
Youth League. But he actually plays a far more important role on
the team than the Communist Youth League members.''
</P>
<P>
   Yu added, ``He also knows our team needs him and he needs to
develop the basics. If he goes to America now, he might just be
sitting on a cold bench.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
