<SLUG> BC-JORDAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM NOW ON, VOTES ON LABOR WILL COUNT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT A. JORDAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; As part of its aggressive new agenda for this legislative
year, the Massachusetts AFL-CIO has developed a more comprehensive
report card and tougher tests for members of the Legislature. No
longer, says state AFL-CIO President Robert Haynes, will
legislators be graded only on their voting record on labor bills.
This year, legislators will also be held accountable for other
important aspects of labor's agenda.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past,'' Haynes says, ``we had labor endorsements
predicated on the legislators' voting record, and often times those
votes were not truly reflective of the legislators' actions
regarding labor.'' While some had very good voting records on
issues important to labor's agenda, ``they really didn't carry the
full agenda. For example, they were not actively involved in moving
legislation out of committee and onto the floor. We are now going
to hold legislators accountable in that area also,'' among other
things.
</P>
<P>
   If, for instance, a legislator votes against bringing a labor
bill out of their committee, that legislator will get a negative
mark from the AFL-CIO. Legislators will also be scored on how well
they serve labor in their communities, including the level of their
support on organizing drives to bring more workers into unions, and
their commitment toward protecting workers and working families.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope that legislators will work to defend employees when
employers go after them,'' Haynes says. ``We also hope that they
actively support efforts for good wages and benefits.''
</P>
<P>
   The state AFL-CIO's more aggressive approach toward lawmakers is
its response to the number of times that bills addressing labor's
needs were left to languish in committee, including legislation to
increase the minimum wage and protect wages of construction
workers.
</P>
<P>
   While the new approach will apply broadly to both House and
Senate, it is no secret that labor advocates view House Speaker
Thomas M. Finneran as the key reason important labor bills never
left committees or came to the floor for a vote.
</P>
<P>
   This year, rather than repeat past attempts to work with
Finneran _ which routinely failed _ the AFL-CIO and other labor
groups have decided to take their agenda directly to the
legislators. Some legislators _ despite these new, tougher measures
of accountability _ support this direct approach. They, too, have
been frustrated by what they view as the House leadership's lack of
support for bills filed by organized labor.
</P>
<P>
   The new approach will be tested in the coming weeks as the
AFL-CIO launches a campaign in support of labor-friendly
legislation, new and old. Included are bills that increase the
state's minimum wage; enhance paid family and medical leave;
provide money to renovate or expand schools; ensure severance pay
for workers involved in a plant closing or relocation; improve
workers compensation benefits; and enforce stricter child labor
laws.
</P>
<P>
   To bring more public attention to these bills, the AFL-CIO said
it will organize letter drops, develop phone banks and work closely
with local clergy and community-based organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Other labor groups have also adopted a similar approach. In a
recent letter to state representatives, Painters &AMP; Allied Trades
District Council 35 informed the legislators of a new policy
``regarding contribution requests from House members.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the local's new policy, money that was once given to
candidates will be used instead to finance the cost of mailing to
union members their state representatives' position on labor
issues.
</P>
<P>
   The letter stresses this policy applies only to members of the
House, and not the Senate. Explaining why the focus is only on the
House, the letter's author, John Lauglin, director of political and
public relations for the Painters Council, said, ``for the very
simple reason that in the Senate, President Tom Birmingham has
allowed votes on our bills. In the House, Speaker Tom Finneran
decides for everybody else the fate of a bill.''
</P>
<P>
   While some state legislators have expressed their resentment
with the AFL-CIO's and other labor groups' aggressive new approach
toward them, others say the policy is the best way to get important
labor bills passed in the House.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the last couple of years many House members have felt
that the legislative agenda was too tightly controlled from the
top,'' said Senator Steven Tolman, a Brighton Democrat and a strong
advocate of labor who, after serving two terms in the House, was
elected this year to the Senate seat vacated by his brother,
Warren, who ran for lieutenant governor with Scott Harshbarger.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt there is some risk involved in organized labor's new
approach to Beacon Hill, particularly in the House. Finneran, who
determines committee assigments and chairmanships, may be willing
to test his leadership strength against organized labor's strength.
Aware that some members might be wary of Finneran's power, Tolman
says in response to any such concerns, ``All you need is a desk and
a phone to do the job properly. If that is what you end up with,
you can be proud.''
</P>
<P>
   Legislators who support labor's agenda say they welcome the fact
that they will be held accountable not by the speaker, but by the
people who got them there _ organized labor, workers, and working
families.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Robert A. Jordan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
