<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-E-COMMERCE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDY SUGGESTS BASICS FOR E-COMMERCE SUCCESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WENDY TANAKA  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Some Web sites get a million visits a day, but
success lies in how to convert those visits into actual on-line
sales to customers who visit again and again.
</P>
<P>
   Studio Archetype Inc. professes to have a solution. The company
recently released a study stating that sales are driven by consumer
confidence in a Web site.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issue is trust and maintaining an ongoing relationship
with customers,'' said Clement Mok, founder of the San
Francisco-based Web site designer. ``It's fine to get one-time
transactions. Everyone's willing to buy once. But how do you
encourage people to go back?''
</P>
<P>
   Studio Archetype's report, which was done in conjunction with
Cheskin Research Inc. of Redwood Shores, Calif., said Web sites
that have six characteristics will engender the most trust from
consumers. The six are:
</P>
<P>
   _ Solid brand-name recognition of the company or product.
</P>
<P>
   _ Easy navigation. If customers have to click too many times to
get what they need, they will likely get frustrated and not want to
call up the site again. Customers also get frustrated if they click
on links that don't exist or don't work.
</P>
<P>
   _ Good customer service. Sites must state how merchandise orders
are processed, how orders will be delivered, and how customers can
return products.
</P>
<P>
   _ Good presentation of information.
</P>
<P>
   _ State-of-the-art technology.
</P>
<P>
   _ Seals of approval. The survey found that consumers were more
apt to buy from Web sites that had the logos of security and
privacy endorsers, like VeriSign and TrustE, on their pages. Logos
for major credit card companies that have contracts with the site
also made consumers more comfortable about buying from that site.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Web sites have these signs, it means they're legitimate
sites,'' said Davis Masten, a principal at Cheskin Research.
</P>
<P>
   Although there has been plenty of attention on security and
privacy in Web site transactions, Masten said those issues were
part of the bigger consumer trust issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I liken trust to reliability,'' he said. ``It says what (a Web
site) is going to do and not misrepresent itself.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Studio Archetype clients have found the company's six-point
model useful.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta-based United Parcel Service Inc. said Studio Archetype's
redesign of its main Web site had dramatically improved business.
</P>
<P>
   Rakesh Sapra, director of interactive marketing at UPS, said his
company's Web site _ www.ups.com _ went from tracking 100,000
orders per month in 1995 to about 1 million trackings a month due
to better site navigation and overall design.
</P>
<P>
   Some Internet analysts took issue with some of the findings and
the methodology of the study by Studio Archetype and Cheskin.
</P>
<P>
   Erina DuBois, digital commerce analyst at Dataquest Inc. in San
Jose, Calif., said Web sites with seals of approval did not hold
more sway with consumers.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of consumers don't read about privacy stuff,'' she said.
In addition, DuBois said, ``Certificates, like VeriSign, are not in
wide use. Most consumers don't know what VeriSign is.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the other five components outlined in the report, DuBois
said they were ``basic, 101, Web site stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   But she strongly agreed that Web site customer service is going
to become more and more critical in doing business.
</P>
<P>
   ``People want to know, how do I handle returns? Whom do I call
if I have a return? Is there an 800 number, e-mail, fax?'' DuBois
said.
</P>
<P>
   Now, many consumers don't have an easy way of returning items or
getting more information on line, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything will have to be integrated at the back end,''
DuBois said.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, she sees e-commerce evolving.
</P>
<P>
   ``'97 was like, `Hey here's my site,''' DuBois said. ``'98 was,
`Let's make it easy to buy.' '99 will be customer service. How do I
retain them? Maybe some sites will have a button you can click on
to dial customer service.''
</P>
</TEXT>
