<HEADLINE>
GLOBE CRITICS RATE FILMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
 ! poor, !! fair, !!! good, !!!! excellent  
 
!!!! ``Affliction'' In a career filled with venturesome role
choices, Nick Nolte gives the performance of his career. He plays a
New Hampshire cop trying to liberate himself from the male pattern
of violence inflicted upon him by his brutish and alcoholic father
_ the latter impressively portrayed by James Coburn as human
wreckage still dangerous because he can still do damage.
Writer-director Paul Schrader has made a bleak, piercing, perfectly
pitched film of Russell Banks's novel. (R) 
 
!! ``At First Sight'' Val Kilmer is resourceful and affecting as a
blind man who never courts sympathy as he takes his chances in love
with a sighted woman. As played by Mira Sorvino, she's sympathetic,
too, partly because of the awkwardness and anxiety she expresses.
But the script (based on a true story) and the direction are more
pedestrian, diluting what could have been the film's impact.
(PG-13) 
 
!!! ``The Brandon Teena Story'' The technical roughness and
plainness of this documentary about a homophobic murder in Nebraska
in 1993 make it all the more gripping. Soft-pedaling sensationalism
and editorializing, it depicts a community destined to repeat its
hate-driven patterns of violence because _ to judge by the two men
who killed Brandon Teena so she wouldn't be able to testify aginst
them after they raped her _ denial rules there. (Unrated)
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
!!! 1/2 ``Hilary and Jackie'' The turbulent story of the late
British cellist Jacqueline du Pre, who during the '60s was
classical music's golden girl, and her less celebrated but more
stable sister, Hilary. It's a terrific sister act, thanks to Emily
Watson's bold, daring directness as Jackie, and Rachel Griffiths's
less apparent but more enduring strength in the face of her
sister's increasingly erratic lifestyle before being diagnosed with
multiple sclerosis. (R) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ! ``In Dreams'' Stupid, pointless psychological horror film,
about a woman (Annette Bening) who shares a metaphysical connection
with a serial killer (Robert Downey Jr.). So much wasted talent _
starting with writer-director Neil Jordan, whose career continues
its erratic track. (R) (Renee Graham) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   !! 1/2 ``Varsity Blues'' James Van Der Beek brings his patented
take on coming of age (honed weekly as dreamy Dawson on the TV show
``Dawson's Creek'') to the big screen. High-school football is the
backdrop for this sweetly familiar explication of youthful
idealism, wherein the bitterly ambitious adults are taken to task
by the righteously innocent adolescents. Of course, they're not so
innocent that they don't habitually undress, guzzle beer, and swipe
patrol cars. But it's all in the name of small-town Texas fun. (R)
(Joan Anderman)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
