<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990118.0175 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 14:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7749 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STAGE-RAGTIME-2TAKES-     01-18 1189
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAGE-RAGTIME-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM RAGTIME, RICHES 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATTI HARTIGAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Backstage before a performance of the musical
``Ragtime'' here, the usual bustle prevails _ but there's also a
jovial spirit, a sort of cheerful chaos. The wardrobe folks whistle
merrily as they comb fresh curls out of wig after wig. Technicians
chatter amiably as they breeze through narrow halls. The holiday
season is in full swing in this city at the foot of Mount Rainier,
and snow is falling ever so gently on the clean, efficient downtown
streets. The actors call out greetings as they arrive and share
plans to attend a post-performance latke party being thrown by
Theresa Tova, the self-proclaimed ``Jewish diva'' of the cast, who
plays the charismatic revolutionary Emma Goldman in the epic show.
</P>
<P>
   It's just another routine day on the road for the 100-member
cast and crew of the touring production. Another day, another city,
another show.
</P>
<P>
   But there's also something miraculous about this workaday scene.
The tour, which began in April, was abruptly shut down in
mid-November by the embattled producing company Livent Inc., only
to be resurrected just as abruptly two days later by the Pace
Theatrical Group. For a few fleeting days in between those
announcements, it looked as if the tour would never make it to
Seattle _ or to Boston, where ``Ragtime'' opens a long-awaited
10-week run at the Colonial Theatre on Wednesday. So despite the
business-as-usual atmosphere backstage, this tour has been anything
but routine. It's been quite a journey.
</P>
<P>
   RAGTIME, Page L4 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It began a little more than a year ago in New York, when
rehearsals began with director Frank Galati. ``Ragtime'' _ based on
the novel by E. L. Doctorow, with a book by Terrence McNally and a
score by Stephen Flaherty _ tells the story of three families set
against the backdrop of American society in 1906; it touches on
themes of racism, feminism, immigration, and, of course, the
American dream. Back in the beginning, some folks who signed on for
the tour were drawn to this particular story for personal as well
as professional reasons. There was Tova, the daughter of Polish
Holocaust survivors who had her surname changed by immigration
officials when her family immigrated to North America in the 1950s.
There was Alton Fitzgerald White, who didn't have to do much
research for the role of Coalhouse Walker Jr. because he knows all
too well what it's like to walk through life as a black man in a
racist society. There was general manager Tom Domenici, a
second-generation American whose Italian-born grandmother worked in
a sweatshop until she was well into her 80s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ragtime'' was a story they knew well, and they were eager to
tell it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Where prosperity meets greed
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This tale, after all, is a quintessential American drama, about
the promise of prosperity colliding with the reality of intolerance
and greed. At the end of this century, it provides an opportunity
to look back to the century's beginnings, to try to understand
where we have been and where we are going. And the view isn't
always pretty. ``The world seems to dash our hopes hour by hour,''
Galati says, ``but the story itself is both a way in and a way out.
My job is trying to connect audiences with stories, the same way
you go to a therapist or a friend to tell the story that hurts in
order to be healed. That was Freud's whole idea. Tell me, what did
you dream? How did it hurt? In the telling of the story, there is
something curative. People walk who were unable to walk. Hearts are
mended where they were broken. That's what the national
storytelling impulse is all about.'' One of the last numbers of the
show, in fact, is a song called ``Make Them Hear You,'' a rousing,
idealistic call to repeat tales of injustice, of intolerance.
</P>
<P>
   So from the very beginning, Galati inspired the actors to do
just that _ make audiences hear their message out on the road. The
first stop was Washington, D.C., where the show opened last April.
And it was there, early in the tour, that the relevance of the show
hit hard one fine spring day.
</P>
<P>
   Consider this scenario. The ``Ragtime'' cast is performing for
an audience including the president and the vice president. It's a
big night, and White is bursting with anticipation. He, after all,
sings that final rousing ballad; he has the last bow. And so he
sets off for the theater, a well-dressed black man standing on a
street corner in Dupont Circle, a tony Washington neighborhood. He
puts his hand up for a cab. Zip. One goes by. Zip, another cab
passes. Fourteen taxis fly by before one finally stops, getting him
to the theater in barely enough time. He breathes deep, performs
the show, gets a standing ovation, does the meet-and-greet with the
president, basks in the applause. And then he steps outside the
theater _ and again he can't get a cab. Incensed, he walks the mile
or so back to his hotel.
</P>
<P>
   ``These things happen every day, and I'm lucky I can use that in
the show,'' White recalls. ``I mean, there I am in the nation's
capital and I can't get a taxi to or from the theater. I can use
that. Other black men, I don't know what they do with that.''
</P>
<P>
   White left the show after the Seattle engagement to star in the
production still running on Broadway, but his replacement in the
road company, Lawrence Hamilton, tells similar tales. ``You know
what? I'm a 1999 Coalhouse Walker Jr.,'' Hamilton says. ``I feel it
every day. There are times I can't get a cab. It doesn't matter
what you do. You can make $10,000 a week. So what? This'' _ he
touches the skin on his arm _ ``is what matters. But if I can
change one producer's mind, one fellow in South Boston, one
cabdriver who won't take me to Roxbury, then I've done my job.''
</P>
<P>
   During the course of the tour, which went from Washington to
Denver and Minneapolis and then Seattle, the cast was acutely aware
of news events that mirrored the themes of the show. ``Look what we
deal with,'' says Michael Rupert, who plays the Latvian immigrant
Tateh. ``We saw a black man dragged behind a pickup truck in
Jasper, Texas. We saw a young man beaten to death and left dying on
a fence in Wyoming. The middle class has shrunk and disappeared.
The division between the rich and poor is getting wider. And here
we are at the turn of the century.''
</P>
<P>
   In the show, one of the subplots concerns Evelyn Nesbit, the
first national sex symbol, whose husband murdered the architect
Stanford White. They called it the ``crime of the century,'' but as
one character says in the play, ``It was only 1906, and there were
94 years to go.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Learning on the road
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There are lessons to be learned in those 94 years, and there
were lessons to be absorbed out there on the road. The company, by
all accounts, learned them together. ``This is the most spiritually
together company I've ever worked with,'' says Domenici. ``I've
done `Phantom' and `Miss Saigon' and `Riverdance,' and this is the
most loving group I've ever known.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
