</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEARST-NEWS-BUDGET-HNS </SLUG>
  
 Monday, Jan. 18, 1999    
 Editors      The Hearst News Service will file the following
stories for Tuesday. If you have questions, please call Susie McBee
or Tim Spence at 202-298-6920.    (The ``HNS'' tag appears in all
sluglines.)   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-SPEECH (Washington) _ President Clinton prepares his
State of the Union address for delivery to Congress at 9 p.m. EST
Tuesday focusing on the ``business of the nation'' and not
mentioning his impeachment trial in the Senate. Clinton's
middle-of-the-road proposals seek to reward traditional Democratic
constituencies and court GOP moderates. By STEWART M. POWELL, DAN
FREEDMAN and MARK HELM.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-DEFENSE (Washington) _ When White House Counsel Charles
F.C. Ruff outlines the defense in President Clinton's impeachment
trial Tuesday, he is expected to delve into the facts of the
president's relationship with Monica Lewinsky, a strategy that
House prosecutors never expected. By JUDY HOLLAND and JENNIFER
CORBETT DOOREN.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-SCHUMER (Washington) _ Sen. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y., a
supporter of President Clinton, discusses the president's prospects
as the Senate impeachment trial enters the defense phase. By ERIC
ROSENBERG.
</P>
<P>
   (EDITORS, Marianne Means is on vacation. Her MEANS-COLUMN will
resume Thursday in the COMMENTARY (``k'') category.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-18-99 1401EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990118.0177 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 14:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7751 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STAGE-RAGTIME-2ND &LR;  &UR; TA     01-18 1237
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAGE-RAGTIME-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 SEATTLE: ... ever known.''  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   So imagine how Domenici felt on the night of Nov. 17, in the
middle of the Minneapolis run. He got the word that the show was
closing: The Toronto-based Livent, which was under criminal
investigation for accounting fraud, was filing for bankruptcy and
closing the tour. (Just this week, company founders Garth Drabinsky
and Myron Gottlieb were indicted in New York on charges they
inflated corporate earnings and siphoned off $4.6 million in
kickbacks.) In retrospect, it shouldn't have come as too much of a
surprise: Theater folks have been suspicious of Livent for years.
Drabinsky has mounted lavish shows like ``Ragtime'' and the revival
of ``Showboat,'' sending them out on the road for long runs with
huge advertising campaigns. The numbers may have worked onstage,
but they didn't add up in the accounting department.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Domenici was stunned. As company manager, it was his job
to deliver the news, so he gathered the cast for a meeting on the
stage a half-hour before the curtain. The show was closing in two
days, he told them. The journey was over.
</P>
<P>
   ``My first reaction was, `I'm not finished with this part,' ''
says Rebecca Eichenberger, who plays the role of Mother.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had such passion for this story,'' adds Rupert.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was heartbreaking,'' White concludes.
</P>
<P>
   They got through the performance, choking up during songs like
``Our Children'' and ``Make Them Hear You.'' And then, when the
initial shock work off, practicality set in. Plane reservations
were made. Folks who had sublet their apartments called friends,
pleading for a place to sleep. Agents were contacted, auditions
scheduled.
</P>
<P>
   Two days later, Pace _ and its local producer, Jon B. Platt _
stepped in to resurrect the tour. Everyone had the option to
continue under the new management. Only three ensemble members
turned down the offer.
</P>
<P>
   Bernie Yvon, who plays Harry Houdini, admits he was a bit naive
about the business before this tour. ``In the end, we learned that
money is the bottom line,'' he says with a sigh.
</P>
<P>
   The tour then moved on to Seattle, where citizens are closely
monitoring the Microsoft antitrust suit. The Doctorow novel touches
on the great industrialists and financiers of the turn of the
century _ folks like J. Pierpont Morgan, who faced antitrust suits
of his own. Morgan plays a tiny role in the musical adaptation, but
the echoes of history are eerie, especially in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Intertwining stories
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The entire saga, in fact, has a contemporary pulse. A white
family lives a perfectly proper middle-class life in the upscale
suburb of New Rochelle, N.Y., but the wife discovers herself and
longs for a more meaningful existence. An African-American couple
dream of a bright future for their newborn son. A Latvian immigrant
clings to his daughter as he tries to eke out a living in this
strange, new world. One country, three groups. In the opening
prologue, the groups stand apart from one another at first,
separate but not necessarily equal. As the play proceeds, these
different stories are intertwined as cultural forces and
serendipity bring the characters together.
</P>
<P>
   Those same cultural forces persist today, and the actors
certainly bring their own life experiences and values to the roles.
Tova, for one, is the granddaughter of Old World socialists, and
her parents escaped the Warsaw Ghetto. ``It's in my bones; it's in
my blood,'' she says of her role as Emma Goldman. She says the
producers were astonished by her authentic Yiddish accent when she
auditioned, and she answered them in Yiddish. ``The translation was
`This you didn't think I could do? Who the hell do you think I am?'
'' Since then, she has become the unofficial dialect coach for the
actors playing immigrants; she's also the ``Yiddish soul of the
company,'' as well as the link to the immigrant experience. ``My
uncle worked in a factory making shoes in Lynn, Mass., and every
time I perform, I think of him walking up those seven floors to a
sweatshop in the heat of the summer.''
</P>
<P>
   General manager Tom Domenici thinks of his grandmother toiling
away in a garment sweatshop called Liberty Lace; Eichenberger
thinks of her own role as a working mother. Like the character she
plays, she isn't afraid to say that she gains self-fulfillment
through the noble yet undervalued work of raising her two young
children. She brings her children on the road with her when she
can, but one night, she hadn't seen them for three weeks. ``When we
sang `Our Children,' I sobbed through the whole number, especially
the part where we sing, `Children run so fast toward the future
from the past,' '' she recalls.
</P>
<P>
   Darlesia Cearcy also plays a mother in the show, but her role as
Sarah has an entirely different resonance. ``Sarah represents the
young black single mother, unwed,'' Cearcy says. ``It's the same
story as today: She's the epidemic of 1999. I'm not a single
mother, but I feel so much sympathy for her.''
</P>
<P>
   Her character is initially estranged from Coalhouse, the ragtime
pianist who is the baby's father, but they reunite and sing a love
song called ``Wheels of a Dream.'' And that scene, White says, is
reason enough that the show must go on. ``People aren't used to
seeing black people in love,'' he says. ``The media has us fighting
and kicking. Do you realize how powerful that scene is, when they
are sitting on that blanket and dreaming together about their son?
Wow, they're in love.''
</P>
<P>
   Onstage, the characters travel a long journey to get to that
moment, and the cast and creative team have traveled many a real
road to get to the Colonial Theatre. First there was the business
of distilling Doctorow's sweeping novel into a three-hour
production; many of the subplots, including the exploration of
sexuality and psychoanalysis, have been cut. The adaptation
maintains the glimmer of hope offered at the end of the novel, even
in the face of enormous personal loss, not to mention indignity and
injustice. But Galati, for one, says that hope is tempered by
knowledge. ``It's not a Pollyanna answer,'' he says. ``They're not
walking off into the sunset. They're walking off into the
Holocaust, to Hiroshima, to the carnage of the 20th century. And I
think that's what gives it so much emotional resonance and what
makes it leap from 1906 to 1999.''
</P>
<P>
   That knowledge is what made it so difficult for the actors to
accept the short-lived cancellation of the tour; they want the
journey to continue into the next century. (Producer Platt says the
Pace tour will close after the Boston run, but will reopen in
Houston this summer.) For now, Hamilton will be happy if he changes
one person's mind, if he can get out there and make them hear his
song. (It should be pointed out that ticket prices for the show run
as high as $75, and the actors report that audiences on the road
have been primarily white.)
</P>
<P>
   As for the bigger journey, the one called life, that one never
ends. ``By the time you reach the eleventh hour, you feel like
you've been sitting in a completely different world, all your own,
experiencing your own life, understanding your own culture and
adapting to others, which is basically what this country is
supposed to be about,'' Cearcy says. ``I am on a constant journey,
each and every night. I have to remind myself on a daily basis that
it is never, never over.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-18-99 1402EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990118.0178 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 14:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7752 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-SITCOMS-BOS &LR;      01-18 1438
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SITCOMS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TV'S PURE POP FOR NOW PEOPLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW GILBERT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Watching TV, I sometimes stumble across one of the
Spanish-language channels, where a seemingly endless soap opera is
playing itself out, an emotional novela ripe for director Pedro
Almodovar's campy treatment. She is heartsick, desperate, demeaned;
he is distant, macho, in his bathrobe. I have a vague sense of
what's going on, of the dramatic gist, of who's zooming whom. But I
can't understand the words she cries out at him, and I don't
recognize the curses he mumbles under his breath. The details are
lost to me. I am an outsider.
</P>
<P>
   Are English-language viewers beginning to feel the same way
about TV shows written in their native tongue? Are many of the
jokes, the repartee, the dramatic resonances becoming like
</P>
<P>
   a foreign language to those unschooled in pop culture? More and
more, it seems, series television is relying on specific, hip
reference to carry its scripts, making repeated nods to rock music,
contemporary film, and, yes, of course, TV itself. In most cases,
the references are blended into prime time's zillions of small
moments and punch lines. On ``Jesse,'' for example, the barmaid's
boyfriend says she looks like ``the girl from the Ricola
commercial.'' On ``The Hughleys,'' Milsap scares the kids with an
imitation of Billy Bob Thornton in ``Sling Blade.'' On the new
``Providence,'' a woman with a fresh nose job complains, ``I told
you I wanted Courteney Cox, not Jennifer Aniston.'' On ``Cupid,''
Claire tells Trevor she has a vivid image of Mount Olympus: ``I saw
`Boogie Nights,' '' she says.
</P>
<P>
   But on ``Will &AMP; Grace,'' allusions to pop culture absolutely run
rampant. They are a hallmark of the hyper-witty sitcom as much as
the fact that one of its lead characters, Will, is openly gay. You
can hardly make it through an episode without recalling an
Entertainment Weekly's worth of cool tidbits. Last fall, the series
premiere opened with a George Clooney joke, and it has been a pop
quiz ever since, with evocations of R.E.M.'s Michael Stipe's latest
hairstyle, with lines like ``It's too `Stevie Nicks: The Heavy
Years,' '' and with tart mentions of MTV's ``Real World: Seattle,''
Markie Post's Lifetime movies, ``Party of Five,'' and ``Pop-Up
Video'' on VH1. About the title of an autobiographical play by
Jack, a gay character who is stereotypically queeny, Will quips:
``I guess `There's Something About Mary' was already taken.''
</P>
<P>
   In the light of the present tense, this kind of allusiveness can
seem delightfully clever or, at its most obscure, self-consciously
with-it. Neat references to little-known cable movies can be
postmodern and offer a reward for those many hours and dollars we
might have spent on brain-draining entertainment. They can also
smack of insider trading, exclusivity, and smugness, on the order
of: ``Oh, ha ha ha, you didn't see `Sling Blade'? Everybody else
did.'' They can ground cynical series like ``Lateline'' and the
late, great ``The Larry Sanders Show'' in reality, as they deploy
cameo appearances in the way other shows drop pop allusions. But a
frenzy of in-jokes can also give a show the appearance of
overlooking the majority of the country, who don't really know much
about the Beltway and open lesbian Candace Gingrich. (``There's
nothing wrong with you that the right man couldn't fix,'' G. Gordon
Liddy told her on ``Lateline.'')
</P>
<P>
   For today's networks, the pop jokes are _ what else? _
demographic tools, signals to specific viewers that say, ``This
show's for you!'' The makers of ``Will &AMP; Grace'' are saying, ``Our
viewers of choice are hip enough to know what style Michael Stipe
is working this season.'' The makers of ``Lateline'' are saying,
``Our viewers of choice are politically savvy boomers who know what
guest stars like G. Gordon Liddy represent.'' While these messages
may cause many to surf on by, the networks are no longer overly
concerned about winning a quantity of Nielsen homes. They've
narrowed their ambitions to targeted buying audiences that they can
sell to advertisers. The teen-oriented shows, which are selling
products to the desirable youth market, are particularly laden with
pop code, most notably the WB's ``Dawson's Creek,'' whose
precocious characters are almost painfully media savvy (Dawson
himself is a filmmaker who idolizes Spielberg). On these shows, the
soundtracks are straight off today's Billboard charts.
</P>
<P>
   The networks also use pop reference to plug their own shows _ a
self-serving bit of product placement that is especially evident on
NBC. From a story line built around Conan O'Brien on ``Lateline''
and the ``Friends'' nose-job bit on ``Providence'' to a ``Will &AMP;
Grace'' swipe at Eriq LaSalle's ``ER'' deadpan, the Peacock has
been fairly shameless. Not that ABC was particularly altruistic
when it shaped an episode of ``Dharma &AMP; Greg'' around the final
episode of NBC's ``Seinfeld.'' Let's call that approach an
extension plug _ stealing the juice from someone else's socket.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Pop-up classics
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But what will all this timeliness mean in the future? Right now,
classic television shows like ``I Love Lucy,'' ``The Dick Van Dyke
Show,'' and ``The Mary Tyler Moore Show'' are completely available
to 1990s viewers some 50, 40, and 30 years after they were made.
Sure, they very much remain products of their time, both in terms
of social mores and fashion trends, from Lucy and Rickie's separate
beds to Laura's Capri pants and Rhoda's crocheted hats and hanging
beads. But their line-by-line meanings are not veiled in the
contemporary codes of their day. On Nick at Night and TV Land, they
continue to speak to us in a common language that doesn't require
translation.
</P>
<P>
   In 50 years, will our TV shows require a ``Pop-Up Video''
treatment, whereby explicatory bubbles let future generations in on
our secrets? Ted Baxter's bumbling egotism is perfectly clear to us
in 1999, but will the folks in 2050 get the joke when the Baxter
figure on ``Lateline'' says ``Charlie Rose pees in the shower''?
Will they need to consult their movie databases to know what Ken
Olin on ``L.A. Doctors'' means when he says, ``I might be a father
someday; look at Clint Eastwood''? Will they get the point when, on
``Ally McBeal,'' Calista Flockhart and Lara Flynn Boyle have a
tense moment about skirt length, weight loss, and sharing a cookie?
Will culture professors be writing books on pop tribalism as seen
on turn-of-the-millennium TV?
</P>
<P>
   Not that allusiveness can never hold up over the years. When
``The Drew Carey Show'' models an entire episode on the movie ``The
Full Monty,'' or when ``Just Shoot Me'' does a fun-house-mirror
version of ``Annie Hall,'' or when ``Seinfeld'' borrows from
``Betrayal,'' the humor works without any knowledge of the
alluded-to object. If you haven't seen ``Betrayal'' _ and most
people haven't even heard of Harold Pinter's play and movie _ you
can still fully enjoy the backward-moving ``Seinfeld'' episode, and
if you have seen ``Betrayal'' then you can enjoy the episode even
more. This type of time-based script also stands on its own, more
or less, like crime-show plots that are loosely based on real-life
murder cases. Understanding is not entirely dependent on
familiarity with other entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The way we live now
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Shows like ``Will &AMP; Grace'' raise questions about the future of
classic TV. Allusiveness doesn't appear to affect syndication, as
shows like ``Seinfeld'' thrive outside of prime time in the same
era during which they were prime-time hits. We are still close
enough to the ``Seinfeld'' heyday to understand what's funny when
Elaine doesn't like ``The English Patient,'' or whether or not
Jerry watches ``Melrose Place.''
</P>
<P>
   But pop culture is bigger than ever, and it changes so rapidly
that many of today's hip references may be washed away as the
Culture of the New continues to rain down. The number of movie
releases multiplies, cable TV stations proliferate, new bands hit
the top of the charts and then disappear with increasing velocity.
Our icons are less universal, so that a joke revolving around
Courteney Cox probably doesn't have the endurance of a joke about
Joan Crawford. Much of today's TV may be dating itself, withholding
its reflection of the way we live now from future generations who
aren't prepared to refer to footnotes about the many specific
fragments of our culture. Or maybe our TV shows are looking the
future straight in the eye and saying, ``I guess you had to be
there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
