<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 14:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7753 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-WATSON-BOS &LR;      01-18 1464
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-WATSON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EMILY WATSON IS MAKING WAVES AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RENEE GRAHAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The last time Emily Watson did this, she wound up
hating herself.
</P>
<P>
   It was more than two years ago, and Watson was a spanking-new
face garnering mad attention for her film debut, ``Breaking the
Waves.'' She played Bess, an emotionally fragile and profoundly
devout young woman whose faith in God leads her to extreme measures
in hopes of healing her paralyzed husband. The film won the Grand
Jury Prize at the 1996 Cannes Film Festival, and Watson received
best-actress nominations from the Golden Globes and the Academy
Awards.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, Watson found herself in the center of an unwavering,
unwanted spotlight, as everyone wanted to know the woman behind the
stunning performance. Her life became a blur of cities and
countries, sound bites and photo sessions. She was often startled
by the sight of her own saucer-wide blue eyes staring at her from
newspapers and magazines.
</P>
<P>
   ``I absolutely didn't know when you made a film you had to do
publicity for it, so it was all a bit of a shock,'' Watson said
recently, reflecting on her first year of living publicly. ``It
went on and on, and I felt like I had to talk about nothing but
myself for a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's strange because I sort of came out of it hating myself
because you have to do a really big PR job on the work, and also on
yourself,'' she said with a laugh. ``You just end up sort of nutty,
d'you know what I mean?''
</P>
<P>
   Watson may hate talking about herself, but since her film debut,
critics can't seem to say enough about her. The actress is again
receiving accolades for her latest film, ``Hilary and Jackie,'' a
drama based on the life of famed cellist Jacqueline du Pre, whose
career was cut short by multiple sclerosis, the degenerative
disease that eventually killed her. Watson's fierce performance as
Jackie has earned another Golden Globe nomination as best actress,
and the Oscar buzz (with nominations still a month away) has again
begun.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all very nice and fun,'' said Watson, 32, as she relaxed
in a fussily decorated hotel parlor on Central Park South, a
blood-red room adorned with paintings by Phyllis Diller and James
Dean. She was in New York for a few days before jetting off for
more publicity in Los Angeles. ``It's a nice bonus, but that's not
what it's all about. That's not why I became an actress.''
</P>
<P>
   The film, which opened Friday, also stars Rachel Griffiths,
David Morrissey, and James Frain. It was directed by Anand Tucker
and written by Frank Cottrell Boyce. It is based on the book ``A
Genius in the Family,'' by Hilary and Piers du Pre, Jacqueline's
sister and brother.
</P>
<P>
   As the title indicates, the film is more than an exploration of
Jacqueline du Pre's musical life and accomplishments. It is the
story of the tender, tragic bond she shared with her older sister,
Hilary, played by Griffiths. Both girls, raised in rural England,
were musical prodigies encouraged by their mother. Hilary was a
flutist and, for a time, was considered the more accomplished of
the two. The attention Hilary received pushed Jackie to strive for
perfection on the cello, and soon Jackie was receiving the standing
ovations, and invitations to perform on BBC radio.
</P>
<P>
   At one point in the film Jackie is given a rare cello by her
teacher, who tells her: ``It will give you the world, Jackie, but
you must give it yourself.'' She does, at times to devastating
effect. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Choosing a quiet life &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While Jackie pursues her music, Hilary, realizing she will never
again be as good as her sister, opts for a quiet family life in the
country. The story unfolds through the eyes of each sister, at
times repeating the same scenes, like a piece of chamber music
presented with different interpretations. The sisters were rivals
as much as confidantes. Before filming began, Watson and Griffiths
spent time getting to know each other, to create a credible bond as
sisters.
</P>
<P>
   ``As sisters, they were so finely attuned to one another,'' said
Watson (who says she has a sister, but did not consciously draw on
their relationship for the film). ``I think they both felt bound to
one another.''
</P>
<P>
   But this is also a film about the musician's art, the passions,
even obsessions, that drive genius. To prepare for her role as
Jackie, Watson studied cello for three months, something she also
did briefly as a teenager in her native London.
</P>
<P>
   ``I studied cello for about six months when I was 14, but gave
it up because I was very bad, and because it was very bothersome
lugging it around on the tube,'' as London's subway system is
called, Watson said. ``When I took it up again for the film, it was
really like learning it for the first time.''
</P>
<P>
   Watson learned basic cello techniques while she was in Dublin
making ``The Boxer,'' a 1997 drama starring Daniel Day-Lewis. But
it wasn't enough to learn the fingerings or the proper way to hold
a bow. Du Pre's performances were marked by her distinct body
movements, a vigorous, rhythmic sway attached to every note and
crescendo. In the film, her mother complains about the flamboyant
movements with ``all that hair flying all over the place.''
</P>
<P>
   It became an integral part of du Pre's persona onstage, not
unlike the leaps Leonard Bernstein would make while conducting.
Watching hours of the cellist's filmed performances, Watson found
learning to approximate du Pre's dance with her cello one of the
most physically demanding aspects of the role.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a movement teacher who certainly helped me,'' she said.
``The way Jackie moved, she very much became a part of the music
itself. You don't attempt to portray a musician, let alone a
musical genuis, without trying to capture their artistic style and
personality.''
</P>
<P>
   Therein Watson found perhaps the film's greatest challenge:
portraying an actual person. Watson has never before portrayed a
real person on screen, and she quickly understood the added
scrutiny such roles receive. The public can be very possessive of
its idols _ look at the guff endured by Ray Liotta when he played
Frank Sinatra in the recent HBO film ``The Rat Pack,'' or the
lingering snickers more than 40 years after the unathletic Anthony
Perkins portrayed Boston Red Sox pitcher Jimmy Piersall in ``Fear
Strikes Out.''
</P>
<P>
   But Watson refused to allow such expectations to hinder her
performance or the filmmakers' vision.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly, there's a responsibility to try to get as close as
you can to the person,'' she said. ``But this is a film, not a
historical document. As an actress, my first duty is to the story,
not to doing a perfect imitation.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Unvarnished intensity &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What Watson brings to the role is an unvarnished intensity that
has become a trademark after only three films. In his review of
``Breaking the Waves,'' critic Roger Ebert evoked the words of
Francois Truffaut regarding James Dean, saying Watson seemed to
proceed ``according to instinct instead of thought and
calculation.''
</P>
<P>
   The slight-of-build Watson _ who counts Judi Dench, Steve
McQueen, and Robert De Niro among her acting influences _ hardly
seems feral up close. Quiet and soft-spoken, she won't speak just
to fill the empty spaces, and is not given to lengthy answers when
a few words will suffice. Dressed in a thick gray sweater over a
black skirt and matching ankle boots, Watson said even she doesn't
know where her vivid performances originate: ``I'm as surprised as
anyone else,'' she said. But she understands how these performances
have shaped the public's perception.
</P>
<P>
   ``I probably wasn't at the top of the list when they were
casting `There's Something About Mary' _ I probably wasn't even on
the list,'' Watson said, referring to the zany summer comedy hit
that starred Cameron Diaz. ``But I would like to change that, yeah.
I would like to do something scatological.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps in the future, but don't expect it for a while. She
recently completed ``Angela's Ashes,'' the screen adaptation of
Frank McCourt's Pulitzer Prize-winning memoir of his hardscrabble
childhood in Ireland. That film is tentatively scheduled for a fall
release. There's also ``The Cradle Will Rock,'' a drama directed by
Tim Robbins.
</P>
<P>
   It will be a full, busy year for Watson, a year of doing what
she loves _ acting _ and what she doesn't love quite as much _
talking about acting, and, in particular, herself.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get better at it, and you learn to be a bit more
selective,'' she said. ``But when you're at the top of three days
of continuous interviews, you just don't ever think you're going to
get through it. It's better, yes, but it's still very funny to me
that people now see me as some sort of somebody.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
