<HEADER>
A7754 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-HEART-BOS &LR;      01-18 1194
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-HEART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACTING THEIR AGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RENEE GRAHAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; NEW YORK _ One could easily imagine Sean Connery and Gena
Rowlands as a long-married couple.
</P>
<P>
   Strolling through a doorway, Connery placed a gentle hand,
almost a caress, on the small of Rowlands's back, guiding her into
a midtown Manhattan hotel room doubling as a lion's den chock-full
of whirring tape recorders and eager reporters. As the interviews
began, the two eased into playful bickering and bantering, usually
punctuated with endearing winks and glances. Occasionally, each
fell into the particular cadence of completing the other's
sentences, reminiscent of those who have spent a lifetime breathing
each other's air.
</P>
<P>
   Connery and Rowlands seem so natural together, it's a wonder
Hollywood ever thought of putting them together.
</P>
<P>
   The two veteran actors star in ``Playing by Heart,'' an ensemble
drama about the search for meaningful and lasting love in
contemporary Los Angeles. They play Paul and Hannah, a married
couple who find their 40 years of togetherness threatened by an old
infidelity.
</P>
<P>
   The film, which opens Friday, also stars Gillian Anderson, Ellen
Burstyn, Anthony Edwards, Angelina Jolie, Jay Mohr, Ryan Phillippe,
Dennis Quaid, Jon Stewart, and Madeleine Stowe. But, make no
mistake, the Connery-Rowlands relationship is really the film's
centerpiece. What makes it so extraordinary is that, unlike most
film couplings, Connery and Rowlands actually look like husband and
wife, not father and daughter.
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood is, of course, run by middle-aged men who have long
since abandoned the age-comparable spouse one for the lithe
20-something trophy wife or girlfriend. Hence, too many films
reflect that skewed view of the romantic world _ older actors
hooked up with much younger actresses. In recent years, there's
been Jack Nicholson and Helen Hunt in ``As Good as It Gets''; Clint
Eastwood and Rene Russo in ``In the Line of Fire''; Michael Douglas
and Gwyneth Paltrow in ``A Perfect Murder''; and Harrison Ford and
Anne Heche in ``Six Days, Seven Nights.'' The average age
difference between these celluloid couples is more than a
quarter-century.
</P>
<P>
   But Connery and Rowlands are both in their 60s. It's easy to
believe them as a couple, as a man and a woman who have endured
life's hills and valleys side by side, and still love each other
dearly. In the film, they radiate a realistic sexuality far more
palpable than the strange, unbelievable pairing of say, Douglas
(54) and Paltrow (25).
</P>
<P>
   Both actors can relate to the longevity of Paul and Hannah's
marriage. Connery has been been married to his second wife for
nearly 25 years, and Rowlands enjoyed a lengthy marriage to
actor-filmmaker, John Cassavetes, until his death in 1989. But in
promoting the film, Connery said, ``Eighty percent of the
questions'' have been about the age of the characters and the
``length of their relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   ``One person said, `Well, for me, it's very hard to understand
being married 40 years,' '' he said. ``I guess it's just something
people picked up on because it's not normal.''
</P>
<P>
   Rowlands pondered his statement for a moment, then looked at
Connery quizzically. ``What's not normal?'' she interjected.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well,'' he said, by way of explanation, ``I mean they don't
make movies about people that age, with those sorts of problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Understanding her co-star's point, Rowlands agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never see it,'' she said, referring to couples past middle
age. ``It's kind of a shame because you have lots of people walking
around thinking that by 40 it's over, and you drop off the world
someplace.''
</P>
<P>
   That's exactly why Willard Carroll, who wrote and directed the
film, wanted to create romantic roles for older actors, to
counteract the big-screen impression that love is the sole province
of those under 35.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to do a multi-character love story for a long time,
but had never been able to get a handle on what would make it
unique,'' he said. ``So I decide to deal with it from a variety of
perspectives and a broad age spectrum, from early 20s to mid-late
60s.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really wanted to write an older couple that had the same
passion and vitality as the younger couple I was writing,'' he
said. ``With Sean and Gena, I wanted to look at older people in a
different way where the romance hasn't died, where the love hasn't
died.''
</P>
<P>
   That sentiment proved inspirational to other cast members,
including Phillippe, who, with Jolie, plays a 20-something club
kids trying to find romance amid the swirl of LA nightlife.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hollywood dismisses people over a certain age, and they tend
to forget,'' said Phillippe, 24. ``I thought it was beautiful to
see a relationship between an older couple that was still so alive
and full of passion, instead of seeing a 55-year-old guy with a
22-year-old. I just thought that was cool.''
</P>
<P>
   If only everyone had been as embracing of the film's original
title. Carroll initially called his film ``Dancing About
Architecture,'' which came from a line in the film, ``Talking about
love is like dancing about architecture.'' Sure, it was a quirky
title, but it had more character than the generic ``Playing by
Heart.'' But Carroll had no say in the change, which was ordered by
the Motion Picture Academy of America because it found the title
too similar to ``Dancing at Lughnasa,'' a drama starring Meryl
Streep.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sorry that we lost `Dancing About Architecture,' but
`Playing by Heart' works just as well because it also has a musical
connotation,'' Carroll said. ``I think `Playing by Heart' was my
favorite of the alternates. Putting on my crass commercial hat, I
think `Playing by Heart' is probably a more mainstream title than
`Dancing About Architecture.'''
</P>
<P>
   Carroll may have been robbed of his title, but he got the cast
he wanted. He wrote the role of Hannah, the host of a successful
television cooking show, with Rowlands in mind. When she read the
script, she was ``immediately delighted, and without hesitation
said I'd love to do it,'' Rowlands recalled. Connery's interest in
the project was secured by Rowlands's participation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd never worked with Gena, so it was a golden opportunity,''
he said. ``We've both had a similar pattern of experiences as
actors.''
</P>
<P>
   Rowlands became known for her work in such films as ``A Woman
Under the Influence,'' ``Gloria,'' and ``Faces,'' all directed by
Cassavetes. Connery, of course, made his name as Agent 007, James
Bond (and for many, the only James Bond), in six films. He won an
Oscar for his role as a wily Chicago cop in the crime drama ``The
Untouchables.''
</P>
<P>
   But the role of the loving, imperfect husband in ``Playing by
Heart'' is one Connery can relate to _ even if others see it as
something of a stretch for a man once dubbed by People the
``Sexiest Man Alive.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A while ago I was doing an interview for this film, and
someone asked me if I thought this role was a great departure for
me,'' Connery said. ``Well, I thought about that for a moment and
said, `Well, I suppose I'm just acting my age.' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-18-99 1406EST &QL; 
