<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUTDOORS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MOTHER OF ALL RECREATIONAL VEHICLES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TOM STIENSTRA  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ When you first see the UniCat, there is no
sensation of ``love at first sight.'' You are more apt to think:
``What the heck is that weird thing?''
</P>
<P>
   At first glance, this rig looks like a garbage truck in which
somebody stuck a Mercedes logo on the grill as a joke, or maybe a
giant 4-wheel-drive Brinks truck loaded with a million dollars.
</P>
<P>
   But it turns out this vehicle is like no other 4-wheel-drive
camper in the world _ it can go virtually anywhere, completely
self-contained for 3,000 miles. And as for that million dollars,
well, that's about what it takes to buy one; $600,000 will fetch a
stripped-down model; $1.5 million, the loaded, 6-wheel version.
</P>
<P>
   The first UniCat was sold in the United States this month, to a
rich guy in New York. And the only demonstration model in North
America is in the Cow Palace at the San Francisco Sports &AMP; Boat
Show, where it has folks gawking and talking, both astonished and
bewildered at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   The UniCat is parked adjacent to three Hummers, the go-anywhere
vehicle that sets the standard worldwide for Rambo-venture. But the
UniCat is so big that Arnold Schwarzeneggar could buy one, then tow
his Hummer behind it like an RV towing a Volkswagen.
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks ago, I arranged to check it out and test drive it.
After climbing into the UniCat, the possibilities seemed unlimited,
even after just a few minutes: driving through water 4-feet deep,
over boulders 3-feet high, across fine-sand deserts, through muddy
bogs, and also making 45-degree climbs and descents in the most
remote areas of the world. That means you can deal with any kind of
terrain and go anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Then once you get there, you can stay there, whether it be the
grasslands of Tanzania, Yukon tundra, Nicaraguan jungle or Golden
Gate Park. That's because the gas tanks hold 220 gallons of diesel,
enough to cover 1,700 to 3,300 miles (depending on the terrain),
and the RV compartment of this rig is custom-built as a
self-contained home, with enough water storage for about 10 days.
If you were to head out into nowhere and discover a reliable water
source to refill your tanks, you could stay out for weeks at a time
without having to resupply.
</P>
<P>
   The interior is Spartan _ even ugly. But hey, the whole thing is
ugly. After a while, it starts to look like an ugly mutt you love
more than anything in the world, because inside beats a heart of
gold that will never betray you.
</P>
<P>
   That's the key when Mercedes designed the chassis and engine,
originally as a military vehicle that is known in Rambo circles as
the ``Unimog.'' The engine is a Mercedes turbo-charged diesel mated
with an 8-speed transmission and a drive train where each 4-foot
wheel is driven independently with 30-degree axle articulation (for
crossing boulder fields).
</P>
<P>
   The RV compartment has independent hydraulic air suspensions,
separate from the cab, which allows the unit to contort through
crimped turns and angles. In first gear at full torque, it moves
about a foot per second, allowing the rig to climb across about
anything. In eighth gear, with highway tires, it will cruise at 70
mph at 15 mpg.
</P>
<P>
   After the demonstration, I was ready to drive it. I know a
favorite hill just north of Half Moon Bay where the road is almost
straight up, with tons of giant potholes and a few boulders and
outcrops. I opened the door to the rig, asked for the keys, and the
owner suddenly got this horrified look on her face and said,
``No.''
</P>
<P>
   No? No what?
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I can't let you drive it. I'm sorry. This is my home and I
can't let anything happen to it.''
</P>
<P>
   She explained that she and her husband had taken the UniCat
across the Middle East, through Turkey and Saudi Arabia, into the
depths of Africa, then ferried to the Western Hemisphere, driven
across the Canadian wildlands and into Alaska, then down to Central
America, through El Salvador, Honduras, Nicaragua, and then south
to Argentina. Finally, it had come to the Cow Palace.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the UniCat can handle any of that other stuff. But
apparently, it finally met its match _ San Francisco was just too
much for it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
