<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 14:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7783 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROBISON-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      01-18 0848
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROBISON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEGISLATURE TAKING TURN TOWARD PARTISANSHIP 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Our state government's split personality emerged
again last week as lawmakers convened to see what they can do for
us _ and to us _ during the next five months.
</P>
<P>
   This condition started becoming obvious when Republicans started
building a significant presence in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   The personality disorder, however, is not the partisanship that
has quite naturally developed as Texas has evolved into a two-party
state. It is instead the Dr. Jekyll-Mr. Hyde treatment that public
officials from both major parties give to that partisanship.
</P>
<P>
   Partisan behavior is fashionable _ indeed, required _ in
even-numbered years, when elections are held and Republicans and
Democrats fight each other tooth, nail and campaign contribution
for legislative seats and other state offices.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in January of odd-numbered years, when the Republican and
Democratic winners assemble in Austin to try to govern,
partisanship suddenly becomes taboo _ or so our leaders would have
us believe.
</P>
<P>
   Judging from some of the speeches, partisanship was viewed as an
uglier concept than normal _ even for an odd-numbered year _ at the
opening of this legislative session, which occurred in the shadow
of the impeachment spectacle and all its controversial partisan
overtones in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. Teel Bivins, R-Amarillo, who was elected the Senate's
new president pro tempore, used much of his acceptance speech to
praise the Senate's bipartisan traditions.
</P>
<P>
   Republican Rick Perry, who just two months ago won a partisan
race for lieutenant governor, declared that the ``time for politics
is over.''
</P>
<P>
   Party-bashing certainly wasn't invented by the current crop of
Texas leaders. The practice is as old as the party system, which is
virtually as old as our country itself.
</P>
<P>
   No less a historical prominence than George Washington even took
a swipe or two at partisan behavior.
</P>
<P>
   ``The common and continual mischiefs of the spirit of party are
sufficient to make it the interest and duty of a wise people to
discourage and restrain it,'' the first president said in his
farewell address to the American people in 1796.
</P>
<P>
   But the father of our country was no more able to keep political
parties from developing than his political descendants in Texas or
anywhere else will be able to abolish partisan behavior.
Partisanship can be suppressed, but as long as we elect public
officials in partisan elections it will always be ready to pounce
upon the policy-making process, sometimes for the public good,
sometimes not.
</P>
<P>
   Some elected officials, I suspect, may be less interested in
doing away with partisan behavior than they are in simply wanting
to bad-mouth it. They believe party-bashing plays well politically
because many people don't associate themselves with parties and are
turned off by political game-playing.
</P>
<P>
   Although there were many fierce fights between liberal and
conservative Democrats, Texas' state government didn't have
partisan conflict for most of this century, simply because the
Democratic Party was the only game in town. But that changed with
the growth of the Texas Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Legislature has never organized along the partisan
lines of Congress, where the majority party holds all the key
leadership positions and largely sets the lawmaking agenda _ and
where partisanship has a hugely negative reputation.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Democrats didn't have to organize the Legislature in the
old days, and Republicans, at least in the House, haven't gained
enough numbers to do it now.
</P>
<P>
   There have been periodic partisan fights in Austin over
redistricting, tax policy and a few other controversies.
</P>
<P>
   But most issues before the Texas Legislature still aren't
partisan. And leaders from both parties _ including Gov. George W.
Bush, retiring Lt. Gov. Bob Bullock and House Speaker Pete Laney _
have been able to forge a bipartisan working relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Perry promises to continue Bullock's tradition, and the rule
requiring a two-thirds vote to pass anything out of the Senate will
help to keep partisanship in check in that chamber. And Bush, who
is eyeing a presidential race, doesn't want any major legislative
conflicts this year, partisan or otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   But tax vouchers for private schools, a major priority of
Perry's, could produce a partisan fight. So could Bush's and
Perry's tax cut proposals or a ``hot button'' issue, such as the
proposal to require parents to give consent or at least be notified
before their minor daughters can have abortions.
</P>
<P>
   And even if this session manages to mostly avoid partisan
fights, watch out in 2001. That will be a redistricting session,
when legislative and congressional district boundaries are redrawn
by state lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   The parties' stakes will be huge, and no one will even pretend _
at least not very convincingly _ that partisanship won't be a major
factor.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
