<DOCNO> NYT19990118.0186 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 14:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7784 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      01-18 1002
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISCOVERING THOSE UNEXPECTED GEMS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By HARRY SHATTUCK 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ As we formulate our vacation timetables, we usually
give priority to the ``must-see'' attractions: the Alamo in San
Antonio, the French Quarter in New Orleans, the Tower of London.
</P>
<P>
   But one of the most satisfying aspects of travel is when we come
upon a place, or a happening, that takes us completely by surprise.
A secret find. Until, that is, we share our discovery with friends.
Or readers.
</P>
<P>
   The nature of my job is such that I plan almost every element of
a trip. And yet I never imagined purchasing carrot and corn soap in
tiny Roadtown, Tortola. Becoming infatuated by vintage
black-and-white photographs inside a small chapel in Natchez, Miss.
Rekindling the stagecoach era at the Wolf Creek Tavern in southern
Oregon.
</P>
<P>
   OK, I sensed your grimace at the thought of carrot soap.
``Smooths dry, inflamed skin,'' read the label on the bright orange
handscreened cloth container at Roadtown's Sunny Caribbee Spice Co.
_ yes, suds and spice, what a combination _ in the British Virgin
Islands.
</P>
<P>
   Corn soap? ``Helps reduce wrinkles by improving softness,
natural tautness and elasticity of the skin.''
</P>
<P>
   Bran soap, I learned, ``protects the skin from the adverse
effects of environmental pollution,'' Passionfruit soap is
``renowned for its healing and restorative powers.'' Lime soap
``softens and protects while stimulating the senses.'' Honey soap
is ``rich in vitamins, hormones and sugar.''
</P>
<P>
   At only $5.50, I bought a bouquet of, er, fragrances. I was
especially intrigued by chamomile soap, which ``protects the skin
from redness caused by air pollution.'' Should be ideal for
Houston. And to complement my bath, I picked up mango bath gel,
coconut shampoo and tangerine citrus splash, even though I have no
idea what health potion they possess.
</P>
<P>
   I also tucked away a half-ounce container of Voodoo perfume.
Given the label's caution that it ``captivates as it casts its
mysterious spell,'' I'm saving it for a special occasion.
</P>
<P>
   Sunny Caribbee offers plenty of edible spices, too. Indeed, its
herbal teas could fill an entire medicine chest: breadfruit tea for
high blood pressure, hibiscus tea for stomach disorders, lemon
grass tea for fever and flu, papaya tea for indigestion and gas,
soursop tea for insomnia.
</P>
<P>
   I also found it hard to resist Island Nutmeg Mustard, Caribbee
Curry, Hot Pepper Jelly and an Arawak Love Potion described as an
``invigorating brew'' and tucked into a wooden apothecary jar.
</P>
<P>
   Not headed to Tortola any time soon? You can explore Sunny
Caribbee _ and order your own Voodoo Perfume _ on the Internet at
www.exoticfood.com/sunnycaribbee. But do plan to visit; you'll
likely be amazed by the entire inventory.
</P>
<P>
   Closer to home, many travelers will make an annual spring
pilgrimage to Natchez between March 10 and April 10, when most of
that Mississippi River city's great antebellum homes _ Longwood,
Stanton Hall, Rosalie, 31 in all _ will be showcased.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a suggestion on how to gain a deeper appreciation for
these landmarks and for the people who built them and lived along
the river. I was in Natchez not long ago as part of an excursion
aboard the River Explorer barge vessel, and thanks to a tip from an
onboard staff member I wandered into the Stratton Chapel at the
First Presbyterian Church in the center of town. What I saw _ and
the story behind this ``Natchez in Historic Photographs''
collection _ was mesmerizing.
</P>
<P>
   Henry C. Norman arrived in Natchez by steamboat during the
1850s. For the next 43 years, his camera captured life in and
around the city. Upon his death, Norman's son Earl assumed the same
role and continued until he died in 1951.
</P>
<P>
   In 1950, Dr. Thomas Gandy, a Natchez physician, purchased the
collection from Earl's widow, with no inkling that it included
75,000 negatives. Gandy and his wife, Joan, devoted 35 years to
sorting through the collection, and now several hundred photographs
_ including some of the finest ever made of riverboats and river
life, haunting portraits and early glimpses of the great mansions _
are displayed in rooms adjoining the church.
</P>
<P>
   A suggested donation is only $3 per person. The chapel, at 405
State St., is open 10 a.m.-5 p.m. CST daily except Sundays, when it
opens at 1 p.m. following church services.
</P>
<P>
   Permit to me to share one other ``surprise story.'' Year before
last, while driving in southern Oregon, the co-pilot and I detoured
a quarter-mile or so off Interstate 5 into the tiny village of Wolf
Creek, about 20 miles north of Grants Pass. We paused at a rustic
lodge whose sign informed us it was the Wolf Creek Tavern.
</P>
<P>
   Striking up a conversation with an engaging waitress, we learned
that this was the oldest active travelers' inn in that part of the
United States, dating to 1883, and a celebrated stop during the
stagecoach era. We enjoyed a delightful meal, then continued our
journey.
</P>
<P>
   Several months ago, I read that the Wolf Creek Tavern's
restaurant and nine lodging rooms were all but shuttered because
the Oregon Parks and Recreation Department, which oversees the
establishment, couldn't find suitable operators.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, I called the Wolf Creek Tavern (541-866-2474)
expecting to hear one of those ``this number has been
disconnected'' recorded messages. Instead, a friendly voice
answered _ maybe the same waitress _ and said the one-time
stagecoach stop is thriving as never before. ``The state took over
management; all nine rooms are available for overnight stays again;
and the restaurant's open every day from 11 a.m. to 7 p.m.,'' she
said. ``You'd better get back here quick; our new chef makes a
great steak and wild mushroom soup and jalapeo cornbread.''
</P>
<P>
   As I hung up the phone, I couldn't help smiling. Just as I do
when I think about carrot and corn soap on Tortola and beautiful
photographs in Natchez.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
