<HEADER>
A7789 &Cx1f; tad-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PANAMA-TRAVEL-$ADV23-     01-18 1078
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PANAMA-TRAVEL-$ADV23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PANAMA PUSHES TOURISM AS CANAL TAKEOVER APPROACHES
 &HT;    With photos placed in the International and Travel folders on
the Cox Server.
 &HT;    With PANAMA-BOX-$ADV23.
 &HT;    Moving in both the (i) International and (t) Travel categories.
 &HT;    For Use Saturday, Jan. 23 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By SHELLEY EMLING 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PANAMA CITY, Panama _ In the Panama Canal, ships are raised like
toys, step by step, through three sets of locks to a height of 85
feet above sea level, on their way from the Atlantic Ocean to the
Pacific and back again.
</P>
<P>
   The vessels are tugged through the locks by ``mules,'' or
electric locomotives on train tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Each passage requires 52 million gallons of fresh water to
equalize the water levels in these locks.
</P>
<P>
   Surprisingly, no pumps are used, meaning that gravity is all
that pulls the swirling water from the surrounding watershed into
the locks' chambers.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 85 years after its completion, these 50 miles of man-made
ditch are still an engineering wonder to behold, and the most
popular tourist attraction in this Ohio-sized country.
</P>
<P>
   The Panama Canal is one of the greatest civil engineering
achievements of this century, which are often referred to as the
Seven Wonders of the Modern World.
</P>
<P>
   The others are the Suez Canal, the Dneproges Dam in Ukraine, the
Alaska-Canada Highway, the Golden Gate Bridge, the Empire State
Building, and the Eifel Tower.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, this S-shaped isthmus has its share of white beaches,
dense rainforests, and colonial architecture.
</P>
<P>
   But so does Panama's better-marketed neighbor to the north,
Costa Rica.
</P>
<P>
   What Costa Rica doesn't have, of course, is the canal.
</P>
<P>
   Situated between Costa Rica and Colombia, Panama links North and
South America and the Atlantic and Pacific Oceans.
</P>
<P>
   The Panama Canal runs northwest to southeast, utilizing locks at
both ends, an existing river and a man-made lake.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as the Panamanian government prepares to take control of
the canal and surrounding properties, a massive push has been
launched to attract tourists.
</P>
<P>
   Panama's always been a comfortable place for Americans to visit:
English is widely spoken, tap water is safe for drinking, and the
U.S. dollar is the official currency.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Panama Canal treaties signed in 1977, Panama will take
sole possession not only of the canal on Dec. 31, 1999, but also of
some 250,000 acres of land, along with seven U.S. military bases,
golf courses, movie theaters, airports and other installations
bordering the canal.
</P>
<P>
   Tourism is a giant part of the Panamanian government's plans to
redevelop these properties.
</P>
<P>
   Already underway are projects to build new hotels in the
rainforests and to re-establish passenger service within two years
on the 143-year-old Panama Railway that runs alongside the canal.
</P>
<P>
   Nicolas Ardito Barletta directs the Inter-Oceanic Regional
Authority, the agency charged with overseeing foreign investment in
the converted areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have 300 cruise ships passing through the canal every year
but none of them stop because we don't have the facilities to serve
them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He said Panama's biggest goal is to build facilities on both the
Pacific and the Atlantic within five years that can accommodate up
to 250 cruise ships a year.
</P>
<P>
   And, for sure, the passengers on those ships will want to see
the canal.
</P>
<P>
   Today, visitors can see the canal at Miraflores Locks, which
offers an air-conditioned visitors center and an observation deck
where ships can be viewed as they pass through the locks.
</P>
<P>
   By October 1999, construction of a new, three-story visitors
center is due to be finished, complete with a higher observation
deck, as well as a bar, restaurant and interactive game area.
</P>
<P>
   Here, ships look like corks trying to squeeze through the
opening of a bottle.
</P>
<P>
   ``The locks are only 110 feet wide and the biggest ships are 106
feet wide, so there's only two feet of clearance on either side,''
explained Jamie Robleto, a tour guide.
</P>
<P>
   In general, it's easy to see why a French company employing a
small army went bankrupt trying to excavate this huge path in the
ground.
</P>
<P>
   The project was launched in 1882 and ended in disaster seven
years later with over 22,000 people dying from malaria and other
diseases.
</P>
<P>
   The United States took over the project in 1903 and finished
construction in 1914.
</P>
<P>
   At Miraflores Locks, a short film in English and a team of
bilingual guides provide visitors with all sorts of canal-related
facts and figures.
</P>
<P>
   For example, more than 13,100 ships traverse the canal each
year, paying tolls based on tonnage and number of passengers
aboard.
</P>
<P>
   The highest toll was $141,344, paid by the Crown Princess Cruise
Ship in 1993. The lowest toll was 36 cents, paid by Richard
Halliburton, who swam the canal in 1928.
</P>
<P>
   Miraflores Locks is just minutes by car from Panama City, the
oldest Spanish settlement on the American mainland which is really
three cities rolled into one.
</P>
<P>
   Stone ruins are all that's left of Panama Vieja, the original
settlement burned in 1671 by pirate Henry Morgan.
</P>
<P>
   In its place is the colonial Casco Viejo, a picturesque section
of the city where white houses with ornamental iron balconies line
winding, narrow streets.
</P>
<P>
   There's also the flashy, modern part of the city, where gleaming
high-rise banks and hotels dot the skyline.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly half of Panama's 2.8 million people live in and around
Panama City, which sits on the Pacific side of the country.
</P>
<P>
   Not only is the canal an easy visit from Panama City, but the
capital is also a good point from which to set off on day-trips to
see the wildlife in the Soberania National Park and in the
rainforest part of the Barro Colorado Nature Monument, which
consists of the 3,800-acre Barro Colorado Island and five adjacent
peninsulas in the man-made Gatun Lake.
</P>
<P>
   In Panama, which boasts large, unspoiled forests, a fourth of
the land has been established as national parks and preserves.
</P>
<P>
   According to Barletta, 357 varieties of birds have been spotted
in one day by the National Audubon Society in some parts of Panama.
</P>
<P>
   ``Panama has more biodiversity than even Costa Rica, it's just
that few people know about this,'' he said. ``We want to let people
know that, while the canal is the main thing, there's lots to see
here.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
