A7792 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-4WD-SCHOOL-HNS &LR;      01-18 0534
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-4WD-SCHOOL-HNS </SLUG>
  
 4-BY-4s MAY OFFER FALSE SENSE OF SECURITY ON ICE, SNOW  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JAY JOCHNOWITZ  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ You can't miss them on the highway, where they
mostly own the left lane in icy weather, gliding along in
four-wheel-drive glory or worse, coming up full speed on your tail.
</P>
<P>
   But there's a reality even 4-by-4 drivers have to come to grips
with: When it comes to stopping, all cars are pretty much equal.
And in this icy winter, it's a reality specialists say many drivers
don't accept until it's too late.
</P>
<P>
   ``Four-wheel-drive enables you to go better, but not stop
better,'' said Greg Nikolas, an instructor at the Land Rover
Driving School in Manchester, Vt. ``It's not magic. It doesn't turn
a wet road into dry pavement.''
</P>
<P>
   The Land Rover school opened in April 1997 as a place where
drivers could learn the techniques of four-wheeling. It charges
$150 for the first hour and $100 per hour after that. This time of
year, the school, Nicholas said, gets drop-ins from people visiting
the area who are suddenly interested in learning how to use the
cars in snow, or honing their skills.
</P>
<P>
   While there is little question 4WDs take off and steer better on
slippery roads, in winter, New York Department of Motor Vehicle
statistics show, they have a higher-than-average accident rate on
roads with snow, ice or slush. Among some popular models like Jeep
Cherokees and Wranglers, Ford Explorers, Chevrolet Blazers and
Isuzu Troopers, the accident rate was about 30 percent higher than
the norm. The statistics, however, do not account for other
factors, including whether 4WD owners are more likely to go out for
a spin on days other drivers would consider too treacherous.
</P>
<P>
   Drivers who feel emboldened by their 4WD abilities might want to
make sure the vehicles really work. Ken and Amy Broz of Malta,
N.Y., found this winter that their 1998 Kia Sportage couldn't even
get through a few inches of snow on their nearly flat driveway. Kia
spokesman Geno Effler said the company had found problems with a
new vacuum-assisted system that is supposed to automatically lock
the front hubs.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have had difficulty in sub-zero temperatures getting
their car into four-wheel-drive,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Kia is offering owners with problems a retrofit with an older
hub system, Effler said.
</P>
<P>
   Sellers of 4WDs warn motorists to know their vehicles' limits.
Dan Clancy, a car salesman in Albany, remembers driving the first
front-wheel drive Omnis and Horizons through the snow, passing
rear-wheel drives like they were standing still. But, he said, ``I
had to realize that it isn't going to stop any better.''
</P>
<P>
   Four wheel drives feel more stable in snow not only because all
the wheels are driven, Clancy explained, but also because the front
axle spins just a little faster than the rear. So in a situation
where a two-wheel drive might swerve _ going through a slush pile
in the middle of a highway lane, for example _ a 4WD drive car is
constantly being pulled and pushed.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, Clancy said, ``This may give you a false sense of
security. They think they can do anything.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
