u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-TRAVOLTA-PROFILE     01-18 1128
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-TRAVOLTA-PROFILE-2TAKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAVOLTA MAKES HIS CASE FOR `A CIVIL ACTION' 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By LOUIS B. PARKS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Everything was perfect for the John Travolta interview.
</P>
<P>
   The room in the swanky Mansion on Turtle Creek was large and
comfy.
</P>
<P>
   The flowers were fresh and fragrant.
</P>
<P>
   Studio representatives were on hand to smooth any problems. So
were several of the hotel staff, eager to see Travolta in person.
</P>
<P>
   Only one thing was missing.
</P>
<P>
   Travolta.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can you hear me?'' Travolta asked over a noisy phone hook-up
hastily arranged from his private Boeing 707. ``Where are you?''
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in the hotel room where we were supposed to be talking
in person that very hour.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, darn,'' he said, managing to sound genuinely disappointed.
Probably just good acting. And yes, he really said ``darn.''
</P>
<P>
   Travolta had planned to fly into Dallas for interviews about ``A
Civil Action,'' his new film that opened recently as the top
box-office draw in the country. But Dallas-Fort Worth International
Airport was socked in with fog, and he was not allowed to land. So
now he was making calls from his plane.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sad I didn't get to Dallas because I was looking forward
to it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He's sad? He should see the long faces on the waitresses around
here.
</P>
<P>
   The plane Travolta didn't land in Dallas is one of four he owns.
Travolta, 44, has been a jet pilot since he was 26. He is even
qualified to fly a Boeing 707, a 189-seat, four-engine passenger
plane. Visions of a glum Travolta, sitting in the cockpit flying
the plane while balancing the telephone on his ear were tempting,
but not quite accurate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, almost,'' Travolta said with a little laugh at the
image. This time one of his private pilots was at the controls, and
Travolta was just a passenger.
</P>
<P>
   Since he was off in the wild blue yonder somewhere, it was
natural to ask why he loves flying so much.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, gosh, now that's a loaded question,'' Travolta said.
``Ever since I was 5 years old (living in New Jersey in the flight
path for New York's LaGuardia Airport) I've had this unusual
passion, preoccupation, desire for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I loved every aspect of it. I love the art of it, I love the
look of aircraft, I love the ability it takes to fly one, and I
think I like the sensation of flight, too. I like the objectivity
of seeing everything from this perspective.''
</P>
<P>
   Travolta sounded perfectly willing to go on talking about
flying, but there was still ``A Civil Action'' to discuss, so back
to work.
</P>
<P>
   In the movie, based on the best-selling book by Jonathan Harr,
Travolta plays Jan Schlichtmann, a lawyer who specializes in sleazy
lawsuits. He presents himself as a concerned seeker of justice who
lies awake nights worrying about his clients. In truth, if he lies
awake nights, it's contemplating what sporty foreign car he will
buy next with the money he extorts from corporate defendants.
</P>
<P>
   But Schlichtmann is not as clever as he thinks. He bets
everything on winning a difficult case against two of the country's
big food companies. A small business connected to the companies is
polluting a stream near a small town in which several children have
died of leukemia.
</P>
<P>
   A strange thing happens to Schlichtmann as he works on the case.
He gets involved. To his surprise, he has a conscience, after all.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the usual black-and-white Hollywood morality play
(``Patch Adams'') in which everything neatly ties together in the
end, this movie sticks close to the facts. There will be no rousing
victory in which the hero is granted near-sainthood.
</P>
<P>
   ``The book had the same ending, right?'' Travolta said about the
unusual downbeat finale. ``When you make the book, unless you are
willing to change the ending ... There was always concern, but why
was the book successful?''
</P>
<P>
   If the book had not been such a big seller, and a star of
Travolta's skills and box-office success had not been willing to
tackle the lead, the movie might never have been made.
</P>
<P>
   Travolta had his doubts when producer Joe Roth (not listed in
the film's credits) and Disney chief Michael Eisner called him
about the movie.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said they had a part they really felt strongly I should
play,'' Travolta said. ``I asked why, and they said `Because we've
never seen you play anything like this, and it's a great script and
says a lot of interesting things about people and the
environment.'''
</P>
<P>
   Travolta remained unsure after his first reading, but Eisner and
Roth persisted. So Travolta got some friends together for a group
reading.
</P>
<P>
   ``We read it aloud. I realized that `Wow, if I can pull this
off, make it watchable ...'.''
</P>
<P>
   But Schlichtmann was, to be blunt, a jerk, a kind audiences
usually hate.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I could make him funny to watch as an egotist, I could
solve him as a watchable character. Not a likable character, a
watchable character. That's all I think matters, is that you want
to watch him. You don't need to like him.''
</P>
<P>
   But the movie is a drama, and Schlichtmann's change needed to be
serious.
</P>
<P>
   ``How do you make a guy who is unaware of his flaws, unaware of
his insensitivity at first, have a wonderful growth?'' Travolta
said. ``He would basically have to give up his firm in order to win
this.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought, well, that's a growth. He goes from an egocentric,
me, me, I, I guy, all for the buck, greed and all that, and turns
into this other guy who basically gives up everything for what he
believes in. It's an extraordinary thing. I thought, `I have never
done that before.' I'd like to see if I could.''
</P>
<P>
   Travolta found the key to making the character work by building
his change around scenes in which Schlichtmann is exposed, bit by
bit, to the personal tragedies behind the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then, when you segue into him, realizing the lack of regard
for him, the lack of respect for his professionalism and integrity
(among the opposing lawyers and his clients), it challenges him. It
forced him to have some professional integrity and sentient
concepts as a human being.''
</P>
<P>
   Travolta met Schlichtmann but did not imitate the lawyer in his
portrayal.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, I really didn't grill him because I felt much more
interesting references from my 23 years of dealing with lawyers. I
saw an evolved Jan, and I understood those evolutions because I had
to do them myself in my life. I knew what it was like to give up
everything for a reason or a cause.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I had to go somewhere I had never gone before in being so
cold and not understanding people's tragedy. Jan had already
resolved his own issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the film's indefinite ending, Travolta is confident that
it will work for viewers.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(MORE) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, you'd have to be almost a complete cynic or dead to
walk out of the theater and not suddenly be affected by what's
going on in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Does Travolta believe the movie might have an effect on public
policies regarding environmental issues?
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't until I saw the movie,'' said Travolta, who had seen
the finished film the night before. ``I had only seen a rough cut
(before), to be completely honest with you. I let two months go by
and let (director) Steve Zaillian mess around with the movie and
fix it, and my God, I was so affected by it last night.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no guarantees, but it's got a heck of a shot at
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Travolta, who can command $15 million to $20 million plus
extensive (in Travolta's case near-legendary) perks for each film,
also has a small role in ``The Thin Red Line,'' which he did for a
token salary. He appears as a general in a scene lasting maybe two
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   He did the part as a favor for director Terrence Malick, who was
making his first movie in 20 years. Malick's last film, ``Days of
Heaven'' in 1978, was a critical success and became known for its
beauty. But it was not a box-office success. After it came out,
Malick, disgusted with Hollywood, retreated to Paris (he now lives
in Austin) and shunned all offers to make another movie.
</P>
<P>
   According to Travolta, much of Malick's anger at the Hollywood
system grew out of his inability to use Travolta, then a hot TV
star on ``Welcome Back, Kotter,'' in ``Days of Heaven'' (Richard
Gere eventually played the role).
</P>
<P>
   ``I was not let out of my (''Kotter``) contract by ABC,''
Travolta said. ``That was a real loss for Terrence Malick, and he
never got over it.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he came up with a script (for ''The Thin Red Line``) he
wanted me to be part of it in any way I could be, so I said, `Well,
whatever you want.' As a favor, I did this one small part. However,
I said, `I'm doing this for you, but don't make it look like I have
the lead in the picture. Don't bill me as a lead.'''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Travolta understands some of Malick's need to succeed
this time around. After a meteoric rise that included three hits
(``Saturday Night Fever,'' ``Grease'' and Urban Cowboy), Travolta
suffered through a long lull in the 1980s. It began with several
bad films _ ``Two of A Kind,'' ``Perfect,'' ``Staying Alive'' _ was
alleviated a bit by the success of the ``Look Who's Talking?''
comedies, but did not really end, at least in the public's mind,
until Travolta's triumphant comeback in ``Pulp Fiction.''
</P>
<P>
   Travolta doesn't argue about this lull, but he does not agree
with it either.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kind of liked it, to be honest, but I don't think I was
aware that there was one,'' he said, with a small laugh. ``You see,
not only did people do movies less in my earlier days, but studios
were entertaining certain offers all the time that I was close to
getting, so it didn't seem (to me) that I was out of the loop as
much as I kind of was.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would do ''Look Who's Talking?``, a big hit, and then
(director) Ronnie Howard would want me to do the fire-engine movie
(``Backdraft'') with DeNiro, but then he decided not to go with me
at the last moment. That was a big director, and I didn't feel as
much out of the loop as everyone thought I looked.''
</P>
<P>
   Say something Travolta disagrees with, and he will politely put
you straight and make a pretty convincing argument for his side.
For example, suggest that his acting skills are more appreciated
since his return, and he reminds you of his early acclaim.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't forget when I first started out, I had an Oscar
nomination in ''Saturday Night Fever.``
</P>
<P>
   ```Saturday Night Fever,' `Grease,' `Urban Cowboy' and
`Blow-Out' were all taken very seriously. I was (New York Times
film critic) Pauline Kael's favorite actor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was probably taken seriously, without exaggerating, just
going by facts, as much as James Dean or (Marlon) Brando when they
first started. Except James Dean died after three films, and Brando
chose better than I did.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you do a few projects in a row where it's not up to what
they expected from you, then you start to lose a little bit of
credibility. That's what I think may have happened.''
</P>
<P>
   And he doesn't agree with the suggestion that he has been
working at a frenetic pace _ 12 major films in three years _ since
``Pulp Fiction'' made him hot again.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you compare me to (Tom) Hanks or Robin (Williams) or
(Bruce) Willis or any of the guys getting a lot of work, we are all
working at about the same pace,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Fast or moderate, Travolta will apparently stick with the pace
for the immediate future. He has already completed shooting ``The
General's Daughter,'' and will soon begin a film of Annie Proulx's
best-selling novel ``The Shipping News,'' which he will do with his
wife, Kelly Preston (``Jerry Maguire,'' ``Holy Man'').
</P>
<P>
   And he definitely plans to do a film from the best-selling
ber-science fiction novel, ``Battlefield Earth,'' written by L. Ron
Hubbard, a pulp writer who became the founder of Scientology.
Hubbard's style and plots can be generously characterized as broad,
but Travolta, who practices Scientology, is a fan.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's brilliant,'' he said of ``Battlefield Earth.'' ``It's
probably, if not the best, probably one of the two or three best
science-fiction books ever written.''
</P>
<P>
   And Travolta will continue to mix up his roles.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a conscious effort in that I like to do something next
that I have not done before,'' Travolta said. ``I like to mix up
genres so I'm never expected to do one genre. It would not be as
interesting to me as an actor. It's like you would never want to
read the same book every time.''
</P>
<P>
   There's one more thing. It's obvious from the variety and types
of roles he plays, that Travolta has an almost compulsive need to
create.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I do,'' he said. ``I live for it basically, and I
splurge on it when I can.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
