<SLUG> BC-PRIEST-LAWSUIT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRIEST ACCUSES ARCHDIOCESE OF DEFAMATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ELIZABETH FERNANDEZ  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ In an unusual legal complaint to secular
authorities, a Roman Catholic priest has filed a lawsuit against
the archbishop of San Francisco alleging that he was defamed and
penalized for reporting suspected child abuse.
</P>
<P>
   The complaint by the Rev. John Conley, whose clash with his
religious superiors occurred while he was serving as parochial
vicar of a Burlingame church, said Archbishop William Levada and
others in the archdiocese abused their authority and tried to
discredit him.
</P>
<P>
   Conley, 55, is a former federal prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
   His lawsuit, filed in San Francisco Superior Court, seeks
damages for defamation and intentional infliction of emotional
distress.
</P>
<P>
   ``The lawsuit filed by Father Conley against the archdiocese is
based on false premises and is totally without merit,'' archdiocese
spokesman Maurice Healy said last week. ``We expect it to be
dismissed.''
</P>
<P>
   Such a suit against a bishop, to whom diocesan priests promise
obedience, is extremely rare, church observers said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's walking on eggs here as a priest, you are not supposed to
take your bishop to court,'' said Tim Unsworth, author of books on
the priesthood and a columnist for the National Catholic Reporter.
</P>
<P>
   Conley's suit is based on his November 1997 discovery of a
wrestling encounter, reportedly in a darkened room, between an
underage male and the pastor of St. Catherine of Siena Catholic
Church. He reported the incident to church and law enforcement
officials.
</P>
<P>
   The San Mateo district attorney's office decided that evidence
did not justify filing criminal charges. But the pastor, the Rev.
James Aylward, publicly apologized for his ``foolishness and
imprudence'' in engaging in conduct forbidden by diocesan policy.
He also told parishioners that he had ``committed myself to the
care and treatment of a mental health professional in order to have
the benefit of his evaluation.''
</P>
<P>
   About six months later, Aylward resigned from the Burlingame
parish. He was transferred to another church.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after the wrestling incident, Conley was placed on
administrative leave. He remains without official assignment and
lives at a Menlo Park retreat.
</P>
<P>
   Conley worked as an assistant U.S. attorney from 1972 to 1978,
serving for a time as chief of the criminal division in Detroit. He
entered St. Patrick's Seminary in Menlo Park in 1988 and was
ordained five years later.
</P>
<P>
   In his lawsuit, he said the archdiocese ``took numerous actions
... designed to retaliate for plaintiff's fulfilling his legal
obligation to report an incident of suspected child abuse.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, when Conley's situation was publicized, the
archdiocese said he was disciplined not for reporting the wrestling
incident but for public displays of anger, for insubordination and
disrespectful behavior toward his bishop.
</P>
<P>
   ``The record of Father Conley's behavior is publicly known,''
Healy said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The lawsuit itself indicates the state of Father Conley's mind
and reveals the misplaced anger that caused him to be relieved of
his duties and asked to seek evaluation and counseling.''
</P>
<P>
   Conley's lawyer, John Hill of Oakland, said the priest lodged
his complaint ``very reluctantly.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The church has criticized Father Conley for causing grave
damage to the reputation of a brother priest and to the good name
of archdiocese officials,'' Hill said. ``He was doing what he was
morally and legally required to do. Rather than being condemned, he
should be held up as an example of what the church should be doing
to combat the problem of sexual improprieties.''
</P>
</TEXT>
