<SLUG> BC-TURNING-30-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUMOROUS BOOK MAKES COPING WITH 30 EASIER FOR WOMEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CRAIG MARINE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Julie Tilsner was in New York, working as an
assistant editor at Business Week magazine, when some of her female
office mates noticed she was less than her hard-charging,
high-energy self. Indeed, she was moping.
</P>
<P>
   A group of the wiser types _ ranging in age from the mid-30's on
up _ finally took Tilsner aside.
</P>
<P>
   ``They told me they knew what was happening,'' said Tilsner,
sipping tea at a coffeehouse near her apartment. ``They said, `We
know you are about to turn 30, and we want to tell you not to
worry, it just gets better from now on.' Naturally, I dismissed
them right away.''
</P>
<P>
   Tilsner reacted to her landmark birthday by quitting her job,
packing a backpack and joining an Israeli kibbutz, where she worked
at a rubber factory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I figured that I wanted to do manual labor,'' she said. ``I
learned how to make chicken pluckers. You never know when that
might come in handy.''
</P>
<P>
   She also went more than a little wild, but by the time she moved
to the San Francisco area, she had met her future husband, found
out that those women in her office were totally right, and come up
with the idea for her book, ``29 and Counting: A Chick's Guide to
Turning 30''; Contemporary Books; $13.95).
</P>
<P>
   ``29 and Counting'' is a humorous, light-hearted look at what
can actually be a traumatic subject for many. Tilsner, now 34,
figured that there were plenty of self-help books about becoming 40
or 50, but nothing on the subject that was affecting her peers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes I get criticized for being a little flippant, but
honestly, this is meant to be funny. It's meant to tell the women
who are approaching 30 with trepidation to calm down, life really
does get better and better,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its funny approach, Tilsner's book addresses the angst
women often feel about getting older.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a feeling that now they have to act `grown-up,' that
they may not have accomplished all the things they thought they
might when they had teen-age dreams,'' Tilsner said. ``If you turn
30 and you're not married, don't have that best-selling novel out,
don't own a house, whatever it might be, there's a tendency to view
your life as a failure. I try to get women to recognize that they
might not be alone with those feelings, that they are in fact
pretty common and, most importantly, you have great times still
ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   The benefits of turning 30 far outweigh the drawbacks, Tilsner
said. One of the great things about being 30 is that ``you're old
enough to know better, but young enough to do it anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Other advantages include being taken more seriously by other
adults and just plain knowing more about the ways of the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all about being more comfortable in your own skin,''
Tilsner said. ``You don't have to conform to someone else's
expectations of what you were supposed to have done or be doing.
Once you reach that point, everything becomes easier.
</P>
<P>
   ``Relationships are better because you become more at ease with
yourself, your looks, what you want from a person. You've heard all
the lines by now so you can sort out the jerks,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   For now, Tilsner lives with her husband and 2-year-old daughter,
working on a book in the same vein about parenting.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
