<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOMENRULE-2000(4TAKES)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEN WHO'VE LED THEIR COUNTRY WITH A STRONG, FEMALE HAND
</HEADLINE>
 
(DUPLICATION ALERT: Story also moving in ``a'' general news
category) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LIZ STEVENS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Poor old U.S.A. Here we are playing catch-up again.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Dole hints at a bid for the White House and it throws
the pundits into a frenzy: ``Are Americans ready for a female
president?'' Many a Sunday-morning news show will no doubt debate
the question into oblivion.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, much of the world yawns. From an international
perspective, female heads of state are old hat. There are currently
24 living women who are or have been presidents or prime ministers,
according to the Council of Women World Leaders, and don't count on
that number shrinking.
</P>
<P>
   Estrogen has governed the modern countries of Canada, Haiti,
Bolivia, Rwanda, Norway, Burundi and Bangladesh, to name a few, and
female leaders include some of the most influential and admired
figures of the 20th century: Indira Gandhi, Golda Meir and Margaret
Thatcher.
</P>
<P>
   As a reminder of this not-so-new phenomenon, we've compiled a
list of 10 women who ruled the world _ or parts of it, at least.
Liddy Dole might do well to take notes.
</P>
<P>
   1. BENAZIR BHUTTO, born 1953
</P>
<P>
   Prime minister of Pakistan, 1988-1990 and 1993-1996
</P>
<P>
   Political background: Educated at Harvard and Oxford, Bhutto is
the eldest child of Zulfikar Ali Bhutto, president and then prime
minister of Pakistan from 1971 to 1977. After the elder Bhutto's
government was overthrown and he was hanged, Benazir became her
political party's most powerful voice. Her opposition to the new
military government landed her in jail, although eventually she was
allowed to leave Pakistan for London. In 1986, hundreds of
thousands of Pakistanis celebrated her return to the country. Two
years later,
</P>
<P>
   Bhutto, at age 35, became the first woman to rule a modern
Islamic nation.
</P>
<P>
   Known for: Having spent time in the United States and England,
Bhutto knew how to deal with the Western press, one of her
strengths on the international stage. ``Her foreign persona was a
really powerful one,'' said Laura Liswood, co-founder of the
Council of Women World Leaders. Bhutto also established women's
police stations, where women could report rape. During both of her
rocky governments, Bhutto faced charges of corruption and abuse of
power. In September, Swiss authorities handed over to Pakistani
officials evidence that Bhutto may have laundered money and taken
kickbacks while in office. The fiery Bhutto denies the charges and
continues to be an outspoken critic of the current Pakistani
government.
</P>
<P>
   Personal facts: Now 45, Bhutto is the mother of three. Despite
her international prominence, she is acutely aware of her place as
a woman in a Muslim society. ``I must always maintain a certain
degree of formality,'' she has said. ``For instance, I have to be
accompanied by a proper chaperone, I must be careful how I talk to
people, I can't develop the same kind of camaraderie that exists
among men.''
</P>
<P>
   2. GOLDA MEIR, born 1898
</P>
<P>
   Prime minister of Israel, 1969-1974
</P>
<P>
   Political background: Meir was 8 when her father, a carpenter,
moved the family from the Ukraine to Milwaukee. As a young woman
she became drawn to Zionism and moved to Palestine with her
husband, Morris Meyerson, in 1921. Through positions with the
Israel Labor Federation and World Zionist Organization, Meir drew
recognition as a powerful political force. She was elected to the
Knesset in 1949, appointed minister of labor that same year and
then minister of foreign affairs in 1956. In 1969, after the sudden
death of Prime Minister Levi Eshkol, party officials chose Meir,
then 70, as the fourth prime minister of Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Known for: Meir took a hard line toward the Arab world. Her
government refused to stop building settlements in the occupied
Palestinian territories and rejected a peace agreement with Arab
states. But she encouraged emigration of Soviet Jews to Israel and
strengthened Israeli ties with the United States. Meir resigned as
prime minister in 1974, in the aftermath of the 1973 Yom Kippur
War, in which Arab attacks caught the country by surprise.
</P>
<P>
   Personal facts: A chain-smoker who rejected makeup, Meir ranked
fourth on the list of women most admired by Americans in a 1969
poll. David Ben-Gurion once called her ``the only man in my
Cabinet.'' Meir had two children and was, by several accounts, an
accomplished cook.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
<P>
   3. ISABEL PERON, born 1931
</P>
<P>
   President of Argentina, 1974-1976, not to be confused with Eva
Peron, a k a Evita, the popular demagogue and second wife of Gen.
Juan Peron.
</P>
<P>
   Political background: The third wife of Juan Peron, Isabel Peron
met her future husband in the mid-1950s while working as a dancer.
Gen. Peron recently had been ousted as the ruler of Argentina, and
she became his personal secretary, settling with him in Madrid.
They were married in 1961 when he was 65 and she was 30. Through
several diplomatic visits to Argentina, Isabel paved the way for
her husband's triumphant return in 1973, when he was re-elected
president and she assumed the vice presidency. Less than a year
later, Juan Peron died of heart failure, and Isabel came to power.
</P>
<P>
   Known for: Like Evita before her, Isabel championed the causes
of Argentine women, but could not overcome the economic and
political strife in her country. Her government imposed martial law
and saw inflation rise to 200 percent, which led to crippling union
strikes. A military junta overthrew her regime in 1976, and she
eventually went into exile in Spain.
</P>
<P>
   Personal facts: Isabel Peron is said to have believed in
astrology and enjoy fencing. Unlike Evita, she was shy and often
compared negatively with her husband's second wife. A 1973 profile
in Time magazine commented that she sometimes appeared ``as if she
had been laminated in plastic.''
</P>
<P>
   4. CORAZON AQUINO, born 1933
</P>
<P>
   President of the Philippines, 1986-1992
</P>
<P>
   Political background: Aquino was born to a wealthy family with
political ties and schooled at convents in the United States. She
married Benigno Aquino in 1954, raised five children and watched
her husband's political career take off. When Ferdinand Marcos
declared martial law in 1972, he jailed his political nemesis,
Benigno, for nearly eight years before allowing the Aquinos to flee
to the United States. In 1983, Benigno returned to the Philippines
and was gunned down at the Manila Airport; Corazon vowed to
continue his work, and in 1986 forced Marcos into exile in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   Known for: During her tumultuous tenure, Aquino restored some
civil rights and released political prisoners, while her government
survived at least seven coup attempts. Her presidency inspired a
renaissance in the arts in her country and renewed international
economic interest in the Philippines, although critics said she
didn't advance the country economically as much as she might have.
</P>
<P>
   Personal facts: The petite Aquino, 65, is a devout Roman
Catholic who found the Marcos' opulent presidential palace
uncomfortably extravagant and set up an office in the guest house
of her more modest home.
</P>
<P>
   5. MARGARET THATCHER, born 1925
</P>
<P>
   Prime minister of Great Britain, 1979-1990
</P>
<P>
   Political background: With an eye to his daughter's political
future, the lower-middle-class father of Margaret Thatcher paid for
his daughter to take extra lessons in the classics and Latin. At
Oxford, she studied chemistry and became involved in Conservative
Party politics. After marrying, giving birth to twins and
practicing law, she ran for Parliament in a wealthy suburb of
London and held the seat from 1959 to 1992. In 1975, she took the
reins of the Conservative Party, and four years later was elected
prime minister on a platform of abolishing the welfare state.
</P>
<P>
   Known for: Thatcherism, the prime minister's major contribution
to political science, not only encompassed her policies but her
style. ``Under her forceful, if sometimes strident, leadership, the
Conservatives accomplished what no previous British government in
the postwar period had done: They emasculated the unions,
denationalized important industries, curbed inflation and swelled
the ranks of the middle class,'' according to Current Biography
Yearbook. Meanwhile, unemployment soared and the gap between the
haves and have-nots grew.
</P>
<P>
   Personal facts: Since her resignation, Baroness Thatcher has
written her memoirs and continues to weigh in on matters of state.
She recently came out against the extradition of Chilean Gen.
Augusto Pinochet and, as of December, was still the
fourth-most-admired woman by Americans, according to a Gallup Poll,
right after No. 3, Elizabeth Dole.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
<P>
   6. MARY EUGENIA CHARLES, born 1919
</P>
<P>
   Prime minister of the Commonwealth of Dominica, 1980 to 1995
</P>
<P>
   Political background: Charles was born in 1919 on the eastern
Caribbean island of Dominica and received her bachelor's degree
from the University of Toronto and her law degree from the London
School of Economics and Political Science in the 1940s. She
returned to Dominica, becoming the first female lawyer on the
island. Her involvement in politics culminated in election to the
House of Assembly in 1975, as leader of the opposition Freedom
Party (the country achieved independence from Britain in 1978).
Charles' harsh criticism of the Labor Party government was
partially responsible for the resignation of Prime Minister Patrick
John, whom she succeeded in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   Known for: Dominica was a founding member of the Organization of
Eastern Caribbean States in 1981. In 1983, Charles requested that
the United States send troops to another OECS member nation,
Grenada, to thwart an overthrow of that country's government by
leftist extremists. The invasion drew criticism from the United
Nations. A forceful presence, Charles is nicknamed the Iron Lady of
the Caribbean. Her detractors claimed Charles, a fiscal
conservative, ran the country too much like a business, with little
regard for its citizens.
</P>
<P>
   Personal facts: She was the granddaughter of a former slave, and
Charles' father was a successful fruit exporter who lived to be
107. In 1994, she told an interviewer that the person she admired
most in the world was Golda Meir.
</P>
<P>
   7. VIGDIS FINNBOGADOTTIR, born 1930
</P>
<P>
   President of Iceland, 1980 to 1996
</P>
<P>
   Political background: Finnbogadottir studied drama and
literature at the Sorbonne in France and in 1972 was appointed
director of the Reykjavik Theater Company. She hosted a television
series on drama and lectured on Icelandic culture before becoming
the chairwoman of the Advisory Committee on Cultural Affairs in
1978. At the time, women's issues were coming to the fore, and
colleagues persuaded Finnbogadottir to make a run for the
presidency. She won her first four-year term, beating four male
opponents, in 1980. She ran unopposed in 1984 and in 1992; in 1988
she won the presidency with 92 percent of the vote.
</P>
<P>
   Known for: Although the presidency in Iceland is more a
ceremonial role than a political one, Finnbogadottir has championed
numerous causes including Icelandic culture and reforestation. She
founded the Save the Children Association of Iceland and in 1995
was the keynote speaker at the UN Conference on Women in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   Personal facts: In 1972, Finnbogadottir became a single parent
after adopting a baby girl. She remains a national icon since
leaving office, and is now co-founder of the Council of Women World
Leaders based at Harvard's Kennedy School of Government.
</P>
<P>
   8. MARY ROBINSON, born 1944
</P>
<P>
   President of Ireland, 1990 to 1997
</P>
<P>
   Political background: Robinson's activism evolved at a young
age: While at an exclusive Catholic boarding school, Robinson
petitioned for the right to read the Protestant Irish Times. She
graduated from Harvard Law School in 1968 and became the first
woman to be a faculty member at Trinity College Dublin, where she
began working to improve the lives of women through the law. She
fought for the right of women to sit on juries, for laws protecting
illegitimate children and for gay rights. Upon her election to the
Senate in 1969 (she was only 25 years old), she introduced a bill
to legalize contraceptives. In 1989, she resigned from the Senate,
only to accept the Labor party's nomination as its presidential
candidate the next year.
</P>
<P>
   Known for: As in Iceland, the Irish presidency is a largely
symbolic post. But Robinson's victory seemed ``to symbolize
Ireland's desire for genuine change, given her stands on such
charged issues as abortion and reproductive rights, which have been
anathema to other Irish leaders. ... Mary Robinson has indeed used
her title to promote tolerance, compassion and national debate,''
according to ``A Rising Public Voice: Women in Politics
Worldwide,'' edited by Alida Brill.
</P>
<P>
   Personal facts: Upon her entry into politics, Robinson was
derided for what some considered a lackluster personal appearance.
When she became president, she underwent an image makeover.
Robinson resigned the presidency in September 1997 to become United
Nations human rights commissioner. She was succeeded as president
by Mary McAleese.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
<P>
   9. VIOLETA CHAMORRO, born 1929
</P>
<P>
   President of Nicaragua, 1990-1997
</P>
<P>
   Political background: Born into a wealthy, landowning family,
Chamorro was schooled in San Antonio and Virginia. Back in
Nicaragua, she married Pedro Joaquin Chamorro, an activist against
the Somoza dictatorship and scion of the family that owned the
liberal La Prensa newspaper. His articles consistently landed him
in jail. Pedro was ultimately assassinated by the right-wing
dictatorship in 1978, and Violeta took over the newspaper. When the
Somoza government fled, Daniel Ortega's Sandinista party became the
dominant political force, and Chamorro became an outspoken
opposition leader.
</P>
<P>
   Her political defeat of Ortega ended 10 years of civil war.
</P>
<P>
   Known for: Chamorro's presidency faced significant challenges,
including rising unemployment, strikes and continued fighting
between Sandinista militants and rebellious contras. Her most vocal
critic was Sen. Jesse Helms, who accused her of selling out to the
Sandinistas and who threatened to withhold financial aid to the
country.
</P>
<P>
   Personal facts: Chamorro ``was very symbolic of the unity of
Nicaragua,'' said Liswood, of the Council of Women World Leaders.
``She had four children, two Sandinistas and two contras.''
Chamorro's autobiography, titled ``Dreams of the Heart,'' received
generally favorable reviews in the United States when it was
published in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   10. INDIRA GANDHI, born 1917
</P>
<P>
   Prime minister of India, 1966 to 1977 and 1980 to 1984
</P>
<P>
   Political background: Indira Gandhi, the only child of
Jawaharlal Nehru _ India's first prime minister, from 1947 to 1964
_ was enmeshed in Indian politics from her earliest years. Although
she was not related to India's spiritual leader Mohandas Gandhi, he
was close to her father and encouraged her involvement in the
resistance movement against British rule. Because her mother had
died in 1936, Gandhi became India's ``first lady'' during her
father's government, accompanying him on trips and gaining a
prominent political reputation. In 1959, one year before the death
of her husband, Feroze Gandhi, she was elected president of the
Congress Party, the second-highest political position in the
country. When Prime Minister Lal Bahadur Shastri, Nehru's
successor, died in 1966, Gandhi was elected prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   Known for: In the early 70s, Gandhi was said to be perhaps the
most popular leader in the world, although her term was not so
rosy. Under Gandhi, India exploded its first nuclear device.
Although she promised to abolish poverty, she was also beholden to
the rich for her power base. In the mid-'70s, Gandhi limited
personal freedoms and began jailing political rivals. In response,
she was voted out of office in 1977, but regained power in 1979.
When her son and heir-designate, Sanjay, died in a plane crash, she
began grooming son Rajiv as her successor. In 1984, after ordering
a violent raid on a Sikh temple, she was assassinated by two of her
bodyguards.
</P>
<P>
   Personal facts: Gandhi wrote in her autobiography, ``To a woman,
motherhood is the highest fulfillment,'' and the Nehru-Gandhi
dynasty continues to play a vital role in India's politics.
Although Rajiv, who followed his mother as prime minister, was
assassinated in 1991, his widow, Sonia, now chairs the opposition
Congress party.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
