<HEADER>
A7865 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-PARTICLE-PHYSICS-     01-18 0899
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-PARTICLE-PHYSICS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MILLENNIAL ANGST FOR PARTICLE PHYSICS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif., Ill., Mass.)   (af)  
 By MALCOLM W. BROWNE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As the directors of all three of the world's preeminent particle
accelerators retire this year, hopes are high that technical
advances they helped to bring about will lead to major discoveries.
But all three agree that high-energy physics is facing an uncertain
long-term future.
</P>
<P>
   And although American particle physicists will continue to do
trail-blazing research, the directors agreed, hundreds of American
scientists have already moved to European laboratories and more
will certainly follow.
</P>
<P>
   The three retiring administrators _ Dr. Burton Richter of the
Stanford Linear Accelerator Center, or SLAC, in California; Dr.
John Peoples Jr. of the Fermi National Accelerator Laboratory,
known as Fermilab, in Illinois, and Dr. Christopher Llewellyn
Smith, a Briton, of the European Laboratory for Particle Physics,
known as CERN, near Geneva, agreed in interviews that the field
faced enormous obstacles.
</P>
<P>
   The immediate prospects for particle physics seem as exciting as
ever. But the expense of building new high-energy machines runs to
billions of dollars, and the era of giant particle accelerators may
be approaching its twilight.
</P>
<P>
   Machines that smashed subatomic particles together at energies
like that of the Big Bang greatly expanded the horizons of
physicists, cosmologists and philosophers in the past few decades,
and in the near future they are likely to answer some intriguing
questions.
</P>
<P>
   Some examples: What is it that endows all matter with mass? Is
there an underlying framework in the universe that ties together
gravity with the other forces of nature? Do supposedly fundamental
particles like quarks and leptons actually have internal structure?
What is the mechanism that created more matter than antimatter in
the universal creation event, so that enough matter was left over
after the mutual annihilation to build the universe?
</P>
<P>
   Physicists hope that answers to these and other puzzles will
emerge from the handful of accelerator laboratories working at the
frontiers of physics. But the big question is whether the world's
governments are willing to spend the money for such knowledge.
</P>
<P>
   Existing accelerator projects are maintaining the research
momentum in the United States. Both SLAC and Fermilab, which have
been upgrading their accelerators, are still making important
discoveries.
</P>
<P>
   But in 2005, a proton accelerator with a circumference of 17
miles, the Large Hadron Collider, is to begin operating at CERN.
From then on, particle physicists agree, the center of high-energy
research will shift to Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Because the retiring directors have presided over a critical
period of accelerator physics, colleagues regard their passing as
bench marks.
</P>
<P>
   Richter, 67, will leave the directorship of SLAC on Aug. 31
after 15 years as chief. While in his 30s, he pioneered the
development of colliding-beam accelerators, in which opposing beams
of particles slam into each other head-on, creating showers of
debris and new particles.
</P>
<P>
   In 1974, using beams of electrons and antielectrons, or
positrons, Richter discovered a particle that came to be called
Psi/J. It contained two quarks possessing a previously unknown
flavor called charm. For this discovery, Richter and Dr. Samuel
C.C. Ting of the Massachusetts Institute of Technology shared the
1976 Nobel Prize in Physics.
</P>
<P>
   Peoples, 66, director of Fermilab, will retire on June 30 after
28 years there, 10 as director. Peoples directed the development of
a source of antiprotons for use in the colliding beams of
Fermilab's gigantic Tevatron accelerator.
</P>
<P>
   In the past few years his main concern has been building a new
main injector for the Tevatron, which will soon increase the flow
of particles in the opposing beams from a trickle to torrents. The
more particles a beam contains the greater the likelihood of
collisions with particles in the opposing beam _ collisions that
yield discoveries.
</P>
<P>
   The Tevatron is the world's highest energy particle accelerator,
and when protons collide with antiprotons inside its detectors,
they do so at energies just under two trillion electronvolts. The
stupendous power of the Tevatron made possible the 1995 discovery
of the top quark _ the last of six flavors of quarks predicted by
the standard model theory of particle physics.
</P>
<P>
   The Tevatron will remain the most powerful accelerator in the
world until CERN's Large Hadron Collider, or LHC, opens. This
accelerator will be seven times more powerful than the Tevatron and
is expected to yield a flood of discoveries.
</P>
<P>
   The director of CERN for the past five years, Dr. Llewellyn
Smith, 56, retired on Jan. 1, and is now the provost of University
College of London University. Among his major accomplishments was
persuading the 19 member governments and many collaborating
nations, including the United States, to pull together to build the
collider, which will cost about $2 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The United States had already spent about that amount on its own
54-mile-circumference Superconducting Supercollider, or SSC, in
Texas when Congress canceled the project in 1993. The project's
demise marked the shift in high-energy particle physics from the
United States to Europe.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   American physicists began flocking to Geneva to work on the new
collider. The Large Hadron Collider will have only a third of the
energy the SSC was designed to achieve, but from 2005 on, the LHC
will be, as one physicist put it, ``the only game in town.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt that getting the LHC going was critical, because it
came in the aftermath of the supercollider cancellation,''
Llewellyn Smith said. ``If that had failed it could have spelled
the end of our field, I suppose.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, he said, 590 American scientists and engineers _ more than
two-thirds of them refugees from the defunct American SSC _ are
working on the new European machine. The American contingent, about
15 percent of the total, is the largest in the LHC collaboration;
the next largest are the Italian group, with 467 scientists, and
the French, with 411.
</P>
<P>
   Peoples of Fermilab simultaneously served for a year presiding
over the dismantling of the embryonic SSC and dismissing hundreds
of employees while trying to find new jobs for them.
</P>
<P>
   All three directors agreed that the cost of large accelerators
that might follow Europe's LHC in the next century would be
staggering and would have to be shared among many nations. But they
called into question America's willingness to join such
collaborations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The United States has a very bad reputation as an
international partner now,'' Richter said, ``particularly since the
fiasco over the International Thermonuclear Experimental Reactor.''
</P>
<P>
   The project, an experimental fusion reactor, had the support of
the United States, Russia, Japan and Europe. About $1 billion was
spent on the project in the past decade. On Sept. 22, Bill
Richardson, the secretary of Energy, signed what his department
called ``a unilateral agreement extending United States support for
international fusion collaboration.''
</P>
<P>
   But Rep. F. James Sensenbrenner Jr., R-Wis., who heads the House
Science Committee, announced that he would not support further
expenditures on the international reactor aside from those needed
to close down the project, which now appears to be dead.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, he condemned the reactor as unacceptably
expensive and unpromising. After spending more than 10 years and $1
billion, he said, the parties had designed a fusion device that was
unaffordable. He said it was clear the device would not be build.
``The project failed and it's time to move forward,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   The action came as a rude shock to America's science partners
abroad, Richter of SLAC said. ``The Japanese are really steaming
over that,'' he said. ``They look on Washington's attitude toward
international scientific collaboration as something like Lucy and
the football _ raising expectations and then yanking them away.''
</P>
<P>
   SLAC has an agreement with Japan's particle physics laboratory,
KEK, by which the two institutions will design and perhaps build a
new accelerator some 22 miles long, in which beams of electrons and
positrons, each speeding along a straight track at an energy of
about one trillion electronvolts, will collide. But Japan's
disenchantment with the United States as a collaborator is likely
to affect the project, Richter said.
</P>
<P>
   CERN's Llewellyn Smith, who enlisted the financial and
scientific cooperation of the United States, Japan, Canada, Russia,
India and Israel along with the 19 CERN members for building the
Large Hadron Collider, agreed that dealing with Washington presents
special problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's certainly true that in the negotiations that I've been
involved in, dealing with the United States was the hardest,''
Llewellyn Smith said, even though the British and German
governments balked at the LHC budget at times.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem with the United States is that you can't tell who
decides things in Washington,'' he added. ``We foreigners are
supposed to deal with the administration, but you must deal with
the Congress or you get nowhere. So, as director of CERN, I spent a
lot of time taking a crash course in American politics and I still
don't know who makes the decisions, although I guess it's
Sensenbrenner.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
