<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-STAGE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THREE MEN AND A PAINTING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By REED JOHNSON 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; ``Art'' is the mouse that roared.
</P>
<P>
   Arriving with little fanfare, French playwright Yasmina Reza's
seemingly slight comedy about three middle-age friends who feud
over a work of modern art became one of the most enduringly
hard-to-get tickets in London and New York _ a level of popularity
that is almost unheard of these days among spoken-word plays.
</P>
<P>
   In London, it opened in 1996 with an all-star cast (Albert
Finney, Tom Courtenay and Ken Stott), changing actors every few
months and attracting return visits. The American-debut production,
which featured an unusual if talented Anglo-American cast _ Alan
Alda, Victor Garber and British actor Alfred Molina _ became an
instant Broadway hit when it opened last March. It has captured
almost every major British and American prize, including a
best-play Tony and an Olivier Award for best comedy.
</P>
<P>
   That success prompted a furious behind-the-scenes battle for
West Coast debut rights. Finally, the show's producers, including
actor Sean Connery, decided the best ``Art'' for California was the
New York version. Alda, Garber and Molina reprise their roles in
the production opening tonight at the Doolittle Theatre.
</P>
<P>
   Alda plays the supercilious Marc, the eldest of the three. When
his friend, Serge (Garber), buys an artwork that consists of
nothing more than white paint on canvas, Marc can't contain his
contempt. He sees Serge's purchase as an act of aesthetic
gullibility; worse, it symbolizes a rupture in what Marc perceives
to be a mentor-student relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Their disagreement escalates into a battle that explores the
very nature and limitations of male friendship. Molina's affable
Yvan at first tries to be the referee but soon gets caught up in a
three-way struggle of ego, pride and testosterone.
</P>
<P>
   Alda admits to being somewhat surprised at the play's New York
reception, although he was convinced of its quality from the
beginning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know if American audiences would take to it the way
other audiences had, although I also didn't know at that time that
it was as big a hit around the world as it was. I thought it had
just played in Paris and London. I found out later that it had
already played in about 80 cities.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I knew was that it was one of the best plays I'd ever
read. It didn't really matter to me if audiences liked it as much
as I did. I just wanted to play it.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, maybe not completely. Many critics and observers have said
that no trio of red-blooded American guys would be caught dead
arguing about such highfalutin topics as deconstruction and the
aesthetics of modern art. Push us beyond the holy trinity of male
conversational topics _ money, women and sports _ and we're out at
sea.
</P>
<P>
   Such a quirk is part of the play's essential Frenchness, but it
doesn't get in the way of Americans' enjoyment of it, Alda said.
</P>
<P>
   ``True, there are plenty of American men who wouldn't talk like
that. But the fact is it's written about three French guys. I think
deconstruction is an idea that even well-educated Americans would
tend to leave out of their conversation. But it would mean more to
Frenchmen, since it's a French movement.''
</P>
<P>
   Garber thinks ``Art's'' enduring popularity stems, in part, from
the many levels of insight and interpretation it offers. It means
different things to different people, he said. &QL; 
ENDIT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
