u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-UNION-SOCIAL19-COX     01-18 0495
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UNION-SOCIAL19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GOP URGES CLINTON TO ADDRESS SOCIAL SECURITY IN SPEECH
 &HT;    With UNION.
 &HT;    By LARRY LIPMAN
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Republican leaders urged President Clinton again
Monday to offer specific Social Security reform proposals in
Tuesday night's State of the Union message.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. E. Clay Shaw Jr., R-Fla., who chairs the House Social
Security subcommittee, asked Clinton in a letter Monday to answer
three specific questions about the nation's retirement system:
</P>
<P>
   _ How he will fix the system to provide as much protection for
``our children and grandchildren as it has for us and our
parents.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Whether Social Security investments in the stock market should
be managed through individual accounts or by the government
investing the program's surplus.
</P>
<P>
   _ How much of the estimated $1.5 trillion federal budget surplus
over the next 10 years will be needed to save Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw noted that Clinton's State of the Union message last year
set the stage for a year-long discussion of how to reform Social
Security.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is now time for you to fulfill your promise to the nation
and provide your specific ideas for how to get the job done,'' Shaw
wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw's letter echoed demands by House Ways and Means Committee
Chairman Bill Archer, R-Texas, that Clinton go first in offering a
detailed plan for making sure Social Security will be able to
continue paying full benefits beyond 2032, when the system's trust
fund is projected to run dry.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, House Speaker Dennis Hastert and Senate Majority
Leader Trent Lott sent Clinton a letter urging him to present a
detailed Social Security plan ``as soon as possible'' and offered
to hold a joint House-Senate hearing on March 1 to receive the
plan.
</P>
<P>
   Because most Social Security rescue plans require sacrifices
from taxpayers or beneficiaries, both Republicans and Democrats are
eager for the other party to take the lead in suggesting remedies.
</P>
<P>
   A senior White House official declined to comment Monday on what
Clinton will say Tuesday night about Social Security, but aides
have indicated he likely will refine his goals for saving the
program while continuing to reserve the surplus for Social
Security.
</P>
<P>
   One proposal which has been gathering steam within the
administration is using a portion of the budget surplus to set up
individual investment accounts outside the Social Security program.
While this would let the government test such accounts, it would
not solve Social Security's long-term solvency problem unless it
was later coupled with either a tax increase or gradual benefit
reductions.
</P>
<P>
   The investment measure is expected to appeal to Republicans,
many of whom have been clamoring for individual accounts, without
alienating Democrats, who have express concern with tinkering with
the existing system.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
