<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 16:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7901 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DAVIS-CONSULTANTS-HNS     01-18 1081
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DAVIS-CONSULTANTS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAVIS CAMPAIGN STAFF SHAPES POLICY WELL AFTER ELECTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ZACHARY COILE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ California Gov. Gray Davis, who casts
himself as a Clinton-style moderate Democrat, is following the
president's lead by keeping a close circle of consultants and
pollsters around after the election.
</P>
<P>
   ``We call it the 365-days-a-year strategy,'' said Bob
Mulholland, a top strategist for the state Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   It's what Clinton and his aides called the ``eternal campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis is hardly the first politician to use the strategy.
Presidents since John Kennedy have relied on paid political
consultants. Richard Nixon had a pollster on retainer throughout
his time in office. Big state governors, such as George Pataki of
New York and George W. Bush of Texas, have kept close ties with
their campaign consultants.
</P>
<P>
   In California, former Govs. George Deukmejian sought the advice
of consultants and Pete Wilson used pollsters to test public
response to many of his initiatives. More than 30 years ago, Ronald
Reagan relied on a kitchen cabinet of Republican lawyers and
businessman for ideas.
</P>
<P>
   What is unusual about Davis is he will keep his entire campaign
team intact: campaign manager, pollster and three national media
strategists. Instead of shaping Davis' campaign, the group now will
play a central role in how he governs.
</P>
<P>
   Garry South, Davis' sharp-tongued campaign manager, leads the
effort. South, who has earned a reputation as the California
equivalent of James Carville, Clinton's puckish adviser, was chief
of staff when Davis was lieutenant governor and is seen as his
political confidant.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are huge stakes involved here: This is our first
Democratic governor elected in 20 years and only the fourth in the
entire 20th century (in California),'' South said. ``We can't screw
this up.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul Maslin directs the governor's polling. He has worked for
three Democratic presidential campaigns and has advised Sen. Dianne
Feinstein, D-Calif., and former Sen. Alan Cranston, D-Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``We won't be polling every day or every week or on every
issue,'' Maslin said. But education is one area, he said, where it
will be critical to ``find out how (the public is) responding, what
they are looking for and what their expectations are ... of his
administration.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis also will rely on the Washington media firm of Doak,
Carrier, O'Donnell &AMP; Associates. Longtime Democratic strategist
David Doak, who founded the firm, will be a top adviser, as will
Tom O'Donnell, who for eight years was chief of staff to House
Minority Leader Richard A. Gephardt, D-Mo.
</P>
<P>
   Michele Carrier, also a partner in the firm, will continue to
work on communications and fund-raising for Davis. A former top
aide to the Senate majority leader in the Wisconsin Legislature,
Carrier also handles advertising for several major corporations.
</P>
<P>
   The group plans twice-weekly conference calls as well as
occasional face-to-face meetings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever the governor wants us to do to help him, we'll assist
in any way,'' O'Donnell said. ``We'll have ideas. Mostly we'll be
at his beck and call, to bounce ideas off of us and to talk
strategy.''
</P>
<P>
   One political observer questioned the role of the consultants in
the Davis administration because the advisers are not on the public
payroll nor subject to rules about conflict of interest.
</P>
<P>
   ``My concern would be accountability,'' said Ann Crigler,
director of the Jesse Unruh Institute of Politics at the University
of Southern California. ``I'm not sure how you go about holding
those people accountable if they are not on the public payroll and
not responsible to anyone's inquiries other than the governor's.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the details have yet to be worked out, the team will be
paid from Davis' campaign account, which held an estimated $2.5
million as of December. The group may also be paid by the
Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   South dismissed the concern about conflict of interest saying he
and other members of the team would avoid situations that could
embarrass the governor.
</P>
<P>
   He argued that the group's best advantage was being outside of
state government. That is why South turned down a job as chief of
staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``First of all, the pay is nothing,'' South said. ``Second, it
puts too many constraints on your activities. If you come to work
for the government full time, you are severely constrained in what
you can do politically, and I don't want that. I'm of more value to
Gray, frankly, on the outside. I'll have more freedom to do what
needs to be done.''
</P>
<P>
   None of the team members works in Sacramento. South lives in
Brentwood, Calif.; Maslin works in Oakland; Carrier lives in
Madison, Wis., and Doak and O'Donnell are based in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Davis has turned to the team largely because of its success in
the campaign _ the group helped engineer a surprise June primary
victory over two wealthy Democratic opponents, and his landslide
victory over the Republican candidate, Dan Lungren.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Each adviser had a role during the campaign: Doak edited
commercials; O'Donnell oversaw advertising and helped in debate
preparation; Carrier helped develop the fund-raising organization;
Maslin directed the polling; and South oversaw day-to-day
operations.
</P>
<P>
   After the election, the group stayed together. They worked
behind the scenes over the inaugural weekend to help write and edit
Davis' inaugural address. They also helped Davis edit and rehearse
his State of the State speech, which was written mostly by the
governor's communications staff.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson, the former Republican governor, was criticized for
polling on virtually every major issue. Clinton has faced the same
criticism for his use of polling data and focus groups in shaping
his policies.
</P>
<P>
   And some see a danger if Davis relies too much on polls and
consultants.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think pollsters provide a very useful function, and many of
them _ and certainly Gray's are _ very skilled and able,'' said
Steve Merksamer, a Republican lawyer and former chief of staff to
Deukmejian. ``But I think it's good for a governor, in addition to
getting political advice, to have seasoned advisers around him to
advise him about what the best policy is.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not every decision should be made based on what politically is
the right thing to do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-18-99 1643EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990118.0221 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 16:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7902 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-RETURN-TO-THE-WIL     01-18 0896
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-RETURN-TO-THE-WILD-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: Galapagos tortoise.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Through the National Zoo, Beck is coordinating an international
project that is on the verge of creating a self-sustaining
population of zoo-bred golden lion tamarins in the Atlantic coastal
forests of eastern Brazil. After 14 years of reintroductions, the
project has 228 of the squirrel-sized monkeys in the wild, but
perhaps more significant to the tamarin's survival was the
Brazilian government's creation in 1974 of the Poco das Antas
Biological Reserve north of Rio de Janeiro.
</P>
<P>
   There the remnant wild population has recovered more
spectacularly than the released animals have adapted, so that today
it numbers well over 600.
</P>
<P>
   As a rule, Beck said, it is better to move wild animals into new
habitats, as was done with wolves in Yellowstone National Park and
the Bitterroot Mountains in 1995, or to concentrate widely
dispersed animals into one or two larger reserves. The wild stock
is healthier and better equipped for survival than its captive-born
kin. ``Reintroduction of captive-bred animals is the tool of choice
in only a few cases,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Even then, said Donald Lindburg, head of the behavior division
of the Center for Reproduction of Endangered Species at the
Zoological Society of San Diego, the most successful candidates are
those who are brought in specifically for return to the wild as
quickly as possible to prevent the development of ``behavioral
distortions.''
</P>
<P>
   Some mammals appear to make the leap from the zoo, albeit with
considerable human assistance and sizable losses, but for the big
cats, great apes, bears, and even rhinos and elephants, familiarity
with humans and ignorance of their own culture is highly
problematic.
</P>
<P>
   ``With chimps and some of these other animals, cultural
transmission of knowledge is vital,'' said Roger Fouts, professor
of psychology and director of the Chimpanzee and Human
Communication Institute at Central Washington University. Many of
them spend years learning how to live in their landscape and for
that reason putting a captive-bred animal in the wild is
``equivalent to dropping a contemporary human being in a remote
area in the 18th or 19th century and saying, `Let's see if you make
it,''' said Bryan G. Norton, professor of environmental public
policy at the Georgia Institute of Technology.
</P>
<P>
   David Parsons, coordinator of the Mexican wolf recovery project,
says that the wolves released last spring ``figured out how to hunt
a whole lot earlier than I expected, but they didn't figure how to
run from people. They had learned in their pens to move 100 feet
away and stop, and that's what they seem to have done in the wild,
but that doesn't take you out of range of a gun.''
</P>
<P>
   Faced with the hard facts of reintroduction, Michael Hutchins,
director of conservation and science for the American Zoo and
Aquarium Association, has for several years urged member
institutions to modify ``the Noah's Ark paradigm.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Reintroduction is not the primary reason for captive
breeding,'' he said. Rather, its chief purpose is to allow zoos to
maintain populations of certain ``flagship species'' _
attention-grabbing animals like rhinos, the big cats, primates,
elephants, pandas, and rare and spectacular birds _ that can be
used to raise money for conservation projects in their country of
origin.
</P>
<P>
   By Hutchins' calculations, 93 percent of the mammals and 75
percent of the birds on display in North American zoos were bred in
captivity. Those animals also provide a pool for scientific
research and a sort of living gene bank to guard against extinction
and to supplement fragmented wild populations.
</P>
<P>
   The top zoos have also spent millions of dollars in recent years
to create more naturalistic or parklike environments for their
animals. But critics argue that with no prospect of sending animals
back to the wild, there is scant justification for keeping animals
locked away, sometimes for decades, or killing them before their
time to make room for younger, more robust, or rarer specimens,
although zoo officials say culling is on the decline.
</P>
<P>
   Multi-generational captive-bred animals are neither domestic nor
wild, these critics maintain. In addition to behavioral changes,
the animals may be undergoing subtle genetic alterations that make
them more adaptable to confinement.
</P>
<P>
   ``The evolution of those animals is being directed by humans,
not nature,'' said Eric Dinerstein, chief scientist of the World
Wildlife Fund. ``You have to ask whether that is fair?''
</P>
<P>
   Their differences notwithstanding, proponents and opponents of
captive breeding are close to unanimous in supporting habitat
preservation and protection from human hunting and collection as
the surest way to insure the survival of endangered species. They
would also establish corridors to link highly fragmented habitats.
</P>
<P>
   With proper nurturing, many of those animals will recover,
although perhaps more slowly than if they were forced into breeding
programs.
</P>
<P>
   When all else fails, Hutchins said, zoos and other qualified
organizations must be prepared to pull animals from the wild and
try to restore the species' vitality in the relative security of
captive breeding operations. But in those circumstances, there
might be no more habitat, and those animals will become passengers
on an ark they cannot exit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
