<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCIENCE-Q&AMP;A-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCIENCE QUESTIONS AND ANSWER 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
(jt) 
 By C.CLAIBORNE RAY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Greek Fire &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Was there a secret Byzantine naval weapon called Greek fire?
</P>
<P>
   A. Historians agree Greek fire existed, but debate its nature.
</P>
<P>
   In a new introduction by Bert S. Hall to the classic 1960 book
``A History of Greek Fire and Gunpowder,'' by J.R. Partington
(Johns Hopkins, 1999), Kallinikos of Heliopolis gets credit for
building fire-spouting ships that defended Constantinople from the
Arabs in 678.
</P>
<P>
   Greek fire was described as a liquid that burned even on the sea
surface; it generated frightening smoke and whooshing sounds. Its
secret was apparently lost in the Fourth Crusade in 1204.
</P>
<P>
   Candidates for ingredients include petroleum, resin and
quicklime, plus a possible secret ingredient. Some theorized that
this was saltpeter, which would make Greek fire an important
precursor of gunpowder.
</P>
<P>
   Partington, a chemist, was skeptical of theories that saltpeter
was added to unrefined petroleum that naturally seeped from the
ground, arguing that the Byzantines instead used some form of
distillation to make kerosene or gasoline.
</P>
<P>
   However, Hall, associate professor at the Institute for the
History and Philosophy of Science and Technology at the University
of Toronto, says that later researchers have rejected Dr.
Partington's ideas.
</P>
<P>
   One newer theory suggests that undistilled petroleum, collected
in the cooler months so that its volatile fractions were less
likely to evaporate, was kept in heated containers on board ship.
Another theory holds that the weapon was a kind of flame thrower
mixing a petroleum product with an oxidizing agent, probably
saltpeter.
</P>
<P>
   Readers are invited to submit questions by postal mail to
Questions, Science Times, The New York Times, 229 West 43d St., New
York, N.Y. 10036-3959, or by e-mail to: Question(AT)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   Questions of general interest will be answered in this column,
but unpublished letters cannot be answered individually.
</P>
<P>
   Requests for medical advice cannot be honored and unpublished
letters cannot be answered individually.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-18-99 1644EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990118.0224 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 16:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7905 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-COLLIDER-DRUGS-NY     01-18 0581
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-COLLIDER-DRUGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUST HOW MUCH IS THAT GIZMO IN THE TUNNEL? 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Texas, Mass.)   (af)  
 By MALCOLM W. BROWNE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In 1993, with $2 billion already spent on construction of what
would have been the world's mightiest particle accelerator, the
Congress killed the project, known as the Superconducting
Supercollider, or SSC. All that remains are some buildings, a lot
of land around Waxahachie, Texas, and a section of the planned
54-mile tunnel that would have housed the accelerator.
</P>
<P>
   But a small company, International Isotopes Inc., has acquired
some very expensive apparatus from the project for a song ($2.9
million), moved the machinery to its headquarters in Denton, Texas,
and will soon use it to manufacture radioactive pharmaceuticals.
</P>
<P>
   The company says its operation will help free United States
hospitals from dependence on military and foreign sources of these
vital substances.
</P>
<P>
   International Isotopes has modified an 80-foot-long linear
accelerator, or linac, built for the SSC and will use it to make a
dozen or more radioactive chemicals essential to diagnosing and
treating cancer and other diseases.
</P>
<P>
   When a proton from such an accelerator strikes the nucleus of an
atom it sometimes merges with the nucleus, changing it into a
different _ and often radioactive _ element. Depending on the
chemical nature of the new element, it can be used to target tumors
in a specific part of the body; radioactive iodine, for example,
seeks out tumors in the thyroid.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the SSC, the completed linac would have given a beam
of protons a preliminary shove of up to 70 million electronvolts
before injecting the beam into the main accelerator ring, where the
protons would have been further accelerated to 20 trillion
electronvolts. The main ring was abandoned after a small section of
its tunnel was dug. But the linac was nearly finished.
</P>
<P>
   Carl W. Seidel, president of International Isotopes, said that
his company had modified the linac to greatly increase the number
of protons in ts beam. The company expects to begin using the
linac to make the radioactive chemicals starting in June.
</P>
<P>
   The Department of Energy has encouraged the project partly
because it will assure a reliable domestic source of short-lived
radioactive chemicals, most of which must be used within hours of
their manufacture. One such substance, fluorine-16, used to
pinpoint cancerous tissue in the brain, decays so rapidly that half
of any amount of it disappears in 110 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Clinicians depend partly on the production of radioactive
chemicals as byproducts of Defense Department reactors, which do
not operate continuously. Most of the shortfall must be obtained
from foreign sources.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors using radioactive substances for diagnosis and treatment
must obtain these materials from reactors or accelerators that are
nearby, although the longer-lived isotopes can survive short air
trips. But Seidel said his company would use its linear accelerator
as a prototype for similar accelerators it would build for sale or
lease.
</P>
<P>
   High-energy physicists continue to lament the demise of the SSC.
But President Clinton, who signed the legislation that killed the
project, has had second thoughts. In June, after the discovery of
mass in neutrino particles, Clinton told students at the
Massachusetts Institute of Technology that the discovery ``calls
into question the decision'' to abandon the project.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-18-99 1645EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990118.0225 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 16:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7906 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCIENCE-WATCH-NYT &LR;      01-18 0516
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCIENCE-WATCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCIENCE NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
(jt) 
 By HENRY FOUNTAIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Extinction, Ancient Style &LR;
</P>
<P>
   As a protector of fellow creatures, modern humans' record is
spotty at best. The steamroller of progress has put some species on
the endangered list, and even flattened some to extinction. But now
comes word that not-so-modern humans didn't do so well either.
</P>
<P>
   A team of Australian and American researchers has concluded that
the earliest humans in Australia may have inadvertently wiped out
most of the large animal species on the continent 50,000 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Like other parts of the world, Australia was at one time home to
a diverse assortment of so-called megafauna. In Australia's case,
these included a marsupial that weighed as much as a linebacker, a
horned tortoise that was about the size of a compact car, and a
flightless ostrich-like bird, Genyornis newtoni, that tipped the
scales at 200 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Many of these large animals became extinct around the same time,
but exactly when has been unclear. The reason has been unclear as
well, with some scientists blaming climate change and others, human
activity. The researchers, who wrote about their work in a recent
issue of the journal Science, used a variety of newer dating
techniques on fossilized eggshells of Genyornis to calculate that
the birds suddenly disappeared 50,000 years ago. This was a time of
only mild climate change, the researchers note.
</P>
<P>
   But it was about 5,000 years after the first humans arrived on
the continent. So the researchers speculate that systematic burning
of vegetation by these aboriginal Australians disrupted the food
chain enough that Genyornis and other shrub- and tree-loving
species became extinct.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Tracking Temperatures &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Back to modern times for a moment. Much has been made of the
fact that human activity is causing global temperatures to rise.
But the picture is more complex than that: In land areas, average
annual minimum temperatures (that is, nighttime temperatures) are
increasing at twice the rate of average annual maximum (daytime)
temperatures.
</P>
<P>
   Three Colorado State University researchers, studying the growth
of vegetation on range land since 1970, have discovered that there
appear to be ecological consequences to this phenomenon. The
researchers, writing in Science, found that higher minimum
temperatures have cut the production of buffalo grass, a prime food
source for grazing cattle, and increased the abundance of invasive,
nongrassy plants.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers speculate on several reasons for this. For one
thing, they say, the warmer nights extend the growing season, which
would primarily benefit cool-season plants (like the nongrasses)
that grow most rapidly. These plants would rob the hot-season (and
slower growing) grasses of nutrients and water. Warmer nights also
increase plant respiration, which will speed up loss of carbon by
the plant (thus slowing growth) if there is not a corresponding
increase in photosynthesis during the day.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-18-99 1648EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990118.0226 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 16:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7907 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCIENCE-WATCH-NYT &LR;      01-18 0516
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCIENCE-WATCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCIENCE NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
(jt) 
 By HENRY FOUNTAIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Extinction, Ancient Style &LR;
</P>
<P>
   As a protector of fellow creatures, modern humans' record is
