<SLUG> BC-MONEY-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN SPINOFFS, LOOK FOR THE PRODIGY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By PAMELA YIP 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ When thinking of investing in a spinoff, think about
parents raising a child to live on his or her own.
</P>
<P>
   You're looking for a situation where the offspring is likely to
thrive out in the cold, cruel world.
</P>
<P>
   First, you should determine whether the parent company has given
its corporate child a strong foundation to prosper alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``It depends on how much time and devotion was given to the
child,'' said Mark Minichiello, analyst at Spin-Off Advisors in
Chicago, an investment banking boutique specializing in spinoffs.
``If the parent was helping the company before the spinoff, that
may put them on a better footing when they become a stand-alone
company.''
</P>
<P>
   Winning spinoffs have a strong market in their product or
service, have good brand identity and experienced management.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the child was neglected, when you put them on their own,
there's going to be a larger adjustment period,'' Minichiello said.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most measurable signs of parent-company abuse is the
amount of debt dumped on the spinoff company.
</P>
<P>
   It's common for a parent company to shift some of its debt to
its offspring so the corporate parent's balance sheet looks better.
</P>
<P>
   To see whether this debt loan will turn into a crushing burden,
first read the financial section of the prospectus to see if the
warnings are really stern. Also, look on the financial reports on
the cash flow statements and see if there's any cash left after
paying the debt.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
REPUTATION COUNTS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Closely consider the intangibles.
</P>
<P>
   The reputation of the company's products makes a big difference.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the stock of Bally Fitness Corp., which was spun
off from Bally Entertainment in 1996, has soared since its spinoff.
</P>
<P>
   If you regularly visit a Bally health club and always see lots
of members pumping iron and you like the service, that may be a tip
that it would be a good investment.
</P>
<P>
   Don't give up if the spinoff needs work. The parent company
typically spins off what looks like a duller child.
</P>
<P>
   Pay a lot of attention to the management. With the right
leadership, an operation that never fit in after a takeover might
begin to shine.
</P>
<P>
   ``The management of the company that is spun off gets to be
management of a public company,'' said Harry Pinson, managing
director of the Houston office of Credit Suisse First Boston, an
investment banking firm. ``They can be rewarded for the performance
of their little piece, as opposed to having that be filtered
through the larger enterprise from which it came.''
</P>
<P>
   Houston-based PennzEnergy Co. is an example of two ways that a
company involved in a spinoff can be appealing.
</P>
<P>
   First, the management now has the added pressure to focus on
efficiently adding reserves since the company's future depends on
it. But before you invest, it's wise to wait for some sign it's
able to achieve that goal.
</P>
<P>
   The second appeal is that a stand-alone company might make an
acquisition target. Many analysts have listed PennzEnergy as a
possible takeover target this year, when depressed energy prices
are likely to spawn a spate of acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   For Pennzoil-Quaker State, which was formed when Pennzoil Co.
spun off its specialty-automotive products and oil-change
businesses, going solo means being able to allocate resources to a
more sharply focused business, said spokesman Greg Panagos.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
COMMUNICATION CAN MAKE, BREAK &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A spinoff often is designed to create a company Wall Street
understands because it's focused on a single industry.
</P>
<P>
   So look for children who have talents that will let them earn
some big money on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   These can be promising new products or profitable lines of
business that just haven't been noticed because they are buried
inside a big company.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the reasons companies spin off subsidiaries is because
they believe the marketplace isn't recognizing the value of that
company,'' said Lanny Sachnowitz, manager of the Aim Charter Fund,
a Houston mutual fund.
</P>
<P>
   It's the job of the spinoff to communicate that.
</P>
<P>
   Some good signs are articles about the company in the business
media, analysts' coverage of the company and public appearances by
company executives.
</P>
<P>
   ``The public communication is important because they have to
convey to the shareholders, as well as the outsiders, what their
strategic plan is, what their goals are, and they have to convey
that in a way that the analysts and shareholders, as well, will
understand,'' Minichiello said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Pamela Yip can receive electronic mail via the Internet. Address
your comments and questions to pamela.yip(at)chron.com, or call
(713) 220-2000 and enter access code 1003. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
