<BODY>
 AM-PAGE1-CONSIDER-NYT 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
Page 1, Tuesday, Jan. 19. The N.Y. Times News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Will move in ``i'' news file.)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-U.S. (Washington) _ Secretary of State Albright warns
Slobodan Milosevic he would make a ``grave mistake'' and invite
bombing if he does not comply with his Kosovo peace commitments.
But, in a series of provocative measures, Yugoslavia orders an
American peace verifier, William Walker. out of the country within
48 hours and refuses to let a U.N. war crimes prosecutor, Louise
Arbour, in while Serb forces pounds the hills outside a village
where ethnic Albanians were massacred. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-DISSENT (Beijing) _ As they very publicly send the most
strident democracy campaigners to prison, China's leaders have also
quietly tightened the screws on liberal intellectuals, journalists
and publications. By Erik Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   ANGOLA-U.N. (United Nations) _ Kofi Annan, the U.N.
secretary-general, calls for an end to the U.N. mission in Angola,
citing a resumption of the civil war and hard-line government
propaganda against world body. By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
