<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 16:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7917 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-MISCARRIAGE-485&AMP;A     01-18 1166
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-MISCARRIAGE-485&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMMUNE SYSTEM AS SUSPECT IN MISCARRIAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By DOROTHY J. BARNHOUSE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Women who have had repeated miscarriages or for whom in-vitro
fertilization has failed are often told that nothing can be done to
help them. While almost 70 percent of miscarriages over all are due
to chromosomal defects, at least 50 percent of recurrent
miscarriages have no apparent explanation, according to the
American College of Obstetrics and Gynecology.
</P>
<P>
   Now a few doctors are looking at one possible cause of
unexplained miscarriage: problems in the immune system.
</P>
<P>
   These doctors theorize that when a woman miscarries again and
again it may be because her immune system is wrongly attacking her
embryo as foreign. If this is the problem, and it can be overcome,
they say, the women may be able to carry pregnancies to term.
</P>
<P>
   This approach is controversial. For one thing, it remains to be
proved that immune system disorders are associated with infertility
or miscarriage.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Joseph Hill, the director of Reproductive Medicine at
Brigham and Women's Hospital in Boston and associate professor of
obstetrics-gynecology at Harvard Medical School, warned that ``many
hypotheses or mechanisms have been proposed for pregnancy loss with
an immunologic bent, but there is very little data to support any
of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, some doctors are treating infertile women with
immunoglobulin, a blood product pooled from thousands of donors and
used to regulate abnormal responses of the immune system. They
believe it somehow modulates the action of the immune system's
killer cells _ the body's first line of defense against illness and
the cells that may be responsible for destroying embryos in some
women.
</P>
<P>
   The College of Obstetrics and Gynecology says that ``no efficacy
data exist to warrant expensive immunoglobulin therapy at this
time.'' Dr. Benjamin Younger, executive director of the American
Society of Reproductive Medicine, said the group regarded any
immunoglobulin treatment as ``experimental'' and recommended that
patients receive it only as ``informed, consenting participants in
a board-approved randomized clinical trial.''
</P>
<P>
   The National Institutes of Health had planned such a study, but
it was put on hold six months ago because of an insufficient supply
of immunoglobulin, said Dr. Donna Vogel, research coordinator for
the National Institutes of Child Health and Human Development. ``If
we had the drug today, we would do the study,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The immune system fights infection by identifying tissues
foreign to the body and sending out antibodies to destroy them. In
a normal pregnancy, the immune system differentiates an embryo _
technically a foreign tissue _ from other, abnormal tissues and
develops a protective response toward it, keeping antibodies away
and creating a supportive environment in the uterus.
</P>
<P>
   Some scientists believe that the immune systems of women
suffering from recurrent reproductive failure may lack this
protective response.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Immunoglobulin, often called intravenous immunoglobulin or IVIg,
is licensed and approved for marketing by the Food and Drug
Administration for a variety of conditions including immune
deficiencies and bone marrow transplantation.
</P>
<P>
   But because doctors may legally prescribe any approved drug for
any purpose, some are using it to treat women suffering repeated
pregnancy loss. Their number is unknown.
</P>
<P>
   The College of Obstetrics and Gynecology estimates that at least
15 to 20 percent of all pregnancies end in miscarriage, many before
a woman even knows she is pregnant. For that same reason, it is
possible that many instances of unexplained infertility may
actually be early miscarriages. Recurrent pregnancy loss,
traditionally defined as three or more successive miscarriages,
occurs in 4 percent of pregnancies, according to estimates of the
obstetrics college.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Carolyn Coulam, director of reproductive immunology and vice
president for medical affairs at the Center for Human Reproduction,
a private fertility clinic in Chicago, estimates that immune
disorders may lie behind as many as 50 to 80 percent of recurrent
miscarriages for which no apparent cause is found and as many as 40
percent of unexplained fertility problems.
</P>
<P>
   Elevations in natural killer cells are found in 12 percent of
women with recurrent pregnancy loss and 25 percent of women with
repeated in-vitro fertilization failures, said Dr. Alan Beer,
professor of obstetrics-gynecology and microbiology and immunology
at the Chicago Medical School. Proponents of immunoglobulin say
that these are the women who may be helped by the therapy.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Susan Cowchuck, clinical professor of obstetrics-gynecology
at New York University Medical Center, is not as sure. While there
is ``no doubt that IVIg blocks killer cells in a test tube, we
don't even know that natural killer cells have anything to do with
miscarriages,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, both Drs. Beer and Coulam claim an 85 percent
success rate for immunoglobulin among those patients who have had
recurrent miscarriages and infertility and have high levels of
natural killer cells.
</P>
<P>
   Hill, however, questions these results, saying that most cases
of pregnancy loss are due to chromosomal abnormalities in the fetus
which lead to its demise regardless of the therapy given. He also
said that after three consecutive pregnancy losses, for reasons
doctors did not fully understand, the chances of a live birth were
70 percent without any therapy. ``That's a high background success
rate,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, anecdotes about the treatment, many spread on the
Internet, are prompting patients to ask doctors for the treatment,
a trend that troubles some doctors. ``There's no effective therapy
out there _ none,'' Hill said. ``The trouble is, you've got all
these people on the Internet claiming that IVIg works. ''
</P>
<P>
   But patients like Nancy Hemenway believe in the treatment. Ms.
Hemenway, the executive director and co-founder of the
International Council on Infertility Information Dissemination, a
nonprofit group based in Arlington, Va., said she had had four
miscarriages before being treated with IVIg. She now has a
3-year-old daughter. ``It's my unscientific point of view that
without IVIg my daughter wouldn't be here,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But the treatment is not without its own risks. Although all
blood products are now screened for viruses like HIV and hepatitis
C, there remains a risk of new viruses or diseases for which
screening and cleansing methods have not yet been perfected. Steve
Manzo, the director of public affairs for the Plasma Products
Industry Association, said the FDA had tightened its regulatory
requirements, a process that caused a temporary reduction in
supply.
</P>
<P>
   Still, many women are eager to try it. ``Hope sells,'' Hill
said. ``Skepticism doesn't.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
