<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HALBERSTAM-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`PLAYING FOR KEEPS': WHEN HE SHOT, HE SOARED: JORDAN THE MAN AND
ATHLETE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Publication notes at end) 
(JT) 
 By MICHIKO KAKUTANI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   He was an athlete who exhausted our supply of superlatives, a
magician whose sleight of hand never failed to amaze. In a
profession measured by harsh, unforgiving statistics he was
compared to Michelangelo, Baryshnikov and Picasso, and hailed as
Miracle and Superman. In an age of celebrity and hyperbole, he
remained one of those rare performers whose achievements matched
the hype. He took Bill Russell's definition of sport _ ``a mixture
of art and war'' _ to a new level, and in the process he became the
most recognizable person in the world, ``the flying man,'' as one
Chinese newspaper called him, the man who defied the laws of
physics and redefined his sport.
</P>
<P>
   With his retirement from the Chicago Bulls last week, Michael
Jordan demonstrated his usual impeccable timing: going out at the
top of his game, and leaving fans with one final image on his
highlight reel: that beautiful clutch jumper with 5.2 seconds on
the clock that gave the Bulls the win over Utah in game six of the
NBA finals and their sixth championship last June.
</P>
<P>
   The timing of ``Playing for Keeps,'' David Halberstam's new book
about Jordan and the Bulls' arduous 1997-98 season, has turned out
to be nearly as perfect: coming out only days after M.J.'s
departure from the NBA and only weeks after the end of the league's
six-month lockout.
</P>
<P>
   Although there isn't much in ``Playing for Keeps'' that most
basketball fans didn't already know _ Jordan did not grant any
interviews for the book and much of the volume is a compendium of
compelling but familiar stories fleshed out with new reporting _
the volume is animated by the author's own passion for the game.
Halberstam uses that knowledge to convey to the reader the extreme
mixture of talent, will and old-fashioned hard work that went into
Jordan's achievements. His determination to situate M.J., ``the
phenomenon of him,'' in a historical context provides both the
casual sports aficionado and the ardent basketball fan with an
appreciation of how No. 23's success helped change the NBA and how
those changes, in turn, reflected larger developments in the world
of sports.
</P>
<P>
   Halberstam touched upon similar themes in his baseball books
(``Summer of '49'' and ``October 1964''), and in this volume he
dwells at some length on the changes that have overtaken
professional basketball since his last book on the subject, ``The
Breaks of the Game,'' 17 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   When Larry Bird and Magic Johnson, Jordan's two great
predecessors, entered the league in 1979, Halberstam writes,
professional basketball was ``considered to be badly tainted'':
``it was seen as far too black, and the majority of its players, it
was somehow believed, were on drugs and willing to play hard only
in the last two minutes of the game.'' Few games were broadcast on
network television, and the total of all players' salaries in 1978
was roughly $40 million, less than a third of the $126 million deal
Minnesota made with the unproven Kevin Garnett in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years free agency, cable television, an international
audience and the sneaker wars have turned the NBA into a wildly
lucrative business, and professional sports have increasingly
become a form of entertainment, vying with rock concerts and movies
for audiences' attention. As ticket prices have escalated, team
owners have glitzed up their games with cheerleaders and Jumbotron
graphics and wealthy corporate types have begun to replace die-hard
fans in the seats. At the same time advertisers and television
networks have worked hard to promote individual players instead of
teams, creating superstars readily identifiable to the general
public.
</P>
<P>
   Halberstam argues that America's domination of the international
cultural market and the marketability of basketball (based in part
on the fact that its players' shoes, unlike baseball spikes or
football cleats, can be worn by millions of wanna-be civilians)
made it inevitable ``that the player catapulted forward as the
signature commercial representative of this great new
athletic-cultural-commercial empire would be an American and a
basketball player.'' It is an observation based on retrospective
wisdom, of course, and an observation that oddly underplays
Jordan's own unmatched talents, detailed so vigorously in the
remainder of this book.
</P>
<P>
   ``Playing for Keeps'' gives the reader a keenly observed picture
of Jordan's career: from his Wunderkind debut at North Carolina,
where Dean Smith's vaunted program honed his work ethic and
defensive skills as a player, through his early years with the
struggling Bulls to his apotheosis as a modern basketball god; from
his temporary abdication to play minor league baseball after his
father's slaying, to his triumphant delivery of a second three-peat
championship for Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   We are reminded of the razzle-dazzle pyrotechnics of the young
Michael Jordan, with his slashing drives to the hoop, his ferocious
slam-dunks, his dazzling, Dr. J-like moves in midair. We are
reminded as well of an older Jordan's addition of new skills like a
fadeaway jumper to his arsenal and his continued growth as a player
whose uncommon physical gifts were matched only by an indomitable
mental toughness and a ferocious competitive will.
</P>
<P>
   While Halberstam's often lumbering prose is decidedly at odds
with his subject's breathtaking finesse, he manages, through
understatement, to remind the reader of those iconic moments that
galvanized Jordan's career as the greatest player ever to play the
game: his winning shot, as a freshman, against Georgetown in the
1982 NCAA finals, his record 63-point masterpiece (after coming
back from a broken foot) against the Boston Celtics in the 1986
playoffs; his heroic 38-point performance in Game Five against Utah
in the 1997 NBA finals while suffering from a debilitating fever,
and, of course, his parting shot in last June's finals, his 25th
game-winning shot.
</P>
<P>
   Even as he is chronicling Jordan's exploits, Halberstam uses his
storytelling skills to give the reader a vivid sense of the
personalities surrounding him on the court, most notably Scottie
Pippen, Dennis Rodman, their coach Phil Jackson, and their
struggles with the Bulls' front office. He shows us the
difficulties of assembling (and maintaining) a championship team,
examines the unreckoned consequences of fame that attended Jordan's
success and makes us marvel, once again, at M.J.'s dazzling feats,
his singular ability to deliver performances commensurate with _
and often surpassing _ his own legend.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   PLAYING FOR KEEPS: Michael Jordan and the World He Made
</P>
<P>
   By David Halberstam
</P>
<P>
   Illustrated. 426 pages. Random House. $24.95.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
