<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 17:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7928 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-SMELL-NYT &LR;      01-18 0616
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-SMELL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE ROSES OF YOUTH SMELL LESS IN OLD AGE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Pa.)   (af)  
 By JOHN O'NEIL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here is yet another reason to stop and smell the roses: They
might not smell as sweet later on.
</P>
<P>
   Science has confirmed what many people have long suspected _
that the sense of smell starts to wane with age. For some people,
the loss begins in their 30s.
</P>
<P>
   But because smell is not the most precise of human senses,
charting the decline in ability, let alone understanding its
mechanism, has been difficult. Older people often complain about a
loss of their sense of taste when it is actually olfaction that has
been impaired.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers have determined that the loss happens in complicated
ways, said Dr. Marcia Levin Pelchat, a biological psychologist with
the Monell Chemical Sense Center, a nonprofit institute in
Philadelphia. ``Older people have a higher threshold for noticing a
smell,'' Dr. Pelchat said, ``and given an odor that is detectable,
an older person will perceive it as less intense.''
</P>
<P>
   There is also a change in adaptation _ the phenomenon that makes
a strong odor seem to fade. ``For older individuals, that process
seems to take place more rapidly and be longer lasting,'' she said.
Finally, older people are less able to identify what they smell.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, researchers have begun studying individual
living olfactory receptor neurons _ the nerve cells that translate
chemical molecules in the air into electrical signals to the brain.
Over five years, Dr. Nancy Rawson of Monell collected samples of
these neurons, found in the upper part of the nasal cavity, from
more than 200 subjects, covering a wide span of ages.
</P>
<P>
   In earlier experiments, Dr. Rawson had found that cells from
younger adults responded to some types of smells and not others,
differences that some researchers suspect have to do with the types
of biochemical pathways the cells use to produce different
electrical signals to send to the brain. The human cells showed a
higher level of ``response selectivity'' than had been found in
animal olfactory cells.
</P>
<P>
   So she decided to compare the young human cells with cells from
older people. She took smells that had provoked the either/or
response in cells in younger adults, that is they responded to one
set of smells or the other but not both. (One set of odors
contained things like clove and rose odors, and one had smells like
fish, vanilla and fruit.) To her surprise, about 20 percent of the
neurons from the older people responded to both smells.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Pelchat said the research team was pursuing a couple of
ideas in trying to figure out the meaning of this finding, which
appeared in the latest issue of The Monell Connection, a newsletter
summarizing the institute's research.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's possible that this loss of selectivity is causing some of
the decreased accuracy in naming odors,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Another possibility, she said, is that ``perhaps adaptation
becomes less specific'' with age. ``What if smelling roses makes
you less sensitive to coffee's odor?'' she asked. If very different
odors can trigger similar neurons, adaptation may be triggered more
often: sort of the equivalent of hitting the mute button when any
politician comes on the TV, not just the ones you detest.
</P>
<P>
   Not all older people notice a change in the sense of smell. ``We
do know that very healthy aging people tend to have a better sense
of smell than the less healthy,'' said Dr. Pelchat. ``What we don't
know is if that's because they are taking fewer medications _ since
many have side effects that interfere with smelling _ or if it's
just another aspect of successful aging.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
