<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    On the Newsstands
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Academic overload: When the kids complain about too much
homework, they aren't just whining. Time ($2.95) reports that
after-school assignments have soared.
</P>
<P>
   School crunch: Most of us remember homework as something we did
in study hall or on the bus ride home. Not any more. According to
Time ($3.50), kids today come home with more schoolwork than ever
before and at a younger age. The levels of homework have fluctuated
from a high in the post-Sputnik era to a low in the late 1960s and
'70s. But a 1983 government report on the failings of American
schools spurred educators to get serious again. In addition, baby
boomer parents are pressuring their kids even harder to get into
top secondary schools and colleges. American students are
stressed-out, but Time notes that they still ``work less, play more
and peform worse than many of their counterparts around the
world.''
</P>
<P>
   The Jordan legend: Everyone is familiar with the Michael Jordan
who soared above the net _ and every other player. But what is he
like off the court? In the wake of Jordan's announced retirement
last week, Newsweek ($3.50) talked to friends and family about the
superstar's private life and his plans for the future. The portrait
that emerges is one of a quick-witted man who loves his family but
who prefers hanging out with a tight circle of male friends. Even
with the guys, Newsweek says, he plays golf, cards, or geography
games (he loves to quiz friends on state capitals) with the same
cutthroat competitiveness he exhibited on the basketball court.
</P>
<P>
   Buying the past: The New Yorker ($3) takes us into, of all
places, a hardware store. Not just any hardware store, however.
Restoration Hardware is a paradise for people like New Yorker
writer David Brooks, who found spiritual redemption among the
crystal radios, old-fashioned kazoos and dustpans. Browsers in the
stores see the artifacts of days gone by as keys to the wisdom that
our ancestors possessed, Brooks writes. ``Maybe the little salt
cellars can bring back the old traditions and the old virtues. And,
anyway, at only twelve dollars it's worth a shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Coming attractions: Not surprisingly, the 1999 preview issue of
Entertainment Weekly ($3.50) predicts that George Lucas' ``The
Phantom Menace'' will be the blockbuster of the summer. Other
likely movie hits include ``Austin Powers: The Spy Who Shagged
Me''; Kevin Costner's baseball film, ``For Love of the Game''; and
``Mission Impossible II.'' And in books, `` 'Tis,'' Frank McCourt's
sequel to his best-selling memoir ``Angela's Ashes,'' is expected
to be as big as Tom Wolfe's ``A Man in Full'' when it hits stores
in September.
</P>
<P>
   Quick reads: Does love at first sight really exist? Absolutely,
reports Life ($3.99) in an article about the science of love.
Researchers now say one glimpse of the right person can set off a
chemical reaction leading to romance.
</P>
<P>
   Don O'Briant writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
