</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Put two-part `X-Files' under `A' for answers
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ The biggest tease in television, ``The
X-Files'' creator Chris Carter, swears that this time he's going to
deliver the goods the show's fans have been waiting for: real
answers.
</P>
<P>
   In a two-part episode airing in February sweeps, ``X-Files''
Agent Fox Mulder (David Duchovny) will learn definitively who his
biological father is and what happened to his sister Samantha, who
was abducted by aliens, the show's original driving engine.
</P>
<P>
   ``The show will have to change because so much is going to be
explained,'' Carter told the nation's TV critics meeting here to
preview the midseason schedule. ``You'll understand how Mulder
didn't choose the X-Files, they were chosen for him. Cigarette
Smoking Man is all but stripped of his mystery. He's going to be
exposed.''
</P>
<P>
   The popular series about FBI agents exploring a massive
government cover-up of alien infiltration of Earth (or something
like that) is at its peak popularity in its sixth season,
frequently landing in Nielsen's Top 10 shows. Carter said one
reason he's revealing secrets next month is that the plan is for
next season to be the last, and the complex conspiracy must be
unraveled.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone is prepped for the seventh year to be the last,'' he
said. ``An eighth season could happen, but I'm not expecting
that.'' He is, however, expecting to make another ``X-Files''
feature film, though there are no plans to start it any time soon.
</P>
<P>
   In the Feb. 7 show, titled ``Two Fathers'' (a reference to
doubts about Mulder's paternity), alien abductee Cassandra Spender
returns to Earth and threatens to expose the conspiracy. In the
Feb. 14 episode, ``One Son,'' Mulder learns a fair amount of the
truth, but the next question to be raised will be: What is he going
to do about it?
</P>
<P>
   Carter would not confirm or deny rumors that Agent Krycek (Nick
Lea) will be killed in the two-parter.
</P>
<P>
   Carter also is working on another series for Fox, which may be
ready for next fall: ``Harsh Realm.'' It will be a science-fiction
exploration of virtual reality and a parallel universe with a
detective twist. No casting yet.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Kloer writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga. E-mail: channelsurfer(AT)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
