<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VITAL-SIGNS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN OXYGEN RUSH: GOOD, BAD OR INDIFFERENT?  
 LESBIAN HEALTH: A MATTER OF MYSTERIES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: Businesses called oxygen bars, which provide customers with
oxygen-rich air, are cropping up on the West Coast. Do these
provide any health benefits?
</P>
<P>
   _ ALISHA BERGER
</P>
<P>
   YES
</P>
<P>
   It is well known that oxygen is a necessary nutrient for the
function and health of every cell in the human body, and there is
more than enough literature in favor of oxygen therapies. I have
seen the practical effect of oxygen on the reversal of many
diseases at my clinic, the Wilshire Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the most common benefits are related to lung conditions
such as asthma, and it has even been beneficial in sinusitis. It
has relieved migraine headaches, muscle stiffness and tension, has
been important in chronic fatigue syndrome as well as Epstein-Barr
and other conditions like depression. If you use oxygen for 20
minutes you will notice a change. Muscles become loosened,
headaches and stress seem to disappear. There is a renewed energy
level if you are feeling down, and a feeling of relaxation if you
are feeling tense. I am confident that oxygen works.
</P>
<P>
   _ DR. RICHARD DE ANDREA
</P>
<P>
   Clinic medical director and partner in a West Hollywood, Calif.,
oxygen bar, O2
</P>
<P>
   NO
</P>
<P>
   The inhalation of pure oxygen gas has been proven beneficial in
humans suffering from illnesses that compromise the function of
lungs and the cardiovascular system. And the application of
concentrated oxygen gas given to normal, healthy people has proven
efficacious in activities at high altitudes, where the partial
pressure of oxygen in air is diminished.
</P>
<P>
   However, there is no evidence that breathing oxygen by healthy
people at sea level produces any significant benefit. The body
cannot store oxygen and the brief inspiration of concentrated
oxygen will minimally, if at all, elevate the amount of oxygen
being supplied to the body's tissue. At best, breathing oxygen at
sea level by healthy people will have a greater psychological
effect than any known physiologic effect. It is probably not
detrimental and represents a harmless activity which, at best,
could have some placebo effect.
</P>
<P>
   _ DR. PETER JOKL
</P>
<P>
   Chief, Section of Sports Medicine, Yale University School of
Medicine
</P>
<P>
   LESBIAN HEALTH: A MATTER OF MYSTERIES
</P>
<P>
   After surveying the body of scientific literature on lesbian
health and holding workshops with researchers and clinicians, a
panel of experts convened by the Institute of Medicine issued a
report last week deploring the gaps in reliable information about
lesbian health. The panel called for large-scale studies to counter
rampant ``myths and misconceptions'' and to improve the quality of
treatment lesbians are receiving.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the face of little empirical information, there are
numerous beliefs and misconceptions about the health risks of
lesbians that can affect their health outcome,'' said the report,
called ``Lesbian Health: Current Assessment and Directions for the
Future.''
</P>
<P>
   Some beliefs are true, but many are not, the report said. For
example, lesbians commonly believe they do not need regular Pap
tests or routine gynecological care. And many also worry that there
is an epidemic of breast cancer among lesbians. Though there is
anecdotal evidence that lesbians experience higher rates of breast
and cervical cancers, lung cancer, cardiovascular disease, sexually
transmitted diseases, hypertension, and mental health and substance
abuse problems, the panel found no reliable research proving that
lesbianism itself was a risk factor for disease.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still don't know whether they're at higher risk for certain
cancers per se, because many of them have not had children,'' said
Dr. Ann Burgess, a nursing professor at the University of
Pennsylvania who headed the panel. Hormonal fluxes of pregnancy can
lower the risks of breast and ovarian cancers. Also, as a group,
lesbians smoke more and weigh more than heterosexual women, which
may explain the higher rates of heart disease.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the panel noted, lesbians tend to visit their
doctors less frequently, either because they fear discrimination or
they are less likely to have health insurance because lesbians
generally cannot share spousal benefits. Managed care often limits
women's ability to choose lesbian-friendly providers.
</P>
<P>
   Lesbian leaders have cheered the report's publication. ``This
will be a wonderful resource,'' said Dr. Jocelyn White, co-editor
in chief of The Journal of the Gay and Lesbian Medical Association.
The Institute of Medicine, which is the nongovernmental health
policy arm of the National Academy of Sciences, conducted the study
for the National Institutes of Health, which provided financing.
</P>
<P>
   The report calls for more research on lesbian health and on ways
to improve lesbians' access to care. It also urges researchers
studying women's issues to include questions about sexual
orientation in study designs.
</P>
<P>
   _ DAVID FRANCE &QR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
