<HEADER>
A7937 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-MOORE-COLUMN19-CO     01-18 0582
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-MOORE-COLUMN19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    In Denver, Broncos season just as 'magical'
 &HT;    By Terence Moore
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ Around the Rockies, they don't care about that Southern
fairy tale. They know about those in Suwanee, Ga., rallying around
Dan Reeves' heart. They've seen that Dirty Bird thing. They also
realize teams rising from nothing to something in a hurry such as
the Atlanta Falcons always receive the public's hugs and kisses.
</P>
<P>
   Still, none of that matters to those partial to the Denver
Broncos. They suggest ``Orange Crush'' was the rage long before
there was the flapping of imaginary wings with the fluttering of
feet.
</P>
<P>
   As for Reeves' heart, well, it's like this: Been there, done
that. They had the heart of the Falcons coach, along with his mind,
body and soul for a dozen years when he ran the Broncos through the
1992 season. They saw Reeves push the Broncos to five AFC West
titles, four trips to the AFC Championship Game and three Super
Bowl appearances.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the only thing they really care about these days is the
Broncos' current season. Just like that of the Falcons, it has
featured enough pretty moments along the way to the Super Bowl to
make linebacker Bill Romanowski gush, ``This is a magical team.''
</P>
<P>
   That's funny. That's what many say about the Falcons, but they
say so about the Broncos in these parts for different reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the season, Jason Elam reached the NFL record book by
tying Tom Dempsey with a 63-yard field goal. Terrell Davis was
named the league's Most Valuable Player after rushing for 2,008
yards.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was John Elway, always the people's choice. He moved
his career passing yards over 50,000. Not only that, he continued
to prosper under the speculation that this is his 16th and final
season.
</P>
<P>
   So it comes down to the following: Which is the biggest catalyst
for a world championship? Reeves' heart or Elway's farewell?
</P>
<P>
   Tough call.
</P>
<P>
   Well, not for the Broncos. They did the impossible Sunday by
playing so poorly against the New York Jets in the AFC Championship
Game that they silenced the eternal screamers inside packed Mile
High Stadium. The Broncos trailed 10-0 moments into the third
quarter, and the Jets gathered even more momentum after a blocked
punt.
</P>
<P>
   Then Elway walked into the Broncos' huddle. Right tackle Harry
Swayne smiled, saying, ``There was a little more oomph in his
inflection after (they blocked the punt). John Elway has had so
many comebacks that we didn't see why 10 points would fluster
him.''
</P>
<P>
   It didn't, not with the Broncos racing to a 23-10 victory on
Elway's arm and Davis' legs.
</P>
<P>
   Just so you know, the Broncos are chasing the ghosts of potent
NFL teams of the 1990s. The Dallas Cowboys won three Super Bowls in
five years. The San Francisco 49ers took Super Bowl XXIX and
appeared in three consecutive NFC Championship Games. The Green Bay
Packers won a world title after reaching two Super Bowls and three
NFC Championship Games.
</P>
<P>
   By handling the Jets, the Broncos joined the 49ers as the only
NFL team ever to win 45 games over a three-year stretch.
</P>
<P>
   By handling the Falcons, the Broncos would become only the sixth
team to win back-to-back Super Bowls.
</P>
<P>
   The Broncos also would answer our previous questions about fate.
</P>
<P>
   Terence Moore writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga. E-mail: tlmajc(AT)aol.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
