<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-BRAZIL-$ADV24-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHY ECO-TOURISTS ARE SHUNNING BRAZIL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Jan. 24)  
 (bl)  
 By DIANA JEAN SCHEMO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil _ Blessed with a rain forest the size of
Western Europe, wetlands where rivers magically swell from 300
yards to 37 miles in the rainy season, and a dazzling string of
waterfalls in the south, Brazil would seem to be a natural magnet
for ecologically driven travelers. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In fact, it was not long ago that eco-tourism represented the
great hope of Brazilian environmentalists and tour operators: they
hoped to show business interests that doing the right thing by
leaving rain forests and wilderness intact could pay. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But nature travel in Brazil has failed to take off as once
expected, say tourism experts here, and instead has declined
steadily through the 1990s. While Costa Rica and other Latin
American countries have captured the imagination of nature lovers,
such travelers have been bypassing Brazil, where the
accommodations, infrastructure and expertise come up short. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Statistics are scarce, but Roberto Mourao, president of the
Brazilian Ecotourism Association, estimates that over the last
decade, eco-tourism has fallen by half, driven down by failures on
the part of government and the tourism industry to build on the
surging interest in the environment with well-prepared programs for
tourists.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A recent survey of environmental attractions by the Ecotourism
Institute of Brazil found serious obstacles throughout the country,
from lack of road signs to poor accommodations and ill-trained
guides.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The Amazon has a name that seduces people, so you don't have
to position your product, but there are other problems,'' Mourao
said. About 70 percent of tourists to the Amazon want to see
wildlife, he said, but the Amazon is a dense forest where days or
weeks may pass without any sightings of animals or rare birds.
Guides may know less than amateur bird watchers or animal lovers
who have traveled thousands of miles for a glimpse of a rare or
beautiful creature.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Brazil is laced with natural wonders. Its rain forest alone
would cover half the continental United States. The Amazon contains
20 percent of the world's fresh water supply. Unspoiled, fauna and
flora seem to spill over each other from every bit of soil and
bark, and tropical parrots, toucans and other birds flit through
the lush landscape. The string of waterfalls at Iguacu in the south
was the backdrop for the 1986 movie ``The Mission.'' And the
80,000-square-mile Pantanal, the world's largest wetland, is
prolific in wildlife. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In a sense, the problem may have its roots in successful
marketing. Brazil began promoting its ecological wonders without
first creating the infrastructure necessary to receive tourists.
Rare is the hotel outside a major city that will accept
international credit cards, for example. Nor was much market
research done to discover what eco-tourists were after. Often,
Mourao said, tourists reach a remote destination for a prepaid
one-week stay and end up stranded at a rustic inn without enough
programs to explore their surroundings. Though travel agents say
foreigners represent 95 to 98 percent of those who visit the Amazon
or the Pantanal, Brazil's two major eco-tourism destinations, most
guides there speak little or no English, French or German.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Renato Riedel, the head of Hotel Partners, which represents a
number of regional hotels and tour boats that ply the Amazon, said
that tourism was down 15 percent over the last two years. El Nino
dried up parts of the rain forest last winter, lowering the water
level of rivers and spreading fires to parts of virgin forest.
``With that, people left and said, `Shoot, this Amazon is
terrible,''' Riedel said. ``And word spreads.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The dramatic economic downturn that began last year, he added,
is also responsible for reducing eco-tourism, which is usually more
expensive in Brazil than in smaller countries. He also noted that
Brazil's extremes of wealth and poverty _ among the most dramatic
in the world _ make tourists particularly vulnerable to crime, from
assaults on the beaches to hotel operators who add fraudulent
charges to credit card bills. ``All of that contributes to leaving
us behind when it comes to eco-tourism,'' Riedel said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The destinations of environmental tourists are usually remote
specks on the map, but foreigners inevitably spend some time in Rio
de Janeiro or other cities, and leave shocked by the piles of
houses crammed into the hillside slums and the general lack of
hygiene. When it rains, the raw sewage overflows into the Atlantic
Ocean in Rio, leaving what the Brazilians call a ``black tongue''
of waste along the water's edge.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Brazil's eco-tourism also suffers because of the country's size
and the expense of domestic travel. For $1,000, the cost of some
bargain packages covering air fare and hotel, a New Yorker can
spend a week on the beaches of Costa Rica, with a jaunt into the
rain forest. Depending on your departure date, the same amount
would just cover the coach air fare to Manaus, but would not be
enough for the fare to Rio plus the $500 bargain air pass for
domestic travel (available only abroad) to more remote airports in
the Amazon or the Pantanal. Once there, the tourist may still face
an expensive charter flight or cab ride. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The environment, Riedel said, is a ``natural patrimony that
Brazil has, and it's the best in the world . . . a tremendous
potential that's not being exploited.''
</P>
</TEXT>
