<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 17:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7942 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-BRONCOS19-COX     01-18 0821
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-BRONCOS19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Broncos confident of putting stop to Falcons run game
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ Only four times in 18 games this season has Atlanta
Falcons tailback Jamal Anderson failed to gain at least 88 yards
rushing. That number _ ``the double eights'' as Denver Broncos
defensive tackle Keith Traylor referred to it Monday _ is
significant for another reason as well.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last four games, the final two of the regular season
and a pair of victories in the playoffs, it represents the total
rushing yards surrendered by the Denver defense. In those four
contests, opponents had a combined 67 carries for a microscopic
average of 1.3 yards per attempt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stopping the run is something we have a lot of confidence in,
because it's something we have done all year,'' Denver middle
linebacker Glenn Cadrez said after the Broncos' 23-10 victory in
the AFC championship game on Sunday. ``The way we have been
playing, teams have to throw the ball 50 times and complete 40 of
them, (because) they're not going to beat us on the ground. That's
just the way it's been.''
</P>
<P>
   New York Jets tailback Curtis Martin was the latest victim. He
logged 13 attempts on Sunday and finished with a puny 14 yards.
Excluding his 1-yard touchdown run early in the third quarter,
eight of Martin's 13 rushes netted 1 yard or less and his longest
run was for only 4 yards. One week earlier, in a 38-3 romp over
Miami, the Denver defense also limited Dolphins backs to 14 yards
on 13 carries.
</P>
<P>
   Take away a 12-yard run by Miami backup Bernie Parmalee and the
Broncos allowed an average gain of less than two feet per rush.
</P>
<P>
   Against the Dolphins, the rushing totals were a bit skewed,
because Denver sprinted to an early 14-0 lead and effectively
forced Miami to abandon the rushing game. But in a first half on
Sunday that was scoreless until the final play before intermission,
the typically hard-running Martin managed just 11 yards on eight
rushes.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a man matched up on me everywhere I went,'' said
Martin, who in his career has just 101 yards in four games against
Denver. ``They pursued the ball really well and they wrapped up.
They just didn't hit, they made tackles.''
</P>
<P>
   It has been quite a transformation for a Denver run defense that
last year was arguably the worst ever to advance to a Super Bowl.
The Broncos statistically ranked No. 16 in the league versus the
run. Opponents averaged 4.7 yards per rush, the worst number in the
NFL, and the highest ever for a Super Bowl champion.
</P>
<P>
   Despite losing run-stuffing middle linebacker Allen Aldridge to
free agency during the offseason, and inserting second-year tackle
Trevor Pryce into the lineup, the Broncos jumped all the way to No.
3 in run defense this season.
</P>
<P>
   The journeyman Cadrez has been better than coaches anticipated
in replacing Aldridge and, like outside linebackers John Mobley
(weakside) and Bill Romanowski (strongside), is very active. Pryce
likewise has played well and Traylor over the last several years
has been an unheralded inside anchor. The Broncos may play a bit
more one-gap than they did in the past, but their signature under
coordinator Greg Robinson has been as a quick and penetrating front
that tries to surround the ball.
</P>
<P>
   The frenetic Romanowski, who had a game-high 11 tackles on
Sunday, plays off blocks well and Mobley (nine tackles) is one of
the NFL's most athletic linebackers.
</P>
<P>
   Denver has been most impressive stuffing opponents on first
down. In their postseason victories, the Broncos held the Dolphins
and the Jets to 8 yards total on 14 first-down rushes. As a result,
the two teams averaged 7.8 yards-to-make on third downs and they
converted on just five of 22.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're not going to (sustain) many drives when it's always
third-and-8,'' said New York quarterback Vinny Testaverde.
</P>
<P>
   The Broncos' success aside, they have not faced a back as good
as Anderson all season. The Atlanta star saw a lot of eight-man
fronts on Sunday, when Minnesota defensive coordinator Foge Fazio
kept bringing strong safety Robert Griffith on run-dogs. He may
face a similar strategy in Super Bowl XXXIII, but the Broncos
acknowledged on Sunday evening that they'll have to tackle
extremely well against the Falcons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anderson is a runner who will rip your arms right out of the
sockets if you don't wrap him up,'' said Pryce. ``From what I've
seen, you don't arm-tackle that guy. You have to get a lot of
people around him and force him to run laterally if you can. It's
going to be one of our biggest challenges.''
</P>
<P>
   SUPER BOWL XXXIII
</P>
<P>
   _ Who: Atlanta Falcons vs. Denver Broncos.
</P>
<P>
   _ When: 6:18 p.m., Sunday, Jan. 31.
</P>
<P>
   _ Where: Pro Player Stadium, Miami.
</P>
<P>
   _ TV: Fox.
</P>
<P>
   _ Records: Falcons 16-2, Broncos 16-2.
</P>
<P>
   _ Line: Broncos by 7.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
