<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 17:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7947 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-HURRICANE-RECO     01-18 0837
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-HURRICANE-RECOVER-$ADV24-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HURRICANE MITCH SPARED KEY TOURISM AREAS 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, Jan. 24.) 
(ms) 
 By LARRY ROHTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GUATEMALA _ Hurricane Mitch has come and gone, but the damage
wrought by the most devastating natural disaster to strike Central
America this century will take years to repair. The pattern of
destruction throughout the region was capricious, however, meaning
that some areas were pummeled while others were barely touched, if
at all. So here is a quick assessment for potential visitors:
</P>
<P>
   The two nations most severely affected by the storm, which at
its peak in late October had winds of more than 180 miles an hour,
were Honduras and Nicaragua. Most of the 10,000 people estimated to
have been killed by Mitch died in those countries, which also bore
the brunt of the $3 billion in damage to property and
infrastructure in the region.
</P>
<P>
   But even in those two countries the devastation was hardly
generalized. In Nicaragua, damage was concentrated in the far
northwest, well off the tourist track, while in Honduras, the
capital, Tegucigalpa, was ravaged but important tourist sites such
as the Maya ruins at Copan were not affected. As a result, tourism
officials in neighboring countries now complain that the entire
region has been unjustly tarred by the travails of a relatively
limited area.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hurricane Mitch did not really hit us, other than some damage
to docks and some beach erosion on the outer islands,'' said
Valerie Woods, director of the Belize Tourist Board. ``The real
damage we have suffered is a result of people lumping us together
with Honduras and Nicaragua and thinking we were wiped out, which
unfortunately has led to some reservations being canceled.''
</P>
<P>
   At the opposite end of the Central American isthmus, hundreds of
miles away from the path of the hurricane, Costa Rica and Panama
suffered even less damage: minor flooding and a bit of debris when
the storm was still far out at sea and before it turned inland from
the Gulf of Honduras, but no harm to infrastructure. In El
Salvador, the storm killed more than 240 people and wreaked havoc
with roads and agriculture; the damage was mostly in the eastern
third of the country, where foreign visitors rarely venture.
</P>
<P>
   Guatemala's situation is more complicated. President Alvaro Arzu
decreed a state of national emergency, which was lifted earlier
this month, and later said that, though the death toll was much
lower than that of the 1976 earthquake, material damage caused by
Mitch was higher. Nearly 100 bridges were destroyed or damaged,
most of them in the departments of Zacapa and Chiquimula, which
border Honduras and are often used as staging points for day trips
to Copan.
</P>
<P>
   By year's end, though, much of the damage had been repaired and
traffic was back to normal, most notably on sections of the
Pan-American Highway west from Guatemala City toward the Mexican
border. That means visitors to Lake Atitlan and its surrounding
volcanoes, or to Chichicastenango and other popular market towns in
highland areas such as the Quiche, should not have to endure
anything other than the usual delays. Weather in the highlands has
been unusually cold, though, with overnight temperatures in the 30s
in the wake of the storm.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, the route from Guatemala City northward to
the Peten still has delays for repairs and one-lane pontoon bridges
where permanent bridges were washed out, according to tour
operators and bus lines. Even in the best of times, the route is a
long, slow trek _ some of it on paved roads, but other long
stretches on rugged surfaces. But the airport at Flores, in the
heart of the Peten, is operating normally, and no hotels in the
jungle region were damaged by the storm, whose path across
Guatemala took it parallel to the Pacific coast in the far south.
</P>
<P>
   Neighboring Belize, also part of the popular Ruta Maya (a
circuit of archeological sites in Mexico, Guatemala, Honduras and
Belize), took only a glancing blow, largely confined to offshore
areas such as Ambergris Cay and the Turneffe Islands. But even
there, damage was mostly cosmetic: The Belize Hotel Association
says that only one of its members, on Glover's Atoll, was forced to
close even temporarily, but notes that overall bookings were off
about 8 percent in November and December because of lingering
concern over the storm's impact.
</P>
<P>
   In a perverse way, Mitch may actually have benefited the diving
aficionados who flock to the Bay Islands of Honduras and the many
keys, atolls and reefs just off mainland Belize. While a few
denizens of the deep such as sea fans and tube sponges were hurt,
sea life as a whole has been invigorated and the overall marine
environment cleansed. The storm swept some silt buildup from the
reefs and everything looks a little cleaner, said Hugh Parkey,
owner of the Belize Dive Connection in Belize City. ``It's like
someone took a giant feather duster and dusted it off,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
