<HEADLINE>
RUFF TO ARGUE DEFENSE CASE IN CLINTON'S IMPEACHMENT TRIAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JUDY HOLLAND and JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN  
 &HT;     c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ White House Counsel Charles F.C. Ruff is expected
to delve into the facts of President Clinton's relationship with
Monica Lewinsky when White House lawyers begin their defense case
Tuesday at the president's Senate trial.
</P>
<P>
   The strategy is likely to increase the likelihood that the
Senate will call witnesses later this month so that the lawmakers
can try and decide whose version to believe.
</P>
<P>
   Ruff, 59, a widely respected veteran of Washington legal circles
who served as the fourth and final Watergate special prosecutor
from 1975 to 1977, is scheduled to be the sole White House lawyer
to speak Tuesday when the trial resumes at 1 p.m. EST.
</P>
<P>
   The House prosecutors are hard pressed to persuade two-thirds of
the Senate to impeach the president, but it appears increasingly
likely that the Senate will vote to hear from witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Minority Leader Thomas Daschle acknowledged Monday that
witnesses ``may be inevitable.'' Daschle said he believes witnesses
are unnecessary but conceded the political momentum was moving
toward having some witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   After House prosecutors wrapped up their three days of
presentations Saturday, many Republican senators said they hoped to
see the White House dispute the facts laid out by the House
prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's incumbent upon the president or the president's attorneys
to show where these facts are wrong,'' said Sen. Orrin Hatch,
R-Utah. ``They are going to have to explain why this isn't perjury,
why this isn't obstruction of justice.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If all they do is come in here and say the bar has to be very,
very high, we all know that,'' Hatch added. ``It's phony to (state)
that this doesn't rise to the level of impeachment.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Gordon Smith, R-Ore., also said he was waiting to see White
House lawyers address the evidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to see if the tight web the House managers have woven
can be torn by the White House,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   White House Press Secretary Joe Lockhart continued the defense
attack on any plan to bring witnesses to the trial, saying such a
step would ``only extend and delay this process.'' Many of them
have already been deposed and testified over 20 times, Lockhart
complained, and ``asking them to do it one more time is not likely
to provide any new or shocking revelations in the case.''
</P>
<P>
   Ruff, who was U.S. attorney in Washington from 1979 to 1982,
uses a wheelchair because of a paralyzing disease he caught when
visiting Africa as a young man.
</P>
<P>
   His presentation will be an overview that will launch three days
of White House attacks against the prosecution's case, arguing the
facts, the law and the Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   White House spokesman Jim Kennedy said the defense team expects
to attack what he said was the House prosecutors'
``mischaracterizations of the evidence in the record.''
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy said House prosecutors ``painted a false picture'' by
``taking things from the record out of context.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that if you look at the full record and the
testimony in context it will become clear that the allegations
don't hold up,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   House prosecutors last week accused the president of plotting to
get Lewinsky, the former White House intern, to file a false
affidavit in the Paul Corbin Jones sexual misconduct lawsuit and to
cover up their relationship by hiding gifts that Clinton had given
to Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   House prosecutors also said the president helped find a job for
Lewinsky in exchange for her silence and tried to illegally
influence the testimony of other witnesses. They also claim the
president lied to the grand jury about his relationship with
Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart expressed confidence that, at the end of the three days
of defense argument, ``people will have a different view of the
case that's been laid out and the facts that have been laid before
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart said Ruff will point out that the president
acknowledged to the grand jury that he had an inappropriate
relationship with Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somehow that message hasn't gotten out there,'' Lockhart said.
</P>
</TEXT>
