<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Leap from wide bodies to well bodies appeals to RoeckBy Scott
Thurston
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ There's life after airlines for Tom Roeck, even if
it's not with a wide-bodied corporation.
</P>
<P>
   The former Delta Air Lines Inc. chief financial officer,
jettisoned along with other top executives in the management
overhaul at Atlanta's biggest employer, has landed with a small but
growing health care firm that blends business and altruism.
</P>
<P>
   Roeck is ``executive committee chair'' at Chamberlin Edmonds &AMP;
Associates, which helps hospitals convert uninsured patients into
Medicaid or Medicare recipients. The business focuses on two goals:
boost the hospitals' bottom lines and help patients get coverage
for better treatments.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea of doing well by doing good has great appeal,'' said
Roeck, still looking corporate in a crisp button-down and striped
tie during an interview at the firm's Buckhead office.
</P>
<P>
   Roeck is chief strategic and financial advisor to Chamberlin
Edmonds owner and CEO Judy Starkey, who started the firm in 1986.
She had the idea after navigating the health care maze to get
treatment for her autistic son.
</P>
<P>
   Starkey said Roeck, who has a two-year contract, adds
``tremendous long-range vision and expertise'' to her firm, which
employs about 180 people.
</P>
<P>
   Chamberlin Edmonds has hospital clients in 11 states and plans a
rapid national expansion, Roeck said. It collected about $100
million in Medicaid and Medicare funds for hospitals last year and
got a percentage of that in fees. Patients pay nothing for the help
they get.
</P>
<P>
   Roeck is no stranger to health-related causes. He chairs AID
Atlanta's finance committee, has worked for the United Way on
children's health-care projects and is on the board of Mission New
Hope, which fights drug abuse.
</P>
<P>
   Upon leaving Delta in late 1997, where he made $490,000 in
salary and bonus in his last full year, Roeck could afford to take
his time assessing his future and begin it with a small company.
</P>
<P>
   He still closely follows events at Delta and betrays no
bitterness about the management shakeup. He praises the airline's
chief executive, Leo Mullin, who arrived in mid-1997 and replaced
Roeck a few months later. Mullin has since eased out other
old-guard Delta executives; so far Roeck is the only one who's
emerged with another company.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Leo's done a terrific job recruiting some terrific
people,'' Roeck said.
</P>
<P>
   Roeck said he got along with Mullin initially, but added:
``There comes a point when you get the feeling the chemistry just
isn't there....it was just one of those things.'' After the ax
fell, he said, Mullin ``was very gracious throughout the process.''
</P>
<P>
   He's less forthcoming about his relationship with former Delta
CEO Ronald Allen, whom Mullin replaced. One story had it that a
quiet move by Allen to sack Roeck without board approval was one of
the flashpoints that led to Allen's forced early retirement.
</P>
<P>
   Allen remains in Atlanta but hasn't given interviews about his
departure. In light of that, ``it wouldn't be fair for me to
speculate on what I might have had to do with it,'' said Roeck.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not think it was a knee-jerk reaction to any one event,''
he said, adding he has had only one chance meeting with Allen since
both left the airline.
</P>
<P>
   But Roeck worked closely with Allen in the early 1990s as Delta
lurched into an international expansion that coincided with a deep
industry downturn. ``When we got into 1992 and started losing the
kind of money we were, I didn't expect that,'' Roeck said, adding
that his finance department raised $3.6 billion in capital just to
sustain the airline's daily operations over an 18-month period.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994 management imposed layoffs and cutbacks that finally
restored profits but sapped morale and created service problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did the best we could and had to make a lot of tradeoffs,''
said Roeck. He added management knew service might suffer but
underestimated the impact of staff cuts in customer-contact areas.
</P>
<P>
   Some blame the troubles on a 1991 move to buy bankrupt Pan Am's
Europe routes and absorb 7,800 of its workers in the midst of a
recession. By some accounts, Roeck opposed Allen's pursuit of the
deal, but that isn't true, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I could say I knew all along how it would turn out. I
was an active supporter of the Pan Am deal. The industry was in
turmoil and these routes were being offered up and they were vital
to establishing a position in Europe,'' he said. Roeck said he
believed _ wrongly, it turned out _ that the best part of the deal
was Pan Am's Frankfurt, Germany, hub, while its New York operations
were questionable. Delta has since dismantled the Frankfurt hub and
built up overseas flights from the Kennedy Airport gateway.
</P>
<P>
   Roeck is aware some Delta workers and customers will always
blame the old management team for tarnishing the company's culture
and service commitment. But he takes an upbeat view. ``The way I
look at it, the airline industry in general went through a very
difficult period. All of us can be proud we got the company through
it in fairly good order, considering the pressures on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
