<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRACTICAL-TRAVELER-2TAKES-$ADV24-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRETCH MARKET FOR LIMOUSINES  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JAN. 24) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.J., Mass., Fla.)   (af)  
 By BETSY WADE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The passengers in those limousines are not all haughty film
stars sipping Cosmopolitan cocktails. In the last few weeks, I
heard about a Halloween birthday party where 15 costumed
8-year-olds had a ball riding to a New York restaurant in a maximo
limousine.
</P>
<P>
   A friend, at loggerheads with a son about who would drive the
second car needed to get seven people to Connecticut for Christmas
dinner, hired a stretch limo for the whole group for $240 each way
and was delighted with the trip and the sociability.
</P>
<P>
   Even I, after years as a limo shunner, have at last seen the
inside of a super stretch. At the travel agents' convention in Los
Angeles in October, a hotel organization sent a long white limo to
take a group of us to a reception.
</P>
<P>
   Lacking an alternative, I climbed aboard with nine others: three
facing front, two facing back and five along the side. I have since
learned that this was probably a 120-inch stretch, meaning that the
sedan had been cut apart and 10 more feet of car inserted in the
middle.
</P>
<P>
   If 8-year-olds and people like me, who are neither getting
married nor going to a prom, are riding in limousines, it dawned on
me that things must have undergone a radical change. And indeed
they have.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Kosman, president of 1-800-Limo-Center, a new national
network of companies with headquarters in Rochelle Park, N.J., said
there has been an explosion in the chauffeured-car business in the
last two to three years.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was young, a limo was something of a luxury,'' he said.
``Today the corporate world has realized it is the most
cost-effective way to get around. If a $500,000-a-year executive is
flying to someplace to close a $10 million deal, it does not make
sense for him to get a rental car, figure out where he's going,
drive there, find a parking place and walk in wilted.'' He said
that estimates in the business, which is quite fragmented, put
annual growth at 11 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine Limousine and Chauffeured Transportation, published
in Torrance, Calif., reports that nationally 65 percent of company
operators reported average revenue increases of 29 percent last
year; 6 percent reported a decline, the rest level revenues.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine's editor, Sara Eastwood-McLean, said that companies
now tend to buy each other out so that after 13 years of growth or
stability in the total number of companies, 1998 saw a decline from
9,600 operators to 9,100.
</P>
<P>
   Scott A. Solombrino, president of Dav El Chauffeured
Transportation Network, with headquarters in Chelsea, Mass., said
his company has grown an average of 28 percent a year for five
years. The worldwide fleet, he said, totals 10,400 vehicles. Like
Kosman, he said that corporate business was powering the expansion,
particularly businesses' belief that resources were being wasted
when executives were using rental cars.
</P>
<P>
   ``The second big force is the advent of the female executive,''
Solombrino said. ``A company knows it is incurring a liability if a
female CEO arrives in Dallas at 11 p.m. and takes a cab to the
hotel. They have demanded the use of chauffeured cars, and pretty
soon everyone in the company begins to see the value of protecting
all executives. Women executives are our best clients.''
</P>
<P>
   A third factor he cited was an out-of-control economy, saying
that the same prosperity that was soaking up the first-class and
business-class airline seats was causing car-service fleets to
expand on the double. Right now, with gasoline prices way down, the
companies are doing well and can expand. But, Solombrino said, he
was not sure that growth would stay at 28 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
   Dav El is business-oriented, he said: Less than 5 percent of its
volume involves proms, weddings, nights on the town or gambling
expeditions. In any case, he said, not many cars are sitting in the
parking lot on Saturday and Sunday: Weekend corporate business has
tripled in five years because so many companies now hold meetings
over the weekend to take advantage of lower air fares.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, according to Limousine and Chauffeured
Transportation magazine, corporate business accounted for 24
percent of the operators' income last year, airport trips 22
percent and weddings 20 percent. In 1996, corporate business was at
19 percent, airport trips 23 percent and weddings 24 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Corporate clients use black sedans, most often Lincoln Town
Cars, rather than the extra-long babies seen at Oscar night or prom
time. On Christmas Day, when three of us needed to get from Captiva
Island, Fla., to Fort Myers, and local taxis were not available,
employees at the marina recommended Royal Palm Luxury Car Service.
</P>
<P>
   A comfortable black Town Car driven by the small company's
president, Anthony Paolercio, who had a career at IBM and left New
York three years ago, scooped us up. He packed our luggage into the
big trunk, recommended a place to buy oranges to take home, and
three of us glided to our meeting spot for $75. We asked him to
recommend a service as smooth and reliable as his elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   That was difficult, he said, and limo people agree, because if a
recommended company proves a lemon, this could alienate a longtime
customer from the original car service. So Royal Palm is part of
still another of the growing number of limo networks: Empire
International, in Norwood, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   It is headed by David Seelinger, who owns the part of the
company serving New York, New Jersey and Connecticut, and has
affiliates in 250 cities worldwide. It is growing so rapidly that
the telephone message that played spoke of 100 cities, which
Seelinger said was only a year out of date.
</P>
<P>
   The listings under Limousine Service cover most of nine pages in
the Manhattan Yellow Pages, and almost four more pages of listings,
some duplicates, appear under Car Service. It's pretty easy to tell
which companies have contracts with corporations and law firms
(clients use vouchers rather than cash) just by looking at the tags
in the limo windows outside big office buildings, especially late
at night on Wall Street. But the profusion of choices for the
individual consumer means that a network or a trade name is a big
help.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   That is how 1-800-Limo-Center got into the business in July,
Kosman said. After months of travel and checking into existing
services in other cities, he said he was trying to think how to
market directly to customers. He decided that 1-800-Flowers was the
model to follow, and eventually he got American Express to be his
``messenger'' and put his leaflets into customer mailings.
</P>
<P>
   Like the two other networks discussed here _ and there are
doubtless others _ Limo Center takes reservations and credit card
numbers and then bills the client for everything, including tip, so
no cash is needed at the time of the ride.
</P>
<P>
   The networks have varying prices and ways to respond to
foul-ups, particularly cars that do not show up, but networks'
basic response is to cancel the charge. Clients who do not find
their cars waiting call the 800 number, according to the operators,
and another car is dispatched if need be.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the network system, in a city like New York, when law
firms and similar businesses have contracts with limo companies,
they may not be able to fulfill a request if the weather turns bad,
or it is a major holiday.
</P>
<P>
   The big networks use airline computer systems to find out if the
flights they are meeting will be severely delayed. These companies
have access to buses for large groups, and also have minibuses with
conference tables for business groups that want to work on the way.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some details on the three networks.
</P>
<P>
   1-800-Limo-Center is the company's name, and the 24-hour number
translates to (800) 546-6236. The company started in July, and
headquarters are at 336 West Passaic Street, Rochelle Park, N.J.
07662. It operates in the top 150 airports in the country through
its links to 200 companies, 190 in the United States and the rest
in London, Paris, Rome and Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Prices are based on distance, which is determined by a computer
program showing ZIP codes. These rates are quoted on the phone; a
sheet of sample rates shows a trip from O'Hare Airport in Chicago
to a downtown address in the 60618 ZIP code starts at $44 for a
trip in a sedan, $74 in a 6-passenger limo and $94 in an 8- to
10-passenger limo. To Evanston, Ill., the rates are $40, $70 and
$90.
</P>
<P>
   To these rates, the company adds a 15 percent tip for a sedan
(20 percent for longer cars) and a 10 percent processing fee. For
domestic flights, the first 30 minutes of waiting time after the
posted arrival is free. There is a $15 charge for meeting
international flights, but no further charges for waiting time.
</P>
<P>
   There is a 15-minute grace period for non-airport pickups. The
additional charge for each 15 minutes of waiting time is $11 for
sedans and $15 for limos.
</P>
<P>
   If the car does not show up in 15 minutes, the customer must
call the 800 number; if no car then responds, this call avoids a
no-show charge, which is the cost of the trip, the tip and waiting
time. If the car never does show up, the cost of alternative
transportation is paid by the company. Cancellations not made two
hours or more in advance incur a charge of $44 for a sedan, $60 for
a limousine.
</P>
<P>
   Dav El Chauffeured Transportation Network, 200 Second Street,
Chelsea, Mass. 02150, operates in 458 cities, 284 of them in the
United States. The toll-free number is (800) 922-0343. Reservations
may be made by phone, fax or Internet, and travel agents can reach
the company on Apollo or Sabre reservation systems. The company
approves customers' credit and opens an account.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States and Canada, the company uses standard
indexed hourly prices, which Solombrino says represent a national
average. These are below the market rate in New York, he said,
although they may be above elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   A sedan costs $49 an hour, plus 15 percent tip. An 80-inch
stretch Lincoln, holding seven people (six in two back seats, one
in the front passenger seat) costs $63 an hour, plus 20 percent
tip. An executive van for nine people with a table costs $63 plus a
15 percent tip. A regular passenger van for 15 people is $63 an
hour, plus 15 percent. Waiting time costs the same as driving time.
</P>
<P>
   Empire International, 55 Walnut Street, Norwood, N.J. 07648,
(800) 451-5466, operates in 250 cities through a licensing
arrangement. Outside the New York three-state area, it uses
regional prices based on a computer program that gives the
distance. In Chicago, for example, the trip from O'Hare to ZIP code
60618 would cost $80 in a sedan, plus a 15 percent tip. The same
trip by limo or van would be $115 plus 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In smaller cities, the price is a minimum of $100, which is the
two-hour minimum at $50 an hour, plus 15 percent. The company will
establish individual accounts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
