<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 17:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7953 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GPCO-COX     01-18 0827
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GPCO-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Genuine Parts growth lag an incentive for changes
 &HT;    By Robert Luke
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Companies, like cars, eventually need a tuneup.
</P>
<P>
   That's what Genuine Parts is getting, in hopes of reigniting
double-digit sales and earnings growth in its slow-growing but
highly profitable distribution businesses.
</P>
<P>
   The company, best known for its NAPA Auto Parts outlets, last
year embarked on a $600 million acquisition spree to boost market
share in its auto and industrial replacement parts businesses, and
in its office supply unit. It also added a business segment by
buying a distributor of electrical and electronic equipment with
annual sales of $500 million.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Larry L. Prince, chairman and chief executive,
predicts sales and earnings growth will return to double-digit
levels, something the 71-year-old company hasn't seen since 1994.
Sales could increase as much as 20 percent this year, he said. But
profits probably won't return to double-digit levels until 2000.
</P>
<P>
   More acquisitions could be on the way, financed either with
cash, stock or a combination. The company has strong cash flow and
a solid balance sheet with modest debt.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt that we could have a certain amount of market-share
gains in our current markets,'' said Prince, 60. ``But to really
get to double-digit sales growth, we really would have to make some
acquisitions.''
</P>
<P>
   That epiphany came about two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought we were poised to hit double-digit (sales) growth
in 1997, but as the year progressed, we saw that business was
slower and tougher,'' Prince said.
</P>
<P>
   That took a toll on the company's stock, which has lagged the
benchmark Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index, of which it is a
member. Last year Genuine Parts' stock lost 1.47 percent of its
value. Over the past five years, it gained 33.3 percent. In
contrast, the S&AMP;P 500 appreciated 26.7 percent last year and 163.5
percent over five years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shareholder value certainly is one of our reasons for
recognizing the need to grow,'' said Prince, who has been chief
executive since 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the performance of its shares, Genuine Parts has
compiled an enviable record: Sales are up 49 years in a row.
Profits are up 38 consecutive years. The company has consistently
met its target of at least a 20 percent return on beginning-of-the
year shareholders' equity.
</P>
<P>
   But sales growth of its biggest business _ distributing auto
replacement parts _ has slowed to 3 percent to 5 percent annually,
in part because of better-made vehicles. Profit margins have shrunk
from a peak 12 percent in 1989 to 10.6 percent in 1997, largely
because of increased competition, which has limited price
increases.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, management has been trying to jump-start that
segment, which this year is expected to account for just over half
of Genuine Parts' total revenue of $8 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The company took several steps. It changed its NAPA Auto Parts
stores to become more retail friendly. The refurbished stores, with
extended hours and increased inventory, saw profits increase 5
percent to 8 percent on sales growth of 10 percent to 15 percent,
according to Jerry Nix, senior vice president of finance.
</P>
<P>
   Do-it-yourselfers now account for 40 percent of the company's
auto parts sales, up from 30 percent five years ago. Professional
installers account for the rest.
</P>
<P>
   The latter is a growing market, considering the complexity of
today's vehicles. To strengthen that business, the company started
a program that provides access to national advertising and business
support to a network of more than 8,600 independently owned repair
shops.
</P>
<P>
   To widen its distribution channels further, Genuine Parts this
month completed the acquisition of a company that last year sold
$120 million worth of parts to large fleets and new car dealers.
And it acquired its Canadian partner, which has annual sales of
$550 million.
</P>
<P>
   The managements of each business unit continue to hunt for
growth opportunities. For example, the office products group now
also distributes janitorial products.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the moves haven't helped Genuine Parts' stock price. It
finished Friday at $32.31 1/4, up 68 3/4 cents, on the New York
Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has to be shown that we're going to bring earnings along
with this sales growth,'' Prince said.
</P>
<P>
   Once that occurs, he thinks investors will give the stock a
richer price-to-earnings multiple. It now trades at 14.9 times
estimated 1999 earnings of $2.16 a share, according to IBES
International.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it would be the multiple of some of the newer
developing companies,'' Prince said. ``But if it moved to a 20
times earnings range, I don't think that would be out of the
question, provided we produce the earnings.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Luke writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
