<HEADLINE>
EXCHANGING CONFIDENCES WITH AN ELECTRONIC NEIGHBOR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., Ill, Maine., N.Y., Ore.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By JO THOMAS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the national radio ocean of wisecrack and punditry, canned
music, and network news, Delilah surfaces night after night with a
voice that is altogether different.
</P>
<P>
   From Los Angeles to Long Island, from Jacksonville, Fla., to
Bangor, Maine, the new queen of nighttime radio cuts through the
loneliness of traffic jams and dinner dishes, playing requests and
sharing stories and feelings, everything but her last name, with
listeners. She has 1.2 million a week, her syndicators say, and she
invites them to share, too. By the thousands, they do.
</P>
<P>
   On and off the air, she is the friendly next-door neighbor with
time to talk over a virtual backyard fence. She is no Dr. Laura
Schlessinger. (Delilah will be the first to say she is not a
counselor, licensed or otherwise.) But she is more than a disk
jockey taking dedications. And although digital technology helps
her sound local, her studio is in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Her two-year-old show is carried by 176 stations five evenings a
week from 7 to midnight, with a recorded reprise on Sundays. (In
the New York region, she is heard on WHUD-FM, 100.7; WLVG-FM, 96.1,
and WEBE-FM, 107.9.) She does the show live from 5 to 10 p.m.
Pacific time, filling in the first hour in the East with the last
hour from the previous day. The last two hours in the West are
tapes of the first two hours that evening.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the show, via tape, Delilah will give the local
station's call letters in her silken, best-friend voice. If the
station sends her the material, she may also tape comments on local
events, big and small.
</P>
<P>
   ``People guess it's not local because they hear the Southern
callers,'' concedes Jill Dedrick, who screens the calls. (Some
100,000 times a night, people try to get through.) Ms. Dedrick, 23,
talks to 150 callers each night and passes along the 25 who get on
the air. Most of them want to talk about love, good or bad, found
or lost, double dealt or sacrificed.
</P>
<P>
   Delilah tapes and edits their conversations, finds their
requests and puts them on the air.
</P>
<P>
   ``A woman called last night,'' Delilah said in a recent
telephone interview from home. ``She was a single parent. She had a
little boy, and she had been dating this guy. She loved him. Her
son loved him. But he told her he was moving out of state, and he
was not looking for a committed relationship. She asked me, `How do
I make him stay?'
</P>
<P>
   ``I told her: `You don't. He told you up front how he felt.' She
said, `But I love him.' I said: `He's made it clear he has a
different agenda. You've got to find someone with the same agenda.'
</P>
<P>
   ``She said, `If you play this song, will it change him?' and I
told her: `No, ma'am. This song will not change someone's mind.'
She said, `Will you tell him how much my son loves him?' And I
said: `No, it will only hurt your son. It will make him feel
abandoned.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Delilah, 38, has heard most of it before. She grew up in
Reedsport, Ore., she said, in a family of four children with an
alcoholic father and ``a classic, raging co-dependent'' mother.
``They had an abusive marriage, with a lot of physical violence,''
she recalled. She graduated from high school with honors, but left
home the night of her graduation party, after her parents locked
her out.
</P>
<P>
   At 21 ``I fell in love'' and married a black man, said Delilah,
who is white. They later had a son, and her mother invited the
couple to come home for Christmas. But when they stepped onto the
front porch, ``my father freaked out and jumped up and ran to the
gun closet,'' she said. ``He chased me off with a shotgun.'' He did
not apologize, she said, until a few days before he died in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   In junior high school, Delilah won a speech contest, reciting
the Gettysburg address. After the contest, the judges, who owned a
radio station, ``approached my folks and me and said, `Wow, she
likes to talk a lot.''' They offered her a chance to report school
news and sports several days a week. In high school, during a
work-study program, she learned to write copy, produce commercials
and read newscasts, and she worked in the station every weekend. In
college, she did traffic reports.
</P>
<P>
   ``I left home thinking I would escape the insanity,'' she said.
``Little did I know I would become the insanity. When you're raised
where deceit is the norm, you don't grow up normal. You develop
survival skills that numb the pain, but eventually end up killing
you.'' She had developed an eating disorder. ``Then I repeated my
parents' marriage.''
</P>
<P>
   When her son was 10 months old, Delilah's brother, who was to be
the child's godfather, and his wife were killed on the way to the
christening, their small plane crashing in the mountains. ``A
couple of months after that,'' she said, ``my son's father moved in
with his girlfriend, and my life fell apart. I lost my job at the
radio station, which changed format.''
</P>
<P>
   She continued: ``It was the best thing that happened to me,
having my heart broken, because I said, `I don't have all the
answers.' I started searching for the answer. I became a Christian.
I found Al-Anon. Since then I haven't done anything addicting. God
saved my life.''
</P>
<P>
   She worked at an oldies station in Seattle until her son was 5,
then went to work for stations in Boston, Philadelphia and
Rochester, N.Y. She married again, had a baby and nursed her mother
through the final stages of brain cancer.
</P>
<P>
   She started her current show in Rochester in February 1996.
Broadcast Programming began syndicating it at the end of that year.
She moved back to Seattle, and by January 1997 had 12 stations. The
target was the 25- to 54-year-old women who listen to adult
contemporary music.
</P>
<P>
   ``Delilah broke all the rules,'' said Jim LaMarca, senior vice
president for sales at Broadcast Programming, a radio consulting
company, and director of its broadcast division, which also
produces ``Neon Nights,'' a country music show.
</P>
<P>
   Initially station managers, who tend to be men, resisted her,
LaMarca said. ``They told me: `I spend all day making the program
consistent, run the same 200 songs. Now she's going to talk two to
three minutes at a time and then play a song I don't know? I can't
do that.''' But many did. At the end of her first year, Delilah had
70 stations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were getting hundreds of calls a night,'' recalled Peter
Oleshchuk, program director of WHMS-FM, a light-rock station in
Champaign, Ill. ``And when we're out and about in town, people will
say, `Which one of you is Delilah?'''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   She explains her national appeal this way: ``People are people.
Even though you can fax someone across the world, and they can
e-mail you, it seems communication is less and less effective. I
try to encourage people to form relationships.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're a parent, love your children. If you're married,
honor your spouse instead of looking on the Internet for love in
all the wrong places. I'm talking about real relationships, not
false intimacies. To show love for people, that's what the whole
show is about.''
</P>
<P>
   Delilah, now pregnant with her third child, also has an adopted
son and is seeking custody of the boy's sister and brother. ``I
went from being the single parent of one to a married mom of four,
soon to be six, in five years,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Delilah ``keeps no secrets,'' Ms. Dedrick said. ``She uses every
aspect of her life to sympathize with people, and she has
incredible power of empathy. She seems able to dig into their
brains and tell them what they need to hear, not necessarily what
they want to hear.''
</P>
<P>
   Her name, Delilah said, is the real thing. ``My older brother
was named Matthew Mark Luke. My parents decided to counterbalance
good and bad, so they named me Delilah. For a while, I lived down
to my name.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people ask me, `Why did you pick that for a stage name?'
I say, `I didn't.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
