<SLUG> BC-NYLITE(SMILE)-NYT </SLUG>
  
 No. 2889 Mon., Jan. 18: 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (NYLite items can be published if desired; &LR;  please credit the
contributor. Contribute to NYLite and get a NYT rolling-writer
style pen.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BILL'S WORLD &LR;
</P>
<P>
   A genius in marketing? That would be someone who could make
money selling videotapes of the Senate trial of Mr. Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   _ (Bill Tammeus, The Kansas City Star)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE TIMES THEY AIN'T A CHANGIN' &LR;
</P>
<P>
   A quote attributed to one of America's founders, John Adams, in
the play 1776: `I have come to the conclusion that one useless man
is called a disgrace, two men are called a law firm, and three or
more become a Congress.'
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CITY STREETS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   During the holiday season, about 200 men and women converged on
St. Luke's Church on Hudson Street for the annual Christmas carol
walk. We divided into groups, each heading into the West Village,
song sheets in hand containing all the old-time carols as well as
more newfangled fare like ``White Christmas.''
</P>
<P>
   We shrugged off our shyness as we started singing and were soon
spreading Christmas cheer. We sang for diners in an Italian
restaurant and were rewarded with a bottle of wine. We serenaded a
big town house, at which point a couple of pedestrians joined us.
Finally we sang our way down Christopher Street. At a fitness gym,
our serenade fell flat; the members were more in the mood for bench
presses than for us. Somewhat dejected, we continued.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, three stories up one building, a window flew open and
a young woman stuck her head out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Please sing a carol,'' she said. ``I just moved here and my
parents in Illinois are worried about New York.'' We launched into
``God Rest Ye Merry, Gentlemen'' and looked up to see her holding a
phone receiver out the window. We sang even louder, hoping our
voices would carry up three flights.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank you,'' the woman shouted as we finished. ``My parents
are feeling much better. Merry Christmas.''
</P>
<P>
   _STEPHEN M. MORRISON
</P>
<P>
   It was early morning on the 96th Street crosstown bus, so packed
that even standing room was at a premium. A group of sleepy-eyed
prep school students were spread out across the back four or five
seats, schoolbooks spread across their laps, hard at their
homework. This 50-plus-year-old teacher was feeling weaker by the
moment.
</P>
<P>
   Leaning toward the nearest teen-ager, I quietly asked if I could
have her seat, explaining that I was feeling a bit weak. She looked
up and told me her teacher would kill her if she didn't turn in
this assignment on time. I leaned down again and with a smile, told
her that I, too, was a teacher, wasn't feeling well and might kill
her first if she didn't have the decency to let me sit for a
minute. She cocked her head. ``Whatever,'' she said, and went back
to her homework.
</P>
<P>
   _JUDITH NICHTERN
</P>
<P>
   On a recent mall trip, Michael Sorum Rockefeller came across a
men's room towel dispenser with a sticker: ``Gambling Anonymous.
Call 1-800'' followed by the numbers. Beneath it, someone had
scrawled ``10-1 they don't answer.''
</P>
<P>
   Margo Arceri was on a crowded car on the Long Island Rail Road
where half the passengers were standing.
</P>
<P>
   An elderly woman entered the train, standing behind her. A man
in front of her, also standing, suggested that a nearby male
passenger give up his seat for the elderly woman. The man brushed
off the suggestion, at which point Ms. Arceri arose and insisted
that the older woman take her seat. Then she and the man who had
made the original suggestion began discussing their astonishment at
the male passenger's refusal to give up his seat.
</P>
<P>
   At Huntington, their exchange ended as the fellow standee
prepared to get off. ``That was very kind, what you did,'' he said
and slipped something into her pocket. ``Have a drink on me.''
</P>
<P>
   The train emptied nicely. Ms. Arceri found a seat, reached in
her pocket and found a $100 bill.
</P>
<P>
   My friend Linda's mother, Sis, died after relocating to Naples.
Fla., but before her move her friends had been full of advice about
security measures for women living alone. ``Now Sis,'' one of them
advised, ``be sure to have a can of Mace in the car for your
protection.''
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, Sis was never a carjacking victim. But Linda had to
smile when she looked in the glove compartment not long after her
mother's funeral. There, at the ready, was the small red and white
can that McCormick spices come in _ she had followed the advice
given her. It was, indeed, a can of mace.
</P>
<P>
   _PENNY KEMP
</P>
<P>
   Scene: Fifth Avenue bus traveling south.
</P>
<P>
   Players: Bus driver, anonymous New Yorker, woman of a certain
age.
</P>
<P>
   Observer: Walter Jamieson Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Driver: ``The machine doesn't accept dollar bills.''
</P>
<P>
   Woman: ``I'm from Philadelphia, and buses there take dollar
bills.''
</P>
<P>
   Driver: ``Sorry, you'll have to ask someone for change.''
</P>
<P>
   A New Yorker several rows back offers the woman a dollar's worth
of change.
</P>
<P>
   Woman: ``Thank you. You see, I'm from Philadelphia, and the
buses there take bills.''
</P>
<P>
   New Yorker: ``Do you need 50 cents too?''
</P>
<P>
   Woman: ``No, thank you.'' She offers the driver 50 cents in
coins and a dollar bill.
</P>
<P>
   Driver: ``It all has to be in coins.''
</P>
<P>
   Woman: ``Well I'm from Philadelphia and the buses there accept
bills.''
</P>
<P>
   New Yorker offers the woman another dollar in change.
</P>
<P>
   Woman: ``Thanks so much, You see I'm from Philadelphia and. . .
. ''
</P>
<P>
   New Yorker, interrupting: ``Being from Philadelphia excuses some
things, but it doesn't excuse everything.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
