<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Tuesday, Jan. 19, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(bl) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Potent thunderstorms fueled by a strong jet stream disturbance
ripped through the Middle Atlantic states Monday, producing 70
miles-per-hour wind gusts near Pittsburgh, Pa. Tuesday, relatively
tranquil weather will return to the Middle Atlantic and
Northeastern states in the wake of the disturbance. Indeed,
abundant sunshine and seasonable temperatures will be found from
Washington, D.C., to Boston, though gusty winds from the west will
make the air feel cooler.
</P>
<P>
   Farther inland, residual moisture in the lower portions of the
atmosphere will cause clouds to linger from the Great Lakes to
western New England. Occasional snow showers will add slightly to
the substantial snow pack across the region, particularly east of
Lake Ontario and in the Adirondack mountains.
</P>
<P>
   Subsiding air currents associated with high pressure will
suppress clouds across the Southeast and southern Plains on
Tuesday. The plentiful sunshine will help to boost temperatures
into the 60s and lower 70s over the region. Slightly more humid
conditions will support scattered clouds across southern Texas and
south Florida where isolated showers may develop.
</P>
<P>
   Overcast skies and showers will cover the Pacific Northwest and
northern two thirds of California as a steady flow of moist air
from the Pacific Ocean persists. Upon being lifted and cooled, the
damp air will produce heavy snow in the Sierra and Cascade
mountains. Valley showers and mountain snow will also occur near
much of the west-facing slopes of the Rockies.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Tennessee Tornadoes &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Deadly tornadoes descended on western Tennessee on Sunday night
as a cold front from the Pacific crossed the Mississippi Valley.
Oddly, fronts of Pacific origin tend to trigger more severe storms
in the South during the winter than do Arctic fronts. The Pacific
fronts, while lacking sharp temperature contrasts common with polar
fronts, tend to draw large quantities of very mild, moist air,
vital to thunderstorms, northward from the Gulf of Mexico. Pacific
fronts are often preceded by very strong winds just a few thousand
feet above the ground and this is a critical ingredient for
twisters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
