<HEADLINE>
LET'S HEAR IT FOR THIS CASH COW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Wednesday Jan. 20)  
 By DAVID GRIMES   
 Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is possible that you were so preoccupied exhaling a huge sigh
of relief that Dennis Rodman is going back to work that you missed
the story of Lucy the cow.
</P>
<P>
   Lucy is an 8-year-old Holstein (for all you bovine-challenged
folks, that is a make of cow, sort of like a Chevy Vega, only with
better acceleration) who lives at La-Foster Farm in Rowan County,
N.C. Lucy made (small) headlines recently for (possibly) setting a
new international record for milk production in a single year.
</P>
<P>
   Dairy farmer Terry Foster and his wife, Sarah, said Lucy
produced 75,275 pounds of milk in a 365-day period. For those of
you who don't buy your milk by the pound, that translates to 8,753
gallons, or an average of almost 24 gallons of milk each day.
</P>
<P>
   One day, Lucy was feeling particularly generous and produced
nearly 30 gallons of milk, which is 5 times what other Vegas
-excuse me, Holsteins - usually produce.
</P>
<P>
   I will admit at the outset that I am not an agricultural kind of
guy. In fact, the only knowledge I could share with you about dairy
farms is that you should roll up your window when you drive by one.
</P>
<P>
   Still, even someone who thought 2-percent milk came from
2-percent cows can be deeply impressed and humbled by Lucy's
accomplishment.
</P>
<P>
   The question, to me, is not how but why Lucy produced so much
milk. Does she come from a long line of overachievers? Do the
Fosters offer perks, like extra hay or, perhaps, monogrammed
bathrobes to cows that go the extra mile, or quart, as the case may
be? Or has the whole Monica Lewinsky thing got Lucy so upset that
she's producing extra milk simply as a means of relieving her
anxiety?
</P>
<P>
   (There was no mention in The Associated Press story as to
whether Lucy is a Democrat or Republican, nor does it say how North
Carolina cows, as a group, feel about impeachment. By my guess is
that they've been subjected to Clinton-like behavior many times
around the barn yard and consider it no big deal.)
</P>
<P>
   What is clear is that Lucy does what she does very well, and she
does it without drawing a lot of attention to herself, which is
refreshing in these days of overexposed celebrities. Although Lucy
had the kind of year at the milking machine that Mark McGwire had
at the plate, she has not hired an agent, asked to be traded to a
bigger-market dairy farm nor signed an endorsement contract with a
major shoe company.
</P>
<P>
   For better or for worse - and you can put me down in the ``for
better'' column - dairy cows, even record-setting dairy cows - are
not as popular as professional athletes. When, for example, was the
last time you saw 70,000 people pack a stadium to watch a cow eat
grass? While it could be argued that such a spectacle would be more
exciting that your average Super Bowl, the fact remains that dairy
farming, like World Cup soccer, has thus far failed to generate
much interest among average Americans.
</P>
<P>
   When Lucy delivered her world-record 8,753rd gallon of milk,
fans did not fight each other for the plastic jug like they did for
Mark McGwire's 70th home run ball. When Lucy heads to the barn
after a hard day of cud-chewing, she isn't besieged by hordes of
autograph-seekers. Whether this is because dairy cows are uncool or
because autograph-seekers are averse to getting their shoes dirty
is hard to say; all I know is Lucy has thus far escaped writer's
cramp from signing too many T-shirts and visors.
</P>
<P>
   Although she is unsung, Lucy's accomplishment is every bit as
amazing as McGwire's. If you think it's hard hitting a 500-foot
home run, try producing 30 gallons of milk in one day.
</P>
<P>
   Way to go, Lucy. You earned your extra hay, and your monogrammed
bathrobe, too.
</P>
<P>
   (David Grimes is a columnist for the Herald-Tribune in Sarasota,
Fla.)
</P>
</TEXT>
