A7986 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-Q&AMP;A-$ADV24-NYT     01-18 1094
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-Q&AMP;A-$ADV24-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WALKING IN WALES  
 BRAZILIAN RHYTHM FESTIVAL  
 RARE BOOK SHOPS IN PARIS 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By SUZANNE MacNEILLE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. (italics)I am planning a hiking trip to Wales this spring,
and would like some general information on trails. _ Mindy Dillon,
Buffalo, N.Y.(end italics)
</P>
<P>
   A. There are thousands of miles of walking paths throughout
Wales, ranging from those that traverse the heather moorlands and
mountainous terrain of the 845-square-mile Snowdonia National Park
in the north, to less demanding trails that crisscross the gentle
countryside of central Wales.
</P>
<P>
   Other popular destinations are in the western coastal regions of
Pembrokeshire National Park and southern Wales' mountainous Brecon
Beacons National Park. Wherever you roam, especially in the parks,
you're likely to encounter abundant wildlife, including seals and
numerous bird species.
</P>
<P>
   The Wales Tourist Board publishes a free 53-page guide called
``Walking Wales'' that includes a selection of walks long and
short, tough and easy. Nearby accommodations and a small map with
Ordnance Survey references accompany each entry.
</P>
<P>
   Among the short walks is the four-mile St. Brides Major Walk
that incorporates both inland countryside and segments of the
14-mile Glamorgan Heritage Coast in southern Wales. Sites on the
route include a ruined castle, the remains of an old walled garden,
the sandy beach at Dunraven Bay, traces of a Celtic settlement and
an ancient church.
</P>
<P>
   Among the longer walks are the 182-mile Offa's Dyke Path, which
crosses the England-Wales border 13 times; and the 186-mile
Pembrokeshire Coast Path with its rugged cliff trails and sandy
beaches.
</P>
<P>
   The guide also includes a 10-page list of publications on hiking
in Wales, a list of tourist office addresses and phone numbers,
advice on transportation; and other useful information. It is
available from the Wales Tourist Board, Department PP12, Post
Office Box 1, Cardiff, Wales; telephone (44-1222) 457766, fax
(44-1222) 482436.
</P>
<P>
   Among the companies specializing in hiking in Wales are Acorn
Activities, in Hereford, (44-1432) 830083; fax (44-1432) 830110,
and Heart of Wales Farm and Country Holidays, telephone and fax
(44-1686) 688444.
</P>
<P>
   You may also be interested in a spring walking festival. From
May 28 to 31, the Llanelli Festival of Walks will include 10 hikes
along coastal paths, and through the hills of southern Wales; the
walks range from 6 gentle miles to 10-mile strenuous walks. The fee
is $24.50. A festival dinner costs $16. The Festival Office in
Llanelli, telephone (44-1554) 770077, can provide information on
lodgings in the area. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. (italics)I would like to go to the Panorama Percussivo
Mundial festival in Salvador, Brazil. Please provide information. _
Mabel MacDonald, Aspen, Colo.(end italics) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. The six-year-old Panorama Percussivo Mundial (World
Percussive Panorama, or Percpan, as it is called in Brazil) is a
jubilant festival that showcases international percussion-based
music _ both traditional and modern _ from Brazil, Africa, the
Caribbean and other areas.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the festival is only two months away, promoters for
the event, which will be held March 22 to 27 in Salvador, the
capital of the northeastern state of Bahia, are not releasing
details about international performers, with whom they're still in
negotiation. It has been announced that the Brazilian songwriter
Gilberto Gil and Nana Vasconcellos, a percussionist, will act as
masters of ceremony. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   You're likely to see some colorful performances by musicians and
dancers decked out in headdresses, feathers and flowing robes.
Calabash and gourd rattles, cowbells, an exotic variety of drums,
even a pair of wooden shoes, provided the rhythms for last year's
festival, which included Doudou N'Diaye Rose, a Senegalese drum and
dance ensemble, the Japanese group Wadaiko Yamato and the Brazilian
composer Hermeto Pascoal.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the evening performances (there are about five a
night), you can attend daily two-hour workshops, led by
participating musicians.
</P>
<P>
   Percpan will take place in downtown Salvador's Castro Alves
theater (Praca 2 de Julho, Campo Grande). Nightly ticket prices are
likely to be the same as last year: $8, $4 for students. For more
information call (55-71) 243 6364, or by e-mail to
percpan(AT)e-net.com.br. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. (italics)Do you know the names of bookstores in Paris that
specialize in rare books? Simon Lagroste, Providence, R.I.(end
italics)
</P>
<P>
   A. Most of Paris' antique book stores (called librairies) are
concentrated in two distinctly different neighborhoods: on the Left
Bank, in the fifth arrondissement near the Sorbonne and in the
sixth arrondissement between St.-Germain-des-Pres and Odeon; and on
the Right Bank in the area around the Rue du Faubourg St.-Honore,
as well as in the eighth and ninth arrondissements.
</P>
<P>
   The Left Bank shops are in a neighborhood for printers and book
shops, which were established in the 15th century. At that time,
the first printing press arrived in the city, and was housed in the
Sorbonne.
</P>
<P>
   Shops you might come across include: Alain Brieux, at 48 Rue
Jacob in the sixth arrondissement. It was established at the end of
the 19th century, and began specializing in rare medical and
scientific books and instruments in 1958. It is open Monday to
Saturday from 10 to 1 and 2 to 6:30; telephone (33-1) 42.60.21.98.
</P>
<P>
   Librairie Gourmande, 4 Rue Dante in the fifth, stocks many rare
books on the art of dining from the 16th century to the present. It
is open every day from 10 to 7; (33-1) 43.54.37.27.
</P>
<P>
   Librairie Beres, 14 Avenue Friedland in the eighth, is reputed
to have the best collection of rare books from the 9th to the 20th
centuries, on subjects ranging from politics and economics to
literary first editions. Hours are 9 to 6 daily; (33-1)
45.63.85.53. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Laurent Coulet, 166 Boulevard Haussmann in the eighth,
specializes in handsomely bound works of French literature from the
16th to the 18th centuries. It is open Tuesday to Saturday from 10
to 12:30 and 2 to 6:30; (33-1) 42.89.51.59.
</P>
<P>
   For rare maps, atlases and engravings from the 15th to the
mid-19th centuries, you might want to go to the Librairie La
Bail-Weissert, 5 Rue Lagrange in the fifth. The shop includes
original topographical maps of the world, as well as maps of
European cities, regions and a collection of architectural
engravings. Hours are Monday to Saturday, from 10 to 12:30 and 2 to
7; (33-1) 43.29.72.59.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
