<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 18:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7990 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-COSTA-RICA-$AD     01-18 1025
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-COSTA-RICA-$ADV14-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN OPEN-AIR PERCH IN THE JUNGLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For release on Sunday, Jan. 24)  
(ms) 
 By FRANCES FRANK MARCUS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A red dugout canoe floated on the calm aqua sea, orchids were
blooming in the garden, large grapefruit and limes hung
languorously in the orchard. And on a steep slope above, we
glimpsed the edge of a deep green, mysterious Costa Rican rain
forest. Nothing wrong with the view. But something was definitely
amiss. A rather big something. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Surveying the vista from our room at the top of the stairs in a
jungle lodge reachable only by boat, we could see the canoe, citrus
trees and forest clearly for a good reason. On three sides, between
the beaded board wainscoting (which came up to my waist) and the
roof, there was nothing but tropical sea air. Our room was almost
without walls. My husband, Bernard, and I had known this in advance
but even so, seeing it up close was disquieting. In any case, the
space was now ours, and paid for in advance. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   We set down three small pieces of luggage. Then there was a
flutter of wings. A large toucan flapped straight toward us,
stopping a few feet away in the branches of a tall water apple
tree.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Hmmm,'' Bernard said, as he looked at the bird looking at him
through the gap beneath the roofline.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There was a reason for staying in a room that was half-porch at
the top of the lodge operated by Rainbow Adventures-Costa Rica, in
the southwestern part of the country near Panama. It is set in a
1,200-acre rain forest, blessed with spectacular scenery and
gorgeous birds. Here, we wanted to test an idea embraced by Alec
Waugh, the English writer, who liked to size up unfamiliar
territory from a veranda. Like him, we wanted to find out if we
could see a respectable amount of jungle life from the edges. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Either you are the explorer, who leaves no corner unexamined,
who hurries from place to place collecting and codifying facts; or
else you are the observer,'' Waugh wrote in ``Hot Countries,'' his
book about travels in the tropics. ``Myself, I have always chosen
to let life come to me.''  &QC;  Still, there were questions. The main
one: how much of our third-floor room would we be sharing and with
how many varieties of wildlife? Costa Rica is said to have 850
species of bird and more than 35,000 species of insect, including
hordes of mosquitoes. We had learned that Rainbow's owner, Michael
Medill, had not installed ceiling fans because they could
annihilate hummingbirds.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Guidebooks to the country are full of advice about jungle
safeguards, suggesting insect repellent strong enough to cloud
plastic, masses of first-aid equipment and other precautions,
which, if we had listened, could have displaced our clothing. The
small planes we were booked on had a limit of 25 pounds of luggage
per person. In the end, I checked to see if my tetanus shot was
still valid, packed bath oil, which a forest ranger friend had
recommended as a mosquito deterrent, and threw out an umbrella to
make room for an extra sun hat.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Our trip to Rainbow Adventures had progressed in stages of
declining amenities. It began with an overnight stay in Costa
Rica's mountainous capital, San Jose, in the cozy Hotel Grano de
Oro, which, except for the tropical garden and the excellent local
beer, was reminiscent of a comfortable New England inn. Early the
next morning we flew in a twin-engine plane 50 minutes southeast
over the mountains to Puerto Jimenez, a village on the Golfo Dulce
near the Pacific Ocean. Bernard and I were headed for the Osa
Peninsula and Lapa Rios, an upscale jungle lodge, where the rooms
were protected by mesh screens. Two mornings later we checked out
of our pleasant room with mixed feelings and climbed into a
four-wheel drive truck that would take us to Puerto Jimenez for the
boat trip across the Golfo Dulce to our room without walls. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rainbow's boatman, Balto Villareal, wearing shorts and no shoes,
was waiting at the dock with the lodge's 22-foot skiff for the
35-minute ride to the lodge. ``Peligroso?'' I asked apprehensively,
pointing to a darkening bank of clouds toward the north, where we
were headed. We were traveling in November near the end of rainy
season and what is considered winter in southern Costa Rica's
Pacific region. Balto laughed and pointed to three brown pelicans
circling lazily overhead and later to dozens of fish jumping off
our starboard side, a school of skipjack tuna.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At Rainbow, built in a grassy clearing between the volcanic sand
beach and the steep forested ridge, Brian Strehlow, a co-manager,
wearing camp counselor shorts and T-shirt, was waiting as we
stepped from the skiff onto rocks and splashed through tidal pools
to reach the shore.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   We stopped briefly on the veranda-cum-lobby and dining room, to
test a large hammock and handmade polished hardwood chairs. The
coffee table was hidden under stacks of nature books and a
backgammon board. A chart of Costa Rica's snakes hung on a wall. In
the library behind the veranda, shelves held hundreds of books on
natural history.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In our third-floor room at the top of the stairs, we walked into
a hodgepodge of collectibles (not the upscale antiques that
guidebooks had led me to expect), panels of stained glass, small
tables of Art Nouveau objects, several vases filled with bouquets
of fresh flowers, faded prints on the wall and polished hardwood
floors. Fine mesh mosquito netting shadowed the double bed. Along
the room's edges, where the walls should have been, there were
shiny wood swivel chairs positioned for spotting the birds and
animals that roam Rainbow's grounds. Even with gaps in the walls,
it felt homey. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the spacious bathroom, shielded from the bedroom by an
interior wall, a bidet sat beneath a mola of a fire-breathing
dragon. Hanging stained-glass panels screened some of the views.
Thanks to hydropower, an unlimited amount of hot water flowed
freely in the large tiled shower. Rainbow's electricity is
generated by the inn's high-tech water wheel, propelled by a stream
from the hills above.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Downstairs on the breezy veranda, the kitchen smells were
enticing, the work of a cook, Juana Villareal (a common last name
in the area). She was bent over a behemoth stainless-steel stove
that had been shipped to the lodge from the Golfo Dulce's main
port, Golfito, south of Rainbow, in a huge dugout canoe. The
home-style lunch was delicious: fresh tamarind juice, a large soft
tamale filled with chicken and fresh vegetables and a salad of
marinated cauliflower. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Energized by the tamarind juice, we decided to go for a walk
with Brian, included in the daily rate for room and meals. He
helped us find the right size rubber boots from a cache by the
front steps for an hour and a half tour of the grounds, the orchard
and organic vegetable garden. On an easy trek wading up one of
Rainbow's clear rocky streams we saw a green kingfisher in a wild
avocado tree, beautiful fungi that looked like tiny white caps
growing on tree limbs, and a plant species with an elephant-ine
trunk, which Brian said ``has been sitting out in the jungle since
dinosaur times, the cycad.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But we saw nothing on our walk as beguiling as the frangipani
tree in Rainbow's side garden, festooned with hanging clumps of
pastel orchids growing in coconut husks _ though the ylang-ylang
tree with a languid yellow flower came close. Hummingbirds sipped
from the bird-of-paradise-like blossoms of the heliconia plant. The
tree sheltering a family of bats was less appealing. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Just before dinner, a small boy, about 4 years old, emerged from
the foliage and ran up the lodge steps with a shout, ``A moth, a
moth!'' That was Max, calling to his father on the veranda. The
family of five, from England and Atlanta, the only other guests at
Rainbow that day, had spent a week in one of the two cabins without
walls, built near the lodge, and Max was showing talent as a
wildlife spotter. During a four-hour river boat trip, between naps,
he had helped his mother, father, grandmother and 2-year-old sister
spot 35 species of birds. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Later at dinner on the veranda, when a bat zoomed out of the
darkness and jetted over the main course _ excellent grilled red
snapper, served with green salad and crisp green beans _ I was the
only person who flinched. At the next table, Max's mother smiled,
saying, ``You're as jumpy as we were when we first arrived.'' I
recovered over the soothing fresh coconut flan.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After dinner, we drifted outside to look for tree frogs and
other creatures near the 48-foot nonchlorinated, spring-fed
swimming pool, part of Rainbow's evening ritual. The frogs flatten
themselves against green leaves until they are almost
two-dimensional. There were plenty of frogs but no sign of the boa
constrictor that had visited the pool area a few days before.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Night falls early in Costa Rican jungles, and so do
bird-watchers. By about 10 p.m. you crawl under the mosquito
netting to wait for dawn, when you're awakened by silvery bird
calls. Later the rain came down in torrents as loud as disco music,
but the room stayed dry, protected by the wide roof overhang.
Beyond the buckets of rain that fell in the inky black, I was aware
only of perfume from the ylang-ylang tree.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The next day began with glasses of fresh orange and grapefruit
juice, eggs cooked to order, served with rice and beans, and
magnificent coffee. It was brewed from freshly ground Costa Rican
beans, and we poured copious amounts from a pot that sat on a
counter between the dining area and the kitchen. The round polished
hardwood dining tables were decorated with dewy fresh flowers in
jelly glasses. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After breakfast, we left the veranda with Balto for a trip to
the main attraction in Rainbow's world, Casa de Orquidias, a
botanical garden that is a 15- or 20-minute boat ride south of the
lodge. The garden was created by two Americans, Ron and Trudy
MacAllister, who prefer living in a place without roads,
telephones, television and newspapers, dependent only upon their
home-grown vegetables, shortwave radio and boat, which takes them
south to Golfito once a week to shop for supplies. The beguiling
70-acre garden surrounding the small house they built themselves 19
years ago out of native woods lies between the steep jungle
hillside and the beach. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the garden's wild tangle of tropical splendors _ plants
growing on top of plants and sprouting from every visible cranny _
one orchid species grows up to 12 feet tall and another has a bloom
no bigger than four pinheads. Inviting pathways curve through
thickets of mango, papaya, guanabana, cashews, and star fruit
trees, spiky bromeliads, giant strangler figs, heliconias, a
variety of gingers and countless other species. There were
cactuses, which grow much faster in Costa Rica than in the desert,
and a palm tree that, Trudy said, ``you can see grow _ five feet in
two weeks. I sit on my porch and watch it grow.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ordinarily the tour means stopping for fruit-tasting sessions
under sheltering trees but because it began to rain, we did our
tasting on the front porch, biting into juicy grapefruit and star
fruit, fleshier and more intensely flavored than any shipped fruit
I'd ever tasted, and a red berry called the miracle fruit, sour
when eaten plain and sweet when sprinkled with lemon juice. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The garden has 100 species of orchid but ``Costa Rica has about
12,000,'' Trudy said.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Back at Rainbow, early the next morning, I saw Carol, a newly
arrived guest from Seattle, wandering distractedly up the path to
the lodge after a stroll around the garden with binoculars and a
thick guide to the birds of Costa Rica. ``There's so much to see,
you can't move very far,'' she said.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Just before leaving, I sat in front of the lodge on a seaside
bench made of a split log for a last look, spotting brown pelicans
circling above dolphins. The pelicans followed our boat south to
Golfito and its small landing strip. Waiting for the plane back to
San Jose, we sat on a bench under trees hung with bromeliads. My
wildlife tally after two days beside the rain forest was paltry by
Costa Rican standards: a dozen bird species I could name, dozens of
others I couldn't name, an agile racoonlike coatimundi, a tayra (a
weasel that looks like a fisher) and no mosquito bites. But what we
did see was choice. And we had learned what we had hoped to learn,
that you can see quite a bit without straying far from a veranda.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
