<HEADLINE>
BRITISH COURT RECONSIDERS PINOCHET'S BID TO BE FREED
</HEADLINE>
 (bl) 
By WARREN HOGE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ A panel of Law Lords, Britain's highest court, Monday
opened a rehearing of Gen. Augusto Pinochet's plea to be freed from
house arrest and allowed to return home to Chile.
</P>
<P>
   Alun Jones, the British lawyer arguing the case against the
former dictator, said the Lords should disregard his supporters'
claims that trying him was a matter for Chile alone or that
prosecuting him would destabilize Chilean democracy.
</P>
<P>
   Jones said that the liability for the crimes against humanity
that Pinochet is charged with lies with him and not with Chile. He
cited the Nuremburg war crimes tribunal's conclusion that ``crimes
against international law are committed by men, not by abstract
entities, and only by punishing individuals who commit such
offenses can the provisions of international law be enforced.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones also introduced evidence that Pinochet may not have been
officially head of state at the time that the killings and torture
occurred, calling into question his claim of sovereign immunity.
Lord Browne-Wilkinson, chief Law Lord, said the court might ask the
Foreign Office for a certificate clarifying when Britain recognized
Pinochet as head of state.
</P>
<P>
   ``We better look at this overnight,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Pinochet, 83, is protesting his arrest in London on Oct. 16,
saying that as Chile's former head of state he enjoys sovereign
immunity. That view was upheld by the High Court on Oct. 28 but
reversed by a five-man panel of Law Lords on Nov. 25.
</P>
<P>
   The British police arrested the general in response to an
application from a Spanish judge seeking his extradition to Madrid
to stand trial on charges of genocide, torture and kidnapping in
connection with the death or disappearance of more than 3,000
people in the 17 years that he ruled Chile after seizing power in a
coup in 1973.
</P>
<P>
   After the Law Lords' decision, Home Secretary Jack Straw
validated the Spanish claim, and the general, in his only public
appearance, went before a London judge for a bail hearing Dec. 11
that continued his house arrest and prompted predictions that he
would be unable to leave England for at least a year.
</P>
<P>
   But on Dec. 17, in a development that deeply embarrassed the
British judiciary and led to this week's reopening of the case, the
Lords set aside its earlier decision because one of the judges who
ruled against the general, Lord Hoffmann, had not disclosed his
involvement with Amnesty International, which is a party to the
case.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's hearing was the first time the Lords had ever reviewed
one of their rulings, and the panel numbered seven instead of the
customary five Law Lords, a measure of the gravity of the case for
Britain and the reputation of its court system. Chile was granted
the right to make its case in support of the general's release
during what is expected to be at least four days of hearings.
</P>
<P>
   If the seven senior judges now find in favor of Pinochet, he is
expected to fly home on a Chilean air force plane that returned
Monday to Brize Norton Royal Air Force Base in Oxfordshire, where
it had been parked this fall to provide the general a quick exit
from England. If they rule against him, he would have to remain in
the suburban house he has been living in under police guard for the
many months it will take the extradition process to wind through
the courts.
</P>
<P>
   Baltasar Garzon, the Spanish judge who started the case as part
of his investigation of atrocities during the so-called dirty wars
in Latin America in the 1970s, was present Monday as an observer.
His petition has since been endorsed by the Spanish government, and
Jones emphasized that the extradition effort was not ``an isolated
exercise by a single magistrate.''
</P>
<P>
   Returning to arguments he made in the past that crimes like
torture and kidnapping cannot be covered by immunity, he said
methods put into practice by Pinochet were ``the most hideous
imaginable.'' He cited systematic rape and sodomy and added, ``On
occasions dogs were used in a sexual way against victims.''
</P>
<P>
   The case that Garzon began has inflamed opinions in Chile and
among exile groups in Europe, and rival gatherings of demonstrators
thronged either side of the street outside Parliament on Monday
chanting slogans and waving banners and placards. On Sunday
hundreds of Chilean exiles staged a protest in London against
Pinochet, while hundreds of his supporters were arriving here from
Santiago to rally for his release and return home.
</P>
<P>
   A senior aide to former Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher, a
friend of the general's who says he ought to be treated with
gratitude for his support during the Falkland Islands war of 1982,
has published a widely circulated pamphlet called ``The Real
General Pinochet,'' portraying its subject as the victim of ``a
politically inspired kidnap.''
</P>
<P>
   The author, Dr. Robin Harris, former head of the Conservative
Research Department, said, ``Senator Pinochet is the closest thing
Britain has to a political prisoner.'' The onetime Chilean
strongman had himself declared senator for life as a way of
immunizing himself from any prosecution in Chile.
</P>
<P>
   A group of 22 Chilean lawyers issued a statement here saying
that, contrary to the claims of the general's supporters, Chile's
sovereignty was not infringed by his being brought to justice in a
foreign country.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is something that really has affected our national
sovereignty and dignity, it is precisely the systematic violations
of human rights during his dictatorship, which have been denounced
and condemned internationally,'' the lawyers said in a statement
read by Fabiola Letelier, sister of Orlando Letelier, a
pre-Pinochet Chilean defense minister assassinated in a car bombing
in Washington in 1976.
</P>
<P>
   In a weekend interview with The Sunday Telegraph from the home
he has rented in an exclusive residential enclave in Surrey, south
of London, Pinochet said he was resigned to dying in England.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
