<SLUG> BC-OPERA-LOCKOUT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
N.Y. CITY OPERA HALTS TOUR REHEARSALS
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: N.Y., Texas) (bl) 
By ALLAN KOZINN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The New York City Opera National Company canceled
musicians' rehearsals Sunday and Monday for its annual tour, which
is scheduled to begin in San Antonio next Monday, because of a
dispute with the musicians.
</P>
<P>
   The disagreement, which threatens the tour, is over the
musicians' demand for a guarantee that the touring ensemble have a
minimum of 28 or 29 players. In a dispute two years ago, the
company considered sending out its singers with piano
accompaniment, a proposal that angered the musicians and many
organizations that had planned to present the company's
performances. No such plan has been suggested for this year's tour,
which is scheduled to run 9 weeks, down from 16 last year, with 56
performances of Puccini's ``Madama Butterfly.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Moriarity, president of Local 802 of the American
Federation of Musicians, said that when the musicians arrived for
rehearsal Sunday morning, they were told that rehearsals could not
begin until the musicians had ratified the contract they have been
negotiating for the last year. The last contract expired in June.
</P>
<P>
   ``We met, we considered the offer, and we approved all the
terms,'' Moriarity said, ``but the only change we asked was that
they guarantee a minimum number of musicians, no more than they've
hired in the past. So we proposed playing the rehearsals on Sunday
and Monday and discussing it further, but the management said no,
without a ratified contract, rehearsals are off.''
</P>
<P>
   Susan Woelzl, a spokeswoman for the New York City Opera, said,
``We have been advised to say that we don't negotiate in the press,
therefore we have no comment.'' Moriarity said he was having
telephone discussions with Julie Samuels, the company's negotiator.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
