u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRITAIN-MARCONI-175&AMP;A     01-18 0501
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-MARCONI-175&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRITISH AEROSPACE IN TALKS TO BUY GEC'S MARCONI UNIT
</HEADLINE>
 (bl) 
By ALAN COWELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Britain's leading military contractors _ British
Aerospace PLC and the General Electric Co. PLC _ acknowledged
Monday that they were in ``advanced discussions'' on a deal for
General Electric's Marconi Electronic Systems that could be worth
as much as $13 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The brief announcement, confirming newspaper reports here,
pushed British Aerospace stock down by 25.5 pence, or 5 percent, to
493.5, reflecting analysts' fears that the company would pay too
much for Marconi. Shares of General Electric, which is not related
to General Electric of the United States, rose 8 pence, to 577.5,
on a day when London share prices rose 3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said news reports valuing the prospective deal at up to
$13 billion could indicate that British Aerospace was prepared to
offer a big premium for Marconi, which makes warships, missiles and
military electronics. Based on military companies in the United
States, which carry a valuation of about 1.3 times sales, analysts
calculated a fair value of the deal at about $10 billion.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The announcement was the latest in a series of developments in
efforts to consolidate Europe's military industry _ fragmented
among key players in France, Germany and Britain _ in the face of
overwhelming competition from U.S. giants.
</P>
<P>
   An all-British deal would initially set back the building of a
European military group unless other companies reached deals with
the British company.
</P>
<P>
   A merger of British Aerospace and Marconi Electronic Systems
could create a company worth at least $23 billion _ depending on
the outcome of negotiations and stock price fluctuations _ but
neither company seemed prepared Monday to give more than a terse
confirmation of their negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The boards of GEC and British Aerospace have noted recent
press comment and confirm that they are in advanced discussions,''
their joint statement said. ``A further announcement will follow in
due course.'' General Electric's board is scheduled to meet
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   While analysts have depicted the planned deal as part of a
broader, European consolidation, recent moves have shown the
sensitivities surrounding the issue of cross-border mergers in
Europe's military industry.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, British Aerospace was reported close to a deal with
DaimlerChrysler Aerospace that would have created a company with
combined sales of $23 billion. But those negotiations foundered
when it emerged that General Electric had renewed its overtures to
British Aerospace.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, France's Thomson-CSF was reported to be seeking a
separate merger with General Electric. And DaimlerChrysler
Aerospace said last week that it was talking to the French company
Aerospatiale, apparently piqued by the scuttling of its deal with
British Aerospace.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
