<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 18:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8003 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAMPAIGN-ART-2TAKES-N     01-18 1123
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEED FOR EARLY MONDAY HAS PRESIDENTIAL CONTENDERS OFF AND RUNNING
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Iowa, N.H., Calif., Ohio, Mo., Ariz., Mass., Minn. Neb.,
Texas, Tenn.)  (ART ADV: photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The compressed calendar of presidential primaries
has set off a competitive frenzy among Republican and Democratic
contenders who believe that they must begin _ almost immediately _
to raise money or they may find it impossible to catch up.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, this year is more crucial than 2000 in determining
whom the two parties will nominate. That is because the survival of
candidates, until next winter when issues and personal appeal may
be noticed, depends on one practical fact: who has enough money.
</P>
<P>
   Candidates who do not start collecting the $20 million to $25
million that a primary will require _ that amounts to $55,000 to
$70,000 a day, seven days a week by the end of the year _ may find
it difficult to wage a full-fledged campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Candidates may no longer enjoy the luxury of scoring an upset
early in the Iowa caucuses or the New Hampshire primary and using
that victory to raise money to keep their campaigns alive for
another round of contests.
</P>
<P>
   Snapping his fingers for effect, Mel Sembler, the national
finance chairman of the Republican Party and a 20-year veteran of
presidential campaign fund-raising, said: ``It's going to be quick.
Keep your eyes on the guys, or gals, who can raise the money
because those are going to be your serious, viable candidates.''
</P>
<P>
   While some candidates have not broken stride since Election Day
1996, the maneuvering has grown especially intense since the start
of the year. Several candidates have declared themselves in or out
or announced the creation of skeletal political committees. Behind
the scenes, they are engaged in bidding wars to recruit strategists
and scrambling for people to raise money.
</P>
<P>
   Even Vice President Al Gore, who for years had refused to
acknowledge his desire to succeed President Clinton _ and had been
particularly careful to appear loyal during the impeachment inquiry
_ announced that he has formed a campaign organization. Even though
he dominates the Democratic field, Gore's advisers said he could
not wait any longer to begin soliciting contributors.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's almost an irrational gold rush with these guys,'' said
Mike Murphy, a Republican media consultant. ``It's like you get a
prize if you announce by the end of January.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the first votes will not be cast for 12 months, the
contenders are jumpy for good reason. The campaign laws require
that the money they raise be collected in individual amounts of no
more than $1,000 _ a daunting, if not impossible, task for most
candidates. The goal of each candidate is to raise $10 million more
than the top goal set in the 1996 primary. Almost all of the
candidates are expected to abide by the overall federal spending
limits of about $45 million, which will allow them to collect
federal campaign subsidies next year based on how much they raise
on their own.
</P>
<P>
   The reason the candidates must come up with their own money in a
hurry is because with California, New York and other large states
seeking more influence by moving up the dates of their primaries
and caucuses to early March, nearly two-thirds of the national
convention delegates could be selected by the end of that month _
traditionally the time when primaries just get going. Never before
have so many contests been bunched so closely.
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys out there running, they don't have a lot of time,''
said Kelly Guesnier, a Republican fund-raising consultant who has
yet to sign up with anyone. ``They need to get out there and
hustle.''
</P>
<P>
   Ed Gillespie, who is assembling a campaign organization for Rep.
John Kasich of Ohio, said: ``The jockeying is white-hot intense. In
states like Iowa and New Hampshire the retail element is critical _
as is landing someone who knows all the important bits of
information, like what fish fry to attend.''
</P>
<P>
   The Republican field is roughly the size of the one in 1988, the
last time no incumbent president was running.
</P>
<P>
   Among the potential Republican candidates, Gov. George W. Bush
of Texas is the early favorite in the polls despite some lingering
uncertainty that he will actually make the race. But the surprising
moves by Elizabeth Hanford Dole and Sen. John McCain of Arizona,
who said in recent days that they would begin assembling campaign
operations, demonstrated that the race was not being conceded to
Bush.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, the circle of Democratic prospects is shrinking,
which is good news for Gore. For more than two years he has been
quietly assembling an organizational juggernaut that his advisers
hoped would scare off rivals. Thus far, the only other prominent
Democrat who clearly intends to run is former Sen. Bill Bradley of
New Jersey, who this week announced a full-fledged campaign
committee. Two senators who had been viewed as possible candidates,
Paul Wellstone of Minnesota and Bob Kerrey of Nebraska, announced
recently that they would not take on Gore.
</P>
<P>
   And advisers to Rep. Dick Gephardt of Missouri, the House
Democratic leader who for two years had been energetically building
a possible campaign organization, said he was increasingly inclined
to stay in the House.
</P>
<P>
   They said he began rethinking his plans after the Democrats
performed better than expected in the November election. Gephardt
would almost certainly become speaker if Democrats win back the
House next year. Already, Gephardt has sent top operatives who were
working on his possible presidential bid to jobs on the Democratic
Congressional Campaign Committee, whose goal is to elect more
Democrats to the House.
</P>
<P>
   Once the primary contests begin, the rapid-fire calendar could
put a premium on candidates who had defined themselves _ and their
positions _ early. The danger is that the schedule could give
voters less opportunity to get to know and evaluate the
contestants. ``Chances are the Republicans are going to have to
chose someone whom the public does not yet know intimately,'' said
Geoff Garin, a Democratic pollster. ``We're going to wake up with
someone whom we only just met.''
</P>
<P>
   Former Vice President Dan Quayle, who is preparing to run
himself, agreed that the dash to the nomination might be too hasty.
``It probably would be better to have time for everyone to reflect
after you've had a primary,'' he said. ``But it's wishful thinking
on my part that it's going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   For a year or so, the maneuvering of prospects has taken place
under the shadow of the White House scandal, which has drawn most
of the press coverage. But Gore's advisers said they believed that
the president's troubles had actually helped the vice president
politically because no other Democrat has been able to break
through and draw great attention.
</P>
<P>
   And they said Democrats who take on Gore now risk looking as if
they are taking on the president while the party faithful rally
behind him. The risk, of course, for Gore is that Clinton's
troubles will ultimately tarnish the vice president.
</P>
<P>
   Yet even Roy Romer, the Democratic Party's general chairman, had
to concede the obvious: ``It's clear that Al Gore is a very strong
front-runner. Very clear.'' Romer, who by party tradition is
supposed to stay neutral, quickly added a caveat, ``But it is
early.''
</P>
<P>
   For months, many Republicans have touted Bush as the leading
candidate, although he is untested nationally. He is in a
commanding position because he is a popular chief executive in a
large state, places at the top of the polls and can tap into the
connections of his father, former President George Bush. Bush has
been coy about his intentions, even as his advisers have in recent
weeks been quietly contacting people about raising money.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the announcements of Mrs. Dole and McCain that they plan to
take the first steps to assembling campaigns underscores that not
all Republicans are willing to cede the field. Mrs. Dole, a
two-time Cabinet secretary who is stepping down as president of the
American Red Cross, and McCain, a popular war hero, could draw from
moderates inclined toward Bush.
</P>
<P>
   A prominent Republican strategist, speaking on the condition of
anonymity, said Bush's advisers were ``thrilled beyond words''
about Mrs. Dole's move because it takes pressure off him as the
front-runner and tamps down expectations.
</P>
<P>
   But Murphy, the Republican media consultant, disagreed, saying:
``In a fantasyland they're keeping expectations low. The
expectations are there. The game has already begun for him. It's
the price of being the front-runner.''
</P>
<P>
   The candidate whose financial prowess is undeniable is Steve
Forbes, the magazine publisher who plans to dip into his own
fortune to pay for his campaign and forgo the limits on spending
for candidates who accept federal subsidies. While Forbes is viewed
by Republicans as a top-tier contender because of his financial
wherewithal, he is also potent because he has run before, in 1996,
and has successfully courted conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   Another candidate from 1996 who never stopped running is former
Gov. Lamar Alexander of Tennessee. Alexander is a disciplined
candidate who already has strong organizations in Iowa and New
Hampshire. But he may draw from the same base of support as Bush,
Mrs. Dole and McCain.
</P>
<P>
   Another Republican actively preparing a campaign is Gary Bauer,
the head of the Family Research Council, who has never served in
public office. He is expected to compete with Quayle for support of
religious conservatives.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Kasich, the House Budget Committee chairman hopes that his
energetic and youthful image will catapult him to the top. Pat
Buchanan, the conservative columnist who ran in 1992 and 1996, may
also try again, as may former Gov. Pete Wilson of California. Sen.
Robert Smith of New Hampshire, another conservative, also plans to
run.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John Ashcroft of Missouri announced last week that he was
not running. He did so even though he had gained the most ground in
the last year, elevating himself from being considered a hopeless
long shot to becoming a favorite of religious conservatives. But he
was still a long shot and feared losing his Senate seat in 2000 if
he was not nominated for president.
</P>
<P>
   On the Democratic side, Bradley, who is preparing to take on
Gore, announced a full-fledged campaign committee this week. But
while he was a respected senator and brings star appeal as a former
professional basketball player, he has kept a relatively low
profile in recent months and it is far from clear whether Bradley
can compete financially.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John Kerry of Massachusetts is also seriously considering a
bid. He could tap into the fortune of his wife, Teresa Heinz,
although he has said he would not do that.
</P>
<P>
   Jesse Jackson, who has run twice before, also said he was
weighing a run; he might carry particular appeal to liberals.
</P>
<P>
   Besides raising money and assembling staffs, candidates are
trying to figure out how they will pace themselves; with the
primary set for March 7 in California and New York, they can no
longer simply concentrate on Iowa and New Hampshire. Some
politicians say those states will be even more important because of
the shortened primary season; others say they will be overshadowed
by larger states.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's the potential for California to make New Hampshire
even more important,'' said Gov. Jeanne Shaheen of New Hampshire, a
Democrat. ``One of the lessons to me about the primary process is
to be careful of unintended consequences. Trying to manipulate the
process to benefit certain ends does not always turn out the way
you expect it to.''
</P>
<P>
   Former Gov. Michael Dukakis of Massachusetts, the Democratic
presidential nominee in 1988, said he could not fathom trying to
campaign simultaneously in Iowa, New Hampshire and California.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least when I ran, it was a one-hour difference with Iowa
and New Hampshire,'' he said of the time zone. For candidates in
2000, Dukakis said, ``sleep patterns are going to be badly
disrupted _ I'll tell you that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
