<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CULTURE-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: U.K., N.Y.)  
 CULTURE NOTES: A SILENT FILM MASTERPIECE RESTORED; WORDS FOR THE
NEXT MILLENNIUM; ECLECTIC VICTORIAN PAINTINGS; NEW VOLLEY IN ELGIN
MARBLES BATTLE
</HEADLINE>
   (js) 
 By LAWRENCE VAN GELDER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SINISTER DOINGS
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A dictatorial mastermind. A global crime syndicate.
Enemies dispatched in a supposed ``health clinic.'' These are among
the elements of ``Barrabas,'' the restored silent film masterpiece
that will unspool for nearly seven and a half hours beginning at
12:30 p.m. Tuesday at the Museum of Modern Art. Made in 1919 by the
pioneering Louis Feuillade, whose early works included such
fantasies as ``Judex,'' ``Fantomas'' and ``Les Vampires,'' this
film is a 12-part serial restored by Gaumont, the French studio
that produced it 80 years ago for weekly release. ``Barrabas'' will
be shown in a single session only once, but the first five episodes
will be shown at 2:30 p.m. Jan. 30 and the last seven at 2:30 the
next day.
</P>
<P>
   LASTING WORDS
</P>
<P>
   And the winner is ``Ulysses.'' That's the decision of the 47
literary critics and writers asked by the British bookseller
Waterstone's to choose 10 essential classic novels from any century
that were likely to survive the next millennium. Finishing in a tie
for second to James Joyce's masterwork (which was banned in Britain
in its early days) were ``The Great Gatsby'' by F. Scott Fitzgerald
and ``Remembrance of Things Past'' by Marcel Proust. These were
followed by Virginia Woolf's ``To the Lighthouse'' and Orwell's
``1984.'' In the bookshop's ``Test of Time,'' works by writers like
Ernest Hemingway, Evelyn Waugh and D.H. Lawrence fared better than
those by Charles Dickens or Jonathan Swift.
</P>
<P>
   COLORFUL AGE
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The eminent Victorians cast their spell once more,
beginning Tuesday at the Dahesh Museum at Fifth Avenue and 48th
Street. There, with 35 major British paintings by such artists as
Albert Moore, Dante Gabriel Rossetti and Edward Landseer, an
exhibition titled ``A Victorian Salon: Paintings From the
Russell-Cotes Art Gallery and Museum, Bournemouth, England'' opens
a run through April 17. These works, drawn from the collection of
Merton Russell-Cotes, a wealthy hotelier and patron of the arts,
include examples of Pre-Raphaelite, neo-classical, Social Realist
and Esthetic Art, as well as local landscapes and Orientalist
depictions of distant sites.
</P>
<P>
   PROPERTY RITES
</P>
<P>
   In the latest chapter of the long-running battle over the Elgin
marbles, Greek officials claimed a victory Monday. The source of
their elation was a petition signed by 339 of the 626 members of
the European Parliament urging Britain to return the 2,500-year-old
collection of figures, which were part of a frieze that adorned the
Parthenon on the Acropolis. Next month the Parliament is expected
to ratify the petition formally. But it carries no legal authority
to force Britain to return the marbles, which bear the name of Lord
Elgin, the British ambassador to the Ottoman Empire who removed
them to England in 1806. Britain has consistently rejected appeals
for their return.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-18-99 1829EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
