</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHONES-COMPETE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BELL ATLANTIC FEELING DISCONNECTED WHEN AIRTOUCH BID FAIL
</HEADLINE>
   (ms) 
 By SETH SCHIESEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's hard being a regional Bell these days. When the regulators
are not shooting down your latest scheme for getting into the
long-distance business or opposing your merger plans, your powerful
unions might be threatening to strike or some upstart
telecommunications wunderkind is breaking up a promising deal.
</P>
<P>
   That pretty much summed up the feelings of executives at the
Bell Atlantic Corp. Monday after finishing second with their bid to
acquire Airtouch Communications Inc. Instead of creating the
world's largest wireless communications carrier with a strong base
in the Northeast, they watched Airtouch announce at a news
conference in London that it was joining forces with Vodafone Group
PLC, Britain's biggest wireless company.
</P>
<P>
   Disappointment and frustration have become recurring themes in
the evolution of the local phone companies _ the remaining Bells
spun off in the break-up of AT&AMP;T, and the GTE Corp. Even as many
have posted strong gains in financial performance and stock price,
and even as they have continued to reinforce their stature as some
of the nation's largest and most powerful corporations, they have
been frustrated in their most far-reaching strategies.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the local phone titans have no reason to cry. The
seven Baby Bells that emerged from the 1984 breakup of the American
Telephone and Telegraph Co. have in the last few years merged into
five and are poised to become four. What is more, they still
control perhaps the most valuable communications asset in the
world: copper wires into almost every commercial and residential
building in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Still, financial and regulatory realities are clearly limiting
opportunities for these companies even as their ambitions expand.
What is unclear is whether those realities benefit consumers and
stockholders and whether today's fetters will adversely affect the
local phone giants' growth for years to come.
</P>
<P>
   Ask a senior regional Bell executive to name his biggest problem
and he will almost surely say regulation. The Telecommunications
Act of 1996 opened the door for the local phone companies to enter
the much-coveted long-distance market, but none has yet reached
that promised land by convincing the Federal Communications
Commission that it has fully opened its local network to rivals.
</P>
<P>
   That is why Reed Hundt, then the FCC's chairman, pulled out the
heavy rhetorical artillery in 1997 and blasted SBC Communications
for its merger talks with the AT&AMP;T Corp., the No. 1 long-distance
carrier, as ``unthinkable'' _ even before the two companies could
announce a deal. It may also be why Bell Atlantic runs into more
hurdles than it anticipates as it tries to acquire GTE, which runs
a big long-distance Internet operation called BBN.
</P>
<P>
   But if the battle for Airtouch proved anything, it was that in
mergers and acquisitions the local phone companies are held back by
their own shareholders at least as much as by regulators,
especially when the going gets tough.
</P>
<P>
   Here's why. The Bells and GTE have shareholder bases dominated
by conservative investors. For years, the local phone business has
been regarded by many investors as akin to a utility. Those
shareholders are focused on dividends, which could otherwise be
reinvested in the company's operations, and a steady growth of the
bottom line, which could be diluted by big acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   That kind of conservative, steady-hand investor is fine when
everyone is in the same boat. The problem for the local phone
companies is that many of their new competitors have aggressive
shareholders who are more tolerant of dilution and more focused on
growth in revenue and cash flow. That gives the new players a lot
more financial flexibility when it comes to making deals.
</P>
<P>
   Vodafone, for instance, could simply afford to pay more for
Airtouch than Bell Atlantic could. Not only does Vodafone's stock
trade at a much higher multiple to earnings than Bell Atlantic's
does, but Vodafone's shareholders care less about those earnings in
the first place.
</P>
<P>
   Almost the same thing happened to GTE in 1997. After Worldcom
Inc. made an unsolicited bid to acquire the MCI Communications
Corp., breaking up MCI's deal with British Telecommunications PLC,
GTE also made its own offer.
</P>
<P>
   But GTE discovered that even as it offered cash, it just could
not win a bidding war; Worldcom continued to increase its all-stock
offer in billion-dollar increments. As a younger company with
faster growth, Worldcom could afford more dilution of its existing
shares without risking a massive selloff by investors. The fact
that Worldcom projected huge synergies from a combination with MCI
did not hurt, either. MCI is now MCI Worldcom.
</P>
<P>
   Run this concept past top Bell company executives and they tend
to agree that their market profiles do not allow them the same
flexibility their newer rivals enjoy.
</P>
<P>
   Still, they almost always come back to regulation. They note
that companies like General Electric and Merck are also valued on
an earnings-per-share basis, but those companies get richer
valuations because they grow faster.
</P>
<P>
   If only the FCC would let them into the high-growth segments of
communications _ especially high-speed data _ without the
regulatory conditions they must satisfy, these executives say,
their companies could grow faster and get higher valuations for
their shares, even with the same shareholder profile.
</P>
<P>
   There is probably something to that, but it raises a thorny
question. Which is easier: persuading a new sort of investor to buy
into the local phone industry or persuading federal regulators to
buy into a new mode of regulation?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
