<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-MLK-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH CELEBRATES MLK'S BIRTHDAY AS PART OF INAUGURAL THEME 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By ALAN BERNSTEIN 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Gov. George W. Bush, preparing to deliver his
inaugural speech about ethnic inclusiveness Tuesday, said that
Martin Luther King Day and its message are for ``all Texans to
celebrate.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush and Lt. Gov.-elect Rick Perry attended a Houston event
Monday celebrating the slain civil rights leader's birthday as part
of their inaugural theme.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let us remember his wisdom and his legacy,'' Bush said. ``Let
us remember that compassion will overcome all.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who promotes himself as a ``compassionate conservative,''
spoke to an audience of mostly children at the annual celebration
of King's birthday, sponsored by the local Black Heritage Society.
</P>
<P>
   But this year's event became an official part of Bush's
inaugural activities, which continued Monday and Tuesday in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Historically people have viewed Martin Luther King Day as
something that only African-Americans are to celebrate,'' Bush said
at a news conference after his speech. ``That's not the way I feel.
I feel all Texans ought to celebrate Dr. King and his message.''
</P>
<P>
   The message, Bush explained, is ``judging people for what they
are, not lumping people into groups, but giving each individual a
chance to exercise their heart and soul and conscience.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said his inaugural speech will focus partly on ``what
challenges we face to make sure everybody participates'' in the
future of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Bush was scheduled to take his oath of office, to a second
four-year term, at noon CST Tuesday in Austin. Fellow Republican
Perry, the outgoing agriculture commissioner, was to be sworn in as
lieutenant governor, replacing retiring Democrat Bob Bullock.
</P>
<P>
   Bush acknowledged that blacks voted overwhelmingly for his
Democratic opponent, Garry Mauro, in the November election.
</P>
<P>
   But now, he said, the race is over and ``I am still going to be
everybody's governor.''
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. Rodney Ellis, D-Houston, said during the King
celebration that King's visit to Houston in 1958 did not draw
attention from state officials.
</P>
<P>
   Now, he said, Texas has made progress by having its elected
leaders honor King's memory.
</P>
<P>
   Perry, who will preside over the state Senate, told the audience
that every day he stands in the Senate chamber, ``I can look to my
left and see a portrait of Barbara Jordan. It's a reminder of how
far Texas and America have come thanks to the work of individuals
like Martin Luther King.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan served in the state Senate before becoming the first
black in this century to be elected to a Texas congressional seat.
</P>
<P>
   Years behind most other states, Texas made King's birthday a
full, official state holiday in 1991. Conservative Democrats and
Republicans in the Legislature blocked earlier bills on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said Monday he did not know if King would have wanted him
to fight the U.S. Supreme Court decision in the Hopwood case, which
was interpreted by former state Attorney General Dan Morales to
require the end of affirmative action programs in state college
admissions.
</P>
<P>
   The Hopwood case was named for Cheryl Hopwood, one of four white
plaintiffs who sued after being denied admission to the University
of Texas Law School in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   But, Bush said, he is working with legislators such as Ellis and
state Rep. Al Edwards _ African-Americans who attended the King
celebration with him _ to improve public schools and make sure that
``people from all walks of life'' apply to public universities.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also said he hopes that Houston's Texas Southern
University, a mostly black school facing financial problems, will
remain independent from other Texas universities. The Legislature
has considered moving TSU under the administration of other
university systems.
</P>
<P>
   In Austin later Monday, Bush and Perry attended an inaugural
children's program, which featured martial arts and science
demonstrations and music and dance acts.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who briefly addressed the youthful audience at the end of
the show, thanked them for sharing his and Perry's ``special day.''
</P>
<P>
   He also advised children to stay in school and avoid drugs and
plugged his reading initiative program.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope I'm looking at another governor. I hope there's a new
governor out there,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But guess what? You'll realize you can't be governor if you
abuse drugs. So, I want to thank you all for sending a clear
message _ no drugs in the state of Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   The governor also asked how many of the children read more than
they watched television. A number raised their hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tell the truth,'' Bush teased. ``My dream is for everybody to
be the best reader in Texas. When you read, reading is freedom.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``We wish you to be able to realize your dream. Stay
in school. Don't use drugs. Go to college. Dream the big dream, and
you can be anything you want to be in the great state of Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's parents, former President George Bush and Barbara Bush,
were scheduled to attend their eldest son's second swearing-in.
</P>
<P>
   ``This time I hope to be able to observe it,'' Bush said. ``Last
time I was so emotional I didn't pay much attention to what was
going on.''
</P>
<P>
   Percolating in the background is Bush's pending decision on
whether to run for president in the middle of his second term. Bush
said the question is still under discussion in his family.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a huge decision, as everyone knows, and we haven't made
it yet,'' Bush's wife, Laura, told reporters. ``Right now we're
focusing on Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Bush's discussions about the White House contest have
reached well beyond relatives. In private sessions in the
Governor's Mansion, he has talked about the race with policy
experts, campaign financiers and legislators from other states.
Would-be campaign contributors are scheduled to meet with Bush in
Austin on Thursday, according to sources who did not want to be
named.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's inaugural ceremonies in Austin start with a private
prayer service at the First United Methodist Church near the
Governor's Mansion. Bush is a Methodist.
</P>
<P>
   The noon inauguration and speeches at the state Capitol will be
offered live to television stations statewide and can be seen on
the Internet at www.governor.state.tx.us/inauguration.html.
</P>
<P>
   The inauguration will be followed by a barbecue on the Capitol
lawn before the parade up Congress Avenue. Four inaugural balls
take place in downtown Austin on Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
