<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEN-THEATER-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`GEN': HOPE FOR A BAREFOOT CHILD IN A CITY SHATTERED BY THE BOMB
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Production notes at end of review.) 
(ms) 
 By LAWRENCE VAN GELDER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A vastly ambitious autobiographical Japanese-language
musical built around the atomic bombing of Hiroshima on Aug. 6,
1945, will reach the end of its brief but meritorious
five-performance run Wednesday at the Sylvia and Danny Kaye
Playhouse at Hunter College.
</P>
<P>
   Titled ``Gen,'' this engrossing, well-acted, touching and
horrific plea for peace is based on the work of Keiji Nakazawa, a
graphic novelist and cartoonist who survived the bombing that
immediately claimed the life of his father, brother and sister,
soon killed a newborn sister and years later led to the death of
his mother from radiation.
</P>
<P>
   With Nakazawa as its author and Kyo Kijima as its adapter,
lyricist and director, ``Gen,'' a short form for
``Hadashi-no-Gen,'' or ``Barefoot Gen,'' focuses on the
impoverished family of a little boy named Gen Nakaoka (Miyuki
Tanaka). Unfolding by means of dramatic action, narration, song,
music, stylized dance, mime, documentary slides and ominous and
awesome sound effects and lighting, ``Gen'' is a complex mix.
Bitter toward a government that continued fighting when it was
clear well before the bombing that the war was lost, it is bitter
as well toward the death and suffering that the atomic bombing
inflicted on the people of Hiroshima.
</P>
<P>
   Remorseful about Japan's brutal treatment of subjugated Koreans
and about the country's military, it upholds Japanese values and
speaks through Gen's courageous father, an opponent of the war,
about the importance of standing up for one's beliefs and for
upholding the family.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the bombing itself, with its hellish flames, wailing
winds and smoke, the musical's scenes of survivors in silhouette in
procession across the stage while long strips of skin dangle from
their burned hands and of starving children tending an angry,
reeking, infected artist for a few yen to try to feed and buy
medical care for a dying infant are among many that have immense
impact.
</P>
<P>
   Yet this reflection on the end of World War II in the Pacific
from the vantage point of more than half a century is suffused with
hope. Children were told that nothing would grow in Hiroshima for
70 years. But, as Gen discovers, in the midst of death there is
life.
</P>
<P>
   For those who speak no Japanese, individual earphones transmit a
helpful translation of the one-hour-40-minute intermissionless
performance, which was powerful and intriguing despite the absence
of the production's normal sets, costumes and props, stranded by
snow in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   GEN
</P>
<P>
   Hadashi-no-Gen
</P>
<P>
   By Keiji Nakazawa; adapted and directed by Kyo Kijima; music by
Hajime Hayashi; lyrics by Kijima; choreography by Mamoru Nishimori;
sets by Mitsuru Ishii; lighting by Seiji Moriwaki; sound by Akira
Oyamada; costumes by Kiichi Arai; vocal training, Mineko Yamashita;
stage manager, Kazuhiro Aibara; coordinator, Kazumi Sakabe;
producer, Kiyoshi Kiyama; translated by David W. Griffith and
Mariko Hori; simultaneous translator, Faubion Bowers. Kiyama
Theater Productions, Japan, presented by the International Cultural
Production. At the Sylvia and Danny Kaye Playhouse, Hunter
Colllege, 68th Street between Park and Lexington Avenues.
</P>
<P>
   With: Miyuki Tanaka (Gen Nakaoka), Masako Tanaka (Kimie
Nakaoka), Teruhiko Ogimi (Daikichi Nakaoka) and Noboru Mitani
(Narrator).
</P>
</TEXT>
