<HEADLINE>
SOMETIMES THE PRESIDENT IS CLUELESS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``l'' lifestyle file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   Conservative publisher  &UR; Mike Antonucci  &LR; wishes to add something
to last week's item about  &UR; President Clinton &LR; 's crossword wizardry:
A 1993 story that ran in the Boston Herald said the president at
least occasionally used an aide to call the New York Times'
crossword answer line. Suspecting that Clinton used the line
routinely, early in the day, and then filled in the puzzle _
quickly, with answers he already knew _ so as to dazzle visitors,
Antonucci challenged the president to a puzzle-off.
</P>
<P>
   Antonucci forwards a copy of a March 1994 letter from the White
House declining his offer. It is signed by the aide that the Boston
newspaper had named as the answer-retriever, who the White House
says is now working at the Justice Department.
</P>
<P>
   White House press aide  &UR; Roger Salazar &LR;  said that the president
does crossword puzzles all the time, and ``just like anyone else,
when he's stumped, he'll ask for help. But for anyone to suggest
that he's cheating is a seven-letter word for lunch meat.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; REMEMBERING CARL PERKINS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   New York nightclub/gallery impresario  &UR; Baird Jones  &LR; talked with
 &UR; Carl Perkins &LR; , whose most famous song was ``Blue Suede Shoes,'' a
few weeks before Perkins' death, which was a year ago Jan. 19,
Perkins described his worst performing problem:
</P>
<P>
   He always wore blue suede shoes in concert, he said, and fans
would always line up afterward to step on his shoes. ``You can't
believe how much of a problem that becomes. My feet get horribly
sore, my toenails not only bruise but they crack, and I get
infected toenails all the time. I've seen my fans get older, which
means they put on weight, so every year, it seems my feet get
crushed more.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try to alternate left and right so they both get an equal
bruising. ... Once when I thought my toe was actually broken, I
tried to convince the fans to let me untie my shoes, take them off
and then have them stomp on them to save my poor feet, but that
didn't work. ... It's gotten to the point where if I see any kind
of a line, like even outside a movie, I can't help but cringe and
think they are all lined up to step on my poor feet.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; KINGDOM OF THE BEASTS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ The men's wear daily DNR reports on the advent of a deluxe
wool worsted fabric, CEO, which is woven from 14- to 14.9-micron
wool taken from a flock at Emu Creek, a famous Australian sheep
farm.
</P>
<P>
   ``The farm has 114,000 sheep, every one bar-coded (in an ear),''
says DNR. ``Only 500 of them produce 16-micron wool, and of those
only 50 produce finer than 15-micron wool. The very select 500
(something like New York society's old 400) actually wear jackets
to protect their wool from the environment, such as sun rays,
burrs, etc. Reports are that the jackets are made of polyester.''
</P>
<P>
   _ The Web site www.firstdog.com, about &UR; Elizabeth &LR;  and  &UR; Bob &LR; 
 &UR; Dole &LR; 's 17-year-old dog, Leader, is being updated, says
 &UR; Jeannette Walls  &LR; of MSNBC, to reflect the presidential availability
of the mistress instead of the master. &UR; Mary &LR; 
 &UR; Vincent &LR; , a neighbor who says she is Leader's ``nanny,'' is also
working on a book ``written'' by the dog, a great presidential
tradition.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Alec Baldwin &LR; , whose interest in politics has long led to
rumors about his intentions of running for office, said in a New
York TV interview over the weekend that he won't do it. ``I see now
the danger of how people launch political careers,'' he said.
``They go to enough of these events where people say, `When are you
going to run?' And they buy it, and they believe them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having people suggest to you that you might be a good
candidate and actually becoming a full-bodied, red-blooded
candidate for office are two completely separate and distinct
things.''
</P>
<P>
   _ TV Guide editors have chosen a segment in the ``Tonight'' show
of Oct. 16, 1987, as the funniest moment ever in TV.  &UR; Johnny &LR; 
 &UR; Carson &LR;  was interviewing  &UR; Myrtle Young &LR; , a woman who had come to
the show with a collection of potato chips that she said looked
like objects: a dog, a bird and the like. While Carson's sidekick
distracted her, Carson reached into a bowl offscreen and bit down
on a chip; the woman thought he had eaten one of her prizewinners.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
