<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 19:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8039 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISTANBUL-BAGELS-ART-5     01-18 1019
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISTANBUL-BAGELS-ART-520&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAGELS AND OTHER TASTES OF AMERICA ARE A HIT IN ISTANBUL 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By STEPHEN KINZER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISTANBUL, Turkey _ Sitting in New York last year, two ambitious
young Turks plotted a return to their homeland and wondered what
they would do once they got back.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Rafi told me he wanted to open a bagel shop, I started
laughing, because I had come up with the same idea,'' one of them,
Hikmet Ongan, said during a break from serving customers on a
recent morning.
</P>
<P>
   Ongan, 27, and his business partner, Rafi Karako, 30, opened
Istanbul's first bagel cafe in November. It is already thriving.
The cafe's neighborhood, called Yenikoy, is home to many
foreigners, and dozens of them have become regular customers. But
about 80 percent of the patrons are Turks.
</P>
<P>
   Most who come to the cafe enjoy the bagels, which few have ever
tasted before. They often comment on the coffee, which is rich and
flavorful, not like the watery instant to which they are accustomed
or the potent brew served in tiny cups as an after-dinner drink.
</P>
<P>
   But neither a bagel nor coffee is the main attraction at the
cafe, which is called Tribeca. Nor are the muffins, the brownies or
the cappuccino cheesecake. Ongan and Karako are selling something
that they believe is even more irresistible. They are selling
America, a product that is becoming ever more popular here.
</P>
<P>
   The Tribeca cafe is hardly the only sign of growing American
influence in Turkey. Moviegoers flock not just to Hollywood epics
and animated features, but also to quirky films like ``The Big
Lebowski,'' which recently completed a long run. Multiplex movie
theaters have begun sprouting in big cities, and a new one opened
in Istanbul on Friday with features including ``Meet Joe Black''
and ``The Mask of Zorro.''
</P>
<P>
   Fast-food outlets led by McDonald's and Burger King are part of
many Turks' daily lives. In one Istanbul neighborhood, a Burger
King opened a few months ago just as a store next door that
specialized in stuffed grape leaves and other Turkish specialties
closed. Doughnuts have arrived in the form of three Dunkin' Donuts
outlets.
</P>
<P>
   During the recent Christmas season, more shop windows than ever
were decorated with holiday designs, and almost every shopping mall
featured visits from Santa Claus. This was despite the fact that
about 99 percent of Turks are Muslims, although many are highly
secular.
</P>
<P>
   The annual Istanbul Jazz Festival has become a magnet for
audiences hungry for American music. This year's scheduled
performers include Santana, John Lee Hooker and Grover Washington
Jr.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of Hollywood, America is becoming the official culture
of the whole world,'' Ongan said at Tribeca. ``Maybe people in
other countries don't understand what a bagel is, but they saw
Bruce Willis eating one in `Die Hard' so they want to eat the same
thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``A couple of cops came in here the other day, and we gave them
some coffee to take out in a paper cup, with a lid on top. They had
never had that before. They looked at each other for a minute, they
looked at the cups in their hands, and then one of them said: `Wow!
Just like N.Y.P.D. Blue'!
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``Turkey will stay Turkey. France will stay France. But that
American daily culture will become the world culture because
Hollywood is so powerful. It is a huge power.''
</P>
<P>
   The atmosphere at Tribeca evokes the United States. Framed
photos of the Manhattan skyline hang on the walls. The ceiling is
high with exposed beams. Behind a glass counter sit baskets of
poppy seed bagels, sesame bagels, cinnamon bagels and, in a
concession to local tastes, black olive bagels. Sixties tunes play
in the background.
</P>
<P>
   There are even plans for ``Seinfeld Nights,'' at which patrons
will be able to watch video reruns of the television show that came
to represent New York in the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Brady, a 28-year-old American architect who moved to
Istanbul two years ago, is a regular customer at Tribeca. She stops
in most mornings on her way to work for two mocha coffees and two
bagels.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what it is, but the place feels typically
American,'' Ms. Brady said. ``The bagels are very good, better than
any I've ever had outside of Boston or New York. The only thing
that's missing is those refillable car mugs. I'll have to bring one
back from Starbucks next time I'm in the States.''
</P>
<P>
   Turkey is full of teahouses, kebab houses, nightclubs where folk
music is played until dawn, and every variety of restaurant. But
the cafe where no alcohol is served, where one lingers over good
coffee and reads a newspaper or talks with friends, is something
new.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't Turkish style, like going to a kebab place,'' said
Asli Aslan, a young Turkish woman who sat with her friend at
Tribeca on a recent afternoon. ``I think I'll be coming here a
lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Not every Turk, however, has surrendered to the trend. ``It's
true that we are becoming very, very Americanized,'' said Gulser
Cetin, owner of a Turkish restaurant near the Tribeca cafe. ``But I
sense that the desire to eat Turkish and Ottoman food is slowly
coming back.''
</P>
<P>
   Ongan, who earned a degree in business administration at Fordham
University, and Karako, who worked for a Turkish-owned textile
concern in New York, have no intention of stopping where they are.
They plan to open a second Tribeca next month, and are scouting
locations for more than a dozen others. There are also plans for a
catering service and home delivery.
</P>
<P>
   ``My friends in New York all had full-time jobs, but they also
worked out, saw every new movie, had girlfriends and went to
restaurants,'' Ongan said. ``They were doing everything at the same
time. People don't do that here, but they have an idea that there's
a lifestyle like that in America. The common culture is
convenience. That's the style and the image we're selling.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
