<HEADER>
A8040 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-SPEECH-1STLD-     01-18 1170
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-SPEECH-1STLD-WRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STATE OF UNION TALK TO SHOW CLINTON PLANS TO REMAIN PRESIDENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: DELETES 6th graf beginning Clinton will become...)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEWART M. POWELL, MARK HELM And DAN FREEDMAN  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton, focusing on kitchen-table issues
rather than impeachment, on Monday readied a State of the Union
address that maps middle-of-the-road proposals to appeal to
traditional Democratic constituencies and Republican moderates.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton hoped to use the speech to show he plans to finish out
his presidency with forward-looking initiatives aimed at winning
support from women, suburbanites, minorities, the elderly and union
members as well as and the more conservative armed forces.
</P>
<P>
   The president is scheduled to deliver his annual address to a
joint meeting of the House and Senate at 9 p.m. EST Tuesday, just
hours after White House counsel Charles F.C. Ruff opens Clinton's
three-day defense in the Senate impeachment trial.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton stands accused of perjury and obstruction of justice in
trying to cover up a sexual relationship with former White House
intern Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials insisted that Clinton will not mention his
impeachment as he tries to set the nation's agenda as a lame-duck
president halfway through his second term.
</P>
<P>
   White House Press Secretary Joe Lockhart said Clinton looked
forward to speaking to the American people and dismissed
suggestions that the president would be uncomfortable speaking
before a GOP-led House that voted two articles of impeachment
against him on Dec. 19 and a Republican-led Senate that is weighing
his conviction and removal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president is always comfortable when he's dealing with
issues that impact real people's lives,'' Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
   Americans will come away from the nationally televised address
seeing ``an administration that is energized and is looking forward
to moving into the 21st century with an ambitious and activist
agenda,'' he predicted.
</P>
<P>
   White House aides said they hoped to keep the public focus on
Clinton's agenda with a quick trip to Buffalo, N.Y., and
Norristown, Pa., on Wednesday by the president, First Lady Hillary
Rodham Clinton, Vice President Al Gore and Mrs. Tipper Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Oppenheimer, a political scientist at Vanderbilt
University, said Clinton's decision to avoid mentioning impeachment
underscores his ``assumption that he's going to remain president.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul Rothstein, a law professor at Georgetown University, said
Clinton needed to make ``some vague reference'' to impeachment or
he would appear ``somehow disconnected from what's happening.''
Rothstein added: ``He can't ignore it entirely because it would
seem like he's unaware of most important event affecting his
life.''
</P>
<P>
   But Ross Baker, a political scientist at Rutgers University,
said he expects Clinton to try to present himself as ``absolutely
buoyant'' and ``act as if impeachment never happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the proposals Clinton will outline Tuesday night _ which
will make up the $1.8 trillion budget he submits to Congress on
Feb. 1 _ have already been leaked to the press.
</P>
<P>
   Aides said the initiatives will include sweeping changes in
federal support for locally-controlled public education, increased
federal spending on civil rights enforcement, a boost in the
minimum wage, tax breaks for Americans providing long-term care for
family members, increased federal support for after-school programs
to help working parents, and the largest Pentagon spending increase
since 1985, containing the biggest boost in pay and benefits for
the armed forces since 1981.
</P>
<P>
   Returning to a strategy that has given Democrats a wide edge
among women voters, Clinton will lay out a nationwide effort to
hold state and local school districts accountable for the
performance of students and teachers.
</P>
<P>
   He will also renew his call for $4 billion in federal spending
over five years for construction of new schools to relieve
overcrowding. Clinton will ask for more than $1 billion to help pay
for the hiring of 100,000 new teachers.
</P>
<P>
   As part of an $18 billion, five-year program to help working
parents take care of children, Clinton's address also outlines a
tax credit of up to $500 per child one year old or younger to add
federal support to parents who choose to stay home with their
infants.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton seeks tax breaks for Americans providing long-term care
for family members and increased federal support for after-school
programs to help working parents.
</P>
<P>
   In an appeal to middle-aged Baby Boomers who begin facing
retirement in 2011, Clinton will challenge Congress to devote a
projected $1.6 billion federal budget surplus over the next 10
years to bailing out the imperiled Social Security system rather
than using the money to finance GOP-backed tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton planned fresh efforts to help the poor by seeking
additional tax breaks for companies that invest in poor urban and
rural areas. He also will ask Congress for $1 billion over five
years to improve health care for many of the nation's 32 million
uninsured adults. The administration wants Congress to boost civil
rights enforcement spending by 15 percent to $663 million in the
fiscal year beginning on Oct. 1.
</P>
<P>
   In a move to preempt the GOP's cherished claim of being the
party that supports a strong national defense, Clinton will ask for
a $112 billion increase in Pentagon spending over the next six
years with a hike in pay and benefits for the nation's 1.4 million
armed forces.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's State of the Union address and his Feb. 1 budget
submission launch a nine-month period of bargaining between the
White House and the Congress over federal spending for the fiscal
year that begins Oct. 1.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   He faces an uphill battle. A study of the process in 1998
released by Congressional Quarterly, a weekly magazine, found that
Clinton prevailed in only 51 percent of the 154 House and Senate
floor votes that the White House took a position on last year.
</P>
<P>
   The study ranked Clinton's sixth-year performance with Congress
lower than those of his two-term predecessors going back 46 years
to President Dwight D. Eisenhower _ even lower than President
Richard M. Nixon's in 1974, when he was forced to resign in the
Watergate scandal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Almost none of the priorities that Clinton set at the
beginning of the year became law, and few of them even got a floor
vote,'' the authoritative publication reported
</P>
<P>
   When Nixon delivered his State of the Union address to Congress
in 1974 just eight months before resigning, he said, ``The time has
come to bring that (Watergate) investigation and the other
investigations of this matter to an end.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``I want you to know that I have no intention whatever
of walking away from the job that the people elected me to do for
the people of the United States.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
