<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 19:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8042 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-HEALTH-INSURANCE-2     01-18 1024
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-HEALTH-INSURANCE-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEALTH INSURANCE PRICE INCREASES HIT SMALL BUSINESSES HARD 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Optional trims indicated throughout.) 
(fe) 
 By JENNIFER STEINHAUER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When the notice came in December that his company's
health insurance premiums were going up 22 percent, Jonathan South
knew what he had to do.
</P>
<P>
   South, the office manager for a small Manhattan company that
makes costumes for Broadway shows, dropped the plan with Cigna
Health Care, one that allowed employees to go to doctors out of the
network and would now have cost the company $241 per employee each
month, and signed the company up for a plain vanilla health
maintenance plan offered by Aetna, at a cost of $179 a month.
</P>
<P>
   The company, Eric Winterling Inc., also cut its contribution to
its employees' premiums from 50 percent to 25 percent. Half of the
15 full-time employees chose to go without insurance, South said.
</P>
<P>
   While all U.S. businesses _ and in many cases, their employees _
are facing some of the steepest price increases for health
insurance in almost 10 years, small businesses are feeling the
worst of it, insurance experts and business owners say.
</P>
<P>
   For small employers, the increases have led to tough decisions
about whether to absorb the higher costs, pass them on to employees
or not offer benefits at all. The problem is particularly
pronounced in New York, where several factors combine to make the
increases even less palatable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly small businesses are getting whacked,'' said Elliott
Shaw, the director of government affairs for the New York State
Business Council. ``Unlike in the '80s, when everyone had the same
experiences, in the last six months larger employers have been able
to keep their increases at inflation, and small businesses are
seeing double digits.''
</P>
<P>
   In January, insurance prices for businesses with more than 100
employees rose about 6 percent on average around the country,
experts said, while small businesses are facing increases in the
range of 10 percent to 13 percent, with more increases expected.
The New York State Insurance Department is considering requests
from several companies for rate increases for small businesses
ranging from 7 percent to more than 600 percent.
</P>
<P>
   And in New York, where small businesses employ more than half
the state's work force, there are deeper implications than simply
higher rates.
</P>
<P>
   The cost of doing business, especially in New York City, is
significantly higher than in other areas, making increases all the
more painful. Further, New York has the most stringent form of
community rating _ businesses with fewer than 50 employees are
subject to prices set by geographic area _ giving small businesses
no negotiating power with insurance companies.
</P>
<P>
   Most gravely, New York's uninsured population is far higher than
the country's average _ 28 percent versus 17 percent _ and
employees who become priced out of the market may end up adding to
the numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Five years ago small businesses were among the most vociferous
opponents of President Clinton's failed health plan, arguing that
if they were forced to offer health insurance benefits to
employees, many would go broke. But some analysts argue that the
Clinton plan would probably have led to more uniform rates, easing
the economic strain that small companies are now facing.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to ease this strain, Clinton administration
officials said Monday that the president would propose a tax credit
for companies with fewer than 25 workers that established or joined
purchasing alliances to buy insurance.
</P>
<P>
   The effect of the latest increases will vary according to the
fiscal health and, in some cases, the generosity of the companies.
While the extremely tight labor market will make it difficult for
employers to drop health insurance entirely, employees will see
costs increase in the form of greater weekly contributions, raised
deductibles and co-payments, or less generous plans.
</P>
<P>
   Further, many employers who were thinking of adding insurance
this year may find the costs prohibitive, Shaw said, while
struggling companies may be forced to eliminate benefits.
</P>
<P>
   As it is, 73 percent of the state's uninsured population
consists of people who have jobs, like Sarup Arora and his
employees at Party Glitters, a store in Brooklyn. ``Right now, we
pay cash when we go to the doctor and try not to get sick,'' Arora
said.
</P>
<P>
   Many companies are still enrolling in insurance programs, and
others will not renew their contracts until later this year. But
the increases are giving some employees pause.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Nathan, who owns the restaurant Frontiere in SoHo,
regrets that he cannot offer insurance to more of his employees. He
has insurance for only himself and his two managers, but the
restaurant covers the full cost, even in the face of rate
increases.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't turn to a restaurant manager and say, `I can't pay
that,''' he said. ``A restaurant manager often works an 80-hour
week. They have a high rate of sickness. So insurance is a costly
necessity. I would love to be able to offer it to more employees if
I could be financially successful and do it.''
</P>
<P>
   And many employees who are offered insurance feel they cannot
afford to take it because of the amount they must contribute. ``I
have considered it, but basically I can't afford it,'' said
Laurence Woodbury, the manager of Doggie-Do, a pet grooming,
boarding and retail store on the Upper East Side.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   His boss, Larry Roth, pays half of the company's policy with
Oxford, which went from $300 to $336 a month recently. He was
dismayed by the increase, Roth said, and ponders what he will do if
there is an increase next year. ``I find this is the perk that is
most significant to employees,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Woodbury said he cannot find it in his budget to pay.
``I probably don't worry about it because I probably don't think
about it,'' he said. ``I know that's not very smart. But I very
rarely get ill. What worries me is getting hit by a bus.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   While small businesses make up the largest employer group in the
country and are a powerful lobbying voice, individually they
generally hold little power with suppliers, including insurance
companies.
</P>
<P>
   The companies charge higher rates to small businesses because
their volume is smaller and because the risk of illness is spread
out among fewer people. And with community rating, which was
intended to spread that risk among employers, small businesses are
barred from cutting their own deals.
</P>
<P>
   In opposing the Clinton health care plan, small businesses, led
by the National Federation of Independent Businesses, argued that
they could contain costs better on their own.
</P>
<P>
   And indeed in recent years, employers have faced modest
increases as insurance companies fought for market share, often
offering discounted rates to win business. But a recent
consolidation among the managed-care companies and their
realization that they could not make money offering such low
premiums have caused the rates to rise sharply in the last six
months, taking many employers and their workers by surprise.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think these businesses were deluded into thinking that the
private sector had discovered a panacea for medical costs,'' said
Ted Marmor, a professor of politics at the Yale School of
Management, who has written extensively on health care policy.
``And this is a case of getting what they feared, partly out of the
actions they took to avoid it.''
</P>
<P>
   The business federation does not see it that way. ``Is it cause
for growing concern? Absolutely,'' said Jim Weidman, a spokesman
for the organization. ``But at least now small employers can still
drop insurance, and under the Clinton plan, they would be out of
business. And when push comes to shove, health insurance is a
benefit. We think it is far better to have a job with no benefits
than no job.''
</P>
<P>
   Addressing rising health insurance costs among small businesses
has become a concern with New York City's government _ the rise of
the uninsured is a major public policy problem and is already
putting strains on the city's hospital system.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor's office has announced two pilot plans to try to deal
with the issue. One would offer discounted rates to small business
owners on two of the Health and Hospitals Corp's managed care plans
that require patients to use certain public hospitals and their
doctors. The plan will begin in East Harlem and parts of Brooklyn
and the Bronx this winter.
</P>
<P>
   The other City Hall plan, a joint venture with the New York
Business Group on Health, will form an insurance purchasing
alliance for small businesses. Under this program, employers will
be able to buy insurance through a central office and offer each
employee a choice of many plans. The company can choose to
subsidize the least expensive option, and the worker who wants a
fancier plan can pay the difference.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The advantage, said Laurel Pickering, managing director of the
Business Group, is that employers will have access to many plans
and will not longer have to do the administrative work, one of the
biggest hassles with insurance companies.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Purchasing groups, in a variety of forms, have been used with
varying success around the country. The Council of Smaller
Enterprises in Cleveland, for instance, started one of the
country's first joint purchasing programs 20 years ago and now
offers insurance to 13,000 companies, employing 200,000 people. The
council's program is quite different from New York's _ it offers
only one carrier but is its largest client.
</P>
<P>
   That alliance has helped to hold insurance costs for small
employers in northeast Ohio 20 percent lower than the national
average, said Rob Fowler, executive director of group, who added,
``It's pure price for volume.''
</P>
<P>
   While New York's plan is less ambitious, it has already drawn an
eager audience. ``It will be great,'' said Bill Berry, president of
Berry Communications, a public relations firm with three employees.
``Now we can all pick our own plan. Before, if they hated their
health care, they would hate me. With five choices, everyone will
be able to find something.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the fact that employees will be absorbing more of the
costs is almost inevitable.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Robert Barber, a graphic designer and senior associate at
Russell Design Associates in Manhattan, said that when he worked
for a big company, he paid about $150 a month for insurance for
himself, his wife and two children. Now, he pays $800 a month.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like I have no options,'' he said. ``A lot of people
don't pay that much for rent. And everything I read about HMOs
makes me think they don't know what they are doing and they might
double all the rates tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   His boss, Anthony Russell, who owns the firm and watched Oxford
raise his rates 10 percent in January, said that while he does not
contemplate dropping health insurance, he hates telling his
employees about rate increases.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is always difficult for us to have to be the surrogate for
the insurer,'' Russell said. ``They are insulated from 15 screaming
employees, and I resent having to explain it every time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
