A8044 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HAIR-WARS-ART-NYT     01-18 0971
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HAIR-WARS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STYLISTS AND MODELS IN `HAIR WARS' TOUR CONVERGE ON LOS ANGELES
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Calif., Nev., Fla., Ind.) (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(bl) 
By DON TERRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The City of Angels has seen its share of war.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, there have been gang wars, water wars and, on
Oscar night, star wars. And as dusk fell Sunday, a hair war broke
out in a hotel near the airport, the site of numerous fare wars.
</P>
<P>
   This war is an intense competition and showcase for hairstylists
from across the country.
</P>
<P>
   It is a chance for them to let their imaginations run wild and
their inhibitions, if they have any, disappear _ say, into a
glittery hair sculpture that is twisted, teased, pressed, curled,
sprayed and colored to look like an airplane, complete with
motorized propellers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hair entertainment,'' said David Humphries, who started
the ``Hair Wars'' 12 years ago in a small nightclub in Detroit.
``They're not the kind of hairstyles you wear to work.''
</P>
<P>
   Humphries, who is an event promoter, not a stylist, said that
Detroit was ``the hair capital of the world'' and the wars there
were legendary. But as often as he can, he takes the show on the
road in his ``Hair Wars U.S. Tour.''
</P>
<P>
   About 75 designers and as many as 300 models competed Sunday and
Monday; in addition to Los Angeles, other scheduled stops on the
tour are Las Vegas, Miami and the deck of a Caribbean cruise ship.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hair,'' Humphries said, ``is big business.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday night was the all-California night and about 20 teams of
designers from Los Angeles, Compton, Riverside, San Diego and
elsewhere competed. Their models strutted down a fashion-show-style
runway, spinning this way and that to show off their sparkling
costumes and color-coordinated hairdos, some of which curled and
spiked more than a foot into the air.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some designers hire professional models and sound technicians
to do their skits,'' Humphries said. ``Other people just get their
cousins and sisters.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday it was designers from the East Coast versus designers
from the West Coast. But the hair wars, Humphries said, are more
showcase than competition. Usually, there is no prize money and no
one is declared the winner. The contestants pay their own way to
the wars and do so, he said, to build a name for themselves in the
business of beauty.
</P>
<P>
   Before the competition began Sunday, the master of ceremonies,
LaToya Pearson, told the audience of at least 300 to be respectful
of all the participants.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'll see some tall models and short models and light models
and dark models, some gay models and straight models,'' Ms. Pearson
said. ``Remember, if you can't say anything nice, don't say
anything at all.''
</P>
<P>
   As the models pranced across the stage, Ms. Pearson offered
words of encouragement. ``Walk for me, walk for me,'' she said.
``Come on, throw that hair.''
</P>
<P>
   Then one of the male models caught her eye. ``You're kind of
cute, honey,'' she said. ``Are you single? You are. Do you like old
ladies with money?''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the stylists battling it out in the wars are men, like
Keith Watkins, the designer of the airplane of hair.
</P>
<P>
   Watkins said he used 102 bags of human hair to build his plane,
shaped like a B-52 bomber. He said each bag contained about 12 feet
of hair. The plane is taken on and off the model like a helmet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been in the industry for 17 years,'' said Watkins, 38.
``I was always sort of artsy and nerdy. Science fair was my
favorite event of the year when I was a kid. Hair was the perfect
blend of the two.''
</P>
<P>
   A body builder and hair designer, Big Bad D legally changed his
name and got into the business 14 years ago when he was laid off
from his job at an auto plant in Detroit. Losing his job was a
blessing, he said. Nowadays, he wears an enormous gold ring shaped
like a pair of scissors, and he designed his own salon chair, a
$50,000-throne made out of alligator skin with gold and diamond
claws.
</P>
<P>
   Big Bad D was not competing. Instead, he signed up his top
stylist from Detroit, Cool C, ``the hair superstar.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I enjoy taking a woman from `Cousin It' to a hit,'' said Cool
C, 25. ``You ever see Michael Jordan play basketball? Well, I'm on
that level when it comes to hair.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the designers in the wars are African-American, but
everyone is welcome. Anna (Lucky) Schnitt, 27, a white designer
from Indianapolis, brought several models to Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Two of her models, June Sullivan, 22, who works with the
mentally retarded, and Renita Moore, 26, a claims adjuster for an
insurance company, are African-American and often find themselves
telling disbelieving acquaintances that, yes, ``a white girl did
our hair.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have to teach her or get in her chair and tell her
what I want,'' said Ms. Moore, who was sporting a series of curls
and loops called a roller coaster. ``She knows. She's the baddest
white girl in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Schnitt said she knew so much about African-American hair
care and design because when she was 4 her German mother married a
black American soldier, and she was ``raised in a black family.''
</P>
<P>
   She has been doing hair professionally for seven years and has
built up a loyal following. Some of her clients take her hair
creations with them to the grave, like a 16-year-old girl who
recently died.
</P>
<P>
   When the girl was alive, her mother refused to allow her to wear
colored hair extensions. But the mother called Ms. Schnitt after
her daughter's death and asked her to put the extensions in for her
funeral.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've told all my clients,'' Ms. Schnitt said, ``that if they
pass away, I'll do their hair for free.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
