<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 19:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8048 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TELEMARKETING-CALLS-T     01-18 1089
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TELEMARKETING-CALLS-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS BILLS MAY HELP CURB TELEMARKETING ABUSE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By POLLY ROSS HUGHES 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Texans could hang up on telemarketing calls for
good if a legislative bill that has the stamp of approval of the
state's utility regulators becomes law.
</P>
<P>
   Under the proposal, anyone who wants to ban uninvited salesmen
from ringing up at mealtime or otherwise making themselves a pest
could sign up for a single, statewide ``don't-call'' list.
</P>
<P>
   Telemarketers who persisted in calling numbers on the list would
face hefty fines from the Texas Public Utility Commission, up to
$5,000 a day for each violation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is you've got all these people who are on the
phone just constantly barraging people, saying we want to sell you
this, sell you that. There have been too many complaints,'' said
state Sen. Gonzalo Barrientos, D-Austin. His proposal to curb
telemarketing abuse, Senate Bill 120, has companion legislation,
House Bill 537, sponsored by Rep. Debra Danburg, D-Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of complaints have rolled into the PUC from angry
telephone customers who have pleaded to no avail for individual
telemarketers to quit calling. Even though current federal and
state laws require companies to maintain and respect their own
``don't call'' lists, enforcement authority remains weak and
ineffective, said Saralee Tiede, the PUC's chief of customer
protection.
</P>
<P>
   Out of 562 telephone solicitation complaints the PUC
investigated in the last fiscal year, more than 400 were about
companies that called even after customers asked to be put on their
internal ``don't-call'' lists.
</P>
<P>
   The problem, Tiede said, is that current state law gives
telemarketers so many chances to avoid penalties that the PUC has
only been able to fine one telemarketer _ a Central Texas home
security company called Protect America _ $5,000 for repeated
violations. No penalties have been levied so far this year, even
though complaints in the first four months had already surpassed
the number in the previous full year.
</P>
<P>
   ``What they have sought to do is really tighten up the
(telemarketing) statute and make it much easier to enforce,'' Tiede
said of the legislation. ``It's really a great improvement.''
</P>
<P>
   She expects the statewide ``do not call'' list to be popular.
</P>
<P>
   The impetus for a bigger crackdown grew out of hearings this
past year by the House Subcommittee on Telemarketing, in which
legislators said members of their own staffs had witnessed
companies and organizations ignoring their internal don't-call
lists.
</P>
<P>
   Five other states have already passed similar laws _ Alaska,
Florida, Georgia, Kentucky and Oregon _ to good effect, they say.
In Georgia, where the telemarketing law is new, 90,000 people
signed on to the list the first month it was offered, according to
Tiede.
</P>
<P>
   Rallying nationwide to rein in telemarketing is the American
Association of Retired Persons, which is making passage of such
don't-call bills a priority in every state.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 140,000 telemarketers nationally generate annual
sales of $550 billion, the AARP told the House subcommittee on
telemarketing last spring. The organization noted that about
one-tenth of those telemarketers are believed to be scam artists
who prey on people who are 55 and older. More than three-fourths of
those victimized by telemarketing scams fall into that age group.
</P>
<P>
   Law enforcement stings, according to the AARP, have even
uncovered unscrupulous companies that obtained lists of patients
with Alzheimer's disease to target.
</P>
<P>
   Others who have been ripped off are well-educated people who
simply don't expect anyone to lie to them.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Alexander of Levelland, near Lubbock, is a grandmother of
18 who grew up in an age when people could be trusted. So, she
believed the man on the phone when he said, ``Oh Mary! You have
won. You have won the big money!''
</P>
<P>
   She wasn't sure exactly which sweepstakes she had entered, but
the man on the phone said it was in Canada. She must pay a duty,
however, before he could send her the big winnings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I didn't have that kind of money in my personal account,
so I had to charge it to my Visa card,'' said the homemaker.
</P>
<P>
   The first time it happened, Alexander sent $1,950 from her Visa
account ``and guess what?'' she said. ``I never heard from him
again.'' She's embarrassed to admit it happened again. Another call
from Canada, another $2,000 for duties or taxes, and nothing in
return but an angry husband.
</P>
<P>
   ``What grabbed the representatives was she said she was paying
the Visa (card) back with money out of her Social Security every
month. It just brought tears to your eyes,'' said the AARP's Mary
Lee Comer.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're trying to do is draw a line in the sand. If you put
your name on a non-call list and you continue to be called anyway,
then you know these people are fraudulent because the legitimate
telemarketers and those trying to do the right thing will not call
you,'' she added. ``We're not after all telemarketers. We very well
realize there are people in this country who could not have any
part in our economy if they were not telemarketers.''
</P>
<P>
   The Direct Marketing Association, however, told the committee
that the industry's national and voluntary don't-call list combined
with federal restrictions that bar calls for 10 years to anyone
asking to sign a don't-call list are safeguards enough.
</P>
<P>
   Victor Alcorta, who represents the group's legal interests in
Austin, said he questions whether the PUC's authority allows it to
fine telemarketers operating from outside the state's lines. The
jurisdiction has not been legally challenged, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Inside Texas, Alcorta added, some 20,000 to 100,000 companies
that sell by phone could be harmed.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of jobs out there. This would affect Texas
callers to Texans and a lot of Texas telemarketers,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The subcommittee, however, noted that a 1994 federal law aimed
at telephone consumer fraud gives state law enforcement officers
the ability to prosecute telemarketers calling Texas from other
states.
</P>
<P>
   C. Tyler Prochnow, an attorney representing the American
Teleservices Organization, said statewide don't-call lists, such as
the one proposed for Texas, raise First Amendment freedom of speech
issues. In addition, he said, ``It creates a tremendous amount of
confusion for companies doing business in all 50 states.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
