<SLUG> BC-FBN-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: NO HISTORY, NO FUTURE, ENJOY 1998
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HEMPSTEAD, N.Y. _ At the risk of depressing all Jets fans _ and
there are many more than four months ago _ forget all the babble
about 1998 being the steppingstone to some kind of dynasty.
</P>
<P>
   Put bluntly, next season could stink. Instead, Jets' fans should
relish what Vinny Testaverde and Keyshawn Johnson and Moe Lewis
gave them in the here and now.
</P>
<P>
   The fans should savor it, embrace it, because it may not come
around again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Football is a very transient thing,'' said the coach, Bill
Parcells, looking wan on very little sleep Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The players cannot caress this season because that is not the
nature of their highly pragmatic business. They fumbled, they held,
they blanked out. They lost to the Denver Broncos, 23-10, and they
must look upon that as a failure.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't go to the Super Bowl, nothing's changed,'' said
Keyshawn Johnson, a mensch all season. ``If you don't set your goal
on the Super Bowl, you might as well leave it alone. Give yourself
an extra month's vacation.''
</P>
<P>
   New York being Knee-Jerk City, you could hear it both
extravagant ways Monday. The truly shabby point of view is that the
leering gap-toothed ghost of seasons past somehow pursued the Jets
all the way to Denver and cut off their oxygen supply.
</P>
<P>
   How disrespectful that theory is to the grunts on the line, the
special-team zealots, the so-called skill players, who thrived from
September right through the old witching month of December.
</P>
<P>
   In the age of Parcells, this was a new team, with a new attitude
and new capability. This was a sound football team that worked
hard, that earned the respect of the fans, and in the end made too
many mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very disappointing to be this close,'' said Testaverde,
the local boy from Elmont, just down the Hempstead Turnpike from
here. ``It's very disappointing to be packing up your bags and
going home.''
</P>
<P>
   Packing up is too elegant a phrase. Packing up implies luggage.
Essentially the players throw what they want in garbage sacks and
drag them out to their sport utility vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, Pasta, I'll call you,'' shouted Ray Lucas, the utility
back.
</P>
<P>
   ``All right, Luke,'' Testaverde called out.
</P>
<P>
   There was the sense that most of these guys liked each other, a
far cry from recent Jets' teams. Winning does that, along with
Parcells' inspired goading.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now the younger guys understand what it takes to get to the
Super Bowl,'' Testaverde said, hopefully.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, there are no Six Easy Steps to a Better Super Bowl Life,
to paraphrase Cosmo covers. There have been precious few dynasties
in recent years, as free agency made every season unique.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at Pittsburgh last year,'' said Bryan Cox, the combative
old linebacker. ``Look at the Giants. They played so well last
year, they had high expectations. Kansas City had a great record
and didn't live up to expectations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to sneak up on anybody next year,'' Cox
continued, referring to the weighted schedule that gives better
teams slightly tougher schedules in search of parity. ``We're going
to play the toughest schedule in our division next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some guys are not going to be in this locker room next year,''
Cox added. ``We are going to have to bond again.''
</P>
<P>
   Cox came out of the morning session with Parcells swearing to
work harder next time: ``We need to understand. I need to
understand. I don't want to gain my 30 pounds in the off-season.
I'm going to cut down on my alcohol intake, cut down on fatty
foods, take long walks with my wife.''
</P>
<P>
   On this last morning of the 1998 season, Cox did permit himself
a moment of nostalgia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had fun,'' he said. ``We won a lot of games. We dispelled
the myth of the New York Jets. We put in a lot of effort. We did a
lot of good things. This was as good as it gets, without getting to
the Super Bowl. If this happens again next year, I'll be happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Nobody would predict it could happen again. Parcells, who came
back after heart surgery, gets the booby prize of having to coach
in the Pro Bowl, not what his cardiologist might propose.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells wasn't blustering about changes, but Bill Belichick
could take one of the jobs in Kansas City or Chicago, and free
agents could depart, and trades could happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what the 1999 New York Jets will look like,''
Parcells said.
</P>
<P>
   The 1998 Jets looked like winners. Out of respect to the coaches
and players, the fans just might want to hold on to that image for
a while.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-18-99 1907EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
