<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 19:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8067 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-AUSTRALIA-OPEN-NY     01-18 0992
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-AUSTRALIA-OPEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RIOS AND IVANISEVIC JOIN SAMPRAS ON THE INJURY LIST
</HEADLINE>
   (ms) 
 By CHRISTOPHER CLAREY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MELBOURNE, Australia _ Pete Sampras announced his withdrawal
from the Australian Open in December, when he was home in the
United States. Marcelo Rios and Goran Ivanisevic waited until they
traveled all the way to Melbourne.
</P>
<P>
   Bad backs were the culprits in both Rios' and Ivanisevic's case.
</P>
<P>
   Rios, seeded No. 1 in Sampras' absence, announced his withdrawal
in the late Monday, the first day of play at the Open, because of a
stress fracture in his second lumbar vertebra. David Bolzonello,
the tournament physician, said the injury would likely keep Rios
from practicing for three to four weeks and from returning to the
tour for at least six weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's a good chance he will be playing in March,''
Bolzonello said.
</P>
<P>
   Several hours earlier, the 11th-seeded Ivanisevic had withdrawn
shortly before he was scheduled to play his match because of an
inflamed disk. Ivanisevic could be out of action for several weeks,
as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did the same thing as Sampras,'' Ivanisevic said of his
withdrawal. ``The only difference is I picked up my pass.''
</P>
<P>
   On the courts, top-seeded Lindsay Davenport routed Gala Leon
Garcia of Spain in straight sets.
</P>
<P>
   But Alex Corretja, seeded second but now the top remaining
player in the men's draw, needed five sets to defeat 116th-ranked
Takao Suzuki of Japan, 6-3, 4-6, 3-6, 7-6 (7-5), 6-2.
</P>
<P>
   It was fitting that Suzuki was making his Grand Slam debut in
Australia because he plays like the Australians of yore: pushing
forward to the net whenever possible and patrolling it with
gumption and grace. Monday, he played the style well enough against
Corretja to serve for the match at 5-4 in the fourth set.
</P>
<P>
   But at 15-15, Corretja assumed command as Suzuki stopped
punching his volleys with the same assurance. The Spaniard won the
next point after hitting a looping backhand return that landed on
the line and forced Suzuki to retreat and fire up a weak lob. He
won the next point with a cocksure forehand pass down the line. He
then broke Suzuki's serve by passing him down the line with a
backhand.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice to know that even if you are struggling and you
trust in yourself, good things can happen,'' Corretja said.
</P>
<P>
   Corretja still had to rally from a 3-0 deficit in the fourth-set
tie breaker, but once he had managed that, the fifth set was a
denouement.
</P>
<P>
   Third-seeded Patrick Rafter came out of his recent funk and
defeated Oliver Gross in straight sets.
</P>
<P>
   Rafter then expressed his concern that Petr Korda was able to
defend his title in this tournament after testing positive for the
steroid nandrolone and having his one-year suspension rescinded by
an appeals committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``My opinion on that is I think it's probably killing the
sport,'' Rafter said. ``If someone gets tested in any other sport,
they are out straight away. That's not the case in tennis, and I
think that should be the case unless Petr has got a bloody good
explanation, and we didn't hear it.''
</P>
<P>
   With Korda scheduled to play Tuesday, Rios, the gifted man he
beat in last year's Australian Open final, will rest and ruminate.
He will drop from No. 2 to at least No. 5 in the world ranking and
will drop much lower if his lower back does not allow him to defend
his titles at Indian Wells and Key Biscayne in March.
</P>
<P>
   He has been troubled by leg injuries and back soreness often in
the last three months, and Bolzonello indicated that the same
magnetic resonance imaging scan that revealed his stress fracture
Monday also showed evidence of a previous stress injury on the
other side of the same vertebra.
</P>
<P>
   ``These injuries are potentially serious for all athletes,
particularly those involved in a sport that involves extension of
the back,'' Bolzonello said. ``Now, we that we know it's there he
can follow the appropriate treatment, which is essentially rest,
and there's a very good chance it will heal without any concerns in
the next few weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   There were only two upsets on the opening day: No. 13-seeded
Irina Spirlea was beaten by Anke Huber, the former Australian Open
finalist, 7-5, 6-4. The only seeded men's player to lose was No. 16
Thomas Johansson of Sweden, who had two match points in the fourth
set but ended up losing in the fifth to Nicolas Lapentti of
Ecuador.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Krajicek, seeded ninth, was impressive in his four-set
victory over the creative Hicham Arazi of Morocco. Michael Chang,
unseeded here after an injury filled season in 1998, defeated Brett
Steven of New Zealand in straight sets and will face 14th-seeded
Mark Philippoussis of Australia in the second round.
</P>
<P>
   Venus Williams struggled to a 3-6, 6-3, 9-7 victory over
82nd-ranked Silvija Talaja of Croatia. The fifth-seeded Williams
made a rash of unforced errors _ 87 in three sets _ and struggled
with her serve, double-faulting nine times and often under
pressure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today was an all-time low for the last two weeks,'' the
18-year-old Williams said of her play.
</P>
<P>
   Talaja, a consistent 20-year-old baseliner, forced a number of
Williams' errors by chasing down her powerful ground strokes and
drawing her into long rallies. But Williams shot herself in the
sneaker without assistance, too, and when she served to stay in the
match at 4-5, she soon found herself down by 0-30 on her serve.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just said to myself that this is not my fate; this is
someone else's fate,'' Williams said. ``I can't go out like this.''
</P>
<P>
   As fate would have it, she wouldn't, and Talaja, just two points
from a major upset, lost the next four. She would stay with
Williams until 7-7. But the more experienced Williams prevailed.
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Capriati, the former phenom turned journeywoman, won
her first match at the Australian Open since 1993 by defeating an
Australian teen-ager, Evie Dominikovic, 5-7, 6-3, 8-6. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
