<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 19:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8075 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-DEFENSE-BOS &LR;      01-18 1012
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-DEFENSE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON MOUNTS DOUBLE-BARRELED DEFENSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KRANISH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a double-edged presidential power play,
President Clinton sends his defense team to the Senate Tuesday to
argue against impeachment charges, to be followed by his
state-of-the-union speech to Congress, which Clinton hopes will
reinforce his standing in the polls.
</P>
<P>
   While many Republicans and even some leading Democrats had urged
Clinton to delay the speech until after the Senate impeachment
trial is over, the White House sees a nexus between the two events
that could help the president. With Clinton aides assuming that
most Senate Republicans would vote to convict Clinton, the White
House is anxious to ensure that Clinton's public standing remains
high and thus reassure Senate Democrats it is politically safe to
back the president.
</P>
<P>
   The juxtaposition of the two events prompted some Republicans to
consider walking out on the speech or refusing to applaud, but GOP
leaders over the weekend instructed party members to attend the
speech and clap respectfully. Clinton is expected to make several
proposals that he hopes will resonate with both Democrats and
Republicans, such as a measure to ensure that schools receiving
federal funds meet higher standards, and a renewed call for Social
Security reform.
</P>
<P>
   White House press secretary Joseph Lockhart told reporters at a
briefing Monday that counsel Charles Ruff, widely considered to be
the president's most effective legal defender, will be the sole
attorney speaking at the trial, which resumes at 1 p.m. Ruff will
deliver two themes, aides said. First, he will argue that Clinton
did not commit perjury or obstruct justice, as alleged in the
impeachment articles. Secondly, Ruff will argue that even if
senators believe the charges are true, they do not rise to the
level of ``high crimes and misdemeanors'' needed to convict the
president.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe we have a compelling case to make based on the law,
the facts and the Constitution,'' Lockhart said. ``We will do that.
We look forward to that.''
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart also fired another rhetorical salvo at the House
managers of the trial, saying they are ``singlemindedly'' focused
on having witnesses, even though no witnesses with first-hand
knowledge of the case appeared before the House Judiciary
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that is a stunning admission that they don't believe
that the case that they sent over from the House, and the case that
they presented to the Senate, is strong, and is strong enough to do
what they've set out to do from the beginning, which is remove the
president,'' Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the week, the Clinton legal team's strategy will be
to vigorously fight against as many details as possible in the
charges. An underlying goal during the alloted 24 hours of defense
is to try to convince the Senate that it is not necessary to call
witnesses, which adds an unpredictability factor that Clinton aides
want to avoid.
</P>
<P>
   But with Republicans controlling the Senate 55-45, and only 51
votes needed to call a witness, the White House is preparing for
the growing possibility that former intern Monica S. Lewinsky and
others may be called to the testify in the well of the Senate. As a
result, Clinton's legal team hopes this week to spread doubts about
the usefulness of such testimony. For example, Clinton lawyers will
highlight many lines of testimony from Lewinsky, presidential
secretary Betty Currie and lawyer Vernon Jordan that could be
helpful to the president.
</P>
<P>
   In the most frequently cited testimony, the White House has
noted that Lewinsky said that no one asked her to lie and no one
offered her a job in exchange for her silence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that witnesses certainly could help the case,''
Lockhart said. ``There could be exculpatory information. There is
exculpatory information.''
</P>
<P>
   But as the House managers of the prosecution noted during the
last week, Lewinsky also said that no one discouraged her from
lying and that she knew what Clinton wanted her to say.
</P>
<P>
   Representative George Gekas, the Pennsylvania Republican and one
of 13 House managers of the trial, said Lewinsky's testimony is so
strong against the president that he is surprised Clinton hasn't
volunteered to testify in rebuttal.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a choice that the president would have to make,'' Gekas
said on CNN Monday. ``As a matter of fact, I always felt that
because Monica Lewinsky's testimony is largely unchallenged,
undenied, uncontradicted, as it were, that the president's lawyers
would want to put the president on to contradict that testimony.''
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton aides said the president has no plans to testify.
Instead, Clinton will rely largely on three lawyers: Ruff, Gregory
B. Craig and David Kendall. It is the same trio that defended
Clinton unsuccessfully before the House Judiciary Committee, which
approved the articles of impeachment that subsequently were backed
by the full House and sent to the Senate for trial.
</P>
<P>
   One of the House managers said Monday that it is possible the
White House team might persuade the Senate not to call witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think in this case anything is a foregone
conclusion,'' Representative Asa Hutchinson, the Arkansas
Republican, said Monday on NBC-TV's ``Today'' show. ``Certainly,
the White House defense team, which are terrific advocates for the
president, quality lawyers, will make an outstanding defense this
week, and I'm sure that no decision will be made until after
that.''
</P>
<P>
   White House officials, meanwhile, clearly were hoping that the
president's state of the union speech would boost his standing
during this crucial phase of the trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think at the end of the speech, people will look not at an
administration that has entered the last two years of office and is
slowing down,'' Lockhart said, ``but an administration that is
energized and is looking forward to moving into the 21st century
with an ambitious and activist agenda.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
