<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOTUS-DELAY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOTUS NEEDS MORE TIME FOR NOTES UPGRADE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORLANDO, Fla. _ Corporate software buyers waiting to get their
hands on the latest version of Lotus Notes will have to wait a
little bit longer. But many of them think it'll be worth the wait.
</P>
<P>
   At Lotus Development Corp.'s annual Lotusphere conference at
Walt Disney World, chief executive Jeff Papows had been expected to
announce that the product was ready to ship. Instead, Papows said
the schedule had slipped again. ``We need two to three more weeks
for polishing,'' he said. But when he vowed the new product would
ship next month, the audience of about 5,000 erupted in cheers.
</P>
<P>
   ``That wasn't the expected reaction,'' said a surprised Papows.
``Maybe we ought to slip a few more products.''
</P>
<P>
   Papows got still more cheers when he promised a Linux version of
Domino, the server software that powers Notes. At Lotusphere in
Berlin last year, Papows had rejected the idea of supporting Linux,
the free Unix-like operating system that has developed a growing
following in recent months. But he said his comments in Berlin had
generated a storm of controversy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I literally got back and had more hate mail than you can
imagine,'' he said, ``much of it from my boss.''
</P>
<P>
   Lotus has been promising R5, a new version of the Notes and
Domino groupware programs, since 1997, but there have been numerous
delays in rolling out the product. Now the stakes are especially
high, as Lotus faces fierce competition from Microsoft Corp. and
its Exchange groupware product. Papows called R5 the most important
software release at Lotus since the Cambridge, Mass. company
introduced Notes in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Back then, Lotus found the product a tough sell. Few companies
knew what groupware was, much less how it could be of benefit to
them. Today, it's a multibillion-dollar market. Companies use
groupware to exchange information in highly selective and
sophisticated ways that go far beyond standard e-mail. For
instance, groupware allows teams of workers scattered all over the
world to collaborate on the same documents.
</P>
<P>
   R5 is designed to make the process easier and more powerful. The
new Notes version is designed to resemble an Internet browser, so
that many advanced Notes features can be used simply by pointing
and clicking.
</P>
<P>
   It also features an instant messaging component. A user will be
able to see at a glance if colleagues are logged on to the system.
If they are, he'll be able to type messages to them in real time,
instead of waiting for a response to e-mail. In addition, the front
page of Notes will feature a selection of news and information
provided by America Online Inc. as part of a strategic partnership
between Lotus and AOL.
</P>
<P>
   The Notes client _ the part that resides on a user's desktop
machine _ will be entirely based on Internet standards, so that it
can be used for all types of e-mail, not just mail from a Lotus
server. It's expected to sell for a list price of $29.
</P>
<P>
   The new version of Domino server has been upgraded for easier
control by system administrators, and for easier migration to Notes
from other messaging programs, including Exchange and Lotus'
earlier e-mail product, cc:Mail.
</P>
<P>
   The new versions of Notes and Domino should give Lotus an edge
in this year's market share battle with Microsoft. Papows said
Microsoft probably won't upgrade Exchange again until it completes
work on Windows 2000, its high-end operating system. Windows 2000
will contain a feature called Active Directory that will be used by
Exchange to match some of the features of Notes.
</P>
<P>
   But Windows 2000, which was supposed to have shipped last year,
has suffered repeated delays. Microsoft announced Friday that a
third beta version of the software would be delayed yet again. But
the company still vows Windows 2000 will ship by the end of the
year.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the delay gives Lotus more time to cement its position
in groupware. Papows bragged that Lotus sold 5 million Notes
licenses in the fourth quarter of 1998, for a 1998 total of 14.2
million seats, two million more than they'd expected. That means
there are now 34 million Notes users, compared to about 20 million
last year.
</P>
<P>
   That is considerably higher than last week's estimate from
International Data Corp. in Framingham, Mass. IDC estimated there
are now just under 30 million Notes users, compared to 21 million
users of Microsoft Exchange. Novell Corp.'s Groupwise product is a
distant third at an estimated 14.2 million users.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
