</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-BRADLEY-COLUMN19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A long day's journey into Super Bowl night
 &HT;    By Mark Bradley
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ How many times does it happen like this? How many
times is the biggest victory in franchise history also the greatest
game?
</P>
<P>
   Judging by the 11 1/2-point spread, it was the biggest upset in
a conference championship game since the 1970 merger. It began
according to script and then went every which way. The Vikings had
the ball longer and ran 10 more plays. Robert Smith outrushed Jamal
Anderson. Pressure on Randall Cunningham was slight. The Falcons
made two turnovers and were supposed to come undone before the
raging Vikings and the roaring Metrodome. But no.
</P>
<P>
   Using center Robbie Tobeck's silent count, the Falcons went all
game without a procedure penalty. Every time the Vikings drew
farther ahead, the visitors reeled them in. Given every chance to
join the honorable-but-forgettable ranks of losing semifinalists,
the Falcons simply refused.
</P>
<P>
   They'd opened nicely, scoring after the kickoff. No 17-point
jump for Minnesota this day. But that good early work soon seemed a
faded memory. Harold Green fell and fumbled. O.J. Santiago ran and
fumbled. The Falcons were called for personal fouls on consecutive
snaps.
</P>
<P>
   First-and-10 at the Falcon 19 after Michael Booker's late hit,
the visitors reeling now. Randy Moss broke open over the middle.
Hold Cunningham's pass and it's 24-7 and pretty much over. But the
great rookie could get his hands only on the ball's back half. The
purple tide had broken. The greatest offense in NFL annals would
run 61 more plays and score but one more touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   Up by 13, the Vikes overreached. Chuck Smith stripped Cunningham
inside the half's final minute, Travis Hall recovering, Chris
Chandler finding Terance Mathis for the touchdown that made this a
game again. ``They were going for the knockout punch,'' Smith would
say. ``But nobody had actually gone at them.''
</P>
<P>
   Only once all season had an opponent stayed within seven points
of the Vikings in the Metrodome. The Falcons closed within three.
The Vikings made it 10 again. On third-and-9 Chandler stepped into
a fearsome blitz and delivered the 70-yarder to Tony Martin. Field
goal. Cunningham flubbed a snap, Shane Dronett recovering. Dan
Reeves went for it on fourth-and-4, surely a howling mistake.
</P>
<P>
   The Vikings drove for the kill. Gary Anderson missed. Chandler
threw to Ronnie Harris. The Vikes' Robert Griffith couldn't hold a
deflected pass. On the next play Chandler hit Mathis on a slant.
Touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   Burned once by greed, the Vikes meekly allowed regulation to
expire. The greatest offense in NFL annals took the ball first in
OT, managed 13 yards, punted, got it back, moved 12 yards, punted
again. Chandler hit Santiago once, twice. Hardy Minnesotans began
leaving by the dozens. Morten Andersen kicked it true. Of this
stirring tableau, Jessie Tuggle said: ``All I remember is the ball
going through the uprights. . . . We're headed to Miami.''
</P>
<P>
   They are, but Miami is a mere destination. In the fortnight of
hype to come, let no one forget the long day's journey that got the
Falcons there. Let no one forget team president Taylor Smith's
benediction: ``I don't think I've ever seen so much character.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Bradley writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga. Email: MarkB(AT)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
