</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-RUSSIA-NUCLEAR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON TO PROPOSE SPENDING MORE TO CURB RUSSIAN NUCLEAR THREAT 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By DAVID E. ROSENBAUM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In his State of the Union message on Tuesday night,
President Clinton will insist that the United States substantially
increase its financial assistance to Russia to minimize the threat
posed by the Russian nuclear arsenal, administration officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president believes it's in the national security interest
of the American people that we work with Russia and other former
Soviet countries to reduce the risk that materials, technology and
expertise for weapons of mass destruction fall into the hands of
rogue nations or terrorists,'' said David Leavy, a National
Security Council spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Another senior official, who spoke on the condition of
anonymity, said the president was concerned about ``people trying
to sell what has value.''
</P>
<P>
   ``As Russia is in a period of greater economic distress, it is
even more in our interest to accelerate these programs,'' the
official said.
</P>
<P>
   The administration officials said the president would propose
spending $4.2 billion over the next five years, a 68 percent
increase over the $2.5 billion already budgeted.
</P>
<P>
   The new money would be used in these areas:
</P>
<P>
   _ To dismantle warheads and other dangerous weapons.
</P>
<P>
   _ To redirect Russian scientists and scientific institutes into
civilian pursuits.
</P>
<P>
   _ To tighten controls over non-nuclear weapons and materials
like chemical and biological weapons and missile parts and help the
Russians beef up their export controls.
</P>
<P>
   _ To assist in the relocation of Russian troops now stationed
outside the country.
</P>
<P>
   The president will stress that the money will not be available
to institutions that offer nuclear assistance to Iran. Last week,
the White House announced economic sanctions against three Russian
institutions that the administration said were helping Iran and
possibly other nations develop nuclear weapons and missiles.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Michael Krepon, president of the Henry L.
Stimson Center, a military research organization here, and an
expert on Russian nuclear weapons, said that the increased spending
to be proposed by the president would be ``a good down payment to
solve an important problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked how much it would cost to solve the problem once and for
all, Krepon replied, ``There isn't a soul who knows the answer.''
</P>
<P>
   The request for additional financial assistance to Russia will
be the centerpiece of the one-quarter of the speech devoted to
foreign and military policy, the official said. They said the
president would also talk about efforts to contain the threat from
Iraq and to achieve peace in the Middle East, Northern Ireland and
the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   He will also press for a five-year increase in the Defense
Department budget, with an emphasis on improving the ability of
troops to respond quickly to emergencies, and will call on the
Senate to approve the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty. As long as the
United States does not join the 151 other nations who have signed
the treaty, the president plans to say, this country will lack the
moral authority to persuade India and Pakistan to stop testing
nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Other passages will involve U.S. policy in Asia and Africa, and
there will be a sizable section on trade and international
economics. The president will urge Congress to reinstate his
authority to negotiate trade agreements under a process that would
allow Congress to approve or reject the pacts but not amend them.
</P>
<P>
   In 1991, in the aftermath of the fall of the Soviet Union,
Congress approved legislation that provided money to Russia and
other former Soviet states to help them dismantle their nuclear
arsenals and create safe storage for weapons-grade nuclear
material.
</P>
<P>
   This is called the Nunn-Lugar program after its chief sponsors,
former Sen. Sam Nunn, D-Ga., who headed the Armed Services
Committee, and Sen Richard Lugar, R-Ind., a former chairman of the
Foreign Relations Committee and now the committee's second-ranking
Republican. An administration official said that somewhat more than
$1 billion had been spent since the program's inception.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Lugar said that the senator had been briefed on
Clinton's proposed expansion of the program and supported the
initiative.
</P>
<P>
   But the president's plan could still run into difficulty in
Congress, because many Republicans do not trust the Russians and
are wary about giving them assistance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
