A8089 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MLK-SERVICES-COX     01-18 0560
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MLK-SERVICES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Some remember King by serving communityBy Jennifer Brett
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In years past, Noreen Lewis Cochran has either stayed
home or gone to work on Martin Luther King Jr. Day, but neither
felt right.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always felt an emptiness,'' Cochran said. ``It seems
necessary to mark it in some way.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday, she took time off from her job to help paint a house on
Auburn Avenue near King's birthplace. Hands On Atlanta coordinated
the project in conjunction with the National Park Service, which
has an ongoing restoration project in the neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't stay away,'' Cochran said as she dipped her roller
into a tray of paint. ``This just made the most sense of what to do
today. It's perfect. I can see me doing this every year.''
</P>
<P>
   The Auburn Avenue project was one of more than 20 coordinated by
Hands On Atlanta, a nonprofit volunteer service organization.
</P>
<P>
   Across the city, and across the United States, the nation paused
to honor King, who was assassinated in 1968 and would have turned
70 last week. In Atlanta, the day began with a service at Ebenezer
Baptist Church, where King once preached and continued with the
Hands On Atlanta service projects and Gov. Roy Barnes leading a
parade honoring the civil rights leader.
</P>
<P>
   At Ebenezer, South African Archbishop Desmond Tutu, a Nobel
Peace Prize winner like King, gave the keynote speech, praising
U.S. civil rights leaders for their role in ending apartheid in his
county. Also at the service, King's widow, Coretta Scott King,
presented the 1999 Martin Luther King Jr. Non-Violent Peace Prize
to John Hume, who last year shared the Nobel Peace Prize for his
efforts to bring peace to Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are trying to live out Dr. King's legacy of building
communities through service,'' said Julie Mehan, a staff member
with Hands On Atlanta. She estimated 1,000 volunteers worked at the
various community service sites, which included sorting books at
Goodwill, preparing meals for people living with AIDS and planting
gardens, painting murals or cleaning up a number of schools.
</P>
<P>
   Twelve-year-old DeAnna Weede spent part of Monday at a nursing
facility, where volunteers played bingo with residents.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I help people, I feel good about myself,'' said DeAnna, a
member of the I Have A Dream Foundation. ``I know they enjoy our
company.''
</P>
<P>
   DeAnna sat with resident Mary Darden, marking the bingo cards
when their numbers were called out. Darden recalled the day she
learned of Dr. King's assassination.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was working in Dayton Ohio,'' in a coffee shop, she said.
``A lady was watching TV. She came out and said, `Everybody be
quiet, sit down. Martin Luther King just got shot.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to think it over for a while,'' she continued. ``It
finally came to me what had happened. I said, `No, not Dr. King.'''
</P>
<P>
   The annual observance of Dr. King's birthday is a time of
reflection for her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sit and think about what all he went through,'' Darden said.
</P>
<P>
   It pleased her to have young people visit this year and remember
the civil rights leader by sharing their time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad they're here,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Brett writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
