<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-SCHUMER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHUMER ANTICIPATES A LONG TRIAL IF WITNESSES ARE CALLED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC ROSENBERG  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Sen. Charles E. Schumer, who argued against
impeaching President Clinton as a member of the House Judiciary
Committee, said Monday the impeachment trial would last well into
the spring if House prosecutors are allowed to call witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   The former Brooklyn congressman also predicted that the Senate
would fall well short of the 67 votes needed to remove Clinton from
office for his conduct in the Monica Lewinsky affair.
</P>
<P>
   ``If House managers get four or five witnesses, it'll take
months to depose them and bring them before the Senate,'' said
Schumer, D-N.Y. ``Then the president obviously will want the same,
and there may be counter-witnesses or re-cross-examination or new
witnesses either side might want to bring.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd find it hard to believe we'd finish by May 1st,'' Schumer
added.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer voted against impeachment as a member of the Judiciary
Committee and again on Dec. 19 when the full House approved two
articles of impeachment against Clinton. On Monday, he said the
case argued by the 13 House impeachment managers failed to sway
many in both parties.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you had to have the vote on impeachment on removing the
president right now, I doubt it would get 35 votes,'' Schumer said.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the momentum is building to hear from witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Minority Leader Tom Daschle, D-S.D., acknowledged Monday
that witnesses ``may be inevitable.'' Daschle conceded the Senate
was moving toward having at least some witnesses, despite efforts
by the White House and Senate Democrats to limit the trial to the
existing record.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is charged with perjury and obstruction of justice for
trying to conceal his affair with Lewinsky, a former White House
intern.
</P>
<P>
   House prosecutors wrapped up three days of presentations on
Saturday, while Clinton's lawyers will begin their defense on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   After the president's lawyers finish their presentation later
this week, senators will submit questions in writing to be read by
Supreme Court Chief Justice William Rehnquist, who is the presiding
trial officer. That phase could last up to 16 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Under bipartisan ground rules agreed to by lawmakers, the Senate
won't vote on the issue of witnesses until after they consider a
motion to end the trial, which can be offered after the president's
lawyers finish their case and after the question period.
</P>
<P>
   Many prominent senators in both parties, including Sen. Dianne
Feinstein, D-Calif., and Sen. Mitch McConnell, R-Ky., chairman of
the rules committee, believe that a motion to end the trial before
hearing from witnesses will fail.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer spent 18 years in the House before ousting the incumbent
senator, Alfonse D'Amato, in the November election.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
