<DOCNO> NYT19990118.0325 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 19:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8099 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOUTHERNSTATES-COX     01-18 2645
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOUTHERNSTATES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    South playing high-tech odds
 &HT;    By Ron Taylor
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Celebrating a new century a year early, the Southern
governors of the new millennium have plugged into the vision thing,
promising higher educational standards for a high-tech economy _
and enough gambling money to pay for them.
</P>
<P>
   Education and technology dominated as themes in inauguration
addresses and state-of-the-state speeches delivered over the last
few days by governors who will lead the South through the 2000
curtain and into the 21st century. On Monday, new Alabama Gov. Don
Siegelman sounded his call for a statewide lottery and promised to
make Alabama ``the education state,'' using lottery dollars. The
Democrat said in his inauguration speech, ``Our children will have
state-of-the-art computers. Our children will have preschool. And
our children will have college scholarships. The people demand it.
Our children deserve it. Alabama needs it. It can be done. It will
be done.''
</P>
<P>
   In perhaps the biggest bow to technology, Republican Gov. Jim
Gilmore of Virginia, where Blacksburg has been called ``the most
wired city in America,'' delivered the nation's first ``Webcast''
of a state-of-the-state address. The governor offered Internet
users his live digital image on Wednesday at either 28,800 bits per
second or 56,600 bps. He vowed to make Virginia ``the Internet
Capital of the World.''
</P>
<P>
   In South Carolina, new Democratic Gov. Jim Hodges, who, like
Siegelman, has promised a lottery to help pull his state out of the
educational ditch, urged in his inaugural address last week that
citizens join him in a ``children's crusade _ a 21st century
crusade of textbooks and computers and parents and teachers allied
against the enemies of ignorance and indifference.''
</P>
<P>
   Barring the Second Coming or a chance to be president, seven
Southern governors who took office this month expect to be in
office through 2002: Democrats Hodges in South Carolina, Siegelman
in Alabama and Roy Barnes in Georgia; Republicans Jeb Bush in
Florida, George Bush in Texas, Mike Huckabee in Arkansas and Don
Sundquist in Tennessee. Elected in 1997, Gilmore will serve in
Virginia through 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Three Southern governors will end their terms this year:
Republicans Mike Foster of Louisiana and Kirk Fordice of
Mississippi, and Democrat Paul Patton of Kentucky. Gov. Jim Hunt of
North Carolina, a Democrat, ends his fourth term next year.
</P>
<P>
   Dramatizing the imminence of the turn of the century, Hodges
provided a countdown to his inauguration audience in Columbia on
Wednesday: ``Three hundred fifty-two days, twelve hours. As I
prepared to take the oath to become South Carolina's 114th
governor, I realized that's how close we are _ 352 days, 12 hours _
to the year 2000, what most consider the beginning of the 21st
century.''
</P>
<P>
   By then, many political prognosticators predict, at least one of
the Governors Bush _ probably George, beginning his second term in
Texas _ will be running for president. It was his and brother Jeb's
father, President Bush, who, in groping for a phrase for foresight
and inventiveness, pinned ``the vision thing'' on the aspirations
of the '90s.
</P>
<P>
   But visionaries do not always see eye-to-eye. In Georgia, Gov.
Barnes talks of trains as a key part of a new transportation
philosophy. In Florida, Gov. Bush last week abruptly killed state
funding for a proposed 200-mph train from Miami to Orlando and
Tampa. ``There are better alternatives for $70 million per year
compounded at 4 percent,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   With lottery fever running high in the nonlottery states of
South Carolina and Alabama, desperate to improve education,
Tennessee's governor faces the prospect of being surrounded by
gambling states in another two or three years amid growing concerns
about that state's educational system. The Governor's Council on
Excellence in Higher Education said in a draft report last week
that the Volunteer state needs at least $441 million to improve
public colleges and universities.
</P>
<P>
   Sundquist, beginning his second term, steered away from the
lottery issue in his inauguration speech Saturday, focusing instead
on protecting the environment and reforming government. ``We have
the opportunity to make history anew by reforming our government to
meet the demands of the Technological Age,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Siegelman hit the lottery issue head-on in his
inauguration address Monday in Montgomery, where he took the oath
of office from outgoing Georgia Gov. Zell Miller, who pushed
through the Georgia lottery that funds HOPE scholarships.
</P>
<P>
   ``For those of you who think a lottery is wrong, I want you to
know I respect your deeply held beliefs. I understand that I cannot
sway your convictions, nor would I try,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But let me tell you what I think is wrong. I think it is wrong
for a working mother to hold down two or three jobs, to work her
heart out, to scrimp and save trying to make ends meet with no
hope, no hope she will ever be able to send her son or her daughter
to college. That's what I think is wrong.'' In South Carolina,
Hodges also sought to personalize the frustrations of citizens who
cannot afford to advance their educations, by drawing on his early
labor in a textile mill _ a company he ultimately served as legal
counsel.
</P>
<P>
   ``All day, every day, I shouldered cloth or tended the card
machines that turned raw cotton into fiber. Around me worked men
and women with little or no formal education,'' he said. ``Almost
all wanted a better life for their children and grandchildren. They
knew the wisdom of the old saying, `Education is the one thing in
life that can't be taken away from you.'
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot let those good people, and everyone like them _ we
cannot let them down. We've got to do a better job educating our
children.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, life in some Southern states is pretty rosy
already, as Jeb Bush, in a speech emphasizing a policy of
inclusion, reminded those who watched his inauguration in
Tallahassee last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``From our shores, men have traveled to the mountains of the
moon,'' Florida's new governor declared. ``Our population has
increased more than 25-fold, and we have an economy that is the
16th largest in the world, ahead of entire countries such as India
and Argentina.''
</P>
<P>
   From the height of optimism to the deepest worries, the Southern
governors aired their views. Here's a sampling:
</P>
<P>
   _ ALABAMA, Gov. Don Siegelman, from his inauguration address:
</P>
<P>
   Alabama, the waiting is over. Too much time wasted. Too many
promises broken. Too many dreams shattered. We will dare great
things. We will try new things. If they don't work, we will try
something else. . .
</P>
<P>
   My parents worked as hard as anyone, but could not go to
college. Not because they lacked the skills or the knowledge, but
for one reason and one reason only: They didn't have the money.
</P>
<P>
   Together, we will shatter the financial barriers to college and
open the doors of higher education to every Alabama family. Any
student who works hard, stays in school, stays out of trouble, and
graduates from high school, will have earned the right to go to
college, tuition free. Nothing will hold them back. This will be
our HOPE college scholarship program. And this is my HOPE for
celebrating Alabama children.
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere in Alabama today a child is born. Eighteen years from
now it will cost that family $96,000 to educate that single child
at a public college. $96,000. No child should fail because of the
lack of money. I want every child, white or black, rich or poor, to
have the same hope and expectation that they can attend college,
get a good job and provide for their family's future. If _ if _
they are willing to work for it, HOPE will be there. We will
fulfill the dreamer's dream. Every Alabama child will be judged by
the content of his character and the content of his mind.
</P>
<P>
   _ VIRGINIA, Gov. Jim Gilmore, from his State of the Commonweath
speech:
</P>
<P>
   In Virginia, optimism lives, opportunity abounds. We have
entered the last year of this millennium in a state of unparalleled
prosperity and promise. We're working more _ and earning more _
than at any time in nearly 30 years. We're developing the tools of
technology that will lead our nation into the new economy of the
Information Age . . .
</P>
<P>
   As we address the needs of Virginia's tobacco heritage, we must
also look forward to a new economy. We must be more competitive
with other states and look beyond America's borders. We must meet
employers' needs for a highly skilled, highly educated and
plentiful work force. We must understand that our economy is strong
only when each region shares in the prosperity of all others . . .
</P>
<P>
   My administration is keeping Virginia's economy and government
on the cutting edge of the global technology revolution. I
appointed the nation's first cabinet-level Secretary of Technology,
Don Upson, who is advancing Virginia as a global technology leader
. . . The Internet is the empowerment tool of the 21st century. It
provides unlimited information and unlimited opportunities to
improve every person's life. My Information Technology Commission
has recommended to me the nation's first statewide Internet policy.
The Commission's policy recommendations stay true to market-driven
principles and also embrace our Virginia principles of freedom and
democracy. Web-enabled government, privacy, security and the
protection of children _ these cutting-edge Internet issues are
addressed by my comprehensive legislation. I urge you to support my
package of Internet legislation and seal Virginia's leadership
position as the Internet Capital of the World.
</P>
<P>
   _ SOUTH CAROLINA, Gov. Jim Hodges, from his inauguration
address:
</P>
<P>
   Because the Hodges administration is committed to improving
education without tax increases, we must adopt a statewide lottery
with all the revenues targeted for specific educational needs. We
must begin by aggressively moving to cut class size in the early
grades and implementing a strong pre-kindergarten program. Lottery
dollars, coupled with a commitment to make education the top
spending priority in our state, can help create a truly superior
educational experience. South Carolina's children deserve nothing
less . . .
</P>
<P>
   When I was 3, with the encouragement of my father, my mother
went back to college. With three young children, her only times to
study were early in the morning and late at night. But she kept at
it _ course after course _ until she finally earned her bachelor's
degree. But that was just the beginning. The same year I was
graduated from high school, my mother earned her Ph.D. What
followed was a distinguished career as an educator helping many
nontraditional students like herself realize their dreams. My
mother never gave up on her dreams; she never gave up on her dreams
for me. Join me, so that our children never have to give up on
their dreams.
</P>
<P>
   _ FLORIDA, Gov. Jeb Bush, from his inauguration address:
</P>
<P>
   Faith. Family. Friends. These are what's best. These will
endure. We should trust in these more than we trust in government.
State government, now and forever, must respect and nurture and
rely on these enduring institutions so that we can unleash their
amazing potential.
</P>
<P>
   Public servants must have the humility to listen to and trust
Florida's head, heart and soul. Only then will the body be strong.
Government will be unencumbered to make a true difference where it
is most needed and where it can be most effective: Education,
public safety, public works, and the protection of the frailest and
weakest among us. Give to Floridians a state government that makes
these few precious things the core of its being, and we can match
the lofty challenges illuminated by the wonder of a new tomorrow.
We can see that children learn a year's worth of knowledge in a
year's worth of time, and work with unbridled determination to
ensure that no child in our education system is left behind. . . .
For these are the principles that will guide us. I want state
government to be an ally, not an adversary of positive change
within each community. I want to protect people, not bureaucracies.
I want state government to be more respectful of the earnings of
Florida's families, not more desirous. I want our leaders more
trustful of the choices of our citizens, not more suspicious. And,
I want to rely on the rich debate afforded by diversity, not the
sterile monologue of insular politics.
</P>
<P>
   _ TENNESSEE, Gov. Don Sundquist, from his inauguration speech:
</P>
<P>
   We must build a system of education _ at the elementary,
secondary and collegiate levels _ that will teach and train
Tennesseans of all ages to lead and serve the world of tomorrow. We
must maintain a growing economy that rewards courage and
creativity, that generates jobs, attracts investment, provides
opportunity and promotes the prosperity of every Tennessean. We
must ensure that Tennessee has a health care system on which every
Tennessean can rely, which every Tennessean can afford and which
provides the quality of care that every Tennessean deserves. We
must continually invest in a system of transportation - on land,
through the water and in the air - that moves people and products
safely and efficiently around the state and into the future . . .
</P>
<P>
   We must keep Tennessee beautiful. This commitment cannot be
government's alone but must involve all of us as fellow citizens of
this natural paradise we call home. So I will propose that we mark
the new millennium by making Tennessee look good. Through simple
acts of environmental protection, reclaiming and maintaining the
common areas that are visible, physical symbols of community _ our
parks and playgrounds, our roadsides, our rivers, lakes and streams
and even our vacant lots. . . . It is my hope that one of the
lasting legacies of my service in this office will be a more
beautiful Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   _ ARKANSAS, Gov. Mike Huckabee, from his State of the State
address:
</P>
<P>
   One of the things we need to do here is repeal some of the
restricting legislation that makes it very difficult for schools to
operate because they are busy trying to keep up with legislative
mandates that they don't have time to give full attention to the
students. We also need to make sure we never, ever go backward in
per pupil funding. We won't propose it. And even if we did, you
wouldn't allow it. And I think that's one thing upon which we can
readily agree today and drive a stake in the ground and say
Arkansas students will have more money, not less money. . .
</P>
<P>
   As we focus on education, Smart Start will help our kids get
started right. But if they do what we want them to do, we need to
make sure that at the end of that education there is some reason
for them to go on. We are going to propose an autonomy of our
technical schools, not only to give them the opportunity to better
train our people for the work force but to give us a greater level
of accountability for those technical schools. . . . I'm going to
ask you for something of significance when I ask you to join and
expand the Academic Challenge Scholarship program. Right now, that
scholarship program doesn't go to any great value to families who
earn more than $35,000 or $40,000 a year. There are a lot of
families in Arkansas who earn more than that but struggle to get
their kids in college. As a result, we are losing a lot of our good
kids. They are going out of state. I want to keep the best and
brightest right here in Arkansas. . . . I'll ask you to do it by
raising that limit to $70,000 so more students in Arkansas will
decide that staying here is a good investment.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Taylor writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
