A8103 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-IMPEACH-HNS &LR;      01-18 1077
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-IMPEACH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON'S LEGAL TEAM TO BEGIN ITS DEFENSE IN SENATE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN C. HENRY 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton's legal team plans to begin
defending him against impeachment Tuesday with a two-pronged attack
against the arguments by House Republicans who want to remove him.
</P>
<P>
   White House Counsel Charles F.C. Ruff, leader of the team of
government and private lawyers, will open the three-day defense,
which the president's defenders say will ``point out significant
holes,'' in the case against Clinton. His defenders also will argue
that, even if true, the perjury and obstruction of justice charges
do not merit terminating his presidency.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Clinton's lawyers will argue against removal of a
politically popular president whose job performance continues to
receive high marks, an argument bolstered by a poll released Monday
showing that two-thirds of U.S. adults oppose his impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   A few hours after Ruff's presentation before the Senate, the
president _ in one of the more ironic moments of the impeachment
saga _ makes his annual trip to the Capitol to deliver his State of
the Union address to a joint session of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   At 9 p.m. EST, Clinton will mount the rostrum of the House of
Representatives, the Republican-dominated body that formally
accused him of lying under oath and obstruction of justice in
trying to conceal an extramarital affair with Monica Lewinsky.
Clinton will lay out an agenda for the coming year to an audience
that includes the 100 senators who will decide whether he should be
removed from office.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, it is unusual, it's never happened before, but then a lot
of things have been firsts over the last year,'' said Rep. George
Gekas, a Pennsylvania Republican and one of the House managers
prosecuting the case.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, the nation's 42nd president, is only the second to be
tried in the Senate. Andrew Johnson's impeachment trial in 1868
ended with his acquittal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are preparing a thorough defense showing that the case
presented against the president was not supported by the facts (in
the report by independent counsel Kenneth Starr) or the law,'' said
White House counsel spokesman Jim Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We plan to point out significant holes in the presentation by
the Republican managers, as well as a misleading and overreaching
characterization of the evidence,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   To bolster those claims, the legal team apparently considered
asking some Democratic House members from the judiciary committee
to accompany them to the Senate, although no firm plans were in
place.
</P>
<P>
   Emphasizing perceived weaknesses in the House case and stressing
Clinton's technical innocence, however, could risk raising
questions that can be resolved only by calling witnesses,
particularly former presidential paramour Lewinsky. Many Democrats
and the White House oppose that step.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Senate Minority Leader Thomas Daschle, D-S.D.,
acknowledged that witnesses ``may be inevitable.'' At the same
time, Daschle said, he remains opposed to seeking more testimony,
but he conceded that the political momentum was moving toward
summoning some witnesses to testify during the Senate trial.
</P>
<P>
   White House spokesman Joe Lockhart continued his criticism of
any plan to bring witnesses to the trial, saying such a step would
``only extend and delay this process.'' Many of them have already
been deposed and have testified over 20 times, Lockhart complained.
``It boggles the mind a bit to try to understand how someone
testifying for the 10th time, the 23rd time, or the ninth time,
might provide any clarity.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's allies in the impeachment fight, including Sen. Robert
Torricelli, D-N.J., have begun suggesting that if witnesses are to
be called, then Starr and Linda Tripp should be summoned. A little
over a year ago, Tripp's secret tape recordings of conversations
with Lewinsky were used by Starr to seek expansion of his
investigation of Clinton's business dealings to include his affair
with the former White House intern.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials said the defense presented by Clinton's
team will attack what is seen as weak points in the evidence _ all
of it was gathered during a grand jury investigation overseen by
Starr _ that Clinton lied under oath to the grand jury and
obstructed justice.
</P>
<P>
   There will be an emphasis on statements by Clinton friend Vernon
Jordan, presidential secretary Betty Currie and Lewinsky, key
figures in the obstruction of justice allegation, that the
president never specifically asked them to lie.
</P>
<P>
   To support Clinton's claim that he misled but did not lie to the
grand jury, the president's lawyers plan to focus on grand jury
testimony by Lewinsky in which she said she didn't consider their
relationship to be sex, just ``fooling around.''
</P>
<P>
   Also, the president's lawyers will challenge the prosecution's
claims that efforts to get Lewinsky a job were linked to her
potential testimony in the Paula Jones sexual harassment case. The
defense plans to argue that an accurate look at the timing of the
job search leads to the interpretation that it was simply an effort
to help a young person at the beginning of her career.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's lawyers also will deny charges that Clinton
orchestrated the hiding of gifts he'd given Lewinsky, arguing that
he gave her gifts even after knowing she was to be a witness in the
Jones case. Clinton lawyers will stress that neither Lewinsky nor
Currie, who at one point retrieved the gifts, say Clinton ordered
it as alleged by House prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   A poll released Monday found that fewer than one-third of U.S.
adults are paying close attention to the Senate trial, which was
dominated last week by the House managers' three-day presentation
of their case against Clinton. Sixty-nine percent of those surveyed
said the trial has not changed their opinions about whether Clinton
should be forced from office.
</P>
<P>
   The Jan. 14-18 telephone poll of 1,200 adults, conducted by the
Pew Research Center for the People &AMP; the Press, found 63 percent
approve of Clinton's performance in office, down from 71 percent in
December in the wake of the House vote to impeach the president.
Two-thirds of those surveyed want Clinton to remain in office, and
53 percent are satisfied with the way things are going in the
country _ up from 46 percent a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
