u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POPE-VISIT-HNS &LR;      01-18 1674
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POPE-VISIT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POPE TO VISIT MEXICO CITY, ST. LOUIS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds: Pope's visit begins Friday) 
(Moved in ``a'' and ``i'' categories) 
 
By CECILE S. HOLMES 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pope John Paul II's visit to Mexico and the United States, which
begins Friday, brings an aging church patriarch to two of the
world's most Catholic countries.
</P>
<P>
   Only Brazil has more Roman Catholics than Mexico, which has 86.3
million. The United States has 61.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   To believers in both nations, John Paul II is literally Jesus
Christ's representative on earth. Even if they disagree with him,
his opinions on secular and sacred issues matter. As sovereign of
the Vatican, he commands the respect accorded any visiting head of
state.
</P>
<P>
   The pope's five-day visit to Mexico City is expected to attract
1 million visitors and to cost the local archdiocese more than $1.3
million. Officials say they cannot estimate the visit's total cost.
</P>
<P>
   But the cost to the archdiocese is high in a nation struggling
with high crime in its capital city, a beleaguered economy, ongoing
ethnic and religious conflicts, extreme poverty and government
corruption.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Mexico, he's going to talk about the poor and its
problems,'' said Brian Smith, a religion and ethics professor with
expertise on Latin America at the University of Wisconsin at Ripon.
``But he's also probably going to raise the issue of abortion.''
</P>
<P>
   Estimated costs of the papal visit to St. Louis range as high as
$5 million with, at least, 100,000 visitors expected.
</P>
<P>
   Greeting the pope in St. Louis on behalf of the nation's 300
Catholic bishops will be Bishop Joseph A. Fiorenza, president of
the national bishops' conference and leader of 1 million Catholics
in the Diocese of Galveston-Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Fiorenza predicted that the pope will decry abortion, capital
punishment and euthanasia, encouraging Catholics ``to bring the
moral values of the Gospel into the society of our country.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time in the United States, citizens confront the
impeachment trial of a still popular president. In a recent Gallup
Poll, Americans named President Clinton the most popular man in the
United States, with the pope coming in second. The two will meet
during the pope's 30-hour stop in St. Louis on Jan. 26.
</P>
<P>
   The official reason for the pope's visit is to outline his
response to the Synod of the Bishops for America, held at the
Vatican in late 1997. It brought together Catholic bishops from two
continents to explore common concerns ranging from poverty and
foreign debt in Latin America to declining morality in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   The pope's ``apostolic exhortation,'' a sermon responding to the
synod, is expected to address a cross section of social justice
issues, including the rights of indigenous peoples throughout the
hemisphere.
</P>
<P>
   Frail and stooped shouldered, John Paul is making his 85th
pastoral journey outside Italy. At age 78, he is a far cry from the
robust, dynamic pontiff who won U.S. and Mexican hearts on his
first tours of each nation in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   But he keeps a grueling schedule, still enjoys meeting people
and remains sharp-witted, according to U.S. bishops. Because of his
age and declining health, this trip's schedule is less crammed than
usual.
</P>
<P>
   In Mexico, his itinerary includes a courtesy visit with
President Ernesto Zedillo, celebrating Mass at the Basilica of Our
Lady of Guadalupe, visiting a hospital and attending a rally. On
his first visit to Mexico in January 1979, just months after he was
elected pope, he crammed 26 events into a six-day visit.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a pastoral visit, but, of course, every single
pastoral visit has its political consequences, as is quite clear in
the visits to Bosnia, Poland and Cuba,'' said the Rev. Luis G.
Ramos, director of students at Mexico City's Dominican School of
Theology.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every single papal visit can be manipulated to hide national
problems,'' Ramos said. ``The major problems right now are the
continually rising price of tortillas, milk and gas. The price of
the tortilla has doubled in the past month.''
</P>
<P>
   Only recently has the Catholic Church in Mexico been allowed to
own property and to take an open role in educating its people.
Because the church backed repressive governments during Mexico's
colonial period, it was not allowed certain rights for many years.
Diplomatic relations with the Vatican only were restored in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the nation is central in Vatican strategy, said Bernardo
Barranco Villafan, president of the Mexican Center for Religious
Studies in Mexico City.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mexico is the bridge between South America and North
America,'' he said. ``The South Americans see us as a bit gringo,
and the gringos see us as very South American. ... For the Holy
See, the concept of Latin America has disappeared. It now sees
America as a whole.''
</P>
<P>
   He predicted the pope will use Mexico as a platform to speak to
the whole continent.
</P>
<P>
   In comparison to Mexico, John Paul II's 30-hour St. Louis stop
seems short.
</P>
<P>
   He is visiting the region because it is one of most heavily
Catholic areas in the United States that he has not visited, and
because its archdiocese is headed by his old friend Archbishop
Justin Rigali. Rigali served 30 years in the Vatican before being
named to head the archdiocese in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   In St. Louis, the pope is likely to condemn the bombing of Iraq,
urge U.S. bankers to forgive the debts of developing countries,
condemn abortion and press for stronger interfaith relationships.
He is also expected to urge young Catholics to live their faith
daily with such fervor that they may lead the church into the next
millennium.
</P>
<P>
   The St. Louis stop includes a brief meeting with Clinton, but
analysts expect the pontiff to focus on general issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pope will be more interested in the American people and
that we not compromise our values, our strong sense of right and
wrong,'' said the Rev. Michael Miller, president of the University
of St. Thomas in Houston. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; When Clinton meets the pope right after the pontiff's jet
lands, there will be a tinge of irony in this, their fourth,
meeting. The pope remains a critic of rampant capitalism, but it is
a buoyant economy that analysts believe is behind Clinton's high
approval rating.
</P>
<P>
   Their encounter brings together one of the world's foremost
spiritual leaders with one of its most powerful political figures.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have something of a sense of humor about this visit,'' said
the Rev. Thomas J. Reese, editor of the Jesuit magazine America and
an expert on the Vatican. ``Bill Clinton probably wishes he was a
medieval king. In medieval times, the king would sin, and he could
go before the pope, kneel down, confess his sins, be absolved, get
a penance and then go on with being king.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, a Southern Baptist, doesn't have that option. In
addition, this is a pope who takes ``on systems, not individuals,''
Miller said.
</P>
<P>
   In St. Louis, the pope's chief concern is likely to be urging
that the world's wealthiest nation lead the way in taking the side
of the poor.
</P>
<P>
   John Paul II's traditional views on birth control, ordaining
women and other issues do not play well with Catholic liberals. But
even his critics credit him with a strong record on human rights
before and during his 20-year pontificate. The determination that
served him well when he helped bring about the fall of communism in
Eastern Europe keeps him going.
</P>
<P>
   Human rights concerns will weave through the pope's visit, said
Bishop Fiorenza.
</P>
<P>
   Scholars predict John Paul II will exercise that strength by
urging all of Latin America to implement democratic reforms and
root out corruption. His effectiveness will be measured only by
time.
</P>
<P>
   In Cuba, where the pontiff visited last January, church leaders
report only limited progress toward political reforms since the
papal visit.
</P>
<P>
   In Mexico, analysts are predicting the government will try to
avoid public discussion of its five-year conflict with Zapatista
rebels in southernmost Chiapas state during the pope's visit, even
though this could be President Zedillo's last chance to reignite
the peace process before his term ends in December 2000.
</P>
<P>
   This is John Paul II's first visit to Mexico since the Zapatista
uprising began in January 1994. Church leaders doubt the pontiff
will address the issue directly, though he might bring it up in the
private meeting with Zedillo. But they acknowledge that the pope
always pushes for justice and human rights in his sermons,
especially in economically distressed countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``The visit is a bit uncomfortable for government officials,''
said the Rev. Jesus Garza, provincial head of the Redemptorist
Order of priests based in Mexico City. ``They wish the country were
in better condition.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mexican church remains vital, marking small annual increases
each year, according to church leaders. But there is division in
its top ranks. Some bishops espouse political activism, while
others follow a traditional church-focused course. The rising clout
of Protestant evangelicals worries many. How significant the issue
is varies from diocese to diocese, Garza said.
</P>
<P>
   Opinions vary even more among U.S. Catholics.
</P>
<P>
   Polls consistently have shown that many disagree with the pope's
opposition to abortion, birth control and extending the priesthood
to married men or women. However, it appears liberal church groups
have only limited protests planned in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   So much enthusiasm is associated with a papal trip that too much
protest is counterproductive, said Frances Kissling, president of
Catholics for a Free Choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``My general feeling is that when the pope is in a country, you
can do a modest amount of activity calling attention to the
problems in the church, but the reality is that while the pope is
in any country, this is a moment for celebration,'' she said.
``Whether people disagree or agree with the pope, they're happy
he's there.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-18-99 1954EST &QL; 
