<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 19:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8105 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SUPERBOWL-TRAVEL-COX     01-18 0637
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUPERBOWL-TRAVEL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Atlanta fans hoping to go to Super Bowl discovering sticker
shockBy Clint Williams
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ For fans hoping to travel to Miami to see Super Bowl
XXXIII live, it would help to be making the same kind of money as
the players on the field.
</P>
<P>
   The price of a tour package that includes a game ticket _
usually a crummy one at that _ starts at about $2,500, a price that
could cool the ardor of the most fevered Falcons fan.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fans, I think, are in sticker shock right now,'' said Cary
Dean, president of Esoteric Sports Tours in Duluth, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Yet by Monday, Dean's company had already booked about half the
seats on a chartered flight to Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Travel agents across metro Atlanta - and the country - were
flooded with calls from fans hoping to follow the Falcons to Miami.
</P>
<P>
   AAA Travel Agency, which advertises itself as the official Super
Bowl Tour of the Atlanta Falcons, got more than 200 telephone calls
Monday, said travel manager Rachelle Rabinowitz. And the volume was
expected to get heavier, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Tickets + Travel, a sports tour company based in Indianapolis,
got 2,100 phone calls from the Atlanta area from the time Morten
Andersen's field goal split the uprights Sunday through
mid-afternoon Monday, said Jeff Kaplan, company CEO.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something we've never seen before,'' Kaplan said.
</P>
<P>
   The package being offered by AAA Travel includes four-night
hotel accommodations, round-trip airfare to Fort Lauderdale, ground
transfers and admission to the NFL Experience and NFL Players
Party. The cost, depending where you stay, is $1,599 to $1,849 per
person, double occupancy.
</P>
<P>
   Actually getting into the game will cost an additional $1,350 to
$2,850 a head.
</P>
<P>
   Esoteric Sports Tours' package, available through the company
and area travel agents, includes charter flight, three-night
accommodations, rental car and charter bus transportation to the
game. The cost is $1,099 to $1,299 per person, double occupancy.
Tickets are an extra $1,375 to $1,575.
</P>
<P>
   Some people don't care about seeing the game live, said JoAnn
Starks, an agent with Duluth Travel.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're saying, `Just get me there and get me a room,'''
Starks said. ``They will just go hang out.''
</P>
<P>
   Anyone wanting to go by themselves faces a challenge tougher
than stopping Denver Broncos running back Terrell Davis, travel
experts said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Super Bowl is not really a fan event anymore,'' said James
Amerson of Spectacular Sport Specials in New Orleans. ``This is a
corporate event and they book well in advance. It's almost not
about who is playing. It's just the Super Bowl.''
</P>
<P>
   Most lodging near the stadium, which is between Miami and Fort
Lauderdale, has been booked for months, if not years, experts said.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone looking for cheap airfares will likely have to fly to
Orlando, Tampa or Fort Myers, all several hours' drive from Miami,
said Clara Bosonetto, a travel consultant who writes a column for
the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   When booking a package, Bosonetto said, make sure you're dealing
with a reputable company. Ask if they are a member of the
International Association of Travel Agents, she said, ``and it's
not a bad idea to ask for references.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The most important thing is you don't want to pay anyone with
a check or money order,'' she said. Paying by credit card offers
consumers some protection from rip-off artists, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the cost, plenty of Falcon fans will make the trip,
travel agents said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the type of thing,'' said Rabinowtiz of AAA Travel,
``that if you want to go, you'll pay any price.''
</P>
<P>
   Clint Williams writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
