<DOCNO> NYT19990118.0332 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 19:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8110 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-UNION19-COX     01-18 1033
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UNION19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON TO OFFER FULL AGENDA IN STATE OF THE UNION SPEECH
 &HT;    830&AMP;add. With UNION-SOCIAL.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Hours after White House lawyers wrap up Day One of
their defense in the Senate impeachment trial Tuesday, President
Clinton will take his case directly to the American people.
</P>
<P>
   With some 60 million Americans expected to watch the annual
State of the Union address, the question on many people's minds
will be how Clinton will sally forth into the eerie atmospherics of
the House chamber. Just last month, he was impeached there on
charges of perjury and obstruction of justice and is now on trial
before the other body that will be present, the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   But as he launches the new legislative year, Clinton isn't
expected to mention the Monica Lewinsky scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the speech is crafted to highlight six years of peace
and prosperity, and to outline policy initiatives on everything
from nuclear weapons and Social Security to long-term illness and
lousy schools.
</P>
<P>
   Underlying Clinton's remarks, however, will be the argument that
his leadership and continued focus on bread-and-butter issues far
outweigh the moral shortcomings that have shadowed the White House
for the past year.
</P>
<P>
   ''The president will present a lot of ideas on how we move this
country forward,'' White House spokesman Joe Lockhart told
reporters Monday, ''and we look forward to beginning Wednesday
morning working with Congress.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of the agenda Clinton will outline in his speech, beginning
at 9 p.m. EST, has been previewed in White House events or leaks
over the past two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   He'll call for $100 billion over the next six years in increased
defense spending, for example, reiterate last year's call for a
bipartisan plan to fix the financially troubled Social Security
system, and propose to restructure some $20 billion in annual
education spending to encourage national standards in public
schools.
</P>
<P>
   He has also promised to seek $6.2 billion over the next five
years to help families that provide long-term health care for the
seriously ill or disabled. Aides said Clinton also would press one
more time for national legislation to raise cigarette taxes and
restrict tobacco marketing efforts that target youth.
</P>
<P>
   ''That will be one of our top priorities in the new Congress,''
Clinton's top domestic policy adviser, Bruce Reed, said last week.
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to address a haunting post Cold War security threat,
Clinton is expected to ask Congress for $4.2 billion over the next
five years, in increased funding for a program to help safeguard
nuclear weapons and research facilities in Russia and Ukraine.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond what has been previewed, Lockhart told reporters the
speech _ in the works for more than a month _ would contain
unannounced proposals ''that will knock your socks off.''
</P>
<P>
   For months, Clinton has spoken of ''an American renaissance''
under his leadership. At a time of global economic turmoil, the
U.S. economy is forging ahead _ private economists estimate the
economy grew at about 4 percent in 1998 _ with an expansion that's
nearly eight years old. Unemployment, inflation and interest rates
are at their lowest levels in a generation.
</P>
<P>
   The glowing economic performance enabled the federal government
to show a budget surplus _ expected to top $76 billion in 1999 _
after three decades of deficits.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton will certainly dwell on those achievements, taking
credit for leading the country to a new high-water mark
economically, before calling the nation to turn its resources to
tackling a range of issues that threatens to undermine good times
early in the next century.
</P>
<P>
   A sure cornerstone of the speech will be his call to set aside
future budget surpluses _ which could top $1.5 trillion over the
coming decade, by some estimates _ to address Social Security
shortfalls projected to begin around 2013.
</P>
<P>
   White House aides played down the likelihood that Clinton would
unveil a detailed plan for saving Social Security, but he was
certain to devote time to the issue in Tuesday's speech.
</P>
<P>
   ''I would not expect a detailed comprehensive plan,'' Gene
Sperling, director of Clinton's National Economic Council, told
reporters last week. Sperling said he expected the president to try
to hammer out concrete proposals in meetings with Capitol Hill
Republicans ''over the next couple of months.''
</P>
<P>
   Most striking, though, will likely be what Clinton won't
mention.
</P>
<P>
   Aides insisted as late as Monday that he would say nothing about
the sex-and-deception scandal the White House has been mired in
since the allegations first broke a year ago this Thursday of
Clinton's Oval Office relationship with former White House intern
Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton didn't bring up the subject in last year's State of the
Union address one week after the Lewinsky charges broke. The
difference this time is that he'll be addressing the House, which
last month voted to impeach him on charges of perjury and
obstruction of justice, and the Senate, which now sits in judgment
of him.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   House prosecutors wrapped up three days of building a case
against him on Saturday, a process that appears to have cut
slightly into Clinton's high public approval ratings.
</P>
<P>
   A survey of 1,200 adults polled Jan. 14-18 by the Pew Research
Center for the People and the Press showed Clinton's job approval
rating had slipped to 63 percent. That's still extraordinarily high
for a second-term president, though it's down from his 71 percent
showing in December.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's task Tuesday night, though, could be to hold public
opinion through a convincing portrayal of a president hard at work
on the people's business.
</P>
<P>
   In the Senate, his task appears to be first, do no harm, and
''not to do or say anything that leads to an erosion of his
support, especially among Democrats who are among his 100 jurors,''
said Thomas Mann, director of governmental studies at the Brookings
Institution, a Washington research center.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
