<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 20:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8128 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LLOYD-BUSINESS-LADN     01-18 0825
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LLOYD-BUSINESS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRAYS AT MEETING TIME IN NEED OF SHORT LEASHES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(
 &HT;    Ken LLoyd, Ph.D., is a specialist in organizational behavior.
Questions can be sent by e-mail to lloydonjob(at)aol.com, or they
can be mailed to P.O. Box 260057, Encino, CA 91426. Names will be
withheld upon request.) 
BY KEN LLOYD, PH.D.  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q I'm responsible for running our departmental meetings, but I
feel like I'm trying to herd sheep! I have to round up everyone or
the meeting will never start. I may get most of the attendees in
the meeting room, but as I try to corral the last one, a couple of
others wander off to get coffee or make a phone call. The meetings
are regularly delayed by at least a half-hour because of the
wayward flock. What can I do? B.S.
</P>
<P>
   A: Before focusing on this disrespectful flock, look first at
the shepherd. Since you have to round up and corral the employees
every time you hold these meetings, it sounds like you need to give
the group some serious feedback regarding the necessity of
attending these meetings on time, as well as serious feedback
regarding the sanctions associated with failure to do so.
</P>
<P>
   Look also at the content, organization and usefulness of these
meetings, and whether they are being held at the best time and
place. Having properly placed meetings that are truly productive
can have a definite impact on the attendance and the attendees. You
should also consider soliciting the employees' suggestions
regarding ways to improve these meetings.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the fact is these are departmental meetings
and everyone is expected to attend on time. Although the employees
may view them as an opportunity to engage in some sort of power
play with you, they need to understand that employees who engage in
sheepish behavior can get sheared.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Our company runs ads for open positions, gets lots of resumes
and only responds to the few that interest them. I end up fielding
phone calls from applicants who heard nothing and this wastes my
time. My boss says it is standard procedure to contact the good
applicants and the rest will get the message. What do you think
about this? H.K.
</P>
<P>
   A: The rest will get a message, but it will be more than a
rejection. This practice can also send a message indicating that
the company is shortsighted, cheap, uncaring and places minimal
emphasis on goodwill.
</P>
<P>
   It is neither difficult nor costly to put together a
professional letter that thanks the applicants and informs them
that their skills, education or experience did not fit the
specifications for the given position. Not only is this a courteous
step, it is actually a cost-saving step. After all, there are
direct costs associated with the time that you spend on these
calls.
</P>
<P>
   And, by ignoring a rejected applicant, there will be one more
person in the marketplace who has something negative to say about
the company. With the large number of applicants being rejected and
ignored by your company, this can have a costly impact over the
long term.
</P>
<P>
   Companies that are intent on ignoring applicants whom they
reject are often advised to use ads that provide a box number
rather than the company name. Short of this approach, companies
that fail to contact the rejected applicants are being unfair to
these applicants and to themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Our manager has this thing against job applicants who have
their resumes prepared by a professional service. He claims that he
can spot one every time, and he believes that these resumes point
to a lack of industriousness. Does this make any sense to you? A.G.
</P>
<P>
   A: It makes about as much sense as a consumer who refuses to buy
a particular product because the company used an ad agency instead
of developing the ad themselves. A resume is an advertisement for a
job applicant, and whether it was made by the applicant or a
professional service has nothing to do with the individual's level
of industriousness.
</P>
<P>
   It could even be argued, just as ridiculously, that an applicant
who has a professionally prepared resume is more industrious
because he or she had to find a resume service, put together a
draft of the resume, get all of the data to the service, and then
review and revise the final version.
</P>
<P>
   With so many resume books available and the outstanding printing
options on a personal computer, your boss is probably not as
proficient at spotting professionally prepared resumes as he
thinks. Not only is he making a mistake by screening out applicants
who used a resume service, he is compounding this mistake by
screening out those whose resumes look like they used such a
service.
</P>
<P>
   A larger concern is that your boss is letting some of his biases
and personal beliefs enter the hiring process, and this can spell
big trouble. He would be well-advised to focus more on the content
of each resume and less on who may have prepared it. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
