<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 20:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8129 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BELO-MARKETPLACE-ART-     01-18 1129
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BELO-MARKETPLACE-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: A.H. BELO ENDS BAD YEAR AS ADS FALL AT FLAGSHIP
PAPER
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Texas)  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By ALLEN R. MYERSON and FELICITY BARRINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's as if, as 1998 ended, some prankster turned A.H. Belo
Corp.'s stock chart upside down. Falling from $28 and change to
less than $20 last year, a stock that had long paced the newspaper
industry fell far behind, with its worst performance since Belo
went public in 1981. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The cause that everyone points to is weak advertising at the
company's flagship, The Dallas Morning News, which regularly prints
more column inches of advertising than any other newspaper in the
nation. But total advertising volume dropped by 2.3 percent in
1998, and classified advertising _ the most profitable advertising
newspapers sell _ led the decline. Some company executives and
analysts say that the drop was fueled by the migration of
high-technology help-wanted advertising to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   A quarterly earnings report due Thursday will show whether
Belo's efforts to control expenses in the last six months have had
results. Analysts, absorbing the company's cautions, have trimmed
their outlook to 20 cents a share, from 28 cents three months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Publishing represents about 45 percent of Belo's profits, and
The Morning News perhaps three-quarters of that. But those numbers
alone cannot convey the true heft of the newspaper as the symbol of
the financial and journalistic success of a media company that with
$1.2 billion in 1997 revenue is one of the nation's largest. When
The Morning News does well, Belo smiles and Wall Street smiles with
it. And when The Morning News suffers, Wall Street feels Belo's
pain.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, Belo's situation is stable, or even promising. At its
17 television stations, which now reach one of seven households
around the nation, advertising gains remain healthy. Its other
newspapers, including The Providence Journal-Bulletin and The
Press-Enterprise of Riverside, Calif., had good results in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   But the company and its many acquisitions have been built on the
growth and profitability of The Morning News. Given the strength of
the Dallas economy, investors want to know what's wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Decherd, Belo's chairman, president and chief executive,
has confronted the reversals with the same bravado that has helped
him turn a business run by his family for more than seven decades
into a media giant. He contends that the current doldrums are
simply part of the normal cycle that every business goes through,
especially when digesting major acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the company's stock, which had outperformed the
newspaper industry for two years, beginning in the fall of 1994,
had already begun to slip behind the group just before Belo's $1.7
billion acquisition of Journal-Bulletin Co. in 1997. And the gap
between Belo and the industry increased, so that by the end of
1998, its stock was the worst performer in the group.
</P>
<P>
   But Decherd argues that the stock's downturn should not detract
from the underlying strength that he sees resulting from Belo's
heavy investments in its newspapers and broadcast stations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's clearly a patient-money strategy,'' he said in an
interview. ``Crepe-hanging over the performance of The Dallas
Morning News in 1998 is the most ridiculous idea I can imagine.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Yet underlying the advantages are some of the broadest
uncertainties Belo and Decherd have faced since they won a fight to
the death with The Dallas Times Herald, which Belo bought and
closed in 1991. Decherd, who became the company's president six
years before that, at age 33, must now find among his
contemporaries successors for the two top executives who _ besides
him _ are most responsible for Belo's growth and success: Ward
Huey, the vice chairman and broadcast division chairman, who is 60,
and Burl Osborne, the publisher of The Dallas Morning News and
president of the newspaper division, who is 61. Two other top
executives quit the company last year.
</P>
<P>
   Although Huey and Osborne do not plan to leave before reaching
the usual retirement age of 65, preparing for their departures is
already a Decherd priority. ``The question you pose is one I take
very seriously and about which I have a lot of personal angst,'' he
said, finishing with a word that repeatedly creeps into his speech
these days.
</P>
<P>
   The naming of Robert Mong, 49, who had come up through the
Dallas newsroom, as the newspaper's president last September
appears to put him in a position to eventually become its publisher
and the chief of the entire newspaper division.
</P>
<P>
   Mong is striving to establish his cost-cutting credentials. His
first memo in his new job began, ``I want to let you know that we
will not be having a company picnic this fall,'' and went on to
cite the newspaper's lagging performance.
</P>
<P>
   Reporter's travel has been curtailed, and new parking decks, for
the newspaper and an adjacent television station, have been
delayed. So has construction of a new building for the Riverside
newspaper. And the planned pace for adding high-definition
capability to the television stations has been slowed. All told,
Belo intends to cut capital spending this year from a planned $125
million to $98 million.
</P>
<P>
   Early retirement incentives offered to 300 employees of The
Morning News and the Dallas television station were accepted by
about 180, averting the need to begin the year with layoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Mong succeeded Jeremy Halbreich, who had been president since
1991. Halbreich had worked for Decherd since graduating from
Harvard, which Decherd attended at the same time, in 1974. Although
Halbreich's associates say he was offered other positions with
Belo, he decided to leave.
</P>
<P>
   In June, Belo also lost Michael Perry, its chief financial
officer. Decherd described the resignation as voluntary. But two
people who know both men well said that their relationship had
grown rancorous. The separation agreement, which included
job-hunting services for Perry, reads almost like the terms of a
cease-fire in an armed conflict. One provision, for example,
commits each man to saying nothing negative about the other.
</P>
<P>
   Many of Perry's duties went to James Moroney, a 42-year-old,
Stanford-educated cousin of Decherd's and the son of a former Belo
chairman. Moroney had risen to second-in-command at the broadcast
division. As executive vice president for finance, with the new
chief financial officer reporting to him, he gave the company's
presentation last week at a Salomon Smith Barney investment
conference.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Despite the turnover and pending retirements, Decherd says that
investors should draw assurance from his own continuing tenure and
his status as Belo's largest shareholder. ``I'll be 48 in April and
have no plans to go anywhere,'' he said. Lest anyone doubt his
robust good health, he suggested with a laugh that an interviewer
meet him at the pool where his coach, a champion swimmer himself,
pushes him through hourlong workouts.
</P>
<P>
   At a newspaper generally considered one of the nation's best
regional dailies, Mong and Decherd pledge to continue the necessary
spending and investments. They cite the addition of yet another
weekly zoned section for the fringe suburbs this month and a
personal-technology section a few months ago, as well as the
purchase of new $36 million presses scheduled for installation in
the fall of 2000. The newspaper's reporters are also appearing on
the Texas Cable Channel, which Belo introduced Jan. 4 _ itself a
$15 million investment in plant and equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, even the newspaper's critics have noticed
improvements in The Morning News, which have brought in six
Pulitzer Prizes since 1986. ``The News is getting better, though we
hate to admit it'' said Molly Ivins, the popular columnist for the
rival Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
</P>
<P>
   The cash-flow margins for the newspaper _ perhaps the best
measure of profitability _ peaked at 34 percent in 1997 before
dropping to 32.6 percent in 1998. Newspaper margins in the 20's are
more common.
</P>
<P>
   Although Morning News circulation, like that of other major
newspapers, has been sliding, it was the loss of advertising that
prompted analysts to turn negative. Double-digit growth in
advertising revenue in 1995 and 1996 had tailed off to 7.2 percent
in 1997. And beginning last August, these sales went into a steep
decline. The greatest losses came in what had been the newspaper's
most profitable category, help-wanted, which was off by 6 percent
in September and 3 percent in October, the company told analysts.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts blame rate increases of 32 percent from 1995 to
1998 for retail advertising, 47 percent for general advertising and
75 percent for classified employment ads. But Belo executives say
that advertisers' cost per thousand readers remains below the
average for the largest newspapers. They say that high-technology
employment advertisements may have migrated to the Internet, or may
have dried up with the loss of Asian demand for high-technology
products. Similar weakness in classified advertising dented profits
for newspapers in San Jose, Calif., Los Angeles and Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Decherd sees no broader Internet invasion. ``These are
computer-facile people,'' he said, working his fingers as if his
conference table were a keyboard. ``I don't think it means there is
some sort of broader secular change in terms of newspaper
advertising generally.''
</P>
<P>
   But Decherd sees an even bigger challenge _ demonstrating that
in journalism, high quality can bring high and growing profits.
``If it doesn't work for Belo, my opinion is it won't work for
anybody,'' he said, his voice falling to a distant murmur.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-18-99 2006EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
