<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 20:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8133 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PATTERNS-FASHION-NYT     01-18 0686
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PATTERNS-FASHION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATTERNS: RETURN OF KATE MOSS; A PLUCKY DESIGNER; POCKETS FOR
RECORD BOOKS
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ The fashion industry welcomed back Kate Moss, who was
widely reported to have been in a hospital in Britain last year for
what was described as exhaustion. Photographers at the Versace
Couture show on Saturday hooted approval for the model as she did
her turns on the runway. Last week, she appeared in Milan in the
Versace men's show in one of the few women's outfits shown. On both
occasions Ms. Moss appeared to be well.
</P>
<P>
   Following the couture show on Saturday, Donatella Versace was
host of a 25th-birthday party for Ms. Moss at Les Bains Douches, a
Paris nightclub, but the British model declined to discuss her
health. Among the many fashion insiders who attended were the
designers Azzedine Alaeia and Rifat Ozbek and the photographer
Steven Meisel, who has photographed Ms. Moss dozens of times. Also
on hand were Liv Tyler, the actress, and Goldie, a British deejay.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, Ms. Moss did a photo shoot for W magazine, and Joan
Juliet Buck, the editor of French Vogue, said she, too, had booked
the model for a shoot.
</P>
<P>
   A PLUCKY DESIGNER
</P>
<P>
   It is an unusually brave designer who ventures from the United
States to France to make a living. The few who did it successfully
include Patrick Kelly and Mainbocher.
</P>
<P>
   But Abraham Pelham is unusual. He moved from New York to Paris
18 months ago and showed his second collection of elegant slit
skirts and sexy organza blouses during couture week in the Place
Vendome. He applied to the organizing body for the French shows for
membership to show as a couturier but was turned down. He will keep
trying, he said. Pelham has spent his life overcoming the obstacles
that come with designing from a wheelchair.
</P>
<P>
   Backstage before his show begins, he wheels around, tucking in a
shirt on a model here, tightening a belt there. He calls for
Jean-Marc Benoit, his assistant. ``Jean-Marc acts as two more
hands,'' said Pelham, who must support his left arm with his right
hand as he adjusts a model's belt or takes a cigarette to calm
pre-show jitters.
</P>
<P>
   Though Pelham developed polio at 2, he said he was never allowed
to think it was an impediment to realizing his dreams. He insists
on doing everything a designer who can walk does, like taking his
finale bow. He is wheeled out by an assistant to applause,
undoubtedly as much for his clothes as for his courage.
</P>
<P>
   POCKETS FOR RECORD BOOKS
</P>
<P>
   The apotheosis of functional fashion has arrived. The ``manteau
mobil home,'' available at Rooming, a modish home-accessories store
in the Carrousel du Louvre on the Rue de Rivoli, is a coat with no
fewer than 44 pockets. They are hidden in the hooded nylon coat by
an ingenious series of quilted rectangles.
</P>
<P>
   To reach the pockets, you unzip one of five zippers that run up
and down the coat and from shoulder to wrist. The unisex garment,
which is available in undercover black or screaming orange,
eliminates the need for a handbag or, for that matter, an overnight
case.
</P>
<P>
   Though the coat is made by Perigot, a French company, the source
of this innovation is none other than Issey Miyake, the Japanese
designer, whose name is not on the label.
</P>
<P>
   Kal Ruttenstein, the fashion director of Bloomingdale's, said he
owns three Miyake coats that he bought in the last nine months,
which seem to be earlier versions of manteau mobil home. These
coats, including a clear nylon style bought at the trendy boutique
Colette on Thursday, bear Miyake's name and the Final Home label,
and they have at least three dozen fewer pockets.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're great for traveling,'' said Ruttenstein, who carries
show invitations and giveaways in his pockets. ``They're the style
of the millennium. Hands-free fashion.''
</P>
<P>
   He paid about $300 for his coats (which neither Bloomingdale's
nor the Miyake boutique in New York sells). But Final Home is sold
in New York at Antique Boutique and at Trash and Vaudeville. The
more extreme Perigot version costs about $295 at Rooming.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-18-99 2008EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990118.0347 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 20:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8140 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-ATLANTA-ART-NYT &LR;      01-18 1003
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-ATLANTA-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ATLANTA SOARS ALONG WITH ITS SUPER BOWL-BOUND FALCONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Also moving in `s' category) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By RICK BRAGG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A person can live with losing, David West knows, the
same way he lives with any other chronic pain. But imagine if, one
day, while sitting in his favorite recliner in front of a
wide-screen television, the pain of 33 years just slipped away, and
in its place was pride and joy.
</P>
<P>
   It happened Sunday. West, a 46-year-old driver for United Parcel
Service and an Atlanta Falcons fan since he was a child in Cairo,
Ga., was healed.
</P>
<P>
   ``A miracle,'' he said, ``has happened.''
</P>
<P>
   On the screen, the Atlanta Falcons, the National Football
League's doormat for a third of a century, wildly celebrated their
overtime victory over the heavily favored Minnesota Vikings as the
impossible dream of a Super Bowl suddenly became a reality. In his
home, West just sat there with his hands balled into fists, and
cried like a baby.
</P>
<P>
   ``A chill went through me,'' he said. ``I thought, `Is it true,
or is it a dream?' Tears got in my eyes. My wife came in and said,
`You all right?' And I was speechless. Then I got over it, and I
began to holler.''
</P>
<P>
   Fans used to winning, fans in cities where teams routinely make
a realistic run for the NFL championship, might not understand such
a quiet reaction to winning, but like so many other Falcons fans,
West had to recover from the shock of it before he could whoop,
stomp and shimmy. The Falcons, going into this year, had a record
of 182 wins, 293 losses and 5 ties, which is one of the worst
records in professional football.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kind of got used to them being sorry,'' said Derrick Clark,
a 31-year-old UPS driver. ``We just never expected much. But it's
our team and you've got to pull with them, winning or losing. Now I
say, jump on the bandwagon and ride it through.''
</P>
<P>
   Here, people did not even have the nerve to say, ``Just wait
till next year,'' as losing seasons came and went, coaches came and
went.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wretches,'' wrote Steve Hummer, a sports columnist for The
Atlanta Journal-Constitution, ``the way that Dickens used to make
them.''
</P>
<P>
   In Denver, whose Broncos will play the Falcons in the Super Bowl
in Miami on Jan. 31, it is just one more trip to the championship
game. But in Atlanta, it is a 14-2 regular season with playoff
victories over San Francisco and Minnesota, and that is ecstasy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to couldn't go to sleep, knowing they would lose,''
said Curtis Brown, 34, a furniture refinisher who is out of work.
``It used to give me a headache watching them play. But I knew,
someday, they would get on top.''
</P>
<P>
   They became a team a man could risk his paycheck on, and Brown
encouraged his friends to do just that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd tell them, `Take everything you have and put it on the
Falcons,''' he said.
</P>
<P>
   People here say it was all about believing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it took a lot of faith,'' said West.
</P>
<P>
   Although no one seems sure why fate seemed to favor the Falcons
over the Vikings on Sunday, there were signs of Divine
Intervention. As the Falcons' kicker, Morten Andersen, lined up to
kick what turned out to be the game-winning field goal, several of
his teammates did not even look. They had formed a tight knot on
the sideline, and were in prayer. In the stands, people held hands
and prayed.
</P>
<P>
   Praying, of course, later gave way to hard drinking. Drunks fell
all over themselves in sports bars all over Georgia, hundreds of
wild-eyed fans ran _ well, staggered _ through the streets of
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands swarmed Hartsfield Atlanta International Airport to
greet the Falcons on Sunday night, as many as 6,000 by some
estimates _ so many that the airport closed its doors to all but
ticket-holders.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone seems to have a different opinion of why and how all
this good fortune has befallen this team. At the American Lunch, a
buffet where downtown business types line up for collards and
squash and chicken wings, the people working the steam said it had
to be the new coach.
</P>
<P>
   Last year the Falcons hired Dan Reeves, a Georgia boy himself,
whose drawl seemed to fit here. After going 1-7 at midseason in
1997, the Falcons won 22 of their next 26 games. Reeves had heart
bypass surgery last month, but returned to the sideline in this
post-season, further endearing himself to Atlanta fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``A hell of a coach,'' said Dexter Dawson, 45, mopping up after
the lunchtime rush.
</P>
<P>
   ``A hell of a man,'' said Hilda Reese, 48, standing over the
macaroni and cheese.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves, said Dawson, ``made them believe they could win.''
</P>
<P>
   Willene Patrick always believed. ``I'm a native of Atlanta,''
she said. ``I always had faith.''
</P>
<P>
   But even as the Falcons were winning, disbelievers in this city
of migrants _ in Atlanta, it often seems as if everybody is from
someplace else _ said it could not last. They cheered for their
home teams, for San Francisco and New York and others, and waited
for the Falcons' legacy to catch up with them.
</P>
<P>
   Boe Richardson, 36, a waiter who watched the Falcons victory in
the All Star Cafe downtown, smarted under that talk all season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sweet for us,'' he said. ``All through this year, we
still got a lot of flack, people saying it's just luck.''
</P>
<P>
   As the Falcons lined up for their field goal try to win the game
that would send them to the Super Bowl, ``not one person was
sitting down'' in the All Star Cafe, Richardson said.
</P>
<P>
   Now only the Broncos stand between the Falcons and history.
Atlanta has seen the Braves go to the World Series four times this
decade, and watched them win it in 1995. And the city has the
Olympics as part of its history. But now, in what would have once
been the least likely of chances, it has a shot at football
greatness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought,'' said West, ``this day would never come.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-18-99 2013EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990118.0348 </DOCNO>
