<HEADER>
A8142 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-HUMMER-COLUMN19-C     01-18 0562
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-HUMMER-COLUMN19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Atlanta coach _ and his team _ deemed fit for Super Sunday
 &HT;    By Steve Hummer
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Everybody knows the score and the impact. But how,
exactly, did certain key Falcons grade out after Sunday's gripping
NFC Championship? The doctors couldn't tell until they looked at
the film.
</P>
<P>
   So, they had Dan Reeves in first thing Monday morning for
another round of Piedmont Hospital probing. After a blood test,
X-ray and cardiogram, they perscribed one Super Bowl and plenty of
bed rest.
</P>
<P>
   They passed on one part of the routine exam, however. The stress
test seemed redundant. ''I think you passed that yesterday,'' his
doctor told him, on the theory that an overtime victory in hostile
territory for the ultimate NFL prize was at least as trying as a
few minutes on a treadmill. His insurance company will be pleased.
</P>
<P>
   An obvious aspect to Sunday's miracle in Minnesota was the level
of coaching that has gone into the making of a new and improved
Falcon. A little open-heart surgery was not going to interfere with
the leadership. The job Reeves and his staff did preparing the
Falcons for the NFL's loudest, most mind-rattling venue was
extraordinary.
</P>
<P>
   ''As important as it was for us to do the Xs and Os, it was more
important for us to come up with what was the best way to handle
the crowd noise,'' Reeves said.
</P>
<P>
   Not a flinch, not a buckle, not a twitch. Operating off a silent
snap count, the Falcons offense seemed to barely notice the
Metrodome's notorious din.
</P>
<P>
   ''The thing I was most impressed with was the way our football
team played with with the noise and there was not one single
illegal procedure, no false starts,'' Reeves said. ''And every film
you looked at there were at least six to eight by everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Practice it like you want to play it _ as old school as Reeves
himself. All week before the trip to the Metrodome, they worked
under the assumption that game day was going to be one complicated,
violent pantomime. Eleven Charlie Chaplins couldn't have pulled it
off as well.
</P>
<P>
   Slowly, they installed poise into the gameplan, the one
attribute that kept them viable when the purple crazies were
raging.
</P>
<P>
   ''The poise they had was the thing we talked about as being
really important. And it couldn't be four guys being poised (along
the offensive line), it had to come from all six guys. It had to be
six-out-of-six concentrating on every single play,'' Reeves said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We tried to go through practice without making a single
mistake. There more on Wednesay; we got better on Thursday; we were
a lot better on Friday, so you felt really good.''
</P>
<P>
   Now comes the roman numeraled orgy, which is nothing but two
weeks of distractions momentarily interrupted by a football game.
It is the World Series, cubed. The Final Four on steroids.
</P>
<P>
   Denver was there and won it just a year ago. It has a handle on
surviving the Super Bowl. Now the Falcons coaches and the few
veteran players must again attempt to make these Dirty Birds
unflappable.
</P>
<P>
   It is daunting, but so was trying to make sense in the
Metrodome. Two more weeks of work for Reeves. One more important
message: There is no reason the Falcons have to suffer a galloping
case of the Super Bowl yips.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
