<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 20:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8143 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-FALCONS19-COX     01-18 0884
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    For Falcons, even routine is surreal
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ On a Monday unlike any before at Falcon headquarters
in Suwanee, the sun shone brightly, and there was a general mood of
controled delirium _ if there is such a thing. The only thing that
kept it from being a perfect day was a very stiff breeze.
</P>
<P>
   Call it the wind of change.
</P>
<P>
   In the first 24 hours after the Falcons beat the Minnesota
Vikings 30-27 in overtime to clinch the first Super Bowl appearance
in the 33-year history of the franchise, coaches and players tried
to follow a routine.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing, though, was routine.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of autograph-seeking fans came and went over the course
of the day. Players worked out in the weight room, some got injury
treatment, and they met as usual at 2 p.m. to review film from the
game the day before.
</P>
<P>
   But things were out of whack. For one, coach Dan Reeves _ about
as punctual a person as one might meet _ was some 17 minutes late
for his usual Monday press conference, attended by perhaps three
dozen media.
</P>
<P>
   It was just another amazing development. He couldn't believe the
thousands of people who showed up at the airport Sunday night to
greet the team. He didn't get to finish reviewing game film Monday
morning like he usually does.
</P>
<P>
   Things just weren't the same for coaches and players of a team
that was 1-7 in the middle of last season before winning 22 of 26,
including 11 straight.
</P>
<P>
   ''I got four and a half hours sleep,'' he said. ''There were 38
messages when I got home last night, haven't had time to look at
them.'
</P>
<P>
   Nothing was more amazing that Sunday's win over the Vikings
(16-2), who were 9-0 at home, winning by an average of 25.6 points.
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota scored on its first four possessions to take a 20-7
lead, but then scored just seven points on its last 10 possessions.
Kicker Gary Anderson, who had not missed a kick of any kind all
year, missed a 38-yard field goal with 2:07 left that would have
given the Vikings a 10-point lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons countered with an eight-play, 71-yard drive, tying
the game with 49 seconds left on a 16-yard pass from Chris Chandler
to Terance Mathis.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta's defense held twice in the overtime, and the offense
went on a 10-play, 70-yard drive to history. It ended with a
38-yard field goal by Morten Andersen with 3:09 left in the
overtime _ from nearly the same spot Gary Anderson missed.
</P>
<P>
   Ball game.
</P>
<P>
   ''If . . . somebody was writing a script for a movie, I don't
think they could come up with one that's been like this season,''
said Reeves, who was 2-6 in previous Super Bowls as a player,
assistant and head coach with the Cowboys and Broncos.
</P>
<P>
   ''From my standpoint, this is as excited as I've ever been to be
in a Super Bowl because it's certainly not something you would have
thought was realistic when the season started. This team has been
unbelievable.''
</P>
<P>
   Reeves got something in the mail from the NFL office Monday
regarding the Super Bowl. It was addressed to, ''The Atlanta
Falcons _ head coach Dennis Green.''
</P>
<P>
   Green coaches the Vikings, who were favored by 11 points over at
Atlanta team that had only once once in its history at Minnesota _
in 1966. ''They changed the team,'' Reeves said, ''but forgot to
change the coach.''
</P>
<P>
   That's how big a shock Sunday was.
</P>
<P>
   ''I woke up this morning and pinched myself,'' said wide
receiver Tim Dwight. ''To go to the Super Bowl my rookie year . . .
that's just incredible. This place (Falcons training facility in
Suwanee, Ga.) was jacked when we got back last night, and thousands
of fans were waiting. It's been a different Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ''It just goes to show you it doesn't matter what people outside
the walls (of Falcons headquarters) say; it's what's inside the
walls that matters.''
</P>
<P>
   Middle linebacker Jessie Tuggle, the senior Falcons with 12
years of mostly miserable experience, was still floating.
</P>
<P>
   ''Oh man, it's been like a dreamworld,'' he said. ''I don't know
what the odds were (60-1 before the season against the Falcons
winning the Super Bowl), but we beat them. All the pieces of the
puzzle have just come together unbelievably.''
</P>
<P>
   There was controversy in Suwanee, however.
</P>
<P>
   At midseason, Reeves promised he would do the ''Dirty Bird''
dance downtown if the Falcons made it to the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   He claimed he did it Monday on Peachtree Street at 6:45 a.m.,
stopping his car as he was on his way to film a spot on ABC's
''Good Morning America.''
</P>
<P>
   ''There was nobody on the road. No traffic,'' he said. ''That's
the reason I did it. I was good, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuggle said, ''That don't count. There got to be people there,
cameras, witnesses''
</P>
<P>
   Mathis said, ''That's a copout.''
</P>
<P>
   Defensive end Chuck Smith said players are going to band
together to haul Reeves downtown to do the dance.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm opposed to all that stuff,'' Reeves said, ''but I've seen
how good the 'Dirty Bird' has been for the city of Atlanta. There
were guys standing on tractors at the airport doing it when we got
home. There's no question it's turned this town around.''
</P>
<P>
   Matt Winkeljohn writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
