<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 20:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8144 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VODAFONE-GENT-ART-2TA     01-18 1162
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VODAFONE-GENT-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VODAFONE'S CHRIS GENT: AFFINITY FOR HARDBALL, AS WELL AS CRICKET 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo (NYT8) has been sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(bl) 
By ALAN COWELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Cricket, that languorous English pursuit, looms large
in the life of Christopher Charles Gent, chief executive of
Vodafone Group PLC, which agreed on Friday to pay $60 billion for
Airtouch Communications, the U.S. wireless phone giant, in
Britain's largest takeover ever.
</P>
<P>
   As a teen-ager, he attended a school overlooking the Oval
cricket ground in South London, a premier site for the sport.
Vodafone, indeed, sponsors the English national cricket team, and
Gent's friends include the former Conservative prime minister, John
Major, whose first diversion after being ousted in elections in
1997 was going to watch cricket.
</P>
<P>
   His interests _ other than driving an Aston Martin sports car _
as listed in his company biography include ``playing tennis and
watching cricket.'' And, most recently, Gent, 50, acknowledged with
a tight kind of smile in an interview Monday that he was indeed at
the Sydney cricket ground, where England was playing Australia,
when he began his campaign on New Year's Day to thwart Bell
Atlantic in a battle for Airtouch, the American company he had been
coveting for months as part of his dream of building a global
wireless business.
</P>
<P>
   But Gent's fondness for cricket, in which it can take five days
just to reach a draw, does not signal a leisurely approach to
business. Working his cellular phone over the following three days
in negotiations that spread around the globe, his associates say,
Gent showed a decisiveness and resolution that helps explain why
Vodafone is Britain's leading wireless operator with appetites as
large as Gent's ambitions for the company.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without Chris' leadership and clear thinking on where he felt
Vodafone ought to be, there could have been a different outcome''
to the battle for Airtouch, said Scott Mead, a Goldman, Sachs
managing director who led the team advising Vodafone. ``The guy is
driven. Make no mistake about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Gent said in the interview Monday, his ambition is not
simply to promote the use of wireless communications to complement
fixed-line telephones but to turn mobile phones into a substitute
for them. He wants to persuade half the people in the industrial
world to use a wireless phone by 2003.
</P>
<P>
   And, having acquired stakes in many European wireless markets,
complementing those of Airtouch, he signaled Monday that part of
his strategy was to export to the United States some of the same
marketing techniques that have made Vodafone Britain's top wireless
operator. These include prepaid services that drew in 755,000 of
the 933,000 new British customers that Vodafone says it acquired in
the last three months of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The combined company, Vodafone Airtouch, ``in the next decade
will become on of the top 10 companies in the world,'' he predicted
at a news conference Monday.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, the ambitious forecast is an extension of
Vodafone's own rise, starting as a modest subsidiary of Racal
Electronics, formed in 1985, and spun off in 1988 at a time many
fixed-line carriers saw wireless phone communications as a passing
fancy. Gent, lured away from a computer services business as
managing director of the new company, took a different view,
proclaiming wireless the future of telecommunications.
</P>
<P>
   From then until 1996, he played a key role in building
Vodafone's British operations while Sir Gerald Whent presided over
the company as chief executive. ``Chris is a calm, collected
person,'' Whent said recently. ``I didn't believe he had the verve
tycoons are made of, but he has proved me wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, some of his critics say there is a ruthless streak to
Gent beneath his exterior of snappy shirts, bright suspenders and
apparent diffidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has the ability to take very cold and objective decisions
based on the facts,'' said an associate who spoke on the condition
of anonymity. ``He is definitely not shy, but he's not the
glad-handing type.'' One characterization after his elevation to
chief executive, British newspapers reported, was ``corn-jumper,''
meaning that he trod on business associates' toes.
</P>
<P>
   ``People should not think that it's only American chief
executives who are hard-driving,'' a friend said, disputing the
idea that his presence at the Sydney cricket ground implied ``he
was out there on a complete boondoggle.'' Indeed, Gent stressed
Monday that he had been visiting Australia and New Zealand on
business _ with cricket as a bonus.
</P>
<P>
   Gent took over as chief executive in January 1997 just as
Vodafone was beginning to feel the pinch from such upstart British
rivals as Orange PLC and One2One. He changed the company's logo,
fought aggressively for market share, and in March 1998 presided
over a long-term strategy meeting of the company's board and its
advisers that resolved to make a major acquisition. The choice
facing Vodafone, he told associates, was ``to hunt or be hunted'' _
a perception that underpinned his refusal to let Bell Atlantic
outbid him for Airtouch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Opportunities like that come up and either you take them or
they are gone,'' an associate said.
</P>
<P>
   Gent was born in Gosport, a southern coastal town, and his
formal education ended when he left school to work as a trainee
bank manager. His ambitions were initially political and in 1977,
at 29, he was elected national chairman of the Young Conservatives,
the youth wing of the Tory party. During that period, he formed
political connections that some have depicted as giving Vodafone an
edge when a Conservative government deregulated the
telecommunications business in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, his ties to the Conservatives have loosened,
though not to the point, he said, of switching to the Labor Party.
In the May 1997 national election, Gent urged voters to support the
Conservatives. Late last year, though, he was one of the signers of
an open letter to Prime Minister Tony Blair's Labor government,
urging it to move faster toward adopting the single European
currency, in direct contradiction of Conservative policy.
</P>
<P>
   In taking over as chief executive of Vodafone Airtouch, Gent
will be moving into the U.S. telecommunications world, which, he
says, has been ``slightly disappointing'' compared with the surging
expansion of the wireless business in Britain and Continental
Europe.
</P>
<P>
   That is not the only difference. By some estimates, Airtouch
chief executive Sam Ginn stands to make more than $300 million in
stock options from the deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The compensation packages between the U.K. and the U.S. have
been very different for some time,'' Gent noted.
</P>
<P>
   But would he receive the same kind of windfall as Ginn?
``Absolutely not,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
