<SLUG> BC-MULTICULTURAL-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: PROGRESS CITED IN EXPANDING MINORITY-ORIENTED
ADVERTISING
</HEADLINE>
 (bl) 
By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The organizers of efforts to press advertisers and
agencies to devote more attention and resources to consumers from
minority groups _ and to the media aimed at such consumers _ say
they are generally pleased with the initial responses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm cautiously optimistic,'' said the Rev. Al Sharpton, who
has been the most outspoken leader of the efforts to address
so-called markets of color.
</P>
<P>
   Progress on reversing what he called ``years of entrenched
problems'' can be achieved, he added, ``if we are consistent and
persistent.''
</P>
<P>
   Sharpton's conciliatory assessments were made at a news
conference during a meeting Monday on multicultural markets and
media at the Waldorf-Astoria Hotel in midtown Manhattan. The
meeting drew 250 to 300 participants, including, by Sharpton's
estimate, top executives representing 40 advertisers and 12
agencies.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is in our judgment very significant, in fact historic, to
bring the advertising industry together to deal with this issue,''
Sharpton said. ``This is not a one-night stand at the Waldorf,'' he
added, smiling. ``This is a marriage.''
</P>
<P>
   If wedding bells ring, it will be partly because advertiser and
agency executives quickly agreed to join Sharpton and his advocacy
organization, the National Action Network, as hosts of the meeting.
Among the participants were the American Association of Advertising
Agencies, the Association of National Advertisers and the American
Advertising Federation.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a problem,'' acknowledged Wally Snyder, president and
chief executive of the federation, who added: ``And there are
opportunities. So let's get on with the solution that would allow
us to capitalize on the opportunities.''
</P>
<P>
   The long-debated issue of whether the amount of advertising
spending in ethnic media adequately reflects the size and spending
power of ethnic markets was revived last May with the publication
of an internal memo from the Katz Media Group unit of Chancellor
Communications. The memo suggested that a radio station aimed at
mainstream listeners try to sell commercial time by denigrating
stations with large black or Hispanic audiences, using the argument
that advertisers want ``prospects, not suspects.''
</P>
<P>
   A study released last week by the Federal Communications
Commission concluded that radio stations aimed primarily at black
and Hispanic audiences drew significantly less ad revenue per
listener.
</P>
<P>
   A month after the disclosure of the Katz memo, Sharpton
threatened ``a long, hot summer on Madison Avenue'' if advertisers
and agencies did not respond to complaints that they were
discriminating against ethnic media.
</P>
<P>
   Two advertisers criticized by Sharpton were praised effusively
yesterday for agreeing _ ``in writing,'' as he repeated _ to
address those complaints.
</P>
<P>
   One was Pepsi-Cola Co. unit of Pepsico Inc. and the other was
Federated Department Stores Inc., parent of retail chains like
Macy's and Bloomingdale's. Pepsi-Cola agreed to spend more in
ethnic radio and magazines, Sharpton said, and Federated agreed to
spend more in ethnic radio.
</P>
<P>
   The attendees, who included celebrities like Don King and Isaac
Hayes, listened to presentations that ranged from dry recitations
of demographic data about black, Hispanic and Asian-American
consumers to fervent pleas to end what was portrayed as disrespect
for and discrimination against ethnic groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``An opportunity to get a fair hearing is all we ask for,'' said
Earl G. Graves Jr., president and chief operating officer at Black
Enterprise magazine in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``I truly believe Madison Avenue has a problem,'' Graves said.
``General market advertising agencies don't understand the
African-American market and don't take the market seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You cannot have a 23-year-old white media planner put together
a plan,'' he added, ``and assume you are in touch with what the
African-American market is doing.'' Black Enterprise is published
by Earl G. Graves Ltd.
</P>
<P>
   ``The table is big,'' said Ana Maria Fernandez Haar, president
of the Association of Hispanic Advertising Agencies and president
and chief executive at IAC Advertising Group in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more people we sit at it,'' she added, ``the better it
is.''
</P>
<P>
   There were repeated references to the Rev. Dr. Martin Luther
King Jr.; the meeting was timed to take place on the holiday
honoring him.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of us talking to each other and going forward,'' Sharpton
said, ``is what Martin Luther King would've wanted us to do.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A year from today, we'll have the same summit,'' he added,
``but we'll be giving a report on the progress we'll have made in
the past year.''
</P>
<P>
   There were lighter moments, too, such as when Jeff Yang,
publisher of A. Magazine: Inside Asian America, published by Metro
East Publications in New York, began his presentation on the
Asian-American consumer market by declaring: ``Unfortunately, my
Chinese is pretty terrible. Buenos dias.'' The audience responded
with laughter and applause.
</P>
<P>
   Graves recommended during his remarks that money devoted to
buying ads in black media ought to be significant sums rather than
``part of the `This should keep Sharpton from calling fund.'''
</P>
<P>
   And during the news conference, Sharpton compared his meetings
with top agency managers to discuss his complaints to visiting
``the Rocky Mountains: the higher up you get, the whiter it got.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
