<SLUG> BC-HKN-ISLANDERS-JONSSON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLOUNDERING ISLANDERS LOSE JONSSON, THEIR LONE ALL-STAR
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By TARIK EL-BASHIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYOSSET, N.Y. _ Just when it seemed the Islanders' situation
could not get any worse, the team learned Monday it would be
without its all-star defenseman, Kenny Jonsson, for a month because
of a sprained knee.
</P>
<P>
   Jonsson, who was to be the Islanders' lone representative at
Sunday's All-Star Game, sustained a partial tear of the medial
collateral ligament in his right knee last Saturday in a light
collision with a Florida Panthers defenseman, Robert Svehla. It was
the same knee that Jonsson had twisted earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   Jonsson will not be able to play in the All-Star Game in Tampa,
Fla. As a result, the Islanders will likely not be represented in
the game.
</P>
<P>
   Jonsson was named to the World Team by the National Hockey
League's operations staff last week. But his replacement, to be
named by that same group, headed by Colin Campbell, does not have
to be an Islander. Because of the injuries to defensemen Uwe Krupp
(the Detroit Red Wings) and Roman Hamrlik (the Edmonton Oilers),
both expected to miss the game, Campbell has to pick another
defenseman. The Islanders' only other non-North American defenseman
is the rookie Zdeno Chara.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's news could not have come at a worse time for the
Islanders, who have not won in 10 games and have the league's
second-worst record at 13-28-3. Only the Tampa Bay Lightning
(9-30-4) is worse.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Milbury, the Islanders' coach and general manager, did not
meet with reporters after Monday's practice at IceWorks. Jonsson
was unavailable for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Without Jonsson or his defensive partner Rich Pilon, who is also
out with a sprained knee, the Islanders have only five healthy
defensemen and must promote a minor leaguer. Ted Crowley, an
offensive defenseman just acquired from Colorado, is the leading
candidate, but the decision will not be made until after Gordie
Clark, the Islanders' assistant general manager, scouts their
American Hockey League affiliate, the Lowell, Mass., Lock Monsters,
Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   The Islanders have also lost the enforcer Gino Odjick, who had
season-ending surgery Monday to repair a torn abdominal muscle. He
missed the previous 16 games.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
