<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 20:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8151 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FALL-FASHION-ART-NYT     01-18 1309
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FALL-FASHION-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE BAD BOY OF PARIS WHO MADE GOOD
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(ms) 
 By CONSTANCE C.R. WHITE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ The shock of Yves Saint Laurent's beatnik-inspired 1960
collection for the House of Dior was proof of a rebellious nature.
That was before Saint Laurent made the journey that has brought him
to the stature of a classic in French fashion.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Jean Paul Gaultier is tracing a similar trajectory _
from being the designer once most likely to snub the fashion
establishment to one who has become a supreme practitioner of that
classic of French dressmaking called haute couture.
</P>
<P>
   In fashion history, the three pillars of the couture traditions
are Saint Laurent, Madeleine Vionnet and Alix Gres. And in his
spring 1999 couture presentation on Sunday, Gaultier brilliantly
evoked all three.
</P>
<P>
   The men's suits in metallic organza, the black tuxedo suits and
a sinuous tuxedo dress with a flamenco hemline all recalled Saint
Laurent. But the work was pure Gaultier. His jersey gowns flowed
like heavy cream from plate-shaped necklaces around the models'
necks. Hundreds, if not thousands of plisse tucks must have gone
into a delectable shirtwaist chiffon dress in opalescent white.
</P>
<P>
   Presiding over the show, in spirit and in person, was Countess
Jacqueline de Ribes, a long-admired couture client and a mainstay
of French society, who had already ordered the outfit Gaultier
called Confidence _ a brown stretch sweater and trouser set that
bares one shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   For all the judicious gowns and suits the designer showed, a
Gaultier collection without a drop of irreverence would be like
``Seinfeld'' without Kramer. Gaultier provided several naughty
winks: a sexy jump suit with huge flamenco pants, scarves with
built-in handbags and a strapless sheath gown styled like a pair of
jeans in washed blue denim.
</P>
<P>
   All of Gaultier's pent-up classicism is being released: this
rabble-rouser of design is producing the most classical haute
couture, and it is stunning to see.
</P>
<P>
   If there is a drawback to this emerging side of the designer, it
is the evidence that commercial realities are being felt in couture
design, once the province of fashion for fashion's sake. So
Gaultier's show was laced with pants suits and conservative
shirtdresses.
</P>
<P>
   And he was not alone: from Gaultier to Christian Dior,
Valentino, Givenchy, Versace and Ungaro, there was an unfortunate
tendency to show too-perfect jackets over dresses and pants suits.
</P>
<P>
   At Valentino, there was scarcely anything else. Valentino,
famous for designs of great beauty, failed to get this collection
into the air. The parade of proper caftan jackets and somber sheath
dresses and skirts must have been a soporific to the designer's
fans who jetted in from around the world.
</P>
<P>
   Those calling for more reality in couture may want to think
twice if such clothes are the result. Suits are perfectly nice for
everyday wear, but couture begs for clothes that celebrate
dressmaking virtuosity or design creativity. Couture should be
sublime. There are already enough ``real'' clothes in the world _
maybe too many.
</P>
<P>
   At this time of growing realism, at least one couture designer,
John Galliano, has gone in the opposite direction, recalling the
Surrealist movement of the 1920s through the '40s, a period when
fashion was closest to an art movement, when dress designers,
photographers and artists like Schiaperelli, Man Ray, Dali, Cocteau
and Bebe Berard all fed one another's creativity.
</P>
<P>
   Turning to this period, Galliano created a marriage of artistry
and couture technique for Christian Dior. Wisely, the designer
draws upon the tamer aspects of Surrealism, marrying menswear
inspirations and femininity. In a brief but charming speech at the
start of the show, he talked about his fascination with Dali and
his wife, Gala.
</P>
<P>
   In Surrealism, Galliano reminded his audience _ which consisted
of clients like Alison Eastwood (Clint's daughter), Nan Kempner,
Anne Bass, Veronica Hearst, Diane Von Furstenburg and her daughter,
Alexandra _ ``everything is not always as it seems.'' That could
have been license for boisterous kitsch, but Galliano turned this
inspiration into one of his most refined and wearable collections
to date.
</P>
<P>
   So, yes _ wearable fashion can still be art. Galliano drove home
the point with a Prince of Wales double-breasted pants suit, worn
backward. The power struggle he posited between the masculine side
of the collection (represented by Dali) and the feminine side
(Gala) was resolved creatively with the triumph of his dresses over
wide-leg trousers suits. Though they were beautifully wrought, the
man-tailored suits were outdone by styles like a delicate ecru
off-the-shoulder sheath with side buttons, and a stunning day dress
in Prince of Wales plaid, pulled tight across the bodice.
</P>
<P>
   In a great marriage of Surrealism and couture, Galliano posed
one model, in long black gloves and a glistening white gown,
against a black backdrop. The tableau rendered the model's arms and
hands invisible against the backdrop, thus highlighting the line
and drape of the dress.
</P>
<P>
   Restraint is a virtue that not all designers know how to use.
Alexander McQueen for Givenchy understands how to pull back but
still keep the action going. This designer, who is still in his
20s, recognizes the magic that couture can be. A skirt made of
woven ribbons in as many colors as a pinata and a black and pale
gold harlequin gown with ruffled skirt and a matching overcoat were
expertly rendered. So too, were three lustrous swag-tailored long
jackets over trousers and a remarkable butter-yellow unitard
covered in jeweled triangles. The overall effect was not always
sensational, but this was a purposeful, sturdy couture collection,
full of wearable clothes.
</P>
<P>
   In the wash of unremarkable jackets and pants suits in Paris, it
was sometimes hard to tell where ready-to-wear ended and couture
began. Couture has to be more than custom work: it must have an
element of transcendence.
</P>
<P>
   Emanuel Ungaro offered some of both schools. There were
faultless jackets and dresses, all girlish and sweet, like the
ivory and rose sheer blouse draped under a beige jacket.
</P>
<P>
   His dreams came to life in a top strung from beaded chains with
a rippling floral skirt, or in layers of seafoam over pale green,
in turn layered over antique plum.
</P>
<P>
   Mystery, however, does not abound in Donatella Versace's
designs. She seeks to bring a hard edge to couture. There were bold
ideas in her clothes, but some provocatively draped negligee
dresses she showed a week ago in Milan spoke better to the art that
the Versaces have perfected in fashion.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Versace concentrated on exploring unusual fabrics and
fabric-enhancing techniques, rather than on ways to use these
materials for a flattering effect. Among her interesting mediums
were cashmere pierced with needles of Venetian glass, rosewood
sticks woven with Swarovski crystals, and woven raffia. The
collection undoubtedly had some funk to it, but never found a a
groove.
</P>
<P>
   Leaping from long hems to short is a difficult maneuver, and
both Ms. Versace and Ocimar Versolato tried to span both sides.
Versolato's draped evening gowns strive to embody a kind of ancient
nobility, but with their angular planes they are more reminiscent
of Balenciaga than Mme. Gres.
</P>
<P>
   As the screen on the back of his stage revolved 180 degrees each
time a new model was about to appear, one never knew which
Versolato might make an entrance. Would it be the noble princess
clad in floor-sweeping chiffon or the flip go-go girl in a white
mini dress, the realistic couture or its more exciting and
progressive sister, fantasy?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
