<SLUG> BC-TN-TORNADOES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TORNADOES KILL 8 IN TENNESSEE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(JT) 
 By EMILY YELLIN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEMPHIS, Tenn. _ Tornadoes that cut through Tennessee on Sunday
killed at least 8 people and injured 105, officials reported
Monday, with the most damage in Jackson and surrounding Madison
County northeast of Memphis, where 6 people died and more than 60
buildings were destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   Tornadoes were seen or touched down in 12 counties and damage
was reported in 16 additional counties from the unusual winter
tornadoes, which roared across the state's tornado alley with gusts
up to 100 mph in middle and western Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Topographically, that is where Gulf moisture meets Canadian
jet streams, so it tends to be a breeding ground for tornadoes,''
said Cecil Whaley, director of natural hazards for the Tennessee
Emergency Management Agency. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Even so, most people in the area were not expecting tornadoes in
January. ``This is strange,'' said W. Jerry Smith, 64, president of
the George A. Smith and Sons funeral home. ``We never have storms
like this in the dead of winter.''
</P>
<P>
   Whaley said, ``People get lulled into thinking this is ice storm
season, but you have to watch out because severe weather is a
threat now too as long as these conditions exist.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith's funeral home in Bemis, a suburb south of Jackson, was
destroyed. ``I went out there last night after it was all over,''
Smith said, ``and there was only one wall left standing and a pile
of rubble. At 2 yesterday afternoon we had a large service
there.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Monday, Smith was back at work in his two other funeral homes in
the Jackson area, where part of his day was spent meeting with
three of the families who had lost relatives in the storm. ``I can
build a new funeral home,'' he said. ``But now I'm dealing with
people who have problems that can't be fixed. So that is what is
important.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A fire station next to the funeral home was also damaged and
cleanup efforts continued Monday. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Jackson Sun newspaper lost power at its offices, causing
reporters and editors to pack up computers about 9 p.m. on Sunday
and move the newsroom to the basement of the executive editor's
house.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were working off the Ping-Pong table in my rec room,''
said Richard Schneider, the executive editor. ``We made a portable
darkroom and were drying negatives with my 13- and 16-year-old
daughters' blow dryer.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In Henderson County to the east, an elderly woman was killed in
her home and her husband was seriously injured, said Pam Tolley,
director of emergency 911 communications for the county. ``We were
very fortunate that most of the damage was to power lines and
structures and not people,'' she said.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Joe Wells of the Tennessee National Guard said two helicopters
were destroyed and three others were seriously damaged at the
National Guard hangar at the Jackson airport. ``The odd part was,
the civilian airport across the street was not damaged at all,''
said Wells. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A propane tank and a second fire station were also damaged in
Jackson. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore is scheduled to tour the area Tuesday.
Jackson is his mother's hometown and some of his relatives live
there.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
