<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 20:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8154 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-BRUINS-PREDATORS-     01-18 0802
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-PREDATORS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS EXPLODE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
Bruins8, Predators1 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ By late in the second period, it turned into a mental
health day, a rare opportunity for the Bruins to ease back a few
inches on their bench, relax, take account of the embarrassment of
their riches. One day Internet terminals undoubtedly will be part
of every NHL bench. This would have been one to log on, look for
favorite places, maybe forward a recipe to Aunt Gert.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't get much easier than the Bruins' 8-1 thumping of the
expansion Nashville Predators Monday before a crowd of 15,586 at
the Fleet Center. Never before had they scored so many goals inside
the FleetCenter. Steve Heinze led the way with a couple (Nos. 12,
13), part of a balanced dismantling that acted as a
batting-practice tuneup to the visit here Thursday by the red-hot
Ottawa Senators.
</P>
<P>
   ``We kept things simple, we tried not to be fancy,'' said coach
Pat Burns, his club recovering well from a sloppy, often
inattentive 2-2 tie with the Lightning Saturday. ``I just hope we
kept enough goals for Thursday.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond Heinze's pair, the victory was encouraging on a few other
vital fronts:
</P>
<P>
   --Burns paired two rookie blue liners, Brandon Smith and Terry
Virtue, and wasn't afraid to roll them out, especially as the
winning margin approached a touchdown. They each played 16 minutes
34 seconds and finished plus-3. This was a sharp contrast to
Saturday night when Burns rolled out only four defensemen and kept
Virtue stapled to the bench as a black-and-gold accidental tourist.
</P>
<P>
   --The emergence of (drum roll, please) a No. 2 line. Jumbo Joe
Thornton played the pivot between Peter Ferraro and Heinze, and the
trio collected three goals and three assists. If the Bruins hope to
play beyond April 18 _ and no one is guaranteeing postseason
berths, especially with Pavel Bure now in Florida _ they have to
get some offensive action from something other than the Jason
Allison-Sergei Samsonov-Dmitri Khristich combination.
</P>
<P>
   --Rookie forward Andre Savage, showing a brushstroke of bona
fide big-league scoring touch, carried out from behind the right
post and zipped a forehander under the crossbar, reminiscent of a
John Bucyk roof job. It was Savage's first NHL goal. He has the
kind of knack with the puck that makes him a candidate for duty on
a No. 2 line. Four guys, three jobs: meet the new math.
</P>
<P>
   As for the struggling Predators (15-24-4 in their inaugural
season), their list of goods and bads was weighted heavily on one
side.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't deserve to be in the game _ and we weren't,'' said
coach Barry Trotz, his Predators devoured in a lopsided 37-17 shot
advantage rolled up by the Bruins. ``The score was every bit 8-1.
(The Bruins) won all the battles, because they wanted to win all
the battles.''
</P>
<P>
   The Predators this season typically have surrendered only 3-4
goals per game. With No. 1 goalie Mike Dunham sidelined with a
groin pull, their net these days is entrusted to the likes of Tomas
Vokoun and Chris Mason, a combination that doesn't measure up well
against Dunham, the longtime backup to Martin Brodeur in New
Jersey. Vokoun was yanked when the score hit 5-1 at the start of
the second _ a P.J. Axelsson one-time slapper _ and then Mason
allowed three more goals on 14 shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``We needed this to give everyone a boost, confidence-wise,''
said the Bruins' Rob DiMaio, who set up Axelsson's slapper with a
pretty dish out of the left corner. ``And it came at the right
time, with a big game coming against Ottawa.''
</P>
<P>
   In and of itself, a lopsided win over the Predators doesn't act
as an accurate guage of where the Bruins stand. Ottawa will be a
better read. The Senators are fast and talented and they're gaining
strength as their lead center, Alexei Yashin, gets older, wiser,
and a little tougher.
</P>
<P>
   What's clear halfway through the 1998-99 season, however, is
that every point in the bank will be extremely important. The
Panthers picked up Bure in a big swap with the Canucks Sunday
night, which means an also-ran in the Eastern Conference suddenly
becomes a playoff contender. The Bruins right now look like one of
a half-dozen teams that will spend the next three months battling
it out for the Nos. 7 and 8 playoff spots. It's not late in the
year, but already the squeeze is in force.
</P>
<P>
   ``Points are precious, we have to realize that,'' said veteran
defenseman Don Sweeney. ``We were idle for about 4-5 days and we
lost ground in the standings. It makes you realize, when your games
are up, you have to win.''
</P>
<P>
   When Predators come bearing gifts, accept them graciously.
</P>
<P>
   ``From our standpoint,'' uttered Trotz, ``the best thing is that
the final buzzer went.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
