<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 20:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8156 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-LOBBY-NYT     01-18 1045
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-LOBBY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRO- AND ANTI-CLINTON LOBBYING BECOMES LESS INTENSE DURING TRIAL
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Del., Maine, Pa., R.I., Vt., N.Y., Pa., R.I.)  (See also IMPEACH-RDP, IMPEACH-REPUBS, IMPEACH-SANTORUM) 
(bl) 
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ People for the American Way has organized
anti-impeachment forums in 21 cities for Tuesday evening, just
before President Clinton delivers his State of the Union speech.
The Christian Coalition's Web site is up and hyperlinking, allowing
its constituents to sign even more electronic petitions demanding
Clinton's ouster.
</P>
<P>
   In short, the letters, phone calls and e-mails are flowing again
here, this time directed at the senators who will vote on Clinton's
fate.
</P>
<P>
   But as the Senate prepares for the second week of the
impeachment trial, there is growing evidence that the lobbying
storm that swept switchboards, e-mail servers and post office boxes
during December's House debate is not as intense this time. Some
Senate aides say they have been surprised by what they describe as
a relatively manageable influx of calls and letters, and a number
of the grass-roots organizers even suggest that there is a
going-trough-the-motions element in this second round of the
proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are trying to keep our members inspired to pursue the
fight,'' said Kim Gandy, executive vice president of the National
Organization for Women, which supports the president. ``Some of
them are war-weary from keeping it up so long. But they understand
that we have to keep doing the same thing: We have to keep making
those phone calls.''
</P>
<P>
   The change in tenor here is in effect an acknowledgment that the
dynamics of the Senate proceedings are different from those that
prevailed in the House. Among people following the trial, there is
a growing consensus that the senators are simply not so susceptible
to grass-roots lobbying as House members were in December. In fact,
said Stephen Hess, a senior fellow at the Brookings Institution,
any such lobbying is ``having absolutely no influence.''
</P>
<P>
   There are a number of explanations for this. One is that by now,
the opinions of most senators, on a subject that has been fairly
well aired, may be all but fixed.
</P>
<P>
   ``These senators have fairly hard feelings about what they want
to do,'' said Charles E. Cook Jr., the author of a political report
that tracks congressional races across the country. ``And anything
that would change their mind is something that they heard inside
the chamber, not outside.''
</P>
<P>
   Further, the very nature of the Senate proceedings _ a formal
trial, as opposed to the raucous political debate in the House _
tends to discourage the mass lobbying that has frequently made a
difference in legislative battles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this has far less effect in the trial setting than it
did in the House, where it was a more politically charged event,''
said Tony Bullock, chief of staff to Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan,
D-N.Y. ``The feeling is that this is essentially a trial setting
and the senators are not going to be, and ought not be, swayed by
external input. The decisions should be made on the presentations
that were made and the evidence that was presented.''
</P>
<P>
   What is more, aides to senators who are most likely to be a
target of any lobbying say the lawmakers disregard communication
that comes from outside their home state, especially if there is
any hint that it results from an organized effort.
</P>
<P>
   In one sign of the changed dynamic, the Conservative Caucus,
which has been a leading organization in the drive to oust Clinton,
is focusing not on large numbers of individual senators but on
Majority Leader Trent Lott. The group is calling 500 of its members
a night, urging them to demand of Lott that he resist any
Democratic proposal against calling witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Lott ``is the No. 1 target,'' said Howard Phillips, chairman of
the Conservative Caucus, who explained that by now, any lobbying
was not so much on the question of whether the president should be
convicted _ ``it's hard to change minds on that at this point'' _
as on what procedures to follow.
</P>
<P>
   Another anti-Clinton group, the Christian Coalition, has used
its Web site and phone banks to gather signatures demanding the
president's resignation. The group's executive director, Randy
Tate, said it now had about 300,000 names _ so many, he maintained,
that it has had to clear out furniture from an office to store the
printouts.
</P>
<P>
   The National Organization for Women, meanwhile, has sent e-mail
alerts asking members to demand that Clinton be acquitted. And
People for the American Way is preparing radio advertisements for
broadcast, beginning Wednesday, in states with senators whom the
organization considers less than decided: Delaware, Maine,
Pennsylvania, Rhode Island and Vermont.
</P>
<P>
   On Capitol Hill, some have noticed an increase in activity.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've gotten tons of e-mails: over one weekend 2,200 e-mails,
which was astounding,'' said Nicholas Gramm, a spokesman for Sen.
John Chafee, R-R.I. ``We're Little Rhodey, and we're not California
or Texas. That was a volume that we have never anticipated before,
or ever.''
</P>
<P>
   But aides in the offices of many other senators said they had
seen little or no change in the volume of ``contacts'' _ postal
mail, e-mail and phone calls.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's none,'' said Robert Traynham, a spokesman for Sen.
Rick Santorum, R-Pa. ``There's been no organized lobbying that we
know of to the senator's office on impeachment. I'm speechless.''
</P>
<P>
   In any event, interest organizations say they plan to push
ahead, if only to counteract what the other side is doing. ``Does
it have an impact?'' said Carole Shields, president of People for
the American Way. ``Absolutely.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Shields said that when the House voted impeachment, she
heard ``several congressman who were undecided just before the vote
stating how many e-mail messages they had received.''
</P>
<P>
   But Tate, of the Christian Coalition, gave a more cautious
reading on the effectiveness of the lobbying effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of the things they will consider,'' he said of the
senators. ``It's important to hear from constituents. But at the
end of the day, this is going to be decided on the facts.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
