</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMA-EDITOR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITOR'S FIRING MORE TROUBLE FOR THE AMA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY TYE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The American Medical Association is under siege again after a
yearlong struggle to build back its membership base, regain its
political clout and, most of all, to extricate itself from scandal
and from the headlines.
</P>
<P>
   Late last week, the retired Air Force general the nation's
largest doctors' group had hired to help restore its fraying
prestige generated unwelcome headlines when he fired the AMA's
top-ranking editor for publishing an article that touched on
presidential sex and impeachment politics. The episode has left AMA
watchers wondering whether Dr. E. Ratcliffe Anderson Jr. is up to
running the association _ and whether the AMA can regain the
prestige and power it enjoyed for most of its 152 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, I think the organization is in an amazing
tailspin,'' said Dr. Raymond Scalettar of Washington, D.C., who
chaired the AMA board in 1992-93 and has led unsuccessful reform
bids. ``Our aviator has literally flown the plane into the
mountain. It's a huge embarrassment.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Tom Delbanco, a Harvard Medical School professor who edits a
monthly column in the Journal of the American Medical Association,
was equally distressed: ``The AMA is going to be viewed as simply a
lobby group for a bunch of angry doctors, and that's not going to
help anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   But AMA President Dr. Nancy Dickey said in an interview Monday
that Anderson, who as executive vice president has day-to-day
authority over the organization, ``is committed to assuring that we
maintain the excellence of the things the AMA does well and that we
address effectively the areas in which we have concerns. I remain
supportive of him.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Anderson's firing of Dr. George D. Lundberg, the JAMA
editor, Dickey said ``anytime a key employee has lost the faith of
the chief executive in terms of his or her ability to function
within an organization, changes have to be made.''
</P>
<P>
   The anxiety over Friday's firing was heightened by memories of
the troubles that have plagued the AMA in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   First there was the deal, unveiled two years ago, in which the
AMA would have received millions of dollars for endorsing
humidifiers, blood-pressure monitors and other products made by
Sunbeam Corp. The deal was dropped after AMA members questioned the
ethics of the arrangement, but the brouhaha forced the resignation
of the then-executive vice president back. Sunbeam sued and won a
settlement of nearly $10 million, and a recent independent report
accused AMA trustees of failing to properly police the situation.
</P>
<P>
   Even more troubling for the organization has been the continuing
decline in the percentage of US doctors who belong to the AMA _
from more than 90 percent in the 1950s, to barely 50 percent in
1975, to less than 40 percent today. ``The AMA had tremendous
leverage over the profession as a whole, but all that has broken
down'' and robbed the association of much of its legendary clout,
said Paul Starr, a sociology professor at Princeton University and
historian of modern medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the firing of Lundberg, who over the last 17 years
built JAMA into one of the world's most esteemed medical
publications. The immediate complaint against him was the
publication in the current JAMA the results of a 1990 survey study
in which a substantial majority of college students agreed with
President Clinton's controversial contention that oral-genital
contact does not constitute ``having sex.'' Running the article as
Clinton's Senate impeachment trial is getting underway, Anderson
said, amounts to ``inappropriately and inexcusably interjecting
JAMA into a major political debate.''
</P>
<P>
   The AMA chief had had other differences with Lundberg,
reportedly including JAMA's special issue on alternative medicine
last year and Lundberg's advocacy on CBS' ``60 Minutes'' TV show of
the renewed use of autopsies to check on hospital performance.
Anderson declined to publicly discuss his grievances, and Dickey
would say only that Anderson had given Lundberg ``due process and
fair warning.''
</P>
<P>
   Others question the fairness of the firing and said Anderson has
a history of getting rid of subordinates who question his
authority.
</P>
<P>
   That is apparently what happened at the Truman Health Center in
Kansas City, a 500-bed hospital network where Anderson was CEO
before he was hired by the AMA seven months ago. He fired the
chairmen of the departments of radiology, pathology and medicine
after they signed a letter asking that he be replaced as dean at
the University of Missouri-Kansas City Medical School. In the
aftermath, Anderson was replaced as dean and the three chairmen
sued to hold onto their positions at the hospital, which is
affiliated with the medical school.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the most transparent case of retaliation I've ever been
involved with in 22 years of practicing law,'' says Michael
Manners, president of the Missouri Association of Trial Attorneys
and a lawyer for one of the department heads, whose case is due to
be decided in a Missouri court next month. ``There's certainly a
deja vu there'' with the Lundberg firing.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson, who served as Surgeon General of the Air Force, was
not available for comment Monday on the Kansas City events. Dickey
said ``we had studied carefully the situation in Kansas City before
the decision was made to hire Dr. Anderson. No, I didn't think it
was indicative of some administrative flaw.''
</P>
<P>
   Some doctors worried Monday how Lundberg's departure would
impact JAMA and its affiliated journals, which are the one part of
the AMA empire that has thrived when the rest of the organization
was problem-plagued.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me this clearly shows that political concerns of the
association are premiere and override editorial and scientific
independence,'' said Dr. Kenneth Arndt, chief of dermatology at
Beth Israel Deaconess Medical Center and editor of the Archives of
Dermatology, an AMA publication.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Stephen Webster, an AMA delegate from Wisconsin, said he
agrees with Anderson that the sex survey ``should not have come out
at this particular time in JAMA. Although whether this is a high
crime and misdemeanor for an editor to get fired over I don't
know.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
