</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-TV-SUPERBOWL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUPER BOWL SUNDAY BEGINS EARLY ON FOX SPORTS
</HEADLINE>
   (ms) 
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The National Football League conference championships on Sunday
concluded the normal part of your viewing season. The
Atlanta-Minnesota game began with Fox's hourlong pre-game show and
CBS's Jets-Denver game with a 30-minute show.
</P>
<P>
   The Super Bowl, the next NFL game you see, will last half as
long as the excess that precedes it: seven hours before the game by
Fox Sports, the most since Fox perpetrated five hours at the Super
Bowl in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Fox justifies starting Super Sunday at 11 a.m., Eastern time,
simply: money.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they can sell it, I'll produce it,'' said Ed Goren,
co-executive producer of Fox Sports, which is what he said two
years ago regarding pre-game activities that began at 1 p.m. ``What
are we pre-empting, infomercials?''
</P>
<P>
   Sales are at the heart of the network's Super Bowl programming
strategy. Fox expects to gross $180 million from advertising sold
for the pre-game show, the game and the post-game show on the Fox
network and on the 22 stations it owns. Early in the day,
advertisers are paying $60,000 per 30-second spot; during the game,
they will pay $1.6 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more Fox makes on Super Bowl Sunday, the happier we'll be
since we have it in two years,'' said Sean McManus, the president
of CBS Sports.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Solomon, the president of national broadcast for SFM
Media, a media buyer, said advertisers buying spots in the seven
hours of pre-game programming can buy the reflected glory of the
Super Bowl, even if they are not buying time during the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``The value of the promotion they get is almost as big as being
in the game,'' Solomon said. ``You can promote to retailers the
impression that you're in the game, even if you're really not, and
you may have only spent $60,000.''
</P>
<P>
   How will Fox fill its seven pre-game hours? From 11 to 11:30
a.m., Eastern, Terry Bradshaw, Cris Collinsworth, Howie Long and
others will discuss their Super Bowl experiences, followed by
``Hardcore Football'' through noon. Keith Olbermann will be the
host from noon to 12:30 p.m. of a behind-the-scenes look at Fox's
Super Bowl logistics and the planning for the halftime show,
followed by John Madden's 90-minute All-Millennium Team, a
1,000-year tribute to mud and mucus. From 2 to 6 p.m., Eastern,
Fox's usual hourlong pre-game show will be stretched to four hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Super Bowl started as a game, then it became a day, now
it's a week,'' Goren said. ``The appetite for programming continues
to grow. And already, for the 2 o'clock show, we're 15 minutes over
in our planning.''
</P>
<P>
   Olbermann's half-hour show is his first contribution to the Fox
broadcast network since he signed to be the principal anchorman of
Fox Sports News on cable. If anyone knows excess, it is Olbermann,
who fled the MSNBC all-Monica network. ``If you're talking about
seven hours once a year on one topic, as a party mix to America's
gathering, it's not disproportionate,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Although the league would probably like its pre-Super Bowl
programming to start the week before the game, it isn't pushing the
networks to match Fox's long day's journey into Miami. ``It's up to
each individual network,'' said Dennis Lewin, the NFL's senior vice
president of broadcasting.
</P>
<P>
   Not every network can clear out as much time as Fox will. For
example, when NBC did not carry the Super Bowl, it countered with
National Basketball Association games, which the post-lockout
season will preclude it from doing.
</P>
<P>
   McManus will be watching the results of Fox's excess, as will
ABC, the network of the 2000 game. ``If our people can generate
substantial advertising, we'll produce as many hours as they can
sell efficiently,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   McManus would not comment on a report last week in The Hollywood
Reporter, a trade publication, that CBS had nearly broken even on
the $500 million-a-year average cost of its NFL rights agreement.
Observers thought CBS was crazy for more than doubling NBC's
average $216 million annual payment for the American Football
Conference package. But the publication said the CBS network sold
$360 million in advertising, the 14 stations it owns and operates
generated sales of $80 million, affiliates paid $40 million to help
foot the NFL bill and $5 million came from DirecTV satellite
subscriber fees.
</P>
<P>
   NOT SO JETS CRAZY
</P>
<P>
   The Jets-Denver AFC championship game produced a 27.3
preliminary overnight Nielsen rating on Sunday, down a smidgen from
the 27.7 for the NFC title game last year in the same 4 p.m.,
Eastern, time slot. The Minnesota-Atlanta game generated a 26.2
rating, up from a 26.1 for last year's AFC title game.
</P>
<P>
   The New York market generated a 30.0 rating and a 52 share for
the Jets game, meaning that more than half of the local households
watching television were tuned to the Jets-Denver game. That's a
dandy rating, but not as stupendous as those in the other markets
watching the two title games. The New York rating fell below Denver
(54.4), Atlanta (50.6) and Minneapolis-St. Paul (47.7); in
addition, more than 80 percent of the televisions in use in Denver
and Minneapolis were tuned to the games compared with 52 percent in
the New York market.
</P>
<P>
   But the size of the New York market meant more households _
about 2 million _ watched, compared with Denver's 652,000,
Atlanta's 847,400 and 690,700 in Minneapolis.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-18-99 2039EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990118.0363 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 20:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8164 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-NFL-RUNNING-NYT &LR;      01-18 0912
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFL-RUNNING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: BOTH SUPER BOWL TEAMS UNDERSTAND THE RUNNING GAME
</HEADLINE>
   (ms) 
 By THOMAS GEORGE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ Does successful passing create productive running? Or
is it the other way around?
</P>
<P>
   The entrants in Super Bowl XXXIII on Jan. 31 in Miami cast a
vote for the latter. For the Atlanta Falcons and the Denver
Broncos, productive running creates successful passing.
</P>
<P>
   Both teams run the ball with vigor. Linemen and linebackers step
forward to stop them. Pass defenders begin to cheat toward the line
of scrimmage to support in run defense. Soon, all 11 defenders have
become immersed in stopping the run. Pow! Both teams then clobber
you with the pass.
</P>
<P>
   Elementary. Basic. Old-school football with big-time runners in
Jamal Anderson for Atlanta and Terrell Davis for Denver. Offenses
with fancy formations, big-play receivers, high-powered
quarterbacks, but all of it founded on the basis of run production.
</P>
<P>
   This Super Bowl will not feature a pure West Coast offense in
which the focus is the passing game and short passes are the
equivalent of runs. The run-and-shoot passing offense, an offense
in which run is a dirty word, will not be the order. For Atlanta
and Denver, it is all about balance, a penchant for physical
football first.
</P>
<P>
   Two 16-2 teams in Super Bowl XXXIII. Two teams with versatile
offensive lines that have staying power and tremendous will. Teams
that fell behind and kept pounding away on the ground to set up big
passing plays in their conference championship games.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta beat Minnesota on Sunday in part by outrushing the
Vikings by 110 yards to 102. The Broncos were even more decisive
against the Jets _ 178 rushing yards to only 14 by the Jets, and 38
carries compared with the Jets' 13.
</P>
<P>
   When Dan Reeves, the Falcons' head coach, came to Atlanta before
the 1997 season, the Falcons had employed the run-and-shoot as
their base offense. Small, Smurf-like receivers, four and five of
them in spread formations, with quarterbacks making half-rolls and
quick throws, passes, passes, passes and more passes. Reeves
chucked that. He wanted balance. Physical play. His style: run the
ball and stop the run, and throw play-action passes off the run. He
made the Falcons stronger in the weight room and mentally tougher,
more prone to dispense poundings than to absorb them.
</P>
<P>
   ``People think this game is so technical, but it's not,'' Reeves
said. ``Run the ball, stop the run and get turnovers. Every
football team that I've been around that's been any good does that.
Now, you can do some things as an offshoot from that, but, really,
that's what the game is all about.''
</P>
<P>
   It is what the Falcons are all about. Denver, too.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson weighs 234 pounds. Two hundred of that sometimes seems
to be in his legs. They keep churning, and his robust and powerful
thighs make him hard to tackle. Yet he is light, nimble on his
feet. Fast enough. In football jargon, he is a beast.
</P>
<P>
   Davis rushed for 2,000-plus yards this season. He weighs 210
pounds. Uncanny. Strong. Great vision. Great burst. Tremendous
confidence.
</P>
<P>
   Both backs go nowhere, however, without skilled offensive
linemen.
</P>
<P>
   These are the two best offensive lines in football. Usually in
the Super Bowl, that is where you find the best of everything, but
especially offensive linemen. If the run creates the pass and
gifted running backs shine like silver, then offensive linemen are
the pure gold.
</P>
<P>
   Both lines are coached by dynamic teachers: for the Falcons, it
is Art Shell, for the Broncos it is Alex Gibbs.
</P>
<P>
   Their pupils set the tempo. It was Denver's desire to use its
offensive linemen to break the will of the Jets' defense, to pound
the Jets over the course of four quarters with the run until they
broke. And the Broncos did that, both in the running game and then
in play action off it.
</P>
<P>
   Both the Falcons and the Broncos employ offensive linemen who
understand that their best work is done as a unit. The tight end
helps the left tackle. The left tackle helps the left guard. The
left guard helps the center. He helps the right guard. The right
guard helps the right tackle. And in a two-tight-end scheme, he
helps the other tight end. Down the line, they play off each other,
aid each other, double-team, triple-team, pull, spin and work like
a tapestry.
</P>
<P>
   Both the Falcons and the Broncos use a toss-pitch play where
both give the illusion of a sweep, but the idea all along is for
the running back to cut back inside in the equivalent of an
off-tackle play. Defenses (the Jets did it on Davis' 31-yard
touchdown run) overpursue. The offensive linemen seal them, pin
them toward the sideline, opening a lane. Watch the way the
Broncos' offensive linemen, in particular, block it. They get you
going, roaming one way, and then use your momentum to help block
you, sway you away from the play. An extra nudge, push and shove,
and you are out of the play, partly by your own doing. Zone
blocking at its best. Efficient. Masterful.
</P>
<P>
   That is the offensive lines of both Atlanta and Denver.
</P>
<P>
   Their presence alone makes for quite a Super Bowl, a test of
teams that understand the running game _ the knowledge, importance
and ability of running the football and defending the run _ and how
that parlays into the passing game and beyond. It will make for
quite a show in the Biggest Show, where the real fireworks, for a
change, will be well grounded. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
