A8165 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDITORIAL-FRANCE-BOS &LR;      01-18 0363
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-FRANCE-BOS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a response to a faulty French plan to placate Saddam Hussein,
the Clinton administration has proposed lifting the ceiling on
Iraqi oil sales under the United Nations' oil-for-food program.
</P>
<P>
   The sole virtue of Washington's proposal is that it would not
permit Saddam to retain his weapons of mass destruction and rebuild
his conventional military capabilities, as the Paris proposal would
have done.
</P>
<P>
   The French are willing to scuttle the UN Special Commission,
which the Security Council created after Desert Storm to discover
and dismantle Saddam's biological, chemical, and nuclear weapons
and the missiles to deliver them. Instead, France would end the UN
embargo on Iraqi oil sales, abandon the search for Saddam's hidden
stocks of germs and poison gas, and establish a ban against arms
sales to Iraq in order to prevent Saddam from reviving his depleted
military forces.
</P>
<P>
   This plan would achieve for Saddam one of his two basic aims and
enhance his progress toward the other: It would lift the UN embargo
and allow him to retain his weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
   Washington's answer to this display of French frivolity is
little more than a stopgap suggestion that prolongs a policy of
muddling through.
</P>
<P>
   Since the equipment for Iraq's oil industry remains woefully
decrepit, Iraq is not able to pump even the limited amount of oil
permitted under the current ceiling of the UN oil-for-food program.
Couple this with oil prices that have plunged to $9 per barrel, and
the administration's gesture, meant to show compassion for Iraq's
people, looks like an empty exercise in public relations.
</P>
<P>
   This unproductive standoff between Paris and Washingon comes at
a time when Saddam has resumed his threats against other Arab
governments and they have responded by blaming him for the
cruelties imposed on the Iraqi people and calling for his
overthrow.
</P>
<P>
   The immediate goal of Iraq policy must be to resume inspections
of Saddam's weapons of mass destruction. For the long term, there
is no alternative to the overthrow of Saddam's regime.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
