<HEADER>
A8167 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDITORIAL-KAZAN-BOS &LR;      01-18 0364
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-KAZAN-BOS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Congratulations are due the Academy of Motion Pictures Arts and
Sciences for offering an honorary Academy Award to Elia Kazan, one
of the great film directors of the 1950s. Kazan, now 89 and ailing,
has been denied similar honors because he identified several
friends as members of the Communist Party.
</P>
<P>
   Kazan and a number of colleagues from New York theater were
party members themselves in the 1930s, when the Great Depression
caused many people to question the future of American capitalism.
By the early 1950s, the US economy was soaring, communism was
discredited, and Kazan and his friends were busy making movies.
Kazan produced his greatest works while Hollywood was embroiled in
the Red scare. The House Un-American Activities Committee, where he
testified, used hearings to advance its political agenda but did
nothing to advance national security.
</P>
<P>
   Kazan, at the height of his artistry, was the committee's great
catch. In fact, like many of his friends, he was no hard-line Red,
having left the party after an 18-month flirtation. He was largely
apolitical thereafter, though as his career progressed he developed
great faith in the free enterprise system. His testimony was a
combination of political conservatism and career preservation.
</P>
<P>
   It would make the stuff of a great movie, and perhaps it already
is. Two years after his testimony Kazan directed ``On the
Waterfront,'' which starred Marlon Brando as the two-bit fighter
and longshoremen's enforcer who turns informer to clean up the
union local.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the Waterfront'' endures as a masterpiece, as do ``Viva
Zapata,'' ``A Streetcar Named Desire,'' ``East of Eden,'' and the
autobiographical ``America, America.'' Yet two years ago the Los
Angeles Film Critics Association and the American Film Institute
refused to give him the honors routinely bestowed on other masters
of the craft.
</P>
<P>
   The unanimous vote by an academy committee to give him the Oscar
suggests that old animosities are fading. Kazan's achievements
transcend the vagaries of politics or the frailties of character.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
