<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 20:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8168 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDITORIAL-AFRICANA-BO     01-18 0363
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-AFRICANA-BOS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In 1909, W.E.B. Du Bois had a dream. He wanted to publish an
Encyclopedia Africana: a vast collection of Africa's land and
people written only by Africans that would sweep away flawed and
negative accounts of the continent. It was the wish of a scholar, a
man who had graduated from Fisk University and Harvard. And it
showed a deep faith that knowledge could lead to progress.
</P>
<P>
   Du Bois shook up the foundation of America arguing for and
writing copiously about civil rights. As an older man he moved to
Ghana, where Kwame Nkrumah, president of the Republic of Ghana,
asked Du Bois to supervise the production of an Encyclopedia
Africana. In 1961 the Secretariat of the Encyclopedia Africana in
Accra, Ghana, was established. Du Bois died two years later in
Ghana at the age of 95.
</P>
<P>
   Now two of his successors _ Harvard professors Henry Louis Gates
and Kwame Anthony Appiah _ have finished the encyclopedia. The
newly released Encarta Africana _ produced by Gates's Afropaedia
LLC and Microsoft _ is a CD-ROM version of Du Bois's
turn-of-the-century vision.
</P>
<P>
   The content is sprawling, featuring music, maps, video, history,
politics, and a 4-million-year time line. Lost voices _ Billie
Holiday, James Baldwin _ speak again. There are more than 3,300
articles, virtual tours, and filmed commentary that includes Whoopi
Goldberg and Kofi Annan.
</P>
<P>
   Will this knowledge move people forward? From education to the
news media, coverage of Africa is often sketchy: Events often end
up in news briefs or nowhere at all. History gets boiled down to
pyramids and European colonization.
</P>
<P>
   Encarta Africana's educational component should help. Teachers
have been asked to contribute lesson plans, some of which will be
published on Encarta's Schoolhouse Web page
(www.encarta.msn.com/schoolhouse/). For users with Internet access,
500 integrated Web links will facilitate on-line research. And if
it is used by children, the CD-ROM may help build a more educated
generation.
</P>
<P>
   The test of Encarta Africana will be how well it opens minds and
changes them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
