<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FALCONS' JOY OF WINNING IS SHOCK FOR VIKINGS AND THEIR FANS
</HEADLINE>
   (ms) 
 By MIKE FREEMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ Atlanta Coach Dan Reeves was all smiles Monday
morning while chatting it up on ``Good Morning America.'' He made a
few jokes about his quadruple-bypass surgery, talked about the joy
of returning to the Super Bowl and politely sidestepped questions
about his stormy relationship with Denver quarterback John Elway.
It was a great morning because it followed a great afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Then there were the Minnesota Vikings. After losing to the
Falcons in overtime, 30-27, in Sunday's National Football
Conference title game, a sense of dread filled the Minnesota locker
room and the entire city. On the front page of local newspapers
were photographs of crying fans. Many fans were trying to get
refunds from the airlines after they had booked flights to Miami
for Super Bowl XXXIII. The organization is in a state of shock.
</P>
<P>
   As for the Vikings players, they spent the day meeting with
coaches for the final time and cleaning out their lockers _
something they had not planned to do until after the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons' improbable victory was engineered by quarterback
Chris Chandler, who took the Falcons on a brilliant 10-play,
70-yard drive in overtime that ended with Morten Andersen's 38-yard
field goal. Reeves said the drive proved that Chandler deserved to
be considered among the great quarterbacks, which is interesting,
because the Vikings' focus was on stopping running back Jamal
Anderson _ not Chandler.
</P>
<P>
   Chandler admitted after the game that he was insulted by all the
stop Anderson talk, feeling that the Vikings did not respect him.
</P>
<P>
   The Vikings (16-2) had an outstanding season, setting the
single-season scoring record of 556 points. But many players feel
that the loss to Atlanta took away from some of their
accomplishments.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought it was our year,'' said Vikings cornerback Jimmy
Hitchcock. ``It just didn't turn out that way. It was an
unbelievable experience out there. I just never saw it coming like
this. Never. I just feel empty.''
</P>
<P>
   What Coach Dennis Green must guard against is making sure such a
devastating loss does not have a lasting impact on his team. The
Cleveland Browns never seemed to recover from those killer John
Elway drives in the 1980's. If Vikings players, several months from
now, see Chandler in their dreams, that could be a problem.
</P>
<P>
   The only people who will see Chandler in their dreams are the
coaching staff and players from the Broncos, who will study the
Falcons' offense every day for the next two weeks. What the
Minnesota game demonstrated is that the Falcons can win even if
Anderson has a subpar game. He had 67 yards on 23 carries, and
still the Falcons scored 30 points.
</P>
<P>
   That was because of the great efforts of Chandler, who was 12
for 17 on first-down plays, passing for 151 of his 340 yards and
one of his three touchdown passes.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves, who went with a pass-first game plan, put everything in
Chandler's hands and the quarterback didn't let him down.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kind of took some things personal when the Vikings mentioned
that all they had to do was stop the run,'' said Chandler, an
11-year veteran. ``I wanted to show that we had a passing game,
too, and you can't just figure you're going to stop Jamal and beat
us. I had a little more motivation going into this game.''
</P>
<P>
   What the Broncos also must account for is something less
tangible than Chandler's talent. It is the will of the Falcons, a
tough, stubborn team, modeled after their tough, stubborn coach.
How the Falcons kept battling back from three deficits of 10 or
more points at the hostile Metrodome was one of the most impressive
feats this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't have a big enough lead to put us on the ropes,''
Atlanta defensive end Chuck Smith said. ``We've been down a lot of
times, but have they had a team come in here and fight back on
them? Every time other teams got in these situations, they folded.
We've had San Francisco come back on us, we've been down 14 to
Indianapolis, we were down to St. Louis. We just don't panic.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the sportswriters and people on TV were writing stories
like Minnesota was like Dallas or a San Francisco, like they had
already won four Super Bowls, like these guys can't be beat.
Please. That's what they said about Green Bay.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Smith, who was referring to Denver's upset of the Packers in
last year's Super Bowl, added, ``There's no team in this league
that can go out and win on name alone.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith then summed up perfectly the season of the Falcons: ``What
we've done sends shock waves through the league. A couple of years
ago, if you told me this would happen this quick, I'd have said,
`No, not in two years.'''
</P>
<P>
   And no one would have imagined these improbable scenes: Reeves,
only a matter of weeks removed from open heart surgery, accepting
the conference title trophy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
