<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 20:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8180 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDITORIAL-OLYMPICS-BO     01-18 0354
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-OLYMPICS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IOC PRESIDENT SHOULD RESIGN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There could hardly be a more flagrant contradiction than that
between the spirit of amateur sportsmanship represented by the
Olympic Games and the bribing of International Olympic Committee
officials.
</P>
<P>
   The corrupt practices of committee members who vote on the
selection of sites for the Summer and Winter Games have long been
known to everyone involved. This widespread knowledge of the need
to bribe IOC site selectors became part of their scam. Each
would-be host city knew it had little choice but to outbid other
competing cities by lavishing more and better gifts on the visiting
dignitaries from the IOC.
</P>
<P>
   Within such a corrupt structure, it is important to distinguish
the corrupters from their marks. The IOC bribe-takers did the
shaking down; the bid committees of the cities competing to become
host sites were the parties shaken down.
</P>
<P>
   This Olympic extortion system broke into the news when the Salt
Lake organizing committee disclosed how it bribed IOC officials to
secure its selection as the site for the 2002 Winter Games. It is
understandable that Quebec City, one of three other contending
sites for the 2002 Games, has sought compensation for the losers in
that rigged competition.
</P>
<P>
   The former president of the Quebec 2002 organizing committee,
Rene Paquet, went further and called for the resignation of the
president of the IOC, Juan Antonio Samaranch. ``When you are the
leader of an organization, you have to bear responsibility for what
happens,'' Pacquet said in a simple but compelling indictment of
Samaranch.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of resigning, Samaranch has indicated that the only
people forced to resign will be the two top officials of the Salt
Lake organizing committee and a few of the IOC members caught
accepting bribes.
</P>
<P>
   By refusing to accept responsibility for systemic corruption
that has flourished for years under his stewardship, Samaranch
forfeits his right to commend the purity of the Olympic spirit. He
should be replaced.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-18-99 2051EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
