<HEADER>
A8182 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONSUMERQ&AMP;A19-COX     01-18 1070
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONSUMERQ&AMP;A19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Consumer Q&AMP;A
 &HT;    By Jane S. Greig
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _
</P>
<P>
   Q: How does one get rid of the strong aromas in a microwave oven
from cooking bacon and similar foods? I have tried cooking
grapefruit and orange peels for a minute or two with partial
success. _H.G.
</P>
<P>
   A: Here are some remedies for eau de Oscar Mayer: 1. Try a
solution of baking soda and water (2 teaspoons to one cup warm
water), rinse and dry. 2. Boil a cup of water containing one-third
cup lemon juice in the microwave for a few minutes. Let cool. Wipe
dry. 3. Wipe the interior with a 50-50 solution of vinegar and
water using a coffee filter. (Abrasives are not good on microwave
walls.)
</P>
<P>
   Keep me posted.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What happens to costumes and props used for large productions
such as Olympic ceremonies and Orange Bowl festivities? _C.W.S.
</P>
<P>
   A: The Salt Lake City Olympic Committee is in the midst of
hiring a production director for these shows. Armed with the
committee-provided budget, the director provides (as in makes,
begs, steals, borrows, rents, whatever) costumes and props.
Retirement for these items can differ with each Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   Many bowl games use the services of Bowl Games of America
(Orange, Sugar, Liberty and Gator). This production company has the
world's largest closet, with everything from pompoms to cannons.
Props belong to BGA, not the bowl committees.
</P>
<P>
   The Orange Bowl began as the Palm Festival when Miami leaders
noticed the crowds enjoying the Rose Bowl in California. Hey _ warm
weather was available in Florida! All that was needed was a
football game on New Year's Day.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Where can I purchase a bag cover for a set of bagpipes? I
have an ugly tartan one and want to replace it with something a bit
more tame, like blue or black. _Susan Thickett
</P>
<P>
   A: You can have any kind of bagpipe cover you want by calling
Celtic Craft at (800) 535-5458 _ solid to tartan. Price? In the $70
range. Q: Does the Americans with Disabilities Act apply to people
who are unable to read the new Southwestern Bell telephone book
without a magnifying glass?
</P>
<P>
   _O.C.D.
</P>
<P>
   A: Your complaint about the type size of the new phone book is
not the first I have received, but it is the most entertaining.
</P>
<P>
   The law applies to public accommodations, not products. Every
book in a bookstore, for example, does not have to be legible to
all customers, but the store has to provide access to its facility.
It is not required to modify all books. Southwestern Bell
spokeswoman Alicia Sankar says the new book saves paper and space.
Really want two or three books? Sankar admits SWB ``visits the
parameters of the book every year.''
</P>
<P>
   Want to be heard? Call (800) ICANTREADTHISTHING ... I mean, call
the SWB consumer relations at (800) 422-0499.
</P>
<P>
   Q: In a book on the Old West, I read about a man named Ben
Thompson _ reputed to be a gunfighter and later a peace officer in
Austin. He acquired a lucrative concession to operate games of
chance upstairs in the Iron Front Saloon. The book also mentions a
banquet held at Simon's Cafe in Austin. Where were these businesses
located? _Mary Dees
</P>
<P>
   A: The Iron Front Saloon and Billiard Hall, 606 Congress Ave.,
was billed as the place to ``get the best of wine, liquors, ales
and beer, Havana and domestic cigars'' in an ad in the 1881-82 city
directory. Simon's Restaurant was at 609 Congress Ave. in the
1883-84 directory. Thanks to the staff at the Austin History Center
for the details.
</P>
<P>
   Q: In studying our cats' front paws, we have discovered an extra
claw and pad that appear to serve no useful purpose. We have seen
TV programs about cats and their development, but none has
addressed this particular characteristic. Can you help us? _Paul G.
Griffith
</P>
<P>
   A: Do you mean the pisiform pad or another claw in addition to
the standard five? Cats have five digital pads on their front paws
_ one per claw. There's also a large pad (plantar pad) in the
center of the paw and a small wrist pad (pisiform pad). According
to the feline encyclopedia ``Cat World,'' by Desmond Morris, a
condition known as polydactylism s a common abnormality in which a
cat has extra toes. Teddy Roosevelt's cat Slippers, for example,
had six toes while some Hemingway cats boasted seven! The largest
concentration of many-toed cats? Boston, where 12 percent of cats
are so digited. Other cities' percentages varied directly with the
number of ex-Bostonians in their ranks. Too many baked beans?
</P>
<P>
   Q: In ``Jingle Bells,'' what is the name of the horse in the
one-horse open sleigh? As I understood it, it was the ``bells on
Bob's tail ringing,'' so the horse is named Bob. I recently
mentioned this to some friends, only to have one bring me a copy of
the lyrics reading ``the bells on bobtail ring.'' Can you confirm
the correct lyrics? _J. Tyree
</P>
<P>
   A: It's ``bells on bobtail ring.'' A bobtail is a shortened
tail, but is hauntingly close to ``Bob's tail.'' You are in good
company. There is a Web site for just this sort of thing _
www.kissthisguy.com _ named for the oft-misquoted Jimi Hendrix
lyrics in ``Purple Haze'': ``'Scuse me while I kiss the sky.'' The
informal name of a lyrical misstep is ``mondegreen'' _ from
mistaking ``laid him on the green'' for ``Lady Mondegreen.'' My
favorite is the CCR ``Bad Moon Rising'' lyric, ``There's a bad moon
on the rise.'' Sounds a lot like ``There's a bathroom on the
right.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do you know the mailing or e-mail address for the
commissioner of the NFL? I have looked under NFL.com and do not see
any e-mail addresses listed.
</P>
<P>
   _Tim Alpern
</P>
<P>
   A: Write to Paul Tagliabue in care of the National Football
League, 280 Park Ave., New York, NY 10017 or ask for the public
relations department at (212) 450-2000. Succeeding Pete Rozelle,
Tagliabue has been at the helm of the NFL since 1989. This New York
University School of Law attorney also served in the office of the
U.S. Secretary of Defense and presently is a member of the board of
directors of the Pro Football Hall of Fame and the National Urban
League. Contact Jane S. Greig at P.O. Box 670, Austin, Texas 78767;
(512) 445-3697; e-mail jgreig(at)statesman.com or fax (512)
445-3968.
</P>
<P>
   For copies of Jane's book, ``Thanks for Asking!'' _ a
compilation of more than 600 favorite questions and answers _ call
(800) 424-6291.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
