<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-CONSERVE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNLOCKING A LAND FUND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For 20 years the Land and Water Conservation Fund has fallen
short of its potential to enhance the country's commitment to the
natural world. Now President Clinton has asked Congress to use the
fund for a $1 billion lands legacy initiative that can protect
millions of pristine acres from the violations of development.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's proposed budget for the next fiscal year includes $900
million from the fund, which draws its revenues from offshore oil
leases that have been accumulating since 1964. The money is split
between large federal acquisitions and local matching grants for
projects as small as a town pond or city playground. In past years
the fund has helped preserve beloved natural areas like the
Appalachian Trail and the Everglades as well as countless
fisheries, wetlands, and wildlife habitats in sensitive areas that
might otherwise fall to the implacable march of surveyors and
bulldozers.
</P>
<P>
   Each year some $900 million in oil leases is deposited in the
fund. But since 1978, Congress has refused to appropriate the full
amount, averaging only about $245 million a year. In 1998, the
Republican chairman of the House Budget Committee, John Kasich, cut
the allocation to zero in an unsuccessful attempt to raid the fund
for other uses.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's announcement elevates the fund from obscurity to a
presidential priority. It is a victory for the dozens of
environmental and open-space organizations that collaborated to
raise its profile.
</P>
<P>
   Now it is up to Congress to support the largest investment in
protecting America's natural treasures since the days of Theodore
Roosevelt, who knew the value of the land.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
