<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 20:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8184 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEWPLAY-WIT19-COX     01-18 1643
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWPLAY-WIT19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Atlantan taking bows in classroom and off-Broadway
 &HT;    By Dan Hulbert
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The author of off-Broadway's most lavishly praised
play these days is an Atlanta kindergarten teacher. And she
wouldn't have it any other way. Margaret Edson objects to the title
of playwright because, she says, all the royalties and show biz
offers in the world won't tempt her away from her beloved classroom
in downtown's Centennial Place School, where she's renowned for
setting her lessons to the tunes of George Gershwin and Cole
Porter.
</P>
<P>
   This is just the beginning of the improbable facts surrounding
Edson and her remarkable ``Wit.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not a play full of childhood and joy.
</P>
<P>
   In the drama at New York's Union Square Theatre, a woman's
battle with ovarian cancer climaxes with a breathtaking vision of
her soul breaking free from her doomed body. The patient _ a proud,
frosty, lonely literature professor _ steps silently from her
hospital bed, sheds her gown and reaches up into a shaft of
unearthly light.
</P>
<P>
   Why, Edson was asked, did she choose to show her 50ish heroine,
finally, nude?
</P>
<P>
   ``What else would you wear to a redemption? It's `Come as you
are!''' responds the playwright _ oops, sorry, teacher _ with a
chuckle. ``This is the first moment in the character's life when
she has truly, fully, revealed herself.''
</P>
<P>
   Edson, 37, who goes everywhere by Maggie, is a thin, 6-foot-tall
woman who today wears a blue cardigan and seems born for such
no-nonsense attire. She can appear as serious, even severe, as a
bird of prey. But now, discussing her unclothed heroine, her face
lights up with a mirth as out-of-nowhere as her play.
</P>
<P>
   ``And it's even more (magical) that at that final moment her
hospital bracelet falls away,'' the laughing Edson adds. ``You
can't get those things off in real life, you know.''
</P>
<P>
   The author of ``Wit'' is one herself. This was evident during a
conversation in a Virginia-Highland coffee oasis not far from her
home. Edson's wit explains why a play that deals with terminal
illness has kept audiences laughing even as they struggle to hold
back tears.
</P>
<P>
   The heroine, professor Vivian Bearing (played by Kathleen
Chalfant), begins the evening by telling the audience
matter-of-factly, ``It is not my intention to give away the plot,
but I believe I die at the end.'' She proceeds to narrate the final
weeks of her life, using hard, polished plates of wit to fend off
the miseries and indignities of cancer treatments, isolation, fear.
Between the arrogance of the doctors (who see her as little more
than a test specimen for research) and the arrogance of Bearing
herself (who apparently has no love life or close family), there is
a silence at the heart of ``Wit'' that screams for a voice of
comfort.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a play about kindness, the human touch,'' Edson says,
``and one way to show that is through its opposite.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, a friend of Edson's half-kiddingly described the play
as ``90 minutes of suffering and death mitigated ... by a pelvic
exam and a lecture on 17th-century poetry.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact it was the lecture, not the nudity, that earned the play
rejection slips from dozens of theaters across the country. It's
but one chapter in a story that could be subtitled, ``How Things
Never Happen in the Theater.''
</P>
<P>
   The unlikeliest journey
</P>
<P>
   Edson, who has lived most of her life in Washington and has a
history degree from Smith College, never intended to write a play
before sitting down to pen ``Wit'' in 1991, when she was 30. She
was working as a bicycle store clerk at the time. Hers was one of
1,000 unsolicited scripts submitted to South Coast Repertory in
Costa Mesa, Calif., south of Los Angeles. Except for a half-hour of
cuts, few rewrites were requested. Edson was barely consulted by
South Coast and yet, she says, ``Every actor performed as if I'd
whispered in his or her ear _ it was completely thrilling.''
</P>
<P>
   But no East Coast producer was interested, and it looked again
as if the play might disappear. Then, in 1995, Derek Anson Jones, a
high school classmate of Edson's who is an aspiring director, took
the script to New York free-lance director Doug Hughes. Together
they lobbied producers; again, no takers. Finally in 1997, when
Hughes was named artistic director of Long Wharf Theatre in New
Haven, Conn., he relaunched its second stage with ``Wit,'' directed
by Jones. The enthusiasm of New York critics paved the way for the
play's triumphant transfer last September to off-Broadway in a
co-production of Long Wharf and Manhattan Theatre Club. It reopened
last week in the larger Union Square Theatre. (Though its regional
production rights may not be released in time for the 1999-2000
season, ``Wit'' would work well in the repertoire of any number of
Atlanta theaters.)
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a work that's deeply felt but utterly unsentimental _
and in that way it reflects Maggie's personality,'' Hughes says.
``Every step of the way, the conventional wisdom was that `the
people,' whoever that is, wouldn't sit still for this play, but
Maggie always proved them wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   The mystery celebrity
</P>
<P>
   Edson was the closest thing to an overnight-sensation playwright
in years, but no one in Gotham theatrical circles had any idea who
she was. They had little chance to find out since she'd moved to
Atlanta to join partner Linda Merrill, who'd taken a new job as a
curator of American art at the High Museum of Art. And since that
arrival was only five months ago, the Atlanta theater community has
not been in touch with _ or perhaps even aware of _ Edson.
</P>
<P>
   Nor do all her fellow Centennial teachers know of her theatrical
celebrity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maggie is so quiet about the play, doesn't make a to-do about
it,'' says Leda Tatum, Centennial's assistant principal. ``I saw
the play over the holidays and thought it was wonderful. But all
you have to do is walk into Maggie's classroom and you know there's
a creative spirit. She puts so many of her lessons into songs!''
</P>
<P>
   In her own words
</P>
<P>
   Q: You obviously know something of the medical realities in the
play.
</P>
<P>
   A: Hospitals fascinate me for much the same reason as airports.
I wonder: Where all these people coming from and where are they
going? My mother was a medical social worker. In 1984 I took it
into my head to work in hospitals, first as a volunteer, then as a
unit clerk. I was struck by the bravery of the patients. One was a
science writer with three children, going through very aggressive
treatment for ovarian cancer. I used to bring her a newspaper every
day. Once we were in the elevator and I tried to tell her, in my
22-year-old way, that I admired her courage, and she said very
calmly, ``I don't have much choice, do I?''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Some great plays _ ``Angels in America'' springs to mind _
and movies deal with terminal illness but then so do a lot of
second-rate ones. Did this concern you?
</P>
<P>
   A: In my pile of rejection slips I see the phrase ``disease of
the month'' a lot. But remember, nobody expected this play. Nobody
was waiting for it. I was working in a bike shop. I wasn't trying
to set up a playwriting career. So I wrote exactly the play I
wanted to write, the way I saw it and even smelled it. I was free
as a bird.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I could tell that many in the Union Square had had
experiences like Bearing's with an insensitive doctor. It seems you
almost go out of your way to portray him as a fool.
</P>
<P>
   A: The most arrogant person in the play is not a doctor (it's
Bearing), so doctors shouldn't be so hurt. Everyone's arrogant:
That's the point. There were letters in The New York Times from
people who were disappointed that the doctors were not portrayed as
heroes, but the play is not about doctors or even about cancer.
It's about kindness.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Having seen Chalfant in her role, it's hard to imagine anyone
else playing it.
</P>
<P>
   A: I know! And she and I have barely spoken! Our conversations
have been somewhat rushed and not even private; we're strangers to
each other, really. In a way I don't want to talk to her now!
(Laughs).
</P>
<P>
   Q: You've written another play, about country gospel music?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes, it's called ``Satisfied,'' it hasn't been produced, and
anybody who liked ``Wit'' would hate it! (Laughs). It's hokey, but
then I'm a hokey person.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How are you liking Atlanta so far?
</P>
<P>
   A: I love it! I like being outside. I'm taking a dance class at
the YWCA.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You object to being called a playwright.
</P>
<P>
   A: I had to sit down and think about my future, and I decided
that I love being a teacher. ... I wrote a song to the tune of
``Anything Goes,'' called ``My Body is Me,'' and the kids picked it
right up. How can you beat that? ... If in 10 years I'm moved to
write another play, fine, and I may be a better writer for the life
experience. But at the end of the day, if your feet are tired _
you're a teacher!
</P>
<P>
   Q: You express that like a writer.
</P>
<P>
   A: You should hear me teach.
</P>
<P>
   THE EDSON FILE
</P>
<P>
   _ Age: 37
</P>
<P>
   _ Background: Born and reared in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   _ Employment history: Worked as hospital clerk, bicycle clerk,
elementary schoolteacher before writing ``Wit'' _ her acclaimed
off-Broadway drama about a professor's battle with ovarian cancer _
at age 30.
</P>
<P>
   _ Local connection: Moved to Atlanta last August to teach
kindergarten at downtown's Centennial Place School.
</P>
<P>
   _ The play's future: A film and/or TV version of ``Wit'' is
being discussed. The play will be published in March by Farrar,
Straus &AMP; Giroux.
</P>
<P>
   _ At the play's opening: ``I think I was most grateful for what
(cast member) Helen Stenborg told me at the cast party: `In 50
years in the theater, I can't remember when there's been so much
success for the project I believed in the most.'''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
