<SLUG> BC-EZZARD-COLUMN19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Women's chip off old block: Heart of Madonna lives on
 &HT;    By Martha Ezzard
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Art, politics and being a mother get mixed up in my
life and the lives of a lot of women at the end of the 20th
century.
</P>
<P>
   In medieval times, icons of Madonna and child sent messages
about the value of motherhood. In 1999, a Mormon artist, Maryann
Webster, in her ceramic ``Motherboard Icon Series,'' links those
religious icons of mother and child with subtle computer chip
designs, some imprinted on the Madonna's garment as she cradles an
infant.
</P>
<P>
   My daughter, Shelly, an artist and the mother of a new baby,
introduced me to Webster's art. Its powerful and discomforting
symbols _ sacred figures and computer circuitry _ forced me to make
new connections with ``old'' dilemmas.
</P>
<P>
   At a rally for women and children at the state Capitol last
week, I was reminded again of the timeless questions raised by
Webster's powerful work. From the voices of female leaders to
chilling United Way data on state child care needs, I ran head-on
into the undervalued dimensions of motherhood in our
computer-driven world.
</P>
<P>
   The focus of the rally _ coordinated in capitols around the
country by the nonpartisan Center for Policy Alternatives _ was
economic parity and policies to help balance work and family. About
20 Georgia female lawmakers joined urban and rural community
leaders to push for creation of a women's business resource center,
for contraceptive coverage in health care plans, quality child care
and expanded day care subsidies for poor families.
</P>
<P>
   Women never leave those values behind no matter how long they're
in politics. Mothers or not, women are nurturers.
</P>
<P>
   I'd always hoped it would be easier for my two daughters to
juggle motherhood and careers than it was for me, but in some ways
it's harder. Sure, technology helps. Young mothers can telecommute
and start businesses out of their homes.
</P>
<P>
   But recent reports on childhood development run counter to
career and mothering demands. Research tells mothers to nurse
infants longer _ a year, if possible. It warns that the quality of
child care prior to age 3 determines the extent of intellectual and
social potential. True appreciation of ``mothering'' as essential
to the development of human creativity and potential is still
shallow. Mostly ``family values'' talk. Mostly political lip
service. Welfare mothers with infants and dubious child care
arrangements are mandated to take minimum-wage jobs, for example.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, due to female political power, there are signs of change.
The family and medical leave bill may well be the most
revolutionary piece of legislation of the late 20th century _
Congress' and corporate America's recognition that family and
workplace are linked.
</P>
<P>
   No icons pop up on my computer with Web site answers to the
motherhood conundrum. But everywhere I look, nurturing remains
undervalued. According to United Way of Metropolitan Atlanta, child
care teachers make less money _ $12,340 on average _ than garbage
collectors or bartenders.
</P>
<P>
   The work-family conflict can't be solved by sheer economics or
computer technology any more than machines can take over for
humans. That is the issue Webster's contemporary art caused me _ as
art should _ to wrestle with anew. Central to the artist's
acclaimed exhibit in Dolores Chase's Salt Lake City Gallery is
Robert Brautigan's 1960s poem ``All Watched Over by Machines of
Loving Grace.''
</P>
<P>
   The 53-year-old Webster, in melding medieval mother-child images
with computer chips, drew parallels that span a thousand years. And
she hit on an eternal truth: Technology can't sub for motherhood,
now or ever.
</P>
<P>
   Martha Ezzard is on the editorial board of The Atlanta Journal.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: mezzard(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
