<SLUG> BC-FBC-OSU-COACHARREST-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    OSU's Jacobs placed on leave after assault charges filed
 &HT;    By Susan Vinella
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBUS, Ohio _ Hours after turning himself into authorities
early Monday morning after being charged Saturday with assaulting
his ex-wife, Ohio State University offensive coordinator Mike
Jacobs was placed on paid administrative leave by the university.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Head football coach) John (Cooper) and I have discussed
Mike's situation at length and we both feel that it is in the best
interests of The Ohio State University, the university's football
program and Mike Jacobs that he be relieved of his day-to-day
responsibilities to give him the time to work through his legal and
personal situation,'' OSU athletics director Andy Geiger said in a
statement released by the school's athletics department on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs, a member of the Buckeyes' coaching staff since 1995, was
being held without bond Monday in Franklin County Jail on
misdemeanor charges of domestic violence and assault. He is
scheduled to be arraigned at 9 a.m. today in Franklin County
Municipal Court. Courts were closed Monday because of the Martin
Luther King Jr. holiday.
</P>
<P>
   The complaint against Jacobs accuses the 5-foot-10, 190-pound
coach of pulling Robbin Jacobs' hair, ``striking her across the
face and both eyes, causing swollen blackened eyes.'' The incident
happened at about 12:15 a.m. Saturday in Columbus, according to the
complaint. Jacobs, 49, has four sons.
</P>
<P>
   Through a statement released by his attorney, David C. Winters,
on Monday, Jacobs said, ``I did not do anything improper let alone
illegal.''
</P>
<P>
   He also said, ``I am convinced when the matter is resolved, the
public will conclude I have done nothing to discredit myself, my
family or the University.''
</P>
<P>
   Cooper was out of town on a recruiting trip and could not be
reached for comment. Geiger could not be reached for further
comment.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs' problems come in the midst of a busy recruiting period,
when coaches are permitted to travel to players' homes and try to
persuade them to sign with the Buckeyes. It was unclear Monday how
Jacobs' absence will affect OSU's recruiting efforts and who will
fill in for him. The current contact period runs through Jan. 30.
National signing day is Feb. 3.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs, a Wittenberg University graduate ('72), joined Ohio
State's coaching staff in 1995 as offensive tackles and tight ends
coach. He was promoted to offensive coordinator at the end of the
1996 season.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs previously coached at West Virginia University _ serving
as the Mountaineers' offensive coordinator from 1986-95 _ Bowling
Green, Toledo and Ashland College.
</P>
<P>
   As a player at Wittenberg, Jacobs, a former offensive guard,
helped the Tigers to the Division II National Championship his
senior year.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The DAYTON NEWSPAPERS INC., DAYTON, OHIO
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-01-18-99 1933E
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
