</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KABAT-COLUMN19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Commentary: Parents `no' their stuff
 &HT;    By Vicki Marsh Kabat
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ We all have different roles in life. Some we play
better than others. And in some roles, such as parenthood, the
script keeps changing.
</P>
<P>
   Like many parents, I learned my lines on stage as I went _
improvisation at its best, or worst. Some of the acts that should
have been high comedy, I turned into high drama, and nobody
cheered. A lot of the scenes were pure farce, some were melodrama
and there even were a few tear-jerkers.
</P>
<P>
   And the script just keeps changing. Take parenting teen-agers,
for example.
</P>
<P>
   How in the world are we supposed to know when to say yes and
when to say no? Children this age should be developing their
independence, and yet, they're at the incredibly precarious stage
when sense and reason have little meaning for many of them. ``So,
like what's the problem with going 60 in a 30 mph zone while
changing the CD and checking my hair?''
</P>
<P>
   Teen-agers know their role really well: They push the limits.
They ask and beg and plead in hopes they'll wear you down and tire
you out so that you'll say yes.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe your child, when told no, simply responds quietly ``Yes,
ma'am,'' but that doesn't happen often at our house.
</P>
<P>
   As parents, many of us don't seem to know our roles as well as
the teens know theirs. We've read just one too many contradictory
advice column or book so that we don't trust our own instincts. We
begin to waver.
</P>
<P>
   I mustn't be overprotective, we argue with ourselves. Well,
Johnny's mom must think it's all right or she wouldn't let him go.
So, I guess it's OK if my son goes, too.
</P>
<P>
   No, no, no, no. Faulty reasoning all down the line. First thing
you do with teens is develop a Mommy Network. If you haven't done
it by sixth grade, be darn sure you have by ninth grade.
</P>
<P>
   I don't think children blatantly lie about the details of their
comings and goings, but some do tend to have very selective
memories.
</P>
<P>
   Call the Mommy Network.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what I'm hearing from this end. What are you
hearing?'' You'll be amazed at the particulars that begin to
emerge.
</P>
<P>
   Details. Teens know them, they just don't always share them.
</P>
<P>
   Another tip for parenting teen-agers: ``When in doubt, say no.''
</P>
<P>
   Follow your gut instinct, regardless of what you're told every
other parent in the world is doing. If you don't like the idea of a
newly licensed 16-year-old driver taking your child to a dance on a
rainy Friday night, say no. If you want your child at home studying
all weekend before finals, insist on it.
</P>
<P>
   Parenting isn't about popularity or being your child's bud.
You're probably not going to be popular with your kids during their
teen years anyway, so just accept it and move on. They have plenty
of friends; they need parents.
</P>
<P>
   Here's what we need to remember when all around us are being
permissive: Our kids are counting on us to know what to do. They'll
never admit it, they'll rail against us tirelessly, but when we
stand firm, they secretly heave a huge sigh of relief and then go
off and tell their friends how awful we are. Then we know we've
done our job well.
</P>
<P>
   I've even had a son come to me on rare occasion, after an hour
or two of pitching a fit, and say, ``Thanks for making me stay
home, Mom. I heard that party was supposed to be pretty wild. I'm
glad I wasn't there.''
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't happen often. It may never happen at your house, or
at mine again. Nevertheless that's our role: We say no. We trust
our instincts. We check with other parents. The kids push; we stand
firm.
</P>
<P>
   Somebody around here has to be in charge. It had better be us.
</P>
<P>
   Vicki Marsh Kabat writes for the Waco (Texas) Tribune-Herald.
She can be reached online at VMKabat(at)aol.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
