</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KELSO-COLUMN19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Kelso: Writer will read your knees
 &HT;    By John Kelso
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ You never know when a bad astrology reading is
going to ruin your life.
</P>
<P>
   I mean, some psychic might tell you your financial future looks
bright. And you invest your money in widgets and you end up holding
a ``Will work for food'' sign next to the interstate.
</P>
<P>
   So there should be a market for psychic insurance to protect
people against incompetent clairvoyants, right?
</P>
<P>
   With that in mind, my friend Edd O'Donnell and I went to a
Psychic Fair, posing as representatives from a fictitious psychic
health insurance plan _ Weknow HMO.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cover all of your past and future lives,'' Edd explained.
</P>
<P>
   The Psychic Fair consisted of a roomful of tarot card readers,
at least one face reader, Mother Earth Pillows for sale, a place
where you could get your aura photographed and a woman who for $35
would tell you about your past lives.
</P>
<P>
   At first, I thought the Psychic Fair flier said ``past wives,''
so I almost didn't go.
</P>
<P>
   What I couldn't figure out is why they had me fill out my name
and address for the door-prize drawing. I thought this was a
psychic fair. They should already know my name and address, right?
</P>
<P>
   To look like a psychic health insurance salesman, I wore a
headband decorated with a large piece of costume jewelry, my
tie-dye 1992 Lithuanian Olympic basketball team T-shirt, and my
purple jacket from Roy's Taxi.
</P>
<P>
   Edd, an Austin writer, was decked out in a sheik's headdress,
wraparound sunglasses, a pink-and-blue tie-dye shirt, matching pink
pocket hanky, black sport coat and tasseled loafers.
</P>
<P>
   At first, we were going to set up a card table. But we decided
against that because when I looked into my crystal ball, all I
could see was the police coming. So instead, we circulated through
the crowd with our Weknow HMO Pre-screening Questionnaires.
</P>
<P>
   ``Serving the Psychic Community . . . but you knew that,'' it
says at the top.
</P>
<P>
   The form asks people to check off ``yes'' or ``no'' to a variety
of questions, such as: ``Natural crystals hum or change color when
I pick them up''; ``I receive messages from extraterrestrials
through my fillings''; and ``I have attended a seance and asked a
rich deceased relative for a loan.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My deceased relatives won't give me loans; that's the
problem,'' said Kramer Wetzel, of South Austin, when I showed him
one of our forms.
</P>
<P>
   Kramer, who bills himself as the ``Fishing Guide to the Stars''
and wears a bass lure in his left ear as an earring, reads natal
astrology charts for $25 a pop. He was working the fair. Maybe if
one of his dead uncles would give him some money, he could have
taken the day off.
</P>
<P>
   The first woman we approached with our forms had on a denim
shirt decorated with a Bugs Bunny insignia.
</P>
<P>
   I introduced myself and explained that my associate and I were
offering psychic insurance to fairgoers, to guard them against bad
readings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, I don't think I'm interested, thank you,'' the woman said,
walking off quickly. Maybe it was the cheap costume jewelry on my
headband that put her off.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like making telephone solicitations,'' Edd observed of
our heady task. But we trudged on anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Our next subject was a middle-aged woman who was going from one
reading table to the next.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is this now?'' she asked, looking at the form
suspiciously. ``If you fill this out, I will give you a free
reading of your elbows and knees,'' Edd told the woman, who had on
shorts. ``What in the world _ you want me to fill this out?'' she
responded.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, the free knee and elbow reading was an offer this
woman couldn't pass up. She dutifully filled out the form. Not
surprisingly, she checked off ``no'' to all of the questions,
including ``My primary care physician insists on being addressed as
`Swami,' '' ``Elvis or Liberace have visited me at home in the past
year,'' and ``Animals speak to me in a special language known only
to me.''
</P>
<P>
   After the woman filled out the form, Edd read the woman's elbows
and knees and gave her a free consultation.
</P>
<P>
   He told her that her life had been chaotic and that she needed
to slow down.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you feel a compulsion to do something else with your
life, sit down for 15 minutes and do nothing,'' Edd advised.
</P>
<P>
   I almost got my past lives read by the lady doing the past-lives
readings. But I changed my mind because I was afraid she'd tell me
I used to be a wise guy in 1427.
</P>
<P>
   John Kelso's humor column appears on Sundays, Wednesdays and
Fridays in the Austin American-Statesman. He can be reached at
jkelsostatesman.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
