<HEADER>
A8191 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LANE-COLUMN19-COX     01-18 0747
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LANE-COLUMN19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: A fat lip in the clash of ideas
 &HT;    By Mark Lane
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ News that tells us something about the
profoundly goofy world we live in _ as opposed to who's-on-first
Washington political coverage _ usually is left for the briefs.
</P>
<P>
   At one point in my career, I used to edit long strings of these
three-, four- or five-paragraph news stories. The strings would be
snipped like ribbon and pasted into pages as needed. Newspapers
have come a long way since then. Now, we keep briefs in computer
memory where they can be electronically snipped like ribbon. This
is huge progress.
</P>
<P>
   Most memorable briefs are of the cat-in-the-microwave, dumb
criminals, freak-accident and new-fad-in-Japan variety. But another
kind recently warmed my heart. The headline was ``High school
journalist punched over editorial against violence.''
</P>
<P>
   Here are the first two paragraphs:
</P>
<P>
   ``SCOTTSDALE, Ariz. (AP) _ Sam Claiborn wrote an editorial in
his high school newspaper decrying a culture of violence and
football heroes of today who become the `spouse abusers, drunks and
hamburger flippers of tomorrow.'
</P>
<P>
   ``For his high-minded efforts, Claiborn says he got beaten up
last week _ by a football player.''
</P>
<P>
   Here are the dangers of commentary stripped to their high-school
essence. A bold moral and sociological insight is advanced and an
aggrieved special interest responds forcefully and with, uh,
impact.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the give-and-take of public dialogue outside of high
school is framed in the language of wrasslin'. But despite the talk
about going to the mat, taking off the gloves and no-holds-barred
conflict until the last man left standing is finished fighting the
good fight, punches rarely get thrown. Even on cable. So reading
about the real thing seems refreshingly literal.
</P>
<P>
   But back to the story.
</P>
<P>
   ``Saguaro High School Principal Mike Carden said Claiborn should
have been more careful in his wording in the paper, the Saguaro
Sabercat.
</P>
<P>
   `` `People have a right to a viewpoint that's controversial, but
they also have to put it out there in an appropriate fashion,'
Carden said.
</P>
<P>
   `` `There were some inappropriate comments that were said that
people took objection to.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Here is a familiar call for civility wrapped in administrative
passive voice.
</P>
<P>
   Young Claiborn had the ``controversial viewpoint'' that sports
and violence might be related. A notion that in the time of O.J.
Simpson and Mike Tyson does not seem wildly out of line. The inner
pages of most sports sections have become a mix of stats and police
blotter.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, Claiborn got it all wrong when he wrote of the ``spouse
abusers, drunks and hamburger flippers of tomorrow.'' A few of
those high school athletes won't go on to low-paying jobs, they'll
go to professional sports where they will abuse women other than
their spouses and substances other than alcohol. Some may go on to
Congress. Clearly, he understated the extent of the problem.
</P>
<P>
   As an editorial writer, I support civility. It keeps my nose
shapely and my face youthful.
</P>
<P>
   This is the kind of civility that keeps zoning disputes from
turning into Bosnia. People used to call it ``tolerance.'' I like
that word better than ``civility'' because it implies you don't
have to like anybody. Just tolerate them. Even I can do that.
</P>
<P>
   The principal, however, talked about civility of a different
kind. The kind in which someone with ``a viewpoint that's
controversial,'' who puts it out there inappropriately, is cruising
for a bruising. That kind of civility upholds a kind of bully's
veto.
</P>
<P>
   If such civility were restricted to high schools, we could laugh
it off _ loud and in an inappropriate fashion. But it's not.
Civility that asserts the right not to be upset and the duty not to
be upsetting is in great demand. You see it in campus speech codes
and asserted by lawyers in court and politicians on television.
Sometimes, ``civility'' is just a civil way to tell other people to
shut up.
</P>
<P>
   It is an uncivil truism that the cure for dumb and offensive
speech is to unleash more speech to growl at it in the open. And
anyone who thinks otherwise is asking for a fat lip.
</P>
<P>
   Metaphorically speaking, of course.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Lane is an associate editor for The Daytona Beach (Fla.)
News-Journal. He may be reached at marklane(at)n-jcenter.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
