<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 20:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8192 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NCR-LEXIS-NEXIS-COX     01-18 0394
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NCR-LEXIS-NEXIS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NCR, Lexis-Nexis join forces in $1 data warehouse
 &HT;    By Jim Dillon
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ NCR Corp. and Lexis-Nexis have co-existed in the
Miami Valley for decades, but have not done much business together
in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   But that situation has changed. On Monday, Dayton-based NCR
announced it has installed a $1.1 million data warehouse system
inside Miami Twp.-based Lexis-Nexis, a premium legal and business
information provider, to help that company's 400 salespeople
nationwide keep better track of customers.
</P>
<P>
   Data warehouses are computer database systems that let companies
tap large stores of information and get quick answers to complex
questions about their business.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, Lexis-Nexis salespeople had to rely largely on
monthly summaries and the like to get that information. With the
NCR system, they can access a wide range of specific information
about customers in seconds, said Jack Knapp, assistant vice
president of industry marketing for NCR.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have thousands of sources of information in their
database. But they had no way to, on a real-time basis and in a
detailed fashion, see how these sources of information were being
used and by whom,'' Knapp said. ``They had no way to really
understand their customers' usage patterns and behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   With the data warehouse, a Lexis-Nexis salesperson can now
determine, for example, which contracts are set to expire in 60
days and see where there has been a rapid decline in usage, Knapp
said. ``That could be an indication that the customer is using
another source of information.''
</P>
<P>
   The system was installed in November and will undergo phased
testing throughout this year, said Keith Hawk, vice president of
sales for the Nexis division.
</P>
<P>
   If the data warehouse works as expected, the two companies might
do more business, Knapp and Hawk said.
</P>
<P>
   Also Monday, Harrah's Entertainment Inc. selected an NCR data
warehouse to run its international customer recognition and rewards
system for the more than 14.5 million guests who eat, sleep, watch
live shows and wager at the company's 18 casinos in eight states.
Financial terms were not disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Dillon writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
