A8193 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN19-COX     01-18 0716
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    It's a cold, crazy world
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ This column is especially for my readers in
the sunny South. I know where you are, and I know what you're
doing. I would bet you a buffalo nickel that at this very moment
you are kicked back in a poolside lounger counting blue-tailed
skinks on the hibiscus-ringed, screened
</P>
<P>
   enclosure. From time to time, your reverie may be disturbed by a
distant, guttural rumble as the pool's filtration system kicks in
and sends pristine
</P>
<P>
   wavelets of tepid water lapping into the overflow.
</P>
<P>
   Setting aside your glass of freshly squeezed (probably
homegrown) juice, you
</P>
<P>
   give the morning paper a shake, take one look at the
three-column picture above
</P>
<P>
   the fold, and mutter to your mate: ``Looka' here Fred, those
crazy Yankees are
</P>
<P>
   up to their butts in snow again.'' Old Fred just grins and rubs
a little more sunblock on his bald spot as he squints at the pond
out back for signs of the big 'gator that's been prowling the dock.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, not far from Lake Erie's frigid shores, there's a
silence of another sort, broken only occasionally by the rumble of
the village plow as it scrapes deserted streets in a futile attempt
to budge the foot-and-a-half of snow that covers the layer of ice
that covers a layer of snow that just happens to be on top of three
inches of ice that covers the first half-a-foot of snow.
</P>
<P>
   A warming fire crackles on the hearth and over in the corner
under the window
</P>
<P>
   seats, comes an occasional snore from the cats as they snuggle
in their quilt-lined baskets next to the radiators. At regular
intervals I can hear the grumble of the mysterious innards of the
basement boiler as it throbs its little guts out to keep this cozy
nest (and the seven miles of heating pipes running through its
walls) from freezing over.
</P>
<P>
   Since alligators are seldom spotted crawling over snow banks, I
make do with
</P>
<P>
   studying the distorted shapes of the ice that gorges the
neighbor's gutters. Come the thaw, I know all of that stuff is
going to melt and be looking for a
</P>
<P>
   place to go - like maybe up under the eaves and inside. I don't
EVEN want to
</P>
<P>
   know what my gutters look like.
</P>
<P>
   Charlie, the undertaker across the street, has finished plowing
his parking lot and is working on my front walk. I motion a thank
you through the window and watch as he revs up the machine before
making a full speed head-on run at a
</P>
<P>
   particularly precipitous drift. Unique approach, I'm thinking as
he slams into the snowy equivalent of a brick wall.
</P>
<P>
   There's not a whole lot to do when the snow's this deep. Sharon,
my ex-sister-in-law (we used to be married to brothers but now
we're not), has been on an ``earth mother'' spree ever since the
driveways drifted over. Every night she cooks supper and afterward
we lie on the couch hollering answers at Jeopardy and trying to
calculate how much money we would have made if only Alex
</P>
<P>
   had invited us on the show.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday I made it down the street to Dr. Sam's for my
semi-annual tooth
</P>
<P>
   scraping and buffing. As I lay back in the chair watching the
snow swirl outside the window and pile up on the big pines in Doc's
front yard, I began to suspect I was in imminent danger of coming
down with a severe dose of cabin fever. Moments later my suspicions
were confirmed when I found myself actually enjoying some guy on
the office radio wailing, ``Ya picked a fine time to leave me,
Lucille ... four hon-gry children and crops in the field.''
</P>
<P>
   Odd part of it is, I'm thinking as I contemplate my isolation, I
grew up down there in 'gator country where the only lock-in we
endured was a hurricane which
</P>
<P>
   always went away in a day or two allowing my buddies and me to
go out and play
</P>
<P>
   in the flood and catch odd-looking snakes that washed in from
the Glades. And
</P>
<P>
   now here I am up to my Florida cracker backside in snow while
Fred, who's
</P>
<P>
   probably from Cleveland, languishes poolside. I tell you folks,
it's a world
</P>
<P>
   gone mad.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schuett writes for Cox News Service. Address mail to:
320 West
</P>
<P>
   Madison, Gibsonburg, OH 43431 or email: eschuett(at)nwonline.net
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
