<HEADER>
A8194 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YOUNG-COLUMN19-COX     01-18 0664
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    They love the deputy
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ ``Shoot for the moon and you'll get some cheese.''
</P>
<P>
   These are words my son will remember for a long time. They're a
personal inscription from his favorite deputy.
</P>
<P>
   Words to live by? Actually, they're among many words to laugh by
for a group of fifth graders I know, laughing being a necessary
part of living in these overexerted times. The fifth-grader I know
best is quite a wit already, and I gather so are some of his
classmates. Put them in a room with Officer Will Stevens and watch
out.
</P>
<P>
   He's one of four McLennan County DARE officers _ Drug Abuse
Resistance and Education. Though he's a certified lawman he's also
a certifiable comic, or so says my son, who knows him from Stevens'
visits to his elementary school.
</P>
<P>
   This is an officer who will pull out a nightstick and, rather
than whop you on the head, crane it to his mouth and croon bad '80s
pop into it. He's got a zillion one-liners, and he loves to draw
the kids into the kidding.
</P>
<P>
   Some mugwump might ask: What are the children learning from all
of this?
</P>
<P>
   Plenty. Such would be the assessment from their recent DARE
graduation and essays they read. DARE is a semester-long course,
not just about drug abuse but also about decisions in general.
</P>
<P>
   Approximately 60 percent of America's fifth-graders get DARE. It
has its share of critics, who say the program doesn't yield results
in reduced drug abuse sufficient to what it costs. A few counties
have discontinued it on those grounds. Some critics also charge
that in some cases DARE officers have tried to enlist their
students as snitches on others, including their own parents.
</P>
<P>
   It would appear that DARE, like any device for education, could
be ineffective or misused depending on who carries it out.
</P>
<P>
   But my experience thus far, with two sons going through DARE
classes, is that it's been a worthwhile investment.
</P>
<P>
   Principally, I feel that way because the DARE my sons have known
it is not just an anti-drug harangue. It's a lot about living and
growing up. And if Deputy Stevens is any indication, it hasn't been
an overbearing, sermonizing thing.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly it can't be if officers intend to make meaningful
connections.
</P>
<P>
   Connections alone are a benefit of DARE. It matters to have
symbols of authority, law officers, shed adversarial airs with
young people and show them they're just regular people who care.
Indeed, that's the best way to get a drug-abuse message across.
</P>
<P>
   I well remember the anti-drug films that were cued up for me and
my contemporaries in darkened high school auditoriums of the late
'60s. They were so preachy, melodramatic and overdone as to be
laughable. And, oh, yes. We laughed.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is, that's all we got out of those films _ a hoot.
Someone was frantic to scare us about drug abuse. We sensed that.
That didn't work. It never works.
</P>
<P>
   The difference about the laughter in Deputy Stevens' classes is
that it would appear the class is laughing with him, not just at
him, as he sets the stage for more serious matter.
</P>
<P>
   Getting a message to sink in with young people takes more than a
sermon or a warning. It takes real connections and shared respect.
Yes _ respect the fact that children are more worldly and skeptical
than we want to believe.
</P>
<P>
   And one of the best ways to get respect is to refrain from
preaching. And the best way to refrain from that is to get people
to laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Those anti-drug movies are as vivid in my mind today and stand
as a case study in how not to influence young people to abuse
drugs. I'm gathering from my son's comments that Deputy Stevens
will re remembered, too, but not with disdain.
</P>
<P>
   John Young is the opinion page editor of the Waco
Tribune-Herald. His column appears Tuesday, Thursday and Sunday.
E-mail: jyoung(at)mail. wacotrib.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
