<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-WATERFALL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARADISE FOUND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Western mind usually considers planet Earth explored, set
down neatly in books and maps, while the frontier is outer space.
But explorers back from a National Geographic expedition to the
heart of the Tsangpo Gorge in southern Tibet sound as awe-struck as
Neil Armstrong did on the surface of the moon.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a different dimension of space and time,'' said Hamid
Sardar in a telephone interview. The Cambridge resident has a PhD
in Tibetan and Himalayan studies from Harvard University. Last
November he followed guides down cliff paths to reach a roaring,
100-foot waterfall previously considered a myth. With him were Ian
Baker, an American writer and Tibetan scholar who led the
expedition, Ken Storm, a Minneapolis businessman, and Bryan Harvey,
a videographer.
</P>
<P>
   Explorers had speculated that a dramatic waterfall could exist
where the Tsangpo and Bramaputra rivers meet, but no one could
prove it until two months ago.
</P>
<P>
   The trek was mostly vertical. The walls of the gorge are formed
by two mountains, each with an elevation of more than 23,000 feet.
The falls, usually in shadow, thunder at the bottom of a 4,000-foot
cliff hidden by an overhang and a 90-degree turn in the river.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a lesson in going around the next bend,'' said Storm,
who described the surreal beauty as humbling. The barren cliffs at
the top of the gorge give way to subtropical gardens below,
bursting with huge rhododendrons, lilies, and orchids. ``We came as
pilgrims,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Considered paradise by the Buddhists who live there, the gorge
can be hell to a Westerner. Sardar recalled hiking with his legs
full of leeches that could not be killed because of local belief
that they suck sin out of the traveler. He said the many poisonous
snakes in the area are also welcomed, for they teach
``mindfulness.''
</P>
<P>
   But he is eager to go back, as he has for six visits. He and his
colleagues had the fortitude and spiritual vision that reminds the
rest of us to look for the unknown in what is believed to be known.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
