<SLUG> BC-SHARP-DRIVING19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Autos built on shared platform are not identical
 &HT;    By Linda Sharp
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The term ``platform'' is one frequently thrown around
in automotive circles these days. But if you ask most consumers
what it means when an advertisement or article states certain
vehicles are built on the same platform, most people are lost.
</P>
<P>
   The most common perception of the term platform is it means the
vehicles share the same floor plan or metal stamping that
constitutes the ``floor'' of the car. That may be the case on a
shared-platform vehicle, but not necessarily.
</P>
<P>
   The other most commonly held misconception is if vehicles are
built on the same platform, then they are essentially the same
vehicles with slightly different exteriors. That is most certainly
not the case.
</P>
<P>
   Probably the automaker that has most successfully adapted the
concept of shared platforms is Toyota. It is common knowledge in
automotive circles that Toyota's Camry sedan, Camry Solara coupe
and Sienna minivan, as well as the Lexus ES 300 sedan and RX300
sport-utility vehicle, are all built on the same platform.
</P>
<P>
   They are most assuredly not the same vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   So just what is a platform? What advantages does the concept of
shared platforms offer automakers as well as consumers?
</P>
<P>
   Lexus' national manager for product planning, Bruce Quisenberry,
explains it as the basis or foundation upon which the vehicle is
built. Consider you can pour identical house footings and,
depending upon how you complete the structure, you might end up
with a New England salt box, a California modern, a two-story
traditional or your basic box ranch. The concrete really doesn't
care what sits on it.
</P>
<P>
   The same is true of a vehicle platform. Shared vehicle platforms
typically share the same engine configuration, transmission and
sub-frame mounts as well as braking systems and engine and
suspension cradle assemblies.
</P>
<P>
   It is important to remember the platform is only the starting
point. By sharing these hidden components, the manufacturer not
only reduces manufacturing costs, but actually enhances the
building process.
</P>
<P>
   The shared components also allow for a sharing of development
costs on the nonvisible components providing more extensive
research and development. Result: The consumer gets more for his or
her money.
</P>
<P>
   Quisenberry said about 25 percent of Toyota/Lexus shared
platform vehicles have a common effort. After that, each is
different.
</P>
<P>
   Shared platforms are sort of like identical gift boxes. They all
serve basically the same function, but what they hold can be as
different and varied as the imagination of those who fill them. A
full-length mink or a woolen blanket would fit in the same box, but
no one would mistake them for the same product.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Sharp is a training consultant to auto manufacturers. Her
column is written exclusively for The Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
Write her in care of Wheels, The Atlanta Journal-Constitution, P.O.
Box 4689, Atlanta, GA 30302. Or send comments online to
sharpdriver(at)worldnet.att.net
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
