<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Junkland' worthy of a quick junking
 &HT;    By Yusuf Davis
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ ``Junkland Jam,'' a PC musical adventure game by
Southpeak, hit a sour note for Makia McFarland of southwest
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The adventure is designed to take kids to an imaginary world
filled with games, puzzles and experiments and let them interact
with kooky characters while learning about music in a fun,
entertaining way.
</P>
<P>
   But it didn't do anything for our 8-year-old reviewer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't get into it,'' Makia said. ``It was boring.''
</P>
<P>
   In theory, ``Junkland Jam'' is filled with potential. The CD-ROM
game promises to transport players to the animated world of
Junkland, where trash has been turned to treasure and transformed
into something new, useful and fun. There are 3-D backgrounds to
help immerse players into a fun-filled story line, hidden surprises
and colorful characters. There is also an on-screen notebook of fun
scientific experiments.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, theory differed from reality, and ``Junkland
Jam'' didn't strike a chord with Makia, who tried the game several
times but said she is unlikely to play it again.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pictures are good. The color is good. The sound hurt my
ears,'' Makia said.
</P>
<P>
   The only part of the game that held Makia's attention was using
a magnet to remove a pile of trash that had fallen on the main
character, Simon Fehfer, whom players help as he travels through
Junkland looking for his missing harmonica.
</P>
<P>
   ``That part was fun,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, the other thing about ``Junkland Jam'' Makia liked
was the harmonica that came bundled with the software. The
harmonica was also a hit with Makia's sister, Maya, age 5. The
low-tech musical instrument was included so players could sing and
play along with the game's original songs.
</P>
<P>
   However, Sharon McFarland, the girls' mother, said neither girl
has mastered the harmonica, which is capable of many dissonant
sounds. She implied the real harmonica, like the virtual
instrument, may soon also be lost.
</P>
<P>
   `JUNKLAND JAM'
</P>
<P>
   Developer: Southpeak Interactive
</P>
<P>
   Price: $29.95
</P>
<P>
   System requirements: Win 95/98, 486/100 MHz CPU, 16 MB RAM, 30
MB free space, 2x CD-ROM drive, 16-bit sound card, mouse
</P>
<P>
   Age: 6-10
</P>
<P>
   Makia's grade: D
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
