<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wired celebrities peek into the future
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Read what some leading technologists have to say about
the future in the January issue of Wired magazine. You'll find
comments from a wide range of people, including film director
Francis Ford Coppola, science fiction novelist Arthur C. Clarke and
Yahoo! co-founder David Filo. Songwriter David Crosby says, in
part, ``I want a computer I can talk to. One that would follow me
around with a part of itself and wouldn't forget anything.''
</P>
<P>
   In the same issue of Wired, there's also a tribute of sorts to
the cell phone. It's actually a series of articles that look at the
device's social implications. Called ``The Big Schmooze,'' this
package includes articles on ``the gestalt'' of cell phones and on
the phones themselves. And there's an article about the best place
in the world to have a cell phone: Finland. In that Scandinavian
country, you can use your cell phone to activate a nearby Coca-Cola
machine. Now that, concludes the article, is cell phone nirvana.
</P>
<P>
   On CD-ROM
</P>
<P>
   There's a dogfight under way among makers of combat flight
simulators, and the only sure winner so far has been consumers. The
latest entry to this battlefield is ``Falcon 4.0,'' published by
Microprose. This is the latest version of a popular combat
simulator that has been on the market for some time. This version
features F-16s battling over the Korean peninsula. Available only
for Windows PCs, ``Falcon'' retails for $55.
</P>
<P>
   At work, you may be a peon, but with the computer CD
``Capitalism,'' you can build a magnificent business empire from
scratch. The game, published by Interactive Magic, is a simulation
in which players build a business from the ground up. You'll do
everything from manufacturing to buying real estate and hiring
employees. According to reviewers, ``Capitalism'' is tough _ but
fun and educational, too. Available for both PCs and Macs, it
retails for about $40.
</P>
<P>
   Online
</P>
<P>
   If you're looking to cut back on your meat consumption, check
out the Vegetarian Epicure. This site offers a wealth of
information about eating veggies. There are recipes, recommended
books about the subject and places where you can e-mail the
Webmaster for more information. You'll find this site at
http://www.vegetarianepicure.com/.
</P>
