<SLUG> BC-TECHNOBUDDY19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    First rule of computer shopping: Try not to pay retail
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ I've got a friend who feels comfortable buying and
selling houses that sell for an amount roughly equivalent to the
gross national product of Peru, who drives such a hard bargain when
buying a car that the salesman is often tempted to quit and join
the Marines.
</P>
<P>
   She's scared to death of buying a computer.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't going to be a technical column. This is the last
mention you'll hear from me today about megahertz or gigabytes.
There won't be a single additional mention of bus speeds, I/O cards
or terminal network adapters.
</P>
<P>
   I get a lot of e-mail, and I'm discovering that my friend isn't
alone. There are highly intelligent, streetwise folks who seem
paralyzed by the notion of buying a computer. Some of the fears are
justified _ you really do need to know what to look for when
shopping, and that's what we talked about last week. But that's
pretty simple to figure out. Even if you didn't read my column,
there are magazines and other articles that do a good job of
covering those bases. But that feeling of ignorance (as opposed to
stupidity) seems to freeze a lot of brains when it's time to decide
where to buy the computer and how much to pay for it.
</P>
<P>
   Did I say ``decide'' how much to pay? Wait a minute, these
suckers all have price tags.
</P>
<P>
   So do the cars in the lot; so did that last house have a
specific price. But you didn't feel tempted to just write a check,
did you?
</P>
<P>
   Now wait a minute all you computer retailers, don't start
cranking out a letter complaining that you don't bargain. Some
stores really won't bargain, I know that. But I can promise you
that, over the past few years, I have shopped for enough computers
to stock a mom-and-pop store ... simply because I end up helping
personal friends so often when they're shopping. And I've seen some
bargains struck, prices lowered, extra stuff like a scanner or a
software package thrown in to close the sale.
</P>
<P>
   So my first bit of shopping advice is the same as you'd get from
your Uncle Maxie. Don't pay retail if you can help it. First,
identify the specifications for the machine you want to buy. Then
go shopping.
</P>
<P>
   Don't take a checkbook or a credit card or enough cash to buy
it. Instead, find the hungriest-looking salesmen you can find and
show them your specifications. Tell them you're not browsing, that
you plan to buy a computer just like that. And explain that you'll
be shopping several stores and that you plan to buy from the place
that offers the best price on that specific machine.
</P>
<P>
   If the salesman says he can't bargain, that's fine. Write down
the list price. Some stores start out with their best offer and _
who knows _ your best price may be from a store that doesn't
discount. It happens. Then repeat the process as often as you can.
</P>
<P>
   Now that you've found the best price in town, or as close as you
care to come to it, there's still more to do. Obviously, all
computers (and all technical support) are not created equally. This
part is a personal choice. Decide how much a brand name is worth,
how much good technical support is worth and try to allow for that
in your decision. My own opinion is that _ especially for a
beginner _ the assurance of a brand name and good technical support
is worth several hundred dollars' difference in price. But mileage
may vary ... if you have a friend who is a computer whiz, you also
have a chance to save money by writing off those factors.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly, the point I am making is that you are already an expert
in the art of buying products. Just because you don't know a BIOS
from binoculars doesn't mean you can't do an expert job buying a
computer.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: tecbud(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
