<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Be smart, be safe _ test your battery
 &HT;    By Nora Carter
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Teaching about batteries, starting and charging
systems often directs my attention beyond the normal textbook
theory portion of the class into trade journal publications
pertaining to the subject.
</P>
<P>
   As automotive electrical systems become more complex and
computer-dependent, the once relatively simple role of the battery
takes on a whole new dimension. While this unobtrusive component of
the vehicle's electrical network has remained basically unchanged
since its debut, it has earned the dubious position of being the
most overlooked component under the hood, even in the event of
electrical problems.
</P>
<P>
   How much trouble can that little black box cause? It doesn't
even have any moving parts. Well, I've seen a plethora of starters,
alternators and even computers replaced because of that little
black box.
</P>
<P>
   The battery is the heart and the stabilizing force in a
vehicle's whole electrical system. When it is ``sick,'' you can bet
the rest of the system is feeling the effects. I'm not talking
about something as apparent as a ``no crank'' on a cold morning.
That symptom is only the result of a weakened battery that has
finally reached the ``I quit'' point, much as a heart attack is the
result of extenuating health circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   The irony of this situation is a human ends up in the hospital
with a team of medical people racing to save the heart. The patient
will subsequently undergo tests and treatments for the heart attack
until complete recovery. The battery, on the other hand, ends up on
the receiving end of a set of jumper cables that are disconnected
as soon as the engine sputters to life. It is immediately expected
to return to work full time, usually without even the benefit of a
check-up.
</P>
<P>
   Let me share a personal experience with you. A while ago, I met
my husband for supper at a restaurant. When I got into my car to
leave, it wouldn't crank. Neither of us could find any apparent
reason for the dead battery, so he jump-started my car and I drove
home. It seemed unlikely the battery was bad, as the car was only a
couple of months out of warranty and the battery's ``green eye''
was showing. We put the battery on the charger and went to bed. For
the next few days the car started fine. We figured the battery had
simply become discharged as a result of my short commute driving.
</P>
<P>
   Then, one afternoon it left me stranded in a parking lot.
Another jump-start, another charging session and a complete test of
the electrical system, including the starter revealed no problems.
However, when I ``stress tested'' the battery, it failed. I
replaced the battery. As it turned out, the battery had an internal
break that would work and then not work intermittently. Although
this is not a common problem, it wouldn't have been detected
without the proper test. Had I continued to drive the car with this
condition, it would have destroyed the alternator and very likely
caused other expensive electrical problems.
</P>
<P>
   I got off cheap, but I know people who weren't so lucky. One guy
I know waited for what seemed like forever for a new computer.
Don't ignore a dead battery and don't expect your car's charging
system to rescue it. Get it in to your mechanic and get it tested.
</P>
<P>
   Nora Carter, who has 26 years of experience in the auto repair
industry, is an automotive instructor at DeKalb Technical Institute
and an ASE master automobile technician/ L-1. Write her in care of
Wheels, The Atlanta Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta,
GA 30302. Or send comments online to
nora(at)admin2.dekalb.tec.ga.us or 2wrenchs(at) bellsouth.net
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
