<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Let your mouse find that phone number
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Afew years back, the virtues of the then-new computer
CD-ROM drive found a real home with truly useful programs that
allowed you to look up telephone numbers.
</P>
<P>
   It was a lot more useful than using a telephone directory,
because the programs harness the computer's ability to search
through a lot of information.
</P>
<P>
   So if you had an old friend named Fields who used to live in
Arkansas, you could try directory assistance, but you wouldn't get
very far. But, using the CD, you had a good chance of finding him.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe you remembered his first name, or knew the city he lived
in _ information would help you narrow the search.
</P>
<P>
   But there was a big downside to these CD programs. For one
thing, they were enormous. Even the massive storage provided by the
CD wasn't enough to hold every telephone listing in the country,
all the addresses and all the phone numbers. So, if you had to
search for that same name in several regions of the country, you
might have to change discs three or even four times before finding
the right number.
</P>
<P>
   That's where the online world has made a real difference. There
are several fine Web sites where you can perform the same sort of
searches, looking for names, phone numbers, addresses, even e-mail
addresses.
</P>
<P>
   Although using the Web to look up numbers can be slow, and if
you have only one phone line, you have to log off to place the
call, the advantages far outweigh the disadvantages.
</P>
<P>
   First, the information is stored in a giant database, so you
don't need to spend time changing CDs. Second, the information is
usually updated often. CD programs also offer updates but _ unless
you want to buy a new update a couple of times a year _ it's
unlikely the information will be as current. Third, since there are
several sites that offer this type of help, you can switch from one
service to another and search more records than you could with a
single program.
</P>
<P>
   Now let's take a look at some of these Web-based search
services.
</P>
<P>
   One of the best is called Switchboard, and you'll find it at
http://www.switchboard.com. As you would expect, you can use it to
find a telephone number or an address. And it also is a good source
for e-mail addresses. (Be careful, though. People seem to change
e-mail addresses about as often as shirts and _ before sending off
a personal note based on what you find _ send a test note to make
sure you are reaching the correct person.)
</P>
<P>
   Switchboard is reasonably fast (although there will be times
when the load of a lot of simultaneous users slows things down).
And it's usually accurate. So just those attributes, coupled with
the fact that it's free _ unlike a CD program _ make it worth
using. But, as they say on those late-night TV commercials, there's
still more.
</P>
<P>
   Suppose you don't know the name but do know that you need to
find a specific professional.
</P>
<P>
   If you're looking for doctors, lawyers, dentists, accountants or
Realtors, for instance, you can search the directory using those
categories.
</P>
<P>
   That's especially handy if you are in unfamiliar territory
geographically and need help.
</P>
<P>
   Another service that works much the same way is Bigfoot at
http://www.bigfoot.com/. While, subjectively at least, Switchboard
seems more likely to find a match, Bigfoot is a good service and
definitely worth bookmarking.
</P>
<P>
   That's because neither directory is as complete or thorough as
your hometown phone book.
</P>
<P>
   Some names are missing from these services, and you can't beat
the convenience of searching both services.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
