<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 21:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8215 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-KING-NYT     01-18 0949
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-KING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK HONORS KING AND HIS IDEALS, NOT YET FULLY REALIZED
</HEADLINE>
  (See also CLINTON-KING) 
(bl) 
 By NADINE BROZAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Ronald Glenn, a history teacher at John Jay High
School in Park Slope, Brooklyn, says he still treasures a
photograph of himself at the age of 14 with Dr. Martin Luther King
Jr. Glenn was 14 and editor of his school newspaper at the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``My family was the first black family to live in our
neighborhood in East St. Louis,'' he said Monday. ``My father took
us to a cafeteria that wouldn't serve us, but we didn't leave until
the cops came.''
</P>
<P>
   Glenn, 55, who was arrested 8 times and served a total of 55
days in jail during the civil rights struggles in the South, was at
the Brooklyn Academy of Music, where a host of politicians and
others turned out Monday to celebrate King's legacy. It was one of
several events to honor the civil rights leader, and many used the
day to reflect on how far the nation had come in seeking to correct
the inequalities King had devoted his life to ending, and how far
it has yet to go.
</P>
<P>
   The day was studded with fiery rhetoric, jubilant gospel music,
religious services and political debates around the region. At one
event, Sen. Charles Schumer, state Attorney General Eliot Spitzer
and state Comptroller H. Carl McCall discussed policy in a forum
organized by the Rev. Al Sharpton.
</P>
<P>
   An ecumenical service organized by the Baptist Ministers
Conference of Greater New York and Vicinity drew former Sen. Bill
Bradley, Rep. Charles Rangel and former Mayor David Dinkins.
</P>
<P>
   And on the West Side of Manhattan, students from the Martin
Luther King Jr. High School painted walls at the 74th Street Senior
Home, an assisted-living center, and danced and played bingo with
the residents in honor of the day.
</P>
<P>
   The event at the Brooklyn Academy of Music was so heavily
attended that the 2,100-seat opera house could not accommodate
everybody. There was, of course, a strong political backdrop, with
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, Borough President Howard Golden and Schumer
taking part.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer noted that his first assignment after his election to
the House of Representatives in 1985 was to the Judiciary
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I co-sponsored the bill to make his birthday a national
holiday,'' Schumer said, ``and it is astounding the opposition that
bill garnered. The most pernicious amendment came from an Orange
County, Calif., representative who wanted to strike one word _
`King' _ and make it Martin Luther Day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I explained that although Martin Luther was a great man, he
didn't represent all of us,'' the senator said.
</P>
<P>
   But no one aroused the fervor of the overwhelmingly black
assemblage as much as Rep. John Lewis, D-Ga., and former chairman
of the Student Nonviolent Coordinating Committee, which in the
1960s worked to end segregation in the south.
</P>
<P>
   Emotion tinged the congressman's voice as he described a
childhood in the Alabama town of Troy, where he first tried out
preaching sermons to the chicks he raised on his family's farm and
where he was told that library cards were for whites only. When
Troy State University in Montgomery failed to even acknowledge his
1957 application for admission, he wrote to King, who promptly sent
him a round-trip bus ticket to meet him in Montgomery.
</P>
<P>
   ``He inspired me to take a seat at the lunch counter, and by
sitting down we were standing up for the best in American
tradition,'' he said. Together King and Lewis joined with other
leaders of SNCC in marching for voting rights and equal
opportunities, and Lewis vividly described being met with tear gas,
bullwhips, trampling horses and state troopers during the march
from Selma to Montgomery in 1965.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis was the only speaker of the day to connect the impeachment
trial to issues of discrimination. ``If I was able to forgive Bull
Connor, George Wallace, the Ku Klux Klan, then we should be able to
forgive our president,'' he said, his voice rising with anger.
</P>
<P>
   At the close of his talk, he recalled a childhood incident in
which he and his brothers, sisters and cousins were playing at an
aunt's flimsy house (``a shotgun house because you could shoot a
bullet in the front and have it come out the back''). A sudden
violent storm arose, and he said, ``We ran from corner to corner of
the house trying to hold it down with our little bodies wherever it
was raised up.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Now,'' he continued, ``the lightning may flash, the wind may
blow, the rain may beat down, but we must never leave our house,''
he said. ``Maybe we all came to this country in different ships,
but we are all in one boat together.''
</P>
<P>
   That message was not lost on Kim Wanliss, 33, an assistant
principal at Intermediate School 232 in Brooklyn, who immigrated
here from Jamaica. As she listened to Lewis, she said, ``I realized
that they paved the way for people like me, where there are no
legal obstacles any more.''
</P>
<P>
   But as many others did, she noted that King's vision had yet to
be fully realized. ``There is still plenty of cultural bias,'' she
went on. ``Two years ago, my sister had a problem in the workplace
when she was told that wearing braids wrapped around her head was
not acceptable.'' She subsequently left her job, Ms. Wanliss said.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn, the teacher in Park Slope, waited in a long line for
Lewis to sign his book ``Walking With the Wind: A Memoir of the
Movement'' (Simon &AMP; Shuster). He said that to this day he presses
on with the cause by talking about King to his students.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's ancient history to them,'' he said. ``They don't
understand that those conditions of segregation existed only a
moment ago.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
