<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 21:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8217 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-SANTORUM-NYT &LR;      01-18 0787
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-SANTORUM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PENNSYLVANIA SENATOR FALLS SILENT ON IMPEACHMENT
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa.)   (See also IMPEACH-RDP, IMPEACH-LOBBY, IMPEACH-REPUBS) 
(nk) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Sen. Rick Santorum, the conservative Republican
from Pennsylvania, has been a strident critic of President Clinton,
once accusing him of telling ``bald-faced untruths.'' But these
days, with Clinton's fate in the hands of the Senate _ and with
Democrats lining up to challenge Santorum for his job in 2000 _ the
junior senator's voice has fallen silent.
</P>
<P>
   Santorum, a freshman known for his vocal opposition to an
abortion procedure that Clinton has kept legal, acknowledges that
he has softened his sharper edges. But he says he has done so
because he has sworn to be impartial about impeachment, not to save
his own political skin in a state that has voted twice for Clinton
and gives him sky-high approval ratings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm toning things down because this is not an issue where I
have an opinion going into it,'' Santorum said Monday, hustling
through a hotel lobby on his way to catch a plane.
</P>
<P>
   The presumption by his conservative supporters and liberal
critics is that regardless of what he says, Santorum will vote to
remove Clinton from office. But Santorum insists he has not decided
how he will vote. He says he is keeping his mind open, and his
recent public comments indeed betray no bias.
</P>
<P>
   ``I took an oath of impartiality,'' he said. ``The politics I'm
not going to worry about. You could argue the politics either
way.''
</P>
<P>
   Political watchers here say that he has moderated his tone and
to some extent his positions from his previously purist approach.
He supported a sales-tax increase in 1997 for certain counties in
Western Pennsylvania to build a new stadium to keep the Pirates in
Pittsburgh. (Voters opposed it.) He has also portrayed himself as a
protector of the steel industry, which is being hurt by cheap
foreign imports, although he was shouted down at a recent forum by
a crowd of angry steelworkers who doubted his sincerity. And he has
been active in seeking to shore up Social Security, an important
issue in a state with a heavy proportion of elderly voters. But few
seem convinced that, come reckoning day in the Senate, there is
even a chance that Santorum would vote in the president's favor.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's receding into a more procedure-oriented focus,'' said Sam
Katz, a Republican candidate for mayor and one of the few
Republicans attending a Martin Luther King luncheon here Monday,
where Santorum sat at the head table. ``But I can't imagine he
won't vote to remove the president.''
</P>
<P>
   Santorum's neutrality on impeachment had filtered through to
some in the audience of 2,500 people, many of them
African-Americans. Myrtis A. Gordon, 55, a manager of court clerks,
said his stance was ``kind of encouraging and somewhat
unexpected,'' and she told him as he left to keep an open mind.
</P>
<P>
   But she said later that she still expected him to vote against
the president and added that despite his professed neutrality, she
would never vote for him because he was too conservative. ``I
wouldn't vote for him if he stood on his head,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Santorum's dedicated conservative following here senses that he
will vote against Clinton on principle, even if he has to appear
more neutral now. Michael Geer, president of the Pennsylvania
Family Institute, a conservative group that focuses on state
issues, said: ``There's a distinction between what they say and how
they vote. If Senator Santorum were up in 2004, he might be more
outspoken than he is now. But he won't take a poll and say, `The
people in Pennsylvania like Clinton and won't support me if I vote
to convict him so I won't convict.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Santorum was elected in 1994 with 49 percent of the vote,
ousting the Democratic incumbent, Harris Wofford. One Democrat,
state Sen. Allyson Schwartz, has already announced her candidacy
for Senate in the year 2000, saying that Santorum is too out of
step with mainstream Pennsylvania. Others in the wings include Rep.
Ron Klink, former Reps. Marjorie Margolies-Mezvinsky and Peter
Kostmayer, and Tom Foley, the former state labor secretary.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest names in state Democratic politics _ Edward G.
Rendell, mayor of Philadelphia, and Bob Casey Jr., the state
auditor general _ are more likely to run for governor in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   All of Santorum's likely opponents are on the liberal end of the
spectrum, which suits him just fine. ``If I was running against the
most popular, well-known moderate Democrat, it wouldn't affect my
decision,'' he said. ``I want my children to be able to be proud of
what their father did.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
