<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-MERGERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIGGER AND BIGGER BUSINESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gulp, gulp, gulp. Small fish in the corporate sea are swallowed
by medium fish, which are eaten by sharks, which devour each other.
The consumer paddles along nervously, watching the names change,
reassessing brand loyalties, and wondering who will be next.
</P>
<P>
   Exxon announces it will buy Mobil to create the biggest company
on earth and also creates a moral dilemma for anyone who has
boycotted the former since the Valdez oil spill. Should people
happily doing business at the neighborhood Mobil vote with their
gas tanks?
</P>
<P>
   Daimler-Benz buys Chrysler, and drivers who have stuck with the
car since former chairman Lee Iacocca's personality sold it are no
longer sure what buying American means.
</P>
<P>
   Executives focused on the global economy forget that individuals
take purchasing personally. Stores, products, and workers become
interwoven with people's lives. A department store seems like a
member of the family when people buy everything from baby blankets
to wedding suits there. A restaurant becomes ``our place.''
</P>
<P>
   Even a bank, now mostly a mechanical transaction, is the loan
officer who made the first mortgage easy or the manager who
straightened out the checking account. A consumer wants continuity
with these people, wants to know they will always be there running
interference with the bureaucracy.
</P>
<P>
   Given the galloping takeover trend, a person begins to think
that soon there will be one big corporation in charge of the
universe _ Amalgamated Consolidated Interplanetary Unlimited. Even
the bosses could merge into one great megapersonality known as
``Ted Rupert Gates.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever we buy, wherever we work, however swiftly we paddle,
the company will be there with nothing to gulp but itself. Perhaps
that is how the world will end _ not with a bang but a munch.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-18-99 2107EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990118.0399 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 21:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8219 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EXCLUSIVE-LASER-BREAK     01-18 1170
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXCLUSIVE-LASER-BREAKTHROUGH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAPANESE INVENTOR WINS HIGH-TECH RACE WITH LASER BREAKTHROUGH
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., N.C.)  (EXCLUSIVE; 10:45 p.m. ET EMBARGO for print media; 12:01 a.m. ET
EMBARGO for electronic media.) 
(nk) 
 By JOHN MARKOFF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A lone Japanese inventor has outrun some of the world's largest
and most advanced high-technology corporations in the race to
develop a new generation of short-wavelength lasers. The
achievement is likely to hasten the introduction of high-definition
digital video disks, higher-resolution laser printing and
inexpensive and highly efficient light bulbs for use in the home.
</P>
<P>
   The inventor, Shuji Nakamura, is a semiconductor researcher who
has worked for more than a decade in relative isolation and has
excelled in finding innovations in material science. Last week his
small company, Nichia Chemical Industries, announced that it had
begun shipping samples of violet lasers to a variety of companies
planning to develop prototype products. The lasers have a life span
of 10,000 hours, the level of reliability required by consumer
electronics companies.
</P>
<P>
   Such short-wavelength lasers, in the blue and violet part of the
spectrum, have been pursued for years by companies including U.S.
and Japanese giants like 3M, Hewlett Packard, Sony and Toshiba. In
digital storage such an advance is particularly impressive because
each time the wavelength of laser light is halved, the beam can
then store four times more data.
</P>
<P>
   That the race has so far gone to Nichia (nih-KEY-uh) is a payoff
for its long-term investment in pursuing this technology, which
many corporations deemed a high risk.
</P>
<P>
   But it may also indicate how Japanese and U.S. companies have
reversed roles in recent years. Officials of U.S. companies said
Monday that they still thought they could win the race to
incorporate the technology into products and bring them to market
first. From the 1950s through the 1970s Japanese companies
successfully commercialized technologies invented in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   The next barrier will be reducing the cost of producing the
lasers and devising technical standards that will provide
compatibility with existing applications.
</P>
<P>
   Nakamura first burst onto the scientific stage in November 1993
when Nichia announced that he had succeeded in fabricating a bright
blue light-emitting diode, another kind of widely used light
source.
</P>
<P>
   His advance came just two years after IBM decided to scale back
its effort in laser research, partly in the belief that the market
would not be large enough in the near future. Monday, IBM
researchers said they were impressed by the Nichia achievement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd call it a piece of technical work that is absoutely
remarkable, and it stands on its own,'' said Bill Lenth, manager of
science and technology at the IBM Almaden research laboratory in
San Jose, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   But other American competitors said the international race to
commercialize the technology was still in progress and refused to
concede. And further breakthroughs in short-wavelength lasers _
such as blue lasers, which could lead to higher-resolution computer
displays _ have yet to be achieved.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's really a leader in this field,'' said Waguih Ishak,
director of Hewlett Packard's Communications and Optics Research
Laboratory in Palo Alto, Calif. ``We still see that Nakamura is
ahead of us. He's ahead, but it's a marathon and we've just
started.''
</P>
<P>
   Hewlett Packard ramped up its multimillion-dollar research
program in lasers and light-emitting diodes (LED's) shortly after
Nakamura's breakthrough in 1993. Ishak said the company had now
caught up with him in the LED market, and he said he was pushing
hard to catch Nichia in the laser race.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is something I can't fail in,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The commercial application of the new lasers is expected to have
substantial impact. For example, they will make possible
high-definition digital video disks, or HD DVD's, a step beyond the
current digital video disks. The new compact disk-size platters
will deliver HDTV-quality movies, concerts and stage presentations.
In addition, music publishers could publish entire anthologies on a
single HD DVD, carrying more than a dozen hours of music on each
side.
</P>
<P>
   Besides DVD applications, Nakamura said by e-mail that the
violet semiconductor lasers would enable a new generation of
digital tape recorders that will be similar to today's VCR machines
but able to store high-definition video images.
</P>
<P>
   While the most sought-after commercial applications for
short-wavelength lasers are in the area of digital storage, there
are a wide range of other practical uses, ranging from laser
printers with twice as much resolution as today's best-quality
products to a new class of household lighting that could be two to
10 times more energy efficient than today's fluorescent and
incandescent light bulbs.
</P>
<P>
   The Nichia researcher's breakthrough came from exploring an
unusual class of materials known as gallium nitrides. Other
companies had previously tried to use other matierals to construct
blue semiconductor lasers.
</P>
<P>
   ``He took an unorthodox, high-risk route, and he won,'' said
Richard Doherty, president of Envisioneering of Seaford, N.Y., a
computer and consumer electronics industry consulting concern.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to near-term digital storage applications, Doherty
and other researchers said that inexpensive short-length lasers
might make possible such futuristic technologies as optical
computers, laser-based computer or television displays and a new
generation of optical fiber communications systems or even
ultra-high-speed laser optical communications sent directly through
the air rather than by fiber optic wires.
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Blue Laser Diode,'' a book about his technology
published in 1997, Nakamura wrote that the chairman of Nichia,
Nobuo Ogawa, originally invested $3.3 million in the laser diode
project, or about 1.5 percent of the company's sales that year. The
amount is much higher than what companies usually invest in the
work of a single researcher.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the widespread acclaim for Nakamura's breakthrough,
executives of one small American company that is a close competitor
of Nichia predicted that they would still win the race to
commercialization.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there are still huge questions to be answered about
pricing and volume production,'' said Neal Hunter, chief executive
of the company, Cree Research Inc. of Durham, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   In the race to build inexpensive LED's, Nichia was first to
market, but others ultimately managed to produce them more cheaply,
he argued, saying that the same economics might hold true in the
semiconductor laser race.
</P>
<P>
   Cree is gambling on a technology using silicon carbide, rather
than gallium nitride, and Hunter said the company believed that it
would make products easier to manufacture and afford better heat
dissipation _ properties that will be crucial in low-cost
applications.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
