<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-CANDIDATES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW TO ENCOURAGE CANDIDATES? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Each week now, another potential candidate for president signs
up for next year's election _ or signs off. The number choosing not
to run is worrisome and calls for action on two fronts.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans seem determined to field a good number of candidates
in 2000. Still, former candidate Jack Kemp and Senators John
Ashbrook and Fred Thompson have indicated that they will pass up
the honor. The Democratic field, meanwhile, is alarmingly thin.
Senators Bob Kerrey and Paul Wellstone abandoned campaign
preparations recently, and the House minority leader, Richard
Gephardt, is looking toward an extended career in the House _ he
would likely be speaker if the Democrats take back the majority
next year.
</P>
<P>
   But many of those choosing not to run have no comparable
rationale. The forces working to deter them are neither sensible
nor healthy.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest and most obvious is money. The very idea that the
presidential campaign carries an admission price of $20 million to
$30 million should be abhorrent to all Americans. The Supreme Court
outlawed the disgraceful poll tax for voters in 1966. But there is
now a frightening bar for candidates, who must raise $60,000 a day
every day for the next year if they want to remain competitive.
This limits the choice offered to voters, many of whom are
understandably turned off to the whole system.
</P>
<P>
   Next year's primary and caucus calendar has added another
serious impediment. With California and other large states seeking
early primary dates to augment their clout, it is likely that the
nominees of both parties will be decided in early March. This
schedule heavily favors the well-known and the wealthy.
</P>
<P>
   Remedies for these problems are far easier to identify than to
implement. Campaign finance reform needs a Congress with less
self-interest. A better primary calendar needs states that will put
the nation's well-being above their own.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
