A8221 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-KING-ART-NYT     01-18 0858
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-KING-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EFFORTS OF PAST AND PRESENT MIX FOR CLINTON AT KING DAY EVENT
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Md., Texas)  (See also NY-KING) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By JAMES BENNET   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ For President Clinton, the event Monday offered an
apparently seamless blend of symbolism and substance, just the
right formula to commemorate Dr. Martin Luther King Jr.'s life.
</P>
<P>
   At a retirement home here, the president helped knock down a
wall to make room for a health clinic. Then he announced what he
called ``the largest settlement in history'' of a case involving
lending discrimination in housing _ $6.5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   But while the wall fell without much fuss, the mortgage company
accused of discrimination fought back furiously, declaring that it
had admitted no wrongdoing and had committed no more money than it
would have otherwise to help minority and low-to-moderate income
borrowers.
</P>
<P>
   Still dressed in his blue jeans and invigorated by his volunteer
work, Clinton noted at the Regency House retirement home that
Congress passed the Fair Housing Act, outlawing housing
discrimination, just six days after King was killed.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had worked for years to outlaw discrimination in housing,''
Clinton said. ``And many who voted for the measure said they did it
in tribute to him.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that under the agreement, ``the Columbia National
Mortgage Co. will offer _ listen to this _ $6.5 billion in home
mortgages and extra effort to help 78,000 minority and low and
moderate income families unlock the door to homeownership.''
</P>
<P>
   But David Gallitano, the chairman and chief executive of
Columbia National, said he was shocked by any suggestion his
company had discriminated and was taking dramatic steps to reform
its ways.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure he was very poorly informed,'' he said of the
president. The agreement was reached between the company, based in
Columbia, Md., and the Department of Housing and Urban Development.
Housing department officials said the company signed the agreement
in November, and that the department signed it Friday. But it was
not disclosed until Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``All we did with HUD's concurrence was to take what we had done
over the last five years and reaffirm that it was what we would do
over the next five years,'' Gallitano said in a telephone
interview. ``This might all make good press on Martin Luther King
Day, but it sure as hell is taking a club to our heads when we
haven't done anything wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   But a HUD official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
that Columbia had committed to new spending. ``To make the point
even clearer, in 1997, Columbia nationally made $1.4 billion in
loans'' to all borrowers, the official said. ``It is committing
almost the same amount over five years for low and moderate income
loans and other related benefits alone.''
</P>
<P>
   But Gallitano said that the agreement specifies only that
Columbia must make such funds ``available'' to qualified minority
and low-income buyers _ as step, he said, that regulations already
demand.
</P>
<P>
   Under the direction of Secretary Andrew Cuomo, HUD over the last
two years has stepped up enforcement of the anti-discrimination
law. As a result, Cuomo said, more people are becoming aware of the
law, and complaints are rising. But companies, he said, are also
taking more steps to comply.
</P>
<P>
   ``I firmly believe we'll never be able to come together as a
nation if we can't live together as a people,'' Cuomo said.
</P>
<P>
   He said that at Columbia, ``there were very few loans to
minorities and that was across the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Gallitano called that statement ``grossly inaccurate.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have prided ourselves on our lending practices and we
preach _ and when I say preach I mean preach _ that we are in
business to serve the community,'' he said. ``ALL the community.''
</P>
<P>
   Each side supplied sharply different statistics, to support its
view.
</P>
<P>
   A HUD official said that in 1997, the last year for which
full-year numbers were available, Columbia made a total of $51.6
million in loans to low-and-moderate income borrowers _ just five
percent of its total volume.
</P>
<P>
   But Gallitano called that statistic ``grossly in error.'' He
said that the company, blindsided by the announcement, was
scrambling to analyze its data, and would not have it ready until
Tuesday. But he said that in Texas, the source of the complaint
that led to the agreement announced Monday, 36 percent of the
company's loans in 1997 were to minorities.
</P>
<P>
   At the retirement home, Clinton did not get into such details.
He seemed to prefer to talk about his renovation work, which he did
alongside Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``It did the vice president and me a lot of good to pick up
those hammers and crow bars and tear something down,'' he said.
``You know, we do this desk work all the time and we do this word
work all the time, and there's not always a beginning, a middle and
an end. There was a beginning to that wall, a middle and it is no
longer, it is over.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
