<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-GUNS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MISTARGETING GUN MAKERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Flush from victory against the tobacco industry, cities and
states across the country &UR;  &LR; are contemplating, or have initiated,
lawsuits against gun manufacturers, attempting to hold them
responsible for gun deaths and thereby achieving gun control
through litigation instead of legislation. This is a mistake.
</P>
<P>
   We are firmly in favor of strict gun control and keeping guns
off the street. Yet using the courts in this way abuses the legal
system and derogates the legislative process.
</P>
<P>
   A federal court in New York is hearing a case in which the
families of seven shooting victims are suing major gun
manufacturers, including Colt of Connecticut and Smith &AMP; Wesson of
Springfield.
</P>
<P>
   The plaintiffs' argument is that their youngsters died because
criminals have such easy access to weapons. They claim that the gun
manufacturers are negligently marketing and distributing their
wares.
</P>
<P>
   In six of the seven cases, no guns were found, so it is not even
certain that US-manufactured guns were involved.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike tobacco, if a gun is used the way it is supposed to be by
law and design, it is not harmful to the user. If the product is
being used by criminals or children, that is a matter for parents
and police, not the manufacturers. If the law allows too free a
distribution of guns, that is a matter for legislators and
regulators, who should not so easily avoid their responsibilities.
To blame the manufacturers for gun deaths is the same as suggesting
in a hit-and-run accident that Ford or General Motors or Mercedes
be made responsible, attorney David Gross told National Public
Radio.
</P>
<P>
   More important, ours is a country that is rapidly turning itself
over to rule by lawsuit. Political debate is abandoned in favor of
litigation. The courts are burdened with every social ill because
we cannot agree on the rules we should live by. Suing the gun
manufacturers to get guns off the street is bad law and bad social
policy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
