<SLUG> BC-GEN-MEDIA-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOSE OF ONE-ON-ONE IS NICE SPORTS-TALK FIX
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
((This the first in an annual four-part series on the best and
worst of Los Angeles' sports media. Today: The sports-talk radio
hosts.))
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Given the choice, do you take generic over
name-brand at the pharmacy?
</P>
<P>
   Why not, as long as it does the job.
</P>
<P>
   If radio sports-talk can be considered an addictive drug, the
generic brand in Los Angeles these days might be the one that
doesn't cause drowsiness.
</P>
<P>
   Going up against what's considered the established two
Jacor-owned stations for sports-talk listeners, the Los Angeles
branch of Chicago-based One-on-One Sports on KCTD-AM (1540) has
become the alternative choice of medication for several reasons.
</P>
<P>
   __ The melting pot of sports fans in the L.A. market who aren't
necessarily tied to local teams have found this as an outlet to
call in and talk about !ital!their teams.
</P>
<P>
   __ Those who've given up on locally produced shows have had this
spot on the dial since October '97. Some are finally finding out
its value.
</P>
<P>
   In essence, One-on-One is going one-on-two against KXTA-AM
(1150) and XTRA-AM (690) here. From a business proposition _ trying
to lure the 25-to-54 male demographic with cutting-edge programming
and a 50,000-watt signal at a minimal cost _ the station makes
sense. Now the question is whether L.A. will pick up on the
content.
</P>
<P>
   Based on Arbitron ratings, to which One-on-One does not
subscribe, the playing field here is pretty level. So why not go
for it?
</P>
<P>
   ``This has proven to be the most economical way to do radio
here,'' said KCTD station manager Bob Bordonaro, who has run
stations in adult-contemporary, jazz and general talk before
getting into sports. ``This lineup is solid. The next step is to
get people to listen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our angle is we don't have to be sweet to the Dodgers because
we're not their flagship. We can tell it like it is.''
</P>
<P>
   The challenge for the One-on-One staff in L.A. _ a five-person
operation working out of an office in Burbank _ is to be seen to
get heard. Distinctive orange-and-black billboards went up
immediately when the station started here.
</P>
<P>
   Marketing director Chuck Hayes, who knows about the difficulty
of making inroads in L.A. after working for the former
SportsChannel L.A. premium cable station, has been showing up at
L.A. events _ from pro to high school _ to give out prizes and be
noticed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sports-talk listener in L.A. is intelligent, opinionated,
loyal as the day is long, and they're not fickle,'' said Hayes.
``We want to serve those people. We don't undervalue the Angelenos.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been really exciting to see the attention we've received
around the city the last two months.''
</P>
<P>
   The One-on-One Sports network began with 75 stations when it
purchased the Sports Entertainment Network out of Las Vegas in
1993. From 1997-98, One-on-One established beachheads in L.A., New
York, Boston and Chicago by buying stations. It has grown to more
than 400 affiliates in almost every major market as well as
maintaining a useful Web site (http://1on1sports.com).
</P>
<P>
   So maybe you won't run into hosts like John Renshaw, Peter
Brown, ``Papa'' Joe Chevalier and Arnie Spanier out at the Forum or
Dodger Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   But the One-on-One lineup know its stuff. Just listen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get more and more calls from Los Angeles all the time,''
said Chevalier, on from 3 to 7 p.m. in L.A. ``I think it's because
we're a refreshing alternative to local sports talk. L.A. and New
York are such cosmopolitan areas. And some days you have to battle
the Dodger talk, but at the same time, he have a national
perspective if Rupert Murdoch does something.''
</P>
<P>
   Bordonaro's statistics show that 15,000 to 20,000 calls a month
to the nationwide shows come from the station's Southern California
region, which stretches from Santa Barbara to San Clemente and as
far east as San Bernardino County.
</P>
<P>
   The closest affiliate to Los Angeles is Palm Springs' KNWZ-AM
(1270) and there is none yet in San Diego or San Francisco, so KCTD
has juice in these parts.
</P>
<P>
   Because of KCTD's signal strength, USC has used it as an
affiliate for its football and basketball broadcasts usually heard
on XTRA-AM (690) out of San Diego that has problems reaching parts
of L.A. and the San Fernando Valley.
</P>
<P>
   KCTD has recently signed the Long Beach Ice Dogs for a package
of games and could be doing the Los Angeles Marathon radio
coverage. It will also likely carry other L.A. teams that have
scheduling conflicts with their flagship stations.
</P>
<P>
   Collecting the broadcasting rights to L.A. teams isn't part of
the strategy, Bordonaro says, because research shows they don't
make as big a ratings impact as they used to in this market.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, Bordonaro envisions KCTD airing a locally produced
show _ Joe McDonnell? He's been asked. But management is kind of
partial to the national focus it has got going at this point.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things we say around the office is, `Why do we need
an extra XTRA?' '' Bordonaro said. &QL; 
RADIO SPORTS-TALK HOSTS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE TOP 10 &QL; 
__ 1. Vacant. Would have been Joe McDonnell for a four-peat, but
AM-1150 found him replaceable. Could have been Steve Edwards, but
AM-1150 found itself unable to pay him enough after a recent
tryout. Woulda, coulda . . let's just skip it. &QL; 
__ 2. (tie) John Ireland and Derrick Hall, AM-1150 weekday
mornings: Ireland's energy and Hall's sense of humor (a nice change
from the abrupt wake-up call that Steve Mason used to deliver) make
this a can't-lose combo. Thanks to Ireland for not bailing out at
the end of '98 and to Hall for taking the plunge into the exciting
world of radio after giving up his cushy day job shoveling Dodgers
propaganda. &QL; 
__ 4. Newy Scruggs, AM-1150 weekday afternoons: He works it nonstop
from the TV and radio end with an in to many athletes who matter. A
logical choice for the station based on his fill-in work for Jim
Rome. &QL; 
__ 5. Ross Porter, AM-1150 Dodgers talk: Last year put him through
the royal-blue test, and his commentaries, especially the
year-ender, pulled no punches. Longevity has its benefits. &QL; 
__ 6. Steve Hartman, XTRA-AM (690) weekday afternoons: You don't
realize how strong he is until you understand it's because he has
to carry his partner on his back three hours a day. &QL; 
__ 7. Brian Golden, KAVL-AM (610) weekday mornings: Gotta admit,
the switch to 4-to-6 a.m. doesn't give him much exposure, but he's
able to pull it off. &QL; 
__ 8. Irv Kaze, KIEV-AM (670) Friday evenings: Week in and week
out, the guests are top-notch. He's on Saturday mornings (11
a.m.-to-noon) the next few weeks. &QL; 
__ 9. (tie) Ben Maller and Dave Smith, AM-1150 weekday afternoons:
For a coupla going-nowhere buffoons, they'll grow on you.
Eventually. It is hoped. &QL; 
__ Honorable mention: Ron Kovack, AM-1150 weekend fishing show;
Chick Hearn, KLAC-AM (570) Lakers talk; Ira Fistel, KRLA-AM (1110)
overnights (back on the air to arbitrate Ted Williams-vs.-Joe
DiMaggio debates); Jeff Biggs, AM-1150 fill-in; Chris Elho, XTRA
fill-in (still doesn't get enough work), Steve Kim, AM-1150 fill-in
(what happened to the boxing show?); Sean Salisbury and John
Fricke, XTRA weekday mornings. &QL; 
__ Special recognition: Jimmy ``The Sports Guy'' Kimmel, KROQ-FM
(106.7) morning sports reports. &QL; 
SYNDICATED ALTERNATIVES &QL; 
__ 1. Jim Rome, AM-1150 and XTRA-AM (690) weekday midmornings:
``The Jungle'' has spawned a Rome CD and boosted the career of
comedian Jay Mohr. Rome's star, somehow, keeps ablazin'. &QL; 
__ 2. Peter Brown, KCTD-AM (1540) weekday afternoons: It's the
attitude paired with knowing what he's talking about that sells
it. &QL; 
__ 3. Scott Ferrall, AM-1150 weeknights: He's slowed down a bit _
and finally we're able to figure out what he's saying. &QL; 
__ 4. John Renshaw, KCTD-AM (1540) weekday mornings: Loud,
obnoxious and endearing. &QL; 
__ 5. Bob Berger and Bruce Murray, KCTD-AM (1540) weekends: During
NFL season, their whip-around-the-stadiums show is remarkable.
</P>
<P>
   THE BOTTOM FIVE &QL; 
__ 1. Lee Hamilton, XTRA-AM (690) weekday afternoons: If you're not
part of the nitwit-protection program, why not just use your real
name and get over your phony self? &QL; 
__ 2. Bill Werndl, XTRA-AM (690) weekday afternoons: We've had our
fill of ``Phillie Billy'' and we're fed up. &QL; 
__ 3. Geoff Witcher, AM-1150 Dodger talk: Has already reached the
zenith of a mediocre run. &QL; 
__ 4. Dave Denholm, AM-1150 weekday afternoons: Soon as you're
through being star struck, let us know. &QL; 
__ 5. John ``The Coach'' Kentera, XTRA-AM (690) weeknights: His
radio career continues to defy logic. &QL; 
__ Horrible mention: Vic ``The Brick'' Jacobs and Karl Malone, for
their three-month abuse of the airwaves during the NBA lockout.
Jacobs, the Melrose Larry Green of radio, has been relegated to
updates; Malone has his old job back. Let this be a lesson to any
out-of-touch, publicity-seeking program director: Don't add to the
brain rot that can be sports-talk radio. &QL; 
