<HEADER>
A8229 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOP-EDUCATION-NYT &LR;      01-18 1099
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-EDUCATION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDUCATION PROPOSAL DRAWS MIXED REACTION FROM GOP  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By ETHAN BRONNER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   President Clinton's proposal to use federal education funds to
hold public schools accountable drew a mixed reaction from
Republicans and educators Monday. While almost all said they shared
his goals, some opposed his means: the increased role of the
federal government in local schools.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal, expected to be prominent in Clinton's State of the
Union speech Tuesday night, would financially reward school
districts that adhere to federal guidelines that will be drafted on
the training of teachers, enforcing of classroom discipline and the
ending of the promotion of unqualified students, and financially
penalize schools that fail to meet the guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   Accountability has become the focus of many politicians and
educators who favor increasing funding to schools that produce
results. But the president is likely to run into strong opposition
from many Republicans who argue that the federal government should
leave these matters to the states and local school districts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president has proposed a national school board,'' charged
Lamar Alexander, the former education secretary and Tennessee
governor, who is expected to seek the Republican presidential
nomination in 2000. ``But we should go exactly in the opposite
direction, liberating the schools, not regulating them. We should
send the money to the parents and let them choose where their
children attend school.''
</P>
<P>
   Linda Chavez, president of the conservative Center for Equal
Opportunity and a former senior official in the Reagan
administration, disagreed. She said it was a fine idea to tie
accountability to funding since currently it is generally the
schools that fail that receive more aid, not those that succeed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to see success rewarded and I say that as long as there
are federal dollars going in to the school system, keeping it
accountable is a good idea,'' she said. ``I don't see any point in
being overly ideological on this question of local control. I would
urge Republicans to do what they did with welfare control _ seize
on it and take it further.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Clinton failed to persuade Congress to authorize
uniform testing of fourth and eighth graders and win money for
fixing up schools in disrepair, in both cases because Republicans
argued these should be handled locally. On the other hand, they
agreed on a plan to spend $1 billion to help local districts hire
100,000 more teachers by compromising on how the money would be
distributed.
</P>
<P>
   Federal aid to education is quite limited, amounting to some 7
percent of overall spending on schools. It comes largely through
the Elementary and Secondary Education Act, first passed in 1965
and due to come up for renewal this year. It is likely to be a
contentious debate. Some $8 billion is disbursed to poor schools
through the act and conservatives have expressed doubts about the
effectiveness of the program.
</P>
<P>
   Like Alexander, some conservatives have been arguing that the
public school system needs to be drastically altered through the
introduction of charter schools and the use of vouchers, which give
public funds to parents who can use them to send them children to
private schools if they wish.
</P>
<P>
   Adam Urbanski, president of the Rochester Teachers Association
and a vice president of the American Federation of Teachers, said
Clinton's proposal, which he enthusiastically supports, was an
effort to combat the growing voucher and charter movements by
improving all public schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vouchers and charters are most likely to thrive when there is
no accountability, when there is no way to determine whether public
schools are succeeding,'' he said. ``President Clinton is sending
the message that public schools are salvageable. The best way to
restore confidence in public schools is to get better results in
public schools. And that comes about through tough love.''
</P>
<P>
   The president's proposal calls for schools to meet several
criteria or lose their grants under the federal aid program:
</P>
<P>
   _ Schools would have to end what is called ``social promotion,''
or moving pupils to the next grade irrespective of their
performance;
</P>
<P>
   _ Schools would have to increase the quality of teachers by
insisting on ongoing training for experienced teachers and high
scores on tests for new ones;
</P>
<P>
   _ States would have to identify low performing schools, work to
improve them through teacher training and focus on discipline and,
if all else fails, deprive them of funds;
</P>
<P>
   _ States would have to distribute to all parents annual report
cards for each school and school district;
</P>
<P>
   _ Schools would have to adopt tough discipline policies such as
uniforms, enforcing truancy laws and imposing curfews.
</P>
<P>
   A number of states have already adopted some or all of these
approaches and the president's advisors say his plan aims to
complement and enforce their efforts rather than supplant them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're saying that states and school districts must be
accountable in helping all students reach high standards,''
Secretary of Education Richard Riley told journalists at a
Washington briefing Monday. ``It's really a way to help states and
school districts see that that's done.''
</P>
<P>
   Marc Tucker, president of the National Center on Education and
the Economy, which has been a strong advocate of national
standards, said it seemed to him that the argument over local
control had little meaning as long as the federal government is
spending money.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as the federal government is providing billions of
dollars to schools, taxpayers will reasonably ask what they are
getting for their money,'' he said. ``This should be a proposal
that Republicans who are so interested in results can embrace.''
</P>
<P>
   But Charles Glenn, a professor of education policy at Boston
University who for 21 years directed urban education for the state
of Massachusetts, said there was good reason to be concerned about
more federal regulations on local schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sounds like a terrific idea but unanticipated consequences
crop up,'' he said. ``I consider federal funds to be an awkward
instrument for these policies. This will tie the hands of folks at
the local level.''
</P>
<P>
   Chester E. Finn, Jr., an assistant secretary of education under
President Reagan, said he did not see how the federal government
could ``micromanage 15,000 school districts. The test of this
debate will be to see whether Republicans have a better idea how to
do this.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
