u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INTERNET-HIGHSPEED-NY     01-18 0637
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-HIGHSPEED-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERNET PROVIDER PLANS SERVICE FOR HIGH-SPEED WEB USERS
</HEADLINE>
 (bl) 
By STEVE LOHR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Snap, an Internet provider partly owned by NBC, has developed a
service that is tailored for the small but growing number of users
who have high-speed connections to the World Wide Web. An
announcement is expected Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The high-speed service, called Cyclone, has lined up partners
including telecommunications carriers like Bell Atlantic, GTE and
SBC Communications and online programmers offering a variety of
information on travel, personal finance and entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   High-speed connections promise television-style video and
high-fidelity audio over the Internet, but fast communications
links have so far been expensive and scarce, confined mainly to
corporate users. At the end of last year, roughly 500,000
households had high-speed cyberspace connections using cable modems
or the telephone technology known as asymmetric digital subscriber
lines, or ADSL.
</P>
<P>
   Snap is now an also-ran among the so-called Web portals that
offer everything from search functions to e-mail to a wide range of
online programming. Yet though it trails well behind America
Online, Yahoo, MSN, Netscape and Excite, Snap has tripled its reach
since NBC, a unit of General Electric Co., bought a 19 percent
stake last June from Snap's parent company, Cnet Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Snap has forged close relations with some major phone companies,
and it is hoping to get a lift as the phone companies increasingly
offer customers connections 50 to 200 times as fast as is possible
using conventional phone lines. In the industry, high-speed links
are often called broadband.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're making a heavy commitment to broadband because we think
this is the year broadband becomes real,'' said Cnet chief
executive Halsey Minor. ``We want to be there first.''
</P>
<P>
   All the major Web portals are working on developing high-speed
services, which are expected to be offered this year. But analysts
say that Snap's Cyclone, which plans to begin this quarter, is an
early stake in the high-speed niche of the Internet service market.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, America Online announced an agreement with Bell
Atlantic for offering high-speed connections to Bell Atlantic's
online subscribers for an additional $20 a month. High-speed access
typically costs an extra $40 or so a month.
</P>
<P>
   By 2000, about 2 million of the nation's 100 million households
will have high-speed connections, according to projections by
Forrester Research Inc. ``As a mass market offering, broadband is
still on the fairly distant horizon,'' said Kate Delhagen, an
analyst at Forrester. ``But things like the America Online
announcement could speed up the adoption rate.''
</P>
<P>
   Howard Anderson, managing director of the Yankee Group,
estimates that it may take five years to enroll 8 million American
households in the use of high-speed services. ``But afterward,
usage will really jump quickly,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   The big regional phone companies have ambitious plans for
offering households high-speed connections. SBC, for example, plans
to offer high-speed service to 8.2 million residential customers,
mainly in the Southwest, by the end of this year. Bell Atlantic,
the local phone company in New England and the mid-Atlantic states,
says its high-speed service should be available to 7.5 million
homes by the end of this year and reach 14 million by the end of
2000.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the most common benefit of high-speed access is not
having to wait so long for Web pages to appear. But with a service
tailored for high-speed users like Snap's Cyclone, Minor said that
consumers could get such things as video clips of travel
destinations or video previews of an evening's television programs,
delivered over the Internet.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-18-99 2122EST &QL; 
