<DOCNO> NYT19990118.0409 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 21:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8233 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-DIMAGGIO-NYT &LR;      01-18 0388
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-DIMAGGIO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIMAGGIO LEAVES HOSPITAL FOR HOME
</HEADLINE>
   (ms) 
 By BARBARA STEWART   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   After 99 days in a South Florida hospital and numerous
predictions of his hopeless condition and impending death, Joe
DiMaggio went home Monday. Since entering the hospital in Hollywood
on Oct. 12, he has undergone lung cancer surgery, nearly succumbed
to infectious pneumonia four times, received last rites, had a Do
Not Resuscitate order posted on his bed and awakened from a coma.
</P>
<P>
   George Steinbrenner, hearing of the unexpected recovery, said he
was hoping to watch DiMaggio at Yankee Stadium, throwing the first
ball of the 1999 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joe's recovery, together with my reconciliation with Yogi
Berra, are great news,'' Steinbrenner said. ``Personally, for me,
and for the New York Yankee fans, this is a great moment in Yankee
history.''
</P>
<P>
   Morris Engelberg, the player's lawyer and confidant, said
DiMaggio was also looking forward to throwing out the first ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe it won't happen,'' Engelberg said. ``But I want to
try.''
</P>
<P>
   DiMaggio, 84, barely skirted death several times during his stay
at Memorial Regional Hospital in Hollywood, Fla. Engelberg gave the
credit for the recovery to Dr. Earl Barron, who administered the
antibiotic Refampin intravenously. The doctor gave the credit to
Dr. Nelson Zyde, an infectious disease specialist, who suggested
the drug be administered intravenously, allowing it to be absorbed
into the bloodstream.
</P>
<P>
   ``He saved his life,'' Engelberg said of Barron. ``Joe was dead
on Dec. 11. I had my plane tickets to his funeral. He brought him
back.''
</P>
<P>
   DiMaggio is considered heroic by both baseball fans and many not
in the world of baseball. He hit in a record 56 consecutive games
during his career, and in 1969 was voted the greatest living
player. Among those too young or too uninterested in sports to know
about his playing, he is widely seen at a rare example of honesty
and decency.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Nachio, DiMaggio's friend for 56 years, who has been in
Florida for the last two weeks visiting him, said DiMaggio was
still in a delicate condition. His doctors felt the move to his
home near Fort Lauderdale would ``boost his morale.'' But he will
need round-the-clock nursing care for the foreseeable future,
Nachio said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-18-99 2124EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990118.0410 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 21:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8234 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKW-UCONN-LATECH-NYT &LR;      01-18 0712
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-UCONN-LATECH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOUISIANA TECH EXTENDS CONNECTICUT'S MISERY
</HEADLINE>
   (ms) 
 By CHARLIE NOBLES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   RUSTON, La. _ Svetlana Abrosimova, star of the second-ranked
Connecticut women's basketball team, sat weeping at an interview
table afterward. Shea Ralph, the Huskies' junior guard, talked
about the team's urgent need to play as cohesively as it practices.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Geno Auriemma knew this trip would be instructive, but
even he might not have been ready for the fallout from
fourth-ranked Louisiana Tech's 90-74 victory over the Huskies
Monday before a crowd of 6,949 at the Thomas Assembly Center. It
was Connecticut's second loss in four games after a 13-0 start.
</P>
<P>
   Auriemma sought the game with Louisiana Tech, which, with three
national titles and nine Final Four appearances, is a staple of the
women's game. It was his version of tough love, wanting to toughen
his players for future playoff-caliber opponents. But in one way,
Auriemma did not learn much Monday. With three freshmen and a
sophomore in his starting lineup, he worried about his team's
immaturity. And he was still worrying afterward.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really are lacking that solid thinking that comes from
playing together a long time,'' he said. ``Like when it was 60-59,
nobody was saying, `Here's what we are going to run.'''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the Huskies were giving the Lady Techsters (14-2) all
they could handle until 11 minutes 8 seconds remained in the
nationally televised game. Abrosimova, who had a team-high 24
points, scored on a drive but missed the free throw that would have
tied the game, leaving the score at 60-59. Louisiana Tech _ which
has now won 57 of its last 58 home games _ reeled off the next 8
points and did not look back.
</P>
<P>
   Abrosimova committed two of her 10 turnovers during that
stretch. ``I make a lot of mistakes,'' she said. ``Two in a row,
three in a row, all easy layups. And I did not look for a screen on
my shots. I was trying to do things by myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Tears trickled down her cheeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not your fault,'' said Ralph, slapping Abrosimova's
thigh. ``We just didn't work together as a team. We have to start
playing more like we practice, and soon.''
</P>
<P>
   Louisiana Tech had centered a 25-year celebration of its program
around this weekend, and many former players attended Monday's
game. Venus Lacy, who most recently played for Nashville in the
ill-fated American Basketball League, was underneath one basket
shouting at Connecticut's players whenever they came within
earshot.
</P>
<P>
   Auriemma knew that many of his players were not accustomed to
facing such a talented opponent, but he said they had to see for
themselves what they could or could not do.
</P>
<P>
   On the bench during the game, Auriemma turned to his starting
point guard, the freshman Keirsten Walters, and said, ``You're
trying to be great before you become good.''
</P>
<P>
   Walters had been able to make long passes for easy layups
against most teams, but, as Auriemma said, ``She didn't have
Tamicha Jackson playing free safety.'' Louisiana Tech's Jackson
made five steals and contributed a game-high 26 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had the heart and the energy today,'' Tech Coach Leon
Barmore said. ``In our games before this, we'd have two playing and
three taking the night off. We haven't had it from start to finish
from all five players all season.''
</P>
<P>
   Auriemma, whose team missed 15 of 35 free throws, is hoping his
players become more coachable now.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of these players want to believe in themselves so much
that they won't listen,'' he said. ``That's one reason we
self-destruct at times. But now they know I'm right.''
</P>
<P>
   The Huskies had other problems.
</P>
<P>
   Forward Asjha Jones played just 14 minutes, because of foul
trouble and because Auriemma believed she had freshman jitters.
``She was out of it, hesitant,'' he said. ``You could tell by
looking at her.''
</P>
<P>
   Auriemma determined after the game that another starter, the
freshman Swin Cash, would no longer play until the stress fracture
of her right shin had healed. Cash started Monday, scoring just 3
points in 14 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's done until she's 100 percent ready to go,'' he said.
``It doesn't do anybody any good to play two minutes here and two
minutes there.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
