u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRAN-GERM-WARFARE-NYT     01-18 0317
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAN-GERM-WARFARE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIAN BIOLOGIST DENIES WORK IN IRAN ON GERM WEAPONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By JUDITH MILLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Russian biologist in Iran has denied conducting research that
could have helped the Soviet Union or Iran develop germ weapons.
</P>
<P>
   The biologist, Dr. Valery Bakayev, said in a brief telephone
interview that while he has worked at the Pasteur Institute in
Tehran for more than five years, his work has focused solely on the
civilian development of vaccines against diseases like tuberculosis
and on other nonmilitary research. He denied having worked in any
offensive germ warfare program for the Soviet Union or Iran.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times reported on Dec. 8 that the government of
Iran is seeking to recruit Russian scientists to help it develop
biological, nuclear and chemical weapons, and that Iran had hired
several scientists once associated with institutes that were part
of the Soviet Union's germ warfare program.
</P>
<P>
   The article mentioned Bakayev and Vladimir Rishinski as two
Russian scientists who had once worked for such institutes and who
are now conducting research in Iran. They could not be reached for
comment before the article was published.
</P>
<P>
   After the article appeared, Bakayev denied in an interview with
MSNBC any prior or current participation in the development of germ
weapons.
</P>
<P>
   He said he ``can firmly deny'' that any Russian scientists he
knows ``took part in any illegal activity related to germ warfare
production.''
</P>
<P>
   In the telephone interview, Bakayev said he could not elaborate
on his statement or provide more details about how he came to work
in Tehran.
</P>
<P>
   Both a senior defector from the Soviet Union's germ warfare
program and Western officials identified the institutes for which
Bakayev and Rishinski once worked as having been part of the Soviet
Union's germ warfare effort.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-18-99 2125EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990118.0412 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 21:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8237 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHOE-PRICEFIXING-NYT     01-18 0667
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOE-PRICEFIXING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUIT AGAINST NINE WEST ALLEGES FIXING PRICES OF SHOES
</HEADLINE>
 (bl) 
By MELODY PETERSEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A lawsuit has been filed on behalf of millions of
women who have purchased Nine West shoes at the nation's large
department stores, claiming that the giant footwear company
conspired with the stores to illegally fix prices.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit _ which seeks class-action status _ alleges that
since 1988, Nine West Group executives have met with managers from
the department stores to agree on the prices they would charge for
the company's 12 brands of shoes. Nine West and the stores have
then monitored each other, the lawsuit alleges, so that prices are
not lowered from those agreed upon.
</P>
<P>
   The result, according to the suit filed Wednesday by the New
York law firm of Abbey, Gardy &AMP; Squitieri in U.S. District Court in
White Plains, N.Y., is that women paid more for Nine West shoes
than they would have if the hundreds of department stores and Nine
West's own retail stores had competed on price.
</P>
<P>
   Nine West, based in White Plains, said that it did not believe
the lawsuit would significantly affect the company or its financial
results based on its ``existing policies relating to resale pricing
and the limited information available.''
</P>
<P>
   The company also said that at least two state attorneys general
were investigating its pricing policies. It did not disclose the
states. The company had earlier acknowledged that the Federal Trade
Commission was investigating its pricing practices.
</P>
<P>
   Joel Bedol, Nine West's general counsel, said Monday that the
company had no further comment.
</P>
<P>
   The department stores named in the lawsuit include Federated
Department Stores Inc., which owns Macy's, Bloomingdale's, and Bon
Marche; May Department Stores Co., which owns Lord &AMP; Taylor; Dayton
Hudson Corp., which owns Marshall Fields; Dillard's Inc.; and
Nordstrom Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Brooke White, a spokeswoman for Nordstrom, said that the company
would contest the suit. ``It is our policy to not have any
conversation about price or sale-date setting or other competitive
matters with any other retailers,'' Ms. White said. ``We play no
part in determining what vendor-suggested retail prices are.''
</P>
<P>
   Carol Sanger, a spokeswoman for Federated, said that the company
did not comment on pending litigation. ``We clearly, most
certainly, do not engage in price-fixing,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Spokesmen at both Dayton Hudson and May Department Stores said
the companies did not wish to comment on the lawsuit. Officials at
Dillard's could not be reached.
</P>
<P>
   Under federal antitrust laws, it is illegal for two or more
companies to agree on the minimum retail prices they will charge.
But several recent court decisions have weakened the law's
protections for consumers. For example, the courts have ruled that
it is not illegal for a distributor to demand that stores follow
its price list and then to cut off shipments to those stores that
do not comply.
</P>
<P>
   Nine West sells hundreds of millions of dollars of shoes to the
department stores each year. While it does not disclose sales to
each store, its 1997 annual report said Federated was its largest
wholesale customer, making up 12 percent of its net revenue, or
about $224 million.
</P>
<P>
   The company also sells shoes at its own retail stores and to
other independent shoe stores. In shopping malls around the
country, the small shoe stores are often located near the
department stores.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which says it sells one of every 5 pairs of shoes
that American women buy, offers 12 brands, including Easy Spirit,
Enzo Angiolini and Bandolino.
</P>
<P>
   According to the lawsuit, at least four times a year,
high-ranking representatives from the department stores meet with
Nine West's management in New York and agree on the minimum prices
they will charge. By the end of those meetings, the lawsuit claims,
Nine West and the department stores have agreed to a list of
minimum prices.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
