<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-SIGNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS NEAR PACT WITH WATSON AND SIGN NOMO
</HEADLINE>
   (ms) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Mets on Monday virtually completed a deal with
Allen Watson, a free-agent pitcher, and reached agreement with
Hideo Nomo, one of their six players who had filed for salary
arbitration. They announced the Nomo signing and were expected to
announce Watson's Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   A person with knowledge of the Watson negotiations said the Mets
and the left-hander agreed to a one-year contract with an $800,000
salary, part of it guaranteed, and a series of incentives that
could earn him a maximum of $1.75 million. Watson, 28, earned $2.9
million last year with the Anaheim Angels, who made him a free
agent last month when they did not tender him a contract. A starter
exclusively until last season, when he also relieved, Watson will
have to overwhelm the Mets in the spring to win a spot in a
rotation filled with Al Leiter, Rick Reed, Bobby Jones, Nomo and
Masato Yoshii.
</P>
<P>
   Thinking Nomo will be better because he will be fully recovered
from elbow surgery he had in October 1997, the Mets gave him a
$2,925,000 salary for 1999, a raise from $2.8 million last season. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
