Ginn, chief executive of Airtouch, left, jokes with Chris Gent,
head of Vodafone, during a news conference about their merger on
Monday. The agreement capped a two-week, trans-Atlantic bidding war
that started on word that New York-based Bell Atlantic and AirTouch
were close to a pact. (Jonathan Player/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) WAXAHACHIE, Texas -- Jan. 18, 1999 --
SCI-COLLIDER-DRUGS-B&AMP;W, 1-18 -- Part of the Superconducting
Supercollider is being used to produce radioactive pharmaceuticals.
The company which has undertaken the project, International
Isotopes Inc., says its operation will help free United States
hospitals from dependence on military and foreign sources of these
vital substances. (Jarrold Cabluck/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) UNDATED -- Jan. 18, 1999 -- SCI-MILK-HORMONES, 1-18 --
Skeptical of government assurances about the safety of milk, many
consumers are searching out products that pledge that they do not
use growth hormones or antibiotics. Farmland Dairies has been happy
to oblige. (Igor Vishnyakov/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) LOS ANGELES -- Jan. 18, 1999 -- SCI-OVERTRAINING, 1-18 --
Jill Farwell, working out last weekend in Los Angeles, could not
understand why her rowing performance declined with more exercise.
Overexercise was the answer. (Michael Tweed/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) LA JOLLA, Calif. -- Jan. 18, 1999 -- SCI-AIDS-THERAPY,
1-18 -- Dr. Inder Verma in in his lab at the Salk Institute.
Scientists like Verma are working on stripping the HIV virus of its
ability to cause AIDS while leaving intact its ability to infect
human cells in an effort to deliver genes into human cells for gene
therapy. (Robert Burroughs/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) LOS ANGELES -- Jan. 18, 1999 -- SCI-VITAL-SIGNS, 1-18 --
Forsaking the famed smog of Los Angeles, Dominique Manning and Cord
Coen visit a bar that served up whiffs of oxygen-rich air. Is it
healthful, merely refreshing, a fad or a placebo? If you use oxygen
for 20 minutes you will notice a change. Muscles become loosened,
headaches and stress seem to disappear. (Michael Tweed/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) UNDATED -- Jan. 18, 1999 -- SCI-BLOOD-MADCOW, 1-18 --
Beef is cleaned in a facility in southern England in 1996. A
scientific advisory panel is asking the Food and Drug
Administration to consider barring blood donations from people who
have lived in or visited Great Britain since 1980 because of
concerns about mad cow disease. (Jonathan Player/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) OXFORD, England -- Jan. 18, 1999 -- SCI-PENROSE, 1-18 --
At Oxford University, Sir Roger Penrose, mathematician and
physicist, holds forth on Einstein, the shape of the universe,
quantum theory and chess masters versus IBM. ``I think recent
evidence is pretty potent that black holes are there,'' he says.
``For a long time, the evidence was rather indirect. But you knew
there was an object out there that was too massive to be anything
else.'' (Jonathan Player/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) DENVER -- Jan. 18, 1999 -- FBN-JETS-BRONCOS, 1-17 -- New
York Jets head coach Bill Parcells leaves the field at Mile High
Stadium after his team was defeated by the Denver Broncos. The
Broncos rallied for 20 points in a 10-minute splurge after halftime
and defeated the Jets 23-10 to earn the trip to Super Bowl XXXIII
on Jan. 31. (Barton Silverman/New York Times Photo)
</P>
