<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 21:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8246 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-ST.JOHN-COACH-NYT     01-18 0763
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-ST.JOHN-COACH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JARVIS CALM ABOUT ST. JOHN'S TOUGH 10-DAY SCHEDULE
</HEADLINE>
   (ms) 
 By JUDY BATTISTA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ St. John's Coach Mike Jarvis was sounding serene
Monday, not at all like a coach about to take his team into a
10-day stretch that could either vault it into the stratosphere of
college basketball or send it plunging in the polls.
</P>
<P>
   The lineup is a sadistic schedule maker's dream: Wednesday at
Providence, the surprise of the Big East season at 12-5 over all
and 5-3 in the conference; Sunday, Duke, the nation's No. 2 team
with the country's most terrifying player, Elton Brand, in Madison
Square Garden; Jan. 27 at Syracuse, a top-20 team and the Big
East's best defensive squad, in the cacophonous Carrier Dome; and
Jan. 30, Connecticut, merely the No. 1 team in the country, with a
New York fan base so large that it nullifies the home-court
advantage St. John's has in their matchup at the Garden. If that
isn't enough, Miami, the only Big East team to beat the Red Storm
this season, will be at the Garden on Feb. 3.
</P>
<P>
   St. John's (15-3 and 6-1) is back in the top 10 this week and
playing, by Syracuse Coach Jim Boeheim's admission, much better
than anyone in the Big East expected. Barring a calamitous
collapse, the Red Storm is headed to March Madness, a soothing
tonic for any coach. But Jarvis sounds so calm, even as fans snap
up tickets for the Duke and Connecticut games, you wonder if he has
willfully misplaced his copy of the schedule.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's great we're in this position, where we're going
to go through a stretch with such diverse teams,'' Jarvis said.
``Those are the types of stretches that turn young men into men and
prepare you for the real deal, which is the Big East tournament and
the NCAA tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some will say the whole season hinges on these next two weeks.
That's totally ridiculous. Teams have gone through stretches like
this and won all the games and then got knocked out of the
tournament in the first round. You don't know what real effect
these games have on you until it's all over.''
</P>
<P>
   And, these games may be less of a barometer than what they
seemed even a week ago. With the senior forward Tyrone Grant's
sprained right wrist still swaddled in a soft cast _ he was to be
re-evaluated Monday after the wrist swelled over the weekend _ it
was difficult to make an accurate evaluation of how St. John's
compares with the elite teams in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Although Providence is small and quick with no true big men,
much like St. John's, the rest of the teams in the brutal schedule
have giants who are crucial to their teams. Duke's Brand, Syracuse
center Etan Thomas and Connecticut's Jake Voskuhl can all lord over
the paint, and if Grant is out or at best limited, St. John's will
have to get by on speed _ and some guile _ if it is to emerge with
at least a few victories.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to find teams' weaknesses and expose them,'' St.
John's forward Ron Artest said. ``We'd love to have Ty. But if we
play smart, we can still win the games. They might try to expose us
without Tyrone, but they've got to stop the other four of us.''
</P>
<P>
   Jarvis isn't particularly cowed by a lack of size, largely
because St. John's took Stanford, with its towering post players,
to the wire before losing by 2 points in November, when the
Cardinal was ranked No. 2. That near miss and a 1-point loss two
nights later to Purdue, then ranked No. 11, began the talk at St.
John's of a National Collegiate Athletic Association tournament
bid.
</P>
<P>
   The talk will explode into a roar if the Red Storm upsets one of
the coming behemoths. The outcome against Providence, Jarvis
figures, will have almost no impact on the mood of his team
entering the three big games. While he concedes that neither he nor
his players will be able to view Duke in quite the same way that
they anticipate, say, Rutgers, Jarvis is trying hard to maintain
the balance of a fine sailor, not letting the winds of the next few
games blow his ship either too high or low. Right now, St. John's
is as even-keeled as its coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not even thinking about going into the stretch,'' Jarvis
said. ``I'm thinking about a phase of the season. There are four
phases within a season: the preseason, the regular season, the
league tournament and the NCAA tournament. We're in the regular
season, and I'd give us a solid B. The professor would be pleased
with the progress. We're above average, I think. But B also isn't
good enough. You want to be better than above average.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
