<DOCNO> NYT19990118.0427 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 21:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8261 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-NBC-SFCHRON &LR;      01-18 1094
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-NBC-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NBC'S NEW ENTERTAINMENT CHIEF LEFT HOLDING THE BAG 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN CARMAN  
 c.1999, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. &LR;   &LR; _ Let's say you've just been given the keys
to a new car and the wheels fall off, the doors spring loose from
their hinges, the hood and trunk fly open, the radiator spews a
gusher and a dead weight drops onto the roof.
</P>
<P>
   You might know how it feels to be Scott Sassa, hired in October
as president of NBC Entertainment. Regrettably for him, lemon laws
don't apply to the television business.
</P>
<P>
   Sassa, a few weeks shy of his 40th birthday and the first Asian
American to rise so far in American television, is the front end of
an NBC executive switch.
</P>
<P>
   He replaced Warren Littlefield, but Sassa actually is in
training to take Don Ohlmeyer's job as NBC's West Coast president.
Garth Ancier, lately of WB notoriety, is expected to slide in under
Sassa as NBC's programming goat _ er, chief.
</P>
<P>
   Ohlmeyer is still around, but he seems to have burrowed into a
hole someplace in Burbank. Right now, Sassa is the only available
executive face on a deepening disaster created by his predecessors.
</P>
<P>
   Where to start? There was NBC's stunning largesse in agreeing to
pay $13 million an episode for ``ER,'' and in enriching Paul Reiser
and Helen Hunt to sustain the creatively exhausted and
ratings-impaired ``Mad About You.''
</P>
<P>
   There are the '98-'99 season-to-date ratings, which place NBC in
an aerial state known as free fall: a 15 percent decline in
prime-time ratings; a 20 percent decline among viewers in the key
18-to-49 demographic bracket; a full-scale break in the dam on
Tuesday nights, where NBC removed ``Frasier'' and recorded a 25
percent ratings drop; a scary 16 percent post-``Seinfeld'' ratings
tumble on Thursdays, the night that pays the mortgages at NBC.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, and the National Basketball Association lockout wounded the
league's broadcast partner, NBC. And Michael Jordan decided to
retire, taking with him any of the NBA's remaining television
luster. And the National Football League said adios to NBC. And now
there's an Olympics scandal _ guess who televises the next five
Olympics?
</P>
<P>
   Hard times are closing in on the dominant TV network of the
1980s and 1990s. The general reaction within this sweetly
sentimental industry is: Ha ha ha ha ha ha, couldn't happen to a
more arrogant bunch of SOBs.
</P>
<P>
   NBC has been the sole profitable TV network. To remain so, it's
been trying to horn in on the potential profits of its program
suppliers. You want to be on NBC? Then pay us tribute from your
``back end,'' post-network profits. Or take your shows someplace
else, like the filthy swine you are.
</P>
<P>
   Someplace else is exactly where Warner Bros. Television, the
progenitor of ``ER,'' ``Friends'' and other NBC goodies, says it is
going these days. Tony Jonas, the president of Warner Bros.
Television, says his company has ceased bringing new projects to
NBC.
</P>
<P>
   Even the press, which used to adore NBC, has soured on the
network's high-handedness. Put it this way: In a popularity
contest, NBC would be in the line of succession to serve only if
Saddam Hussein were unable to fulfill his duties.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, that's Sassa's inheritance. Sassa, who built most of his
solid reputation at Turner Broadcasting _ cable, in other words _
began his maiden Television Critics Association press conference
with a slide show about how wonderful NBC is doing.
</P>
<P>
   It may be hemorrhaging ratings points, and it has fallen behind
CBS in overall household ratings. But by God, he said, NBC is still
clinging to the top spot in that 18-to-49 demographic. Also, some
people are watching ``Jesse.'' Just ask around; sooner or later
they'll admit it.
</P>
<P>
   The smartest thing Sassa did was introduce the word ``sex'' into
his presentation. The word has a magical impact on the media. With
visions of plunging necklines and rapt readers flooding their
skulls, many reporters promptly forgot about plunging ratings.
</P>
<P>
   Sassa said he'd like to dial down the emphasis on sex in NBC
sitcoms, to ``use a few more words between `Hello' and `Will you
sleep with me.'''
</P>
<P>
   Bingo. The ensuing hubbub ended with Sassa, appearing almost
desperate, assuring critics, in effect, that he's not outfitting
Jennifer Aniston with a sitcom chastity belt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to be very clear that I'm not saying no sex,'' said
Sassa, on a strange sort of Clintonesque note.
</P>
<P>
   Sassa also said he'd like to de-emphasize New York City as a
setting for NBC shows, reinstate a traditional dad-mom-kids show or
two on singles-happy NBC, and increase diversity in prime-time
programming.
</P>
<P>
   That last goal could prove interesting. Sassa said NBC shows
should ``accurately reflect the composition of the audience we're
serving.'' In the past few years, NBC has been whiter than Wonder
Bread in prime time.
</P>
<P>
   Sassa presumably has more in mind than sprinkling a few more
black actors onto the NBC landscape. In a conversation after his
press conference, he mentioned the huge Latino population in
California. And surely diversity should mean something for Asian
Americans, who are possibly the most neglected group on prime time.
</P>
<P>
   Sassa's own ethnic background is Japanese. He grew up in
Southern California, ``in a neighborhood where I was the only
Japanese kid.''
</P>
<P>
   But Sassa seemed to suggest that not too much should be expected
because of his own ethnicity. Someone in his position, he said,
requires two ``ears'' _ one personal, one professional _ in making
decisions.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, Sassa will move up a corporate step and cede the
primary programming responsibility to Ancier, once Ancier is clear
of his WB contractual obligations. That will be in the spring.
</P>
<P>
   Ancier was at NBC in the early 1980s and was a protege of the
late Brandon Tartikoff. Later Ancier was programming chief at Fox,
and then at the WB. In his spare time, he invented Ricki Lake's
syndicated talk show.
</P>
<P>
   It's a stretch to reconcile Sassa's call for more traditional
families and less sexual titillation on NBC shows with Ancier's
track record.
</P>
<P>
   After all, Ancier's programming credits include ``Married ...
With Children,'' ``The Wayans Bros.'' and the steeped-in-sex
``Dawson's Creek.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, with a Sassa-Ancier team taking over for Ohlmeyer and
Littlefield, they'll be able to clean up NBC's programs while
simultaneously reversing a wild ratings skid and mending Hollywood
fences?
</P>
<P>
   That's not a parlor trick. It's a project, and one that could
take years.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-18-99 2148EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
