<P>
   Since it opened two months ago, word of mouth and the occasional
ad have made the Beauty Bar a favorite hangout for young barflies
who prefer its comfortable kitsch to the frenetic clubs of 16th
Street. The enticing combo of manicures and martinis doesn't hurt,
either. Though if you want your cuticles cut, this is not the
place. They simply polish nails and massage hands.
</P>
<P>
   Devitt concocted the concept of a salon-theme bar years ago with
his partner, Deb Parker.
</P>
<P>
   ``A beauty salon has always been a place where ladies could meet
and gossip, so it essentially serves the same function as a bar,''
he explains. ``We hoped the idea of combining the two would appeal
to women, because there are very few bars designed with women in
mind. We wanted it to be a safe, comfortable place.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
    &UR; (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL ADD FOLLOWS) &LR;  &QC; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The San Francisco Beauty Bar is Devitt and Parker's second. The
original opened three years ago in New York's East Village, in a
space once occupied by a bona fide hair salon. One of its
manicurists, an 89-year-old pro named Florence, even stayed on to
work at the bar after it was converted.
</P>
<P>
   The Manhattan Beauty Bar was an instant success. Trend spotters
and fashion followers began packing the place on its opening night,
and it's been featured in the New York Times, the London
Sun-Herald, Vogue (``French, Italian, you name it,'' laughs
Devitt), Interview and a bevy of other fashion magazines.
</P>
<P>
   When Devitt decided to expand to the West Coast, he teamed up
with a San Francisco friend, Aaron Buhrz, who will take over the
new bar's operations when Devitt returns to New York in March.
After finding the perfect space, the two called for backup.
</P>
<P>
   Parker and painter Gary Hayes, who designed the Beauty Bar's
interior, drove a U-Haul full of vintage salon equipment
cross-country from New York. After only a month of frantic
remodeling, the San Francisco Beauty Bar opened November 19. Like
its predecessor, it's enjoyed quick success.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's a strong connection between New York and San
Francisco,'' Devitt says. ``People are always moving back and forth
between the two cities, so there was already a crowd here who knew
about the original Beauty Bar. So they came to check out this one,
too.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he's had much trouble with the Mission District's
notoriously anti-upscale activists, Devitt shrugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reaction has been mixed. People either love the place or they
hate it.''
</P>
<P>
   Colleen Mclarney, the customer who had her nails polished to
match her Cosmopolitan, loves the place.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's darling. I think every beauty parlor should serve
alcohol.'' She sips her cocktail and looks around appreciatively.
``I feel like I'm on the set of `The Women.'''
</P>
<P>
   Though you'll never see the late Rosalind Russell or Norma
Shearer propped beneath the Beauty Bar's dryers, Devitt is already
expanding his concept. The Bar now offers Saturday night
mini-makeovers, body makeup and bindis, and an L.A. Beauty Bar is
in the planning stages.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the perfect place to stop on your way out to the
clubs,'' Devitt says, watching another customer select a bright
vermilion polish to match her jacket. ``Just come in, get beautiful
and paint the town red.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
