<HEADER>
A8265 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WEISEL-SFCHRON &LR;      01-18 0962
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEISEL-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Tycoon Trying Again  &HT;       
 By Sam Zuckerman 
 &HT;     c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
There is something very familiar about Thomas Weisel Partners, San
Francisco's newest investment bank.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  The firm's Financial District headquarters crackles with the
same feverish energy as Weisel's last venture, Montgomery
Securities. Sleek young men and women dart purposefully through the
corridors, just like before. Even the contemporary American oil
paintings hanging from walls look like those at Montgomery. The
sense of deja vu is no accident.
</P>
<P>
   Founder Thom Weisel is trying to repeat the tremendous success
he had at Montgomery, the firm he started in 1971 and built into
one of largest and richest securities firms on the West Coast.
</P>
<P>
   Four months after leaving Montgomery, Weisel is off and running
with his new venture.
</P>
<P>
   He's raised about $65 million in capital, about half from
partners and half from outside investors. That makes the startup
about a third the size of Hambrecht &AMP; Quist, the city's biggest
independent investment bank.
</P>
<P>
   And he's recruited 16 partners and about 70 other employees,
with the goal of reaching 200 by next month. ``We're adding 10
people a day,'' Weisel said.
</P>
<P>
   About half, including his co-heads of investment banking and his
research director, are fellow refugees from Montgomery who
presumably will bring clients with them. Among them: star Internet
analyst David Readerman.
</P>
<P>
   Weisel sold Montgomery in 1997 to North Carolina's NationsBank
for some $1.3 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Then, last September, he quit in anger after losing control of
the business to NationsBank's CEO, Hugh McColl, a man now well
known in San Francisco for his take-no-prisoners buyout of
BankAmerica. Under the terms of his departure, Weisel was released
from the usual prohibition on competing against his old firm.
</P>
<P>
   As Montgomery slipped from his grasp, the hard-charging Weisel,
a former bicycle and ski racer, lost his edge. Last summer, ``he
was subdued, quiet. He wouldn't say anything,'' recalled Frank
Dunlevy, a Montgomery investment banker who has joined him in his
new venture.
</P>
<P>
   The old Weisel is back. In an interview, he displayed the full
measure of aggressiveness and confidence _ qualities some have
called arrogance _ that made him perhaps the most powerful figure
in San Francisco's investment banking world.
</P>
<P>
   Bank takeovers of several of the city's leading securities
firms, including Montgomery, have caused them to neglect their
traditional clients among fast-growing small and midsize companies,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Montgomery and other firms have shifted their sights to
the big, established corporations served by their banker parents,
leaving young computer, Internet, media and health care companies
ripe for the taking.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's just a huge opportunity,'' said Weisel, who has the
thick shock of hair, the athletic frame and set jaw of a man of
action. ``The space has been vacated by most or all the major
players.''
</P>
<P>
   Where will the firm get its business? ``I obviously have a very
long list of CEOs,'' he said slyly.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to raising capital, doing other investment banking
work for corporate clients and selling securities to institutional
investors, Weisel's firm will run a private investment fund.
</P>
<P>
   Using its own funds and money raised from clients, it will buy
equity stakes in young companies before they go public, typically
between the venture capital and IPO stages. Eventually, Weisel
said, the firm may earn up to half its profits from its
investments.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of WEISEL19 (43671 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  Thomas Weisel Partners doesn't have a real trading room yet _ its
state-of-the-art facility won't open until April. But it's already
doing deals.
</P>
<P>
   The firm will co-manage a $50 million initial public offering of
stock for an unidentified company in the next few weeks, Weisel
said.
</P>
<P>
   His competitors don't doubt Weisel will succeed. But they say
he's exaggerating his ability to establish his firm as a top
contender right out of the gate.
</P>
<P>
   For example, they said, his limited capital will prevent him
from doing more than a few stock offerings simultaneously.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's always room for a very high quality player,'' said
BancBoston Robertson Stephens chief executive Michael McCaffery.
``But to duplicate the success he had at Montgomery, he has to have
a much larger organization with much more capital and much
greater'' ability to sell stock to institutional investors.
</P>
<P>
   The 57-year-old Weisel is already fabulously wealthy. He's
already built a business for which someone was willing to pay more
than $1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   He even has a wing of the San Francisco Museum of Modern Art
named for him. And, in September, in the midst of his showdown with
Montgomery, he married his woman friend of nine years.
</P>
<P>
   Why would he want to take on the aggravation of doing it all
again?
</P>
<P>
   Many in the gossipy world of San Francisco's Financial District
think he's out for revenge, that he's determined to punish McColl
for taking Montgomery away from him.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Indeed, Weisel is free to compete with his old firm because
NationsBank allegedly broke contractual promises to let him control
key business lines. Those alleged contract violations put him in
position to get a release from the standard contract prohibitions
against competition.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Weisel disputed the revenge stories. ``I wish them
well,'' he said about Montgomery. ``There's no animosity. I'd like
to work with them.''
</P>
<P>
   Weisel is not given to introspection. But asked why he threw
himself into his new business when there is nothing left to prove,
he turned reflective.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what I am,'' he said. ``I don't know what else to do.
I don't ever intend to retire.``
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
