<HEADER>
A8266 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXAS-INAUG-KIDS-COX     01-18 0835
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-INAUG-KIDS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A day before taking office, Bush remembers King, meets with
childrenBy Ken Herman and Dave Harmon
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Gov. George W. Bush, who today steps into state
history and a growing national spotlight, travelled to Houston on
Monday to honor a man whose dream changed a nation and then
returned home to look out on the little faces of the future.
</P>
<P>
   On the day before they take the oaths of office at the Capitol,
Bush and Lt. Gov.-elect Rick Perry joined in a Martin Luther King
Jr. Day celebration in Houston and a children's program at Austin's
Paramount Theatre for an afternoon program of karate, science
experiments, song and dance.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of my missions as governor is to call people of good
faith, good heart and good will to unleash their compassion,'' Bush
said at a King Day celebration sponsored by the Black Heritage
Society at Houston's George R. Brown Convention Center.
</P>
<P>
   Bush and Perry didn't generate the applause of two hometown
Democrats _ Houston Mayor Lee Brown and local U.S. Rep. Sheila
Jackson Lee _ but the crowd appreciated their presence.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who today will become the first Texas governor sworn in
for consecutive four-year terms, said he wants individuals try to
improve their communities ``one heart, one soul, one conscience at
a time.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I fully realize one person alone can't do everything, but one
person alone can do something,'' Bush said. ``Let us remember
(King's) wisdom and his legacy. Let us remember that compassion can
overcome all.''
</P>
<P>
   In the audience, Houstonian William Hines said he appreciated
the gesture: ``I thought what he said was good. Inclusive.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearby, Donald Brown, a 46-year-old city worker and not a Bush
fan, said he respected Bush for coming but thought the governor had
ulterior political motives.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there has to be other reasons for him to be here,''
Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   After his speech, Bush said he went to Houston to pay tribute to
a great man, not to politicize the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think his message is relevant to all of Texas. We are a
diverse state and we're going to get more diverse,'' he said. ``I
realize I didn't get a lot of the African-American vote, but I'm
still going to be everyone's governor.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush then fielded another round of questions about his potential
presidential candidacy. He said he remains undecided, but said his
wife and twin 17-year-old daughters have understandable misgivings
about a presidential race.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't met one 17-year-old child who is eager to get
dragged through the national spotlight,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Bush, the first lady, followed up with the family's
standard answer to the persistent question: ``It's a huge decision
as everyone knows and we haven't made it yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Undecided though he may be, Bush is planning to meet privately
in Austin Wednesday with influential potential supporters.
Spokeswoman Karen Hughes characterized the supporters as ``college
friends and old friends from Midland'' and others. She said a
similar gathering with similar guests was held a day after the 1995
inauguration.
</P>
<P>
   Inaugural events continue today, beginning with a private prayer
service and ending this evening with four balls. Hughes said she
had not heard if a final decision had been reached on what could be
the only mystery in a day that is scripted to the second. Bush said
recently he was undecided on whether he will hit the dance floor
tonight. He danced, briefly, at one inaugural ball in 1995, saying
it was the first time he had danced since his wedding and would be
his last dance for a long, long time.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Bush, Perry and other state officials will make
the rounds at the evening's four balls. The ``line of march'' for
the officials' grand entrance at each ball shows just how
Republican the former republic has become. House Speaker Pete Laney
is the only Democrat involved.
</P>
<P>
   When Bush takes the oath at noon today, he will become the first
Texas governor sworn in for consecutive four-year terms. Gov. Dolph
Briscoe, the last incumbent governor to be re-elected, served a
two-year term and a four-year term. The terms were changed to four
years in 1975.
</P>
<P>
   But Briscoe's second inauguration day was a relatively low-key
affair, parade-free because of the energy crisis that gripped the
nation.
</P>
<P>
   A quarter of a century later, energy prices again are a hot
topic around inauguration time. Now, however, the complaint is
about low prices.
</P>
<P>
   West Texas oil industry workers marched on Congress Avenue on
Monday to seek state help in boosting oil prices. They rallied near
the Governor's Mansion and called on Bush to order the Texas
Railroad Commission to limit production. Among the marchers was
Clayton Williams, the GOP's unsuccessful gubernatorial candidate in
1990.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Herman and Dave Harmon write for the Austin
American-Statesman, Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
