r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHOWCASE-SFCHRON &LR;      01-18 0710
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOWCASE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Wireless Rules At Showcase Trade Show  &HT;       
 By David Einstein 
 &HT;     c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
San Diego &QL; 
 &QL; 
If they remade ``The Graduate'' today, instead of ``plastic,''
Dustin Hoffman would be told that the word to think about is
``wireless.''
</P>
<P>
   With cellular telephone service fast becoming pervasive in
business, companies big and small are trotting out technology
designed to provide users of handheld devices with wireless access
to corporate data such as e-mail, calendars and address books.
</P>
<P>
   Several companies announced wireless products and services
yesterday at Showcase '99, an annual trade show here in San Diego
tries to spotlight the latest trends in computers,
telecommunications and the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Among the most prominent new offerings at the show is Revolv,
the first fruit of WirelessKnowledge, a partnership between
software giant Microsoft and Qualcomm, one of the leaders in
cellular technology.
</P>
<P>
   Revolv, which is expected to hit the market this spring, will
let users of cell phones, pagers, laptop computers and personal
digital assistants such as the PalmPilot access e-mail, calendars
and contact information stored on their PCs at work over cellular
connections. They'll also be able to make changes to the data,
using what's called a ``virtual private network.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first time all of these different devices have
been integrated together into a single solution,'' said Tom
Clarkson, vice president of marketing for WirelessKnowledge.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, Revolv only will be able to tap into information
stored in Microsoft Exchange, a popular program for e-mail and
personal information used by many businesses. However, portable
devices don't need Microsoft software to receive the service. The
only requirement is the ability to display a graphical view. Some
cell phones and pagers as well as most PDAs and all laptop
computers can do that today.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of SHOWCASE () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  Based in San Diego near Qualcomm, WirelessKnowledge was created
in November with $25 million each from Qualcomm and Microsoft,
which is based in Redmond, Wash.
</P>
<P>
   The new service will be sold by cellular carriers, including
AirTouch, AT&AMP;T, Sprint and GTE. Each carrier will set its own
pricing, which could be a flat rate similar to the $20 most
Internet services charge or on a per-minute basis, such as 10 cents
a minute.
</P>
<P>
   Industry experts say that affordability will be the key to
success of services such as Revolv.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of people who carry cell phones or pagers or
PDAs and they want to get information wirelessly,'' said Mike
Miller, editor in chief of PC Magazine. ``But they don't want to
pay ridiculous amounts for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question is when will the industry reach critical mass
where the stuff works well and the price is low enough so that lots
of people will want it?'' he said, adding, ``It looks like that
will happen sometime in the next six to 12 months.''
</P>
<P>
   Also debuting yesterday at Showcase was a wireless network
system for small businesses from Intalk of San Jose. Dubbed InPoint
Pro, it uses a base station the size of a video game console to
connect computers within a local area network as well as letting
mobile computers link up to the network. Once connected, users at
home or on the road can have access to all the information and
applications on the network.
</P>
<P>
   The system, which is scheduled to ship this summer, will cost
about $900 for the base station and $350 for an antenna card for
each PC or laptop.
</P>
<P>
   Another example of the wireless trend is a combination cell
phone and PDA unveiled by Motorola. The six-ounce device is
actually a StarTac phone and a credit-card-size Rex handheld
organizer connected back-to-back. Motorola acquired the Rex
technology when it purchased its creator, Starfish Software, last
summer. At 4 inches tall and 1 inch thick, it's significantly
smaller than other so-called smart phones, like the Nokia 9000.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 2 of SHOWCASE () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  Other wireless products at the show include an appliance from
Sharewave of El Dorado Hills near Sacramento that establishes a
high-speed connection between a PC and a television. The link-up
lets you use the TV to surf the Web or play computer games.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
