<HEADER>
A8268 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STREET-SFCHRON &LR;      01-18 0842
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STREET-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;      
</HEADLINE>
  
 Sharper Image CEO Says E-Tailing Statement Wasn't Ploy to
Raise  Stock  By Mark Veverka  
 c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Sharper Image chief executive Richard Thalheimer says he has every
intention of transforming his specialty retailer into a major force
in electronic commerce.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's a tremendous opportunity on the Internet for
retailers with unique content, including us,'' says Thalheimer, who
also took time to explain some insider stock selling at the San
Francisco retailer.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Street Smarts was the first to report that Thalheimer
and other insiders had collectively unloaded nearly a half-million
of their Sharper Image shares during December.
</P>
<P>
   The insider sell-off happened to coincide with a barrage of
public relations dispatches by the company, touting Sharper Image's
e-tailing prowess during the holiday shopping season. The fact is,
less than 5 percent of the company's revenues are generated by
transactions via the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   To his credit, Thalheimer returned telephone calls, but we
failed to connect before the column ran. When we finally caught up
with each other, he explained some of the reasons for the stock
selling and expounded on his company's plans for the Net.
</P>
<P>
   A week ago, Sharper Image stock had more than quadrupled from
its 52-week average to about $25 a share. The spike was triggered
by a Sharper Image press release announcing that the company
planned to launch an ``auction'' Web page. Of course, auction was
the magic word. True auction sites, such as eBay, have been
investor darlings. Part of the reason is that eBay was profitable
before going public.
</P>
<P>
   Sharper Image's auction is quite different, however, in that it
would merely use an Internet auction function to unload its excess
inventory. In other words, bargain shoppers can bid on Sharper
Image merchandise that has been set aside for clearance. On the
other hand, eBay is a live global auction selling a vast array of
personal wares and collectibles.
</P>
<P>
   Still, you have to hand it to Thalheimer. He cleverly helped
goose his stock higher, taking full advantage of the Internet
insanity that has enraptured the stock market.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, we'll have to wait until after the end of this month
to find out if he and other insiders sold more of their holdings in
concert with that particular release.
</P>
<P>
   Yet investors already seem to see through the veneer. Sharper's
shares closed down to around $15 at the close of trading on Friday.
As reported, investors and analysts applauded Thalheimer's sale
because too many of the small-cap company's shares are tied up in
his personal and family stakes, which together exceed 60 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the CEO wanted to clarify why his top lieutenants opted
to sell. For several years, Sharper Image had struggled _ including
seven-straight quarters of losses racked up through October 1997.
However, during the past four quarters (the current period ends
January 31), Thalheimer seems to have righted the ship at the
seller of electronic gadgets and toys, steering his company back
into the black.
</P>
<P>
   Consequently, he encouraged his officers to take some profits.
With Sharper's average stock price lingering under $5 a share
during much of the decade that it has been public (not including
the past two months), December's lofty stock prices offered a rare
chance for insiders to reap some rewards, Thalheimer argues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of these people haven't had any opportunities to sell
their shares, (and) they haven't exactly received big bonuses''
over recent years, Thalheimer says.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, while it is true that both the chief operating
officer and chief financial officer liquidated their entire
``vested positions,'' it was only 20 percent of their total stakes
when considering equity that has yet to vest, Thalheimer explains.
</P>
<P>
   The upshot: Certain insiders still sold every share they
possibly could, but we should wait until they receive more of their
shares to determine whether they are net holders or sellers.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 2 of STREET19 () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  And if you listen to Thalheimer, his management team could have
reason to be holders down the line. After several grueling years of
repositioning the company, which now makes and designs its own
merchandise at fatter profit margins, Thalheimer contends that
Sharper Image has the right stuff to lure cybershoppers to its Web
site.
</P>
<P>
   Meantime, the core business has been shored up. Sales and profit
margins are up at its 90 stores (which account for about 70 percent
of revenues) and at its traditional mail-order business (which
accounts for about 25 percent of sales).
</P>
<P>
   I have to admit that I have a soft spot for ``brick and mortar''
retailers in their bids to expand on to the Net. Time will tell how
earnest Thalheimer's effort is to make e-commerce the engine of his
retail operation.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Mark Veverka can be reached by mail at 901 Mission St., San
Francisco, Calif. 94103, by phone at (415) 777-8444 or by e-mail at
mveverka(at sign)sfgate.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
