<SLUG> BC-QUAKE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Quake Insurance Shakeup  &HT;       
 By Rebecca Smith 
 &HT;     c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Earthquake insurance will probably never be as cheap as it was
before the Northridge earthquake _ which was five years ago on
Sunday _ but prices are coming down this year and homeowners should
have more coverage options.
</P>
<P>
   David Knowles, incoming chief of the California Earthquake
Authority, says the prevailing view _ that coverage is grossly
overpriced and pathetically skimpy _ doesn't recognize recent
changes.
</P>
<P>
   Statewide, rates are down 18 percent since the CEA began
offering a ``minipolicy'' through two dozen member insurance
companies two years ago. In the Bay Area, rates that take effect
this spring will reflect cumulative reductions of 10 to 28 percent.
</P>
<P>
   This spring, the CEA will unveil supplemental policies that will
let homeowners lower their deductibles from today's 15 percent to a
more palatable 10 percent and boost contents coverage to $100,000
from today's chintzy $5,000. Lastly, homeowners will be able to buy
emergency housing coverage of up to $15,000, up from today's paltry
$1,500. All these options will come at a cost, however.
</P>
<P>
   In short, prices remain higher than what homeowners want, but
the coverage is getting to look more like what the Bay Area had
before the Northridge quake lobbed a grenade into the lap of the
property and casualty insurance business.
</P>
<P>
   Premium sampler: A home east of Highway 101 in San Francisco or
on the Penisula, or across the Bay in Berkeley, Oakland, San
Leandro, Hayward or Fremont that's insured for the statewide
average amount of $194,000 (structure only) would cost $856 ($4.41
per $1,000 valuation) for the basic CEA policy, down from $1,019
($5.25/$1,000) two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Insuring that same home west of Highway 101 on the Peninsula or
in San Francisco would cost a bit less, $729 ($3.76/$1,000), down
from $1,019. In much of Marin County, the annual cost would be $369
($1.90/$1,000).
</P>
<P>
   A supplemental policy with a 10 percent deductible, $25,000
contents coverage and $10,000 living allowance would add another
$281 to the cost ($1.45/$1,000) of the minipolicy.
</P>
<P>
   Although costs for coverage have come down a bit, they remain
double what many people were paying before Northridge. The quake
produced such huge losses _ more than $12.5 billion _ that the
industry pulled back from writing homeowners insurance because
state law also required home insurers to offer earthquake
insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Out of the chaos, the CEA was created along with its elaborate
system of policy premiums, industry assessments and reinsurance _
that's insurance for insurance companies _ that are combined to
provide $7 billion worth of protection for some 950,000
policyholders today.
</P>
<P>
   Knowles, a former state Assemblyman from Lake Tahoe who helped
write the legislation creating the CEA, makes it clear that there's
no going back to the good old days of broader coverage, low
deductibles and rock-bottom premiums. Farmers Insurance, for
example, thought its exposure in the Northridge area was about $100
million. It lost more than $1 billion, as it turned out, which was
more than it had derived from premiums the previous 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   Today, 99 percent of the California earthquake market consists
of the minipolicy offered through insurance companies that are
members of the CEA, or nonmembers that basically have replicated
the coverage on their own. However, two companies _ Pacific Select
Insurance Co. of Walnut Creek and Geo Vera of Concord _ have begun
offering stand-alone quake policies that depart from the
boilerplate coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Pacific Select is able to undercut earthquake authority rates by
only insuring homes that are bolted to foundations and have sheer
walls that prevent them from buckling.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect people to do what they can to prevent losses,'' says
Richard Campagna, chief executive of Pacific Select. ``People think
nothing of paying $1,000 or $2,000 to insure their cars, but it's
surprising how many won't spend the money to protect something 10
times as valuable.''
</P>
<P>
   Emerging competition from the outside is putting pressure on the
CEA to lower rates further, Knowles says. He knows that the CEA has
a problem on its hands. Prior to Northridge, 32 percent of Bay Area
residents had earthquake insurance. The CEA doesn't know what
percentage in the Bay Area is covered today, but industry sources
speculate that it's less than 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The fifth anniversary of the Northridge quake, two days ago,
brings to mind something California needs, Knowles concludes.
</P>
<P>
   A shakeup call.
</P>
<P>
   Not a 6.7 quake like Northridge, of course. Nor a 7.1 rattler
like 1989's Loma Prieta quake that killed 64 people and cost
billions. But a ``smallish quake,'' Knowles says. ``Enough to
rattle the china and put an inexpensive crack or two in the
walls.''
</P>
<P>
   Knowles figures that a small quake would grab the attention of
California homeowners better than the television spots that the CEA
plans to introduce later this year.
</P>
<P>
   He'd like to do more to improve the program, but a lot of what
happens hinges on the results of a geological survey in the fall.
The U.S. Geological Survey plans to release a lengthy
earthquake-probability study concerning the Bay Area on October 17,
the 10th anniversary of the Loma Prieta quake.
</P>
<P>
   By law, the earthquake authority must consider the ``best
available'' scientific information when setting rates. Currently,
Bay Area rates are based, in part, on a USGS presumption that
there's a 2-in-3 chance of a 7.0 magnitude quake in the next 30
years.
</P>
<P>
   But the new report very likely will show a greater risk of a
major quake. That's because the report will factor in faults not
even considered in 1990 report. In addition to the Hayward, San
Andreas and Rodgers Creek faults, the new study will include the
San Gregorio fault near Half Moon Bay, the Concord-Green Valley
fault, the Calaveras fault near San Jose and the Greenville fault
in the Livermore Valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``We live in a big seismic stew in the Bay Area,'' says USGS
geologist David Schwartz. ``By adding more faults, we're adding
more ingredients to the stew. The bottom line is that I can't see
the earthquake-probability number getting any smaller.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
