<SLUG> BC-MONEYBAG-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 How Sales Taxes Work On Internet  &HT;       
 By Arthur M. Louis  
 c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; Question: &LR;  I recently wanted to buy something by mail order, but
backed off because the retailer, which is not based in California,
insisted that I would have to pay the California sales tax. When
can a retailer do that _ and does this apply to sales on the
Internet as well?
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &UR; Answer:  &LR; Any retailer engaged in business in California must
collect sales taxes from California customers. That includes those
that sell via the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The retailer doesn't necessarily have to be based in California
to be engaged in business here, notes Laureen Simpson, a technical
adviser with the state Board of Equalization.
</P>
<P>
   If it has a tangible presence in California, such as a factory,
warehouse or sales office, it must collect the sales tax. The rule
even applies if the seller has no people or buildings of its own
here, but contracts with a vendor in California to assemble or
install merchandise.
</P>
<P>
   If you buy from a company that is located entirely in, say,
Mississippi, that company won't have to collect sales taxes from
you.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, in such cases you are legally required to pay
California a so-called use tax, which is exactly equal to the sales
tax. The only distinction between the sales tax and the use tax is
that the seller is responsible for the collection of sales taxes,
while the buyer is responsible for the use tax.
</P>
<P>
   In practice, Simpson acknowledges, only a tiny fraction of
consumers actually pay use taxes. The tax is ``very difficult to
track and enforce,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Federal Gift Tax
</P>
<P>
   Q: I plan to give my son $200,000 this year toward the purchase
of a house. I know I can do this without paying the federal gift
tax, because there is a $650,000 lifetime, tax-free exclusion. I've
read that the exclusion will increase in stages to $1 million in
the next few years. If I make the $200,000 gift this year, will I
be stuck with a remaining exclusion of $450,000 in future years, or
will I be able to take advantage of the future increases?
</P>
<P>
   A: Let me make a nitpicking correction before I answer your
question.
</P>
<P>
   Tax law allows you to give up to $10,000 per year each to as
many individuals as you wish, without depleting your lifetime
gift-tax exclusion. That means the first $10,000 of your $200,000
gift to your son won't be deducted from your exclusion. After you
make the gift, you will have $460,000 in exclusions left, not
$450,000.
</P>
<P>
   The really good news is that you can take full advantage of
future increases in the lifetime exclusion. There is no need to
delay that generous gift to your son, if that's what you have in
mind.
</P>
<P>
   The lifetime exclusion is scheduled to increase by $25,000 next
year _ to $675,000 _ so the balance of your exclusion will increase
to $485,000. The lifetime exclusion jumps again to $700,000 in
2002, $850,000 in 2004, $950,000 in 2005 and $1 million in 2006.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of MONEYBAG (88019 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  That, at least, is what the current law mandates. There has been
talk among the Republican leadership in Congress about raising
those limits further, or eliminating the tax entirely.
</P>
<P>
   IRA Penalty
</P>
<P>
   Q: I know there is a 10 percent penalty if I withdraw money from
my Individual Retirement Account before age 591/2, and I also know
that withdrawals are mandatory starting after age 701/2. What are
the rules for people between those ages? Can they withdraw money at
random, or are they forced to follow a fixed schedule?
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR; A: Random withdrawals are permitted.
</P>
<P>
   People between ages 591/2 and 701/2 can take as much or as
little as they need from their IRAs, as often or as infrequently as
they please, says Internal Revenue Service spokesman Jesse Weller.
There is no fixed withdrawal schedule and no penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Starting with the first April after you turn 701/2, you must
begin withdrawing the balance of your IRA funds according to a
fixed schedule based on your life expectancy.
</P>
<P>
   You can find the table in IRS Publication 590. You can order a
free copy of the publication by calling (800) 829-3676. You also
can order a copy _ or simply read it online _ on the IRS Web site
at  &LR; www.irs.ustreas.gov &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Send questions about how to manage your money to moneybag(at
sign)sfgate.com, or to Arthur M. Louis, Moneybag column, 901
Mission St., San Francisco, Calif., 94103
</P>
</TEXT>
