<SLUG> BC-ECOMMERCE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Net Shoppers' Satisfaction Slipping  &HT;       
 By Jamie Beckett 
 &HT;     c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
More shoppers than ever flocked to online stores over the holidays,
but fewer were happy with their experience, a new study shows.
</P>
<P>
   The number of satisfied Web shoppers slipped 14 percent during
the past six months _ to 74 percent _ as online consumers faced
many of the same challenges found in traditional stores: crowds,
traffic and poor service, according to the study released yesterday
by Jupiter Communications, a New York research firm.
</P>
<P>
   Shoppers surveyed cited problems with merchandise availability
(15 percent), the additional costs of shipping and handling (14
percent), and slow site performance (13 percent) as their top three
reasons for dissatisfaction.
</P>
<P>
   ``The combination of retailers that launched or relaunched their
sites within weeks of the holiday season, combined with the
significant, unanticipated increase in traffic, led many sites to
under-perform,'' said rNicole Vanderbilt, senior analyst at
Jupiter.
</P>
<P>
   In a result that doesn't portend well for future growth of
e-commerce, only 37 percent of online shoppers indicated that they
would spend more next holiday season, 58 percent said they would
spend the same and 5 percent said they would spend less.
</P>
<P>
   Vanderbilt said e-commerce companies, many of which spent
heavily to win over customers, will lose those customers if they
don't improve customer service.
</P>
<P>
   Jupiter said 44 percent of households with Internet access
bought products online during the holiday season. Other surveys
have pegged that number at 8 million consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Jupiter and NFO Interactive of Greenwich, Conn., surveyed more
than 2,300 Internet-connected households.
</P>
<P>
   Jupiter said shoppers spent a record $3.1 billion on the
Internet in November and December. That's nearly triple 1997
spending and more than most analysts, including Jupiter, had
predicted that they would spend.
</P>
</TEXT>
