A8274 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FINBUDGET-SFCHRON &LR;      01-18 0359
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FINBUDGET-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   These are the stories The San Francisco Chronicle Business
section plans to move for Tuesday, Jan. 19, on the New York Times
wire. For questions, please call Marcus Chan at 415-777-8443 or
Catherine Laidlaw at 415-777-6057.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SHOWCASE  &LR; _ If they remade ``The Graduate'' today, instead of
``plastic,'' Dustin Hoffman would be told that the word to think
about is ``wireless.''
</P>
<P>
   With cellular telephone service fast becoming pervasive in
business, companies big and small are trotting out technology
designed to provide users of handheld devices with wireless access
to corporate data such as e-mail, calendars and address books. By
David Einstein
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WEISEL _  &LR; There is something very familiar about Thomas Weisel
Partners, San Francisco's newest investment bank.
</P>
<P>
   The firm's Financial District headquarters crackles with the
same feverish energy as Weisel's last venture, Montgomery
Securities. Sleek young men and women dart purposefully through the
corridors, just like before. Even the contemporary American oil
paintings hanging from walls look like those at Montgomery.
</P>
<P>
   The sense of deja vu is no accident. By Sam Zuckerman
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ECOMMERCE _  &LR; More shoppers than ever flocked to online stores
over the holidays, but fewer were happy with their experience, a
new study shows. By Jamie Beckett
</P>
<P>
   &UR; STREET  &LR; _ Sharper Image chief executive Richard Thalheimer says
he has every intention of transforming his specialty retailer into
a major force in electronic commerce. By columnist Mark Veverka
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; MONEY PACKAGE &QC;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; QUAKE  &LR; _ Earthquake insurance will probably never be as cheap as it
was before the Northridge earthquake _ which was five years ago on
Sunday _ but prices are coming down this year and homeowners should
have more coverage options. By Rebecca Smith
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MONEYBAG _  &LR; Question: I recently wanted to buy something by
mail order, but backed off because the retailer, which is not based
in California, insisted that I would have to pay the California
sales tax. When can a retailer do that _ and does this apply to
sales on the Internet as well? Columnist Arthur M. Louis has the
answer.
</P>
