  (nk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   INDIA: FUROR OVER CRICKET
</P>
<P>
   While militant Hindus in New Delhi demonstrated against the
government's decision to let Pakistan's cricket team play in India
later this month, a rampaging mob in Bombay attacked the offices of
the Cricket Club of India, breaking windows and smashing furniture.
Authorities believe the assailants were members of Shiv Sena, an
ultra right-wing Hindu political group.
</P>
<P>
   NORTH, SOUTH KOREA: NEW TALKS STARTING
</P>
<P>
   The fourth round of talks between North and South Korea, China
and the United States to hammer out a formal peace for the divided
peninsula are set to resume in Geneva. They follow inconclusive
discussions last weekend over access to a North Korean underground
center suspected of being the site of nuclear weapon activity in
violation of a 1994 agreement.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   ZIMBABWE: EX-PRESIDENT SENTENCED
</P>
<P>
   Former President Canaan Banana was sentenced to 10 years in
jail, nine of them suspended, for sodomy and indecent assault.
Banana, 62, was convicted last November, but fled before he could
be sentenced. The former Methodist minister and Zimbabwe's titular
president for seven years, returned home on Dec. 15. Banana was
given leave to appeal.
</P>
