<HEADLINE>
REALTORS GROUP EXPECTS SLOWDOWN IN L.A.-AREA'S HOUSING MARKET
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY GREGORY J. WILCOX  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Bouyed by a strong economy brimming with confident
consumers, the real estate market of L.A.'s San Fernando Valley
area caught a $4 billion wave in 1998 that seems ready to break, a
trade group has announced.
</P>
<P>
   But it won't be an ugly wipeout like the one that occurred in
the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, sales of single-family homes jumped14.7 percent to
13,242 units from the 1997 level, said the Southland Regional
Association of Realtors' report, released Monday. And the median
housing price, the point at which half the homes sold for more and
half for less, soared 14.6 percent to $190,117 from last year.
</P>
<P>
   That's the largest volume since the 15,263 units sold in 1988
and prices increased the most since the median skyrocketed $41,250
in 1989. Including condominiums, Realtors sold $4 billion worth of
properties in the Valley last year, the trade group said.
</P>
<P>
   In the smaller but red-hot Santa Clarita Valley market, sales of
both single-family homes and condominiums soared 33 percent to
3,594 properties. The median single-family home price was $204,575,
up about 13 percent from 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Realtors said 1998's pace, fueled in part by low interest rates,
could be hard to maintain. So this year's sales total may end up
looking a lot like 1998's with little or no percentage increase.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it will be a little flatter,'' Jim Link, the
association's executive vice president, said of the 1999 market.
``My best guess is that sales will run about the same or maybe a
little less.''
</P>
<P>
   Nima Nattagh, an analyst at First American Real Estate Solutions
in Santa Ana, Calif., said that while this year will bring a
slowdown compared to 1998, it will remain a strong market
nonetheless with prices appreciating in the 5 percent to 6 percent
range. Any sales increase would be slight.
</P>
<P>
   Interest rates, though, continue to remain favorable and
inflation in check.
</P>
<P>
   ``The interest rate environment is one of the things that will
remain favorable for the housing market and there is no suggesting
they will go up anytime soon,'' Nattagh said.
</P>
<P>
   Last year's sales could have been even higher had there been
more properties on the market, said Beth L. Sommer, president of
the Valley's Realtors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sales have been on a steady climb for the last six years, yet
no one fully predicted last year's incredible activity,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Signs of the kind of year that may be in the offing arrived
during December.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, escrow closed on 1,015 single-family homes, down 12
percent from a year ago, while the median price climbed to
$198,500, up 17.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Realtors sold 270 condominiums, a 10.2 percent
dip from December 1997. The median price jumped 19.5 percent to
$119.500.
</P>
<P>
   While the dip is seasonal, it was the first time in 19 months
that single-family home sales fell from the year-ago level.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, pending sales of both single-family homes and
condominiums, a leading indicator of what the months ahead will
bring, fell for the third consecutive month on an annual basis.
</P>
<P>
   And the market dynamics are changing.
</P>
<P>
   Sale increases during the last several years have been fueled by
first-time buyers snapping up properties at the low end of the
price scale. Last year saw sales gains across all price points,
Sommer said.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the volume of sales may slow, homeowners should
continue building equity.
</P>
<P>
   When the real estate market collapsed during the early and
mid-'90s, home prices lost about 25 percent of their value.Link
estimated that up to 70 percent of that lost equity has been
recaptured in some cases.
</P>
<P>
   More ground should be gained this year, he said, but not as much
as in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're beginning to see some of the breaks being applied,'' he
said of the market. ``We've reached a point where values will
continue to increase but it won't be as fast as last year.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
