<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NY-JURYDUTY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL OBSERVER: WHERE A NEW YORK MINUTE LASTS FOR HOURS 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By GAIL COLLINS 
  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times says in an editorial for Tuesday, Jan. 19: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   New York City may have turned its back on nature, but it still
lives by seasonal cycles. Alternate-side-of-the-street parking
rules are as relentless as the tides. Street fairs are our
harbingers of summer, arriving with the numbers and general
irritation quotient of mosquitoes. Jury duty has always been our
version of the plagues of locusts. Every two years a summons to
serve arrived in the mailbox and the spirit sank.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every two years,'' chanted the woman who sat next to me in
Manhattan Civil Court last week when a lawyer asked her whether she
had ever served on a jury before. ``Like clockwork, every two
years.'' The rest of the room laughed. It came as a shock later
when the clerk who dismissed us announced that we would not be
called back until 2003.
</P>
<P>
   Most Americans regard jury duty like public opinion poll surveys
_ something that never happens to anybody they know. But having
four years off between summonses is a big deal in New York City,
almost as good as getting a certificate from the Department of
Transportation saying that you can leave your car parked in front
of your house. This reprieve is the work of the state's current
chief judge, Judith Kaye, who is trying to make jury duty less
painful.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Kaye is doing battle with layers of time-honored if
totally loopy legal customs, and the war is still half-won at best.
Thanks to the vigilant lobbying of the court officers' union,
jurors in many types of felony cases are still automatically
sequestered in hotels during their deliberations, no matter how
obscure the crime. Defense attorneys in New York still have more
opportunities to reject potential jurors on a whim than anywhere
else in the country. Every single felony trial requires a grand
jury indictment, by jurors who may wind up spending four straight
weeks deciding issues like whether to try a guy for stealing a
delivery man's pizzas.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, things are getting better. The court facilities
are cleaner, the bathroom doors have locks, and the Manhattan
courts just got a $10,000 grant to buy potted plants for rooms in
which jurors presently enjoy a virtually oxygen-free atmosphere.
(This is a city where photosynthesis does not come cheap.) But the
most Herculean achievement was eliminating jury duty exemptions,
which the eager-to-please state legislature had expanded to include
everyone from lawyers to undertakers to podiatrists. About one
million New Yorkers had been let off the hook before Judge Kaye got
the exemptions repealed, which left the remainder in incredible
demand, particularly since only about 15 percent of the eligible
New Yorkers actually responded to the summonses.
</P>
<P>
   The stolid minority who showed up every two years ran into a
legal system so bizarre that a local magazine editor once told me
the most common topic of articles that came in over the transom was
``My Incredible Jury Duty Experience.'' In civil court the judges
were not required to supervise the jury selection, known as voir
dire. The panels of prospective jurors were locked up alone with
the lawyers, each of whom had been taught in school that a case is
won or lost when you pick the jurors. They regarded the panels as
boxes of candy, and their mission was to reject the masses of
caramels and nougats in the elusive search for that one perfect
chocolate-covered cherry, even if it took all winter.
</P>
<P>
   My most unforgettable voir dire involved a plaintiff who had
been injured in a fall. (Falling down seems to be the single
highest cause of litigation in Manhattan. People come from all over
the world to trip over things here.) The lawyers on this particular
case had gone through one panel of potential jurors after another,
examining their backgrounds with extraordinary zeal, and delivering
commercials posed in the form of questions. (``You would not have
any trouble, would you, Ms. Collins, in giving my client a really,
really,  &UR; really &LR;  big settlement if you thought the facts required
it?'') The people who were chosen during the early rounds were
forced to stay in the small, windowless (and plantless) voir dire
room, listening to day after day of questioning until they knew the
medical and legal history of every other person in the courthouse,
as well as _ I swear this was a question _ everybody's favorite
character on ``L.A. Law.''
</P>
<P>
   Now judges have been assigned to keep the lawyers on a leash.
The attorneys questioning my panel last week each got half an hour.
We barely had time to learn everybody's birthplace and to promise
to give a really, really, really big settlement if the facts
required. Then it was all over. My neighbor, the ``like clockwork''
woman, was so familiar with the routine she whispered the answers
before the lawyers could finish talking. She was picked yet again.
``Four years _ I'll believe it when I see it,'' she said as the
rejects beat a hasty retreat.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
