<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKNOTE-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KNIGHT SEEMS SET FOR RETURN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Tony Battie, we hardly new ye.
</P>
<P>
   Battie, whom the Lakers obtained from the Denver Nuggets last
June, will be an ex-Laker by the time training camp opens. The
Lakers plan to ship Battie to the Boston Celtics in exchange for
former Laker Travis Knight, NBA sources told the Daily News.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers acknowledged their interest in obtaining Knight but
would not confirm the deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not in stone yet,'' one source said.
</P>
<P>
   The Knight deal might be the only one the Lakers make, despite
their efforts to land a marquee name. It's being reported the Bulls
will sign and trade Scottie Pippen to the Houston Rockets, while
Minnesota's Tom Gugliotta is heading for Phoenix or Denver.
</P>
<P>
   No trades or free-agent signings can become official until the
NBA completes its new labor agreement, but the Battie-Knight swap
would work under current rules. They are due to make nearly
identical salaries this season _ Knight $2.4 million and Battie
$2.2 million.
</P>
<P>
   Knight was a Laker in 1996-97 and averaged 4.8 points and 4.5
rebounds in 71 games, making the All-Rookie second team. His hustle
and rebounding skills endeared him to the Lakers and he wanted to
make a career here. But the Lakers couldn't offer a long-term deal
and Boston grabbed him with a seven-year, $22 million contract.
</P>
<P>
   Now it appears he'll return to shore up the Lakers frontcourt.
It should be a welcome change of scenery for Knight, who was
considered a disappointment in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Battie, a bust in Denver in his rookie campaign last season, was
acquired on draft day, along with Tyronn Lue, in exchange for Nick
Van Exel. Battie has not attended the Lakers' voluntary workouts at
Southwest College since Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Shaquille O'Neal, who last week hinted at ``surprises'' to come,
sounded less optimistic about a big Lakers trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know nothing,'' he said Monday. ``They asked me who I
wanted. I said a couple names, but then I look around, and those
couple names signed somewhere else.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Hurry up and wait: Rookies Sam Jacobson and Ruben Patterson
made their first appearance as almost-Lakers on Monday at Southwest
College.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobson, a guard from Minnesota, and Patterson, a forward from
Cincinnati, can't sign their rookie contracts until the lockout is
lifted. But they attended voluntary workouts for the first time and
were eager to get to camp _ whenever it eventually starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It felt good playing with Shaq and Eddie (Jones) and (Derek)
Fisher and all the other guys,'' Patterson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got up pretty early in the morning, I was very excited,''
said Jacobson, who arrived in L.A. on Sunday night. ``It was
frustrating (waiting for the lockout to end). It's tough to keep
your motivation going day after day by yourself working out.''
</P>
<P>
   Jacobson proudly wore a purple Lakers sweat shirt and said
stepping onto the court with a trio of All-Stars in O'Neal, Jones
and Kobe Bryant ``is awesome.''
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys were like idols to me a few years ago, and coming
in and now I'm a teammate of theirs, it's outstanding.''
</P>
<P>
   Counting Jacobson, Patterson and Lue, seven Lakers practiced
Monday. Missing were Sean Rooks, Elden Campbell _ the subject of
trade rumors _ and Robert Horry, who remains in Houston with his
pregnant wife.
</P>
<P>
   __ One more day: Another day, another delay in New York. The NBA
pushed back the start of training camps to Wednesday as lawyers
worked to complete the new labor contract.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers will take physical exams today or Wednesday, then
head to UC Santa Barbara for a five- to six-day camp.
</P>
<P>
   __ Free ride: Fans are invited to watch a Lakers practice and
scrimmage Jan. 27 at 6:30 p.m. at the Forum. Admission and parking
are free. Doors will open at 5:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Tickets will be available beginning Wednesday at 10 a.m. at the
Forum box office and Ticketmaster outlets.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
