u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-NICKLAUS-SURGERY-     01-18 0364
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-NICKLAUS-SURGERY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NICKLAUS SLATED FOR HIP REPLACEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM MCCABE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Jack Nicklaus will be in Boston next week, but it will
be medical business, not golfing pleasure.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Benjamin Bierbaum confirmed Monday that he will perform left
total hip replacement surgery on Nicklaus Jan. 27 at New England
Baptist Hospital. Nicklaus, who will celebrate his 59th birthday
Thursday, told reporters last week that he had decided on the
surgery after a strenuous strengthening program failed to alleviate
chronic hip pain.
</P>
<P>
   Those close to Nicklaus, his family and business partners,
reportedly urged him for months to have the surgery, but golf's
most celebrated champion said last fall that he would stick with
his fitness program. But late last year Nicklaus was unable to play
and was seen at times using a cane.
</P>
<P>
   When the decision for surgery was made sometime around the first
of the year, Nicklaus began exploring a choice of surgeons. Sources
said Nicklaus, at home in West Palm Beach, Fla., is friendly with
an orthopedic surgeon who trained under and recommended Bierbaum,
who is generally regarded as one of the foremost hip-replacement
specialists in the world. Nicklaus met with Dr. Bierbaum Jan. 10 in
Boston.
</P>
<P>
   The operation will keep Nicklaus out of competition for several
months; most notably, he will miss the Masters, which he has won
six times and played in every year since 1959. He also will miss
his own Memorial Tournament in June, as the rehabilitation is
expected to take four to six months.
</P>
<P>
   It has been reported that Nicklaus was eyeing a return to the US
Open at Pinehurst No. 2 (June 17-20), but that seems unlikely,
especially since his record of playing in the majors ended at 146
when he did not take part in last summer's British Open or PGA
Championship.
</P>
<P>
   His 1998 season was unspectacular, soured by the hip problems.
Though he stirred fans' emotions last April when he became the
oldest player, at 58, to ever finish in the top 10 at the Masters,
Nicklaus did not take part in any tournament after the US Senior
Open in July.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-18-99 2209EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990118.0448 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 22:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8288 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-RIEFENSTAHL-SFCH     01-18 0934
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-RIEFENSTAHL-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LENI RIEFENSTAHL'S `WHITE HELL' 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: The ``u'' in ``Palu'' carries an umlaut.)  
 By EDWARD GUTHMANN  
 c.1999, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO &LR;   &LR; _ To some, she's the greatest female filmmaker
of all time. To others, she's the face of evil _ a lingering
reminder of the horrors of the Third Reich.
</P>
<P>
   At 96, Leni Riefenstahl still bears the stamp of her association
with Adolf Hitler and ``Triumph of the Will,'' which documented his
massive 1934 rally at Nuremberg.
</P>
<P>
   In Ray Muller's 1993 documentary ``The Wonderful, Horrible Life
of Leni Riefenstahl,'' she insisted that she wasn't a Nazi and that
she made ``Triumph'' under duress, approaching it as an artist and
not as a propagandist.
</P>
<P>
   The legacy of ``Triumph of the Will'' is so great that
Riefenstahl's early career as an actress and director is scarcely
mentioned anymore. But in the 1920s she was a popular German star
in a series of ``mountain films'' directed by
geologist-turned-filmmaker Arnold Fanck.
</P>
<P>
   The best of that genre, ``The White Hell of Piz Pal &LR; u &LR; '' (1929),
screens Jan. 20 at San Francisco's Castro Theatre as part of the
``Berlin &AMP; Beyond'' film series. The silent film, co-directed by
Fanck and G.W. Pabst (``The Threepenny Opera''), will be shown in a
newly restored print with live organ accompaniment by Dennis James.
</P>
<P>
   Riefenstahl stars as a young bride who braves a mountain
expedition in the Swiss Alps and endures avalanches, her husband's
fall from a mountain and a dramatic search-and-rescue mission.
</P>
<P>
   Although Riefenstahl, a former dancer, had become a skilled
mountaineer in two previous films _ and even scaled mountains in
bare feet and without ropes for the camera _ the making of ``Piz
Pal &LR; u &LR; '' required her to risk her life in freezing temperatures
without the benefit of a stunt double.
</P>
<P>
   ``The film was very hard to make, very cruel,'' Riefenstahl said
recently from her home in Poecking, a village south of Munich. The
crew worked in minus-28-degree weather, and Fanck, a harsh
taskmaster and stickler for detail, thought nothing of tying
Riefenstahl in ropes, hoisting her up the side of a mountain and
allowing a real avalanche to engulf her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I screamed, my eyes and ears hurt,'' Riefenstahl said in the
documentary about her life. ``Fanck kept the camera rolling on and
on. I really hated Fanck.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite frostbite and countless other risks, Riefenstahl made
three more films with Fanck, including ``SOS Iceberg,'' in which
she played a daredevil aviatrix, before she directed and starred in
her own mountain film, ``The Blue Light,'' in 1932.
</P>
<P>
   Riefenstahl once said that, in person, Hitler ``seemed a modest,
private individual. You couldn't imagine him stirring the masses.''
Speaking at his political rallies, however, ``he had a kind of
hypnotic effect that frightened me a little.''
</P>
<P>
   Riefenstahl said that when Hitler proposed that she direct
``Triumph of the Will,'' she didn't want to take on such a large
task _ ``I wanted to act'' _ and strongly suggested another
filmmaker for the job, Walter Ruttmann. But Hitler had made up his
mind. ``It was not possible to refuse,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In her memoirs, published in 1987, in the documentary about her
and in countless interviews, Riefenstahl has always pleaded
political naivete and claimed to be an artist just doing a job on
``Triumph of the Will.'' As for the horrors of World War II, she
has said, ``we didn't foresee the danger.''
</P>
<P>
   During a 30-minute phone conversation, Riefenstahl repeated
those claims and frequently handed the phone to her companion of 30
years, Horst Kettner, asking him to translate. Kettner, 56,
proceeded not only to translate but also to offer his own
interpretation.
</P>
<P>
   Regarding ``The Wonderful, Horrible Life of Leni Riefenstahl,''
Kettner said, the film was edited in such a way that ``the audience
has the feeling Leni is lying'' about her personal relationships
with Hitler and minister of propaganda Paul Joseph Goebbels.
</P>
<P>
   ``She will never escape,'' Kettner said, ``because there are
always people not even interested in the truth. They have made up
their mind, and they will always be against her ... This will
continue till her death.''
</P>
<P>
   Does Riefenstahl wish she could erase the period of her life
when she worked with Hitler?
</P>
<P>
   Kettner turns to Riefenstahl, translates the question into
German and returns to the phone, suggesting that the interviewer
refer to her memoirs for the answer.
</P>
<P>
   ```Triumph of the Will' is a stamp on her body,'' Kettner said,
``and for this she will have to suffer. Naturally, she would like
to erase it as you say, but there is no way to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Guilty or not, Riefenstahl has lived one of the most amazing,
resilient lives of the 20th century. Despite the criticism, she
thrives and continues to find new means of expression. In the '60s
she turned to photography and made two highly praised but
controversial books about the Nuba tribe of Africa.
</P>
<P>
   In her 70s, Riefenstahl turned to deep-sea diving. ``She is
still diving,'' Kettner said, ``but she is very unhappy because
since the end of May, after we returned from Papua New Guinea, she
couldn't dive because she got pneumonia.
</P>
<P>
   ``She dives because underwater she has no pain, and underwater
she is fantastic, like a fish.''
</P>
<P>
   Three days after the interview, a fax was sent to Riefenstahl
and Kettner with follow-up questions. On Monday, Riefenstahl's
secretary replied with a fax saying, ``Mrs. Riefenstahl is heavily
fallen ill with pneumonia.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
