<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE
</HEADLINE>
 ( nk ) 
c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   International
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL CURRENCY TO CONTINUE TO FLOAT AGAINST THE DOLLAR
</P>
<P>
   Brazil has decided to continue to allow the value of its
currency, the real, to be set by market forces, ending its
longstanding monetary policy of anchoring the real to its reserves.
</P>
<P>
   To keep the real from weakening further, Brazil's central bank
raised interest rates on overnight loans, and the administration of
President Fernando Henrique Cardoso said it was determined to take
whatever steps are necessary to avert a crippling new round of
inflation.
</P>
<P>
   The managing director of the International Monetary Fund, Michel
Camdessus, and the United States said they were heartened by
Brazil's pledge to keep interest rates high and slash its budget
deficit. But they offered no new financial aid and made clear that
Brazil's economic fate is largely in its own hands. The finance
minister of Brazil had been meeting with American officials in
Washington since Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   LOAN PAYMENT MISSED BY CHINA PORT
</P>
<P>
   Dalian International Trust and Investment, the finance arm of
one of China's biggest ports, missed a payment on a loan. The
missed payment comes less than 48 hours after the Guangdong
International Trust and Investment filed for bankruptcy. And it
underscores growing concern over loans to investment companies
across China.
</P>
<P>
   RENAULT MAY BUY STAKE IN NISSAN
</P>
<P>
   Renault said it is considering buying a stake in the troubled
Japanese auto maker Nissan Motor. A flurry of reports named
Renault, DaimlerChrysler and Ford Motor as companies considering a
link with Nissan.
</P>
<P>
   HONG KONG UNEMPLOYMENT AT 5.8%
</P>
<P>
   Hong Kong's unemployment rate rose to 5.8 percent in the fourth
quarter of 1998, up from 5.5 percent in the third quarter, and was
expected to increase further.
</P>
<P>
   NOMURA LOST MONEY IN 3RD QUARTER
</P>
<P>
   The Japanese brokerage firm Nomura Securities lost money in the
last three months of 1998, as Japan's economy sagged.
</P>
<P>
   Companies
</P>
<P>
   AT HOME IS EXPECTED TO BUY EXCITE
</P>
<P>
   The Internet Provider At Home Networks is expected to announce
Tuesday morning that it is acquiring Excite, the Internet portal,
in a deal valued at about $6 billion.
</P>
<P>
   HIGH-SPEED CONNECTION TO THE WEB
</P>
<P>
   The Internet service Snap, which is partly owned by NBC, plans
to announce a new service tailored for the small but growing number
of users who have high-speed connections to the World Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
   SOFTWARE TO LINK HOME APPLIANCES
</P>
<P>
   Royal Philips Electronics, Sony and Sun Microsystems plan to
create a computer network stretching from the living room to the
corporate computing center. As a result any electronic device built
with the software standards of these companies, including
televisions, stereo receivers and videocassette recorders, will be
controlled by the network.
</P>
<P>
   LAWSUIT FILED AGAINST NINE WEST
</P>
<P>
   A lawsuit has been filed on behalf of the millions of women who
have purchased Nine West shoes, contending that the footwear
company conspired with large department stores to illegally fix
prices.
</P>
<P>
   BRITISH AEROSPACE IN TALKS FOR UNIT
</P>
<P>
   British Aerospace acknowledged that it is in talks to buy
General Electric Company of Britain's Marconi Electronic Systems.
Analysts said media reports valuing the prospective deal at up to
$13 billion could indicate that British Aerospace was prepared to
offer a premium for Marconi, which makes warships, missiles and
military electronics.
</P>
<P>
   The Economy
</P>
<P>
   NEWS FROM BRAZIL PUSHES STOCKS UP
</P>
<P>
   London's blue-chip Financial Times Stock Exchange index rose
3.08 percent, or 182.9 points, to 6,123.9, as stock markets around
the world climbed after Brazil decided to let its currency float.
The DAX index in Frankfurt increased 2.07 percent; the Paris CAC 40
index ended 2.39 percent higher; the Mibtel index in Milan rose
2.41 percent, and the IBEX-35 index in Madrid was up 4.95 percent.
The Mexican market climbed half a percent, and the Brazilian
Bovespa index jumped 5.43 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Markets
</P>
<P>
   MARKETS REOPEN THIS MORNING
</P>
<P>
   The stock market and other financial markets in the United
States will reopen Tuesday. They were closed Monday in observance
of Martin Luther King Jr. Day.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
