<SLUG> BC-LAWFIRM-EXODUS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SIX DAY BERRY LAWYERS JOIN CHICAGO FIRM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNNLEY BROWNING  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Six lawyers at Day Berry &AMP; Howard, one of New England's
largest law firms, have left to join the new Boston office of
Seyfarth, Shaw, Fairweather &AMP; Geraldson, a Chicago-based practice
specializing in employment and labor law.
</P>
<P>
   The exodus temporarily leaves the employment and labor group at
Day Berry's Boston office with one third-year associate. It also
comes one month after prominent Day Berry lawyer Deval Patrick,
formerly the nation's top civil rights enforcer, quit to join
Texaco Inc. as general counsel.
</P>
<P>
   The new office of Seyfarth, Shaw, a leading 400-lawyer practice
with nine domestic offices and one in Brussels, is headed by former
Day Berry partner Joseph Ambash.
</P>
<P>
   Other ex-Day Berry staffers include partner Lisa Damon, four
associates, and one counsel, all of whom specialize in labor and
employment. The counsel left Day Berry late last year, before
deciding to join Seyfarth, Shaw.
</P>
<P>
   Ambash, 50, and Damon, 48, took over 20 client accounts to their
new employer, including a major New England retailer, a renowned
educational institution, and a prominent insurer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had developed an experienced regional and national practice
and we felt we needed a national law firm to better serve some of
our clients,'' Ambash said of the move.
</P>
<P>
   Ambash and Damon traditionally defend corporate management
against employment and labor-related charges, such as age
discrimination, wrongful discharge, and union issues, but they also
conduct unique managerial training programs and company
``diversity'' audits.
</P>
<P>
   ``While we're saddened by Joseph and Lisa's departure, we're
confident that we'll continue to have a significant presence in
employment and labor,'' Day Berry chairman Robert Siegel said from
Hartford, where the firm is based.
</P>
<P>
   Day Berry now has six partners and 20 associates in its
employment group, spread out over various offices, and will
maintain an employment and labor practice in Boston. The law firm,
New England's fifth largest, has a total of 220 lawyers and offices
in Stamford, Conn. It is expected some Stamford staffers will move
to the Boston office.
</P>
<P>
   But Day Berry will no longer focus on human resources training
and instead will concentrate on traditional dispute resolution,
Siegel said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-18-99 2210EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990118.0451 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
