<HEADLINE>
RANGERS RE-SIGN HELLING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
ARLINGTON, Texas _ Right-hander Rick Helling, who this past season
emerged as only the third 20-game winner during the Rangers'
27-year existence, signed the most lucrative contract awarded to a
first-year, arbitration-eligible pitcher.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Rangers and their 28-year-old pitcher yesterday avoided a
February salary arbitration hearing after the two parties reached
agreement on a three-year contract worth $10.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   This agreement surpassed the three-year, $8.5 million contracts
right-hander Shane Reynolds and left-hander Kirk Rueter received
from the Astros and Giants as first-year, arbitration-eligible
pitchers before the 1997 and '98 seasons, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Helling, who this past season earned $216,500, joined
right-handers Roger Clemens and David Cone and left-hander Tom
Glavine as the major leagues' only 20-game winners.
</P>
<P>
   Helling, who went 20-7 with a 4.41 earned-run average, will
receive $2.25 million for 1999. That compares favorably to the
one-year contract right-hander Jose Lima, 26, signed Sunday with
the Astros.
</P>
<P>
   Lima, an arbitration-eligible pitcher who this past season
earned $240,000, went 16-8 with a 3.70 ERA during 33 starts for the
Astros. Those two parties avoided an arbitration hearing after
reaching agreement on a one-year contract worth $2.15 million.
</P>
<P>
   Helling also will receive $3.75 million for 2000 and $4.5
million for 2001, but the three-year contract represents a gamble
for the pitcher and the organization.
</P>
<P>
   Helling likely would earn much more through a series of
arbitration hearings the next three years should his future
performance approximate this past season. Helling and his
representative, Jeff Moorad, took security in the form of the
multiyear contract.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers likely will benefit from the contract should Helling
remain healthy and approximate his 1998 performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's give and take there, and both sides have to be willing
to give up a little to get something,'' Helling said. ``I'm
perfectly happy with the deal. I wouldn't have signed the deal if I
didn't think it was fair. The one-year contract I would have signed
\Rthrough arbitration\S for whatever amount would have been enough
for me to live off of for the rest of my life.
</P>
<P>
   ``So, I didn't sign the long-term contract just for more money.
It didn't have anything to do with the money. It was the fact the
organization was willing and believed in me that much just to offer
the deal made me feel good.''
</P>
<P>
   Helling's contract also includes performance incentives that
include bonuses of $100,000 for becoming the American League's most
valuable player or Cy Young Award recipient and bonuses of $75,000
or $50,000 should he finish either second or third in the voting.
</P>
<P>
   Helling also will receive $50,000 for being selected MVP of the
AL Championship Series or World Series and can earn an additional
$25,000 for being selected to the All-Star Game or capturing a Gold
Glove Award.
</P>
<P>
   Helling, whose ERA ranked only 26th among AL qualifiers,
benefited from the Rangers' run support. Helling's support of 6.61
runs per nine innings ranked fifth among AL qualifiers, but the
right-hander also emerged as the Rangers' only pitcher with a
winning record in games which the offense produced 2-5 runs.
</P>
<P>
   Helling went 7-3 with one no decision in those games while the
remainder of the rotation went 7-24. It serves as one reason why
general manager Doug Melvin called Helling ``a model of
consistency.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I see no reason in the world, with our offense and improved
defense why Rick Helling can't win 20 games again,'' Rangers
manager Johnny Oates said. Briefly Rangers catcher Ivan Rodriguez,
who assured the organization that he would not play this winter in
the Puerto Rican League, kept his word.
</P>
<P>
   That also prevents the seven-time Gold Glove Award recipient
from being eligible to represent his native Puerto Rico during the
Caribbean World Series next month in San Juan, Puerto Rico.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers yesterday signed right-hander Joe Hudson to a
minor-league contract and assigned the 28-year-old pitcher to
Oklahoma of the Pacific Coast League.
</P>
<P>
   Hudson made his only major-league appearance of 1998 with the
Brewers and spent the remainder of the season with Triple-A
Pawtucket and Louisville of the International League. Hudson, who
owns a 6-7 record with a 4.82 ERA during 102 major-league
appearances, will report to early minor-league camp in February.
</P>
<P>
   Ray Coley joined the organization as a member of the Rangers'
professional scouting staff. Coley spent the past five seasons as
the Twins' major-league advance scout.
 &LR; tagtop:Johnny Paul, (817) 390-7760
 &LR; tagbottom:jpaul\Nstar-telegram.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
