<HEADER>
A8311 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-CLINTON-ADDRESS-     01-18 0681
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-CLINTON-ADDRESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: STATE OF THE AGENDAS 
</HEADLINE>
  ( nk ) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Tuesday, Jan. 19,
1999:
</P>
<P>
   By tradition and the tense circumstances of the moment, this is
President Clinton's day. In the evening, Clinton will march into a
House chamber torn by emotion and partisanship over impeachment to
deliver his seventh State of the Union speech. The address is to
follow, by a few hours, the opening of Clinton's defense in the
Senate. The president is not the only figure on the spot, however.
Today the Republican congressional leadership must begin a year of
engaging a president with high approval ratings on something more
than his personal scandals.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has always seemed most at home in these addresses, and
the White House has skillfully leaked details in advance. There
will be aid for the elderly, disabled and schoolchildren, with tax
credits the preferred mechanism. Projected budget surpluses should
be set aside to ``save Social Security first,'' a mantra that
proved effective last year in fending off Republican tax cuts. The
speech is to call for more teachers, more strict federal education
standards, more police and more money for military readiness and to
preserve open spaces, but not too much more money. It all has a
familiar centrist ring. Riding the crest of a gravity-defying
economic boom, Clinton must feel that there is no sense in
abandoning what works politically.
</P>
<P>
   As they brace for an address centered on these issues, the
Republicans are a picture of fractious internal dissent. Dennis
Hastert, the genial but untested House speaker, has yet to
articulate his priorities, beyond declaring that he is not Newt
Gingrich. In the last couple of weeks, alarmed Republican leaders
have been hit by new polls and complaints from top fund-raisers
that voter impatience with the impeachment process has sent the
party to its lowest standing in a generation. They know that they
must put together their own legislative agenda as soon as everyone
can agree on what it is.
</P>
<P>
   Republican strategists say they want this Congress to
concentrate on five broad areas: tax cuts, primary and secondary
education, crime and drugs, national defense and Social Security.
But the word is that they will try, at least at first, to be
conciliatory to the White House and see if some agreements can be
reached on things like school construction and aid for special
education. Some party leaders seem to fear that the wounds will be
so raw after the Senate trial and verdict on Clinton that they must
seize on something, anything, to show they can cooperate with the
White House.
</P>
<P>
   Whether Clinton will be in a mood to cooperate and compromise is
another question. Some Democrats will advise the White House that
more confrontation with Republicans will better position the
party's candidates in the 2000 election. Social Security is certain
to be the early test. Last week Democrats and Republicans said a
Social Security deal, leaving the system basically intact but
making room for voluntary private investment accounts, is already
being discussed.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, for his part, would like to prove wrong those who are
predicting that the impeachment process will leave him politically
immobilized even if it leaves him in office. He seems to want to
settle the Social Security problem first, rescuing the system from
insolvency as baby boomers start to retire in 15 years. The
administration wants a commitment on using some of the projected
budget surpluses _ $1.5 trillion over the next 10 years, by some
measures _ to keep Social Security functioning, and later decide
whether to make additional surplus money available for other
priorities, like tax cuts. Republicans are likely to want tax cuts
to be a part of any Social Security deal.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has an excruciating balancing act to pull off Tuesday
night. But so do the Republicans. They are now at war over
impeachment. Soon they will have to decide whether to continue that
war on the legislative front.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
