<HEADLINE>
PARCELLS TAKES FIRST STEP TOWARD IMPROVEMENT BY SIGNING MITCHELL
</HEADLINE>
   (ms) 
 By GERALD ESKENAZI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HEMPSTEAD, N.Y. _ Bill Parcells started to work on next season
barely 12 hours after the Jets came within 30 minutes of going to
the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells, still trying to sort his emotions after Sunday's 23-10
loss to the Denver Broncos, said Monday he would return for a third
season as the coach. While the 57-year-old Parcells admitted being
tired as he contemplated starting a playoff run again _ ``I feel
I'm behind already'' _ he said he &UR;  &LR;  was proud of his players.
</P>
<P>
   So was Leon Hess, the club's 84-year-old owner. When the team
arrived back in New York at 1:15 Monday morning, Hess was there to
greet them. He shook each player's hand. Hess has not traveled with
the team since the 1997 season.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells, who has had four heart procedures, gets practically no
sleep after a game, win or lose. But he met with his players, held
a 45-minute news conference and began to retool his roster for
1999. Among his announcements Monday:
</P>
<P>
   _ He surprised nearly everyone by signing Johnny Mitchell _ yes,
that Johnny Mitchell. He was the club's first-round draft pick in
1992, a tight end who played four seasons but ultimately symbolized
the failure of much of the 1990s. He has been out of football since
1996, spending part of the time in Rio de Janeiro and also trying
some modeling roles.
</P>
<P>
   _ He gave Bill Belichick, his highly regarded assistant head
coach and defensive coordinator, permission to speak to the Kansas
City Chiefs and Chicago Bears regarding their head-coaching
positions. Belichick, however, is the heir apparent here. Parcells
also said &UR;  &LR;  his entire coaching staff had been rehired, as was all
the front-office personnel that came with his new administration in
1997.
</P>
<P>
   _ He told the starters Kyle Brady (tight end) and Matt O'Dwyer
(right guard), whose contracts are up, that he would like to have
them back _ but not at any price. He imparted the same information
to linebacker Dwayne Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells said he was proud of the job that he did, pointing out
how the Jets had ``made a lot of strides that the team hadn't done
before _ winning on the road, big games, winning a division _ the
deciding game.''
</P>
<P>
   He characterized his players as a ``hard-working, 90-percent
attentive team. I like this team. I've got kids that know what we
want.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of those ``kids'' such as 35-year-old quarterback Vinny
Testaverde said he ``lay in bed, wide awake, thinking _ if we would
have made this play or converted that first down things would be
different and we'd be going to Miami. But it's not the case today.
We have something to be motivated about coming back next year and
trying to make another run at it.''
</P>
<P>
   There was plenty of second-guessing in the aftermath of Denver's
victory. The Jets led by 10-0 early in the third quarter, moving
the ball well while the defense tied up John Elway and his
receivers.
</P>
<P>
   But while the Jets had overcome first-half fumbles by Curtis
Martin and Keith Byars, it still was &UR;  &LR; n &UR; o &LR; t enough to push Denver
to the brink. Parcells said Monday that with that 10-0 edge, he was
about to start running ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now you're going to see the running attack, but by the time we
got the ball back it was tied,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   After the Jets were up by 10 points, the Broncos struck quickly,
getting a good kickoff return and then a touchdown from Elway to
Howard Griffith. When Meggett was unable to field the ensuing
kickoff &UR; ,  &LR;  the Broncos recovered it and kicked the tying field
goal. It all happened in 3 minutes 33 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't put it on the pressure of the game,'' Parcells said.
Two of his veteran playoff performers, Martin and Byars, dropped
the ball. Parcells said he could not remember the last time he saw
Byars fumble _ ``maybe nine years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   And Testaverde said the mile-high altitude wasn't the reason
that the team faltered in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think all that is all a myth,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells dismissed Testaverde's two interceptions as
meaningless. They came late in the game with Testaverde throwing on
every down. One was a deflection.
</P>
<P>
   If things work out, the Jets will have a more varied offense.
Parcells said that he wanted Mitchell because the Jets were looking
to install plays designed to send tight ends downfield.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells' team has been the repository of revived careers with
Testaverde and Bryan Cox, the linebacker, reaching high levels of
play. The volatile Cox has been a stabilizing influence on the
defense.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell becoming a Jet again might not be such an odd idea. He
was known for his undisciplined routes and for blurting out
whatever was on his mind. Parcells explained that the signing of
Mitchell had been in the works for some time. He said that
Mitchell, who lives in South Florida, has spoken to several current
Jets whom he knew, asked about Parcells, and then called him.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell caught 154 passes in his four seasons, scoring 16
touchdowns and averaging a 13.5 yards a catch. He left the Jets
after 1995 as a free agent, went to Jimmy Johnson's first summer
camp and decided he had had enough of the torrid Miami heat within
a week. Later that season he signed with Dallas and got into four
games, catching one pass. But signing Mitchell is just one step for
Parcells in preparing for yet another season. There are, after all,
at least seven areas on the team to improve, he said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
