<DOCNO> NYT19990118.0459 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 22:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8317 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-RIKER-ENVIRON-2TAK     01-18 1081
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-RIKER-ENVIRON-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPERIMENT IN RECYCLING AND RENEWAL UNFOLDS AT JAIL COMPLEX
</HEADLINE>
  (bl)  
By DOUGLAS MARTIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As weekly pickups of recyclable trash spread to all
the neighborhoods of this city, there is one eco-friendly urban
corner that is way ahead of them, already providing pickups twice a
week.
</P>
<P>
   In the rest of the city, composting is confined to the odd
backyard, but gardeners in this place compost six tons of food
scraps a day. The $5 million plant where they do it, said to be the
world's largest devoted to composting only food, has a roof made of
photovoltaic cells, making it one of the city's most ambitious
efforts to turn sunlight into electricity.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, 30,000 pounds of vegetables were harvested here in
the city's largest community garden. There are daily classes on
garden design, plant care and other horticultural topics. There is
a Zen meditation pond, an ornamental grass garden and a native
woodlands area. Birds peck at suet in feeders as observers keep
lists of species.
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists visiting this spot might think they had died
and gone to eco-heaven, but this New York City address is nobody's
idea of paradise. It is Rikers Island, home to 10 jails and 16,000
inmates, to tall fences, miles of menacing razor ribbon and ominous
guard towers.
</P>
<P>
   But the experimental jail farm here is also a strikingly
unexpected laboratory for solving one of the city's most
intractable problems: getting rid of garbage. As Staten Island's
giant Fresh Kills landfill prepares to close in 2001 and the city
scrambles against mounting opposition to sending its trash out of
state, environmentalists say the jail complex is demonstrating how
to deal with more waste at home.
</P>
<P>
   The Rikers experiment is explicitly part of a waste-management
plan the city drafted in 1992 and updated last year. Ultimately,
experts say, if the city meets its recycling goals, all of its food
waste _ which at that point would be one-fourth of the city's total
garbage _ could be composted within the five boroughs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole purpose here is to remove the word waste from the
dictionary,'' said Thomas McCarthy, a spokesman with the city
Department of Correction. ``To take what used to be called waste
and find a use for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Greater self-sufficiency is also the main benefit of the other
environmental programs at Rikers. The farm last year raised 30,000
pounds of fresh vegetables for use in prison meals, an amount that
would have cost $8,111 to buy.
</P>
<P>
   Even more important, officials here say, are the practical and
psychological benefits inmates gain from learning new, possibly
money-making skills as well as from the simple pleasures of
gardening.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like serenity,'' said Frederick Lewis, 45, an inmate who
finds that the rewards in his job in the landscaping program go far
beyond the 15 cents an hour he is paid. ``There's a sense of
freedom.''
</P>
<P>
   From the prison authorities' perspective, the benefit is greater
control of potentially unruly inmates. ``You hardly have any
violence at all,'' said Gary Pereira, a correction officer for 12
years.
</P>
<P>
   Only inmates convicted of nonviolent offenses are allowed to
participate in the program at Rikers, a maximum-security prison
complex. But given that inmates work with pitchforks, shovels and
shears, security concerns are paramount and gardeners are
pat-searched coming and going. ``No one's going nowhere until all
the tools are counted,'' said Manuel Monserrat, a correction
officer.
</P>
<P>
   Terrariums are made with unbreakable plastic rather than with
glass, and garbage compactors must be searched to make sure inmates
are not trying to escape with recyclable material.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the hands-on work, the program involves daily classroom
instruction: a blackboard has two dozen words, like
``chloroplast,'' ``anther'' and ``mulch.'' Inmates learn how to
cultivate house plants and design outdoor gardens. In the native
plants area, they have planted dogwood, juniper and plum trees.
They make their own decisions on garden design. Women in prison
made the biological symbol for female the centerpiece of one
garden.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, inmates collected worms for a nestful of baby
mockingbirds. They scattered ladybugs about as a weapon against
aphids that were attacking the plants. They were amazed to learn
that tulips grow from bulbs, not seeds. In the farm program, which
runs from April through September, they grew zucchini, tomatoes,
peppers and other vegetables.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nurturing,'' said Frederick Lewis, 45, a former
construction worker from East Harlem who would not specify his
offense. ``Planting a seed and seeing it grow is more satisfying
than just eating the stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   David Brown, 41, of the Bronx, who was convicted of stripping
automobiles, said: ``I knew my cars. Now I know my plants.''
</P>
<P>
   On a day-to-day basis, the Rikers program, operated by the
Horticulture Society of New York, is run by James Jiler, 39, who
quit his job as a Wall Street commodities analyst and joined the
Peace Corps. He advised the government of Nepal on organic farming.
He picked up a master's degree in urban forestry from Yale
University. He works with prisoners five days a week.
</P>
<P>
   More than 200 inmates have participated. For the women, Jiler
teaches a course on house plant care, encouraging them to think of
themselves as doctors nurturing patients. For the men, he is
beginning a program to raise plants for use in landscaping grounds
next to city bus garages. Other plants have gone to the median
islands on upper Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to encourage a sense of creativity,'' Jiler said.
</P>
<P>
   In helping to make things grow, Rikers Island is returning to
its roots. It began as a 90-acre farm owned by the Riker family,
and through the dumping of waste was expanded to 450 acres. It
became a prison in the 1930s.
</P>
<P>
   In 1986, the Horticulture Society started a greenhouse and
landscaping program, but the administration of Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani ended it for budgetary reasons in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   The society returned in September 1997 partly because the
gardening program fit into other programs. For instance, the
society uses plants from Rikers Island to beautify the lawns of
landmark Carnegie libraries. And the new society president, Anthony
Smith, is also a director of South 40 Corp., which helps former
inmates find jobs. The society has promised to pay all of the
program's bills.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Smith contends that the program is more than worth the cost.
``Inmates may be seeing something for the first time that is going
to live or die based on what they do or don't do,'' he said. He
added that in the program's first incarnation, 25 percent of
participants returned to prison after they were released, compared
with more than 60 percent of the general population.
</P>
<P>
   The recycling and composting operations would seem to involve
inmates the least, but their participation is actually crucial. It
is the job of one correction officer, Sandra Simmons, to get the
prisoners' attention; they must sort food waste into the right bins
for the program to have any chance of working.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to be very demanding to be taken seriously,'' said
Ms. Simmons, whom inmates have dubbed the Garbage Queen. ``If you
ask for 100 percent, you get 50 percent. It works.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Simmons got her appreciation for recycling from her mother,
who took her to a recycling and redemption center near their Queens
home when she was a little girl. She found that few inmates had the
same background. Most thought the waste was being taken to hog
farms to be used as swill. ``Some couldn't care less and some were
confused,'' she said. ``But for some, it was like the circle of
life.''
</P>
<P>
   The goal of the composting operation is to take the process from
backyards to a much larger part of the population. If composting
can be shown to be economical in the large Rikers Island project,
other composting centers might be constructed around the city. The
compost could be used in parks, golf courses and botanical gardens
and for other uses, both within and outside the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``How to do anything beyond backyard composting in New York City
becomes very, very complex,'' said Thomas Outerbridge, who
originally planned the project as a Sanitation Department official
and now works as an environmental consultant.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our first idea was that the project must be big enough to
catch the attention of the people at sanitation,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The composting center cost $5 million, mostly from state money,
and is on an isolated corner of the island unlikely to be used for
a new jail. It enables the Correction Department to avoid using
hundreds of garbage trucks that otherwise might pose a security
risk, and the department pays nothing to the Sanitation Department
for running the program.
</P>
<P>
   Each day, the residue of 60,000 meals is mixed with recycled
cardboard into a yeasty substance that smells like manure. The
final result is high-grade fertilizer for use in the gardening and
farm programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the largest composting facility in America used strictly
for food waste,'' said Robert LaValva, the Sanitation Department's
chief of composting. ``This is the point of reference for the rest
of the city.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, maybe. Neighbors have been known to complain about the
odor from composting. Nobody had to ask the prisoners for their
view.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
