<SLUG> BC-HKN-DEVILS-SHARKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEVILS' OFFENSE TURNS COLD IN CALIFORNIA
</HEADLINE>
   (ms) 
 By ALEX YANNIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JOSE, Calif. _ Unable to get their offense in gear, the
Devils began a three-game trip to California on &UR;  &LR; Monday afternoon
with a 3-1 loss to the San Jose Sharks. Even though they took 34
shots at goalie Mike Vernon, the Devils managed only a power-play
goal by Brian Rolston.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd like to start a trip a lot better than we did,'' Coach
Robbie Ftorek said after the Devils' fourth loss in the last five
games. ``But we've got to play 60 minutes in each of the next two
games. We didn't execute as well as we needed to in this game.''
</P>
<P>
   The Devils (23-14-5), who have won twice in eight games this
month, will play at Anaheim on Wednesday and at Los Angeles on
Thursday. The Devils will need forwards Jason Arnott, Patrik Elias
and Vadim Sharifijanov, all of whom missed Monday's game because of
the flu.
</P>
<P>
   The Sharks (15-18-10), who entered the game with their power
play ranked 25th among the 27 National Hockey League teams,
capitalized on their first power play of the game. Jeff Friesen,
who found himself alone to the left of goalie Martin Brodeur,
converted Marco Sturm's pass from the other side for his 12th goal
of the season, 8 minutes 49 seconds into the game.
</P>
<P>
   Rolston tied the score three minutes into the second period when
his blistering shot from the high slot passed through a crowd, hit
the left post and then caromed off Vernon before going into the net
for Rolston's 12th goal of the season. The power-play goal was the
fourth in the last seven attempts by the Devils, who had three
power-play goals in five attempts in their previous game, a victory
over the Tampa Bay Lightning.
</P>
<P>
   ``The plan is to shoot the puck on net with people in front,''
Rolston said afterward. ``We just want to have traffic in front to
distract the goalie.''
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Marleau regained the lead for the Sharks just over two
minutes after Rolston's goal when he outmuscled Kevin Dean with a
move from left to right and flipped the puck over Brodeur's left
shoulder for his ninth of the season. Stephane Matteau closed the
scoring with 2:58 left.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Pandolfo and Bobby Holik had great chances for the Devils
after they pulled Brodeur for an extra attacker with 1:43 left in
the game, but Vernon came up with fine saves both times.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-18-99 2252EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
