<HEADER>
A8456 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXAS-HIGHTOWER-JOB-C     01-18 0554
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-HIGHTOWER-JOB-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Former state representative to head HMO for convicts
 &HT;    By Mike Ward
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Former state Rep. Allen Hightower, the powerful
and longtime chairman of a legislative committee that oversaw
Texas' prison system, is going back to work for the state _ this
time as head of the huge state-run HMO for convicts.
</P>
<P>
   Hightower, a sponsor of the law that created the health
maintenance organization program six years ago, became executive
director of the Correctional Managed Health Care Program on Jan. 13
_ a day after leaving the House seat he held 16 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a 22-hour retirement,'' Hightower said Monday. ``My
replacement (as a legislator) was sworn in on Tuesday, and I was at
work in my new job at 10 a.m. Wednesday morning.''
</P>
<P>
   In his new $120,000-a-year job, Hightower will oversee medical
care for Texas' 145,000 convicts _ a $290 million system run under
contract by the University of Texas Medical Branch in Galveston and
Texas Tech University's Health Sciences Center.
</P>
<P>
   Under state law, lawmakers are not prohibited from taking state
jobs after they leave office. Some prison officials suggested
privately Monday that Hightower, reportedly one of three finalists,
was the natural choice _ because he helped form the system and
because of his long history in shaping Texas criminal justice
policy.
</P>
<P>
   While he was a lawmaker, Hightower chaired the House Corrections
Committee. He also worked as the Huntsville operations chief for
Brazos Valley Transit, which operates rural and urban bus systems
in numerous East Texas communities. Hightower said he resigned that
job to accept the new post.
</P>
<P>
   The Correctional Managed Health Care Program was created in 1993
to save money and has been the target of frequent complaints by
convicts about inadequate care. Those complaints are expected to be
the focus of a federal court hearing on prison conditions scheduled
to begin Thursday in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   State officials hope the hearing before U.S. District Judge
William Wayne Justice is a first step to ending more than two
decades of court supervision of Texas prisons. Convicts' attorneys
hope Justice will retain supervision of the state's prisons.
</P>
<P>
   Hightower said he has no doubt the prison medical system is
constitutional.
</P>
<P>
   He replaces Dr. James Riley, who announced his retirement Jan.
1. Prison officials said Riley, who had headed the program since
its inception, has agreed to stay on through May to ease the
transition. In recent years, the prison health care system has
pioneered use of video exams to allow doctors at one unit to treat
sick convicts at another. The managed care idea was proposed by
former Comptroller John Sharp as part of his once-very-two years
performance review of state government. The idea drew criticism at
first from prison officials and others worried about state jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because I represented Huntsville, I had a lot of constituent
concern about what would happen to prison jobs,'' he said. ``But I
now think John Sharp was right on this one. This has saved a whole
lot of money, a lot more than we thought it would.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Ward writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
