<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-GRANNY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESERT DOESN'T DETER 88-YEAR-OLD FROM CAMPAIGN REFORM
</HEADLINE>
 
(Attention Arizona editors.) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Will also move in the ``n'' California news file.) 
BY MICHAEL COIT  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Striding across the sun-baked desert in eastern
California, Doris ``Granny D'' Haddock was finishing a particularly
lonely leg Monday in her cross-country trek to promote campaign
finance reform.
</P>
<P>
   Haddock, 88, is weathering the remote, rugged area between
Twentynine Palms and the Arizona border with help from volunteers
whose ranks have grown since she started her crusade after the
Tournament of Roses parade on New Year's Day.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's in a difficult spot right now in the middle of the
desert. If we take it slow, it's just a nice walk every day of the
week,'' said Dennis Burke, executive director of Arizona Common
Cause.
</P>
<P>
   Drawing on decades of activism, Haddock wants to generate a
groundswell for campaign finance reform. She said she was furious
when the U.S. Senate last year killed a measure that would have
banned the use of unlimited, unregulated large donations to
political parties, known as ``soft money.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to try to educate the people about why they should
care. This is a social issue because our system is breaking down.
We're losing our democracy, we're giving it away to the
corporations,'' Haddock said in a recent interview.
</P>
<P>
   The diminutive great-grandmother from Dublin, N.H., is following
Highway 62 as it wanders between mountain ranges, with the Colorado
River Aqueduct in frequent view.
</P>
<P>
   Burke and a handful of his Common Cause members are driving a
9-year-old donated camper van alongside Haddock. It provides a
comfortable rest stop, and a haven for meals and sleep.
</P>
<P>
   They took over assisting the pilgrim for political change in
Twentynine Palms on Wednesday. Ralph Langley, an Upland, Calif.,
retiree and Common Cause member, found homes for Haddock and drove
her to speaking appearances for the first 13 days.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hasn't been easy, but this woman is just unbelievable,''
Langley said. ``She deserves it. Here's a lady who's putting her
life on the line with this journey.''
</P>
<P>
   Rest in a Parker, Ariz., motel is on Haddock's itinerary this
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The hiatus also will feature an 89th birthday celebration for
Haddock. The desert location is fine with her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a wonderful birthday present,'' she said in a
recent interview. ``God has been good to me to make me as healthy
as I am at my age.''
</P>
<P>
   Any stop also is an opportunity to make a pitch for her cause.
</P>
<P>
   Haddock is equally earnest about her journey, counting on
strangers to provide meals and lodging.
</P>
<P>
   Recognizing such help would be as sparse as vegetation in the
desert, Haddock was prepared to bear a backpack with camping gear
for nights under the stars.
</P>
<P>
   The contingent in the camper van took that weight off her
shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   ``She gets pretty tuckered after eight (miles), takes a nap, and
then she walks the last two miles for the day and calls it quits,''
Burke noted. ``The only thing that can stop us is her health or her
feet. We're urging her not to stretch herself.''
</P>
<P>
   Burke has Common Cause members across Arizona ready to take in
Haddock. He noted she will need five or six weeks to reach New
Mexico, where that state's chapter is organizing assistance.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are disappointed that they're not along her route.
Those who are are really getting jazzed,'' Burke said. ``She's a
remarkable lady.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
