u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRAZIL-ECON-2NDLEDE-W     01-18 1269
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAZIL-ECON-2NDLEDE-WRITETHRU-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEARING INFLATION, BRAZIL STRIVES FOR A CURRENCY AT MARKET VALUE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS throughout for extensive editing refinements: 1st graf,
qualifying phrase (all but) inserted; 2nd graf, 1st sentence
reworked; 3rd graf, additional sentence added to end; 4th graf,
wording refined; grafs 5, 7-9 ,  11-13 and 15 completely subbed. ) (See also BRAZIL-AID) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(pr) 
 By DIANA JEAN SCHEMO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAO PAULO, Brazil _ Brazil said on Monday that it would continue
to allow the value of its currency, the real, to be set by market
forces, all but abandoning a policy to support the currency, which
was draining billions from its reserves of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   With the government still seeking some control over the
currency, the nation's central bank raised interest rates on
overnight loans on Monday to keep the real from weakening further.
And Pedro Malan, Brazil's finance minister, told U.S. officials in
Washington that President Fernando Henrique Cardoso's
administration was determined to take whatever steps were necessary
to avert a crippling new round of inflation.
</P>
<P>
   The government's move to allow the real to trade freely against
the dollar had lifted the Bovespa stock market index by 33.4
percent on Friday, and its announcement on Monday kindled a further
upswing, with the index rising 5.4 percent. Though U.S. exchanges
were closed for Martin Luther King Jr. Day, markets across Europe
rose. The real, however, fell an additional 10 percent, to 1.58 to
the dollar. It has plunged 24 percent since the government first
moved to devalue the currency.
</P>
<P>
   The decision by Brazil ends a policy that had been geared toward
suppressing once-crippling inflation by pegging the currency to the
dollar, which helps keep a tight rein on the money supply.
</P>
<P>
   That was a key feature of the so-called Real Plan, which
Cardoso's government introduced in 1994. But the country could no
longer afford to defend the currency with its diminishing reserves,
which must also be used to pay foreign debt. Brazil's economy has
been stagnating; unemployment is at near-record levels; exports are
falling and the trade deficit is way up, and the nation's troubles
have aroused fears of an Asian-style collapse that could weaken
economies throughout the region, including in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The central bank said on Monday that ``as of today,'' it would
``allow the interbank market (both free and floating segments) to
define the exchange rate.'' It added that the central bank might
intervene in the future ``occasionally and in a limited way, with
the goal of countering disordered movement in exchange rates.''
</P>
<P>
   With the currency disconnected from the dollar, editorial
cartoons in one newspaper pictured Malan and the new central bank
president, Francisco Lopes, flying in a red purse in search of
solutions to Brazil's difficulties. On Saturday, the handbag was
shown taking them to Washington for talks with the International
Monetary Fund, which has promised to lend $41.5 billion to help
Brazil weather its crisis. Brazil has already received $9 billion
from the package, and another $9 billion is to be released at the
end of February. Brazilian and U.S. officials said on Monday that
there were no discussions about granting the loans ahead of
schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Communications Minister Pimenta da Veiga said the president was
``extremely impressed with the reaction of the markets'' to
Friday's devaluation, during which the real did not lose the 30
percent in value that economists had predicted. He said there would
be ``a period with moments of tension, certainly'' but added, ``The
floating of the currency has had a very positive result.''
</P>
<P>
   A weak currency can help stimulate exports by making them
cheaper abroad. But a weak currency also reduces the purchasing
power of consumers, particularly when buying imports, and puts
downward pressure on the currencies of neighboring nations.
</P>
<P>
   Cardoso told reporters on Monday in Brasilia that free trading
on the currency could lead to a resurgence of the real. Now, he
said, ``we are more dependent on ourselves,'' particularly on the
willingness of the Brazilian Congress to cut spending and special
benefits for vested interests.
</P>
<P>
   The attention of investors is turning to Brasilia, where
Congress is expected to take the second of a series of votes needed
to extend and increase a tax on financial transactions. The tax is
part of an austerity plan, estimated at $23.5 billion in tax
increases and spending cuts before the devaluation, that was a
condition for Brazil to win IMF backing for a standby loan last
fall. The austerity plan is intended to reduce a huge budget
deficit and restore international confidence in the economy.
</P>
<P>
   The government is also sending a bill to Congress this week that
would make civil servants contribute to the public pension system,
which Congress has already rejected four times. Public workers
enjoy generous lifetime pensions equal to, or higher than, their
salaries when working, and benefits for an estimated 1.8 million of
them are expected to produce a $30 billion deficit this year.
</P>
<P>
   If Congress acts decisively, said William Cline, chief economist
at the Institute for International Finance in Washington, a
research institute for major banking, financial and investment
groups, ``chances are relatively good that confidence will rebuild,
and that will allow the central bank to reduce interest rates and
take a lot of the severe recessionary pressure off the economy.''
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, Malan said Brazil would not ask the International
Monetary Fund to speed up the second stage of its standby loan, but
he said that the Brazilian government would have to redouble
efforts to cut spending and would probably increase interest rates
further.
</P>
<P>
   As investment specialists here braced for a possible new round
of austerity moves from the government, short-term interest rates
rose.
</P>
<P>
   Martin Arranz, who tracks international markets at Banco Patente
in Sao Paolo, said he expected the government to announce another
series of measures in the next few weeks to help it pay
dollar-denominated debts due in 1999, which he estimated rose by
$13 billion just with last week's devaluation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The worst is not here yet,'' Arranz said. ``With the money
devalued, economic activity will shrink even more. Companies that
began to invest are going to put on the brakes.''
</P>
<P>
   Cardoso is insisting that Brazil has not abandoned controlling
inflation, which sank below 1 percent last year. Today, he called
on Brazilian businesses not to trigger instant inflation by raising
prices in response to the devaluation.
</P>
<P>
   Banking experts say that despite the devaluation, Brazil is in
better position to meet its external obligations than Mexico in
1994 or Korea in 1997, both of which devalued their currencies in
response to financial crises.
</P>
<P>
   Across Latin America, markets rose modestly on Monday after
Brazil said it had abandoned its policy of spending down dollar
reserves to defend its overvalued currency. Only the Merval index
in Argentina closed down, dropping 2.4 percent, with business
leaders there calling for trade barriers to keep out a flood of
suddenly cheaper Brazilian imports.
</P>
<P>
   The Brazilian devaluation is exerting severe pressure on
Argentina, which backs the value of each peso with a dollar in
reserves and relies on a currency board to set monetary policy. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
