<SLUG> BC-GEN-JANKO-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JANKOVICH: FUND RAISING IS CSUN ANSWER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; LOS ANGELES _ Six weeks as interim athletic director has taught
Sam Jankovich something:
</P>
<P>
   Nearly everything wrong with the Cal State Northridge athletic
department can be solved by overhauling its lackluster fund-raising
efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Offering an in-depth assessment of the oft-troubled program for
the first time, Jankovich said CSUN athletics receive plenty of
money from the state, the Big Sky Conference is ``the right fit''
for the school and none of the 20 sports programs is in jeopardy of
being cut.
</P>
<P>
   Jankovich _ who six weeks ago replaced Paul Bubb, who was
pressured to resign in the wake of Michael Abraham's drug arrest _
believes the university must drastically improve its outreach to
the San Fernando Valley. There it is the most significant
intellectual and one of the most important economic institutions.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing I found is there are a lot of resources available to
the athletic department that might not have been used but that will
be used as far as the future is concerned,'' Jankovich said.
</P>
<P>
   Further, Jankovich _ the former Washington State and University
of Miami athletic director who was brought out of retirement by
president Blenda Wilson to lay the foundation for a permanent
replacement he will help hire this summer _ is emphasizing
individual performance and accountability.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not here to make rash decisions, but people have to be
energetic and enthusiastic,'' Jankovich said. ``The bottom line is
everybody's got to perform. And everybody's got a scorecard.''
</P>
<P>
   Jankovich said he was shocked to learn how athletics at CSUN
operated, including such basics as communication.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past, somebody saw a need, but it wasn't met,'' said
Grace Collins, associate athletic director/business. ``Either three
people tried to fill the need and you had three people working on
it, or everyone saw the need and thought someone else was taking
care of it, and nothing got done.''
</P>
<P>
   That Jankovich has such a grasp on the situation comes as no
surprise to Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a very quick study, a delight to work with and he's
getting his feet under him,'' Wilson said. ``His insights will be
good for us. The people in the community have reached out to Sam in
a very generous way.'' &QL; 
Fund raising: the linchpin &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;
</P>
<P>
   It is Jankovich's highest priority and it's his area of
expertise. When he arrived at the University of Miami in 1983, the
athletic program raised $300,000 annually. It surpassed $3 million
when he left.
</P>
<P>
   Many CSUN coaches have cited state-funding cuts as the reason
behind their tight budgets. However, Jankovich said, that's
nonsense.
</P>
<P>
   During the 1997-98 athletic season, CSUN received $5.2 million
from the state and an additional $1.6 million in student fees,
according to Collins. By contrast, CSUN raised $302,798, including
$100,000 by an outside party.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this program has more potential than people think in
terms of getting outside support,'' Jankovich said. ``We have to
work with all of the club people who are so adamant that they want
these programs, and then we have to see if we can get them involved
to really assist us.''
</P>
<P>
   Community outrage saved four men's sports _ swimming,
volleyball, soccer and baseball _ from budget cuts two summers ago.
The outcry resulted in overwhelming emotional support, but CSUN
never capitalized financially.
</P>
<P>
   Jankovich wants to increase activity in the Matador Athletic
Association, which has 649 members _ a staggeringly low figure
considering more than 100,000 CSUN graduates live in the Los
Angeles area.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody did this job for two years and I'm trying to rebuild
it,'' said assistant athletic director/development Michael Rehm, in
his second year of heading CSUN's fund-raising department. ``There
were no board members and now we have a board. I need to depend on
my board to help me get this thing done.'' &QL; 
Becoming known &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Key to these efforts is getting the persuasive Jankovich, and
CSUN's name and ideas, into the business community. Jankovich is an
accomplished and captivating speaker capable of seducing an
audience. He's been touring the local Rotary clubs and attending
meetings of various chambers of commerce.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Wilson has held dinners at her home for local
community leaders, and more are scheduled as CSUN tries to tap into
a Valley it's neglected.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are a big part of the Valley, and to be a big part of the
Valley you have to be out there,'' Rehm said. ``We have to try to
meet the right people, show them our vision and see if they want to
get involved.''
</P>
<P>
   The school is working on several promotional agreements with
area businesses, including a prominent grocery store, Jankovich
said.
</P>
<P>
   CSUN received more than $300,000 through corporate support last
year, according to Brian Swanson, assistant athletic
director/external affairs. But that includes trade dollars, for
either advertisement or services provided, and is well beneath what
Jankovich projects the school could attract.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're working with some businesses to try to make a more
visible appearance in the community,'' Swanson said. ``We've made a
real concerted effort to get out there more.''
</P>
<P>
   A good place to start might be with the student body. Student
attendance for games at the commuter school is typically mediocre.
</P>
<P>
   So Jankovich charged Brooke Michelle, CSUN's director of
marketing and promotions, with establishing a student board of
directors. These students will be responsible for on-campus
promotions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea behind it is the more people that have a personal
investment in the program, the more people will be interested,''
Michelle said. ``It's very successful at other universities, but I
haven't tried to launch it here because I question whether it can
be successful implementing a program run at bigger schools.'' &QL; 
Facilities &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Inevitably, fans, corporate sponsors and possible donors will
arrive at a Matadors athletic event.
</P>
<P>
   And see the facilities.
</P>
<P>
   They'll sit in the aging 1,600-seat gym for basketball, or visit
the high school-style football stadium or an unkempt track and
field complex.
</P>
<P>
   Jaknovich certainly has seen them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there has to be a significant improvement as far as
the workplace, the environment, the facilities,'' Jankovich said.
``We have to improve the training room, the locker rooms, so kids
don't have to shower at home.''
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for Jankovich, a major facilities overhaul was
already in the works.
</P>
<P>
   A 12-member comittee is holding its final hearing on Thursday,
and is expected to vote in favor for an 8,000-seat stadium on the
North Campus, near the present field.
</P>
<P>
   That would kickstart the building of a $2 million softball
facility and a new baseball field. The second phase in the
renovation to CSUN's gym could take place in the summer. Adding
seats to the second level of the gym would bump capacity to more
than 3,000. &QL; 
Substance-abuse policy &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Jankovich likely would not be at CSUN if it weren't for the
arrest by the FBI of former women's basketball coach Abraham on
cocaine-trafficking charges, which eventually led to Bubb's ouster.
</P>
<P>
   Jankovich, consulting with CSUN faculty athletic representative
Tom Shannon, has formed a ``blue-ribbon committee'' to review the
school's substance-abuse policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's also an extensive employee-assistance program that
includes a monthly seminar,'' Jankovich said. ``I feel that's going
to be most significant with helping people deal with stress, and
the pressures and everything else that goes along.'' &QL; 
Valley pride &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Jankovich realizes CSUN's athletic administration is
understaffed _ and young. Yet after six weeks, Jankovich's belief
that the athletic department can flourish if fund raising improves
to an as yet undefined level is unshakable.
</P>
<P>
   ``The budget is the budget,'' Jankovich said. ``We can't find
reasons on why certain things can't be done but rather how it can
be done.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, you have UCLA and USC and a lot of other things going on,
but this program has to be a great sense of pride for the San
Fernando Valley and Northridge. That's how it will be successful.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-18-99 2318EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990118.0470 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 23:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8472 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-COLUMN-TRASH-NYT     01-18 0757
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-COLUMN-TRASH-NYT </SLUG>
 
(ATTN: Va.) 
N.Y. COLUMN: CULTURE CITY TALKS TRASH TO UNIMPRESSED
VISITORS  (bl)  
By CLYDE HABERMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There is a way to keep the Great Trash War from
spinning out of control and landing in court as Giuliani vs. All
States:
</P>
<P>
   Insist that visitors to New York take their garbage with them
when they go back home. The city could even make money on the deal.
</P>
<P>
   This and other revenue-generating ideas percolated Monday, the
holiday honoring the Rev. Dr. Martin Luther King Jr. No disrespect,
but on the day of tribute to the martyred civil-rights leader, many
New Yorkers were more interested in tax deals that they could get
on clothing purchases than in his reflections on the human
condition.
</P>
<P>
   They took advantage of another week of tax-free shopping, and
looked forward to a permanent reduction of more than 50 percent,
scheduled to go into effect in December on sales under $110. Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani would like to eliminate every last tax on
clothing, and it is hard to imagine many New Yorkers' putting up an
argument.
</P>
<P>
   But since pendulums tend to swing, what will happen when the
economy heads south, causing store sales to slump, retail jobs to
shrink and municipal revenue to sag? The day may yet come when city
and state governments wish they had not waved goodbye to that sales
tax.
</P>
<P>
   Although recommendations on fiscal policy are not normally the
province of this department, the battle over New York's garbage
exports inspired a thought or two, offered here free to municipal
planners.
</P>
<P>
   Virginians, as you may have heard, got their noses out of joint
just because the mayor said they should be thrilled to bury our
trash in their soil. We give the outlanders Broadway and the Met,
and what do they do? They add to our mountains of garbage. There
should be more give and take, Giuliani suggested, a call for a
``reciprocal relationship'' that fell on many deaf ears in
Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   How about a different tack?
</P>
<P>
   If Virginia and other states refuse to help out, why not impose
a garbage-handling fee on the 32 million visitors a year to the
city? You could start with a small surcharge, say, $3 a day, on
each of the city's 60,000 hotel rooms, which are filled these days
almost to capacity.
</P>
<P>
   Three dollars would entail no hardship for guests already paying
close to $200 a night on average. But the fee could produce about
$65 million, roughly 10 percent of the Sanitation Department's
annual budget.
</P>
<P>
   True, it does smell like a new tax, which may cause the mayor to
wrinkle his nose. In that case, to return to the idea at the top,
why not make visitors cart their garbage home?
</P>
<P>
   Trash bags could be handed out at airports and train stations,
with prominent signs informing arriving out-of-towners what is
expected of them. Since most Americans consider themselves more
polite and, over all, more virtuous than New Yorkers, they could be
counted on to comply. They could be charged 25 cents or so per bag,
an inconsequential sum that should cover the cost of the program
and just might yield a profit.
</P>
<P>
   And if the city only breaks even, there will be other benefits.
</P>
<P>
   When the guests are ready to return home, many will inevitably
ask hotel attendants, apartment-house doormen, taxi drivers and
airport skycaps to help them carry the filled bags. That means
extra tips and more money for New Yorkers. The result could be an
income-tax bonanza.
</P>
<P>
   But even if they do not declare these tips, thousands of workers
will have more to spend, which means more sales-tax revenue and
smaller municipal budget deficits in hard times. Everyone benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Please note that New Jersey, too, has crudely told New York what
it can do with its trash. ``Drop dead,'' Gov. Christie Whitman
said.
</P>
<P>
   Does she not know that two can play that game?
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey drivers are notoriously aggressive, and every day
thousands of them bring their road rage into Manhattan, blaring
horns and brushing back pedestrians in the crosswalks. They are
easily identified by their license plates. Why not order a police
crackdown? Public safety and the municipal treasury would both be
better off.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most vexing part of the trash wars is a suggestion
from some in Virginia that Giuliani has been acting a bit loopy.
That is a slur. Maybe it would help if an affirmation that the
mayor makes sense, and New Yorkers support him, were written into
any garbage-disposal contract.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Virginia, there is a sanity clause.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
