</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-BOOK-JETS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JETS NOTEBOOK: A GRATEFUL OWNER; PACKING IT IN; TESTAVERDE
BRISTLES; SAY GOODBYE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By STEVE POPPER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HEMPSTEAD, N.Y. _ The Jets' flight home from Denver touched down
at 1:15 Monday morning at La Guardia Airport, and the players
walked out, tired and disappointed. There was no admiring group of
fans waiting; the combination of the late hour, the bad weather and
the season's frustrating conclusion kept the crowd away. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But as they left the plane they were amazed to find the team's
84-year-old owner, Leon Hess, standing and waiting for them. Hess,
who has not attended a road game since 1997, met the team's plane
and, dressed in a suit and tie, greeted each player, shaking hands
and thanking his players for their effort, despite the team
returning without the Super Bowl berth that he has wished so hard
for.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very classy move,'' running back Keith Byars said.
``If he hadn't been there, nobody would have taken offense. We know
he wants to get to a Super Bowl. He's not getting any younger and
he deserves it. He said he's very proud of us. He's a man of few
words. He shook everybody's hand. You can't help but love an owner
who does that.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jason Fabini, a rookie offensive lineman, added: ``It was a
great gesture for him. At 1:30 a.m., he was there. Win or lose, he
stuck with us.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hess, who was one of the original five owners that salvaged the
team from bankruptcy court in 1963 and renamed it from the Titans
to the Jets, became the sole owner in 1984. Although he calls the
team his greatest enjoyment, he rarely appears at a game. But he
makes an annual visit to the team's practice facility on
Thanksgiving Day.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just wanted to come out and show his appreciation,'' Coach
Bill Parcells said. ``It was very nice. We didn't console anybody.
It was just to shake hands and say thank you.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Chad Cascadden agreed, noting: ``He didn't say much. He just
congratulated us. I thought it was an extremely nice gesture. It
shows his dedication to the team.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PACKING IT IN
</P>
<P>
   Not long after landing, the Jets gathered at their Hofstra
University training site under less memorable circumstances,
emptying their lockers into garbage bags and cans. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The pat on the back from Hess did little to soothe the Jets,
even on the day after. The team took little consolation in the
improvement the franchise has made in the last two seasons, getting
little sleep afterward and finding little solace in the encouraging
words during a team meeting Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one wants moral victories,'' Keyshawn Johnson said. ``What
are you going to say _ `We got to the AFC championship, that's
wonderful,' and everybody should smile and be happy about it? No,
that's not the case.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TESTAVERDE BRISTLES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Vinny Testaverde proved himself this season, earning a spot on
the Pro Bowl roster, and he was steady again on Sunday. Still, the
Broncos, particularly linebacker Bill Romanowski, verbally jabbed
at him after the game, saying that they believed that he could be
rattled and that he fell apart in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got a history of doing that,'' Romanowski said after the
game. ``He gets hot at the beginning of the game. But when things
got tough, he struggled. To me, that's what he's shown over his
career.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Testaverde bristled at the remarks, replying only that: ``I'm
not surprised that they would say that. But for guys that got
ripped pretty good in the passing game, they just better prepare
for the Atlanta Falcons.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Testaverde finished 31 of 52 passing for 356 yards after
completing his first 13 passes. He did throw a pair of
interceptions, but on the first Wayne Chrebet slipped as the pass
was released, and the second was a tipped ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``Personally, a lot of things that were being said early in
camp, most of my career, I think I've hopefully put to bed, put to
rest, a lot of those ghosts,'' said Testaverde, who added that he
believed he would sign a contract that would make him a Jet for the
rest of his career. ``That was just something people had opinions
on, things that I never believed. I always believed I could come in
and be successful and help the team and make it as far as we
did.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SAY GOODBYE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Parcells said that he spoke Monday with the veterans Pepper
Johnson, Keith Byars and Dave Meggett, filling in each of them on
their status with the team. Johnson was told that the team would
likely look to go for a younger player who could contribute on
special teams in his spot, but that the decision to try to continue
his career would be left to him. Meggett and Byars were also
cautioned that the team did not want them to impede the progress of
younger players.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Byars said he believed he could play another year, physically,
but the decision will be whether he can commit to another season,
mentally.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see a rapid decline in skills,'' he said. ``I can
still play, despite what my birth certificate says. I can still
run, catch, and block. There's no question I still love the game.
But, like Brian Cox, my wife and family are away from me. It's hard
to be a part-time dad. I have kids that are 6 and 4, and they ask
me, `When are you coming home?' I tell them I don't know and they
don't understand. It's tough on them and me.
</P>
<P>
   ``At my age, 35 years young, you have to ask yourself, do you
want to. I feel good. I'm healthy and happy. I want to play again.
It's going to take something to pull me away from this working
environment.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
