<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SEASON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NBA GETS CAUGHT IN TRANSITION GAME
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By MIKE WISE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Scottie Pippen appears headed for Houston, and Dennis Rodman may
be teaming up with Shaquille O'Neal in Los Angeles. As to where
Latrell Sprewell will land, no one seems to know.
</P>
<P>
   As the hot stove flares and reports of possible deals spin
wildly, only one certainty has emerged from the shortened National
Basketball Association season: training camps will not open when
originally expected.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the union and the NBA are still trying to define the
terms of the new collective bargaining agreement _ a process that
was supposed to be finished Monday night. With the possibility that
the deal could be reduced to writing by Wednesday, officials on
both sides were concerned that the lockout would not be lifted
until late this week. Camps had been expected to open Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Now the free-agent signing period may not begin until the
weekend, giving general managers more time to work privately in an
effort to improve their teams.
</P>
<P>
   The most tantalizing topic seems to be Sprewell, who, according
to two Eastern Conference executives, the Knicks are in the hunt
for along with Portland and possibly Seattle. The Knicks are said
to be interested in parting with Chris Mills and Chris Childs to
land Sprewell, the Golden State guard who sent the franchise and
the league into turmoil in December 1997 when he choked Coach P.J.
Carlesimo. Sprewell has not played an NBA game in 14 months.
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear whom the Blazers or the Seattle SuperSonics would
trade for Sprewell, though Portland forward Brian Grant has been
mentioned in several reports.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Pippen's expected departure from the Chicago Bulls to
the Rockets may be getting closer. The Associated Press reported
Monday night that Pippen, 33, would sign a deal worth $67.2 million
for five years with the Bulls and then be dealt to Houston for the
forward Roy Rogers and a second-round draft pick.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of both teams would not confirm the deal Monday night,
and on the surface it does not sound like a good trade for the
Bulls. But Pippen is a free agent and can leave the Bulls without
compensation.
</P>
<P>
   Pippen's acquisition should clear the way for Charles Barkley to
re-sign with Houston. That would give the Rockets a front line of
Barkley, Pippen and Hakeem Olajuwon.
</P>
<P>
   Proving that the Bulls are on their way to a complete
disassembling, Rodman's agent has spoken with the Lakers about
playing for the $1 million exception over the salary cap. It was
unclear how many other suitors were interested in the rebounding
leader's services, but Rodman's desire to market himself in
Hollywood does not hurt the Lakers' prospects.
</P>
<P>
   No deals can be signed until the contract agreement is reduced
to writing. Though the two sides have apparently ironed out a major
difference over midlevel exception contracts _ the league has
tentatively agreed that the contracts can be signed for up to six
years _ several minor issues need to be resolved before the union
and the league finish the process.
</P>
<P>
   One involves salary cap circumvention, or how to insure teams
and agents do not conspire to go around the agreement's terms in
their negotiations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-18-99 2325EST &QL; 
