</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LA-RAMADAN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MUSLIMS TO END FAST OF RAMADAN
</HEADLINE>
 
(Attention editors: ``Today''in story refers to Tuesday, Jan. 19.) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Will also move in the ``n'' California news file.) 
BY SHARLINE CHIANG  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Muslims in Los Angeles and across the nation
celebrated the end of the monthlong fast of Ramadan on Monday with
communal prayers at mosques and special treat-filled meals at home.
</P>
<P>
   Ramadan is the Muslim holy month of the lunar calendar, during
which, from the break of dawn to sunset, devoted followers abstain
from eating, drinking and engaging in sexual intercourse. The exact
date of the end of Ramadan is governed by the sighting of the new
moon.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, hundreds of L.A.-area Muslims broke their fast
shortly after 5 p.m. before heading to the Islamic Center
Northridge's Masjid Granada Hills to mark the start of the
three-day Eid ul-Fitr, or ``feast of fast breaking'' holiday.
</P>
<P>
   The masjid's Imam Qazi Fazlullah of Granada Hills said even more
people are expected to convene this morning for a special Eid
prayer and a daylong celebration that involves large family
gatherings, exchanging of social visits and sumptuous meals.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is so much great feeling because the Ramadan is the
month of blessing, of mercy and of forgiveness,'' Fazlullah said.
</P>
<P>
   He said fasting for Ramadan is not only among the highest
commands in the Muslim faith, but ``by doing so we feel some
spiritual development, improvement and satisfaction.''
</P>
<P>
   Many worshippers will dress their best today _ often in
traditional outfits of their ancestral homelands. Some communities
will follow prayers with open bazaars.
</P>
<P>
   Eid ul-Fitr is the first of the two major Muslim holidays. The
second one is celebrated at the end of the hajj, or the pilgrimage
to Mecca. An estimated 2,350 Muslims live in Los Angeles and about
600,000 reside in Southern California. Worldwide, the population is
estimated at 1.2 billion, including some 6 million Muslims living
in America.
</P>
<P>
   Contrary to common belief, most Muslims living in this country _
an estimated 70 percent _ are American-born, according to Hussam
Ayloush, executive director of the Anaheim-based Council on
American-Islamic Relations.
</P>
<P>
   Ayloush and Fazzlulah both said this year's Ramadan was a
particularly sad one for worshippers as they followed news of
violence against Muslims around the world.
</P>
<P>
   In particular, they noted that the month of Ramadan started Dec.
19, shortly after U.S. and British forces attacked Iraq, and
remarked on last week's massacre of 45 ethnic Albanians by Serbs in
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``My feeling is just going around to Muslim centers that
everyone has been feeling kind of down,'' Ayloush said. ``There is
a sadness among the Muslims.''
</P>
<P>
   The two Muslim community leaders said, in addition to spreading
the word about Ramadan, their mission is to build greater
understanding of their faith to the general public.
</P>
<P>
   ``We the Muslims feel that there are people who are busy
spreading violence and prejudice (against Muslims), (saying)
Muslims are terrorists and disturbing the peace, when that is not
true,'' Fazzlulah said. ``Islam is the message of peace and
brotherhood. That's why we try every time to invite non-Muslims to
our mosques, and tell them we are a people who are very peaceful
and who respect humanity.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-18-99 2327EST &QL; 
