<HEADER>
A8486 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-NETS-NYT     01-18 0549
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NETS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NETS GET A DEFENSIVE SPECIALIST IN MCILVAINE
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ For the past two seasons, the Nets have
been trying to build themselves into a championship contender, and
Monday they took another step toward their goal. In a move they
believe will strengthen their defense considerably, the Nets traded
for Jim McIlvaine, one of the league's best shot blockers.
</P>
<P>
   According to a league executive familiar with the deal, the Nets
sent the center Michael Cage, 36, and the forward Don MacLean to
Seattle for McIlvaine, a 7-foot-1-inch, 265-pound center who has
been among the league leaders in blocked shots a minute the last
three seasons.
</P>
<P>
   The deal will not become official until the National Basketball
Association legalizes its new collective bargaining agreement later
this week, so officials from the Nets and the Sonics could not
comment on the trade.
</P>
<P>
   McIlvaine, entering his fifth year out of Marquette, figures to
improve a Nets defense that was among the most permeable in the
league last year. With the converted center Jayson Williams and the
aging Cage manning the middle, the Nets blocked just 314 shots,
fourth-lowest in the league and 201 fewer than their opponents
blocked against them. That was one reason their defense allowed
98.1 points a game, ninth-worst in the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   McIlvaine will back up Williams and Rony Seikaly for the Nets,
so his minutes will be limited. But he is not suited to play more
than 20 minutes a game anyway. He has little offense and is not
much of a rebounder, so he is at his best when serving as a
defensive spark off the bench.
</P>
<P>
   He enjoyed his best season three years ago as a substitute in
Washington when, playing behind Gheorghe Muresan, he averaged 2.1
blocks in less than 15 minutes a game. That ability led Seattle to
sign McIlvaine to a lucrative seven-year, $35 million free-agent
contract despite his paltry averages of 2.3 points and 2.9
rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   One Nets players, when notified of the deal for McIlvaine, said,
``He's just what we need.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics envisioned McIlvaine as a full-time player who would
perhaps block twice as many shots as he had as a sub, but his lack
of an all-around game limited him to disappointing averages of 18
minutes a game two years ago and 15 minutes last season.
</P>
<P>
   The Nets' hopes, however, are not as high. They don't need
offense or rebounding from McIlvaine, just blocks. If he can block
two shots a game in less than 20 minutes, he will have done his
job.
</P>
<P>
   In improving one of their biggest deficiencies, the Nets lost
little. Cage, though a voice of inspiration in the locker room, was
well past his prime. In Seattle, he will return to the site of his
best years, when he averaged 8.1 rebounds from 1988 to 1994. Still
able to bang, Cage will make the talented but soft Sonics tougher
both physically and mentally.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-10 MacLean, who missed all but nine games last season
because of injuries, is in his prime, but with the Nets' abundance
of forwards, he was expendable. With Williams, who will play both
center and power forward, Keith Van Horn, Chris Gatling and Kendall
Gill ahead of him, MacLean, a 12-point scorer for his career, would
have seen little action.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-18-99 2331EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
