r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-STATEOFUNION-     01-18 1114
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-STATEOFUNION-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITE HOUSE RELUCTANT TO ACKNOWLEDGE SCANDAL IN THE MIDST OF
THE  STATE OF THE UNION MESSAGE
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By MARC SANDALOW 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Like other White House officials, Communications
Director Ann Lewis was asked over the weekend what effect the
impeachment trial would have on President Clinton's State of the
Union address tonight.
</P>
<P>
   None, she insisted. No impact on the speech. No impact on the
next two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is about doing the people's business,'' Lewis said,
repeating the White House's populist mantra. ``It is what makes the
biggest difference with people, this year, next year, and into the
next century.''
</P>
<P>
   Even as Congress engages in a historic constitutional exercise
and the Lewinsky matter begins to eat into a second year of
Clinton's term, the White House steadfastly refuses to acknowledge
that the scandal has forced it into making any policy concessions.
</P>
<P>
   Forget Monica. Forget impeachment. Forget ``lame duck-ness.''
The president's posture will be that everything is on track _ the
nation's well-being and the health of his presidency _ as he
delivers what promises to be the most awkward State of the Union
address in history.
</P>
<P>
   Just before 6 p.m. PST, Clinton will stride into the very
chamber where he was impeached exactly one month earlier. The
audience will include members of the House, who just impeached him,
and members of the Senate, who hold his fate.
</P>
<P>
   It is one of Washington's most ritualized displays of political
pageantry. Even most Republicans say they will be there to politely
applaud the president _ the office, if not the man _ even if they
do so somewhat reluctantly.
</P>
<P>
   The speech provides Clinton a rare opportunity to address a
nationally televised audience for more than an hour, without the
prospect of embarrassing questions or the taint of scandal.
</P>
<P>
   White House aides say Clinton relishes the opportunity. ``It is
probably his favorite day of the year,'' said Clinton adviser Paul
Begala.
</P>
<P>
   Aides said it is very unlikely he will mention the impeachment
saga. Instead, he will focus on an ambitious domestic agenda, one
more fitting a new president than one six years into office, they
said.
</P>
<P>
   The focus is expected to be on Social Security and education.
Aides said Clinton will call on Republicans to work with him to
retool Social Security, but he is unlikely to outline a specific
proposal. On education, Clinton will announce a plan to hold states
and school districts accountable for the achievements of students
and teachers, and tie billions of dollars in federal aide to such
ideas as ending social promotion.
</P>
<P>
   He is also expected to propose new school construction; a tax
credit of $250 per child for stay-at-home parents of young
children; a plan to improve health care for many of the nation's 32
million uninsured; and a $110 billion boost in defense spending
over the next six years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think at the end of the speech, people will look not at an
administration that has entered the last two years of office and is
slowing down, but an administration that is energized and is
looking forward to moving into the 21st century with an ambitious
and activist agenda,'' said White House press secretary Joe
Lockhart.
</P>
<P>
   If history is a guide, Clinton's proposals will boost his
popularity. But even if the Senate quickly concludes his trial with
an acquittal, no one knows what effect his impeachment by the House
will have on his ability to move legislation. The only other
impeached president, Andrew Johnson, was virtually powerless after
he was acquitted by the Senate in 1868.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Johnson, Clinton remains quite popular with the public,
and the White House says his proposals will succeed. ``Those are
policies that are going to do well, and we're going to be able to
achieve some legislative agreement on,'' Lewis said, ``because that
is what the American people want us to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Scholars disagree over the extent to which Clinton will be
hobbled by his impeachment. Some argue that relations are so
poisonous with lawmakers that few of his initiatives will be
approved. Others speculate that Republicans will be eager to pass
substantive measures to convince the public that they are not
obsessed with investigating the president.
</P>
<P>
   There is a consensus that the final years of a presidency tend
to be the least productive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if Monica Lewinsky had never flashed her underwear
outside the Oval Office, one would still have the reality of lame
duck-ness,'' observed Richard Haas, a scholar at the Washington
based Brookings Institution and a former national security aide to
President Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Haas said he doubts the trouble will have enormous impact in
matters of foreign policy, but he noted that Clinton may have lost
opportunities for pushing initiatives such as a Middle East peace
accord or expanding international trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most precious resource for a president is often time, and
time spent with lawyers is time not spent with assistant
secretaries of state,'' Haas said.
</P>
<P>
   Some evidence suggests that Clinton's effectiveness has been
eroded. A study of congressional votes conducted by the independent
Congressional Quarterly called Clinton's legislative year ``a
failure,'' noting that ``virtually all of of his major proposals
died.'' They said that just 51 percent of the 154 bills he
supported passed, the sixth worst record of any president since CQ
began tracking such things 46 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Last year in his state of the Union address, for example,
Clinton called for a health care bill of rights, new restrictions
on tobacco sales, campaign finance reform, expanded Medicare
benefits, a higher minimum wage, expanded child care programs and
new school construction. No such measures were passed.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart noted that the president did succeed in what he termed
the two ``central economic challenges'' outlined in last year's
address: staving off tax cuts and preserving the budget surplus
until Social Security is reformed, and winning new funds for the
International Monetary Fund. He was also able to win funds for
after-school care, new teachers and other pet projects, Lockhart
said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, as Clinton's poll numbers rise and Congress' fall, it is
possible to make the case that a year of scandal has done little
harm to Clinton's standing.
</P>
<P>
   The Brookings Institution held a forum last week entitled ``Life
Under a Weakened Presidency,'' prompting the think tank's president
Michael Armacost, a former national security adviser in the Reagan
administration, to muse that ``perhaps one should put a question
mark'' after the title.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
