<SLUG> BC-FBN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELWAY NEEDS TO LET IT GO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   After John Elway finally won a Super Bowl on his fourth try,
some silly scribes advised him to call it a career and get on with
his charmed life.
</P>
<P>
   But enough about us.
</P>
<P>
   We admit it, we urged Elway to retire to that Barcalounger in
the skyboxes after the Broncos' 31-24 win over the defending
champion Green Bay Packers in Super Bowl XXXII. Our concern was
that by coming back for a 16th season, Elway was needlessly
fiddling with a perfectly Runyonesque ending.
</P>
<P>
   Our internal editing mechanism was in overdrive, as usual,
spewing its old, familiar refrain: No more tinkering. Let it go.
</P>
<P>
   We honestly couldn't see how Elway was going to improve upon his
San Diego ending. It would have been like asking Margaret Mitchell
to bang out a sequel to ``Gone with the Wind.''
</P>
<P>
   Great stories are not easily surpassed. If you don't believe it,
look at Bret Easton Ellis' career since ``Less than Zero.''
</P>
<P>
   We didn't think there could be a more stirring final sentence
than the one Broncos owner Pat Bowlen screamed loud enough for all
of Qualcomm Stadium and, thanks to the obsequiousness of
television, the whole world to hear after the Broncos beat back the
Pack: ``This one's for John!''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it's plain now that Elway had one more scintillating
chapter up his sleeve, one more story line that oh so neatly ties
up all the remaining loose ends of his Hall of Fame career. By
hanging around to help lead the Broncos to a second consecutive
Super Bowl berth, Elway has a chance to bury the Atlanta Falcons _
and the hatchet.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons are coached by Dan Reeves, who was Elway's boss in
Denver for 10 years. Back then Reeves was the Terry Donahue of the
NFL, rigidly espousing the system over any individual player. Elway
felt shackled by Reeves' run-oriented offense and he never forgave
Reeves for firing assistant coach (and Elway ally) Mike Shanahan
after the 1991 season.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves' own contract wasn't renewed after the Broncos' 8-8
campaign of 1992. In his farewell press conference, he alluded to
the uneasy alliance he had with Elway, saying, ``I have a lot of
respect for John. . . . But I don't know that John has as much
respect for me as I have for him.''
</P>
<P>
   If he does, he's had a funny way of showing it the past few
years. The characteristic graciousness that makes Elway an easy
target for every autograph seeker and charitable cause has ducked
out on him when talk turns to Reeves.
</P>
<P>
   The former Granada Hills High standout has described his years
under Reeves as ``hell,'' the Broncos' three Super Bowl appearances
in that span notwithstanding. Elway has been especially critical of
the conservative play- calling that set the stage for all of his
last-drive theatrics during the Reeves era in Denver.
</P>
<P>
   The grudge does not become Elway, who in all other respects is a
refreshingly uncomplicated superstar. We're talking about someone
who last summer turned down a spot on a late-night television talk
show so he could spend the time hanging out with his high school
buddies during a brief stopover in Southern California to see the
Granada Hills stadium renamed in his honor.
</P>
<P>
   Understand: The fact that Elway has lashed out in anger and
frustration at a supervisor with whom he didn't see eye-to-eye
doesn't make him a bad human being, just a numbingly normal one.
The trouble is, for too many of us, such vitriol is like an
intravenous drip, nourishing our rancor and resentment.
</P>
<P>
   Elway is blessed with the perfect stage for cleansing. He has
the chance to let the healing begin right here, right now. Some
time in the next two weeks he can stand in front of a bouquet of
microphones and deliver a good-hearted soliloquy.
</P>
<P>
   He took a step in the right direction after Sunday's win over
the New York Jets when he said of Reeves, ``He's got (the Falcons)
playing great and Dan is a great football coach. When you look at
what he's done in the last two years with them, it's just
unbelievable.''
</P>
<P>
   With a few more respectful words about what Reeves did for an
overwhelmed, unsure quarterback in his younger years, Elway, in his
own indubitable way, can show beyond a doubt that he is a bigger
person than the game to be played before an audience numbering in
the millions on Jan. 31 in Miami.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
