<HEADLINE>
A SWEET RENT DEAL FOR 3,000 MAY BE GOING SOUR
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By PAUL ZIELBAUER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Like just about every tenant in the twin red-brick
Ruppert Yorkville Towers, Marie Mitchell knows she has one of the
sweetest living arrangements in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   For her one-bedroom apartment overlooking a rather desirable
slice of the Upper East Side at Third Avenue and 91st Street, Ms.
Mitchell, 54, pays just $603.34 a month. Her last rent increase _
an annual rite for thousands of the city's renters _ was in 1983.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess it is an extremely good deal,'' she said, seated in
her kitchen, coaxing her rotund cat to her lap.
</P>
<P>
   But it is also a deal that was to have ended on Jan. 1. Now, it
is part of a bitter court battle in which 3,000 middle-income
residents of the towers are trying to force their landlord to stay
in a rent-regulation program it is legally permitted to leave.
State and city housing officials say the lawsuit filed by the
Ruppert Yorkville Tenants Association is the first of its kind
involving the statewide program, known as Mitchell-Lama.
</P>
<P>
   The landlord, Yorkville Towers Associates, appears intent on
imposing huge increases, some as much as 200 percent, to convert
its 1,258 units to market-value rents. Last Friday, the company
sent letters notifying tower residents of a countersuit and warning
that it would raise rents even higher if the tenants' association
pursued its case in court.
</P>
<P>
   Last spring, Yorkville Towers Associates announced its intention
to withdraw from Mitchell-Lama, a state- and city-operated program
that regulates rent increases for about 125,000 apartments in New
York City.
</P>
<P>
   The Mitchell-Lama program, named for the two state legislators
who sponsored it in 1955, Sen. MacNeil Mitchell, a Manhattan
Republican, and Assemblyman Alfred A. Lama, a Brooklyn Democrat,
was intended to spur the construction of buildings for
middle-income tenants while providing a 6 percent profit to
landlords. Under the program, landlords can only raise rents with
government approval, a process that usually takes months and often
years. But the law includes a provision that allows landlords to
buy their way out of the program _ by paying off the long-term
bonds that financed construction of their building _ after it has
been occupied for 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   To leave Mitchell-Lama, Yorkville Towers Associates would have
to repay about $63 million in mortgage and other payments to the
city.
</P>
<P>
   At first, when the company announced its departure from
Mitchell-Lama, many Ruppert Yorkville Towers tenants, including Ms.
Mitchell and her neighbor, Hazel Jordan, shrugged. They expected
marginal rent increases. But in November, the management disclosed
new rents that in some cases were triple what tenants were paying.
</P>
<P>
   The renters were furious. Many said the new prices were, in
effect, eviction notices.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're the ones who made this area and now we have to get
out,'' said Ms. Jordan, 65, a retired law office administrator who
pays $606 a month for her one-bedroom apartment. When their leases
expire later this year, she and Ms. Mitchell, who lives one floor
below, must either agree to an increase to $1,596 a month or move
out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm terrified,'' said Ms. Jordan, who relies on a pension and
Social Security income to pay her bills. ``Where am I going to go
where I don't need a car?''
</P>
<P>
   Another tenant, Susan Nier, said she would refuse to pull her
11-year-old son, Sam, out of a school and neighborhood they both
love. ``The bottom line was, `Pay or get out,''' said Ms. Nier, 45,
a single mother whose rent for her two-bedroom apartment is
scheduled to jump from $753, to $2,280, when her lease expires in
June 2000.
</P>
<P>
   No one, it turns out, is going anywhere for now. The tenants'
association's $280 million lawsuit, filed last month in state
Supreme Court, has forced Yorkville Towers Associates to delay its
departure from the program. Among other allegations, the lawsuit
contends that Yorkville Towers has unfairly hoarded rent money and
is obligated to remain under Mitchell-Lama until 2008.
</P>
<P>
   ``They indicated there would be no accommodations made for
senior citizens, the handicapped, anyone,'' said Stuart M. Saft,
the tenants' lawyer. The standard Ruppert Yorkville Towers leases,
he said, do not stipulate management's right eventually to leave
the Mitchell-Lama program.
</P>
<P>
   And some tenants, like Richard Catrone, a tower resident named
as one of the plaintiffs in the lawsuit, said the building's
management had assured tenants that their rents would never rise
without approval from the city's Department of Housing Preservation
and Development, one of the agencies that oversees the
Mitchell-Lama program.
</P>
<P>
   Albert A. Walsh, the lawyer for Yorkville Towers Associates,
declined to comment on the lawsuit except to say the landlord has
no obligation to remain in the program.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Of the 242 developments in New York City under Mitchell-Lama
rent restrictions, all except one are eligible to leave the
program. At a time when at least two other Mitchell-Lama complexes
have applied to buy out of the program, a court victory by the
Ruppert Yorkville Towers tenants could pave the way for other
tenant lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   For now, Ruppert Yorkville Towers tenants are intent on winning.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's all that anyone talks about,'' said Ms. Mitchell, who
is a shipping manager for a West Side printing company and is
considering taking in a roommate or moving to Harlem or New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, she said, she asked an elderly neighbor how he
planned to pay higher rent. ``He broke down and cried,'' she said.
``I felt terrible.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not all faced with the plague, but this is serious,''
she said. ``We're losing our homes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-18-99 2333EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
