<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-MERGER-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT HOME IS EXPECTED TO ACQUIRE EXCITE IN MAJOR INTERNET DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: SUBS 4th graf to be more precise about attempts to reach
executives; ADDS estimated per-share price of deal , explainer on
portals, background.)  
(fe) 
 By JOHN MARKOFF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ At Home Corp., a high-speed Internet service
aimed at cable television subscribers, intends to announce on
Tuesday that it will acquire Excite Inc., one of the leading
Internet destinations, in a stock transaction valued about $6
billion, according to a person involved in the deal.
</P>
<P>
   If completed, the deal would be one of the biggest in a flurry
of recent Internet acquisitions, exceeding even the $4.2 billion
purchase of Netscape by America Online announced two months ago.
</P>
<P>
   The boards of both companies met on Monday night to work on
last-minute issues. Barring last-minute snags, an announcement is
planned in New York before the opening of the stock market. Any
deal would have to be approved by the shareholders of both
companies. It is also possible that a last-minute snag could delay
the agreement, but most of the details have been worked out.
</P>
<P>
   At Home refused to comment on the reports about negotiations,
and Excite officials did not return phone calls requesting comment.
</P>
<P>
   The deal would strengthen At Home's position in the competition
for destination sites, known as portals, that is increasingly
defining the commercial Internet. It would also sharpen the
position of AT&AMP;T, which is now concluding its acquisition of
Tele-Communications Inc., At Home's major shareholder.
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of the agreement, Excite's shareholders would
receive about 30 percent of At Home in a stock transaction
involving the issuing of new shares. The resulting company would be
named At Home, and George Bell, Excite's chief executive, would
become an At Home board member as well as take an executive
position in the combined company.
</P>
<P>
   The value of At Home's stock outstanding is about $10.4 billion,
while Excite's shares are worth a total of about $3.5 billion.
Excite's stock closed Friday at $67.50, up $2.375, while At Home
closed at $102, down 62.5 cents. At $6 billion, the proposed deal
values each share of Excite at more than $116, more than 72 percent
above its Friday closing price of $67.50.
</P>
<P>
   At Home now has more than 330,000 customers for its service,
which provides high-speed Internet data via cable networks. The
deal would give it access to both Excite's users _ it is the sixth
most heavily trafficked site on the Internet _ and to the company's
content development capabilities.
</P>
<P>
   Excite is attractive to At Home as a potential vehicle to market
its high-speed cable modem network to those dialing in with
conventional modems through telephone lines. In addition, Excite
offers a popular Internet brand name as well as the nucleus of an
expanded content development capability that would become the heart
of a future At Home service.
</P>
<P>
   Both At Home and Excite! are based in Redwood City, a San
Francisco suburb on the Northern edge of Silicon Valley. The
offices of Tom Jermolak, At Home's chief executive, and Bell are
separated by a parking lot.
</P>
<P>
   The urgency to strike an agreement was heightened in recent
weeks because several other companies were interested in bidding
for Excite, including Yahoo, a competing large portal and search
engine, and Microsoft, according to people close to the
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   A report of a possible deal between the two companies appeared
on Monday in The San Jose Mercury News.
</P>
<P>
   The purchase would represent the biggest play yet in the rush to
combine Internet access with portals, the starting point for
millions of users. In the last year, portals have evolved by
mergers and acquisitions of Web directories, or search engines, and
content providers, including everything from traditional forms of
printed news to audio and video entertainment, e-mail, and online
discussions.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the recent acquisition of Netscape Communications
by America Online, Snap, an Internet provider partly owned by NBC,
Monday announced a high-speed Internet service with partners
including Bell Atlantic and SBC Communications.
</P>
<P>
   For AT&AMP;T the At Home-Excite deal could ultimately help shape its
strength in a wide range of Internet services, including dialup
access via its AT&AMP;T Worldnet service, which the TCI and At Home
offering that will permit it to offer both high speed Internet as
well as local telephone services. and a new Excite brand which
could serve as both a portal and an important content brand to
rival other major Internet players such as Microsoft, Disney and
America Online.
</P>
<P>
   From a business standpoint, the object of a portal is to offer a
starting point to millions of Web users and then attract
advertisers to place banner ads on the Web pages those users see.
Depending on the sophistication of the portal software, these ads
can often be narrowly aimed just at users who have expressed
interest in certain subjects or products or who have demonstrated
desired buying habits or who fit narrowly defined demographics.
</P>
<P>
   And as America Online has proved by attracting more than 15
million members, providing a combination of access to the Internet
and content that will keep users hanging around the portal's pages
rather than moving out to other parts of cyberspace is a winning
strategy.
</P>
<P>
   Since its inception, At Home has followed that formula. The
difference is that its users are all accessing the Internet at
blazing speeds over cable modems _ in many cases faster than the
access they have over high-speed telephone lines at work. At Home's
cable modems can deliver data to home personal computers at speeds
in excess of 3 million bits per second.
</P>
<P>
   At Home has developed a portal that takes full advantage of that
access speed, offering colorful, animated pages packed with
multimedia content that other portals would not dare offer their
users, the vast majority of whom are using dial-up modems at speeds
less of than 50,000 bits per second.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
