</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-GROSS-PROFILE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOHN GROSS: GIULIANI'S FRIEND AND CAUTIOUS FUND-RAISER
</HEADLINE>
  (bl)  
By ELISABETH BUMILLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ John H. Gross is one of those people you've never
heard of. His name doesn't appear in the gossip columns. His
specialty is insurance law. He spends quiet weekends kayaking on
Sagaponack Pond on Long Island, or taking his two daughters on
nature walks. No one, it is safe to say, has ever called him a
character. But if you had a lot of money, you would let him take
care of it.
</P>
<P>
   So back in 1989, when Gross happened to wander out of the room
when the inner circle was divvying up jobs for Rudolph Giuliani's
first (unsuccessful) run for mayor, the gang made Gross treasurer.
Nobody else wanted it, and Gross was in any case perfect. ``You can
get in trouble if you don't do it right,'' said Peter Powers,
Giuliani's longtime friend and adviser, who described Gross the way
everybody does, as ``a very cautious person.''
</P>
<P>
   That year Gross helped raise $5 million. For the successful 1993
Giuliani campaign, he got up to $11 million. By Giuliani's 1997
re-election campaign, it was $11 million again, with big
contributions from the city's developers _ raised faster and in
larger amounts than for any other mayor in the city's history.
</P>
<P>
   And now, over the next two years, Gross' job is to raise $10
million for Giuliani's campaign for the U.S. Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``A war chest of $10 million would be easily sufficient,'' said
Gross, even though it cost Sen. Charles Schumer more than $15
million last year to run against the incumbent, Alfonse D'Amato,
who spent more than $20 million and lost.
</P>
<P>
   But Gross says Giuliani is known enough upstate to get away with
the discount cost: ``When I go up to St. Lawrence County on
business, and I turn on the news, the news is New York City news.
And the mayor is on those channels. So if you want to go all the
way up to the Canadian border, you see the mayor.''
</P>
<P>
   Officially, the mayor is only ``exploring'' the Senate race even
as his advisers march in that direction. To cover his options, last
spring the mayor formed three political committees _ ``Friends of
Giuliani,'' ``Solutions America'' and ``Giuliani for New York'' _
to raise money for travel, political seminars and potential
Giuliani races for president, senator and governor. So far the
committees have only $600,000 in hand, although more is pledged.
Bruce Teitelbaum, the mayor's former chief of staff, is the new
executive director at Solutions America. Gross oversees that
committee as well as the other two.
</P>
<P>
   Last week Gross, 58, talked in his office at the midtown law
firm of Proskauer, Rose, then over lunch at a Japanese restaurant.
His friendship with Giuliani was forged during their good old days
as young prosecutors in the early 1970s at the U.S. attorney's
office in the Southern District of New York. Giuliani, whose
aggressive work as a prosecutor inspired the book and movie
``Prince of the City,'' got the indictments. Then Gross tried the
cases, and others. A lot were for heroin smuggling. Life in the
criminal division was good.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were all friends,'' Gross said. ``You've really got to get
this. It was an extraordinarily collegial place, where people were
having a tremendous amount of fun doing what they believed in, with
a lot of responsibility. And within that large group, there was a
subset _ Rudy, myself and a few others, who were really, really
good friends.''
</P>
<P>
   Does he have as much fun now? ``No,'' he said simply.
</P>
<P>
   Gross and Giuliani often went out to dinner in those days with
their first wives. ( Gross is now married to Judy Gross, a lawyer
who is studying to be a teacher.) Gross, who grew up in the Shaker
Heights suburb of Cleveland _ his father was a jeweler _ still
seems awed by Giuliani as lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people believe the people in the U.S. attorney's office
are the best and the brightest,'' Gross said. ``If that is true,
then Rudy was the best of the best and the brightest.''
</P>
<P>
   By the mid-'70s, they had parted _ Giuliani to the Justice
Department in Washington, Gross to the New York firm of Anderson,
Kill &AMP; Olick. But they stayed in touch when Giuliani returned to
private practice in New York, then when he worked with Gross at
Anderson, Kill in between his 1989 and 1993 campaigns. Gross moved
to Proskauer in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Gross is most proud of what he calls his cost-conscious
fund-raising, which matters in city races where there are spending
limits. (There are none in the Senate race, but the limit on
individual contributions is $1,000. In the city races, it was
$7,700.) Gross says Giuliani will raise money nationally. In recent
months, the mayor has been to California, Florida, Iowa and New
Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   Gross is especially pleased with his bargaining over fees with
Adam Goodman, the 1997 Giuliani campaign's media consultant. ``That
way you have more money to give to the campaign,'' Gross said,
``and not to give to your media people to put paintings on their
walls.''
</P>
<P>
   Goodman confirmed that he negotiated with Gross for two days
over his contract. ``It was fair enough for me to feel loved and
rewarded, but it was also a no-nonsense, hard-driven contract that
is not one we would normally agree to in other campaigns,'' he
said. Then he added: ``The price is going way up in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Gross said Giuliani could beat Hillary Rodham Clinton if she ran
for Senate from New York, but Gross doesn't think she will.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
