<SLUG> BC-NYC-TRASH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRASH, GIULIANI TELLS VIRGINIA, IS A GOOD DEAL, NOT AN OBLIGATION
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Va. )  (ms) 
 By VIVIAN S. TOY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Responding to politicians in Virginia who continue to
rail against Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's plan to export more of New
York City's trash, the mayor said Monday he never said other states
were obligated to take the city's garbage.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't a question of obligation,'' he said. ``This is a
very big business and it supplies lots of jobs for people. There's
a business here that goes on irrespective of the statements that
the politicians make.''
</P>
<P>
   Saying that the city pays ``a huge amount of money'' to send its
trash out of state, Giuliani said, ``There are more places that
want to do business with us than you could possibly imagine.'' The
city expects to spend $200 million a year on garbage export by
2002, after the Fresh Kills landfill in Staten Island is shut down.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor made his comments Monday after speaking at the 13th
annual tribute to the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr. at the Brooklyn
Academy of Music. But even as he softened his stand on whether
other states had a responsibility to take the city's garbage,
Giuliani emphasized that all of the city's 13,000 tons of daily
trash would eventually find its way out of the state.
</P>
<P>
   New York currently ships 2,400 tons of garbage a day to
Virginia, about 60 percent of that state's imported trash. The
current dispute arose last week when Waste Management Inc., a waste
disposal company, signed a contract with a barge company that would
allow up to 4,000 tons of garbage to be transported to a new port
that the company has been building.
</P>
<P>
   Although New York has not signed a contract to increase the
amount of trash it ships there, the possibility of that much more
New York garbage being barged into Virginia to be dumped in
landfills prompted Gov. James S. Gilmore III to say during his
state of the state message last week that he would try to ban
garbage barges on the state's rivers.
</P>
<P>
   Gilmore and other Virginia politicians also labeled Giuliani
arrogant when he suggested that the rest of the country was in some
way obligated to take the city's trash in exchange for the cultural
and financial benefits generated by New York City.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani said last week that since people from across the
country benefit from the city's role as a cultural and business
center, the rest of the country should help the city with its
garbage problem as part of ``a reciprocal relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   The mayor said that after Gilmore made his comments, three local
politicians from Virginia called the mayor's office ``saying the
governor is displaying his viewpoint, but at the same time about
four or five thousand jobs depend on this and we have a more
practical approach.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean every time somebody makes these statements _ some
politician trying to get on television _ we get five mayors and 10
communities to call us and to say, `Don't listen to him, we need
your business,''' the mayor said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
