<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MLK-LA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOME BUILDERS PRESERVE SPIRIT OF KING ON HOLIDAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Will also move in the ``n'' California news file.) 
BY DOUGLAS HABERMAN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ As the nation and Los Angeles commemorated the
life and legacy of the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr. on Monday,
16-year-old Beth Wilion spent the day building houses for poor
people in Panorama City.
</P>
<P>
   And she bets King would've approved.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole civil rights movement that Dr. King helped was a
great thing for so many people. So it makes me feel good that I
could be part of something like this, which is something that he
probably would have supported and would have been a part of, if he
had been here today,'' said Wilion, a junior at Oakwood High School
in North Hollywood, a Los Angeles-area suburb.
</P>
<P>
   The national holiday was an observance of the 70th anniversary
of the birth of the 1964 Nobel Peace Prize winner. King, who
advocated racial equality through peaceful means, was assassinated
in 1968.
</P>
<P>
   The home-building project was but one way that people marked the
birth of the late civil rights leader _ from parades, to speeches
and banquets.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Richard Riordan and other leaders participated in the 19th
annual Kingdom Day Parade, which started near the corner of
Crenshaw and Martin Luther King Jr. boulevards, and traveled a
two-mile route.
</P>
<P>
   And in Panorama City, an L.A.-area suburb, about 35 volunteers
clad in sweatshirts and faded jeans honored King's dream of
equality by helping nine families achieve the American dream of
home ownership.
</P>
<P>
   The volunteers painted interior walls, plastered exterior walls
and hung drywall at a nine-house Habitat for Humanity project on
Willis Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   The volunteer homebuilders in Panorama City _ including students
from high schools, AmeriCorps members, and active and retired
workers in the building trades _ said they could have spent the day
relaxing like some of their peers, but found it rewarding to work
for a good cause on a day that honors the late civil rights
leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are having a good time,'' said Alissa Bloch, 16, an Oakwood
High School junior, as a group of volunteers cut drywall board.
</P>
<P>
   That combination of enjoyment and rewarding activity is just
what North Hollywood High School student Joshua Lehrer envisioned
when he helped found the High School Initiative in 1996. The
program, which started out with six campuses and has since expanded
to 14, provides opportunities for students to engage in meaningful
volunteer work, such as the Habitat for Humanity project.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to provide a tangible outlet for kids, something
they could point to and say, I did this,'' said Lehrer, 17, as he
took a break from hammering. ``Students want to help.''
</P>
<P>
   Adult volunteers expressed similar feelings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like helping out,'' said plasterer Butch Balle, a San
Gabriel Valley resident who has volunteered on several Habitat for
Humanity projects. ``It makes me feel good.''
</P>
<P>
   The nine two-story homes, each with a two-car garage, are slated
for completion by the end of April. The low-income families buying
the homes must put in 500 hours of work each, either by helping
with construction or working in Habitat for Humanity offices, as
``sweat equity.''
</P>
<P>
   Also on Monday, Riordan was slated to attend the annual King
Week Festival Birthday Celebration Dinner hosted by the Martin
Luther King Legacy Association and the Southern Christian
Leadership Conference at the Bonaventure Hotel downtown.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
