u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OBIT-DEMPSEY-NYT     01-18 0515
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-DEMPSEY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAVID DEMPSEY, 85, WRITER ON WIDE-RANGING SUBJECTS
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: N.Y., Ill.)  (bl)  
By GRACE GLUECK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   David Dempsey, a reviewer, biographer, novelist, columnist,
fiction and magazine writer who as a Marine Corps combat
correspondent during World War II covered four Pacific landings
toting a rifle and a typewriter, died Jan. 13 at his home in Rye,
N.Y. He was 85.
</P>
<P>
   A prolific author, his talents embraced a variety of topics and
mediums ranging from plays to criticism.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was one of the most versatile writers I ever knew, a
consummate craftsman in the way he could size up almost any subject
and get to its essence with ease and finesse,'' said Willard R.
Espy, an autobiographer and writer on language who has been a
friend and colleague of Dempsey's since the 1940s.
</P>
<P>
   While he was a Marine Corps sergeant, Dempsey won the first
prize of $500 in a one-act play contest sponsored by the Third
Naval District. The play, ``It Ain't Brooklyn,'' about an attack on
a troop transport in the Pacific, was begun just before the Allied
invasion of the Marshall Islands, but work on it had to be
suspended until the action was over. The judges included Moss Hart,
John Golden, Rachel Crothers and Russel Crouse, and the play was
included in an anthology, ``Best One-Act Plays of 1944.''
</P>
<P>
   With several co-authors, Dempsey later produced two books about
the Marine Corps: ``U.S. Marines on Iwo Jima'' (1945) and
``Uncommon Valor: Marine Divisions in Action'' (1946).
</P>
<P>
   Dempsey's other books range from a novel, ``All That Was
Mortal'' (1978) to ``The Way We Die'' (1975), a report on new
approaches to the medical, psychological and social problems
associated with dying. In 1968 he collaborated with Raymond P.
Baldwin, a lawyer, on ``The Triumphs and Trials of Lotta
Crabtree,'' the story of a American actress who was a household
name toward the end of the 19th century and whose estate of about
$4 million was contested by more than 100 people at her death in
1925.
</P>
<P>
   With collaborators, he also wrote several books on psychology,
among them ``Psychology and You,'' with Philip Zimbardo (1978).
</P>
<P>
   He produced fiction and articles for magazines including the
Saturday Evening Post, The New Yorker, Playboy, the Reader's
Digest, The New Republic and Harper's. He completed another novel
shortly before his death.
</P>
<P>
   David Knapp Dempsey was born on Jan. 9, 1914, in Pekin, Ill.
From 1949 to 1953, he wrote a weekly column, ``In and Out of
Books,'' for The New York Times Book Review, to which he later
contributed many reviews. From 1954 to 1978, he also wrote articles
for The New York Times Magazine, ranging from a profile of the
anthropologist Margaret Mead to an article on runaway youths. From
1963 to 1970, he wrote a column on the publishing scene for The
Saturday Review.
</P>
<P>
   He was a former member of the board of directors of PEN, the
international organization of writers and editors.
</P>
<P>
   Dempsey's wife, Evangeline Semon, died in 1984. He is survived
by a son, Ian, of New York City.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-18-99 2343EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
