<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 23:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8514 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NJ-STORM-NYT     01-18 0405
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-STORM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WIND AND RAIN DISRUPT TRAVEL AND DAMAGE BUILDINGS
</HEADLINE>
  (bl)  
By ANDY NEWMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fierce winds and lashing rains swept through New Jersey on the
leading edge of a cold front Monday, shearing roofs off buildings
and causing power failures that left more than 10,000 New Jersey
train commuters stalled in their tracks during the evening rush.
</P>
<P>
   The storms also briefly shut down all three major airports, left
6,500 New Jersey homes without power and forced the shutdown of
PATH train service between Newark and Jersey City for 40 minutes.
No serious injuries from the storm were reported.
</P>
<P>
   Between 5:20 p.m. and 7 p.m., 15 Amtrak trains on the Northeast
Corridor line were stranded, as were at least 20 trains on New
Jersey Transit's North Jersey Coast and Raritan Valley lines,
railroad officials said. Service was restored by 8 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   At the Windsor Industrial Park in Washington Township in Mercer
County, 10 miles northeast of Trenton, a powerful wind peeled back
the sheet-metal roofs of several buildings and caused one
cinder-block building to crack, said Michael McCloskey, the park's
property manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a very loud bang,'' McCloskey said, ``and then the
ceiling tiles were rattling. You could just feel the negative
pressure. That's when things started to fly around.''
</P>
<P>
   Car windows blew out from the pressure, McCloskey said, and
other cars were damaged by flying debris.
</P>
<P>
   In Cherry Hill, N.J., near Camden, a concrete wall was blown
down, part of the roof of the Children's Discovery Museum was torn
off, and several buildings in an industrial park sustained roof
damage, the police said.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Wanton, a meteorologist with the National Weather Service in
Mount Holly, N.J., said that while no tornadoes were confirmed,
winds probably exceeded 60 mph.
</P>
<P>
   Parts of western New Jersey receiving up to 1.5 inches of rain,
meteorologists said. Temperatures dropped 10 to 15 degrees after
the front passed through, and skies began to clear.
</P>
<P>
   At Newark International Airport, some arriving flights were
delayed by two hours, said officials at the Port Authority of New
York and New Jersey, which operates the airports.
</P>
<P>
   Across New Jersey, the winds loosened power lines and brought
tree limbs down, leaving 6,500 customers without power in
mid-afternoon, said Kathy Ellis, a spokeswoman for Public Service
Electric and Gas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
