<SLUG> BC-NY-KING-FLAKE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-CONGRESSMAN TELLS BLACKS NOT TO BE VICTIMS
</HEADLINE>
   (See also CLINTON-KING) (nk) 
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Before a cheering crowd at a state celebration marking Martin
Luther King Jr. Day, the Rev. Floyd H. Flake, a former member of
Congress and potential mayoral candidate in New York City in 2001,
urged listeners on Monday to stop ``talking like a victim, acting
like a victim, walking like a victim.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time for a change of attitudes,'' declared Flake, a
Queens Democrat who is black but has in recent years drawn an
increasingly sharp line between himself and many other Democrats
and black leaders. Saying people should not turn to government for
special help, Flake added: ``Sometimes, you've got to work for it.
Sometimes, you've got to work overtime for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Flake's remarks, to a mostly black audience assembled for the
official New York observance of King's birthday in Albany, N.Y.,
responded with cheers, song and shouts of `Yes!'' and ``Amen!''
</P>
<P>
   He delivered his 30-minute message like a sermon, and it was in
many ways familiar to anyone who has attended one of his Sunday
services at the Allen African Methodist Episcopal Church in
Jamaica, Queens, where he is the senior pastor. Indeed, to the
distress of many of his fellow Democrats, he voiced similar themes
in a speech in Manhattan last July to a meeting of the Republican
National Committee.
</P>
<P>
   But Flake's remarks Monday were notable for the venue in which
he chose to deliver them _ the annual observance of King's
birthday, at an event sponsored by the state to commemorate the
civil rights movement. His audience included Lt. Gov. Mary O.
Donohue, a Republican representing Gov. George Pataki, who did not
attend.
</P>
<P>
   That audience applauded and rose to its feet as Flake urged them
to rely on their own resources, rather than on government, and to
learn the processes of government, rather than resisting it.
``There are too many people who still think the solution to
America's problems is merely calling another march,'' Flake said,
according to The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   Flake has become increasingly known in recent years for defying
both political and civil rights orthodoxy, breaking with concepts
about the role of government that have been held by many Democrats
and black leaders since the 1960s. He has established a reputation
as a political iconoclast: Although he is a registered Democrat, he
has in recent years been more apt to endorse Republicans than
Democrats, among them Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, Pataki and Alfonse
D'Amato, the former senator.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, many Democrats and black leaders view him with
either suspicion or hostility and assert that his Republican-themed
sermons and endorsements are designed as a reward to Republican
officeholders, like Giuliani and D'Amato, who have channeled him
grants for church and other projects.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is sad that we come so cheap,'' said Rep. Charles B.
Rangel, a Manhattan Democrat, when informed of Flake's remarks.
</P>
<P>
   Flake has suggested that he might run for mayor in 2001 _
presumably, but not necessarily, as a Democrat _ and the speech in
Albany offered a preview of what he might say in a political
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm here to say that regardless of what color you are,
regardless of what background you come from, you can't spend your
life talking like a victim, acting like a victim, walking like a
victim,'' Flake said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
