A8524 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-CLIPNOTE-LADN     01-18 0557
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CLIPNOTE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NAMES SURFACE FOR GUARD JOB
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 c.1999 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ There are free agents to be recruited, trades to
be unleashed, training- camp fires to build and one question that
captures the spirit of this slow-approaching NBA season:
</P>
<P>
   Are we there yet?
</P>
<P>
   The answer is no.
</P>
<P>
   While lawyers stagger down the home stretch of the new
collective-bargaining agreement, the league has informed its
constituents that the ``drop alive'' date could be Wednesday. Or
not.
</P>
<P>
   The question that defines the Clippers' during the
lockout-imposed inertia is ``Who the heck is going to be the point
guard?'' The answer could be New Jersey free agent Sherman Douglas.
Or their own free agent, Darrick Martin.
</P>
<P>
   Free agents Darrell Armstrong (Orlando) and Eric Murdock
(Miami), popular names on any point-guard acquisition list, were
expected to say put, but now Murdock is believed to be considering
the Clippers. Murdock is thought to be a solid defender, and
defense at the point has been a mandate of Clippers vice president
of basketball operations Elgin Baylor.
</P>
<P>
   Another unemployed playmaker is veteran Phoenix guard Kevin
Johnson, whose marquee name has been linked to suitors with higher
profiles.
</P>
<P>
   Trading for a point guard is an option, but the salary cap
greatly reduces the odds of an equitable swap.
</P>
<P>
   ``We definitely want to upgrade the point-guard position if we
possibly can,'' new coach Chris Ford said Monday, ratifying a plan
that Baylor began offering months ago.
</P>
<P>
   It is believed the Clippers' competition for Douglas is supplied
by the Nets, who might use their $1.75 million exception to retain
the nine-year veteran. Because Douglas played for Ford in Boston
and Milwaukee, Clippersinterest would seem natural.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't really discuss free agents,'' said Ford, ``but he
(Douglas) is someone I'm very familiar with.''
</P>
<P>
   __ No Olowokandi-gram yet: If Bill Duffy has his way, Michael
Olowokandi, the team's and league's top draft pick, could be
leaving Italy for the NBA ahead of the scheduled escape-clause date
of Feb. 15. Duffy, Olowokandi's agent, is trying to persuade his
client's first employer, Kinder Bologna, to allow the 7-foot-1
center to ditch his European team for the Clippers one week ahead
of schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Duffy was not available for comment Monday, but a spokesperson
from his office said there was ``no new news'' on the Olowokandi
front.
</P>
<P>
   With Kinder scheduled to play archrival Benetton on Feb. 14, an
early departure might be tough to negotiate.
</P>
<P>
   But the NBA's sluggish progression in finishing its labor
agreement makes Olowokandi's absence seem less painful. According
to Ford, the rookie's reported intelligence and desire should make
the learning curve a bit less treacherous.
</P>
<P>
   ``From what I hear from those who saw him at Pete Newell's camp
over the summer, I'm really optimistic,'' Ford said. ``After the
daily workouts were over, he stayed on the court, working on his
game.''
</P>
<P>
   __ A nearly full house: The Clippers' other first-round draft
selection, Brian Skinner, was expected to arrive in Los Angeles on
Monday. The 6-foot-9, 250-pound Skinner, who has chosen with the
22nd pick, averaged 18.1 points and 9.5 rebounds his senior season
at Baylor.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
