A8525 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-GUN-SUIT-NYT &LR;      01-18 0858
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-GUN-SUIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPERT WITNESSES IN GUN LAWSUIT OFFERING TESTIMONY THAT HELPS BOTH
SIDES
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ga., Va., S.C., N.C., Fla., Pa., Ill., Mass.) ( nk )  
 By JOSEPH P. FRIED 
  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In a Brooklyn courtroom, lawyers are arguing a case
that could set a precedent on a fundamental national question:
Should the American gun industry be held collectively liable for
the blood spilled with illegally obtained handguns?
</P>
<P>
   A pattern has emerged in testimony in the suit, which was
brought by relatives of six people killed and a seventh wounded
with handguns in New York City and Yonkers, against more than 40
gun manufacturers and wholesalers: Lawyers for both sides have
elicited helpful testimony from the same experts in illegal gun
sales.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the plaintiffs last week called Joseph J. Vince,
who was until recently chief of the crime-gun analysis unit of the
Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms, to bolster one of their
basic contentions _ that the gun companies have saturated southern
states that have weak gun control laws with more new handguns than
the legitimate market there can absorb.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the excess weapons are sold to gun traffickers, who
resell them illegally in states with strong gun laws, like New
York, the plaintiffs contend. They maintain that this ``negligent
distribution'' makes the companies collectively liable for the
shootings in the case _ even if it cannot be proven which company's
gun was used in a given shooting _ an argument that legal experts
term novel in gun litigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``In New York, you have a lot of firearms that come from these
Southeast areas simply because they are abundant down there,''
Vince testified, providing what the plaintiffs' lawyers say was a
factual basis for their accusation.
</P>
<P>
   The companies deny that they oversupply states that have weak
gun laws, and they maintain that they cooperate in every way they
reasonably can in the effort against illegal trafficking.
</P>
<P>
   Under cross-examination by the defense, Vince agreed that the
licensed gun retailers whom the manufacturers and wholesalers deal
with help the Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms fight illegal
trafficking. ``If they see something that is suspicious, they will
contact their local ATF office and report that information,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is a frequent occurrence?'' asked James P. Dorr, a lawyer
for the companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, sir, it is,'' Vince said, adding that the bureau ``very
much'' relies on the licensed retailers as ``our eyes and ears.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there was the testimony of Kenneth McCann, a retired New
York City Police Department lieutenant who headed a joint city and
federal task force on illegal guns.
</P>
<P>
   The plaintiffs elicited his opinion that one step the gun makers
could take would be to visit licensed retail dealers to inspect
their records and ``ascertain if there are unusual patterns of
sales'' to buyers who seem likely to transport the guns to states
where they are illegal.
</P>
<P>
   But then a lawyer for the defendants, John Renzulli, got McCann
to agree that if gun makers did this frequently, it could interfere
with any undercover investigations of the retailers that might be
in progress.
</P>
<P>
   And, seeking support for the companies' position that they
cannot reasonably be asked to do the really effective work it takes
to combat illegal traffickers _ like operations in which undercover
officers buy guns from illicit dealers and then arrest them _
Renzulli asked, ``That is dangerous work, isn't it?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' McCann responded.
</P>
<P>
   ``And it should only be done by law enforcement?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you consider manufacturers and distributors of firearms as
law enforcement?''
</P>
<P>
   ``No.''
</P>
<P>
   The trial, which goes into its third week in U.S. District Court
in Brooklyn on Tuesday, is being closely watched by the gun
industry, gun control proponents and lawyers for cities like
Chicago, Philadelphia and Boston, which have sued or may sue gun
manufacturers and distributors, much as the states have sued the
tobacco industry.
</P>
<P>
   The defendants include giants of the nation's gun-making
industry, such as the Smith &AMP; Wesson Corporation, the Colt's
Manufacturing Company and Sturm, Ruger &AMP; Company.
</P>
<P>
   On the plaintiffs' side, in only one of the seven shootings was
the gun, a 9-millimeter pistol made by Cobray Firearms, recovered.
A plaintiffs' lawyer, Elisa Barnes, told the jury that Cobray had
defaulted in the case. But Ms. Barnes insisted that it did not
matter which companies made the guns used in the shootings because
the companies being sued ``were all negligent in the same way'' in
that they fed the underground gun market by oversupplying dealers
in states having ``lax gun laws,'' including Georgia, Florida,
Virginia, North Carolina, and South Carolina. Nearly half the guns
used in crimes in New York state in recent years have come from
those five states, she said.
</P>
<P>
   But the companies' lawyers responded that more guns were
distributed in the Southeast because there was a stronger legal
demand for them there, not so illicit traffickers could get them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
